<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS CRUSH BLUE JAYS, 11-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Mets raved about Jason Isringhausen four
years ago, it was because they believed he would be a reliable
starter for them for the next decade. When the Mets talked about
the right-hander pitcher during the last three years, it was
usually because they were giving injury updates. So when the Mets
discuss Isringhausen these days, they do it very cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   But Isringhausen gave the Mets ample reason on Tuesday night to
be a little more daring when his name is mentioned by pitching
strongly into the sixth inning and getting credit for an 11-3
victory over the Toronto Blue Jays at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a dominant performance and it will not be enough to
keep Isringhausen in the rotation when Bobby Jones returns. But it
was Isringhausen's first triumph in 21 months and that is
significant. Mostly for him, but also for the recuperating Mets,
who won their third straight after an eight-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen, whose career has been hampered by too many
expectations and too many injuries, had not won a major league game
since he beat the same Pat Hentgen and the Jays, 3-0, on Sept. 1,
1997. He missed the entire 1998 season after undergoing
reconstructive right elbow surgery. That came after he broke his
right wrist and had tuberculosis in 1997, and he endured
arthroscopic surgery on his right shoulder and his elbow in 1996.
Of the first 17 lines of Isringhausen's biography in the Mets'
media guide, 13 are related to injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is funny, in a way,'' Isringhausen said. ``At times, I've
thought that if I didn't have bad luck, I wouldn't have any luck at
all. Those 21 months, I got through it and I kept my mind straight.
I got through everything. It makes me realize I can get through a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a night he has been waiting for and he could put
to rest,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``He can go to bed and
feel that those two years or whatever it was has brought him
fulfillment and the first of many wins.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was obviously a relief to Isringhausen on Tuesday night
when the bullpen did not crumble after he left with a 4-1 lead two
outs into the sixth inning, having yielded two hits and two earned
runs. Dennis Cook replaced Isringhausen and promptly allowed a
pinch-hit two-run homer to Jacob Brumfield. But three relievers
held the Jays scoreless after that and the Mets exploded for four
runs in the seventh and three in the eighth to turn the game into a
rout.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, Rey Ordonez had four hits and knocked in two runs,
Robin Ventura had three hits and drove in a run, Edgardo Alfonzo
stroked a two-run homer and Roger Cedeno had a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   With a fastball that reached 93 miles an hour, Isringhausen
whiffed six and allowed only a homer to Jose Cruz Jr. and a single
to Hentgen. He walked five, but held the Jays without a hit in four
at bats with runners on while improving to 1-1 this year and 18-18
in his career. Half of those victories came during his rookie
season, when Isringhuasen went 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, rallies start in strange places. Could there be any
stranger place for the Mets than with Ordonez and Isringhausen?
After Ordonez's single in the third, Isringhausen tried to bunt him
to second base. Darrin Fletcher, the Blue Jays' catcher, grabbed
the ball and fired it past Homer Bush, who was covering first, to
put runners on first and third.
</P>
<P>
   Hentgen tried to catch Isringhausen napping at first and nearly
picked him off when he started his motion, stepped toward third and
then quickly threw back to first. Isringhausen was safe on a close
play, but the Mets' third base coach Cookie Rojas began shouting at
Umpire Angel Hernandez because he felt Hentgen had balked. Rojas
was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   That caused Valentine to step in as third base coach. Valentine
coached one inning and in it the Mets scored three runs to take a
3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson roped a fly to deep center field, which enabled
Ordonez to tag up from third. When Alfonzo followed with a massive
two-run homer over the left field fence, Valentine hustled down the
line to congratulate both players as they passed. Valentine
replaced himself with Bruce Benedict in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   One inning later, John Olerud stroke a two-out double to left
and scored on Mike Piazza's single through the middle to bump the
advantage to 4-1. Piazza had been batting .220 with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
