<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHNER CONFIDENT OF FUTURE WITH M'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As pivotal as this season is for the Mariners
franchise, it is just as important for right fielder Jay Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, who turns 35 in August, missed most of last season with
injuries, and is on the disabled list with a strained left
hamstring now. The Mariners have a $6.3 million option on him for
next year, with a $400,000 buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Given the Mariners' budget concerns, and the pending free agency
of starter Jeff Fassero, first baseman David Segui and designated
hitter Edgar Martinez, $6.3 million is a hefty price. Buhner said
he's thought about those issues, but he's confident he'll come back
_ somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've got to get myself healthy, and once I do that, I'm
going to be able to help the team win ballgames,'' Buhner said.
``Whatever happens at the end of the year happens. It'll work out
one way or another, if I've got any say-so. The three of us
(Martinez, Buhner and Ken Griffey Jr.) have been together over 10
years, and they know I want to continue to keep doing that and end
my career here, and I'm going to. I'm not worried about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's immediate return is not less than two weeks away, he
said. He ran lightly for the third day in a row Tuesday and will
undergo a more rigorous workout Wednesday. He said his main problem
has been lateral movement, bending down for balls and coming back
up again, and cutting on the bases. Lingering inflammation has
caused the leg to cramp.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner was not on the Mariners' last road trip, but he chose to
make this one. He needs to be with the training staff, but there is
another reason. Even if he can't play, Buhner said, he still can
exercise his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, you're always learning something new,'' Buhner
said. ``You can always take something in and see certain things,
and just being around the game a little bit kind of keeps your
brain working. I may not be seeing a whole lot here, because it's
interleague and we're not facing these guys again, but at the same
time, you're seeing the ball out of the pitcher's hand, and you're
just able to take in the game and be a part of it. So you can make
a positive out of something.''
</P>
<P>
   When Buhner returns, it will put manager Lou Piniella in the
same bind he faced before: how to fit seven outfielders on a roster
that also should have 11 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Jay back, but I don't like to look at the
repercussions,'' Piniella said. ``Let me enjoy it while I can.''
</P>
<P>
   JUGGLING ACT: Piniella made a few lineup changes Tuesday, giving
Rafael Bournigal a start at second base and playing John Mabry at
third. David Segui also returned to the lineup after missing five
starts because of a sinus infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to play our bench some, and we've continued to do
that,'' Piniella said. ``The weather's starting to get hot, and
we're hoping to keep some players sharp. Tomorrow, I'm thinking of
using (Matt) Mieske in left field to give (Brian) Hunter a day off.
We'll give everybody a little playing time on this road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Bournigal, who batted .343 filling in for Alex Rodriguez, made
his second start since Rodriguez returned from the disabled list
May 15.
</P>
<P>
   COORS WEST? With its brick facade, forest-green seats and
three-tiered stands, Coors Field has some similarities to Safeco
Field.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Safeco designers were influenced two ways by Coors. At
both parks, the concourse level offers a field view from every
point. And Safeco Field's home-plate entrance was expanded when the
Rockies told the Mariners that most fans prefer to enter through
one gate.
</P>
<P>
   But Mariners pitcher Jeff Fassero, who took a tour of Safeco
Field last week, said he doesn't see the similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safeco's going to be a pretty different place,'' he said. ``In
foul territory, it's similar, but between the foul poles, it's all
different. The scoreboard's in a different place (left field at
Coors, center at Safeco), they have seats where our bullpens are,
and there's a whole level of seats in left field that they don't
have here.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about that row of purple seats that rings the upper
deck at Coors Field, signifying one mile above sea level?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll have a teal line where sea level is,'' Fassero
said.
</P>
<P>
   A JUNIOR SALUTE: Griffey found himself surrounded by autograph
seekers about 10 minutes before Tuesday night's game. Nothing new,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, these hounds were members of the Super Bowl champion
Denver Broncos. About 50 players and coaches lined up on the Coors
Field baselines, with head coach Mike Shanahan tossing the first
pitch to ``catcher'' Terrell Davis. After the ceremony, about 10
Broncos crowded around Griffey to get him to sign the souvenir bats
they'd received from the Rockies. The Mariners star was happy to
oblige.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
