<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA AND PAKISTAN AGREE TO TALK ABOUT KASHMIR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ For the first time since fighting erupted in
the disputed province of Kashmir last month, senior Indian and
Pakistani officials agreed on Tuesday to discuss ways of defusing
the tension, Pakistan announced.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two countries remain far apart in their perceptions
of the crisis and the possible solutions, the announcement that
they are ready to open peace talks is certain to be welcomed by the
outside world. This is the first conflict to erupt along the border
since both countries successfully tested nuclear weapons last year,
and it has raised fears in some foreign capitals that hostilities
could worsen rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan had offered to send its foreign minister, Sartaj Aziz,
to New Delhi on Tuesday, but India had demurred, apparently hoping
to delay talks until its army could make more progress on the
ground. India suggested Saturday for the talks and on Wednesday
Aziz accepted the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting broke out in Kashmir last month when Indian soldiers
sought to move back into their mountain positions along the border.
The Indians normally hold these positions in warmer months and
abandon them during the forbidding winter. But when they sought to
re-occupy them last month they came under fire. It soon became
clear that hostile forces had seized the snowy ridges on India's
side of the line of control.
</P>
<P>
   India describes the opposing forces as infiltrators supported by
Pakistan and including Pakistan army troops. Pakistan denies any
involvement and says the forces are Muslim rebels seeking to free
Kashmir from Indian control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfair to call them infiltrators,'' said Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan. He described them as members of ``a
freedom movement.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The often violent conflict over Kashmir dates back to the
founding of India and Pakistan in 1947. Under an agreement that
neither side accepts, India came to control two-thirds of the
province and Pakistan the rest. Both claim all of it, and they have
fought two wars to assert their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir's maharaja at partition was Hindu and chose to be part
of India, but the people are mainly Muslim, and the region has
become a rallying point for Islamic militants around the world who
see it as unjustly subjected to the yoke of a Hindu power. India
contends that it respects the rights of the Muslims and offers them
every privilege.
</P>
<P>
   If negotiations begin as planned on Saturday, the agenda is
likely to be the first issue disputed. Pakistan does not agree that
it is a party to the conflict; it says it has done nothing to
promote the infiltration of fighters, and that none of them are
Pakistani soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz, the Pakistani foreign minister, may seek to question the
legality of the division of Kashmir, a gambit India has vowed to
reject. In a nationally televised speech on Monday, India's prime
minister, Atal Bihari Vajpayee, said that if Pakistan seeks to
discuss the Kashmir issue as a whole, ``the proposed talks will be
over before they even begin.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The subject is one and one alone: the intrusion, and how
Pakistan proposes to undo it,'' Vajpayee said.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting along the border is intense. Indian forces have been
bombarding hostile positions in the forbidding mountains, both from
the air and with artillery. India's strategy is evidently twofold:
agreeing to negotiate while pressing its military campaign to
regain control of the high ground along the border.
</P>
<P>
   India claims to have killed dozens of Pakistani soldiers on its
side of the border, but has not given the total. It has reported
the death of 63 Indian soldiers, with 217 wounded and 14 missing
and possibly captured.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of civilians have been forced to flee their homes in
Kashmir, overwhelming the local resources to provide them with
shelter and medical care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
