<HEADLINE>
THEATER GROUP GETS BEHIND CLINTON'S CALL TO CHECK TEEN IDS AT
MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At the request of President Clinton, the
National Association of Theatre Owners announced Tuesday that its
members would require photo identification, most likely a driver's
license, from teen-agers who want to see R-rated movies without a
parent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had challenged the industry to enforce the rating system
more strictly in the wake of the high school shootings in
Littleton, Colo. The North Hollywood-based trade organization
represents 65 percent of all movie screens in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But while the White House heralded the agreement, some in the
theater industry questioned its value. Childrens' advocates
observed, too, that the rule does nothing about cable access to
movie violence, or about video rentals.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, some chains _ including Kansas City area-based AMC
Theatres and Dickinson Theatres _ have been requiring teens to show
proof of age for years.
</P>
<P>
   But the rule is not always effective, said Andrew Armstrong,
Dickinson's director of operations.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers can be sneaky. They buy a ticket to see Macaulay
Culkin in ``Home Alone'' and then, once inside the big megaplex,
they slip in to watch Demi Moore in ``Striptease.''
</P>
<P>
   To prevent the deception, Armstrong said, an employee would have
to be posted at each ``screen'' door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to pay for that?'' Armstrong asked.
</P>
<P>
   At large megaplex theaters, especially, the additional check
points could add substantially to the ticket price.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson provided the extra staffing for ``Showgirls'' which
appealed hugely to adolescent boys. ``Forbidden fruit,'' Armstrong
called it.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong puts the onus on parents. They are the ones who should
be assuming responsibility for the movies their children see.
</P>
<P>
   But parents often drop children at the door and drive away. Kids
can then often find a way into the movie they want to see,
Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   And not only that _ some parents will attempt to purchase
tickets to R-rated movies for children, then leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen parents get verbally abusive when we won't let
their kids into `R' movies,'' Armstong said.
</P>
<P>
   AMC spokeswoman Brenda Nolte said the theater chain has a couple
of secret methods to ensure that youngsters don't get into theaters
where they don't belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it hasn't happened, but I think we do a pretty
good job,'' Nolte said.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed while shopping Tuesday in south Kansas City, a
16-year-old high school student agreed that the AMC Town Center 20
in Johnson County, which she often patronizes, strictly enforces
the rule.
</P>
<P>
   But she's found some movie houses that don't even question a
ticket-buyer's age. Other theaters won't sell tickets to underage
teens, she said, but it's common practice to sneak into forbidden
movies anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen every movie I've wanted to see,'' said the girl, who
asked that her name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   John Shipp of Cinema Consultants, which manages several local
theaters, thinks Kansas City theaters do a good job of policing
movie admission, but acknowledged that some operators aren't as
diligent as they could be.
</P>
<P>
   He suspected the new policy could help bring the others into
compliance.
</P>
<P>
   James Caccamo, executive director of Kansas City's Partnership
for Children, applauded Clinton's idea but said it's not the
solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that they are going to make it harder for kids to
get into those movies, but that's only part of the problem of teen
violence,'' Caccamo said.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed with Armstrong that parents must do more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
