<SLUG> BC-TWA-UNION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION EMPLOYEES VOTE ON TWA OFFER, AND UNION OFFICER PREDICTS
DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Area union employees of Trans World Airlines
voted Tuesday on the company's ``best and final'' offer for a new
contract, and a union officer said he expected the membership to
reject it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the sacrifices our members have made over the years,
they're insulted by what's been offered,'' said Keith Nelson,
president of Machinists Local 1650. ``My opinion is that they're
going to overwhelmingly turn down the contract and provide a very
strong strike (authorization) vote.''
</P>
<P>
   About 600 TWA employees attended a meeting on Tuesday morning,
Nelson said. The terms of TWA's contract were discussed by union
officials and rank-and-file members before balloting was conducted.
Union members also voted on whether to authorize a strike against
TWA.
</P>
<P>
   The morning meeting consisted of workers from the second and
third shifts at TWA's overhaul base at Kansas City International
Airport. An evening meeting was scheduled for those who work the
first shift, and Nelson said about 1,100 people were expected to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City mechanics and ramp workers were the first group
of employees to vote on TWA's contract offer, a process that is
expected to take the rest of the month. TWA workers in St. Louis
will be voting today.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has about 2,300 union employees in Kansas City, and the
Machinists union represents about 16,000 TWA workers systemwide.
The union is not expected to release the results of the balloting
until all the votes are in at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders have urged the members to reject TWA's contract
proposal, which they contend does not provide enough in wage
increases.
</P>
<P>
   TWA management has said its $350 million package of pay raises
and lump-sum payments would stretch the resources of a company that
has not posted a profit in 10 years. The contract would bring TWA
employees to 90 percent of the industry standard by July 2001, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those attending the meeting and election Tuesday was Al
Calhoun, general chairman of Machinists District 142. District 142
is the negotiating arm for the union in its talks with TWA.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said conversations before and after the vote, as well as
comments during the meeting, indicated that the employees were
against the contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, TWA and St. Louis civic leaders tried to make a case
for approving the contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, TWA brought in Darryl Jenkins, executive director of
the Aviation Institute at Georgetown University, to present his
analysis of TWA's contract offer.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said the $350 million package was achievable but would
tax TWA's resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any additional commitment of resources by TWA would be
unrealistic, and the offers as currently constituted could cause
some financial uncertainty in the future,'' Jenkins said in his
report.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson dismissed the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a typical tactic taken when a company is involved in a
labor-management dispute,'' he said. ``There's a lot of stockholder
money out there that wants this new contract, but I don't think
that's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
