<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOBE-SYSTEMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOBE TO ADD NEW DIVISION IN SEATTLE, FOCUSING ON INTERNET
PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Adobe Systems Inc., the San Jose, Calif.-based maker
of publishing and graphics software, on Tuesday announced a new
corporate division in Seattle that will help the company strengthen
its move to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe, which already has about 500 employees in its Seattle
office, plans to add at least 50 jobs to the new division _ called
the Internet Products Group _ by the end of the year. But Hank
Skorny, who is overseeing the new division, indicated that the
number of new hires could be a lot higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``As fast as we can grow, we will grow,'' said Skorny, adding
that he will rely on his contacts in the Seattle technology
community to ramp up recruiting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, Adobe cut 9 percent of its worldwide work force
in a move to reposition the company for the Internet. Only about 10
of the 250 jobs cut were in Seattle. And Tuesday's announcement to
focus the new direction of the company in Seattle could be seen as
a boost to the local technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   It's also another sign that technology companies, some based as
far away as Silicon Valley and London, view Seattle as a hotspot
for e-commerce and Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe, which makes the PhotoShop, PageMaker and Illustrator
software products, joins an impressive list of companies trying to
latch on to the energy in Seattle's Internet and e-commerce
sectors. In March, Getty Images, a company that sells electronic
photographs over the Internet, moved its headquarters from London
to Seattle to be closer to the budding e-commerce community.
</P>
<P>
   The new companies include some of the biggest names in their
fields. HomeGrocer.com, Onvia.com and Concur Technologies are among
those who have moved here in the past couple of years for reasons
such as tax benefits and quality of life issues.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Washington Software Alliance, more than 2,500
technology companies are located in the state, up from 1,600 in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significant portion of Adobe's growth and revenue in the
future will be driven out of Seattle,'' said Skorny, who before
taking over the Internet Products Group served as senior director
of publishing at Adobe.
</P>
<P>
   Like Microsoft and other old-guard software companies, Adobe
Systems _ founded in 1982 _ is going through growing pains as it
attempts to embrace the Internet revolution.
</P>
<P>
   While that repositioning has caused some uncertainty at Adobe's
San Jose headquarters, it could mean a potential boom for the
company's Seattle office. In many respects, Adobe is placing a big
bet on Seattle and its burgeoning Internet community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at Seattle as an up-and-coming player with a lot of
vibrant, young energy,'' said Skorny. ``There is a certain edge
that the Seattle Internet community has.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Adobe's creation of a new division in Seattle caught some
analysts by surprise. ``I really don't know why they are choosing
Seattle,'' said Steve Shepich, an industry analyst at Olde Discount
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Since Adobe recently announced that it was consolidating part of
its international division in San Jose, Shepich said it would make
sense for the company to expand the Internet Products Group there
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there really that much more talent available in Seattle?''
</P>
<P>
   Skorny, who said Adobe plans to host a recruiting ``open house''
at its Seattle facility Thursday from 4-8 p.m., firmly believes the
talent pool in Seattle is stronger than other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least in my experience the availability of (technology
workers) in Seattle is greater than Silicon Valley,'' Skorny said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent study by the Washington Software Alliance,
there are currently 10,000 open positions in the state's high-tech
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe's Internet Products Group will be responsible for
expanding the company's GoLive Web-creating products which it
acquired earlier this year. It will also develop new technologies,
products and services for creating and assembling Web pages.
Expanding into the areas of Internet publishing is a smart and
necessary move for the company, said Shepich.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a huge area of growth potential for these
guys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Vleeschhouwer, an analyst at Merrill Lynch Global
Securities, said Adobe is in the process of adopting a new business
model that is tied directly to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to drive as much attention as they can to
their Web strategy,'' said Vleeschhouwer, adding that the cost
savings from the recent round of job cuts would be transferred to
the Internet division. ``Adobe believes _ and I think rightly so _
that they are well positioned to take advantage of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Two computer scientists from the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center
founded Adobe 17 years ago. The company, which now has revenues of
almost $1 billion, opened a Seattle office in 1994 after it
acquired desktop software developer Aldus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
