<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SAY ONE LOSS IS NOT A CATASTROPHE
</HEADLINE>
 STANLEY CUP SIDEBAR-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In one simple phrase, Mike Modano succinctly and
eloquently wrote the epitaph for Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars lost Game 1 to the Buffalo Sabres, 3-2, Tuesday night
at Reunion Arena because they didn't take advantage of those
chances.
</P>
<P>
   They rained 37 shots at Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek, but got
just two past him. They rarely got to a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played his style of game,'' Modano said. ``Our inability to
get in there and get second and third chances was key.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had eight power plays in regulation, but after scoring
on the first, they were shut out.
</P>
<P>
   They had an almost unheard of two power plays in overtime, when
the referees mostly skate around with the whistles in their
pockets, but couldn't cash in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have that many power plays ... '' Stars forward Mike
Keane said. ``Special teams were a factor. We have to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, they had the lead after the first two periods, and
seemed to be in control of the game. They were playing their usual
brand of aggressive-defensive hockey, taking 24 shots while holding
the Sabres to nine.
</P>
<P>
   In the Stars' system, when you're playing that well and have the
lead, you don't lose.
</P>
<P>
   But the visitors, perhaps spurred by desperation, had the most
energy in the third period. After playing on their heels for two
periods, the Sabres did most of the attacking and scored two goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third period was really a bad period,'' Modano said. ``We
got away from our game, and let them back in it. We lost a lot of
our aggressiveness. We lost our edge in the third period.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hasek made a couple of spectacular saves, including one
in overtime seconds before Jason Woolley's game-winner, the Stars
said they won't let him get in their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hasek played well, but we have to find a way to beat him,''
Keane said. ``We didn't cause enough pressure in their end, or get
enough traffic in front of Hasek.''
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, the Stars did get off the 37 shots, plus
another 25 that went wide or high.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as you have that many chances, eventually they'll go
in,'' Modano said. ``We have to fight for space in front of the
net.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are in a familiar position. They lost Game 1 at home
to the Colorado Avalanche in the Western Conference finals, but
rallied to win Game 2 and eventually the series in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very frustrated,'' Modano said. ``We didn't play our
game. We felt we let each other down as a team, and we'll regroup
as a team. We've done it before, taken losses personally, and come
back and tied the series up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play desperation hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are down in the series, but not in spirit. They are a
veteran group that knows how to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's disappointed, but one game is one game,'' Keane
said. ``We're far from out of this. No one's down.''
</P>
<P>
   They might not be down, but neither are they pleased. The
dressing room was almost deserted after the game, but before they
disappeared, the Stars players vented their frustrations at losing
a game in which they had so many opportunities to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of upset guys after the game,'' Modano said.
``When we have that, we usually regroup.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
