<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-NYT &LR;      06-09 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES DEFEAT STARS, 3-2, IN OPENING GAME OF STANLEY CUP FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ed Belfour, the Dallas goalie, goes by the nickname the
Eagle, and he wears the image of the bird on his head gear. Dominik
Hasek, the Buffalo goalie known as the Dominator, wears an
old-fashioned mask often called a ``bird cage.'' This aviary
rivalry goes back a decade, and Hasek flew highest on Tuesday night
in the opening game of the Stanley Cup finals as his Sabres stunned
the Stars, 3-2, in overtime, before at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal was scored by Jason Woolley at 15 minutes 30
seconds of the extra session after Hasek made two stunning saves.
</P>
<P>
   Woolley scored on a wrist shot from the slot that beat Belfour
after taking a feed from Curtis Brown.
</P>
<P>
   He may have taken the Stars by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came off the bench, said Wooley, who has scored 4
playoff goals. ``I think I snuck up on them a little bit. In
overtime, you just want to shoot. I got lucky and it went in. I
didn;t know how to react''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek stopped 35 shots and seemed weary in overtime, remaining
on the ice long after making saves and lying prone after Woolley's
winning goal. But Hasek said he felt no effects of the groin injury
that kept him out of two games of the Eastern Confgerence fianls
against Tornto.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 is here on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's game mixed excellent goaltending, hard hitting,
wonderful tension and most of the elements that display hockey at
its best.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres finished a lowly seventh seed in the weaker East.
Dallas finished first in the Western Conference and first over all
in the 27-team National Hockey League. Although the Stars must
still be considered the favored team, a Buffalo surprise seems like
a more realistic possibility after Tuesday night's events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too tired; I couldn't even gop to the other side, Hasek
said referring to the celebration around Woolley. ``This building
is so hot. I made a save on Verbeek, I kicked up my leg and all of
a sudden I felt a cramp in my hip.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindy Ruff, the Buffalo Coach, made a reference to his team's
underdog status and the fact that the Eastern Conference
representative has been swept the last three seasons. ``the good
thing is we can't get swept now,'' Ruff said. ``We just won one for
the East.''
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher, the captin of the Stars, said his team will
``have to make it tougher on Dominik'' in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we shot a lot of pucks right at him,'' Hatcher said.
``We like to do things the hard way. ASe have dropped Game Ones
before. We're confident we can come back again.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars led for most of the game, but Buffalo tied it at 1-1
at 8:33 of the third period on a goal by Stu Barnes, who fired from
the slot to beat Belfour. This came while the Sabres skated with an
extra attacker because they had pulled Hasek during a delayed
penalty to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres went up by 2-1 on a goal by Wayne Primeau, who camped
in front of the crease on the power play and knocked in a rebound
with a backhanded shot at 13:37. But Dallas tied it at 2-2 at 19:11
on a goal by Jere Lehtinen, who took a centering pass from Mike
Modano after Buffalo's checking center, Mike Peca, lost his stick
behind the Sabres' net.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars dominated the first two periods but emerged with only
a 1-0 lead despite a 24-9 edge in shots on goal. Brett Hull scored
with one second left in a power play, firing a one-time slap shot
from high in the Buffalo zone after passes from Modano and Lehtinen
at 10:17 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres escaped a worse fate later when James Patrick, their
veteran defenseman, took a double minor for accidentally
high-sticking Pat Verbeek of the Stars. The trend continued in the
second period, with Buffalo's streak reaching seven consecutive
penalties before the referees called a pair against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, who missed two games in the previous series against
Toronto with a groin injury, seemed to be in fine form, dropping to
his knees and side and using moves goalies sometimes call
``swimming.'' Occasionally, he shed his goal stick, as is his
custom. When Jon Sim of Dallas took an extra whack at the puck
after Hasek made a save, the goalie reacted angrily, and so did
several of his teammates. During the ensuing multiplayer scrum,
Brian Skrudland of the Stars hit Vaclav Varada of the Sabres in the
face with a butt of his helmeted head. No penalty was called.
</P>
<P>
   Varada was involved in a complicated play early in the second
period that resulted in an apparent goal being waved off and Varada
going to the penalty box for interfering with Belfour. A Buffalo
shot by Mike Peca got past Belfour, and the puck bounced over the
line just as Belfour was falling to the ice after a light jostle
from Varada.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hasek and Belfour are known for shows of temper when
bothered by opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Both also are 34 years old, and that is not all they have in
common. Although neither has played for a Stanley Cup winner, both
Hasek and Belfour have been to the finals before, when both played
for the Chicago Blackhawks, who lost to the Pittsburgh Penguins in
the finals of 1992. And their memories of their time together show
how differently two people in the same circumstances can perceive
the same environment.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour was the first-stringer under Mike Keenan, the coach and
general manager of the Hawks. Chicago's part-time goalie coach was
then, and still is, Vladislav Tretiak, the Hockey Hall of Famer who
used to play for the national team of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good relationship in Chicago,'' Belfour said. ``In
practice, we competed against each other and worked hard against
each other and I think it was an overall positive relationship for
both of us. We worked closely with Vladislav Tretiak, which I think
helped both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's memories were different. ``Eddie was the starting goalie
and I was the backup goalie,'' Hasek said. ``Our relationship, I
mean, it was tough. But I don't think our relationship was bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Tretiak, Hasek said: ``He never really worked with me. He
worked more with Eddie Belfour. I cannot say he taught me
something.''
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1992, Keenan traded Hasek to Buffalo for
Stephane Beuregard and a fourth-round draft choice. Since then,
Hasek has won the Vezina trophy four times as the league's best
goalie and the Hart trophy twice as the best player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
