<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8242 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-WORKERS-SPI &LR;      06-09 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-WORKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPS FOR CHERRY PICKERS INADEQUATE, FEDERAL GOVERNMENT TELLS
STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As many as 1,600 migrant cherry pickers will end up
sleeping in their cars and camping in the woods of Eastern
Washington this summer because of a disagreement between the state
and federal governments.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Labor recently told the state that its
cherry camp rules are inadequate to protect the health and safety
of farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   And the Labor Department two weeks ago warned growers that
participating in the state cherry camp program could expose them to
$1,000 fines.
</P>
<P>
   Growers expected to provide shelter for at least 1,600 workers
this summer have since begun pulling out of the cherry camp
program, and the state fears it will soon have no growers
participating.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before the cherry picking season begins in earnest,
state officials say they expect living conditions to be far worse
this summer than last. Then, hundreds of workers camped for weeks
without toilets and running water because some growers, frustrated
with tougher new farm worker housing regulations, chose not to
operate their camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a couple more thousand people without any place
to stay this growing season as a result of the U.S. Department of
Labor's position,'' said Rich Nafziger, Gov. Gary Locke's executive
policy assistant on farm worker issues.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 16,000 workers bring in Washington's cherry crop
every June and July. Nafziger said roughly half those workers will
commute from their homes to the orchards. Another 1,500 or so will
stay with growers that have cabins or other solid-wall housing. The
rest will stay with friends and relatives or camp where they can _
often on public land and along rivers and creeks _ Nafziger said.
Because thousands end up camping in rough conditions, the state has
worked to expand its licensed cherry camp program to encourage
growers to house more workers.
</P>
<P>
   The cherry camp regulations the state put in place this year are
less stringent than those for other crops partly because the cherry
season is short. Unlike the months-long apple harvest, it takes
only about three weeks to bring in a cherry crop. During that
intense period of picking, an individual grower often hires
hundreds of workers. And growers say it makes little sense for them
to spend thousands of dollars creating elaborate housing facilities
that are only used a few weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   The state standards adopted this year require cherry growers to
equip labor camps with cooking facilities, showers, toilets and
electricity but allow workers to bring their own tents. The
Department of Health expected about 1,600 workers to use the
state-licensed camps.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations were adopted over the objection of farm worker
advocates who have long argued that the state is legally obligated
to ensure that cherry pickers have housing no worse than that
offered workers who harvest other longer-lived crops.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 10 letter to the state, Richard Terrill, regional
administrator of the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration, warned that state rules ``do not provide a level of
protection equivalent to approved... federal standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires solid-wall housing, or at least
military-style tents with plenty of head room, as well as nearby
showers, refrigerators, electric lighting, toilets and cooking
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Terrill said he made clear to state officials in April that
state cherry camp rules fall short of federal standards. The small
tents being allowed were particularly worrisome, he said. And he
was concerned that state officials would let growers substitute ice
chests for refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you have ever camped over in Eastern
Washington in the summertime, but when you wake up in the morning,
you'll find your food floating in water,'' he said. ``That is not
healthful storage of food.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nafziger said the state was ``blind-sided'' by the federal
agency's tough stance. He said the agency was well aware that the
state planned to enforce less-stringent standards this year and to
bring all camps into compliance with federal standards over a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad public policy to suddenly have 2,000 (fewer) units of
housing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Pacharzina, a lawyer who represents migrant pickers who
have challenged the state's cherry camp standards, said the state
bears responsibility for misleading growers about federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   She and several other farm worker advocates said Tuesday that
the state should ask the National Guard to provide safe,
military-style tent camps for workers.
</P>
<P>
   But Nafziger said such an operation would cost the state at
least $1 million, and that money is better spent on long-term
housing. The state opened a migrant center in Mattawa that
converted cargo containers into homes for as many as 300 workers
this month for $1.3 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be living in unacceptable conditions this summer
as they have been for the last 30 years,'' he said. ``But we are
better off trying to invest incrementally in providing incentives
for growers and building long-term housing than taking heroic
emergency steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gempler, director of the Washington Grower's League, said
he will work to get OSHA to sign off on the state's pilot
Rent-A-Tent program.
</P>
<P>
   Under it, community agencies buy spacious, military style tents
they plan to rent to growers for the cherry season. Terrill, the
OSHA administrator, said he plans to inspect one of the 25 tents to
be bought by the Community Action Council of North Central
Washington, which serves Grant and Adams counties.
</P>
<P>
   Gempler said he hopes rent-a-tents can be used to rescue growers
that planned to have licensed camps where workers would bring their
own tents.
</P>
<P>
   But Nafziger said it's too late for the rent-a-tent program to
be expanded beyond 25 tents this summer, providing housing for just
150 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no program for this year,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
