<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8244 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR &LR;      06-09 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEP EXPERT DENIES KILLING PREMEDITATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of Scott Falater's actions the night he killed his wife
were so strange and illogical that they contradict the charge of
premeditated murder and support the claim that he was sleepwalking,
a sleepwalking expert testified Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roger Broughton, a witness for the defense, said he
concludes that sleepwalking ``is by far the most probable''
explanation of the 1997 attack at the family's north Phoenix home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one were going to commit a homicide, much of the activity
that's documented makes no sense to me,'' said Broughton, referring
to reports by a neighbor who witnessed part of the attack and by
police who investigated it.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton, a Canadian physician, neurophysiologist and sleep
researcher, said a killer acting with premeditation would not have:
</P>
<P>
   Left a body floating in a pool made crimson with blood from 44
stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Waited until he had completed the attack before putting on a
pair of gloves to drag the victim to the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Gone back to bed after the attack and reacted with bewilderment
when police arrived to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton said he had concluded that Falater remained asleep
even though his wife screamed loudly enough for a neighbor to hear
and resisted so desperately that she was stabbed many times in the
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that's what happened,'' Broughton said with a cool
professorial calm that contrasted sharply with the rapid-fire and
almost indignant interrogation by prosecutor Juan Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton even granted Martinez's supposition that Yarmila
Falater, who died just short of her 41st birthday, may have
repeatedly screamed her husband's name during the frenzied attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``And one of the things we know from the literature,'' Martinez
said, ``is that one of the best ways to wake somebody up from
sleepwalking is to call their name.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best ways, but it doesn't always work,''
Broughton responded.
</P>
<P>
   But the doctor acknowledged also that he had based his opinion
on information that he had received directly from Falater, 43, a
former Motorola engineer who could face the death penalty if he is
convicted in Maricopa County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton said his interview with Falater led him to conclude
that he had no motive to kill his wife of 20 years or memory of the
attack, and felt deep remorse for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton relied on Falater's word to conclude that the engineer
had been struggling with sleep deprivation brought on by severe
stress at work, where Falater was confronting the failure of a
sophisticated computer chip developed by a team he directed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was the type of stress that would make
sleepwalking occur,'' the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater was so sleep deprived on the night of the attack that he
fell quickly into a deep sleep when he went to bed after an
unsuccessful attempt to fix a pump for the backyard pool, Broughton
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said sleepwalking episodes begin during deep sleep that
generally is characterized by the unstable brain wave activity
measured in Falater.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I presume may well have happened was that Scott was out
there working on the (pump) and Yarmila heard him and went out to
see if she could help or whatever, and that she probably touched
him,'' Broughton said.
</P>
<P>
   Such contact, particularly if it interrupts a sleepwalker in the
middle of a task, commonly provokes a violent attack, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, 10 women and five men who have remained attentive
throughout the trial, submitted more than a dozen questions for
Broughton. Most were read aloud by Judge Ronald Reinstein.
</P>
<P>
   One juror, mindful of the defense claim that on the night of the
attack Falater had quickly fallen into a deep sleep, asked how long
it took Falater to reach deep sleep on the four nights he was
tested at St. Luke's Behavioral Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton said Falater had needed 60 to 124 minutes to reach
deep sleep. But he noted that Falater was not sleep deprived at the
time of the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Another juror wanted to know whether the study of sleep
disorders relied heavily on speculation rather than hard scientific
data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very detailed knowledge about a wide variety of sleep
disorders,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Martinez sought to undermine Broughton's credibility
by suggesting that the Canadian had played hide-the-ball by
refusing several months ago to provide information on his research.
</P>
<P>
   But with help from defense attorney Michael Kimerer, Broughton
appeared to repair any damage when he responded that he had never
before been part of a U.S. trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize the way it was done in the States,'' he said,
adding that he had responded to Martinez's questions in a five-hour
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is in recess until Monday so that Reinstein can attend
a judicial conference. &QL; 
Jerry Kammer can be reached at (602) 444-8185 or
jerry.kammer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8247 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-WORKERS-SPI &LR;      06-09 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-WORKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPS FOR CHERRY PICKERS INADEQUATE, FEDERAL GOVERNMENT TELLS
STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As many as 1,600 migrant cherry pickers will end up
sleeping in their cars and camping in the woods of Eastern
Washington this summer because of a disagreement between the state
and federal governments.
</P>
