<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-WHITESOX-H     06-09 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WHITESOX-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ Glen Barker is in need of a little redemption. Tuesday
night, he committed a cardinal sin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barker was caught trying to steal third base to end the game as
the Chicago White Sox posted a 4-3 victory over the Astros at
Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret Astros manager Larry Dierker gives his players a
perpetual green light on the basepaths. Houston leads the major
leagues with 77 steals.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Astros down to their final out with arguably their
fastest player already in scoring position, Dierker acknowledged he
should have put a hold on Barker at second base, especially
considering Chicago reliever Bob Howry's quick delivery to the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with the Astros trailing by a run and Ricky Gutierrez
at the plate, Barker headed for third on a 2-1 pitch from Howry.
Gutierrez took the pitch, and catcher Brook Fordyce gunned down
Barker to end the game. Howry earned his 10th save with a scoreless
ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a stupid mistake,'' said Barker, who stole second base
two pitches earlier after being inserted as a pinch runner for
Daryle Ward. ``I should have just let him swing the bat. Any kind
of hit or error, and I could have scored. It was one of those times
I made a bad decision, and it cost us the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take the blame 100 percent. It's not the manager. I should
have been smarter. I've been playing this game long enough to know
I shouldn't get thrown out at third.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros outfielder Carl Everett was willing to cut some slack to
the 27-year-old Barker, who is playing his first big-league season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a young guy. You can't blame it on him,'' Everett said.
``He did his job to get in scoring position. I think he maybe was a
little confused whether to take the base or not. He's learning. You
just have to live and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The blame can't all be placed on Barker. The Astros went back to
their bad habit of late, failing to come up with a clutch hit. A
day after pounding out 17 hits, they were limited to nine on
Tuesday, six of them singles.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox were able to stage a pair of rallies, the latter
coming on Magglio Ordonez's two-run homer in the sixth inning that
wiped out a 3-2 Astros lead. Ordonez drove in three runs in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Astros righthander Shane Reynolds (7-6) lost his third straight
decision, allowing four runs and seven hits in 7 innings. A 19-game
winner a year ago, Reynolds has struggled over the last month. He
is 2-5 with a 5.48 ERA in his last seven starts dating to May 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just struggling right now. It's just I made a mistake, and
they capitalized on it,'' said Reynolds, who retired the first
eight batters he faced. ``I'm not walking a lot of people or
anything like that. I made two mistakes, gave up two runs in two
different innings, and that was enough for the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sox pitcher Jaime Navarro (5-4) held the Astros to
three runs and eight hits over eight innings to win his third
straight decision. Navarro coaxed the Astros into 14 ground-ball
outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was keeping the ball down and had a lot of life on it,''
Chicago manager Jerry Manuel said. ``His ball seemed to explode.
(Jeff) Bagwell is a great hitter, and he struck him out twice. That
was dominant stuff he had tonight. He's been pretty consistent this
year. He's evolving into that guy that we all hoped he would
become.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had taken a 3-2 lead in the sixth inning on Everett's
one-out solo homer, his fourth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox regained the lead off Reynolds when Frank Thomas
hit his second double with one out in the sixth and Ordonez
followed with his club-high 11th home run. Ordonez also had an RBI
groundout in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who went 2-for-3, collected his first major-league RBI
when he hit a two-out single just inside the first-base line in the
fourth to score Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago responded in the bottom half of the inning with two
runs. Mike Caruso led off with a bunt single and moved to third on
Thomas' double off the left-field wall. Ordonez hit a grounder to
second to tie the game at 1, and Carlos Lee followed with a single
to put the White Sox ahead 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spiers, who had two hits Tuesday and has five in the past
two games, tripled in the fifth and scored on a single by Bagwell
to tie the game at 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
