<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATM-SCAM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE WARN ATM-CARD THEFT VICTIMS NOT TO GIVE OUT PINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A rash of bank-card thefts has hit Seattle office
buildings, police say, but the worst part is that the victims are
unwittingly aiding the thieves in emptying their bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Since December, the Seattle Police Department's West Precinct
has had 55 complaints of stolen automatic teller machine (ATM)
cards, said Jim Pugel, precinct commander.
</P>
<P>
   In 25 of those cases, the thief followed up with a telephone
call to the victim. Pretending to be a police detective or bank
security officer, the thief asked victims for their personal
identification numbers (PIN).
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the stolen card and the personal identification
numbers, they then are free to empty the victim's bank account.
</P>
<P>
   A common scenario is for the thief to distract the receptionist,
getting the receptionist to leave the desk. The thief then rifles
through the purse and takes the purse or the wallet or sometimes
just the card.
</P>
<P>
   Pugel emphasized that police and security officers ``never,
never'' ask citizens for PIN numbers and that citizens should never
give them out over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   In the 25 phone calls made to victims after their cards were
stolen, the caller claimed to be bank security officers 21 times.
Claims to be a police officer were made four times, Pugel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sound very credible,'' he said. The call usually is made
within an hour of the time the ATM card is stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sometimes may state they have a person in custody and
will be returning the victim's purse or wallet or card, but just
need to get the PIN to verify they have an account and have the
right card,'' Pugel said.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Eric Sano, head of the police department's check forgery
unit, said victims usually end up getting most of their money
refunded by the bank. But it takes a while and in the meantime the
victims are seriously incovenienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't write checks. Their credit is damaged.'' And the
bank ends up having to take the loss, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The west precinct covers Magnolia, Queen Anne, downtown Seattle
and Pioneer Square.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
