A8251 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOBE-SYSTEMS-SPI &LR;      06-09 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOBE-SYSTEMS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOBE TO ADD NEW DIVISION IN SEATTLE, FOCUSING ON INTERNET
PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Adobe Systems Inc., the San Jose, Calif.-based maker
of publishing and graphics software, on Tuesday announced a new
corporate division in Seattle that will help the company strengthen
its move to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe, which already has about 500 employees in its Seattle
office, plans to add at least 50 jobs to the new division _ called
the Internet Products Group _ by the end of the year. But Hank
Skorny, who is overseeing the new division, indicated that the
number of new hires could be a lot higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``As fast as we can grow, we will grow,'' said Skorny, adding
that he will rely on his contacts in the Seattle technology
community to ramp up recruiting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, Adobe cut 9 percent of its worldwide work force
in a move to reposition the company for the Internet. Only about 10
of the 250 jobs cut were in Seattle. And Tuesday's announcement to
focus the new direction of the company in Seattle could be seen as
a boost to the local technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   It's also another sign that technology companies, some based as
far away as Silicon Valley and London, view Seattle as a hotspot
for e-commerce and Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe, which makes the PhotoShop, PageMaker and Illustrator
software products, joins an impressive list of companies trying to
latch on to the energy in Seattle's Internet and e-commerce
sectors. In March, Getty Images, a company that sells electronic
photographs over the Internet, moved its headquarters from London
to Seattle to be closer to the budding e-commerce community.
</P>
<P>
   The new companies include some of the biggest names in their
fields. HomeGrocer.com, Onvia.com and Concur Technologies are among
those who have moved here in the past couple of years for reasons
such as tax benefits and quality of life issues.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Washington Software Alliance, more than 2,500
technology companies are located in the state, up from 1,600 in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significant portion of Adobe's growth and revenue in the
future will be driven out of Seattle,'' said Skorny, who before
taking over the Internet Products Group served as senior director
of publishing at Adobe.
</P>
<P>
   Like Microsoft and other old-guard software companies, Adobe
Systems _ founded in 1982 _ is going through growing pains as it
attempts to embrace the Internet revolution.
</P>
<P>
   While that repositioning has caused some uncertainty at Adobe's
San Jose headquarters, it could mean a potential boom for the
company's Seattle office. In many respects, Adobe is placing a big
bet on Seattle and its burgeoning Internet community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at Seattle as an up-and-coming player with a lot of
vibrant, young energy,'' said Skorny. ``There is a certain edge
that the Seattle Internet community has.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Adobe's creation of a new division in Seattle caught some
analysts by surprise. ``I really don't know why they are choosing
Seattle,'' said Steve Shepich, an industry analyst at Olde Discount
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Since Adobe recently announced that it was consolidating part of
its international division in San Jose, Shepich said it would make
sense for the company to expand the Internet Products Group there
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there really that much more talent available in Seattle?''
</P>
<P>
   Skorny, who said Adobe plans to host a recruiting ``open house''
at its Seattle facility Thursday from 4-8 p.m., firmly believes the
talent pool in Seattle is stronger than other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least in my experience the availability of (technology
workers) in Seattle is greater than Silicon Valley,'' Skorny said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent study by the Washington Software Alliance,
there are currently 10,000 open positions in the state's high-tech
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe's Internet Products Group will be responsible for
expanding the company's GoLive Web-creating products which it
acquired earlier this year. It will also develop new technologies,
products and services for creating and assembling Web pages.
Expanding into the areas of Internet publishing is a smart and
necessary move for the company, said Shepich.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a huge area of growth potential for these
guys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Vleeschhouwer, an analyst at Merrill Lynch Global
Securities, said Adobe is in the process of adopting a new business
model that is tied directly to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to drive as much attention as they can to
their Web strategy,'' said Vleeschhouwer, adding that the cost
savings from the recent round of job cuts would be transferred to
the Internet division. ``Adobe believes _ and I think rightly so _
that they are well positioned to take advantage of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Two computer scientists from the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center
founded Adobe 17 years ago. The company, which now has revenues of
almost $1 billion, opened a Seattle office in 1994 after it
acquired desktop software developer Aldus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 0124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8253 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS &LR;      06-09 1970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Humility comes easily, naturally. It fits in San Antonio. It fits
the Spurs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other cities are glamorous, celebrated in song and in the media.
Other teams expect greatness, championships, awards. San Antonio
extols its charms more subtly. The Spurs seek their rewards more
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   They could have tried to build a champion by collecting as many
superstar talents as they could find and hiring a flashy coach in
Armani, then just assumed they had championship mettle.
</P>
<P>
   But they have tried the wrong route before. They cast David
Robinson in a do-everything, beat-everyone role that fit him
poorly. They tried coaches with long rsums, from Larry Brown to
Jerry Tarkanian. They even sold their soul for the horribly miscast
Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   That could never work. That would not have been San Antonio. It
would not have been the Spurs. This is the city whose
internationally known symbol is a monument to courage in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo City could win only this way.
</P>
<P>
   It seems fitting now that the Spurs began the best season of
their 26-year, two-league history by playing terribly. Their
greatest players, Robinson and Tim Duncan, came as the result of
horrible slides into the draft lottery. But the Spurs believed
themselves ready to contend.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the season started, we knew we could be a heck of a
team,'' coach/general manager Gregg Popovich said. ``We won 56
games the year before and improved our team with some of the guys
we added. So we had great expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' 6-8 start is now considered a footnote in their
history in the making. It was less significant than a 1996-97
season so horrible that they lucked into the first pick of the
draft that brought them Duncan, or even the 1995 Western Conference
finals loss to the Rockets that left them hungry for another
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we played a game, a lot of people picked us,'' guard
Avery Johnson said. ``When we got off to a bad start, they went
back to calling us soft again and overrated and stuff like that.
Everybody backed off us when we were 6-8.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs did not become so unstoppable in spite of their
slow start. The Spurs became the league's best team in the regular
season and, with second- and third-round playoff sweeps, the most
successful postseason team to this point since the 1988-89 Lakers
because of their slow start.
</P>
<P>
   When the Spurs arrived at Compaq Center in early March with a
losing record, the Rockets were considered a suitable measuring
stick, a more worthy title contender. Popovich was thought to be
running out of time as coach. Spurs fans, still angry about
Popovich's dismissal of coach Bob Hill on the day of Robinson's
return from the injured list in 1997, were calling for his job with
almost every misstep.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Mario Elie, Steve Kerr and Jerome Kersey was not
working. Elie was still coming off the bench, with Jaren Jackson
struggling as a starting guard. The big men were struggling with
the passes necessary to get Kerr going. Kersey was working as a
backup power forward, rather than in his more comfortable spot as a
small forward. And the wrinkles Popovich had added to the offense
were ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We jumped right into the season, and all of our timing was
really off,'' Robinson said. ``Tim and I weren't working well
together at all. It was hard to carry that continuity from last
season. Plus, our offense was just awful. I have to give Popovich
credit, because he simplified our offense. He said, `Let's do some
basic things _ let's do some pick-and-rolls; let's go inside.
Instead of trying to fool everybody, let's go right at them.' That
made us do a better job. A lot of it was just getting our rhythm
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs had lost five of their previous seven games heading
into the March 2 game at Houston. But attacking that game as if the
championship was on the line, they won 99-82.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turning point was definitely at Houston,'' Robinson said.
``We came together that game. A lot of it is because Avery and
Mario are from Houston. That was their big show. Both played really
well that game. That was the turnaround. That was the point we
said, `We're not going to throw this season away.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston was playing real well at that time. We said, `If we
could come in here and win this game, we can go anywhere and win
games.' That was the point where everyone had faith in one another.
We went on a nice little run after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the win over the Rockets, the Spurs won nine
straight games. Including their 11-1 postseason streak to the NBA
Finals, they are 42-6 since their stumbling start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a slow start, of course, but nobody lost any confidence
in each other,'' Duncan said. ``We knew what we could do. We
started turning it around and winning games. People got more
confident in what we were doing and believing in what we could do.
It was a long process of everybody trusting each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But the long process had a sudden turnaround, as if the
struggles forced the Spurs to take stock and discover the potential
that was going unfulfilled. Popovich never addressed his personal
situation, and it will never be clear how much rope he had left.
But there was little doubt the Spurs were at the breaking point,
ready to go either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were talking about (firing) Pop,'' Elie said. ``The team
came together starting in Houston. We got together as a unit and
said, `Hey, we're better than we're playing.' We got on an amazing
roll.''
</P>
<P>
   They have not stopped rolling since.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs had little choice but to be humble.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Robinson and Duncan were first-pick-of-the-draft
selections, the sort of franchise centers who immediately make
teams contenders and gave the Spurs the two greatest season
turnarounds in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   But other than Sean Elliott _ and he has been traded three times
(including a deal to the Rockets that was canceled when he failed
his physical) _ the rest of the Spurs were castoffs or role
players, passed around or kicked out of the league repeatedly. Most
went from team to team, league to league, even country to country
trying to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   Modesty comes naturally. Egos are easily held in check. Effort
is a given.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not being a lottery pick, not going top 10 or first round,
these are guys who worked their way from the bottom to the top,''
Elie said. ``We appreciate where we're at. That's the problem with
a lot of young players. They get stuff handed to them too early. We
have to work all the time. We have to improve. We keep a chip on
our shoulder because of the hard road we took.''
</P>
<P>
   And rather than seek blue-chip celebrities, the sort of big
names who filled the rosters of the now-beaten Lakers and Trail
Blazers, the Spurs came to believe in the role players they already
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last few years, we invested in one another,'' Robinson
said. ``We kept playing and said, `Hey, Avery, you may not be Jason
Kidd, but we love you, and we want you here.' And that's important.
Utah kept their players. They believed in those guys. They may not
be the most talented players in the league, but they invested in
those guys, and they play great together. That's the same way we
feel about Jaren Jackson, guys we're committed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Johnson is shooting accurately. Jackson has overcome
his struggles to become a dangerous sixth man. Malik Rose, at 6-6,
successfully battled the Lakers' Shaquille O'Neal and the Trail
Blazers' Brian Grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes back to one thing I saw that Avery and Sean
said,'' Portland guard Jim Jackson said. ``They believe in each
other. A lot of people say Avery can't hit that shot. But if they
swing the ball and Avery is open, they'll pass it to him and expect
Avery to make that shot. That's the way that team is.''
</P>
<P>
   For every Johnson, Jackson or Rose, the Spurs added a player
with veteran savvy. Kerr, Kersey and Elie were brought in to give
the Spurs added perimeter shooting around Duncan and Robinson and
defensive toughness to a team long labeled soft. Four games into
the season, in a postgame locker-room interview at Minnesota, Elie
ripped into Duncan and Robinson loud enough for both to hear,
setting a tone for the fire he would add.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I spoke up, I took a lot of flak for it,'' Elie said.
``But I knew we had a great team. I saw our big guys getting moved
around. I had to speak up and told them, `You guys have to play
better. If you guys play better, it's going to lift the other guys
around you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was shocked. But he was not angered or offended.
Instead, he seemed willing to accept Elie's point of view,
understanding the compliment implied in the expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't upset me, because I felt like he wanted to win,''
Robinson said. ``I don't have to get along with everybody. You do
have to be on the same page when it comes to this team. Mario is
just a different personality. He talks in the media. I wouldn't
talk in the media, but I said to Mario, `I don't care what you say;
just bring your ``A'' game. If you're going to talk, back it up.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done that for us. That's why I've never criticized him.
He's brought a lot to our team _ intensity and a pressure shooter
and a good defensive player. It was a little unusual for this team.
You don't have to be friends with everybody. You just have to be on
the same page with basketball. When you accomplish your goals, all
the little discomforts along the way don't seem quite as big.''
</P>
<P>
   At 37-13, the Spurs shared the best regular-season record in the
league with Utah but only now seem to be appreciated. When they
beat the Lakers, much of the national focus was on LA's
dysfunctional mix and unfulfilled potential. When they beat
Portland, the Trail Blazers' immaturity was blamed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs did not seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give us the `W,' and you can say whatever the hell you want,''
Popovich said. ``I don't care. Give us the `W,' and you can put the
respect anywhere. Put it in China. Put it in New Zealand. Just give
us the `W.'
</P>
<P>
   ``All that matters is what we do on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Spurs don't seem to give themselves credit for their
accomplishments. Asked about their consecutive sweeps in the
conference semifinals and finals, a feat matched only by the 1982
and 1989 Lakers, they routinely respond that sweeps are
inconsequential if not followed by a championship. Former Bulls
Kerr and Will Perdue said it is too soon to make comparisons to
previous NBA champions. Elie has said the team wins ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work our tails off every night,'' Robinson said.
``We're not an overwhelming team. Look at most of the games, and
they're very close games. We haven't been blowing everybody out. We
win all the close games, but yeah, they're close. My mom and wife
tell me, `We can't watch the games. You guys are killing us.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the situation is. We have to grind it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Spurs' last two wins have actually been routs and
San Antonio is going mad around them, Robinson says the team
remains determined to be a fitting, no-frills representative of a
city and franchise that remember what it means to lose. Humility
still comes easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that kept us in perspective is (that) in San
Antonio everybody is so excited,'' Robinson said. ``They're talking
about the race for the rings in the first round. They don't give
away rings in the first round. It helps us stay focused. We haven't
accomplished anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   They have accomplished a great deal, of course, more than any
Spurs team ever has. But it somehow seems appropriate that
Robinson, Duncan and Co. consider it nothing so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
