<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPLE-SLAYING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE FOUND DEAD IN DAY CARE AT WOMAN'S SEATTLE HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VANESSA HO  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For years, Patricia Whitfield's Mount Baker day care
bubbled with the laughter of neighborhood kids and offered a safe
place for working parents to drop off their children.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, it was the scene of a grisly triple homicide. It
began with a hysterical call to 911 and ended with a close-knit
neighborhood convulsed in grief.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and friends identified the victims as Whitfield, her
daughter Tizi Ingram, and Ingram's daughter, Champagne, believed to
be about 7 years old. Seattle police, however, would not identify
the victims, saying only that they believed they were a mother,
daughter and a granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Police Tuesday night said they had no suspects. When officers
arrived at the day care, which was also Whitfield's house in the
3200 block of South 34th Avenue, they found the two women in a
bedroom, and the little girl in another part of the four-bedroom
home. They were all shot, police say.
</P>
<P>
   Officers also found two babies: A 4- to 5-day-old infant, and a
4- to 11-month-old baby. They are believed to be Ingram's
daughters. Police spokeswoman Pam McCammon said the babies appeared
unharmed. They were transported to Seattle's Harborview Medical
Center for evaluation, a hospital spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:58 p.m., a hysterical person, believed to be a man, called
911, saying ``his sister and mother are dead,'' McCammon, the
police spokeswoman, said. Fire medics raced to the house and found
the victims dead from gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   McCammon said officers did not find a weapon and that detectives
had not mentioned the possibility of a murder-suicide. Neighbors
said Ingram's boyfriend had had run-ins with her five brothers, but
police, despite the presence of gang detectives, would not discuss
a possible motive.
</P>
<P>
   Friends said the boyfriend was jealous of the amount of time
Ingram spent with her family, and that her brothers had forbade him
from coming to the house.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution, officials at nearby John Muir Elementary shut
down the school, where classes ended at 3:15 p.m. Panicked parents
rushed to the school, but the vice principal told students on the
intercom to stay in their seats a few minutes longer. Later, they
exited through a back door.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesdasy, friends and neighbors of Patricia Whitfield waited in
a light rain under cloudy skies for the bodies to be removed from
the home. With ministers, they gathered at the nearby elementary
school to mourn the deaths. They hugged, cried and screamed ``No!''
in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   A distraught neighbor, Ray Rogers, 29 , said Whitfield had taken
care of him since he was 3 or 4 years old and remembered that she
``always had a love for children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it,'' he said, pulling his hair and crying.
``There's no motive whatsoever. This is a quiet neighborhood. You
can't begin to believe why, why.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors described Whitfield, who was divorced, as a tough,
kind, hard-working woman who raised a daughter and five sons alone.
She also worked as a Seattle Times customer service representative.
</P>
<P>
   Some neighbors said they practically grew up at Whitfield's
house, which, with her large family, was always a welcoming
neighborhood hangout.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son played with her grandson, and I grew up with her
kids,'' recalled neighbor Michael Jackson. ``It's tragic to hear
something like that went on over there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was well-kept, very respectful and a hard-driven single
parent with all those boys. She had a respect from the
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Wilkerson said she was one of Whitfield's closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were real neighbors,'' she said. ``We lived right across
the alley from each other. We shared butter, we shared eggs, we
talked every morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson's daughter, Arnell, agreed that Whitfield was a kind
person.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very motivated. She was always happy, but then she was
always going through something, you know, like family situations,''
said the younger Wilkerson.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Wilkerson recalled Whitfield's daughter, Tizi Ingram,
and her daughter, Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl had ``bright eyes the size of half dollars,
velvety skin. She was an angel,'' Wilkerson said. Champagne's
mother, Tizi, was a Franklin High graduate who honored in math and
also helped her mother at the day care.
</P>
<P>
   Tizi Ingram ``had a gentle, quiet spirit,'' J.J. Wilkerson said.
``She was a really smart young lady.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that if something happened to Pat, I could
talk to her daughter,'' she said. ``But her daughter's gone, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As authorities removed the bodies from the home, neighbors
watched and cried. When Champagne was taken out, anyone who hadn't
yet cried, began to.
</P>
<P>
   ``They executed her. Who in the world would execute a little
girl?'' asked a a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The King County Medical Examiner will do autopsies Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said Whitfield had run her day care for at least 10
years. Kathy Spears, spokeswoman for the state Department of Social
and Health Services, said Whitfield had had a license in the past,
but closed her facility in 1996. Last year, Whitfield received
another license and reopened her day care, Spears said.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Holcomb, who has lived in the area more than 30 years,
said her granddaughter used to attend Whitfield's day care and that
this was the first crime to occur there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of frightening,'' she said. ``This is close to
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Rico, a stand-up comic who prefers using only his first name,
has lived near the victims on and off for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a smart woman,'' he said. ``She was a beautiful and
strong black woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer reporters Phuong Le, Judd Slivka, Lisa
Stiffler, Scott Sunde, Jane Hadley and Mike Barber contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
