<SLUG> BC-SHERIFF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIRDRESSER WHO TANGLED WITH SHERIFF TO GIVE FREE MAKEOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MEGAN RYSZKOWSKI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Scottsdale hairstylist who scuffled with Sheriff Joe Arpaio in
a restaurant parking lot will have to snip his way out of his legal
tangle.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Huskisson avoided standing trial for aggravated assault by
entering a plea agreement Tuesday that includes giving free
haircuts and makeovers for inmates released from the county jail
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean's very talented. He suggested this after spending one
night in jail,'' said Huskisson's attorney, Michael Terribile. ``He
wants to help women coming out of jail by giving them makeovers.
Why not utilize his talents?''
</P>
<P>
   Huskisson, 27, who works at Giggles Hair Salon in Scottsdale,
normally charges up to $200 for makeovers.
</P>
<P>
   He was sentenced to 50 hours of community service, 18 months of
supervised probation, one day in jail and ordered to pay $40 a
month in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Huskisson pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of disorderly
conduct, which carries a maximum prison term of six months. In
exchange, prosecutors dropped the more serious charges of
aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the sentence is heavier than necessary,'' said
Terribile, who asked the judge for only community service hours and
not probation. ``If it had been anybody else that Sean would have
been obnoxious with, this case would be filed in city court. It was
bad luck he happened to run into Sheriff Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskisson was arrested last July after he punched Arpaio and the
sheriff's top aide, Dave Hendershott, as he was leaving the parking
lot of When in Naples Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Huskisson said he had been drinking with some buddies to
celebrate the birth of his first child and was about to get behind
the wheel of his car when Hendershott attempted to stop him.
Huskisson became agitated and hit Hendershott, a police report
says.
</P>
<P>
   When Arpaio approached, witnesses claimed that Huskisson became
even more angry and punched Arpaio in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to extend my apologies,'' Huskisson told Judge
Mark Aceto of Maricopa County Superior Court on Tuesday. ``This has
been an embarrassment to me and my family. I meant no harm. I had
too much to drink and I'm very sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskisson recorded a blood-alcohol level of 0.187 at the time of
his arrest. Arizona law presumes that anyone with a reading of 0.10
or above is intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy County Attorney Louis Stalzer said the Sheriff's Office
welcomed Huskisson's offer of haircut and makeover services as part
of his community service. But he told the judge that Arpaio wanted
Huskisson to provide his services within the jail and Tent City.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, however, decided that Huskisson could perform the
service out of his salon. &QL; 
Megan Ryszkowski can be reached at (602) 444-7815 or at
megan.ryszkowski(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
