<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNOVA-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNOVA STOCK DIPS AS EARNINGS FALL BELOW EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares of Unova Inc., a $2 billion industrial
technology products maker, fell 7 percent Tuesday after the company
announced that second-quarter earnings would fall short of
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of analysts by First Call Inc. had pegged earnings at
14 cents a share for the second quarter. But the company said late
Monday that earnings would be in the 6 cents-a-share range. That
would be in line with first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock closed Tuesday at $13.375, down $1, on
trading of 491,000 shares, nearly four times the average daily
volume. That's well below the 52-week high of $23.75.
</P>
<P>
   Woodland Hills-based Unova blamed the lackluster performance on
the same problems that impacted first-quarter earnings, which came
in 8 cents lower than in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Unova said it is still experiencing glitches with a new computer
system used to track orders, manufacturing and deliveries at its
Intermec Technologies subsidiary in Everett, Wash. And it is
dealing with diminished sales and downsizing at the recently
acquired Cincinnati machine tool division that makes equipment used
by other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Problems associated with getting orders shipped on time at
Intermec has forced Unova to hire temporary workers and maintain
higher inventory levels, both expensive propositions.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to correct the problems could stretch into the third and
fourth quarters, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Unova has two basic product lines. The company makes
manufacturing systems and machine tools for the automotive,
aerospace and general metalworking markets. Its high-tech
operations make automated data collection, mobile computing,
wireless network and radio frequency identification systems for a
variety of uses.
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Koerber, Unova's chief financial officer, said turmoil in
Asian and Latin American financial markets is impacting the
Cincinnati operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the U.S. has looked like it was in great shape, factory
utilization in North America was at an eight-year low,'' he said.
``Farming exports came down last year and with that, obviously, the
farmers do not buy capital equipment like tractors.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the company said that at the end of last month, its
backlog was at a record level, helped by large systems contracts
won at the beginning of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Alexander Paris at Barrington Research in Chicago said
the problems are fixable; it is just taking longer than expected to
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are kind of temporary problems. Demand is good, and
they've got good products,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unova has operations in seven states, Canada and five European
countries. The company employs about 10,000 people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
