<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALKING DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers, contrary to popular
opinion, don't need a wakeup call. What's the use after they've
slept through a dozen?
</P>
<P>
   They need a fire alarm. And the flicker of flames and a whiff of
smoke to really give their hearts a jolt.
</P>
<P>
   They continue to excuse their .500 start with variations on
``There's a long way to go.'' The latest was manager Davey
Johnson's lullaby _ ``It's still very early'' _ after Monday's loss
to the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   It's later than they think.
</P>
<P>
   June is baseball's most deceptive month. When it begins, the
season really is young. Hall of Famers are batting .200 and rookies
are hitting .400. Luck and schedule strength haven't evened out
yet. When it ends, you're making plans for the All-Star break. And
the newspapers are handing out the C-minuses on the midterm report
cards.
</P>
<P>
   That quickly, you can go from slow-starting to slow-roasted.
</P>
<P>
   June cooked the Dodgers last year. It was a frantic month off
the field, where they dumped Hideo Nomo, lost Ramon Martinez to an
arm injury and fired manager Bill Russell and GM Fred Claire. It
was a snoozer on the field, where they kept a .500 pace and slipped
12{ games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   June could kill them this year. Only more softly.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Tuesday's game, they were 2-4 for the month and stuck
at .500. And they'd better not be fooled by a quick glance at the
schedule ahead. Oakland, Pittsburgh, Philadelphia and San Diego
come up next. Soft touches? Look again.
</P>
<P>
   The A's, Pirates and Phillies have better records than the
Dodgers. Check the standings if you don't believe it. The Padres,
for their part, will come to town bearing a grudge. Or have you
forgotten their April win over Kevin Brown?
</P>
<P>
   After San Diego, the Dodgers will face San Francisco for the
first time this season, just about the time the Giants get Barry
Bonds back. Then June ends with two more games against the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Remember what Eric Karros said after his throwing error
contributed to a May 9 loss to Florida: ``I don't think we've been
eliminated yet.'' In other words, Don't panic. The Dodgers were
17-14 then, in second place, 1{ games behind the Giants. No cause
for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   It's exactly one month later. They've gone 11-15, slipped to
third and lost 3{ games in the standings. Arizona has jumped over
them and the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' words are still technically correct: They haven't been
eliminated yet. But much more of this and they're in trouble. Look
at their history.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers have won pennants after sub-.500 Aprils.
They've won pennants after sub-.500 Augusts. They've won pennants
after sub-.500 Septembers and Octobers. But they've never won a
pennant after a losing June or July.
</P>
<P>
   That cliche, ``strength up the middle,'' applies to the schedule
as well as the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Either the Dodgers don't know it, or they're not good enough to
do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   Is this all there is to Todd Hundley, a .226 hitter and a .137
thrower?
</P>
<P>
   Is Eric Young a winner's leadoff hitter, with his .365 on-base
percentage?
</P>
<P>
   Is Devon White's groin pull a case of bad luck, or something to
be expected from a 36-year-old center fielder?
</P>
<P>
   Is there really somebody called Chance Sanford on the roster, or
is he a Think Blue Week winner?
</P>
<P>
   If Brown's arrival really improved the pitching staff, then why
are the Dodgers on their way to the franchise's highest staff ERA
since 1958 in the Coliseum?
</P>
<P>
   By June 30, we should have an answer.
</P>
<P>
   The wakeup calls keep coming. The Dodgers are sleeping with the
covers over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   There was the day St. Louis' Shawon Dunston charged the Dodgers'
Jamie Arnold. That was supposed to light a fire under the Dodgers.
That was May 23. They're 6-8 since then.
</P>
<P>
   There was the firing of pitching coach Charlie Hough. That was
supposed to turn up the heat. That was May 26. They're 5-7 since
then.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Chan Ho Park-Tim Belcher brawl. That was supposed
to kick-start the Dodgers. That was Saturday. They're 0-3 since
then.
</P>
<P>
   What's it going to take to rouse these late sleepers? How about
a good look at the schedule? The season is getting away from them.
</P>
<P>
   A June snooze is as bad as a June swoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
