<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES GET JUMP IN GAME 1
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-STARS-SABRES-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For the favored Stars, the night was a series of missed
opportunities, a boatload of chances that went for naught.
</P>
<P>
   For the underdog Sabres, it was the continuation of a remarkable
Cinderella story, a chance early on to say, in essence, ``Take
that, all you nonbelievers.''
</P>
<P>
   The hero of Game 1 of the Stanley Cup finals Tuesday night was
Jason Woolley, a 29-year-old defenseman who has a keen sense of
when opportunity is knocking.
</P>
<P>
   It was Woolley, on a nice feed from forward Curtis Brown, who
came through for Buffalo, charging down the slot and firing a
one-timer between the legs of Dallas goalie Ed Belfour at 15:30 of
overtime to lift the Sabres to a 3-2 victory at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is we can't get swept now, anyways,'' quipped
Sabres coach Lindy Ruff, referring to the fact that the Eastern
Conference team has been swept in the finals the last three years.
``We eliminated that in one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to maybe sneak another one out of here but . . . the
East has been swept the last three years. We just won one for the
East.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two periods heavily favored the Stars. The combination
of a nine-day layoff between games and a young squad's Cup jitters
resulted in the Sabres struggling early and spending far too much
time in the penalty box. They were shorthanded for 11:42 of the
first 29:34. Fortunately for them, they had Dominik Hasek. Though
hampered by a sore groin, the goalie was utterly sensational at
times.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull put the Stars on the board at 10:17 of the first
period during a power play, his sixth goal of the postseason. But
midway through the third period, which was awful for the Stars and
meant a whole new life for the Sabres, Buffalo tied it on Stu
Barnes's strike. Wayne Primeau gave Buffalo its first lead of the
game at 13:37 on the power play. The desperate Stars rallied with
49 seconds left in regulation when Jere Lehtinen beat Hasek, tying
the game at 2-2 and sending it into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Then Woolley pulled the Sabres through.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had a chance to win midway through the overtime on a
power play that came courtesy of a foolish boarding penalty taken
by Geoff Sanderson, who drilled Richard Matvichuk from behind at
9:06.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres staved off the penalty, and Sanderson, coming out of
the box, took off up ice with the puck and blasted a shot that
Belfour turned back. It was Sanderson who was denied by Belfour on
a breakaway with a chance to put the Sabres up, 3-1, at 16:50 of
the third. A few minutes later, Lehtinen tied it.
</P>
<P>
   But there were so many missed opportunities for the Stars. Too
much Hasek, too little finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our team played a very, very strong hockey game,''
said Stars coach Ken Hitchcock. ``I thought we went a little bit
flat when they scored their first goal and we were in a little bit
of shock because I think that certainly in the first period and
second period that's as sound a hockey game as we've played. To
give up those two goals was a little bit of a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Mike Modano, who had an excellent game, said the
loss was particularly painful because of the team's play in the
third and the fact that Dallas was only 1 for 10 on the man
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third period was a bad period,'' he said. ``We got away
from our style of play. We lost our edge and let them back into the
game. We had our chances to put it away but we didn't take
advantage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
