</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOX OUT OF THEIR LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
 BB-RED SOX-EXPOS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ This interleague stuff didn't take long to get old,
did it?
</P>
<P>
   Seems like only yesterday that the Red Sox were knocking down
the big shots in the American League with an ease bordering on
insouciance.
</P>
<P>
   But remove them from their usual little milieu, and suddenly the
Sox have taken on the aspect of accidental tourists, fumbling for
their passports, stumbling on the language, and bumbling down paths
that looked harmless in the guidebooks.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox took another detour in the wrong direction Tuesday
night with their fourth straight loss, a 5-1 beating administered
by the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have lost four in a row to National League teams, two to
the Braves, the so-called America's Team, and now two to the Expos,
a team that only 7,233 Canadians chose to call their own Tuesday
night in Olympic Stadium. And that number shrinks when you count
the Vermonters in the house who showed up to root for the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason the Sox remain in first is that their closest
pursuers in the AL East, the New York Yankees, are having their own
crossover problems. The Bombers blew a 5-0 lead and fell to the
Phillies, 11-5, their third straight defeat to their National
League cousins.
</P>
<P>
   No one appeared more lost here Tuesday night than Jeff Frye, the
miscast third baseman, or Jim Corsi, the downcast reliever, during
the Expos' three-run uprising in the eighth inning that took the
air out of a pitching duel in which the Sox trailed only 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Frye, playing because John Valentin was laid up with a sore
groin, couldn't get Vladimir Guerrero's chopper out of his glove
after a ground single by Rondell White began the inning against
Corsi, who had taken over after seven strong innings by Tim
Wakefield. Wakefield, who allowed just five hits while striking out
nine, wound up paying dearly for one misspent knuckler, the one
Guerrero drove for a two-run home run in the sixth to wipe out a
1-0 Sox lead.
</P>
<P>
   With two on and none out against Corsi, Manny Martinez bunted
the runners over _ the sacrifice bunt still being an art form
practiced with some degree of competence in the National League _
and Corsi issued an intentional walk to Shane Andrews, loading the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   Corsi fell behind, 3-and-1, to the next hitter, Chris Widger,
who had entered the game batting .163 (7 for 43) with runners in
scoring position but drove a full-count fastball to left for a
two-run single that made it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   After another base hit by Mike Mordecai and a fly out, Frye
bobbled Orlando Cabrera's grounder to third, then threw late to
second on an attempted force as another run scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 3 feet away from being the goat or the hero,'' said
Corsi, who lately has had the look of a pitcher who should be
wearing a bell around his neck. ``The ball's moving good, the mound
feels good, I just have to get them to hit it at people. I can't
control where they hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be true, but Expos pitchers have had no such difficulty
with Sox hitters. Rookie righthander Dan Smith, making his big
league debut Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, gave up a run in the first inning on a
single to Jose Offerman, a double by Brian Daubach, and a single by
Nomar Garciaparra. He then set down the next 20 Sox batters until
being lifted for a pinch hitter in the seventh, finishing with nine
strikeouts while not walking a man.
</P>
<P>
   In the series opener Monday, another kid, former Sox prospect
Carl Pavano, retired 18 of 19 in one stretch. In their last five
games, the Sox are batting .199 (39 for 196) as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to play behind a guy who has that type of intensity
and tempo,'' Expos manager Felipe Alou said of Smith, a 23-year-old
righthander from Girard, Kan., who until this season had a losing
record in the minor leagues. ``You don't have to be Pedro Martinez
or Kevin Brown. Just throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially on a night when Boston batters were missing most of
them. In all, 13 Red Sox went down on strikes, including the last
four, the final three succumbing to Expos closer Ugueth Urbina, who
has a name like a Secretary-General of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach, the Belleville Basher, fanned three times. Garciaparra
fanned to end the game. The first three batters in the order _
Offerman, Damon Buford, and Daubach _ combined to whiff seven
times.
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of numbers hardly make for conversation pieces,
which apparently is why most of the Sox who played Tuesday night,
with the exception of Wakefield, Corsi, and catcher Jason Varitek,
didn't stray from the shelter of the players-only lounge. Since
they couldn't hit _ which is an active verb _ the Sox must have
figured they didn't have much use for adjectives, adverbs, or (a
Jimy Williams favorite) gerunds, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some good at-bats in the first inning, then he retired
a bunch in a row,'' said manager Williams, who threw extra batting
practice for Varitek and rookie Trot Nixon but might need to
schedule double sessions this afternoon if every Sox batter who's
struggling shows up for extra tutoring. ``We didn't sniff too much
after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good hitters. They'll come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they don't? Well, there's always Pedro. It's his turn
Wednesday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
