<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8272 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-HNS &LR;      06-09 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ The word had come up early, and it had become a sore point
with a No. 7 seed that had made such a remarkable run through the
Eastern Conference, only to be told once again it didn't belong.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday night, then, Lindy Ruff brought it up himself. All of a
sudden, it didn't sound so bad in light of the Buffalo Sabres' 3-2
overtime win over the Dallas Stars in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup
Finals at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is we can't get swept now,'' the Sabres coach
said with a smile. ``We eliminated that in one night.''
</P>
<P>
   One long and intense night, ending with the heavily favored
Stars contemplating their mortality in a series that no longer
looks so one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   Just seconds after Dominik Hasek made the last of his 35 saves,
robbing Dallas' Pat Verbeek from point-blank, Jason Woolley ripped
a shot from the high slot that got under Dallas' Ed Belfour 15
minutes, 30 seconds into overtime. Given little chance against the
two-time Presidents' Trophy winners, the Sabres drew first blood.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 is here Thursday night, and suddenly a Stars team many
deemed capable of sweeping this series turns its thoughts to
earning a split of the first two games at home.
</P>
<P>
   For that, they can thank Hasek, who kept his team in the game as
the Sabres weathered two periods of intense pressure before
beginning to turn things their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as their goaltender, if we have to get 70 (shots) to
score three, we'll get 70,'' Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said after
watching his team come up dry on nine of 10 power plays. ``We have
to find a way to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolley's shot capped an evening that offered a bit of something
for everyone. Hasek stopped all but those two Stars shots but gave
up the tying goal with less than a minute remaining in regulation.
His teammates managed only 24 shots on Belfour, but that would be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had the best of it for two periods, outshooting the
Sabres 23-9 and keeping the play in Buffalo's end most of the way.
To that point, the Sabres looked like the low seed that entered
these playoffs with limited expectations, but Dallas had only a 1-0
lead on Brett Hull's first-period goal to show for its trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could have gotten that second goal, we might have been
able to open it up a little more,'' Hitchcock said. ``But they were
able to hang in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Things changed quickly in the third period. First, Stu Barnes
fired a shot from about 20 feet that beat Belfour high and to the
glove side, tying the score at 8:33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we went into a little bit of shock after that first
goal,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   A little more than five minutes later, Wayne Primeau put Buffalo
ahead when he poked a rebound past Belfour at 13:37. That was
looking like the game-winner until the final minute of regulation,
when the Stars' No. 1 line came through again.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Mike Modano went behind the net, turned and found
Jere Lehtinen in front of Hasek. Lehtinen took a perfect pass and
slipped it by Hasek low and under the goalie's glove at 19:11,
sending the game to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas outshot the Sabres 7-5 in the extra period, but Woolley's
was the only one that counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have that many chances, that many just-abouts,
sometimes those things come back and haunt you,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Any concerns the Stars would be flat coming off the emotional
seven-game series with Colorado were quelled early. Dallas took the
offensive from the start and dominated the first period, keeping
the puck in the Sabres' end most of the 20 minutes and outshooting
Buffalo 11-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``The less time they have with the puck, the better for us,''
Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo might have broken through earlier. The Sabres got the
puck past Belfour at 4:53 of the second period, but winger Vaclav
Varada was called for goalie interference for bumping Belfour. The
Buffalo bench complained Belfour had taken a dive, and replays
seemed to support the contention, but the goal didn't count.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the Sabres' few real chances through 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Sabres were just a shot away going into the final
period of regulation in a game the Stars had dominated in just
about every other respect. That shot finally came 8:33 into the
third when Barnes pulled Buffalo even.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Stars' struggles with Hasek, Primeau's go-ahead
goal seemed to be more than enough to get the Sabres out with a
win. A few minutes later, Buffalo missed a chance to add to the
lead when Geoff Sanderson got loose on a breakaway, only to have
Belfour come up with a save that would look even bigger soon
enough.
</P>
<P>
   With the seconds ticking down, Lehtinen finally got the puck
past ``The Dominator,'' forcing the OT.
</P>
<P>
   ``The far side was open, and it was a great pass from Mike,''
Lehtinen said.
</P>
<P>
   But the game-winner would be considerably more elusive. Hasek's
save on Verbeek was a double deflection the goalie knocked away as
he rolled over.
</P>
<P>
   The near miss would haunt.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Thursday night takes on a whole new importance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
