<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8287 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-09 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ Listen, pardner. It's about time the NHL got this thing
right.
</P>
<P>
   Got the puck to stop here, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this isn't just the Lone Star State. It's also home
to the Fort Worth Brahmas, Austin Ice Bats, Amarillo Rattlers and
Corpus Christi IceRays.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the champion Houston Aeros of the IHL.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Jean-Claude, there is more professional hockey played
in the state of Texas than in all of Canada. You could look it up.
</P>
<P>
   Which was, of course, the vision of Lord Billy Bob Stanley way
back in the 19th century when he and some ol' boys actually
invented the game one slow day out on the prairie by using the butt
end of their rifles to swat buffalo chips through the open flap of
an abandoned tepee.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know, Billy Bob's missus gets sick and tired of
that big silver spit bucket from his chaw constantly tipping over
onto the floor of the ranch house and makes him give it away to a
friend who's going on a trail ride up north.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at long last, it returns.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas vs. Buffalo. Where are Troy Aikman, Emmitt Smith, Jim
Kelly and Thurman Thomas? It sounds like an old Super Bowl rematch.
We know how those turned out, and according to the form chart
Dallas should come out on top again. But that was football, and
this is, well, almost-summertime hockey in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek put on one of his trademark
late-game performances with circus stops, and then defenseman Jason
Woolley darted down the left side to beat Eddie Belfour 15:30 into
overtime and give Buffalo a 3-2 victory in the series opener.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure the Stars, who had the game under their thumb for more
than two periods and let it get away in front of a raucous home
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   And while you're at it, try to figure out this winter wonder
called the NHL, supposedly the pride and passion of all of frigid
Canada and the rest of the places above the Arctic Circle. It goes
belly up in frozen outposts like Winnipeg and Minneapolis and then
becomes the coolest thing in June since the double-wide
refrigerator in a land where an afternoon high of 80 degrees is
considered a cold snap.
</P>
<P>
   So along came Tuesday night at Reunion Arena, and the Stanley
Cup Finals will never be the same. This was more, much more, than
just faded jeans and ostrich-skin boots, 10-gallon hats and a few
thousand natives trying hard to pronounce names like Smehlik and
Zhitnik through a drawl.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup Texas-style is Hawaiian-print shirts, tank tops,
silicone and more heat than a mouthful of jalapeos. It's the Stars
taking the ice to the brain-splitting sounds of heavy-metal band
Pantera, whose drummer, Vinnie Paul, grew up in Arlington,
befriended Dallas defenseman Craig Ludwig a few years back and has
become an unofficial mascot of sorts. It's equal parts music video,
exotic dance club and Friday night football frenzy, all played on
an ice surface that melts faster than a frozen margarita at a
high-noon barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's June and it's Texas,'' said one NHL official. ``It
was 90 degrees down here two months ago, and the ice was already in
bad shape. You just deal with it the best way you know how.''
</P>
<P>
   Which maybe explains why the Sabres brought in No. 81, Miroslav
Satan, to play the wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask me, `Is that really your name?''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It's pronounced Shuh-tan. But you can call him Lucifer.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the favored Stars temporarily avoided the hell of
surrendering the home-ice advantage in the series opener when Jere
Lehtinen's tying goal with 49 seconds left in regulation time
rescued them.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Stars found themselves happy to be headed for overtime
after they had controlled most of the first 48 minutes with their
tight defensive style but managed only a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   When Dallas couldn't close the deal, the Sabres got back-to-back
goals from Stu Barnes and Wayne Primeau in the space of five
minutes, and Lehtinen's score could only force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Or Hasek-time. The Dominator was dominating. Stifling.
Suffocating. Impossible. Impenetrable.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had their OT chances. So many. Pat Verbeek was point
blank, and Hasek stopped him. Standing up and lying on his back
with the puck rolling across his chest, arms and legs flailing.
Then Woolley broke free, and it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you get that many chances, that many
just-abouts, it can turn on you,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``But I think this is the way the series is going to be. Both teams
passionate, both physical, both putting a lot on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Stanley Cup Finals Texas-style, extra spicy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
