<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CLIMB ALL OVER ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ This is what exhaustion looks like: Tom Lampkin pulling
into third base on a stand-up triple in the seventh inning, and
doing it a mile above sea level. The Mariners catcher, who admits
he's ``not the most fleet of foot,'' had suffered six innings of
foul tips and short hops before going for the triple in the seventh
Tuesday night, but he knew he had to get there.
</P>
<P>
   As physically tiring as Coors Field can be, it's even even
tougher psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballpark is so mentally draining,'' said Lampkin, a
former National Leaguer, after the Mariners downed the Colorado
Rockies, 10-5. ``I've played here so many times, and there are days
when you get a six-spot in the first inning, like we did tonight,
and they come back and score eight or nine runs in the eighth. When
you play games here, you've got to be ready to face that.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing it for the M's Tuesday night was right-hander Frankie
Rodriguez, who was making his first Seattle start. The Mariners
gave him a six-run lead, thanks in part to the first of two homers
by Ken Griffey Jr., who now is tied with Tampa Bay's Jose Canseco
for the major league lead with 22.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rockies went right to work on Rodriguez. They had scored
twice and had runners at first and second by the time they'd sent
five batters to the plate. Then Rodriguez escaped the inning by
getting Todd Helton to ground into a double play, preserving a 6-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin told his starter after the inning that although no lead
is safe in Colorado, all Rodriguez needed was to keep making
pitches; he was not hit hard in the inning. That's just what
Rodriguez did, working five innings and allowing only one more run.
He never once shook off Lampkin on pitch selection.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was buoyed by his early lead. It was exactly what he'd
envisioned when the Mariners claimed him off waivers from the
Minnesota Twins on May 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the other side, pitching against the Mariners, and
sometimes you would sit in the dugout and just wonder what it would
be like to pitch for them, with that kind of firepower behind
you,'' he said. ``It allows you to pitch aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   That Mariner offense overwhelmed Rockies rookie Mark Brownson,
who allowed consecutive singles to open the game, then took on
Griffey. He fell behind 2-and-0, then hung a 66 mph curveball that
Griffey ripped into the right field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get away with pitches,'' said Brownson. ``I
didn't get away with anything tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Butch Huskey pounded a solo homer, John Mabry
doubled, Lampkin singled him home, and two batters later, Rodriguez
had his first major league hit, a run-scoring single up the middle
that knocked out Brownson. Rodriguez, a former shortstop, said he
was too nervous to ask for the ball until the inning was over.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's single extended the hitting streak for Mariner
starting pitchers to four games. Coming into the game, all other
American League pitchers had combined for one hit.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only statistical oddity. With four innings to
finish up, Cloude recorded his first professional save.
</P>
<P>
   Also, first baseman David Segui committed just his second error
of the season, one more than he had all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Blinded by the setting sun in the second inning, Segui reached
for the throw by third baseman Mabry after a Vinny Castilla
grounder. He said he could not see it for the final 10 feet, and
was surprised he even caught it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played in anything that bad; it'll be real fun
tomorrow,'' said Segui, referring to today's game, which starts 90
minutes earlier than yesterday's. ``I couldn't even see Alex
(Rodriguez, the shortstop) or the third baseman. I've never been
scared to play first base before, but I was petrified that they
were going to hit it over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella was also uncomfortable, but for a different
reason. Like Lampkin, he's aware of the perils of mile-high
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel comfortable until the last out was made,''
Piniella said. ``I read some of (Rockies manager Jim) Leyland's
quotes, about how he `perseveres.' There's no question you have to
keep scoring runs here.''
</P>
<P>
   And as a pitching staff, you have to prevent them. Ironic, then,
that this is the park in which the Mariners finally brought their
earned run average below 6.00. It stands at 5.92 after a pair of
well-pitched games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the important thing,'' said Griffey of the staff's
success. ``Pitching's going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners (30-27) are three games over .500 for the first
time since the end of the 1997 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
