<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGR2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS OUTLAST DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers have this knack for
teasing, adding drama, that makes winning exciting and losing most
agonizing.
</P>
<P>
   Trenidad Hubbard was tagged out after oversliding second base
for the second out of the ninth inning, but Eric Young followed
with a solo homer off Texas Rangers closer John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't much matter, though, as Rafael Palmeiro singled in a
run in the top of the 13th and the Texas Rangers beat the Dodgers
7-6 Tuesday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It drops the Dodgers (28-29) below the .500 mark for the first
time since April 26 when they were 9-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the kind of season he's been having,'' said
Rangers manager Johnny Oates, who has used Palmeiro as a DH until
interleague play becasue of an injury. ``Every night I'm not sure
he's going tyo play until game time. But he's always there at the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had the leadoff batter on via walks in both the 11th
and 12th innings but couldn't get a two-out hit to score the
winning run. Mark McLemore began the winning rally with a one-out
single. He was erased on Rusty Greer's fielder's choice.
Pinch-hitter Gregg Zaun walked and Palmeiro singled sharply to
right field. Raul Mondesi had a chance to catch Greer at the plate
on Palmeiro's hit but his throw was up the third base line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make excuses, but the ground was a little wet
and the ball slipped,'' Raul Mondesi said. ``If I make a good throw
I get him, but I can't make perfect throws all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mills (1-1) allowed the two-out hit to Palmeiro in his
second inning of relief. It was the only run the Dodgers' bullpen
allowed in 81/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' Jeff Zimmerman (6-0) pitched two scoreless innings of
relief to remain undefeated. Mike Munoz pitched the 13th inning for
his first save.
</P>
<P>
   Young's second homer of the season represented Wetteland's
second blown save in 22 opportunities. It's similar to the Dodgers'
4-3 loss to Houston on May 20th when Tripp Cromer homered Astros
closer Billy Wagner in the 9th only to for the Dodgers to lose in
the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a flashback,'' Young said. ``We kept battling back, but
they kept battling back too _ but they got one more run.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers pulled within a run at 6-5 in the eighth inning on
Raul Mondesi's 19th homer of the season. Mondesi, who had a two-run
triple in the third inning, hit the first pitch Texas reliever Rob
Crabtree threw.
</P>
<P>
   Texas right fielder Juan Gonzalez hit his 16th homer of the
season in the first inning. He was ejected by home-plate umpire
Wally Bell in the ninth after being called out on strikes for the
second time in three innings. Though he walked straight to the
dugout, he left his bat at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were forced to try to come back for a second time
after the Rangers scored three times in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Darren Dreifort got the two outs that should
have been integral to success. The Rangers got the first two
runners on base in the fifth, but Dreifort retired Rusty Greer and
Gonzalez. Two-thirds of a great escape were done before sudden
nemesis Rafael Palmeiro batted.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro had three hits and an RBI in the series opener, and he
didn't let Dreifort off the hook either. Palmeiro singled to
right-center to score Tom Goodwin and tie the score 4-4. So close
to being the turning point for the Dodgers, it turned the other way
for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort didn't make it out of the inning. He had trouble
fielding Ivan Rodriguez's come-backer as the Rangers went ahead 5-4
on the infield single. Todd Zeile followed with a basehit to right
in which Mondesi fired to catcher Todd Hundley in an effort to get
Palmeiro at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The throw was in time, but Hundley, playing for the first time
since injuring his left wrist in a home plate collision against
Pittsburgh last Wednesday, dropped the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson summoned Jamie Arnold from the
bullpen to end another start for Dreifort prematurely. Dreifort
allowed six runs on nine hits in 42/3 innings. But the relief
contingent of Jamie Arnold, Mike Maddux, Doug Bochtler, Jeff Shaw
and Alan Mills didn't allow a run for the next 71/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Rangers activated Mike Morgan for the
start. The right-hander was on the 15-day disabled list with
inflammation in his right shin, had allowed eight earned runs in
two-thirds of an inning in his last start and opponents were
hitting .324 against him.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Dodgers until the third inning to inflict some
damage upon Morgan, and by then the Rangers had a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin led off the game with a single, stole second and
moved to third on Hundley's throwing error. He scored on Mark
McLemore's ground out. Gonzalez's put the Rangers ahead 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers added a run in the third on Greer's RBI double
before the Dodgers got to Morgan in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard, starting in center field for Devon White, doubled to
lead off the inning and eventually scored when Morgan's spikes got
caught on the mound for a balk. Jose Vizcaino and Gary Sheffield
walked and Mondesi tied the game 3-3 with a triple to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later the Dodgers took the lead and knocked Morgan out
of the game, which may have been the biggest detriment. Young
delivered the RBI single through the right side to put the Dodgers
up 4-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
