<HEADER>
A8316 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUPSTARSSI     06-09 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS POWERLESS IN GAME 1 LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 CUP STARS SIDEBAR-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Remember the powerless play of the Dallas Stars?
Remember the 2-of-22 performance against Edmonton and the 3-of-28
performance against St. Louis?
</P>
<P>
   It's baaaaaack.
</P>
<P>
   During the Sabres' 3-2 overtime victory Tuesday night, the Stars
were 1-of-10 on the power play. Buffalo all but lived in the
penalty box for the first two periods, but the best the Stars could
manage was a one-goal lead in the first period, earned by Brett
Hull on their first power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to move with the puck quick, get some shots and
traffic,'' Mike Modano said. ``When we do that, plays like the one
to Brett open up.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining nine opportunities, instead, closed down _
including a four-minute power play resulting from defenseman James
Patrick's high stick on the Stars' Pat Verbeek.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars sat on a one-goal lead until it wasn't a lead anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got a little bit in a situation where we tried to
protect in the third period,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock doesn't like his team sitting on a lead at all, let
alone a one-goal lead against a slick-skating team like Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could have got that second goal, we could maybe made
them open it up a little bit more, but they were able to hang in
there and hang in there,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive penalty kills have given the Stars fits all season,
Hitchcock has said. But Hitchcock said that wasn't the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in our power play is that we didn't score on
quality chances,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres' penalty kill did get the job done, however, most
memorably when defenseman Richard Smehlik fished behind Dominik
Hasek to rescue Hull's shot off the goal line where it sat, sending
it to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second and third efforts, that's what you have to count on,''
Sabres center Michael Peca said. ``You've got to battle for loose
pucks and then clear the zone as much as you can and make them work
for it. We were working extremely hard and did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   But here's the thing: The Sabres have hardly proved invincible
on the penalty kill. Buffalo has allowed 14 power-play goals, so
why should it be so hard for the Stars to do better than 1-of-10?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's that Hasek guy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the shots were there _ 37 in the game _ the Stars might
need more.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as their goaltender, if we've got to get 70 \Rshots\S
to score three then we'll get 70 to score three,'' Hitchcock said.
``dWe have to find a way to get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
