<HEADER>
A8317 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GALLOWAYCOLUMN-ST     06-09 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS POWERLESS TO STOP SABRES AFTER STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-STANLEY CUP-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Eager anticipation suddenly was transformed into stark
reality Tuesday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the long odds Buffalo supposedly faces in the Stanley Cup
Finals. After a stunning overtime victory in Game 1, the Sabres
have at least temporarily short-circuited Las Vegas odds, the
predictors, and the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   What began as drowsy hockey became a whirlwind of third-period
and overtime action, but when the Stars rode a near-miracle goal
into OT, they still couldn't survive the stout challenge of Buffalo
or the crease work of that man Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:30 left in overtime, the Sabres' Jason Woolley cruised
down the slot, took a perfect feed from Curtis Brown and blasted
the puck past Eddie Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh seed from the East was in seventh heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo by 3-2 sent an alarming message to anyone in the
Metroplex who might have been assuming too much too soon. And that
means the Stars most of all.
</P>
<P>
   Two fact-filled story lines came out of last night's loss for
the Stars, starting with Game 2 now being a must win. But winning
can't happen if the Stars repeat 1-for-10 on the power play,
including nine consecutive failed chances.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo seemed to take one ``stupid'' penalty after another,
including two in overtime. But ``stupid'' became ``smart'' when the
Stars couldn't convert.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Sabres completely dominated the third period, scoring
twice to take the lead. The had the look of a younger, fresher
team, which they are. The only reason the Stars had an overtime
chance was Jere Lehtinen's goal with 49 seconds to play in
regulation after a great play behind the net by Mike Modano set it
up.
</P>
<P>
   New life meant new legs for the Stars. Overtime actually had the
Stars with more jump. They were the aggressive club. Except Hasek
would not fold. Hasek made a brilliant save, sending the puck the
other way, and that led to Woolley's game winner. Near-elation for
the Stars became despair, but that's just Hasek when he's on his
game.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two periods, all the critics blaming the Stars for
bringing ``boring'' and ``ugly'' to the NHL's showcase event were
at least partly right.
</P>
<P>
   Right about a homely snooze-fest breaking out due to style of
play.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, however, the Sabres had more to do with turning
prime-time hockey into a dreaded Knicks-Pacers imitation.
</P>
<P>
   You might also say Buffalo had a great scouting report: Give the
Stars the power play as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In a flashback to what happened against Edmonton and St. Louis
back in April and May, all the extra man meant was extra futility.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull crammed home a power-play goal on Buffalo's first
penalty of the game, but the Stars went 0-for-ever after that. In
fact, a fruitless four-minute power play in the second period
seemed to take the sting out of what had been a dominant Dallas
attack.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the second period, Buffalo took three penalties
in less than five minutes, but with no damage done. And then there
were those two in OT.
</P>
<P>
   With the Stars a meager 1-for-7 on the power play through two
periods, it gave Buffalo exactly what it needed: a one-goal deficit
with 20 minutes still to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres were rewarded for hanging around and keeping it
close. They pounced immediately in the third period, first with a
chain of big, jarring hits. The Stars seemed to soften up as
Buffalo became the pedal-to-the-metal predator. Stu Barnes popped
from the slot at 11:27, scoring on only the Sabres' 12th shot of
the game. That tied it, but there was no question the Sabres also
seemed to have the lead in incentive.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, they had the lead on the scoreboard, too.
The Sabres' power play finally clicked on an excellent Wayne
Primeau effort when he went upstairs on a rebound goal off Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   With a 2-1 lead, Buffalo appeared headed for a quick advantage
in the series. And while it took awhile longer, the Sabres
eventually achieved what they had earned in the third period, and
in penalty kills.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
