<HEADLINE>
HASEK SAVED HIS BEST FOR LAST
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-SABRES SIDEBAR-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Through the first 60 minutes of Game 1, Buffalo goalie
Dominik Hasek left you wondering: Is this it?
</P>
<P>
   Is this the goalie who has been beaten down with every possible
superlative _ from world's best to best ever.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't bad. He showed flashes of brilliance when Buffalo was
killing penalties, but he wasn't the Dominik Hasek you had heard so
much about, the Dominik Hasek who steals games all by himself, the
Dominik Hasek who can't be scored on.
</P>
<P>
   He instead saved that type of performance for overtime, and the
Sabres turned his excellence into a 3-2 victory against the Stars
in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals Tuesday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The crescendo was two point-blank saves on Stars forward Pat
Verbeek just seconds before Sabres defenseman Jason Woolley scored
the game-winning goal at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Dom,'' Sabres winger Dixon Ward said. ``That's why he
was the best goalie in the game. That's why he's our best player.
He allows us to win games with saves like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hasek: ``I went down and then I made the save on Verbeek,
and when I kicked up I got a cramp in my leg. Then we scored.''
</P>
<P>
   The record will credit Woolley with winning the game, but give
the assist to Hasek. He kept the Sabres in the game so there could
be a game-winning goal for Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars made Hasek prove it in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   They came out of the locker room for overtime still buzzing from
their game-tying goal by forward Jere Lehtinen with 49 seconds
remaining in the third period. They were flying, creating lots of
chances. The play, at times, seemed suspended in the Sabres end.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunities were there for the Stars, too.
</P>
<P>
   They had two power plays in overtime; that happens about as
often as snow in July in Fort Worth. They were in addition to the
seven power plays the Stars had in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allowed them to get momentum where Dom was called upon to
save us at times,'' Sabres center Michael Peca said of the number
of power plays Buffalo allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Much like in regulation, Hasek wasn't tested on the first Stars'
power play in overtime, facing a single shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we shot a lot of pucks at him,'' Stars defenseman
Derian Hatcher said. ``Not to take anything away from him, but I
don't think we forced him to make too many spectacular saves.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not until overtime, the second power play especially.
</P>
<P>
   There was Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor firing a shot in from
the point. There was Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk flying in front of
the net and pushing a shot on goal. There was Stars center Mike
Modano unloading one from just below the faceoff circle.
</P>
<P>
   Each time there was a save by Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could probably list two years, probably 20 or 30 like
this,'' Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said.''It was just a great
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dominator'' as he called was dominating. He stopped 35
shots in all, including seven in overtime. The two biggest were the
flopping, flying saves on Verbeek with about five minutes left in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know how he got that,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said when it was all over.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres do.
</P>
<P>
   They've seen it time and time again so much so that they've come
to expect it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our superstar is in the net as opposed to Mike Modano,''
Sabres defenseman Jay McKee said. ``He's not going to go out and
get the goal for us. He's just going to stop them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
