<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HEIKA-COLUMN-STANLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD PERIOD DIDN'T FOLLOW `THE BOOK'
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ How does Ken Hitchcock put it? ``We textbooked 'em,''
is the way he likes to say the Dallas Stars played a nearly
flawless defensive hockey game.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, the Stars tried to use their defensive book to
hit the Buffalo Sabres over the head. And they almost did. But
there was no book for what happened in the final 6:23 of the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   What was interesting, as strategy goes, on the final two goals
in regulation _ the Sabres at 6:23 and the Stars with 48.3 seconds
remaining _ is that each coach made a nice move to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   On the Sabres' goal, coach Lindy Ruff made a nice move,
inserting burly Wayne Primeau in front of the net to battle the
Stars' defense, which had been dominant. And Primeau, who had seen
little time on previous power plays, earned the goal, fighting off
the checks of Craig Ludwig to get to the net.
</P>
<P>
   On the Stars' final goal, Hitchcock made the somewhat risky
choice of calling a timeout with 1:20 remaining and pulling goalie
Ed Belfour. It could have cost the Stars, as the Sabres had a
chance to clear the puck, but it ended up giving the Stars the time
they needed to get in and make the play on Jere Lehtinen's
game-tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   What's important for Game 2 is that the lessons learned in the
first 55 minutes aren't lost.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars say they don't care about a lack of beauty or skill in
their game, just as long as they outwork their opponent. The Sabres
say they, too, don't mind being the villain, they don't mind
dragging the game into the gutter. And both coaches were able to do
that for much of last night.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the game wasn't that far off what both teams like to
do.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars want to work harder in the areas that they can control
_ checking, winning one-on-one battles, forcing the puck deep,
making the simple plays.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock worked his strategy to the letter. He rolled four
lines, he switched his matchups slightly, and he tried to keep the
pressure on the Sabres' defenseme&AMP;/ &QR; &AMP;~specialty-teams-filled second
period hurt momentum for
both sides _ the Sabres didn't have the puck and the Stars couldn't
score. But the game stayed on pace.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to criticize Hitchcock for the Stars' inability to
score. He drew up a strong game plan, a plan that kept the puck in
the offensive end of the rink for the first two periods, an
offensive plan that had the Sabres running around so much that they
put the Stars on the power play eight times in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   It was textbook Stars hockey. The Stars even took a 1-0 lead
into the third period and they were previously 5-0 in playoff games
when leading after two periods.
</P>
<P>
   But all that didn't matter because the Stars couldn't extend
their lead. They hurt themselves with the power play and they
didn't close the deal at even strength.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, this was exactly the way the Sabres won Game 1
against the Ottawa Senators. They were outshot, they gave up nine
power-play chances and they simply just wouldn't let the Senators
score.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff does a great job of staying clam. He doesn't overreact when
his players take penalties. He likes them to have the attitude that
they can afford to take penalties. And that calm paid off in the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   What's guaranteed from the coaching strategy is that both men
will continue to play the referees, both will fight the little
battles to get the edge in the face-off circle or in the battle of
obstruction. And both will find ways to change the ``textbook.''
Because there's no textbook written for this kind of finals.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
