<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY CUP NOTEBOOK: STANLEY STEAMER WORRIES ICE MAN
</HEADLINE>
 CUP NOTEBOOK-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Like nurses at the patient's bedside, trailers sat
parked at its flanks. Giant orange and yellow tubes dangled like
IVs from the building's bowels and doorways.
</P>
<P>
   Reunion Arena looked like a gasping victim, not a genial Stanley
Cup host.
</P>
<P>
   As the first game of the NHL final series neared, Luke Kortegast
was checking the baby's temperature. His spoiled child, the Reunion
ice, has the most scrutinized belly in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather's got me a little concerned,'' said Kortegast, who
bears the title of Ice Supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Even with extra air-conditioning units rented for the series,
game time temperature in the arena bottomed out Tuesday night at 64
degrees. But it wasn't the heat; it was the humidity. Without the
rented giant dehumidifiers that have spaghettied through the
arena's hallways for two months, Reunion Arena might look like the
world's largest margarita.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty percent humidity is a realistic goal,'' Kortegast said.
``But all day today we've been right at 55, 57 percent. The
humidity is what really hurts us.''
</P>
<P>
   As springtime in Texas began to pant its hot breath, the arena
ice was pelted with well-earned criticism. A monster truck rally
hadn't helped things.
</P>
<P>
   But after Game 2 of the Stars' series with St. Louis, Kortegast
and his crew went in and completely replaced the ice. At the behest
of Dan Craig of the NHL's hockey operations office, Kortegast
chunked the water purification system that they had been using and
filled the rink with what amounted to tap water.
</P>
<P>
   Reviews are mixed, but it certainly looks much better.
</P>
<P>
   As supervisor of ice, Kortegast gets the neatest seat in the
house _ for a few minutes, in any case. He drives one of the
arena's two Zambonis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Kortegast said, ``I didn't get as big a kick out
of it tonight as I did for Game 7 of the Colorado series. I don't
know _ after that night, this one seems almost anticlimactic.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Kortegast does not have one of those bumper
stickers attached to his car's rear window _ the stickers that say,
``My other car is a Zamboni.''
</P>
<P>
   His is. But Kortegast noted, ``I own a motorcycle.''
</P>
<P>
   GIVING 'EM THE EAGLE: Amid the painted faces and the makeshift
Stanley Cup fedoras, Bonnie Sweitzer of Dalworthington Gardens had
created her own nest of hockey voodoo.
</P>
<P>
   Her homemade picnic-sized basket featured a stuffed eagle
wearing an Eddie ``The Eagle'' Belfour goalie mask. A brass chain
extended from the one of the wings to the neck of another stuffed
creature, a tiny buffalo. An old plastic water bottle, covered in
foil, formed the obligatory Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be our Eagle leading Buffalo by the nose,''
Sweitzer explained.
</P>
<P>
   All season long with her season tickets behind the visiting
penalty box, Sweitzer has been making the personalized ``voodoo
nests'' and hanging them from the railing, where enemy players like
the Sabres can see them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They usually wind up whacking the glass at it,'' she said,
``or occasionally the glove will come off and I'll recognize the
hand symbol they use.''
</P>
<P>
   HORNS APLENTY: They shoot, they score. And at that moment at
Reunion Arena, a familiar blare booms through the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' vice president of marketing, Jeff Cogen, wanted a
foghorn, like the one that Joe Louis Arena, old St. Louis Arena and
the old Chicago Stadium used to have.
</P>
<P>
   So Reunion has a foghorn. Four foghorns, actually. One is
perched in the rafters at each corner of the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Cogen himself activates the horns with a single plunger at his
seat. If the horn seems to linger a little longer than your basic
Civil Defense Warning, as it did after Jere Lehtinen's final-minute
goal last night, blame Cogen.
</P>
<P>
   The only things said to be louder are jet engines and, perhaps,
any rock-and-roll music played at Reunion. Whatever happened to the
dulcet tones of Erma Woodward at the Mighty Wurlitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Music at Reunion is Ty Wubker's department. He is best known by
afternoon talk-radio fans as the man who discovered ``The Darkness
Music,'' a few bars of which are played whenever enemy players
score a goal against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   It is the only music at Reunion whose volume isn't likely to set
cats wailing or induce inner-ear damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people do say it's too loud,'' Wubker confessed.
</P>
<P>
   CHERRY, HOLD THE LIME: His suit was lime-green, and my first
question for renowned CBC hockey analyst Don Cherry is how did that
thing ever make it through customs?
</P>
<P>
   ``You do look like Austin Powers _ has that occurred to you?''
his Canadian network partner, Ron MacLean, asked on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry, who reached the NHL finals twice during his years as
coach of the Boston Bruins, has picked the Buffalo Sabres to win
this best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're going to win this game tonight,'' he
said after the Stars-dominated first period. ``I still think
they'll win, but it's no contest right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who have never had the viewing pleasure, Cherry is
part Dick Vitale, part John Madden, part Deion Sanders' Spare
Closet. His on-air outfit last night was, in fact, an electric lime
shade, topped off with a puffy dark handkerchief and white
boutonniere.
</P>
<P>
   He has a personality to match.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stars scored first, Cherry pointed out that he had
suggested to viewers that the key to beating Dominik Hasek was to
get traffic in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidently, (Stars coach Ken) Hitchcock was watching,'' Cherry
said, proudly.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
