<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-GAMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES CAPITALIZE ON STARS' POWER OUTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars suffered a power outage last night, the kind
that could have melted the ice at steamy Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse, it could be the first step in melting the Stanley
Cup hopes of the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars went 1-for-10 on the power play, including two rare
opportunities in overtime, and lost a 3-2 game when Buffalo Sabres
defenseman Jason Woolley whipped in a one-timer from the slot at
14:30 of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The goal gave the Sabres a one-game lead in the best-of-seven
Stanley Cup Finals and pushes the Stars into a near must-win
situation for Game 2, scheduled for 7 p.m. tomorrow at Reunion
Arena. It also broke a 12-game losing streak for the Eastern
Conference, which had been swept in the three previous Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get swept now, anyways,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff
said. ``We just won one for the East.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres, who were dominated for the first two periods by the
Stars, now hold home-ice advantage; the Stars must win at least one
game at Marine Midland Arena, where the Sabres are 7-0 in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 2 is a game that has a lot of pressure on the home team
regardless of what happens in Game 1, and the same thing goes for
the home team in Game 3,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``There
will be some pressure on us in Game 2, and there will be some
pressure on them in Game 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolley's goal was a result of the hard-working forecheck of the
Sabres as Curtis Brown stole a soft clearing pass from Stars
defenseman Derian Hatcher at the halfboards and fed Woolley, who
was coming off the bench and had sneaked into the slot after a line
change.
</P>
<P>
   Woolley's shot went between the legs of Stars goalie Ed Belfour
and stunned a crowd of 17,001.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shocking ending for a rowdy crowd that had been pumped
up to its highest volume after the Stars sent the game into
overtime on Jere Lehtinen's goal with 49 seconds remaining in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had pulled Belfour for the extra attacker and
benefited from a great play by center Mike Modano. Modano squeezed
past Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek, stole the puck from Sabres center
Michael Peca behind the net and fed Lehtinen for an easy shot past
a stunned Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The far corner was open, and it was a great pass from Mike,''
Lehtinen said of the slam-dunk. ``I was just out there, and it went
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal gave Stars fans hope after the Sabres had rallied from
getting only nine shots in the first two periods to scoring two
goals in the third. The Stars took a 1-0 lead on a Brett Hull
power-play goal at the 10:17 mark of the first period. But then
they squandered power-play chance after power-play chance until the
Sabres made them pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our standpoint, we'll have to get more desperation and
play for 60 minutes instead of 45,'' Hitchcock said. ``We didn't
score on the quality chances we had.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres took advantage as they finally skated up the ice that
had seemed to be tilted toward their goal all night and scored at
the 8:33 mark of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Barnes got the goal for the Sabres, whipping a shot through
a crowd to give the Sabres new hope.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Primeau then showed just how important the Sabres'
NHL-leading power play has been in the playoffs. Primeau chipped in
a rebound on the power play after camping out in front of Belfour
to put the Sabres ahead, 2-1 with 6:23 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars would get their own power-play opportunity a minute
later and fail on that. They would also fail on two power-play
chances in the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of game the Sabres had been hoping to steal. And
it was clear that this robbery had a lot to do with turning out the
Stars' power and sneaking in through the dark. But the Stars say
they know what it's like to lose Game 1 at home. After all, they
did the same thing against the Colorado Avalanche in the Western
Conference finals and won that series in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to do things the hard way,'' Hatcher said. ``We've
dropped Game 1s before. We're confident we can come back again.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
