<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUEHNE DRIVING TOWARD LPGA STARDOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The LPGA Tour's gallery favorite of the 21st century wears an
insulin pump, an ankle tattoo, a permanent smile and a Nike cap.
</P>
<P>
   You got any problems with that?
</P>
<P>
   If so, you're in the minority. Kelli Kuehne, over the past three
weeks, has earned her stripes with peers and fans on the LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   She jump-started a stagnant career with a top-10 finish in
Austin, followed that with her first career victory in Corning,
N.Y., and topped those accomplishments by becoming the star of the
U.S. Women's Open last week in West Point, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   True, she did not win the event. Juli Inkster did. But Kuehne,
22, dominated air time during telecasts and drew the largest
galleries at Old Waverly Golf Club while finishing third, her top
career effort in a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Dallas native and former University of Texas
golfer finally started providing endorsers with a return on their
multimillions in investment dollars. Reportedly, Kuehne is in line
to earn more than $6 million over four years from a group of
sponsors that includes Nike, Top-Flite and Hain Foods (a producer
of diabetic foods).
</P>
<P>
   Of that total, $1.3 million came from Nike in November 1996 _ a
record-setting sum at a time when Kuehne had yet to acquire her
LPGA Tour card. Initially, that ruffled a few veteran feathers,
including those of Inkster, who lost a $30,000 shoe deal with Nike
for the 1997 season when the money was redistributed to Kuehne.
</P>
<P>
   But those wounds have healed. Kuehne proved herself to peers by
surviving qualifying school in December 1997. Now, they see her as
a potential heir to Nancy Lopez, someone who can lift the
popularity of an LPGA Tour that suffers from a serious lack of
young, American stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelli is young, and she is still learning,'' said Inkster, 38.
``Personally, I think she does a great job. She reminds me so much
of me when I was first out here, with her guttiness and her desire
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, there will never be another Nancy Lopez. She's
the ultimate. But as Kelli gets older, along with the other young
players, I think they will mature and understand that we really
need them to take this tour to the next level. I think they can do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   After wilting under self-imposed pressure in 1998, her rookie
season, Kuehne is showing signs she might be at the head of that
class. The player who became too reserved and too serious last
season spent Open week whistling or singing pop music hits
Sometimes and Love Ya, Love Ya while strolling between the ropes at
Old Waverly.
</P>
<P>
   `I've decided you've got to have a little fun out here. That's
what's helped me out this whole year,'' said Kuehne, who has jumped
from 88th to eighth on the money list ($278,234) by virtue of her
three-week hot streak.
</P>
<P>
   Additional help has come from caddie Tracy Phillips, who doubles
as her short-game teacher. But the biggest boost might have come
from the insulin pump, an addition for the 1999 season that gives
Kuehne _ a diabetic _ better control of her fluctuating blood-sugar
count.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three weeks, success has followed. Nike and fellow
endorsers look farsighted in signing a player who is charismatic,
well-spoken, talented and young.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne stands as a heroine for her ability to produce at the
highest level despite battling diabetes. Having a 150-megawatt
smile and being engaged to an NFL player (Minnesota Vikings
offensive tackle Jay Humphrey) simply adds to the appeal for fans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a combination that can sell the LPGA Tour to the next
generation of fans. LPGA peers now join endorsers in banking on it.
SPOTLIGHT ON ...
Kuehne calls on insulin pump to control diabetes
</P>
<P>
   Every week at LPGA Tour events, Kelli Kuehne can count on one
recurring comment from gallery members.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say, `No pagers on the course,' '' said
Kuehne, whose pager look-alike _ an insulin pump she wears on her
belt _ has helped her control her fluctuating blood-sugar levels
and contributed to improved play in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A diabetic, Kuehne began wearing the pump in October and said it
helps her maintain a consistent energy level during competition. A
40-inch, intravenous tube is hooked to the pump and Kuehne can
regulate her insulin intake by pushing buttons instead of taking
multiple daily injections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an artificial pancreas,'' said Kuehne, a Dallas
resident who finished third at the U.S. Women's Open last week.
``If I'm in a situation where I need some energy and feel like I
need to eat some food, I hit a couple of buttons on my insulin
pump. It gives me insulin and I don't need to eat the food.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne said she hopes to send a message by wearing the pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``A common misconception about being diabetic is you can't be
successful \Rat athletics\S because you're diabetic,'' Kuehne said.
``I disagree. You can take your medicine, check your blood sugar
and live a happy, fulfilling life. Or you can not check your blood
sugar, not take your medicine and die. I've chosen to take this
route.''
CHIP SHOTS Colonial renovation starts
</P>
<P>
   Construction crews began moving dirt Monday on a $4.5 million
facelift to Colonial Country Club that will result in new greens,
reshaped bunkers, additional tee boxes and more trees when golfers
return for the 2000 MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   The primary thrust is to improve course irrigation and drainage,
rid the bent-grass greens of an infestation of Poa-annua grass and
eliminate the effects of long-term erosion from bunker lips. In
addition, the project is expected to add more than 100 yards in
length to the 7,010-yard, par-70 layout. The course will remain
open with temporary greens throughout the bulk of the construction
work, which is scheduled to be completed by April 1, 2000.
Next goal: Hall of Fame
</P>
<P>
   With three victories this season, U.S. Women's Open champion
Juli Inkster finds herself three points from qualifying for the
LPGA Hall of Fame. Problem is, Inkster is committed to cutting back
her schedule to 10 to 12 events per year beginning in 2001, when
both her daughters will be in school.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the rest of this season and all of next for Inkster,
38, to meet Hall requirements before golf takes a back seat to
family considerations. She can get in by winning three tournaments
(one point each) or one major (two points) and a regular tour
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can keep giving myself opportunities to win, I think I
can get those three points,'' Inkster said. ``In the next two
years, that's what I'm shooting for. That's my next goal.''
INSIDE THE NUMBERS Different strokes
</P>
<P>
   How varied were scoring conditions at the past two U.S. Women's
Opens, where the winners' scores varied by 22 strokes in relation
to par? Here is a breakdown: Category 1999 1998 Winning score 16
under 6 over Lowest round 64 68 Highest round 88 91 Sub-par rounds
136 20
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
