<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BIG FINISH, RANGERS MUST CUT OUT ERRORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lessons learned and opinions formed one-third of the way through
the season with the Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   The knee-jerk reaction to the Rangers' pitching overlooks their
defensive problems. They went into last night's game with the
third-worst defense in the American League and are on pace to
commit 133 errors for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile's nine errors have stood out at third base, but the
combined 12 errors by their shortstops have been even more glaring.
Royce Clayton's shoulder has been a bigger problem than anything
the pitching staff has presented and the Rangers' defense won't get
better until he's full strength.
</P>
<P>
   Talk is cheap.
</P>
<P>
   New club president Jim Lites came on board saying everything was
fine with general manager Doug Melvin and manager Johnny Oates, and
their jobs weren't on the line. But if that's really true, it's
time to junk the old Tom Schieffer policy of limiting the manager's
contract to no more than two years in length.
</P>
<P>
   Oates is signed through 2000, and there were times when Bobby
Valentine and Doug Rader had better contracts. At the All-Star
break, the Rangers should announce an extension through at least
2001. Oates has won two division titles, and he's about to win a
third. Any traces of doubt about the manager's job security need to
be erased once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   The early line on the Rangers' All-Star representatives: Juan
Gonzalez, Ivan Rodriguez, Rafael Palmeiro and John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland's earned-run average is a little high for a closer,
but it's coming down. He's still the best reliever in the American
League and an old favorite of Yankees manager Joe Torre, who picks
the American League team.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, definitely no on Jeff Zimmerman. Well ... probably not.
</P>
<P>
   Better make that, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, we'll get back to you on that one.
</P>
<P>
   Expediency still wins out over patience. Ryan Glynn wasn't ready
for the major leagues any more than Kelly Dransfeldt was, but the
Rangers decided they were what's best for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers constantly being rushed by almost every major-league
team is one of the biggest causes of the offensive proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcaster Tom Grieve astutely pointed out during Monday's game
two more examples of hitters getting their way. (1) The huge elbow
pad worn by Gary Sheffield and (2) Devon White's getting
ridiculously annoyed when Aaron Sele hit him on the leg show that
hitters aren't afraid any more of diving out over the plate. But,
they get enraged with the rare pitcher who isn't afraid to pitch
inside.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, hitters have gained the upper hand in such matters.
</P>
<P>
   People speculated that Palmeiro's presence in the lineup would
make a huge difference for Gonzalez. Wrong. It's the other way
around. Palmeiro is the one reaping all the benefits right now. But
that could change if he continues to punish teams for pitching
around Gonzalez, the way Ismael Valdes did Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   An idle thought toward 2001: Do you make Jeff Zimmerman the
closer or do you re-sign John Wetteland and make Zimmerman a
starter?
</P>
<P>
   Nice to have Lord Stanley's tankard in town. But for excitement,
intensity, suspense and great games to watch, I'll take the
Rangers' four games against the New York Yankees in the 1996
playoffs over anything Canada's favorite sport can generate.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, no doubt, are thrilled they have Roger Clemens. The
Rangers and Astros should be, too.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, every day Ruben Mateo spends in Oklahoma City
gives him that much better chance of being successful when he
finally arrives in Arlington. Remember, Gonzalez didn't come up
until the end of his Triple-A season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' most important asset is their offense. No. 2 is
their professionalism, and nobody has exhibited that more than the
way Lee Stevens has conducted himself the past week.
</P>
<P>
   If you have tickets for Saturday night's game, do yourself a
favor and show up early for the pregame ceremonies honoring Hank
Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are going to win the American League West, and if
their bullpen is as good as it is now, then, yes, they have a
chance against the Indians and the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But they've got to play better defense.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
