<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIMMING-POOLS-HNS &LR;      06-09 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIMMING-POOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUGS AND GERMS LOVE SWIMMING POOLS
</HEADLINE>
   (With BC-FOOD POISONING)  
 Repeating for all needing)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE YOUNG  
 c.1999 Redbook Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last summer, E. coli in a Marietta, Ga., water park infected and
hospitalized six children who were swimming in the kiddie pool. It
was the same strain of the germ-0157:H7-that in 1993 killed four
children who ate contaminated fast-food hamburgers in the
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``E. coli isn't the only bacteria you need to worry about in
pools. Microbes that cause gastroenteritis, salmonellosis,
shigellosis, and rotavirus (all of which result in vomiting,
diarrhea, and stomach distress) can all survive in water,'' says
David F. Knoop, technical service consultant for Arch Chemicals.
Here are his tips on what to look for in a pool that's safe for
your kids to swim in:
</P>
<P>
   _ CLEAN ON THE OUTSIDE: If a public pool's changing rooms, rest
rooms, and diaper-changing areas are messy, chances are the aquatic
housekeeping is not up to snuff either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get cross-contamination between the pool and the
bathroom and diaper decks,'' says Knoop.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLEAR WATER, SPARKLING WALLS: Water that's hazy and pool walls
that are slippery with (invisible) algae indicate poor maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   _ A BARELY NOTICEABLE CHLORINE SMELL: The stronger the chlorine
odor, the more you should be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chlorine smells more the more it reacts with nitrogen
products, such as urine and perspiration,'' says Knoop. A stronger
smell means dirtier water.
</P>
<P>
   _ FEWER SWIMMERS: If your pool is always crowded, the chlorine
is less able to do its job. And the more people there are, the more
germs they're potentially spreading.
</P>
<P>
   If yours is a busy pool, don't hesitate to ask the manager or
senior lifeguard how often the pool is cleaned (the answer you want
to hear: at least once a day) and how often the pool is ``shocked''
or treated with high concentrations of chlorine (anywhere from
every two days to once a week, based on the number of swimmers, is
acceptable).
</P>
<P>
   _ A BUBBLY SPA: The pool may look okay, but check out the spa,
if there is one. Jacuzzi jets churn the water, but you should not
see foam on the surface. Foam comes from accumulated skin oils and
other microscopic debris and it means the spa is not being properly
cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   _ IF YOUR KID GETS FOOD POISONING: ``Infants and small children
are particularly vulnerable to the toxic effects of food-borne
illness,'' says Michael Reed, M.D., director of the Poison Control
Center at Rainbow Babies and Children's Hospital in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The younger the child, the greater the risk of dehydration from
vomiting and diarrhea, which can put the body into shock.
</P>
<P>
   Since 50 to 70 percent of outbreaks arise from mishandling of
food in the home, there's plenty you can do to keep your family
safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your child is puking and pooping, whether it's food
poisoning or something else, it's important to be in contact with
your pediatrician,'' says Cornelia Franz. M.D. ``You and your
doctor can determine whether the child needs medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Most cases of food poisoning go away by themselves, but you do
have to guard against dehydration, according to Franz.
</P>
<P>
   Tell your doctor how long the vomiting and diarrhea have been
going on, whether you've noticed any decrease in urine production
in the past 12 hours, and whether the urine looks dark or smells
particularly strong. These are all signs of dehydration, which, if
left untreated, can lead to organ failure, shock, and possibly
death.
</P>
<P>
   Your doctor may recommend that you give your child an
electrolyte-based drink, such as Pedialyte or Gatorade, says Franz.
(If your child doesn't like these, try mixing several ounces with a
clear soda.) ``In the long run, it's more important to get fluids
in, no matter what kind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 0848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
