<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Great Floridians a dead deal, but maybe there's hope in Miami
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ They're having trouble finding nominees
for the Great Floridians Program.
</P>
<P>
   Really. It's getting so bad, they might have to settle for a
Pretty Good Floridians Program. I'll explain.
</P>
<P>
   A couple years ago, the state legislature thought it would be
nifty to mark the end of the millennium by honoring 2,000
Floridians. So the Great Floridian Marker Program was started,
coordinated by the Florida League of Cities and the Florida
Department of State.
</P>
<P>
   A call for nominees was issued last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Floridians Program seeks to recognize individuals
who have made important contributions to Florida's history and
culture,'' proclaimed a state Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Floridians 2000 Committee would be convened to
separate the honorary wheat from the millennial chaff. The idea was
that the best 2,000 nominees would have plaques made in their
honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaques will be mounted on the selected building or
structure with which the individual was identified in the
application,'' the state announced.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for applications was the end of last year. Then it
was extended to April. And now it has been moved again to the end
of September.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the problem?'' I asked Allison Herrington, who is
handling applications for the state's Division of Historical
Resources. ``Are you having trouble getting nominees?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many do you have?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, 170,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you need 2,000?'' I asked. ``It doesn't sound like you're
going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   I suggested that possibly the problem was the ground rules of
the program, rather than a lack of public awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you should start taking nominations for people who are
still alive,'' I suggested.
</P>
<P>
   You see, one of the main rules of the Great Floridians contest
is that you have to be dead to be nominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Herrington said. ``We're not going to take any live
Floridians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because live people have a tendency to say stuff or do
something bad, and usually it's on the day you're hanging the
plaque on the building,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Greatness, it seems, is a perishable commodity that's only
assured upon perishing. And people, no matter how significant their
achievements, still have the option of making messes of their
lives. Or as Herrington so succinctly put it:
</P>
<P>
   ``The only Great Floridian is a dead Floridian.''
</P>
<P>
   And I guess not many Florida cities are willing to fork over the
$175 application fee to nominate somebody who won't be around to
offer a tearful acceptance speech at the plaque-hanging ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   This millennial stunt has the potential of being very
embarrassing for Florida. When a state that's known as a haven for
the dead and dying can't find enough dead people to honor,
something is wrong. We're setting ourselves up for national
ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there are people who have made significant
contributions to our history and culture.
</P>
<P>
   (The inventor of the electronic bug zapper. Let's not forget
that guy.)
</P>
<P>
   Or else, maybe we need to lower our sights a bit. Forget about
great. How about just finding 2,000 Pleasant Floridians?
</P>
<P>
   OK, I see your point. Maybe that wouldn't be easier.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Great Floridians Program just needs a way of finding
1,830 more worthy dead people in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   I've got an idea. Concentrate on Miami, where many dead
Floridians have recently achieved a rare form of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Finding them won't be too hard, either.
</P>
<P>
   Start with a list of registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
