<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERRY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sad ending ahead in ferry tale?
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONKEY ISLAND, La. _ Seven days a week, 24 hours a day, a gray
and white tugboat pushes a small barge back and forth across the
Calcascieu River from here to mainland Cameron Parish. The 600-acre
island in southwest Louisiana has no stores or services; the seven
families who live here use the four-car ferry to get to work, do
errands and go to school. A few river pilots have an office on the
end of the island facing the Gulf of Mexico. And fishermen come
here to catch speckled trout in the murky brown waters off the
rocky shore.
</P>
<P>
   Without the ferry service, which began in 1939 with a rowboat,
the island would be, for all practical purposes, uninhabitable. And
uninhabited it may become, thanks to a bill passed last month in
the state House of Representatives. The bill, which still faces a
Senate vote, would kill the state-run ferry service, which costs
$521,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to move,'' says Robinetta Bourg, 67, who has lived
on the island for 40 years. Her husband, Benny, dubbed the mayor of
Monkey Island by locals, was born here. The Bourgs can't live on
the island without a ferry to carry them and their car back and
forth.
</P>
<P>
   Their son, Chris, was born here, too, and he still lives around
a bend from his parents with his wife, Linda. The younger Bourgs
would like to stay on the island _ perhaps leaving a car on the
mainland and boating across _ but since Linda works an hour away in
Lake Charles, it may be too time-consuming. And if the parish can't
get to the island easily to maintain utilities, living there would
become impossible.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the ferry seems like an expensive luxury for seven
families. But Cameron Parish says the state has an obligation to
continue the service. Monkey Island was not an island at all until
1939, when the government dredged a ship channel to carry vessels
north to Lake Charles. The land never was connected to the town of
Cameron _ where the ferry now runs _ but it was connected to the
mainland west of Cameron, near Holly Beach. In 1939, the Louisiana
Highway Commission promised a ferry across the ship channel, and a
bridge to Cameron. Neither materialized, but the state did begin
ferry service across the river to Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now they want to take the ferry away,'' says George Le-
Boeuf, president of the parish police jury, which is like the
county commission. His family settled on Monkey Island before the
Civil War. ``We don't have the funds to operate it or we could take
it over.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the families on Monkey Island have roots here that
stretch deep into history, into the mid-19th century. When two
Union ships tried to land in Cameron for supplies during the Civil
War, the Confederates, perched on what is now Monkey Island,
cannonballed them to the bottom of the river. Soldiers, Union and
Confederate, are buried on Monkey Island, in graves whose markers
have been lost in the weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the descendants of the earliest settlers live here in a
cluster of modest frame homes on Bourg Street, just off the one
state road that cuts the island in half. Their heritage breathes on
this flat, scruffy patch of land so small you can stand in the
middle and trace its perimeter with your eye. Their parents and
their children grew up playing under the sycamore trees, fishing
off the rocks and hunting for critters in the island's marshes.
</P>
<P>
   More families used to live on Monkey Island, and there once was
a seafood processing plant and a Coast Guard base here.
</P>
<P>
   The island got its name because of the Coast Guard uniforms,
which were nicknamed ``monkey suits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to say, `That's where the monkeys live,' and that's
how it got its name,'' says LeBeouf as he looks around the
abandoned barracks, gray houses on stilts hidden in an overgrown
forest of Chinese tallow trees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, state Rep. Steve Scalise, a Republican from suburban New
Orleans who authored the bill to eliminate the ferry, says spending
more than $500,000 a year on seven families doesn't make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've spent $30 million on that ferry since 1960,'' he said.
``You could buy everybody on that island a mansion and a yacht and
it would have been cheaper. It's been a craw in my side to
eliminate that ferry.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana operates 12 ferries, all of which lose money, and the
Legislature tried to kill five of them in a bill last year. When
that bill died, Scalise decided to target the Monkey Island ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the worst,'' he said. ``It just doesn't serve a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has offered Cameron several options. The parish can
have the ferry if it will pay to keep it running. Or the state will
build a bridge. If neither of those options works, the state will
buy residents' land at market price.
</P>
<P>
   None of these is too tanta-lizing. The parish's general fund
totals about $3 million, of which only $200,000 could be made
available for operating the ferry, and that would mean sacrificing
road improvements. Times are lean in Cameron, thanks to the
downturn in the oil and gas industry, the backbone of the parish.
</P>
<P>
   The police jury voted in favor of the bridge, but some jurors
now are reconsidering, due to opposition from some residents. The
state says it will build a flat-level bridge, but that would block
boat traffic in the river. In this community of shrimpers and oil
service workers, who use that part of the river daily, a flat
bridge is not popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably have to close the island,'' said police juror
Malcolm Savoie.
</P>
<P>
   What the parish really wants, LeBoeuf and Savoie say, is a
bigger ferry. The present barge is too small for heavy equipment,
and that's what has hindered further development of the island,
they say. A developer is interested in building a marina with a
restaurant on the island, but can't without a bridge or a bigger
ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just about the seven families living there, it's
about economic development,'' Savoie says.
</P>
<P>
   LeBoeuf watches the island get smaller as the ferry pushes
toward Cameron on a gentle, humid afternoon. ``Look at this little
old thing,'' he says, looking down at the red-painted metal floor
of the barge and then up at the tugboat. ``Is it such a burden?''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8508 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN10-CO     06-09 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A weekend centuries in the making
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``This time a week ago, we were at ``The
Last Lecture'' . . . the theater . . . the Dean's Brunch . . . `` I
play this mind game daily, trying to keep vivid the details of our
trip last month to attend our youngest son's graduation from
Northwestern Law School.
</P>
<P>
   When my husband and I flew to Chicago, I left behind in Florida
a semi-comatose father in hospice care. His dream of college ended
with his father's sudden death. The prism of Daddy's frustrated
hopes was the lens through which I viewed the entire weekend. For
me, then and now, he provokes the question: How do we honor the
past that paved a better future?
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, my husband and I went with our son to the
law school for ``The Last Lecture.'' This tradition is laughingly
described as a chance for relatives and friends to share in the fun
the students experienced for three years. The graduating class
chose legal history scholar Stephen Presser to be the speaker.
Seated on the hard, upright wooden benches in the law school's
oldest lecture hall, I felt no discomfort after he referred to our
son as one of his best students.
</P>
<P>
   I thought of Daddy's brother, Uncle Emmette, who in the late
'40s worked at night to pay his tuition at Boston University Law
School. Although his academic standing was good, he had to leave
without earning a diploma because he refused to stop dating a white
woman and was expelled. He had dared to dream of a clerkship with a
judge, a dream that our son will realize when he clerks for a
federal appeals judge.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, we saw Ragtime. This musical is based on E.L.
Doctorow's book heralding the diversity of America even as the
diverse groups commit violence upon each other. My father's
generation was shaped in a time when brute force silenced such
candor about America's social problems. More profound than the
play's entertainment value was its acknowledgment that we live in
an America struggling to become its better self.
</P>
<P>
   We attended Dean David E. Van Zandt's brunch the next morning.
Among the many student leaders, distinguished guests and professors
we met was Dorothy Roberts, author of Killing the Black Body. Her
presence was inspiring in light of the tensions women and
minorities confront to find acceptance on law-school faculties.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Sunday afternoon, accompanied by our oldest son and
daughter and a family friend, we went to commencement, at which
Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., spoke. Before the address, Leonard
Rubinowitz, recipient of the annual award for teaching excellence,
announced the winner of the Wigmore Key. This award, named for the
law school's first dean, is given to the graduate whom classmates
and faculty consider ``the student who has done the most to help
preserve the traditions of the School of Law.'' Our son received
this honor.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of our trip is a blur: a congratulatory dinner at an
upscale restaurant, presentation of gifts, return to the hotel,
where insertion of our room key in the elevator yielded access to
the hospitality suite at the top. Daddy would understand. This
memorable weekend was centuries in the making.
</P>
<P>
   All the while I was in Chicago, I had visions of relatives gone.
I thought of those who worked as domestics on Palm Beach, admitted
to the island only with a required identification pass. I thought
of those who endured and respected a system that did not respect
them. Equally on my mind were so many I've known who were bright
with potential but who faded under the white heat of
discrimination, allowing the bigotry of others to define them.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Professor Rubinowitz urged the graduates not to
get so caught up in the quest for fame and fortune that they forget
to cherish each other. I also urge African-American youths who are
inclined to move on up and distance themselves from their roots to
always cherish their ancestors, both the successes and failures. To
reject them is to betray oneself.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
