<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Starting to feel fried? No sweat
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's summer in Austin. The heat is on us like a
cockroach on a cat food dish. Friends and neighbors, here's your
weather forecast for the next 3 2/3 months:
</P>
<P>
   Highs in the 90s to 100s, lows in the morning (for about five
minutes) from 72 to 77.
</P>
<P>
   So you're new to town, and you've never dealt with Texas heat.
How do you stand it? Here are a few helpful tips on how to survive
summer.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning to go barefoot on pavement, practice first
by walking on hot coals.
</P>
<P>
   Stick with light colors. Never go to a daytime costume party as
Darth Vader. And never drive a black car unless you're operating a
hearse.
</P>
<P>
   Don't leave perishables in your car for more than five minutes
unless you are trying to attract a buzzard.
</P>
<P>
   Air conditioner doesn't work? Cover yourself in Mentholatum and
sit in front of a fan.
</P>
<P>
   No car air conditioner? Open all the windows and drive 85 mph.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to wear your leather outfit, Vaseline yourself
first so you can be removed from your pants at the end of the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Don't eat an ice cream cone outside in the afternoon unless you
want to wear it all over your shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Never leave your car without putting the sunscreen in your
windshield, unless you plan to wear kitchen mitts while driving.
</P>
<P>
   Jump in a pool and refuse to come out until about Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   You've been meaning to do it for years. Now's the time to try to
set that Guinness world record for sitting on a block of ice.
</P>
<P>
   Don't allow any dog up on the bed who weighs more than 9 pounds,
especially if he's a heavy breather.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid all events held in fields. Don't volunteer to be a judge
at any chili cookoff that doesn't have a tent.
</P>
<P>
   Get to know the guys who work at Reddy Ice, and spend the summer
hanging around with them.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of turning on the stove, learn to enjoy raw treats.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Dallas in the Stanley Cup finals. Even if you hate hockey,
it'll make you feel cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Empty a tray of ice cubes into your shorts and see how long you
can stand it.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
