<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why do teachers `rely lav' school's last day? The hugs
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If I were to ever teach school, which I
will not because I'd rather be on my feet for eight hours straight
scanning groceries than alone in a room with 25 children, I've
decided I would teach kindergarten. And not because 5-year-olds are
cute and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   They're not.
</P>
<P>
   No, I'd teach kindergarten because I've decided kindergarten
teachers get all the good gifts. Call it The Newcomer Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   First-time school parents are so helpful, so thankful, so
gushing. At least I was, and I found myself in similar company.
That first year, I bought copies of my favorite book and wrote a
little note in each one. I bound them with grosgrain ribbon and
tied each with a pretty bow. I remembered the classroom teacher and
the classroom aide and the speech pathologist.
</P>
<P>
   But things change.
</P>
<P>
   I know this because my 8-year-old left Tuesday for his last day
of second grade. There he went, practically skipping, rain and all,
carrying a mildew-stained backpack and a bedraggled brown paper bag
with 12 oatmeal cookies stuffed inside. No ribbon. No copy of my
favorite book. No nice letter from me. Just cookies and a note from
the kid: ``Thanks for teaching me this year. I really liked that.''
</P>
<P>
   First-grade teacher Jackie Miner says that's OK. What really
matters is not what we do but what the kids do. See, she has the
right heart for the job.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Miner might get a gardenia, ants and all, snatched
from a tree on the walk to school. And hugs, lots of hugs.
</P>
<P>
   But her favorites are the poems, the letters, the stories. The
ones the kids write with their big, shaky letters. ``I rely lav
you,'' they might write. They say such nice things, like how
beautiful she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not,'' says Miner. But we all know she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends who get gift certificates, and I might get a
few store-bought gifts. But the biggest gift to me is something the
kids make,'' says Miner, who teaches at Lake Park Elementary
School.
</P>
<P>
   How about Mr. Barker at Hagen Road Elementary School in Boynton
Beach, Fla.? If you ever find your kid in his classroom, remember,
he's a sentimentalist. I bet you could even make him cry. Last
year's class got him a coffee mug with their picture on it. Every
little smiling second-grader. All those kids who failed to listen
and misbehaved in the bathroom. All those kids who struggled with
math and sailed through reading, or perhaps vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the sentimental things,'' says Jeremy Barker. ``They
get to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Carr taught first grade this year at Acreage Pines
Elementary School in Loxahatchee, Fla. and finds the last day of
school bittersweet. She's happy to be done, but she'll also find
herself missing the kids. For about two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard. I get a little upset because you get attached to
them,'' she told me. I neglect to remind her that a person can also
get used to sea lice, hemorrhoids and cold sores. Why upset her?
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, Carr is just another teacher who loves the last-day
hugs, the last-day notes of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the letters they write.'' Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   The ones that tell her she's nice.
</P>
<P>
   The ones that tell her she's beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
