<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Multi-generational teacher puts down her chalk
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Edith Coleman first started
teaching in Palm Beach County, Harry S Truman was president, Truth
and Consequences was everybody's favorite game show, and local kids
could still buy a soda for a nickel and bowl at the Carefree
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   But at 10 a.m. Tuesday, 49 years and 179 days after Coleman
first stepped into a cottage classroom in the Glades, she said 'Who
Needs Help?' for the very last time. Five hours later, as 145,000
Palm Beach County students streamed from 140 schools on the last
day of school this year, Coleman would bring her career to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman spent the last 47 years at U.B. Kinsey/Palmview
Elementary, which she and her three children once attended. In some
cases, she has taught three generations of West Palm Beach families
_ and she says that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When parents bring in their children, they say, 'She taught
me.' But now I'm teaching their grandchildren, so I think it's time
to retire,'' said Coleman, who plans to spend more time in the
family business, Coleman Funeral Home in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:15 a.m., second-grader Kenneth Gilley asked for permission
to stand and read a poem he neatly pencilled in the minutes after a
math review:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunshine bright in the light, I wish everybody a happy night.
When you go home and lay in your bed, all the memories flow through
your head. I love you all and most of all, my teacher Mrs. Coleman
and my road dog Jermaine.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman always knew she wanted to be a teacher, a wife and a
mother, she said. And while the world around her changed in the
past half-century _ West Palm Beach has doubled in size since she
took her first teaching job _ her manner of teaching has not. Every
year, she tells her students they have a job to do _ to learn.
Maybe that's old-fashioned. But Coleman believes that while
learning can be fun, the classroom is not the playroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same basic things we need to teach our children have
stayed the same _ reading, writing and arithmetic. But it's a
little harder to get the job done. Some students aren't coming to
school focused on school. They think it's play,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm firm, I try to be fair and I demand the best. I want to
know you've tried _ that hasn't changed over all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   During the last hour of school, the good-bye cards kept coming.
Parents stopped by to say thank-you. Second-grader Zakary
Rakszawski handed her a gift and a note that said, ``Thank you for
helping me write and have better handwriting,''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman smiled. She wouldn't have been able to read it nine
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:45, with just 15 minutes to go, her students conspired to
shout `Happy Retirement and We'll MISS YOU!' Ears up, Coleman was
still smiling while she quashed their plan. There might be
hollering at other Palm Beach County schools, but there will be no
shouting in Mrs. Coleman's classroom _ not even on the last day.
</P>
<P>
   And then, at 3 p.m., after more than 1,500 children have heard
her best advice _ Think First! _ it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel relieved,'' she said. ``I feel good about the work I've
been doing all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Flannery writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
