<SLUG> BC-MIDLIFE-JOURNEY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All hail the moose, grand pooh-bah of Alaskan souvenirs
 &HT;    (EDS: This is Installment 18 of Ron Wiggins' ``Midlife Journey
to Mount McKinley. If you are interested in other installments,
call CoxNet at 404-526-5456. WITH ART.)
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRBANKS, Alaska _ There's this thing about Alaskans that I
don't know how to break to you delicately, so here goes:
</P>
<P>
   Alaskans are big into moose droppings.
</P>
<P>
   The souvenir counters from one end of the state to the other
offer moose nugget jewelry and swizzle sticks, ``poo-pourri,''
``s___ kabobs,'' and even moose dropping chap sticks that won't
moisten your lips ``but sure stops you from licking your lips.''
</P>
<P>
   One enterprising Alaskan even came up with moose droppings
impregnated with forget-me-nots. Add water and stand back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand this obsession with moose droppings,'' I
said to a souvenir store clerk.
</P>
<P>
   The young lady shrugged. ``The nights are very long here,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   So are the days, and I've had plenty of time to figure out why
Alaskans find moose droppings hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's because moose are dopey looking, and yet you can't
laugh at them because they kill 10 times as many people as
grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   Mama mooses commonly wander through neighborhoods with their
calves, and if mama has any doubts about your intentions toward her
baby, she will stomp a puddle into you, and then stomp the puddle
dry just as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   You don't make moose jokes when the next person might have lost
a loved one to a raging herbivore.
</P>
<P>
   But they're so darned funny looking. So you do the safe thing
and laugh at their droppings.
</P>
<P>
   Let's lighten up with the only moose joke I know.
</P>
<P>
   A movie director needs to shoot a moose scene and writes an
animal trainer as follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sid _ I need two mooses delivered to the set by Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't look right, so he dashes off another letter
specifying ``two meese.'' It still looks funny. Finally, he writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sid _ Can you get me a moose on the set by Monday?
</P>
<P>
   P.S. While you're at it, send two.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
