<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CANSECO10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting bash for the buck
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jose Canseco knows the value of a good investment. He
bought stock in Yahoo and amazon.com more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating his own worth, Canseco said, ``I'm probably the
cheapest guy around right now.''
</P>
<P>
   His bargain with the Devil Rays has paid dividends for Tampa Bay
_ who signed him in December for a guaranteed $2.5 million after
Toronto offered a $1 million deal. Canseco is also activating some
$2 million in incentive clauses this year.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven other American Leaguers who hit 40 home runs last
season _ Canseco had 46 _ five are getting at least $8 million. As
for his fellow Bash Brother from the 1980s Oakland A's, Mark
McGwire. . . well, his 70 home runs last year sent his income
skyrocketing.
</P>
<P>
   But look who's now leading the majors in home runs: Canseco hit
his 22nd Monday night against the Braves for his 419th career shot.
He also has homered in 10 consecutive series. Only four American
Leaguers this decade have reached 22 homers faster: Ken Griffey Jr.
(twice), Cecil Fielder, Albert Belle and Frank Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good because I'm healthy and because I'm contributing
to the ballclub,'' said Canseco, 34, who could become the first
major-league player to hit 30 or more home runs for four different
teams: Oakland, Texas, Toronto and now Tampa Bay. ``I've got some
luck on my side right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1988 MVP still has the same powerful physique but is free of
the injuries, most recently back problems, that put him on the
disabled list 10 times. And Canseco's making headlines only for
baseball, not for speeding tickets, gun violations, a liaison with
Madonna, domestic disputes, exotic animals or his own personal
1-900 number.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco, who is quietly going through a divorce, believes those
old stories were blown out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what the big deal is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays were impressed by his Toronto statistics _ which
also included 107 RBIs and 29 stolen bases _ but were wary of his
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk (in signing him), obviously was the off-the-field
stuff you hear about,'' said manager Larry Rothschild. ``But he had
gone through a year of not having any problems. I didn't know Jose
before, but when I met him he seemed mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk was more the physical. But that was covered through
incentives.''
</P>
<P>
   The designated hitter in AL games, Canseco is playing the
outfield against the Braves, which is the NL rule ``if I want to
keep that bat in the lineup,'' Rothschild said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits some pretty towering shots,'' said shortstop Kevin
Stocker. ``When he hits them, you usually know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco is the only player to hit a ball that lodged in the
catwalk at Tropicana Field, which cost him a home run May 2 when
the shot was ruled a ground-rule double.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching 500 homers is considered a sure ticket to Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' said Canseco. ``I don't really know if that's the
criteria. Hopefully I can stay healthy and move on, and if I'm
lucky enough, hit 600.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
