<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   EDITH _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When Edith Coleman first started
teaching in Palm Beach County, Harry S Truman was president, Truth
and Consequences was everybody's favorite game show, and local kids
could still buy a soda for a nickel and bowl at the Carefree
Theater. But at 10 a.m. Tuesday, 49 years and 179 days after
Coleman first stepped into a cottage classroom in the Glades, she
said 'Who Needs Help?' for the very last time. Five hours later, as
145,000 Palm Beach County students streamed from 140 schools on the
last day of school this year, Coleman would bring her career to an
end. (Flannery, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MIDLIFE-JOURNEY _ FAIRBANKS, Alaska _ There's this thing about
Alaskans that I don't know how to break to you delicately, so here
goes: Alaskans are big into moose droppings. The souvenir counters
from one end of the state to the other offer moose nugget jewelry
and swizzle sticks, ``poo-pourri,'' ``s___ kabobs,'' and even moose
dropping chap sticks that won't moisten your lips ``but sure stops
you from licking your lips.'' (EDS: This is Installment 18 of Ron
Wiggins' ``Midlife Journey to Mount McKinley. If you are interested
in other installments, call CoxNet at 404-526-5456. WITH ART.)
Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MASON-FAN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ James Mason as the
enchantingly mad Captain Nemo in ``20,000 Leagues Under the Sea''
eyes survivors of a whaling ship captured by his futuristic
submarine, Nautilus, and commands his crew: ``Search the boat!'' As
Nemo seized the moment, the actor seized a 12-year-old girl's
imagination. ``He was so dark, so suave, and he had that voice!''
Barry Imhoff explains. Just how lastingly she was affected is
merely hinted at by the living room wall covered with photos of
Mason. Or the box of old letters, hers and his. To understand the
portal she passed through that night in the movie theater it's
necessary to step through the portal in her hallway, the one that
looks just like a reinforced compartment hatch from the Nautilus.
Only beyond that door does the depth of Imhoff's devotion to a
movie made in 1954 and a man who has been dead for 15 years become
clear. This is a sweet story of a fan who realized her dream of
meeting her idol. (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
