<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8520 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASON-FAN10-COX     06-09 1449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASON-FAN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A star devotion is born - and lives - for James Mason
 &HT;    (EDS: WITH ART.)
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The scene that changed Barry Imhoff's
life when she first watched it 28 years ago is cued up on video
tape, ready to play on the 35-inch television that dominates the
cozy living room in her West Palm Beach home.
</P>
<P>
   James Mason as the enchantingly mad Captain Nemo in ``20,000
Leagues Under the Sea'' eyes survivors of a whaling ship captured
by his futuristic submarine, Nautilus, and commands his crew:
``Search the boat!''
</P>
<P>
   As Nemo seized the moment, the actor seized a 12-year-old girl's
imagination. ``He was so dark, so suave, and he had that voice!''
Imhoff explains.
</P>
<P>
   Just how lastingly she was affected is merely hinted at by the
living room wall covered with photos of Mason. Or the box of old
letters, hers and his.
</P>
<P>
   You might well decide you've seen enough when she pulls out his
nightshirt, make-up towel and a well-worn pair of pink, argyle
socks, but that would be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the portal she passed through that night in the
movie theater it's necessary to step through the portal in her
hallway, the one that looks just like a reinforced compartment
hatch from the Nautilus. Only beyond that door does the depth of
Imhoff's devotion to a movie made in 1954 and a man who has been
dead for 15 years become clear.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that door lies . . . Nemo's bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, you never see it in the movie,'' she says. ``But you
have a pretty good idea what it looks like. I did, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Imhoff thought the walls would be green-tinged copper plate, so
she figured out how to make facsimiles from plywood, epoxy and
textured paint. There are bolt heads everywhere in the movie, so
the bathroom is studded with a hundred or more that she cast from
plaster.
</P>
<P>
   Nemo insisted on knowing the sub's position at all times, so a
duplicate of his ocean map is laminated into the back wall of the
shower.
</P>
<P>
   Every surface, from toilet to sink to pipes, is coated or
colored to mimic visible or imagined details. Imhoff even angle-cut
the doorway, curved the shower entrance and bolted in overhead
pipes so that a visitor can't help ducking into a submarine
posture.
</P>
<P>
   She also supplies appropriate reading material: Three copies of
the 1870 Jules Verne novel that inspired the movie. Next step: a
sound system that will pipe in the voice of Nemo.
</P>
<P>
   There's no point asking how much time she's spent, or how much
money. ``It just happens,'' she says. ``It just keeps on going. I
think of something and I do it. You think I should keep going with
this theme down the hallway?''
</P>
<P>
   The effect so far is anything but cheesy. Imhoff, a
self-employed illustrator of product labels and packaging, has the
talent and patience to elevate her tribute well beyond decoration
into the realm of art.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, she outdoes the original.
</P>
<P>
   The film, already 17 years old when Imhoff first saw it in
re-release, was a wide-screen marvel of 1950s technology. The
special effects shots of the stingray-like Nautilus gliding through
a murky world of giant squid were oceans apart from the flying pie
plates of Plan Nine from Outer Space.
</P>
<P>
   But this was before Star Wars spoiled everybody. Watching
``20,000 Leagues'' today, even Imhoff chuckles at some of the sets
and costumes. In one scene, the crew waddles around the ocean floor
in diving suits with what appear to be iron bread loaves strapped
to their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd swear those are mailboxes,'' says Imhoff, 40.
</P>
<P>
   She's watched it _ who knows? A thousand times?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear out the tape every so often and have to replace it,''
she says. ``Sometimes, I just like having it on. There's something
warm and familiar about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching closely can be maddening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colors change from scene to scene,'' she says. ``The walls
look purple in one scene. Then, look _ now they're green! I just
had to decide what I wanted them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   What doesn't change or fade or ever look silly is Mason, in the
prime of life and career: Dark hair parted high; dark, bushy brows;
dark, sculpted beard.
</P>
<P>
   He had already won an Oscar nomination for ``A Star is Born,''
but was still years away from ``Lolita.'' No matter the role or
year, his voice was unmistakable. Deliberate, patrician, biting _ a
bit like Bette Davis, but two registers lower.
</P>
<P>
   Young Imhoff asked her father about him. ``He said, `It's an old
movie. The guy's probably dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Imhoff saw his name in another movie
advertisement. Her curiosity returned with a vengeance. She began
sending fan letters to his agent in England. Then she spotted a
picture of Mason in People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The caption said, ` . . . outside his home in Lausanne,
Switzerland,'''' she recalled. ``So I wrote a letter and addressed
it to James Mason, Lausanne, Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   Mason sent her a letter, a recording he'd narrated and a
hard-bound copy of The Films of James Mason. Imhoff wrote again,
and again Mason replied. Her letters, written during study hall,
became longer and more elaborately illustrated. She drew pictures
on the envelopes of Mason in various film roles.
</P>
<P>
   Mason responded with increasing enthusiasm. He sent her more
books, pictures, a mustache he wore in a movie. He wrote postcards
from movie locations around the world. He sent her Christmas cards.
The salutation was always, ``To TLW.'' The Letter Writer.
</P>
<P>
   Imhoff, then a high school student in Mattoon, Ill., wrote that
if Mason ever found himself changing planes in Chicago, she'd rush
right over to meet him at the airport. She kept up the
correspondence when she went away to college at Southern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a roommate who was kind of weird; she used to read the
TV Guide at the beginning of the week and circle what she wanted to
watch,'' Imhoff says. ``One day she hands it to me. The Tonight
Show is circled. The guest is James Mason.''
</P>
<P>
   Imhoff illustrates by pulling the TV Guide page from her box of
letters. The listing for Oct. 2, 1978 is circled in red. Imhoff
gave it very little thought before taking her life savings out of
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something like $400, enough for a plane ticket,'' she
says. Her brother was living in San Diego. They planned to drive to
Los Angeles the next morning and stand in line for tickets to the
show.
</P>
<P>
   While Imhoff was on the plane, her parents' phone rang. It was
James Mason. He was in Chicago, changing planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother gave him my brother's number,'' she says. ``He
called me there. He said, `I'm here in Chicago and I hear you've
gone dashing off.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mason arranged for Imhoff to get tickets, and the thrill of her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy Davis Jr. was the guest host,'' Imhoff says. ``They came
back from a commercial break and Sammy said, `You were telling me
about a fan of yours. Why don't you tell everyone?'''
</P>
<P>
   Mason told America about the girl in the fifth row who flew to
California without so much as a ticket, hoping to meet him. Then he
waved her up to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to kiss James Mason on national television!'' Imhoff
exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   In a flash, she was back in the fifth row. In another, the show
was over and Mason was gone. At least the show was recorded, so she
got to watch it later that night in a bar. But this was pre-VCR, so
she's never seen it since.
</P>
<P>
   She did get to meet Mason one more time, years later in New York
over lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him why he was so nice to me all those years,'' she
says. ``He told me he got lots of letters, but he picked a handful
of fans who seemed the most enthusiastic. One from England, one
from Germany, one from South America.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued to write until shortly before his death from a
heart attack in 1984. Soon after, she took one more
curiosity-driven flight, to Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have gone to his home while he was alive unless
he invited me, but he never did,'' Imhoff says. ``But I thought it
was all right after he died. So I called Mrs. Mason.''
</P>
<P>
   Clarissa Mason was more than pleased to have company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed for three days,'' Imhoff says. ``We drank his
favorite wine. We watched his movies. That's when she gave me the
socks.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience helped demystify the man without lessening
Imhoff's devotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``After seeing stacks of his underwear and his old shoes, I
gained a healthy disregard for fame,'' she says. ``He was just a
man. A very nice, nice man.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
