</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS10-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I saw an article saying Cold War veterans now were getting
federal recognition. Are any benefits available to them, and how
does one apply?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Cold War Recognition Certificate, established by Congress
as part of the fiscal 1998 National Defense Authorization Act, is
symbolic, with no financial reward attached.
</P>
<P>
   All members of the armed forces and federal government civilian
personnel ``who faithfully served the United States during the Cold
War era'' are eligible. The specified dates for such service are
Sept. 2, 1945, to Dec. 26, 1991. An application letter, along with
documentation proving service during the period, is required.
Acceptable documentation includes any government form _ copy, not
original, because it can't be returned _ that includes the
applicant's name and Social Security number (or military service or
Foreign Service number) and date of service.
</P>
<P>
   The mailing address for requests for the certificate: Cold War
Recognition, 4035 Ridge Top Road, Suite 400, Fairfax, VA 22030. The
fax number is 703-275-6749. Information also is available on the
Internet at http://coldwar.army.mil/ or by calling 703-275-6279.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A steak dinner rides on the answer to my question, which
arises because of a recent TV travelog about Australia's Great
Barrier Reef. I say it's natural, but my son-in-law says it's
man-made. Who is right?
</P>
<P>
   A: We hope you'll enjoy a thick T-bone at your son-in-law's
expense. Outback, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists believe the Great Barrier Reef began forming about
500,000 years ago. The coral reef is a limestone formation made of
the hardened skeletons of dead water animals called polyps.
Billions of living coral polyps are attached to the reef, so it's
continuing to form _ naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When discussing conservatives and liberals, the press often
uses ``left'' and ``right'' with regard to people's views on an
issue. Can you elaborate on the origin of these labels?
</P>
<P>
   A: These are just two terms describing the ideological spectrum,
which (from left to right) includes radical, liberal, centrist (or
moderate), conservative and reactionary. Safire's New Political
Dictionary traces left wing-right wing descriptions to the seating
arrangement used by the presiding officers of the French National
Assembly. They placed the radicals at the cote gauche (left side),
the moderates in the center directly in front, and the conservative
nobles on the droit (right). Like so many political terms, the
``wings'' derived from military use.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Pep Boys has as its logo the caricatures of three men named
Manny, Moe and Jack. Were they real people?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. They were Emanuel ``Manny'' Rosenfeld, Maurice ``Moe''
Strauss and Graham ``Jack'' Jackson. In 1921, they _ along with
another Moe, Moe Radavitz, who left the company after a few years _
founded a business originally known as Pep Auto Supplies in
Philadelphia. The word Pep came from one of the products they were
selling, Pep Valve Grinding Compound, and the change from Auto
Supplies to Boys evolved through common usage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1923, Strauss went to California, where he saw a dress shop
named Minnie, Maude and Mabel's. When he returned he asked a
friend, Harry Moscovitz, to create the caricatures you still see
today. Ironically, the three faces that have become so recognizable
as Manny, Moe and Jack aren't truly theirs. Jack's face appeared
briefly when the caricatures first were penned. However, after
Graham Jackson left Pep Boys, his face was replaced with that of
Strauss' brother, Isaac ``Izzy'' Strauss. After Izzy left the
company, Rosenfeld's brother, Murray, joined the team, but Izzy's
face remained and continues to this day to be part of the company's
icon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Back during the Clinton impeachment proceedings, actor Alec
Baldwin, appearing on a late-night TV show, made remarks
encouraging people to murder Rep. Henry Hyde and other Republicans
and their families. The Capitol Police, I believe, were
investigating that. Did anything come of that investigation?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was no investigation by Capitol Police. The episode
started when Baldwin, a shrill critic of Congress, made an outburst
Dec. 11 against House Judiciary Committee Chairman Hyde (R-Ill.) in
a skit on NBC-TV's ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien.'' In it,
Baldwin shouted, ``If we were in other countries, we would . . .
all of us together would go down to Washington and we would stone
Henry Hyde to death. We would stone him to death. . . . And we
would go to their homes and we'd kill their wives and children. We
would kill their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who had received a number of death threats at the time and
was under armed guard, reacted by saying he was ``sickened'' by the
comments. ``To kill my family because you disagree with me? To
laugh about that? There are people out there, sick people, just
waiting for a push.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Kasteler, a Baldwin publicist, said people angered by his
remarks were stiffs. ``They ought to lighten up,'' she added.
``It's a comedy show.'' NBC promised never to rerun the program,
with a network spokesman adding that the skit ``was obviously a
joke and meant to be taken as such.'' Baldwin, meanwhile, wrote a
letter of apology to Hyde, apparently putting an end to the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I get information online about the 2000 Super Bowl
in Atlanta? I found several sites for prior games, but not for the
upcoming one.
</P>
<P>
   A: The address: www.superbowlXXXIV.org/ Q: Do you know anything
about a recent recall of Saabs? I need to know which models were
involved and what the problem is.
</P>
<P>
   A: The recall, announced last week by Saab Cars USA, affects
26,000 Saab 9000s from model years 1992 through 1994. The automaker
said the covers on the air bag's electronic control module, located
in the engine compartment, could allow moisture to enter and
corrode its circuit boards, possibly causing the air bag to
malfunction. The manufacturer said owners of affected models would
be notified by mail in July to have the parts replaced by a dealer,
if necessary, and at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm told that President Clinton has issued 11 executive
orders. What are they?
</P>
<P>
   A: He has issued and signed far more than 11 executive orders,
which are presidential proclamations that carry the force of law.
According to the National Archives and Records Administration
Federal Register, as of May 25, Clinton had issued 13 such orders
this year alone. In 1998, there were 38; 1997, 38; 1996, 46; 1995,
43; 1994, 54; and 1993, 57.
</P>
<P>
   Those signed this year include Identification of Trade Expansion
Priorities and Discriminatory Procurement Practices; Using
Technology to Improve Training Opportunities for Federal Government
Employees; and Designation of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
(Serbia/Montenegro), Albania, the Airspace Above, and Adjacent
Waters as a Combat Zone.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, check www.nara.gov/fedreg/eoclint.html to read
details of all the executive orders issued during Clinton's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Postal Service has a Cinco de Mayo stamp. What does that
mean, and why is it on a U.S. stamp?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cinco de Mayo is the name of the annual celebration
commemorating the victory of Mexican troops over the French at the
Battle of Puebla on May 5, 1862. In Spanish, cinco is five, and
mayo is May. The U.S. Postal Service first issued the stamp, in a
32-cent version, on April 16, 1998, as part of its Holiday
Celebrations series. The 33-cent version of the same stamp was
issued this past April 27.
</P>
<P>
   When the 32-cent stamp was introduced, the Postal Service
explained that it ``celebrates not just the victory of Mexican
troops on May 5, 1862, but the victories Mexican-Americans have
fought and won to make American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stamps in the Postal Service's Holiday Celebrations series
honor Hanukkah and Kwanzaa.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has there been any progress in the development of vegetable
oils for use in vehicles as a replacement for the petroleum-based
product?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's coming along. The developer of the new product, Agro
Management Group of Colorado Springs, Colo., recently licensed a
Michigan group to be the first to sell AMG 2000. The new oil, which
will cost about $2.25 a quart, is a 100 percent vegetable oil
blend. A big advantage touted by its developers is that, compared
to traditional motor oil, it's almost as environmentally friendly
as salad dressing: biodegradable, nontoxic and producing fewer
harmful emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Allen of Agro Management said the product's blend is
secret, but he added that it includes soy oil and canola oil. It
was developed over six years at a cost of $2 million, with $250,000
in research funds contributed by the United Soybean Board, a group
founded by soybean farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The developers recently concluded an 18-day tour through 18
states using two trucks, one lubricated with conventional motor
oil, the other with the new soybean product. The two materials
performed equally, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, they cautioned consumers not to try pouring oil
from their kitchen cupboard into an engine, because high
temperatures would cause it to gel. AMG 2000's formulation prevents
that.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
