<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, June 9, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COUNSELING-HOMELESS (Houston) _ The Baylor/Star of Hope Family
Counseling Center is one of only a handful in the country that
offers intensive, individual and group counseling, psychological
testing and evaluations to the homeless. The program is helping an
abused woman understand the anger she's now free to feel. By
JANETTE RODRIGUES. (For release Sunday, June 13. Photo available on
the NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-COPS (San Francisco) _ Much to the Police Department's
dismay, the San Francisco Unified School District has passed a
resolution that limits the presence of police on campuses. The
resolution requires that staff members first contact school
administrators to resolve a problem with a student unless the
student poses an immediate threat to others or has broken the law.
It also requires on-campus officers not to carry guns while on
school grounds for non-emergency matters. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL (Aboard the Konkar Star, Panama) _ Here on the
Panama Canal, Robert Holden is part autocrat, part artist. His curt
instructions set off a chain reaction of bustle and fuss by the
captain and crew of a ship he is piloting through the waterway. We
look at Holden's life and work, both of which are fast disappearing
as Washington prepares to surrender one of the key engineering
marvels of the American Century _ the Panama Canal. By JOHN OTIS.
(For release Sunday, June. 13. Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL-WINDFALL (Balboa, Panama) _ What does the Panama
Canal mean to most Panamanians? Instant wealth for the country. By
JOHN OTIS. (For release Sunday, June 13.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For folks just entering the job
market, here are a few things I wish I had known half a lifetime
ago, when my face was as fresh as yours, By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-OUTLOOK (San Francisco) _ For business fossils still
stuck in the Stone Age, Internet boosters at the vanguard of the
online revolution slammed home the message that electronic commerce
is transforming business faster than you can say ``new economy.''
By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-PROFILE-THOMAS (San Francisco) _ Were it not for the
televised presidential news conference, Helen Thomas speculates
that she would be as anonymous as any other wire-service reporter
in Washington. Instead, TV has made the veteran White House
correspondent for United Press International something of a
celebrity _ or, as she puts it, a ``bit player on the national
stage.'' By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PREVIEW-APES (Undated) _ Has it really come to this? That
television has gone from live action to animation and now the third
wave, chimps, as characters? ``The Chimp Channel'' (7:05 p.m.
Thursday, TBS) is a half-hour sitcom, neatly replacing ``Friends''
if you think about it. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
