<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8578 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANNIBAL-REVEIW07-COX     06-09 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANNIBAL-REVEIW07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Lecter fans, Harris serves up a worthy sequel
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hide the chianti and fava beans. Hannibal Lecter, the
cannibalistic psychiatrist from Thomas Harris' best seller ``The
Silence of the Lambs'' is back. And he's as hungry as ever.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, it's Dr. Lecter who's on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask.
</P>
<P>
   A million copies of Harris' long-awaited sequel, ``Hannibal,''
arrive in stores Tuesday, and the novel is a stunner. (Dino
DeLaurentiis has already paid $9 million for movie rights.) The
novel picks up seven years after Lecter escaped from custody and
Clarice Starling, the feisty young FBI trainee, disposed of
``Buffalo Bill,'' the serial killer who skinned his victims.
</P>
<P>
   Clarice is a full-fledged agent now, but she has made some
powerful enemies in the bureau. When a drug raid goes sour and
Clarice is forced to kill five people, including a woman carrying a
baby, she faces dismissal. But just when it looks as if her career
is over, she receives a letter from Lecter, and the manhunt for one
of the most vicious killers in history resumes.
</P>
<P>
   But Clarice is not the only one who wants to find Hannibal.
Mason Verger, the doctor's sixth victim, has offered $1 million to
anyone who kills Lecter and $3 million to anyone who captures him
alive.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought Hannibal was a monster, just wait until you meet
Verger. Paralyzed from the neck down and kept alive with a
respirator, the one-eyed Verger is faceless and lipless _ a result
of a little drug experiment Lecter employed in which Verger allowed
his face to be eaten by dogs.
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy sadist before he met Lecter, Verger plays mind games
with troubled children in a day care center in his mansion, feeds
crippled ornamental carp to the giant moray eel he keeps in an
aquarium and attempts to track his nemesis' movements via a
worldwide web. Verger plans to exact his revenge in a particularly
gruesome fashion by feeding Lecter slowly to a herd of omnivorous
pigs and filming his demise.
</P>
<P>
   Foiled for years in his efforts to capture the elusive
sociopath, Verger decides that the best way to draw Lecter out is
to set a trap with irresistible bait: Clarice Starling.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting manhunt is a thrill ride through a house of
horrors, from the scene of a nightmarish 15th-century murder in
Florence to the bizarre interior of Verger's Maryland estate.
Harris introduces a fascinating supporting cast that includes
Verger's sexually abused sister, a lesbian bodybuilder on steroids;
Barney, the hospital orderly who once cared for Lecter; and Paul
Krendler, a misogynist bureaucrat intent on destroying Clarice.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Harris takes us into the mind of Lecter to
revisit the traumatic event in World War II that spawned Hannibal
the Cannibal. Like Clarice, who is tortured by the childhood memory
of slaughtered lambs screaming, Lecter has his own demons that he
deals with by retreating into his ``memory palace,'' a mnemonic
system well-known to scholars in the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the horror, Harris weaves in a wealth of artistic and
scientific details. In Florence, he has Lecter quoting Dante's
``Inferno'' to a group of scholars, listening to harpsichord
compositions by Henry VIII and expounding on the beauty of
Botticelli's art.
</P>
<P>
   Back in America, he has the doctor watching the film ``A Brief
History of Time'' and considering astrophysicist Stephen Hawking's
theory that at some point the universe would stop expanding and
events of the past could be reversed. A teacup that falls off a
table and breaks into pieces may gather itself back together. When
that happens, Lecter believes, dead relatives would be made whole
and nightmares would cease.
</P>
<P>
   Harris uses this image again in an ending as unsettling as any
in contemporary literature. Writing in language as bright and
precise as a surgeon's scalpel, Harris has created a world as
mysterious as Hannibal's memory palace and as disturbing as a Goya
painting. This is one book you don't want to read alone at night.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST LOOK: An excerpt from ``Hannibal''
</P>
<P>
   Starling turned and saw it all in a single image that would last
as long as she lived. Side by side on their stainless-steel tables
lay a deer and a man. From the deer projected a yellow arrow. The
arrow shaft and the antlers had held up the covering sheets like
tent poles.
</P>
<P>
   The man had a shorter, thicker yellow arrow through his head
transversely at the tips of his ears. He still wore one garment, a
reversed baseball cap, pinned to his head by the arrow.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at him, Starling suffered an absurd burp of laughter,
suppressed so fast it might have sounded like dismay. The similar
positions of the two bodies, on their sides instead of in the
anatomical position, revealed that they had been butchered almost
identically, the sirloin and loin removed with neatness and economy
along with the small filets that lie beneath the spine.
</P>
<P>
   Starling touched her lips with her knuckle. ... ``Dr.
Hollingsworth, were the livers missing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The deer's liver is missing. Mr. Barber's liver apparently
wasn't up to standard. ... The sweetbreads, yes, missing in both
cases. Agent Starling, nobody's said the name yet, have they?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Starling said. ``Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
