 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 433 - June 9, 1999  ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY
-- No. 433 -- June 9, 1999 We are offering the following articles
for sale. Please contact us for availability your country. Best
regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. BUBBLE-GUM GODDESS : BRITNEY SPEARS AND THE MAKING
</P>
<P>
   OF AN ADOLESCENT IDOL They may be making her into a teen idol,
but 17-year-old singer Britney Spears isn't letting controversy
stand in her way. Her debut album, ``Baby One More Time'' spent
four of the first six weeks of its release at No. 1 on the
Billboard charts. Overnight, its midriff-baring video turned Spears
into a sex symbol for the pubescent set. She says she isn't
surprised that her music has found a ready market, especially in
the wake of young, male vocal groups. ``I think people feel it
would be nice to hear a change, to hear a girl sound.'' By Gary
Graff. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
BEETHOVEN'S FRIGHTENING POSTERITY Of all the Romantic composers,
Ludwig van Beethoven was the one who most embodied the power urge
that tempts certain creators to try to rival God. That ambition,
combined with his striking, memorable and rousing musical motifs,
has probably made him an ideal subject for political exploitation,
as Esteban Buch shows in his fascinating book, ``Beethoven's Ninth
: A Political History.'' The composer's ``Ode to Joy'' has come to
symbolise an ongoing fraternal Utopia, a universal message much
more than a piece of music. By Philippe-Jean Catinchi. From Le
Monde. 1,500 words. (English translation available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
SPECIAL STAR WARS PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   Please contact us for the release date in your country of the
new ``Phantom Menace'' film, plus copies of special Star Wars
articles (with art) from The New York Times Syndicate.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
ISAAC HAYES ON 'SOUTH PARK,' 'SHAFT,' MUSIC AND MORE Call him an
entertainer. ``That pretty much encapsulates the whole thing,''
Isaac Hayes says. ``I've been at it for 40 years.'' These days, the
56-year-old artist is enjoying an unlikely surge in popularity with
college students and preteens. By Ian Spelling. 1,300 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
CHER : SHE'S BACK, ON SCREEN AND ON CD In salvaging her career
after the end of Sonny and Cher's brief fame in the 1970s, in
reinventing herself as a solo singer and an Oscar-winning actress,
Cher earned a spot in the Comeback Hall of Fame. On the eve of her
53rd birthday she has a multimillion selling single, ``Believe,''
and great reviews for her role in Franco Zeffirelli's film ``Tea
With Mussolini.'' ``See what happens when I take a big rest?'' she
jokes. ``I'm like John Travolta - I come back big.'' Her fans are
sometimes surprised that the person they meet isn't the feather and
rhinestone glamour queen they've seen on the Oscars. ``I'm very
soft in a certain way ... it's just that you can't be too soft and
survive in my world.'' By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
THE SNUFF FILM : THE MAKING OF AN URBAN LEGEND One of the most
enduring, and little-recognized, urban legends about cinema is the
``snuff film,'' in which actresses are supposedly actually killed
onscreen. Over the course of nearly a quarter of a century, the
snuff film has transformed from grade-Z slasher film to hoax to
antio-pornographers' straw man to urban legend and shows no sign of
slowing down. By Scott Aaron Stine. From Skeptical Inquirer
magazine. 3,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
FOR THE RECORD, JENNIFER LOPEZ HAS MUSIC ON HER MIND It isn't
enough that Jennifer Lopez is a gorgeous movie star, famous and
rich beyond most people's wildest dreams - the highest-paid Latina
in Hollywood - she can also sing. The dominant voice on her album
is that of a young woman fired by determination to get everything
life has to offer. ``The music is a little like me. It's street,
but there is also a soft side ...'' By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words
+ photo. 
