<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET OFF TO A GOOD START AFTER COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you're a college graduate starting your first
real job, you're entering the working world at a time unlike any
other. Now that Susan Lucci has won an Emmy, everything else that
happens in the American workplace is pretty much anticlimactic.
</P>
<P>
   But since it will be, oh, half a century until your Social
Security kicks in _ if it hasn't already kicked the bucket _ you
might want to get a handle on this ``real world'' thing, and how
school did and did not help you prepare for it.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few things I wish I had known half a lifetime ago,
when my face was as fresh as yours:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mediocrity rules.
</P>
<P>
   Schools and workplaces focus so much on improving their weakest
people that they often ignore their best. You won't have the kind
of clear path and constant feedback you had in school, and your
company may never tell you exactly what skills you need to advance.
So find a mentor or seek advice from people you respect.
</P>
<P>
   How can you stand out? Even if all you do is perform a task well
(details and all) the first time you're asked, you'll be ahead of a
huge chunk of the work force. Learn how to do things other people
can't.
</P>
<P>
   And don't overlook the most valuable skill any worker can have:
the ability to read the handwriting on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you would ever use this advice for evil purposes, of
course, but there are two great things about having special skills:
They give you power, and no one really knows when you're goofing
off.
</P>
<P>
   Say you're at a company with only one tech support person. He
says he can't fix your software problem until tomorrow afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, you don't really know if the delay is because (a)
it's a time-consuming job; (b) it's a 10-minute job, but you're low
on his priority list; (c) it's a 10-minute job for most tech
support people, but not him; or (d) it's a 10-minute job, but he's
devoting his day to finding the best Internet porn sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop habits you can live with.
</P>
<P>
   Work 60 or 70 hours in each of your first two weeks, even if
many of those hours are spent studying at home rather than in the
office. Getting a reputation as a quick learner is well worth the
unpaid overtime.
</P>
<P>
   When you have questions, look for answers in a manual or help
file. If you have to ask people, write down their answers so you
don't have to ask again.
</P>
<P>
   Realize that engineers have invented a device that robs you of
your creativity, your individuality and your soul. They call it a
cubicle. If you're stuck in one, figure out if there are certain
tasks _ such as brainstorming _ that you're better off doing
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get comfortable, take a weekend and evaluate your
personal and career goals, from buying a car to starting a family
to figuring out how many hours you want to work each week, and put
them in priority. Get into the habit of doing this once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Understand that the status quo is a decision in itself. If you
choose to do nothing, that's probably what you'll get.
</P>
<P>
   _ Choose your words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   In college, candid conversation is encouraged. Many workplaces
are like that, but not all.
</P>
<P>
   Knee-jerk rule of thumb: Ask 20 questions for each opinion you
offer. Learn from ``Jeopardy''; the right answer often comes in the
form of a question. Like, ``Is there a reason we don't ...?'' And
realize that helping people is an art form. Do it whenever you can,
but don't make the person you're helping feel like an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't underestimate the importance of money.
</P>
<P>
   College finances are usually unrealistic. You either have a free
ride through scholarships or parents, or you get loans and scrap
for every penny.
</P>
<P>
   Now you have a real job, making real money. Splurge if you need
to, but then learn how to save and invest. Your first job isn't
just the foundation for your career, but for the rest of your life.
</P>
<P>
   Say you save $10,000 in an IRA by the time you're 30. If you
earn 5 percent a year and make no further deposits, you'll have
about $55,000 at age 65. At 10 percent, it's $280,000; at 15
percent, $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy at this stage to say that money doesn't matter. Maybe
it never will. Maybe you'll win the lottery, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't be a victim.
</P>
<P>
   Bosses and teachers play favorites. No matter what race, sex or
age you are, you might feel as if you've been discriminated against
_ and you might be right. There is always going to be someone who
has more money, more influence and more Emmy Awards than you do.
</P>
<P>
   Before winning the Emmy, Lucci had been nominated 18 times, but
the award always went to someone else. She never failed; someone
else just did better.
</P>
<P>
   During all those years, America's most famous loser stayed with
the same husband, raised two children, earned millions of dollars
and became a soap opera icon, better known than any of the women
who received the Emmy.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of victories in work and in life, and most of
them don't come with gold statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His e-mail
address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
