<HEADER>
A8672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-WEEKLY-BUDGET-NYT     06-09 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEEKLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS, attention features, technology page editors:
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of selected computer-related stories from the
past week from  &UR; The N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  and its partners.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are being repeated with a distinguishing ``CPT''
in the slugline and an ``a'' general news category code.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories planned for Thursday's New York Times will be
listed on  &UR; BC-CIRCUITS-BUDGET-NYT &LR; , moving later this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MA-HIGHTECH-ART-BOS (Lowell, Mass.) _ John Thibault has built
a technology empire of his own. Geotel Communications Corp. designs
the software used by American Express, Fidelity Investments, and
the nation's major airlines to route customer calls. Last April,
Thibault and Geotel's other founders received the ultimate
endorsement of their success: Cisco Systems Inc., the nation's
largest computer networking company, agreed to buy their 5-year-old
firm for $1.9 billion. By Kimberly Blanton.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ELECTRONIC-ARTS-BLOOM (Redwood City, Calif.) _ Electronic
Arts Inc., the No. 1 maker of video-game software, said it's
producing a figure-skating game endorsed by world champion skater
Michelle Kwan, its first title designed specifically for girls. By
Greg Chang.
</P>
<P>
   BC-DOCTORS-INTERNET-TEX (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Someday soon, you
will be able to dial ``star'' DR (''star'' 37) on your push-button
phone, ask your medical questions, and get within hours
personalized answers from a doctor who specializes in your medical
problems. By Carolyn Poirot.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TECH-HANDICAP10-COX (Atlanta) _ A little more than a year
ago, Sharon Mazzotti's 17-year-old foster son, Danny, walked
through the door of her home for the first time. Danny is mentally
and physically handicapped. Cerebral palsy kept his hands in an
almost permanent fist. Much of that has since changed. And
Mazzotti, 55, attributes it to a computer. By Mark Clothier.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WEB-AD-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ An emerging category of Web
software that blocks advertising is challenging the Web industry
and rankling the nerves of some Internet executives. By Laurie J.
Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-OVERSIGHT-ART-NYT (Washington) _ Members of the
interim board of the Internet's new oversight body are beginning to
make decisions and shape policy that could ultimately affect
everyone who uses the global network. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CHIP-SFCHRON (Undated) _ Forget solitaire. Laptop-toting
travelers soon may be able to while away the airborne hours with
Quake, Unreal and other hot 3-D action games. By Henry Norr.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CD-BURN08-COX (Dayton, Ohio) _ Few innovations have had as
much impact in the field of personal technology as the introduction
of the compact disc in the 1980s. From its humble beginnings, the
CD has managed to establish a dedicated following willing to
abandon their beloved vinyl records for dependable digital discs.
By Alexis Larsen.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NETWATCH08-COX (Atlanta) _ I'll probably lose my membership
in the hip Internet writers club for saying this, but I kind of
like America Online. By Frances Katz.
</P>
<P>
   BC-Y2K-LAWSUITS-HNS (Albany, N.Y.) _ It was 1995, and Mike
Yarsike, owner of a gourmet grocery store in a Detroit suburb, had
just become one of the first victims of a Y2K problem. Soon after,
he also became one of the first people to file a Y2K lawsuit _ in
this case against the maker of his registers. By Alan Wechsler.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-INTERNET-RESEARCH-NYT (Washington) _ The director of the
National Institutes of Health has touched off a passionate debate
by proposing that scientists disclose and disseminate on the
Internet the results of biomedical research, so the full text of
their reports would be available at no cost to anyone with a
computer anywhere in the world. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   BC-INTERNET-CHILDREN-LADN (Los Angeles) _ As if parents don't
have enough to worry about when it comes to the Internet, a new
study reported Monday that online marketers are increasingly
targeting youths as a back door to mom and dad's pocketbook. By Ben
Sullivan.
</P>
