<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PREVIEW-APES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV FALLS FOR MONKEY BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There is a weird kind of beauty and a right kind
of justice in the fact that a show called ``The Chimp Channel''
debuts at the end of the television season. In a surreal way,
watching chimpanzees and orangutans in costume, spoofing such show
biz as ``The Larry Sanders Show,'' just makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the time, mind you. Often you're left to wonder if you
haven't fallen into some hellish ``Planet of the Apes'' nightmare
in which you've not only accepted your situation, you're pretty
excited about a new TV show littered with simians.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you with a keen ability to read between the lines,
you'll notice throughout that this is a plea for help.
</P>
<P>
   Has it really come to this? That television has gone from live
action to animation and now the third wave, chimps, as characters?
``The Chimp Channel'' (7:05 p.m. Thursday, TBS) is a half-hour
sitcom, neatly replacing ``Friends'' if you think about it.
</P>
<P>
   The all-ape experience, as TBS likes to say, is a spin-off of
its popular between-show fillers called ``Monkey-ed Movies,'' which
used apes to spoof popular movies. Viewers loved the idea so much
that TBS decided to make a series out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, we see that cable is the land of the really big
thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem with reviewing ``The Chimp Channel.'' I
couldn't help but stare at the screen and say, ``Are you kidding
me?'' Even worse _ I was liking it. When you find yourself
dissecting the premise as well as plot twists while watching
monkeys, then two things are abundantly clear: 1) It's June and the
TV season should be over; and 2) Because it's not, you have TV
poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   As part of me kept thinking, ``Houston, we have a problem,'' the
other part said that absurdity is a good thing and that this is a
show far superior to much of the creatively blanched network
offerings. And so, you go with it. That'd be my advice. Because
``The Chimp Channel'' has moments when you're laughing out loud.
It's only when you catch yourself, look around the room and think,
``I've been reduced to laughing at monkeys in wigs,'' that there
may be a tiny question about sanity or a bigger issue about taste.
</P>
<P>
   Too late. I watched two episodes and if it is the end of
television creativity as we know it, count me in.
</P>
<P>
   Monkeys in wigs are funny. Maybe not as funny in January as they
are in June, but funny nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's good to have a TV show you don't have to watch every week.
A show like ``The Chimp Channel'' is disposable. It takes the
stress off you. If you catch it, great. If you miss it _ hey, just
a bunch of monkeying around. No big deal.
</P>
<P>
   The premise _ and, yes, there is a premise _ of this show is
that a handful of simians are running TCC, ``The Chimp Channel.''
The fictional network airs movies, TV series, news and commercials.
(All starring chimps.)
</P>
<P>
   The characters include Ford Carter, the owner of TCC, who is
seen only on his jet, often leering at women. He has an Australian
accent, so if you guessed Rupert Murdoch, you're pop savvy enough
to continue watching this show.
</P>
<P>
   There's Harry Waller, TCC president. Straight out of central
casting. Brock Hammond _ ``hunky star'' _ who often is forced to be
in every TCC show because of budget problems (and he often plays
more than one role in each). Then there's superdiva Marina,
``ruthless and power mad'' and meant to be a cross between Pamela
Anderson and Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   There's Murray Price, a not-so-subtle jab at Larry King, a
celebrity interviewer and multiple-marriage bed-hopper. Timmy Briar
is the young intern (played by a cute monkey, by the way), who is
naive beyond belief. There's Candy, the makeup girl, who is sweet
but also sarcastic. And there are the two writers of most of the
shows, Biff, a slacker (he's actually a nice send-up of real-life
young TV writers), and Stan (a thinly veiled Woody Allen type).
TCC's news anchor is George W. Heinlein, and the ``W'' indicates he
takes himself very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   What gets spoofed on ``The Chimp Channel''? Everything. There's
``Treewatch,'' complete with red bathing suits. ``NYPD Zoo,'' an
Ebert-like character for ``Movies on Film,'' Larry King's show, and
a bevy of modern hits such as ``Ally McBeal,'' ``The X- Files,''
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and even ``The Teletubbies.''
</P>
<P>
   Often these spoofs are dead on, so if you're a fan you'll be
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, there's a nice skewering of ``Touched by an
Angel,'' which becomes ``Touched by an Anvil,`` and ``America's
Most Uncomfortable Videos,'' a deadly send-up of all those groin
thwacks.
</P>
<P>
   When the spoofing is done, it's the behind-the-scenes moments
with the characters that drive the narrative. That is, if the laws
of criticism even allow the use of ``drive the narrative'' when
referring to monkeys in clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chimp Channel'' isn't always funny. It's often just silly.
</P>
<P>
   Other times, it's hilarious. And sometimes it's surprisingly
racy.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't need much more to go on than this: We're talking
about apes, here. Dressed up like dolls. With a ``Mystery Science
Theater 3000'' sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't PBS. But then again, it's probably not as low as TV
will go.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
