<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAXES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PLEDGES HE'LL OPPOSE ANY INCOME TAX INCREASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Read his letter: Gov. George W. Bush will
``oppose and veto'' any income tax increases if he's elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   Reminiscent of the famous ``read my lips, no new taxes'' pledge
his father lived to regret, the son of former President Bush made
the promise in a letter to Grover Norquist of the influential
Americans for Tax Reform of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will oppose and veto any increase in individual or corporate
marginal income tax rates or individual or corporate income tax
hikes,'' Bush wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He also promised the group that he would oppose any efforts to
wipe out tax deductions or credits unless they were offset ``dollar
for dollar'' by tax rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said such increases would hurt the country's ability to
provide ``high quality, high paying jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, then Vice President George Bush told the nation he
would not stand for any new taxes if elected president. Two years
later, in a decision many say cost him re-election, President Bush
accepted tax increases as part of a deficit reduction package.
</P>
<P>
   Some have accused Gov. George W. Bush of committing a similar
gaffe by promising in a 1994 letter to oppose any increases in the
state sales tax. As governor three years later, Bush proposed a
sales tax increase _ unsuccessfully _ but said he didn't break his
word because it was part of a broader package of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The new tax pledge came as Bush begins to firm up his political
positions in advance of his first out-of-state trip to drum up
support for an all-but-certain 2000 presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday, just days before he heads for the
first-test states of Iowa and New Hampshire, the man widely
regarded as the Republican presidential front-runner broke a long
silence on one of the most gut-wrenching political decisions in
U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes that President Clinton should have been
removed from office because of improprieties stemming from his
involvement with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who had steadfastly declined to take a position on the
impeachment and subsequent trial of the president when it was
happening, told reporters he would have voted for Clinton's removal
in February if he had been a member of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have voted for it, yes,'' Bush said. Asked why, the
governor said: ``Because I thought the man lied.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was impeached by the House in December on two charges _
perjury and obstruction of justice _ stemming from his trysts with
Lewinsky. He was acquitted two months later by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the acquittal, Bush declined to say whether he
thought the Senate made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision was made, and that's the good news,'' he said.
``It's off our TV screens, hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush defended his early, cautious approach: ``I
didn't talk about it during the time because I thought the House
and Senate members could make up their minds. I did say it was
embarrassment, and I did say it was important to blow the whistle
on not telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
