r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PROFILE-THOMAS-H     06-09 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PROFILE-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THAT NEWSWOMAN' REPORTS ON LIFE IN THE FIRING LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Were it not for the televised presidential news
conference, Helen Thomas speculates that she would be as anonymous
as any other wire-service reporter in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, television has made the veteran White House
correspondent for United Press International something of a
celebrity _ or, as she puts it, a ``bit player on the national
stage.''
</P>
<P>
   When the president steps to the podium, the cameras dwell on him
for a moment, then zoom in on the diminutive woman in the front
row, hunched over a note pad, whose seniority has earned her the
right to ask the first question at presidential news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   She says she often is stopped on the street or at airports by
strangers. ``What's the president really like?'' they ask.
</P>
<P>
   Often they urge her to pester the commander-in-chief for more
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll say, `Keep asking those tough questions' and `You're
talking for us,''' Thomas said in a recent interview. ``Sometimes,
they'll look at you and do a double take, and then they sort of
place you. `Aren't you that newswoman? Aren't you the woman they
love to hate?'''
</P>
<P>
   In 38 years on the White House beat, she has covered every
president from Kennedy to Clinton. She is the longest-serving
correspondent at the White House and the first woman to take over
the tradition of closing a news conference with, ``Thank you, Mr.
President.''
</P>
<P>
   She has become enough of a White House fixture that in
Hollywood's 1993 presidential parody, ``Dave,'' she was asked to
play herself. When the president, played by Kevin Kline, makes a
supposedly bold policy announcement, the camera catches Thomas
rolling her eyes. Asked later if she was coached by the director,
she claimed, ``It was a natural reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   A pioneering journalist, she was one of the first female
reporters at the White House to cover the president rather than the
first lady. An outspoken feminist, she helped browbeat the
previously all-male National Press Club into accepting women
members.
</P>
<P>
   Now Thomas has written a new book, ``Front Row at the White
House'' (Scribner, $26), a memoir of four decades spent covering
eight presidents _ Kennedy, Johnson, Nixon, Ford, Carter, Reagan,
Bush and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On a tour to promote the book, she said she has no plans to
retire, even as she approaches her 79th birthday in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never leave my job,'' she said. ``I love my work. When
you love your work, it's not work.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for her relentless questioning, she has gotten under the
skin of every president she's covered. Although Clinton has called
her ``the embodiment of fearless integrity,'' Gerald Ford called
her approach a ``fine blend of journalism and acupuncture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They hate us,'' Thomas said of the relations between the
president and the White House press corps. ``They wish that they
could blow a whistle and we would be there when they need us. But
we really are a pain in the neck to them.''
</P>
<P>
   For Thomas, who is on leave, the book tour has its perks.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving at the Hotel Nikko in San Francisco last week,
she was recognized at the front desk and the hotel staff upgraded
her room to a lavish suite.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a cream-colored suit and a double strand of pearls,
she talked about her middle-class upbringing in Depression-era
Detroit and her start in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   She was the seventh of nine children born to parents who
immigrated from Syria at the turn of the century. Her Arab lineage
is a little-known fact, even in Washington, mostly because of her
Anglo-Saxon last name. Her father's surname, Antonious, was
Anglicized to Thomas by an immigration officer at Ellis Island in
1892.
</P>
<P>
   Though a member of the only Arab family on a block of Italians
and Germans, Thomas never viewed herself as an Arab-American. As
she writes in the new book, ``We did not think of ourselves as
hyphenates, which seems to be the standard description when one
talks of ethnic background. The term melting pot has fallen into
disrepute these days, but that is how we saw ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither of her parents could read or write English, but Thomas
found her passion writing for her high school newspaper. After
college, she moved to Washington. Her first job was as a copy girl
for The Washington Daily News. As more men were drafted to fight in
World War II, she was promoted to cover local news.
</P>
<P>
   When the war ended, many of the same men returned to reclaim
their jobs, forcing women reporters out. But Thomas, who was then
working the early-morning shift writing radio stories for United
Press, stayed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to work at 5:30 in the morning,'' she recalled.
``No one really wanted my job, so I lucked out.''
</P>
<P>
   When she first started at the White House in 1961 after John F.
Kennedy's election, women reporters there were seen largely as
society columnists. And many of her early reports were about what
the first lady wore or about daughter Caroline and her pets. But
being at the White House also meant covering the daily news
briefings, and Thomas soon found herself writing about the
president.
</P>
<P>
   As she began to cover the same stories as her male counterparts,
she bristled at the rules that barred women from the National Press
Club. She joined a revolt with other female journalists to open the
club to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't belong to the National Press Club, because I was a
woman, until 1971. 1971!'' Thomas said, still incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   The book is, at times, too narrowly focused on the minutiae of
her years in Washington. For example, an entire chapter is devoted
to her favorite D.C. restaurant. But sprinkled throughout the book
are bright anecdotes and often trenchant insights into the tense
relations between presidents and the White House correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In October 1965, when Thomas surprised President Lyndon Johnson
by breaking a story about his 18-year-old daughter, Luci, flying to
Texas with a boyfriend to get her father's blessing for an
engagement, a fuming LBJ had his daughter's plane diverted from the
airport to avoid reporters. The engagement was announced two months
later.
</P>
<P>
   After Ford earned a reputation for stumbling, falling down
stairs and bumping his head, Thomas tells how his press secretary
hid reporters behind bushes when Ford was boarding a helicopter to
try to keep them from witnessing more mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   She also describes the emotion of seeing Air Force One return to
Andrews Air Force Base with the body of a slain JFK and watching
Jackie Kennedy deplane, still wearing her blood-stained pink wool
suit. Thomas says she was holding back tears as she dictated
another reporter's account of the assassination over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, she discusses her 11-year marriage to her former
competitor at the White House, Doug Cornell of the Associated
Press. Thomas helped care for him during his last years as he
suffered from Alzheimer's disease. He died in 1972 at age 75.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said her younger UPI colleagues do most of the travel
with the president, but she still clocks in at the White House most
mornings by 5:30 a.m. and hates to be beat by competitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
