<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF WE'D WON, WOULDN'T IT LOOK BETTER?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So. Is the war over or not?
</P>
<P>
   You'd have thought from listening to the weekend gabfests on
television and reading the ponderings of the pundits in the Sunday
papers that the last bomb had been dropped, the last missile fired,
the last civilian structure inadvertently blown to smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   But then Monday rolled around, and suddenly the peace plan that
was being touted as the ``endgame'' in NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia
was coming unglued and the war was on again.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, nobody seemed to know which end was up: One news
report warned of ``significant roadblocks'' to peace, while another
promised that the deal was about to ``fall back into place.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it all depended on which spinmeisters were talking to
which newshounds.
</P>
<P>
   The head spinmeister, of course, is William Jefferson Clinton,
president of the United States. But Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright is no slouch when it comes to the art of spinning, which
as we know requires the spinner to say nothing and make it sound
like something.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Albright said, according to The Associated Press:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting the pieces into place. It all depends on
compliance, verifiable compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, sure. Everybody knew that. Didn't they?
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Albright, Clinton and other happy warriors who
are trying to paint this Yugoslav military adventure as a great
success is a simple one: It isn't a great success.
</P>
<P>
   If the good guys had really won this war against indicted war
criminal Slobodan Milosevic _ as the commentators have been
suggesting for days on end _ wouldn't they be dictating the terms
of peace instead of negotiating with him? It's one of the few good
things about war: The side that wins gets to tell the side that
loses what's going to happen next.
</P>
<P>
   But then, when the war is a half-baked operation like the one
NATO has been conducting against Yugoslavia, it only stands to
reason that the result will be half-baked as well. By taking the
option of a ground invasion off the table at the outset, NATO _ or
should we say Clinton? _ could achieve victory only by bombing
Milosevic into submission.
</P>
<P>
   That obviously hasn't happened. Milosevic clearly had enough
fight left in him by the time NATO proclaimed peace to be at hand
that he was able to throw up ``significant roadblocks'' to the
cessation of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to dictate to a dictator, you have to bring him to
his knees. And the smart money has said all along that you can't do
that with bombing alone.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, let's give Clinton and NATO the benefit of the doubt.
Let's say that the air campaign has achieved the hoped-for result:
an agreement under which Milosevic will remove Serbian troops from
Kosovo and allow an international peacekeeping force to oversee the
return of ethnic Albanians to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   That may constitute victory as Clinton and the spinmeisters
define it, but it's no victory in any meaningful sense of the word.
Such an arrangement merely intensifies American involvement in the
Balkans, merely drags the U.S. deeper into the quagmire of ethnic,
political and religious strife that has plagued the region for
hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers _ a significant number of whom will be
Americans _ will be tantamount to an occupying force in Yugoslavia.
But they will be occupying a country that they haven't conquered, a
horrendous situation that was virtually guaranteed when Clinton
ruled out the use of ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that a ground war would have been a good
idea. It would have been a mistake, just as the air war was a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. involvement in a European civil war that is not, never was
and never will be our business is a no-win situation,
notwithstanding any claims of victory by the idea's instigators.
</P>
<P>
   Even if this poorly conceived and executed war should
miraculously bring peace and stability to a part of the world where
war and instability have been the status quo for centuries, it was
a terrible idea.
</P>
<P>
   And it's only getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
