<HEADLINE>
DR. BOB'S INTERNET SERVICES ARE REALLY CLICKING
</HEADLINE>
 CPT- DOCTORS-INTERNET-TEX 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  FORT WORTH,
Texas _ Someday soon, you will be able to dial ``star'' DR
(''star'' 37) on your push-button phone, ask your medical
questions, and get within hours personalized answers from a doctor
who specializes in your medical problems.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The telephone, that most basic of communication tools, is being
integrated with computer software, radio and television to get
consumers the medical information they want when they want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information exchange is going to be ``the issue'' in medicine
for at least the next 20 years,'' says Dr. Bob Lanier,
physician-broadcaster and president-elect of the Tarrant County
Medical Society, who is already aggressively using the Internet to
provide information for a growing number of people with health-care
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   His Web site, www.askdrbob.com, averages 1,000 hits a day, and
he gets 300 to 400 e-mail questions daily.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a new software package Lanier has created, he is able
to answer a lot of questions very quickly, but he is enlisting the
help of a dozen other Tarrant County physicians, specializing in
various areas, to help with the service as it grows worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next phase will involve live chats, and we will have the
ability to push people to the Web sites they need,'' Lanier says.
``Every disease you can think of has dozens of Web sites, and there
are pharmacists available 24 hours a day to answer drug questions.
You can get people psychotherapy over the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the new medical service to coordinate and expand
the computer services already in effect came up when Lanier
realized that his ``Sixty Second Housecall'' television and radio
broadcasts were generating a lot of questions from people in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The medical advice program is carried over 17 stations in Canada
and 47 stations in this country, yet more than 60 percent of his
e-mail was coming from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, why would people in a country where health care is
free use this service so much, and I realized it's because they
have to wait even longer for their medical care than Americans.
People can't get into their doctors' offices,'' Lanier says.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Lanier gets the most questions from young boys and
older women, who seem to use the service in part because they want
to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers ask questions they don't feel comfortable asking in
person. Women often ask about sexual function, new mothers about
colic, young boys about their genitalia, little girls about
menstrual cycles and child abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanier says he often makes referrals, including international
referrals to allergists he knows in Scotland and France. When he
doesn't know a specialist needed in a particular part of the
country, he tells people how to contact their own local medical
societies and how to ask for the information they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible now to have this global reach, to help people
all over the world,'' Lanier says. ``We are there to give
information, but not medical therapy. It's not exactly practicing
medicine. We're not writing prescriptions or doing diagnostic
tests. Our action step is education.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-08-99 1705EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
