<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8739 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MA-HIGHTECH-ART-B     06-09 1737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MA-HIGHTECH-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE FIRMS EMPOWER A RESURGENT HIGH-TECH SECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers 
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOWELL, Mass. _ The old office is empty on the 14th floor of the
former Wang Laboratories tower, where John Thibault once addressed
his boss, ``Dr. Wang,'' about the day's business.
</P>
<P>
   But one floor below, 10 years later, Thibault has built a
technology empire of his own. Geotel Communications Corp.'s offices
whir with personal computers as 300 employees design the software
used by American Express, Fidelity Investments, and the nation's
major airlines to route customer calls.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, Thibault and Geotel's other founders received the
ultimate endorsement of their success: Cisco Systems Inc., the
nation's largest computer networking company, agreed to buy their
5-year-old firm for $1.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of upheaval, in which the giants of the high-tech
community in Massachusetts have faded away, a new generation of
companies like Geotel has risen to take their place. Unlike their
predecessors, which staked their fortunes on making computers, the
hundreds of start-ups that now dominate the state's high-tech
landscape are selling software rather than hardware and ideas and
services rather than products.
</P>
<P>
   They are, to a large extent, creatures of new technologies,
especially the Internet. Many are small ventures, with only a
handful of employees. Most will never approach the size of Wang or
Digital Equipment Corp., the once-giant companies synonymous with
the Route 128 culture of the 1980s. Instead, like Geotel, many are
being acquired when they are only a few years old by larger
companies hungry for their innovations.
</P>
<P>
   As these new companies have flourished, they have created a
high-tech economy that is far broader than it was a decade ago,
with a dozen or so sectors ranging from telecommunications to
Internet software development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts has probably the most diverse set of high-tech
companies in the country,'' said Sara Johnson, an economist and
former member of the state Council on Economic Growth and
Technology. ``Most other tech centers are focused on one or two
industry clusters. We have them all.''
</P>
<P>
   And these high-tech companies have also been a major force in
propelling growth in a variety of industries from financial
services to medicine, driving employment to record levels in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers help illuminate the transformation of the high-tech
industry in Massachusetts:
</P>
<P>
   --Employment in software and Internet companies jumped 75
percent from 1992 through 1997, to 68,983 jobs from 39,501 jobs,
according to a study by the Massachusetts Technology Collaborative,
a privately funded research group. During the prior five years, the
gain was a modest 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   --Massachusetts is now home to some 2,751 software companies, up
from 800 in 1989, according to the Massachusetts Software Council,
a trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   --About half of the high-tech workers in the state hold
nonmanufacturing jobs, a shift from 1988 when more than two-thirds
of the technology work force was employed by manufacturers,
according to the state's Department of Employment and Training.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic changes in the high-tech industry are being driven
by a new generation of entrepreneurs and engineers, many of whom
were educated in Boston and stayed after graduation. Some left jobs
at Wang, Digital and other established companies to start anew.
They are taking advantage of a wave of capital generated by a
booming stock market and a so-far unwavering belief that the
Internet is transforming the US economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, venture capital firms poured a record $141 million a
month into fledgling Massachusetts companies, according to the
accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers. The total of $1.7 billion
invested last year was more than triple 1995's investment of $470
million.
</P>
<P>
   The ventures started with this money epitomize a new high-tech
culture where employees seem animated by ideas more than loyalty to
any one company. Ken Lang, the chief technology officer for Lycos
Inc., the state's most prominent Internet company, put it simply:
``I don't think there are 1950s company men any more, especially in
the Internet industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang's path to Waltham-based Lycos, an Internet search service,
began after he graduated from Duke with a quadruple major in
physics, computer science, math and engineering. He quit work on a
doctorate in artificial intelligence, on the advice of his
professor and Lycos founder Michael Mauldin, and started WiseWire,
which compiles profiles of Internet users. Last year, Lycos bought
WiseWire _ and hired Lang.
</P>
<P>
   Two walls of Lang's office are whiteboards covered with a
magic-marker rainbow of diagrams of ``mind-blowing'' ideas for new
products, including a game site and an interactive Web site. He
sees his job as not just designing products but as shaping the
World Wide Web's future. ``When you're stepping into areas nobody
has stepped into before, it's up to you to decide what the future
is like,'' Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   While other Massachusetts high-tech companies have become
national names _ EMC Corp. in Franklin, for example, has become the
dominant maker of computer-storage systems _ most remain largely
unknown, with mysterious sounding names like Altiga Networks,
Sapient, and Dragon Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Often, they are nearly invisible because they focus on
``under-the-hood'' software or services used by other businesses.
Many are start-ups barely off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, Tom Leighton, a math professor at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and one of his students, Dan
Lewin, started Akamai Technologies Inc. in Cambridge's Kendall
Square, a high-tech mecca. The pair are using mathematics in an
attempt to solve a vexing problem on the Internet: system crashes
like the one that occurred when millions of users tried to visit a
Victoria's Secret fashion show that was advertised during last
year's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dolce, chief executive of Redstone Communications Inc. in
Westford, compared the Internet to the Industrial Revolution of a
century ago. His company _ and others clustered along Interstate
495 _ is developing technology to enable telephone, cable, and
computer companies to handle the exponential growth in the amount
of data moving through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet ``has changed from a toy _ an entertainment device
_ to a real business tool,'' Dolce said. ``No one realizes  &UR; today &LR; 
the kind of impact this will have in the next five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the Internet, the breathtaking expansion of the
technology sector in Massachusetts has grown to encompass other
businesses. The state is experiencing a boom, for example, in
computer consulting companies, such as Cambridge Technology
Partners and Sapient, that help clients update computers and
software systems. Boston has become a center for the design and
sale of interactive CD-ROMs for education and business, an industry
that didn't even exist 10 years ago. And increased use of computer
technology over the past decade has driven innovations and growth
by medical device companies in the state.
</P>
<P>
   These changes and more have created a high-tech economy that is
much different from a decade ago when high tech meant one thing:
manufacturing. The computer giants that fueled the high-tech boom
in the 1980s, such as Digital and Wang, failed to keep up with the
PC revolution. As computer manufacturing headed south, these giants
suffered massive layoffs that devastated the state's entire
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1990, said Craig Moore, an economics professor at
University of Massachusetts at Amherst, ``a lot of economists were
saying, `Did we just go over the precipice?' It was devastating. ''
But, the economy  &UR; today &LR;  ``doesn't look anything like it did in
1990,'' he added. ``We now have 10 or 12 major industries (in
high-tech) that have grown and flourished.''
</P>
<P>
   While the industry has successfully remade itself, some of the
high-tech jobs that were lost in the late 1980s and early 1990s
still have not been replaced. According to the Massachusetts
Division of Employment and Training, 303,300 residents work in the
high tech industry _ 31,900 fewer than in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard deKaser, an economist for BankBoston Corp., stressed
that these numbers are based on old and outmoded ways of measuring
high-tech employment. The impact of the booming industry goes far
beyond companies counted as high-tech concerns by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The employment numbers tend to underrepresent the importance
of the industry'' to the state's economy, DeKaser said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the high-tech transformation has brought lasting changes
to Massachusetts' work force and has spilled into businesses as
seemingly unrelated to the industry as financial services.
</P>
<P>
   At State Street Bank &AMP; Trust Co.'s computer operation in Quincy,
Herbert Clark oversees a state-of-the art system that tracks $4.8
trillion in investment dollars as closely as NASA tracks a space
flight. Clark, who grew up in Braintree and attended Blue Hills
Technical College, clearly prefers this challenging job to his
previous job in the checking-processing department of a bank,
because ``the technology's constantly changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation in the high-tech sector has also forced
employees of the old economy to change with it.
</P>
<P>
   Workers such as Bob O'Brien, 46, have been retrained after years
of joblessness. Laid off by Wang in 1990, O'Brien said he is just
as busy now working in EMC's immaculate huge new plant in Franklin,
where data-storage computers are tested in a steamy tropical room,
a ``cool room,'' and a ``vibrating room.''
</P>
<P>
   While O'Brien has benefited from a surge in EMC's employment to
3,800 currently _ and 1,200 more will be hired this year _ his
memories of the 1980s bust still sting: ``The whole world stopped
spinning,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien speaks with some disbelief about the sweeping changes he
has witnessed firsthand. ``I never would have thought,'' he said,
``it would be at this same pace as it was in the mid to late
'80s.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-08-99 1508EDT &QL;
</P>
