<HEADER>
A8740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECH-HANDICAP10-C     06-09 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-HANDICAP10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Opening lives by keyboard
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A little more than a year ago, Sharon Mazzotti's
foster son, Danny, walked through the door of her home for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Danny is mentally and physically handicapped. When he walked in,
his head hung low, like he had just been caught stealing. He was
17, and he was not able to brush his teeth or bathe himself.
Cerebral palsy kept his hands in an almost permanent fist.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that has since changed. And Mazzotti, 55, attributes it
to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' she said. ``Learning how to do basic things on a
computer opened a door. It made him realize he could think, that he
could use his brain. If you could have seen him when he walked
through this door, just his posture and his facial expressions. Now
he stands up straighter. We never have to tell him to hold his head
up anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny took computer classes on Saturdays through a group started
by Tony Perrone.
</P>
<P>
   A former computer network administrator, Perrone was injured in
1986 when a pickup truck he was working on fell on him. He has not
had use of his legs since. But he still had his computer expertise.
</P>
<P>
   After a few years of physical therapy and a few unsuccessful
attempts at trying to get paid for what he knew, Perrone, 58,
decided to give it away.
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, word had spread among the North Georgia disabled
community that Perrone had a lot of computer knowledge and a lot of
free time. People started calling, asking if he could help their
disabled children learn how to run a PC. Perrone would come to them
and teach, for free. He asked for gas money in return.
</P>
<P>
   Demand grew, and Perrone started a training center. In September
1997, he opened Project Re-Compute, with two metro Atlanta offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could still do it, but when you go for a job in one of
these,'' Perrone said, gesturing toward his wheelchair, ``they
don't see you, they see the wheelchair. I felt if they could do
this to me and I've got a master's degree, what are they going to
do to other people with disabilities?''
</P>
<P>
   The main benefit to education, Perrone said, is self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more that people can believe in doing, the more they want
to learn,'' he said. ``They gain the confidence they didn't have
before, and they have a new respect for themselves because of the
technology they learn.''
</P>
<P>
   The courses are free. They are open to anyone with a disability
and a yearly income of less than $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Students attend classes for 16 weeks. As a graduation perk, each
student receives a computer, as long as there is one to give. In
return, they are asked to commit to 50 hours of community service
at any non-profit agency.
</P>
<P>
   Perrone relies on donated computers and donated time. His
non-profit organization has an all-disabled, all-volunteer staff of
26. He repairs the computers, upgrading them so they run popular
operating systems like Windows 95 or Office 97. Perrone does
repairs and upgrades, replaces hard drives and adds memory. For
kids in the Saturday classes, he loads Windows 3.1, games and
educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   Until last summer, he ran the center using his Social Security
check. Now it is day-to-day. He receives office space in exchange
for maintaining the building's computer network.
</P>
<P>
   Perrone said his goal is to give people with disabilities an
employable skill. Last year, 269 adults attended classes at
Perrone's centers. Of those, 22 percent found full-time work, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzotti's foster son, Danny, started attending Saturday classes
last June. His goals were more basic: learning how to type his
first and last name and knowing where each letter is on the
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the computer might open a door for him, and it
did,'' she said. ``It seemed to me that the door to his mind really
opened. He started trying to talk and he still continues to. I
don't think he knew he could do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny comprehends everything you say, but now he is able to
let you know that he does,'' Mazzotti said. ``I really believe that
seeing what he could do, seeing that he could find the letters on
the keyboard _ these are simple things to you and I, but he had
never experienced them before.''
</P>
<P>
   If you know of others who use technology to help in your
community, tell us about them. E-mail: altantatech(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
