<SLUG> BC-CPT-CHIP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Fast Chip Lets Laptops Play 3-D Games By Henry Norr  &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  Forget solitaire. Laptop-toting
<TEXT>
travelers soon may be able to while away the airborne hours with
Quake, Unreal and other hot 3-D action games.
<P>
   At least that's what S3 Inc. says its new graphics chips for
mobile computers will make possible. The Santa Clara company claims
that its Savage/MX and Savage/IX 3-D accelerators will deliver
three times the speed and six times the image quality of the chips
now used in notebook PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Overall performance won't match that of the latest graphics
chips for desktop PCs, but it'll be good enough, S3 said, to make
leading games playable on laptops for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The new chips will go into mass production by the end of this
month, according to the company. Notebook PCs that include them
should show up on retail shelves by September, in plenty of time
for the holiday shopping season. S3 said ``numerous top-tier PC
manufacturers'' are redesigning their notebooks to incorporate the
Savage chips, but officials declined to name specific customers.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Glaskowsky, senior editor of the Microprocessor Report, an
industry newsletter published in Sebastopol, said he's seen actual
games running on prototypes of the mobile Savage chips. ``They
looked fine to me,'' he said. ``Not as good as on a 500-MHz Pentium
III with a Voodoo card (a 3-D accelerator favored by desktop
gamers), but that doesn't matter _ people don't expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Glaskowsky said, few notebook models have graphics
chips tailored to 3-D, but ``eventually, they all will.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chips owe their speed, plus the low power consumption
required of notebook chips, in large part to the new,
state-of-the-art production process S3 will use to build them.
Circuits on the chips will be only .18 micron wide, or about one
five-hundredth the width of a human hair.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile Savage chips also will let users connect their
notebooks to standard desktop monitors and use both screens at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   The new products could boost S3's effort to pull out of a severe
slump, Glaskowsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1989, the company led the market in graphics chips
for PCs through the mid-1990s. But it fell behind competitors such
as ATI Technologies, and in 1998, it reported losses of $113.2
million on a 46-percent drop in sales compared with the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this year, S3 lost another $13.9 million
and sales were down 48.5 percent compared with the same quarter a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But its Savage4 graphics chip for desktop PCs, introduced in
February, has been well received, and first-quarter sales were up
slightly from the last quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-06-99 2118EDT &QL;
</P>
