<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8750 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERB-POLICE-KOSOVO-NY     06-09 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERB-POLICE-KOSOVO-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB POLICE MUST GO, BUT SO WILL KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ The Serbs are right that their future sovereignty over
Kosovo will be put in doubt by the force withdrawal NATO has
demanded, even though reference in the Rambouillet text providing
for a referendum after three years has been eliminated.
 &HT;    This is part of the wages of war. Short of dramatic, ideally
democratic changes in former Yugoslavia, no international accord
can guarantee that Kosovar Albanians will abandon their claim to
independence in the foreseeable future. And it is absolutely
essential, for an orderly end to the war, that all Serb force in
Kosovo be removed.
 &HT;    Although they don't seem to be specifically mentioned in the
agreement, local Serb police and paramilitaries who are themselves
Kosovars must be included. In effect, they would be expelled rather
than withdrawn. But this is necessary if the international force is
to have a reasonable chance of disarming the KLA and encouraging
conversion of the guerrillas into a political movement.
 &HT;    It is precisely the local police who mistreated the ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo for so long and committed some of the worst
atrocities. They are known to their former neighbors and victims.
 &HT;    The pacifist Kosovar leader Ibrahim Rugova speaks now of
reconciliation and protection of those Serbs who remain in the
province. But it is too much to expect that there will be no
attempts at vengeance and retribution if known killers and
torturers remain.
 &HT;    It is doubtless illusory to suppose the allied peace-keepers can
fully disarm the KLA. In the best of circumstances, arms will be
stashed away and hidden, a Balkan tradition. But to achieve civil
peace, it will have to be clear that the ethnic Albanians are fully
protected, and for that the former police must go.
 &HT;    Many Kosovar Serbs are likely to flee to other parts of Serbia
as a result, since they know what happened and the fierce degree of
hatred which will not soon diminish. The eagerness of Moscow, no
doubt at Belgrade's insistence, to have a special sector under
control of Russian troops without any NATO presence is obviously
aimed at enabling these Serbs to remain.
 &HT;    But NATO is right to refuse flatly, since that would assuredly
lead to partition of the province. It is the other side of ethnic
cleansing. The instigators lose their ability to keep their own
homes by the fury they have provoked among their neighbors.
International forces will have to protect Serb monasteries and
monuments until some distant day when there is real,
self-sustaining peace in the region.
 &HT;    Presumably the Russian demand not to have their forces under
NATO can be accommodated by the kind of sleight-of-hand they
accepted in Bosnia, where their contingent is directly under an
American commander, who is himself under NATO orders. They might
prefer a French or British intermediate level, but whatever
solution is found it must be clear that Russians cannot apply
different rules where they are in the field. Otherwise, returning
refugees would not feel secure.
 &HT;    The importance of getting peace-keeping mechanics right from the
start is that this will determine the way Kosovar politics will
develop and the chances for organizing democratic, nonviolent
contests for power under an international administration.
 &HT;    Confidence in security is needed both for relaunching civil life
and for preventing guerrillas or armed bands from organizing their
own rival systems. The worst nightmare would be an Afghanistan-type
conflict of clans, which is not impossible.
 &HT;    Rugova, who was elected in unofficial, more or less clandestine
elections which the Albanian Kosovars conducted some years ago,
boycotting the Serb administration, evidently intends to assert his
claim to leadership now. He is an honest, profoundly decent man who
can be trusted to seek peace, but it isn't clear whether his
failure to achieve any concessions whatsoever from Serbia over a
decade has left him any influence on his compatriots.
 &HT;    In any case, he is no less dedicated to the goal of independence
than the armed rebels, he just never believed in fighting. It is
allied policy to reject that goal, partly because other countries
worry about the precedent of secession among their own minorities,
partly because of fears it would bring possibly violent efforts for
border changes throughout the region.
 &HT;    But ordinary Serbs are aware that an autonomous, internationally
protected Kosovo is not going to be a real part of their territory,
whatever the legal pretense. It is as well to push the issue off
into a future where hopefully such things can be handled with calm
political negotiation. The dream solution would be a new,
democratic Yugoslav or even Balkan confederation, European
Union-style.
 &HT;    That is a very long way off, but as Jean Monnet understood for
western Europe in the aftermath of World War II, it is the real way
to assure peace.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1999 Flora Lewis 
