<HEADER>
A8752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY08-COX     06-09 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Most computer glitches are hiccups, not heart attacks
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few of the people I hang out with in what passes for
my personal life are technologists. And since I do this stuff for a
living, most of them have the naive belief that I am a walking
library of hidden computer tips _ things that are too secret and
complex to reveal in my column.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, I do know some computer secrets, and I truly do
hesitate to reveal them in this column. But that's not because they
are complex. It's because the real secrets of fixing a computer are
so simple, they're disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   But since we know each other pretty well by now, I will invite
you into the hidden world of computer mysteries. These are some of
the methods used by real computer techies when all else fails.
</P>
<P>
   The first secret tip is the most important. It's something I
have learned from my brother the doctor, computer repairmen and
mechanics. If there is a problem, start with the easiest and
least-invasive treatment first. When it comes to computers, many
novices cause enormous problems trying to fix a temporary glitch.
At the first sign of trouble, they are tempted to reformat the
disk, reinstall all their programs and jerk cards out of the
machine with great vigor.
</P>
<P>
   Since so many problems are mere computer hiccups, try simply
restarting the computer if something doesn't work right. In about
70 percent of the cases, the problem will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   But let's say that you've tried that and the problem remains.
Now's the time to think instead of act. Try to recall the last
major change you made to the computer _ whether it was adding new
software or a device. If you've recently made a change, try
removing the new device or software and see if that fixes the
problem. Then, reinstall it.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give you a recent ``for instance'' of that. My uncle's
computer refused to correctly identify the modem. Now, my uncle has
a master's degree in electrical engineering. But you don't need an
EE degree to fix a similar problem. He removed the modem and the
modem driver (just open up Windows' Modem folder in the control
panel and follow the directions for removing the driver). Then he
reinstalled the modem, started the computer again and let Windows
recognize the modem and install the driver.
</P>
<P>
   There are times _ and these are the really frustrating glitches
_ when neither of the first two tips will help. That's when you
need to take the next step. It really isn't a very big one.
Reinstall Windows. But don't remove the old copy. Instead, simply
pop the installation CD in the drive and reinstall. (Make sure you
have the Windows Upgrade disc, not one of the discs included with
some computers that restore the computer to its
right-out-of-the-box configuration _ if you do that, you'll lose a
lot of programs and data.) But, if you use the Microsoft Upgrade
disc, everything _ including the icons on your screen _ will stay
just as they were. (A prudent computer user will have a backup copy
of data on a Zip drive or some other backup device, just in case).
</P>
<P>
   What if that doesn't work?
</P>
<P>
   Now we are getting into the really ugly fixes. These involve
working with the System Registry or even reformatting the hard disk
and reinstalling Windows and all your programs. If you know how to
do these things, then you'll know why I warn novice users not to
try this without more knowledge than I can give them in this
column. So if all that sounds mysterious and intimidating to you,
then good _ you're right to feel intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   So if you are a beginner, your final fix is also a simple one.
Take the computer to a repair shop and get help. I promise that,
whatever the cost of the repair, it will be less expensive than
trying to do it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
