<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8760 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SCI-INTERNET-RESE     06-09 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SCI-INTERNET-RESEARCH-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 UNDATED: government agencies. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Physicists and mathematicians already post many of their
findings, prior to publication in a journal, on a Web site operated
by the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico (xxx.lanl.gov).
But doctors say that biomedical research, especially clinical
research, is different because it can influence the care and
treatment of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Frank, executive director of the American Physiological
Society, which publishes more than 35,000 pages a year in its
journals, said a patient could be injured or killed if a doctor
prescribed a certain course of treatment based on unverified
information posted on the proposed E-biomed site.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard M. Glass, interim co-editor of The Journal of the
American Medical Association, said articles ``often get changed
very extensively'' as they go through the review process. Because
authors are enthusiastic about their work, he said, they often draw
conclusions that go beyond the data, and they may see new
treatments as being more effective than they really are.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, supporters of E-biomed say it could make
valuable information swiftly available to doctors, patients,
researchers and the taxpayers who pay for much of the research.
</P>
<P>
   Charles V. Mobbs, an associate professor of neurobiology at the
Mount Sinai School of Medicine, in New York City, said, ``The
taxpayer is willing to pay for our research; we have an obligation
to make the results of that research available as quickly and
efficiently as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobbs praised Varmus' proposal, saying it could ``revolutionize
the way in which biomedical scientists carry out their work.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, in the electronic version of their
reports, scientists could include film sequences, three-dimensional
images and large sets of data for which there is no space in
printed journals. This would presumably make it easier for other
scientists to replicate and build on the results.
</P>
<P>
   Varmus said that all reports filed in E-biomed could be searched
with a single computerized ``search engine,'' and readers could
jump electronically, by ``hyperlinks,'' to other articles, data
bases and Web sites. In addition, he said, E-biomed could become
``a communal site'' for worldwide discussion of scientific issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-biomed could be the most important change in scientific
communication since the formal journal,'' Dr. David J. Lipman, a
co-author of the proposal for electronic publishing, said in an
interview. Referring to NIH's new $15.6 billion budget, he added,
``We want to get the greatest public benefit in return for that $15
billion investment. We want the most possible eyes to see the
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipman is director of the National Center for Biotechnology
Information, a unit of the National Library of Medicine at the NIH.
</P>
<P>
   In outlining the proposal last month, Varmus said, ``The single
greatest attraction of E-biomed is that all of its scientific
content will be available without barriers to any user with
Internet access.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the proposal profess not to be alarmed at the
potential distribution of ``junk science'' over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One researcher who sent an e-mail comment to the NIH, Dr. Bruce
Swanson of Adelaide, Australia, drew an analogy to the spread of
literacy and printing technology in medieval Europe. ``Were all
books going to be authoritative and accurate?'' he asked. ``Were
some dangerous to society? We can imagine priests saying, `Mass
printing and wide dissemination of books is OK so long as we insure
that every book is approved by a priest review process.'''
</P>
<P>
   Other commenters worry that E-biomed would expand the role and
power of the government. ``I am adamantly opposed to any federal
clearinghouse for scientific information,'' said David H. Farrell,
an associate professor of oral molecular biology at the Oregon
Health Sciences University, in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence P. Reynolds, a professor of reproductive physiology at
North Dakota State University, in Fargo, said: ``It's intrusive for
the government to play the role it's proposing. More than that,
it's unnecessary. Journals are already beginning to publish reports
in electronic format.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Reynolds acknowledged, in many cases, the full text of
articles is available only to paid subscribers or to consumers who
pay a special fee.
</P>
<P>
   E-biomed, as described by Varmus, would have a ``governing
board'' composed of scientists, editors, computer specialists and
representatives of agencies that finance biomedical research. The
NIH would ``assemble'' the board, which in turn would develop
``rules of operation'' for the E-biomed site, Varmus said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, of the American Physiological Society, said he worried
that the choice of board members might be influenced by politics,
and that appointments might have to be cleared through the
department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and critics of E-biomed agree that something like it
is probably inevitable. ``Scientific communication is going to go
electronic,'' said Anthony J. Mazzaschi of the Association of
American Medical Colleges. ``It's just a question of when and
how.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-07-99 1656EDT &QL;
</P>
