<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8827 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-SANCTIONS-$ADV13     06-09 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SANCTIONS-$ADV13-1STLD-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN EDs: updates, fixes, adds throughout
 &HT;    AS WORLD TURNS AWAY FROM IRAQ, IRAQI SUFFERING CONTINUES
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With IRAQ-SCHOOL-$ADV13.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq _ Like most Iraqis, Hamed Khalaf has nothing but
bad choices.
</P>
<P>
   As his country's economy collapses, the 32-year-old unemployed
taxi driver struggles to support his mother and two war-disabled
brothers. First, they sold the house, then the taxi, then the
furniture and the carpets.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he was in Baghdad's outdoor book market. The dour
Khalaf sold off his brothers' collection of Arabic culture picture
journals for about 40 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the last of what I have,'' he says. ``Next, I'll
sell my clothes. I mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, diplomats at the United Nations Security Council are
trying to make their own difficult choices about the sanctions on
Khalaf's Iraq. Proposals range from maintaining the severe status
quo to lifting the sanctions entirely.
</P>
<P>
   When they were imposed after Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
invaded Kuwait in 1990, few thought the sanctions would be needed
more than a year. More than eight years later, life for the 22
million Iraqis in the land of Babylon has taken on truly Old
Testament elements, from pestilence to hunger.
</P>
<P>
   Children die daily for lack of common medicines and from the
``epidemic'' spread, according to the UN, of treatable maladies
like diarrhea and malaria. Much of the drinking water is unclean.
Tuberculosis is about five times more prevalent than before 1990
and 70 percent of Iraqi women are anemic.
</P>
<P>
   In increasing numbers, children drop out of school to become
beggars or street sellers. In school, they sit on classroom floors
and recycle last year's workbooks.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, U.N. reports issued dire warnings about conditions
in Iraq. In fittingly cruel irony, the warnings came as the world
is distracted trying to contain Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic -- another dictator seemingly unharmed by the sanctions
on his country. Iraqi suffering will grind on a while longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is on hold at this point,'' says former
undersecretary of state for the Middle East Richard W. Murphy, who
himself is unsure about what can be done. ``It is a deep
stalemate.''
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions are unprecedented. Notes Richard Garfield, a
sanctions expert and epidemiologist at Columbia University, such
sanctions were nearly impossible during the Cold War. A country
like Cuba could be shut out by one side but get help from the
other. Iraq is isolated by all.
</P>
<P>
   ``No country has experienced such comprehensive sanctions in
this century,'' Garfield says. ``It is a new weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   In a study released in March, Garfield concluded that mortality
rates for children under five years of age are double what they
were before the sanctions. It means that an extra 110,000 to
225,000 Iraqi children have died since the sanctions began.
</P>
<P>
   While Iraq is not as poor as many African or Latin American
nations, it has fallen far. Just 10 years ago, the oil-rich land
had a medical system that was the most respected in the Arab world
and living conditions that compared well with the region.
</P>
<P>
   As years go by, the sanctions get harder to justify, especially
in light of their limited results.
</P>
<P>
   The plan after the war was for weapons inspectors to destroy
Hussein's chemical, biological and nuclear weapons programs of mass
destruction. Hussein was to comply with other obligations, such as
paying reparations to Kuwait, and the sanctions would be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   But the program has lurched from crisis to crisis. Hussein has
not cooperated with the weapons inspectors and, amid repeated U.S.
air strikes, now refuses to let them back in the country.
</P>
<P>
   True, the sanctions have kept Hussein from rebuilding what was
once the fourth largest army in the world. He is not a threat to
his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   However, even some Middle East experts who support the sanctions
concede that they have strengthened Hussein's hold on Iraq by
consolidating the country's little wealth in his regime. A
stalemate, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, with concern building about the privation facing
Iraqis, the U.N. approved the so-called oil-for-food program. It
began in late 1996, and now allows Iraq to sell up to $10.4 billion
in oil annually. One-third goes to repaying Kuwait, the rest is for
food, medicine, clean water and electricity. The money is held and
tracked by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. says that health and nutrition have stopped
deteriorating, but they are not getting better. About a quarter of
Iraqi children are still malnourished.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials point to the oil-for-food program to show they
mean no harm to ordinary Iraqis. But, Iraq's hobbling oil industry
cannot produce anywhere near the $10.4 billion cap and the U.N. has
concluded that even that would not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hussein's own cruel negligence hurts his case for
lifting the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Through oil smuggling, some of which is tolerated by the United
States because the precious commodity goes to allies like Jordan
and Turkey, Hussein can raise an estimated $500 million a year that
is not monitored by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   He spends it on palaces -- building about a dozen since the
sanctions started. Last month, he opened a new vacation village,
with an amusement park, stadiums and a bronze statue of himself. He
is beginning to build what he says will be the largest mosque in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's police have brand new Hyundai patrol cars and the
streets signs brandish new, well-lit portraits of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, though the U.N. monitors the oil money, Iraq
dispenses the goods. It has not done so well.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. recently reported that Iraq has distributed only 48
percent of the $570 million in medical supplies bought over the
last two years. Warehouses, the U.N. noted, are ``literally
overflowing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is that they don't want their people to stop
dying,'' says Amatzia Baram, an Israeli expert on Iraq at
Georgetown University. He says Hussein contributes to his people's
misery to build world sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   But just because a dictator does not care about his people does
not mean the world should turn its back.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. concluded in April that, even with the government's
failings, ``the Iraqi people would not be undergoing such
depravations in the absence of the prolonged measures imposed by
the security council and the effects of war . . . the country has
experienced a shift from relative affluence to massive poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   True, lifting the sanctions would give Hussein access to the
kind of money he needs to rebuild his army, which some estimate
would take $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In March, U.S. Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering told a
Senate committee that U.S. policy seeks to get Hussein removed from
office, but in the meantime will rely on the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.N. sanctions of Iraq are critical to our efforts to contain
Hussein. The sanctions deprive Hussein of the revenue he would
otherwise use to reconstitute weapons of mass destruction. That is
why Hussein has set the lifting of sanctions among his highest
priorities,'' Pickering said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Baram says that Hussein was spending 80 percent of his
money on arms before the Kuwait invasion, so lifting the sanctions
may not improve the lives much for regular Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the sanctions counter that Iraq took care of its
humanitarian needs before the sanctions. They say that if U.S.
officials want to stop Hussein from re-arming, they could lead an
arms embargo or continue the frequent air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   There is a middle option. British diplomats are pushing a
proposal that would require Hussein into cooperate for several
months with weapons inspections, then remove the cap on oil sales.
The money would still be controlled by the U.N., but foreign
companies would be encouraged to rebuild the Iraqi oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the plan is logical, but has two important drawbacks
-- neither the Americans nor the Iraqis have accepted it.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have supported the concept of removing the
cap, but worry that this plan -- highly complex with possible
loopholes -- could give Hussein too much money or reward him for
not complying with weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
   It could take months to sort out, in part because of the world's
pre-occupation with Milosevic and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, now a senior fellow at the New York-based Council on
Foreign Relations, a foreign policy think tank, says U.S. officials
seem in no hurry to deal with Iraq, satisfied that Hussein is
crippled.
</P>
<P>
   He says that is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a moral dimension,'' he says. ``A society has been
eviscerated.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
