r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTSERRAT-BOX-$ADV13     06-09 0256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTSERRAT-BOX-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONTSERRAT: AT A GLANCE
 &HT;    With MONTSERRAT-VOLCANO-$ADV06.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTSERRAT
</P>
<P>
   Population: About 4,500 (down from 12,000 before volcano
eruption).
</P>
<P>
   Area: 39 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Location: 350 miles southeast of Puerto Rico, just off the
Caribbean islands of Antigua and Nevis.
</P>
<P>
   History: Columbus spotted Montserrat in 1493, naming if after an
abbey of the same name in Spain. Irish Catholics settled on the
island in the mid-1600s after leaving their uneasy base on the
Protestant island of St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   Volcano's history: The Soufriere Hills Volcano erupted in July
1995 after nearly four centuries of dormancy. By 1997 it had killed
at least 19 people, forced two-thirds of the population into exile,
and rendered most of the island unsafe for human habitation. The
volcano is still active, though it is becoming dormant.
</P>
<P>
   Government: A British dependent territory, Montserrat has a
representative government with a ministerial system. Queen
Elizabeth II is head of state and is represented by a resident
governor, now Tony Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: The East Caribbean dollar, although most people accept
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   To get travel information: Call the Montserrat Tourist Board at
1-664-491-2230.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
