<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     06-09 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IS A LIVING PHOENIX, RISING REPEATEDLY FROM THE ASHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 13)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Let it be recorded that Bill Clinton is a human
Phoenix, rising repeatedly with renewed life from the ashes of doom
and destruction, like the colorful bird of Egyptian religious
legend.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the most resilient presidents in the 210-year
panorama of the republic. No matter what troubles ensnare him or
how dark the future appears, he manages to emerge victorious.
</P>
<P>
   The latest example of his ability to ride to triumph when
disaster was predicted is the tenuous peace agreement in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, politicians, columnists, editorial writers and
television commentators labeled NATO's air assault a failure. The
war against Slobodan Milosevic's treachery, they claimed, could not
be won through air power alone; ground troops were a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, some said, Milosevic already had won the war when he
achieved his goal of forcing roughly a million ethnic Albanians
from their homes in Kosovo. And, they added, echoing pre-World War
II isolationists who viewed the Atlantic and Pacific oceans as
giant protective moats, the United States had no business fighting
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his fellow NATO leaders did err badly in declaring
they had no intention of sending combat troops into Kosovo. But
Milosevic knew when he finally entered into a peace accord that
Clinton was considering the use of troops toward the end.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, filled with hate for Clinton, probably hoped,
either consciously or subconsciously, that the president's policy
would fail. Some complained that Clinton was building up an old
enemy by getting Russia involved in the peace dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia has a long history of good relations with Yugoslav
Serbs and Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, working with Finnish
President Marrti Ahtisaari, played a vital role in persuading
Milosevic to yield to NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   But that happened only because of the resolve of Clinton and
other NATO leaders in pushing the air war.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite the continued uncertainty of events in Yugoslavia,
we are on the road to peace _ and once again we have witnessed the
emergence of William Jefferson Clinton from the ashes of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The first such political resurrection at the national level
occurred in 1992 when, after revelations of his extra-marital
affair with Gennifer Flowers, Clinton won a strong second place in
the New Hampshire Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the votes were tallied that night that Clinton
declared himself ``the comeback kid.'' He then went on to defeat
George Bush in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   But early in his presidency, Clinton became involved in an angry
controversy over his campaign promise to permit openly gay
individuals to serve in the military. He was forced to settle for a
compromise that was not wholly acceptable either to gays or to
those who opposed their service in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was the disaster in Somalia where American soldiers
were killed and their bodies dragged through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   He and Mrs. Clinton then put together a cumbersome and costly
health care plan that was to be the centerpiece of their White
House tenure. It was treated to ridicule and rejection on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Without a single Republican vote in Congress, Clinton pushed
through an economic program that included a tax on the wealthy,
which Republicans promptly denounced as the ``biggest tax
increase'' in history.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of those and other embarrassments was the Democrats'
loss of the House and the Senate in the 1994 congressional
elections. The House last had gone Republican 42 years before.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton rebounded in January 1995 when he told the nation in
his State of the Union address that the era of big government was
over. He promised to work in harmony with the Congress and its GOP
leaders, Speaker Newt Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Special Counsel Ken Starr continued to probe the
Clintons' role in the Whitewater affair and other questionable
ventures. Some of the president's one-time business partners were
indicted and sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the Republicans' time to err. They pushed through
policies that were not overwhelmingly popular with the public and
they twice shut down the government. In 1996, despite the many
controversies of his first term, Clinton won a second term.
</P>
<P>
   Then both houses of Congress launched investigations of
Clinton's 1996 campaign fund-raising practices, including the
practice of allowing big contributors to spend a night in the
Lincoln bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   That probe was followed by shocking revelations about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, which led the House Judiciary
Committee to vote to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the revelations about the sordid affair dragged on,
weakening Clinton's moral authority and his leadership. Finally,
the Senate proved unable to win the two-thirds vote required to
find him guilty and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, he agreed to commit American air power to a war
against Serb cruelty in Kosovo. But as the weeks wore on, with no
sign of Milosevic capitulating, public confidence in his conduct of
international affairs dipped.
</P>
<P>
   Many hurdles remain to be surmounted in the Balkans, where a
massive effort must be undertaken to help rebuild the homes and
businesses of the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   But air power did its job, when critics asserted that it would
fail. And Clinton, despite the scars and wounds of an
often-endangered presidency, once again emerged triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to find a parallel in history _ to discover a
president who successfully has weathered a storm as powerful as the
one that had battered Clinton for six-and-a-half-years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
