<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The lowly beet deserves high praise
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The beet is the most intense of vegetables. The radish,
admittedly, is more feverish, but the fire of the radish is a cold
fire, the fire of discontent, not of passion. Tomatoes are lusty
enough, yet there runs through tomatoes an undercurrent of
frivolity. Beets are deadly serious.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Robbins
</P>
<P>
   Beets can also be rambunctious, rowdy and downright disorderly.
Unlike with most foods, it is wise to check what you are wearing
before you begin to cook or eat them. If you are not careful, beets
can leach, bleed and stain a garish purplish-pink anything they
touch. That's why, after one or two experiences with the rowdy
root, many people stroll right on by the beet section of the
produce market, partaking instead of the safer canned and pickled
variety.
</P>
<P>
   Beets have a lively social history in America. At the turn of
the century, beets helped nourish masses of Slavic and Jewish
immigrants, who adored them. In the meantime, mainstream society
turned up their noses at the earthy vegetable and their association
with the teeming masses and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Farmer (the Martha Stewart of her day) had some success
in putting a polish on the lowbrow reputation of beets by toning
them down with a cornstarch sauce and giving her recipe a
high-class moniker _ ``Harvard'' beets.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing a social trend, and not to be ``beet'' by its
archrival, Yale University came up with a recipe for ``Yale'' beets
using butter instead of cornstarch and orange juice instead of
vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Beet cuisine has expanded a great deal since the days of those
Ivy League dishes and the borscht of the immigrants. And
considering that beets are packed with good nutrition from leaf to
root, it may be time to quit beating around the bush and give beets
another chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is there, of course, to help you with handling
tips, loads of creative recipes, a bit of history and some humor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Proving once again there is a fanatic with a Web site on just
about every subject, you must check out hometown.aol
</P>
<P>
   .com/Beetlady/index.html. The author, ``the Beet Lady,'' says
she fell in love with beets when she visited Russia and decided
they get a bad rap in the United States. Hence her site, where you
will find beet recipes, beet poems, beet crafts, beet links and
beet silliness. For puns, this site ``beets'' all.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On a more serious note see www.sallys-place.com/food
</P>
<P>
   /columns/fussell/beets.htm and www.bpe.com/food/columns
</P>
<P>
   /ferrayfiszer/beets.htm. Both sites have a bit of history,
recipes and consumer and handling tips.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For an overview on the latest nutritional research on beets,
see www.cals.wisc.edu
</P>
<P>
   /media/news/1197
</P>
<P>
   /beetsfolicacid.html.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the University of Wisconsin have recently
declared beets a treasure-trove of folic acid, an essential
nutrient that may help prevent certain types of birth defects,
cancer and can protect against heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you plan on growing beets in your garden, you may want to
visit www.jcsolutions.com/
</P>
<P>
   jcsgrower/beets.html for growing tips and
www.botany.com/beta.html for more in-depth botanical information.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For beet recipes see: www
</P>
<P>
   .mfy.com/class030.html and www.vegweb.com/
</P>
<P>
   food/vegetables/index-vegetables-beets.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget www
</P>
<P>
   .empirekosher.com
</P>
<P>
   /momsfamous.htm for Mom's Famous Beet Borscht.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Beet Caviar
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Refrigeration time: Overnight
</P>
<P>
   3beets or one 15-ounce can whole beets
</P>
<P>
   2Granny Smith apples
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup walnuts, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   Grate beets into medium bowl. Set aside. Grate apples and add to
beets. Add walnuts and garlic. Toss with mayonnaise and mix well to
coat. Refrigerate overnight. Serve with crackers or crostini.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 63 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 41), 6 grams carbohydrates, 2 milligrams
cholesterol, 97 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Beets and Carrots With
</P>
<P>
   West Indian Spices
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1pound beets, about 4 medium
</P>
<P>
   1pound carrots, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons grated fresh ginger root
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   grated zest of 1 orange
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon mace
</P>
<P>
   Wash beets well and cut off leaves, leaving 1 inch or so of
stem. Cover with cold water and bring to a boil. Simmer, covered,
until tender, about 40 minutes. Drain and cover with cool or
lukewarm water. When cool enough to handle, slip off skins. Cut
into slices or chunks. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and cut carrots into slices or chunks resembling beets in
size and style. Steam or boil in lightly salted water about 5
minutes or until tender but not soft. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan, put ginger, brown sugar, orange juice,
vinegar, orange zest, cinnamon, and mace. Mix well, cover and bring
to a simmer. Cook until thickened, stirring occasionally. Add
cooked beets and carrots, stirring well to coat. Cook 5 minutes.
Serve.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Per serving: 137 calories, 2 grams protein, 1 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 2), 34 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 77 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the matter: Beet sites run the gamut from serious
(www
</P>
<P>
   .bpe.com/food
</P>
<P>
   /columns/
</P>
<P>
   ferrayfiszer
</P>
<P>
   /beets.htm) to
</P>
<P>
   humorous (hometown.aol.com
</P>
<P>
   /Beetlady/
</P>
<P>
   index.html).
</P>
