<HEADER>
A8841 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     06-09 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Picking beers of summer
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The neighborhood pool opened over Memorial Day weekend
and a couple of us smuggled in a little cooler filled with
contraband _ two bottles of beer and glasses wrapped in towels. A
glass _ and not a frosted one _ is the only way to drink beer, but
in these circumstances my natural caution might have led me to
settle for plastic picnic cups. The club, reasonably enough,
doesn't allow bottles or glass at poolside, although I did see one
bikini-clad woman flouncing about with a glass of white wine. One
misstep and she and her drink would have been swimming.
</P>
<P>
   We were less conspicuous, encamping sedately to the side of the
splashing.
</P>
<P>
   It was summer again, and the surest sign was kids doing
cannonballs off a springboard. The next surest was the two lugs
hauling cases of cheap, canned beer to the barbecue area. I don't
think they cared one way or another about the beer, just so long as
it fizzed like soda pop and gave an alcoholic buzz.
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem anything calling itself a ``summer beer''
faces: It's thrown itself into a sea of indifference. If a summer
beer is supposed to be light, crisp and all the rest _ standard
descriptions of the genre _ what's to distinguish it from the
mainstream flood that's already light, crisp and generally lousy?
</P>
<P>
   The variety of summer beers on the market would suggest there's
no consensus. On the one hand you have Belgian White Ales, which in
Belgium are enjoyed year-round, and on the other you have lagers
that a German might associate with a region more than a season.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, conditioned more by marketing than by history or
tradition, think differently. First you conjure up the image and
create the label _ those being what most consumers buy _ and then
you make something you hope fits.
</P>
<P>
   This is why I could go an entire summer _ a whole year, for that
matter _ without a ``summer beer.'' Apparently I'm not alone. In a
market crowded already, at least one Atlanta wholesaler decided not
to distribute summer beers this year.
</P>
<P>
   Not that some of these beers aren't enjoyable. Several are fine
examples of one style or another. But it's the style and not the
season they bring to mind. Here, then (and in no particular order),
is a rundown on some of the better beers of summer:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red Brick Summer Brew. A repeat of last year's, which was
named one of the Journal-Constitution's 10 Best in Atlanta.
Dry-hopping with Ahtanum
</P>
<P>
   hops gives this light-bodied ale its distinctive note, although
I don't detect the subtle, almost pearlike quality of last year's.
Just right for picnics and ballgames, this might be the best beer
Atlanta Brewing Co. produces.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sierra Nevada Summerfest. A California pioneer in craft
brewing shows the industry giants how well a lager can be done.
This isn't a ``big'' lager, but it has the Sierra Nevada signature
of balance and perfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't brew it to any particular German style,'' Sierra
Nevada's Steve Harrison says. ``We just wanted to do a
bottom-fermented beer, and get it to where we wanted it.'' Where
they have it is somewhere close to the Munich Hellas style, soft on
the palate and always drinkable.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Redhook Blonde Ale. Fuller in flavor than most summer beers,
and not quite as crisp. Redhook has done well with this beer _
better, evidently, than it had with the splendid Redhook Rye, which
to my mind fit the definition of ``summer beer'' as well as any.
And it wasn't even marketed as one. Alas, though, it's no longer
available year-round or even this summer. The Blonde Ale does its
best, but the two really aren't comparable.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dogwood Summer Brew. Another of the Journal-Constitution's 10
Best in Atlanta last year, this is a Belgian White Ale with an
orangey color and a delightful spiciness. Where most summer beers
are suited to hot dogs and mustard, a beer as delicate as this one
travels in better culinary company, from shrimp salads to grilled
salmon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Samuel Adams Summer Ale. Always well-made, always popular. A
touch of lemon gives it a zestiness that's not too obvious, and the
malt background has a nice complexity. But many will wonder why
this is a summer beer and the same brewery's White Ale _ available
year-round _ is not.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bert Grant's Summer Ale. One of Grant's four single-varietal
seasonals, this one debuting the Amarillo hop, a proprietary strain
from Hop Union of Washington state. Reddish in color and, at 32
International Bitterness Units, hoppier than most summer beers. The
seasonals are some of Grant's best.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biere du Soleil. Brewed by D'Achouffe in Belgium, this amber,
bottle-conditioned beer might be the most interesting of the lot, a
true Belgian beer made just for summer. It has a sparkling
character but a surprising hoppiness (32 IBUs). New to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these is likely to suit a different mood and moment. But
there will be times when none of them hits the spot like a lambic,
fruity and slightly tart. Served in a champagne flute, lightly
chilled, this is an elegant aperitif. Many people who think they
don't like beer find, to their great surprise, that they love
lambics. Lindeman's framboise, kriek and peche are all good
choices.
</P>
<P>
   PICK OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   They're those banana beers, although you can sometimes taste
clove as well.
</P>
<P>
   Hefeweizens are another whole class of summer beers, but a class
unto themselves. In recent years, Americans have become better
acquainted with this style whose first obstacle to enjoyment is the
name itself.
</P>
<P>
   First things first: In German, ``Hefe'' means yeast and
``weisse'' means white, the latter implying a high proportion of
wheat in the grist. Combined, ``hefeweizen'' refers to any
unfiltered wheat beer. Because the beer is unfiltered, the yeast is
suspended _ hence the cloudiness. Often served with a slice of
lemon, hefeweizens sometimes resemble (but only superficially)
Belgian Whites in their tartness and their pale yellow color. But
where a Belgian White has notes of coriander and orange peel, the
yeast in a hefeweizen produces esters that hint of apple or plum,
banana or clove.
</P>
<P>
   A number of excellent hefeweizens are widely available, but
there is none like Schneider Weisse, brewed by the Schneider family
in the Bavarian town of Kelheim. Closer to amber in color,
Schneider Weisse is as ``big'' as a hefeweizen gets, fuller
flavored without being heavy. Served in a tall, vaselike glass, it
produces a huge, creamy crown _ and if you don't like the foam on a
beer, well, you have to wait a long while before this one loses its
head.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of beer best enjoyed by itself or with mild to
medium-strong cheeses. As big as it is, Schneider Weisse can take
on stronger cheese than most hefeweizens, but this is a beer to
drink at leisure and not to wash down food.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find it in six-packs or in many supermarkets. It's
available only in a pint-plus bottle (about 18 ounces) that goes
for about $2.75. Hefeweizens can be an acquired taste, and not
everyone acquires it. But even those drawn to more robust beers
acknowledge that here is one of the world's classics.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
