<HEADER>
A8855 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      06-09 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
June 10. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   GRAY: A Philadelphia company linked to political consultant Pat
Gray is in line to manage Kemper Arena and Bartle Hall. The
company, SMG _ one of the largest private operators of arenas in
the nation, including the Superdome and Miami Convention Center _
paid Gray to conduct a poll on whether Kansas City residents
favored the private management of the city's convention facilities.
SMG officials confirm they will meet with Mayor Kay Barnes in a few
weeks to discuss their plans. Barnes has said she favors letting a
private company operate Kemper and Bartle, even though City Manager
Bob Collins' studies are not complete. SMG is the second company to
hire Gray for help in taking over a city facility. Meanwhile,
Councilman Paul Danaher _ Barnes' point man in privatization
efforts _ has approached a Maryland firm to take over operations of
Kansas City International Airport. Gromer Jeffers. 30. Photos,
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   JESSE: Jesse Jackson _ still glowing from his successful efforts
to free three American POW's _ is in Kansas City on Wednesday for a
noon luncheon celebrating diversity. While here, Jackson also got a
tour of the Negro Leagues Baseball Museum. Mary Sanchez. 20.
Photos.
</P>
<P>
   LEX (tentative): All this week, nearby Lexington, Mo., is
reincarnating that 19th century rural education ritual known as the
Chautauqua. Reincarnated historical figures, like Civil War Gen.
William Tecumseh Sherman and writer Louisa May Alcott, make
appearances. Photos. Trisha L. Howard. 15.
</P>
<P>
   CARLA. Kansas Attorney General Carla Stovall holds a press
conference to discuss concerns about internet distribution of
prescription drugs. John L. Petterson.
</P>
<P>
   EXPLORE (business) - Local high school students participating in
Explorers groups are wrapping up their business projects. By Mark
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN (business) _ Humana Inc. is evaluating whether it wants to
sell or transfer the operations of about 50 clinics around the
country, including seven in the Kansas City area. By Julius A.
Karash.
</P>
<P>
   STAFFORD (business) _ What's a ``serious health condition''? The
answer decides whether an employee is eligible for Family &AMP; Medical
Leave Act leave. At Work column. By Diane Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   MEETING (sports): Previewing Thursday's meeting in Milwaukee
between prospective Royals owner Miles Prentice and Major League
Baseball officials. Steve Rock. 12 inches.
</P>
</TEXT>
