<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, June 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP _ Possible lede-all. Dateline to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ U.N. Security Council may _ but
may not _ vote on Kosovo resolution. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS (Skopje, Macedonia) _ NATO talks resume with
Yugoslav military. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Somewhere in Kosovo) _ Talking to some Yugoslav
soldiers (hitchhikers), and what Kosovo looks like. Also, Serbs who
say they'll stay rally in Pristina. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ Clinton's people made
Kosovo the defining moment of his presidency: So what's the
definition of ``defining moment'' at this point? By R.W. Apple.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO confusion and backtracking over
German general's announcement that air strikes have stopped. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Morini/Kukes, Albania) _ Anxieties about trying
to get home: Talking to refugees without documents and ex-prisoners
forced to sign confessions they were KLA fighters. By Elizabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-FOOTPRINTS (Paris) _ The oldest footprints of modern-day
man have been found in the Chauvet cave discovered in 1994 in
southern France, the Culture Ministry said Wednesday. The
footprints, between 20,000 and 30,000 years old and believed to be
those of an adolescent, were discovered in the clay floor of the
Chauvet cave in the Ardeche region. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Jakarta) _ Growing anxiety over delay in
election returns; many see incompetence. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-STANDOFF (Tokyo) _ North Korean warships intruded into
South Korean waters Wednesday and refused to immediately withdraw
for the second time in two days, the Defense Ministry said. While
South and North Korean naval vessels faced off throughout the day
in the Yellow Sea, the ministry warned that the standoff could
degenerate into an armed clash. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE-SPENDING (Washington) _ House takes up defense
authorization bill with many Kosovo and China spying amendments.
Late vote expected. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLICE-RACE (Washington) _ President Clinton orders
federal law enforcement officials to collect data on the race and
gender of the people they stop to question or arrest. (Wire
summary.) By Steven Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-JUVENILES (Washington) _ The ever shifting line between the
possible and the over-reaching comes into focus through a close
examination of how the House Republicans put together their gun
control package. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FUND-RAISING (Washington) _ While fund raising is a feast
for George W. Bush, the Texas governor's huge financial success has
left the other GOP presidential contenders (except self-financed
billionaire Steve Forbes) fighting or table scraps. By Don Van
Natta.
</P>
<P>
   EXPORT-CONTROLS (Washington) _ Updates debate over export
controls. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARDSON-SPY-CASE (Washington) _ Energy secretary testifies
before congressional panel on who, if anyone, should be fired as a
result of the delays in the Chinese espionage case. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-CHARTER (Los Angeles) _ Voters cast off the city's
74-year-old constitution in favor of a streamlined document meant
to thwart secession movements by meeting citizens' complaints about
remote, unresponsive government. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-SENATE (Binghamton, N.Y.) _ First lady makes first
campaign swing after announcing her exploratory committee. By
Jonathan Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BONDS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Bond investors are worriers by
nature, but they seem edgier now than they have been at any time
since the Russian crisis of last September. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Lockheed Martin, the second
biggest U.S. aerospace company, is projecting a loss in the second
quarter instead of a profit in part because of delayed plane
deliveries and failed satellite launches. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-FISHER (Undated) _ George M.C. Fisher, 58, will step down
as chief executive of Eastman Kodak at the end of the year and will
be replaced by his top lieutenant, Daniel Carp. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G-REORG (Undated) _ Offering details of the reorganization
that was outlined last week, Procter &AMP; Gamble will cut 15,000 jobs,
or 13 percent of its work force, and close 10 plants worldwide to
cut costs and free more money for new products. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-CHIP (San Francisco) _ Intel announces the latest advance
in wafer technology that will enable it to create higher-power
computer chips. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   ALLSTATE-CNA (Undated) _ Allstate will pay $1.2 billion for the
personal insurance division of CNA Financial in an effort to become
the largest seller of home and car insurance through independent
agents.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-SUN (Chicago) _ Motorola and Sun announce a new $1
billion 10-year contract aimed at producing products that will
ultimately allow wireless telecommunications equipment to connect
with the Internet. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Cross-examination of the IBM
executive who negotiated with Microsoft continues. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-PHONE-TAKEOVER (Tokyo) _ Japan's first hostile takeover
battle pitting a foreign suitor against a domestic titan ended in
victory for the outsider, Cable &AMP; Wireless P.L.C. of Britain, which
gained majority control of International Digital Communications, a
struggling telephone carrier. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   SINGAPORE-FOOD-BAN (Singapore) _ Anything containing meat or
dairy products from Europe has been yanked from grocery store
shelves here after a snap government order last weekend in response
to news that animal feed contaminated with the cancer-causing
chemical dioxin may have poisoned a variety of products from
Belgium and elsewhere in Europe. But perhaps no country has been so
quick or so thorough as Singapore in eradicating all trace of
Continental products from its shopping list. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-AD-COL (Undated) _ A look at a new campaign from
Motorola with the tag line ``digital DNA.'' By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-CLOUD (Undated) _ Researchers from the Scripps Institute
of Oceanography have discovered a mysterious haze covering an area
of the Indian Ocean as big as the continental United States. By
William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
