<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ After picking up a rapid pace
during the day Tuesday, the efforts to bring peace to Kosovo bogged
down with NATO and Yugoslav military leaders unable to come up with
an agreement on Serb troop withdrawal from Kosovo and the make-up
of an international peacekeeping force. Developing. (Deans, Cox
News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SEARCH _ TIRANA, Albania _ An Albanian-American
busniessman from Lake Worth, Fla., has traveled here to find (and
maybe rescue) members of his family who are refugees from Kosovo.
Is he too late? We follow him on his journey. Developing. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SPYPLANE _ MIRKOVICI, Macedonia _ In still another
mysterious twist to the Balkans crisis, Macedonian police on
Tuesday displayed a sophisticated Israeli-made spy plane that they
had seized on a montainside near the Kosovo border from seven
Israeli technicians who said they filming for an Israeli TV
network. Developing. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service). 20. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SARAJEVO-BOSNIA _ Dayton contingent arrives in Sarajevo. Story
recaps mission of the trip and looks at the city through Dayton's
visitors eyes. Will try for some of the group visiting the horror
sites of the civil war: sniper alley, destroyed national library
and Holiday Inn hotel, where the delegation is staying and from
which masked gunmen opened fire on a peace demonstration in 1992 in
the unofficial start to the seige. (Bebbington, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-TROOPS _ MIAMI _ Nearly five years after the United States
invaded Haiti to restore democracy, the U.S. House of Reps. is
expected to vote Wednesday on whether to end the permanent U.S.
military presence there. A growing number of lawmakers are
demanding the withdrawal of the remaining 500-member U.S. Support
Group in light of a rapidly deteriorating security situation in
Haiti that has left even military leaders concerned about the
safety of U.S. troops. The House will be voting on an amendment
proposed by Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla. and Rep. Ben Gilman, R-N.Y.
Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Emling, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   RATINGS _ WASHINGTON _ The voluntary rating systems that parents
and the government are relying on to protect children from
excessive sex and violence in media are unreliable tools, watchdog
groups say. These systems _ largely run by the film, television,
video game and music industries themselves _ often ignore or
downplay objectionable material, or engage in ``ratings creep'' in
which a category allows more extreme content over time, they say.
(Dart, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ The House Ways and Means
Committee begins two days of hearings on its main Social Security
reform proposal, offered by Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla. (Lipman,
Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Banking Committee hears from
congressional witnesses, including Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, on
threats to Americans' financial privacy. (Hill, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GA-TOBACCO _ Follow on Tuesday's report that the governor is
considering a push to direct a third of Georgia's $4billion-plus
tobacco settlement to South Georgia economic development, after
insisting that it'd all go to health care. What are other states
doing. Alabama used some of it's money to lure an auto plant to the
state. Florida appears to be sticking closer to the settlement.
(Judd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GOLFGOUGE _ PINEHURST, N.C. _Visitors to next week's U.S. Open
golf championship need to listen for that dull thud in the seat of
their pants. It could be a hotel, restaurant or golf course taking
a divot from their wallet. A night's stay in a two-bedroom suite at
the Marriott Residence Inn will cost $499, more than double the
typical rate. A round of golf at Plantation Golf Club will go for
$200, an $85 premium over the regular green fee. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   FERRY _ MONKEY ISLAND, La. _ Seven days a week, 24 hours a day,
a gray and white tug boat pushes a small barge back and forth
across the Calcascieu River from here to mainland Cameron Parish.
The 600-acre island in southwest Louisiana has no stores or
services; the seven families who live here use the four-car ferry
to get to work, do errands and go to school. Without the ferry
service, which began in 1939 with a rowboat, the island is
uninhabitable. And uninhabited it may become, thanks to a bill
passed last month in the state House of Representatives. The bill,
pending a Senate vote, kills the state-run ferry service, which
costs $521,000 a year. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
