A8873 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-OUTLOOK-HNS &LR;      06-09 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-OUTLOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET BOOSTERS WARN BUSINESSES TO GET ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ For business fossils still stuck in the
technological Stone Age, Internet boosters at the vanguard of the
on-line revolution slammed home the message Tuesday that electronic
commerce is transforming business faster than you can say ``new
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   When the mostly government-run Internet became commercialized in
1984, skeptics scoffed at its potential in the brutal corporate
realm.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, some traditional investors and business people pooh-
pooh the idea that on-line commerce will rule the day in the near
future. Look at those wild stock market valuations, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Look at those virtual companies with no profits or real
products.
</P>
<P>
   But at a venture capital conference in Palo Alto sponsored by
the Asian-American Manufacturers Association, Internet executives
and investment bankers offered more hard business proof that the
on-line revolution is here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is fundamentally real despite all the hype and
the volatility,'' said Michael Parekh, head of Internet Research at
Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. in Palo Alto. ``We feel the Internet is
actually underhyped, and this is only the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of hedging, mainstream companies beyond Silicon
Valley are finally leaping aboard. Corporate spending on
information technology next year will rise to 6 percent of the
nation's gross domestic product, compared with 1 percent in 1994,
according to Goldman Sachs. Today, millions of businesses are
linked on line.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street still is bullish on the future of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the recent swoon in Internet stocks, the market
capitalization of Internet companies skyrocketed to $300 billion
over the past four years, the executives said. As the on-line
infrastructure grows and profits come, Wall Street will pour even
more money into virtual companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, consumers continue their love affair with the
Internet, spending an average of one hour a day on line. About 250
million personal computers have Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The next five years will bring billions of non-computer devices
from set-top boxes on televisions, to personal digital assistants
and various telephone-style devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a hurricane creating opportunities in all
sectors of technology: software, hardware, semiconductors,
computing systems _ everything,'' said Geoffrey Yang, general
partner at Institutional Venture Partners in Menlo Park. ``It's all
about the Internet _ nothing else matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all is paradise, though. The Internet boosters warned that
technology companies are having serious trouble finding good
engineers. The larger Internet-related companies are starting to
resemble the old, lumbering IBM of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Too many eager and ill-equipped players are flooding niche
markets, with many dying and few surviving. Foreign competition is
warming up, too, with European and Japanese companies slowly
awakening to the vast potential of on-line commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the Internet tsunami _ it's very big and very
disruptive,'' Parekh said. ``It's creating a lot of wealth, and
it's destroying a lot of wealth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
