<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about the satellite Starshine, released by the
space shuttle, said it would be visible from Earth and could be
tracked by the naked eye. How can we find information about
Starshine and about viewing times and locations?
</P>
<P>
   A: Detailed information about the satellite can be found on the
Internet at www.azinet.com (and click on Starshine Project). For
details on viewing locations, check www2.gsoc.dlr.de/starshine (and
click on ``Select From the Database''). A tip: Be sure you have a
good observing site, out in the open, away from a lot of trees or
buildings and, most importantly, away from bright lights. Most
satellites, including Starshine, are pretty faint, so you'll have
to be sure there's no strong skyglow from city lights. The
satellite is expected to be visible during the next six months to a
year at certain morning and evening twilight periods to observers
located between latitudes 60 degrees north and 60 degrees south.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently read that Russia is the largest country in the
world, with Canada No. 2. If the United States and Canada were
merged into a single entity, would it then be larger than Russia?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. Canada's area is 3,849,674 square miles (including
inland water). The area of the United States is 3,615,292 square
miles (including inland water, but excluding the Great Lakes and
Lake Saint Clair). Add them and the total is 7,464,966 square
miles. Russia's area is 6,592,850 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A brief item in the newspaper reported that the Israeli navy
was looking for a submarine that was lost 31 years ago. Do you have
any more details?
</P>
<P>
   A: The wreckage of the Dakar was found May 28. The Dakar, an old
British submarine that had been refitted in Portsmouth, England, as
an Israeli vessel, was on its way to Israel when it disappeared in
the Mediterranean shortly after midnight on Jan. 25, 1968. At the
time, there was speculation that it had been sunk by the Egyptians
or Soviets. But now that investigators have examined video shots of
the wreckage, it's believed that the evidence indicates a
collision.
</P>
<P>
   The sub was discovered by American search-and-salvage experts
about 300 miles from Israel, between the Greek island of Crete and
the island nation of Cyprus, in about 9,600 feet of water. As
reported by The Associated Press, Capt. Doron Amir, a retired
Israeli navy investigator, and other investigators theorize that
the sub probably spotted a big ship coming at it and attempted to
crash-dive to avoid a collision. But its conning tower was struck
and ripped open, flooding and sinking it.
</P>
<P>
   The Dakar's entire crew of 68 presumably died in the accident.
The investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: News reports say the new owner of the Washington Redskins is
34-year-old Daniel Snyder. How did someone so young make enough of
a fortune to pay for such a team?
</P>
<P>
   A: Snyder didn't come up with the entire amount, but he is
investing a lot: $120 million in cash, according to The Washington
Post. Family members are adding another $90 million and minority
partners Fred Drasner and Mort Zuckerman each are putting up $90
million Snyder, a lifelong Washingtonian, made his $500 million
fortune in marketing and advertising. Zuckerman and Drasner have
known Snyder since the mid-1980s and were original investors in
Snyder Communications of Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I always thought Memorial Day is intended to honor all U.S.
soldiers who died in battle. But my mother says there's a separate
Memorial Day for Confederate soldiers. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're both right. While Memorial Day originally honored
military personnel who died in the Civil War, it now honors those
who died in any war while serving the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most of the southern states also have their own days
for honoring the Confederate dead: Georgia, on April 26, the date
in 1865 of the final surrender of Confederate Gen. Joseph E.
Johnston to the Union army's Gen. William T. Sherman; Mississippi,
the last Monday in April; Alabama, the fourth Monday in April;
North Carolina and South Carolina, on May 10, the anniversary of
the 1865 apprehension of Jefferson Davis by Federal cavalry;
Virginia, on the last Monday in May; and Louisiana, on June 3,
Davis' birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A relative is planning to work in China in the next couple of
months. Is it safe? What agency can give me up-to-date information
about the political climate for foreigners there?
</P>
<P>
   A: The State Department issues travel warnings when it
recommends that Americans avoid a certain country. China isn't on
the current list, but it is the subject of a public announcement,
which the department uses to disseminate information about
terrorist threats and other relatively short-term conditions that
it says pose ``significant risks or disruptions'' to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The public announcement for China _ issued May 27 with an
expiration date (as of June 2) of June 18 _ advises American
citizens to exercise caution while living or traveling in China, in
view of the 10th anniversary of the June 4 Tiananmen Square
demonstrations and the ``lingering tension'' resulting from Chinese
reaction to the May 7 NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   To hear recorded information, call 202-647-5225 or, on the
Internet, check www.state.gov and click on Services, then on Travel
and then on Travel Warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the TV program ``JAG,'' the time is often referred to as
``Zulu.'' What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: A code word used internationally for the time at Greenwich,
England, Zulu time is used as a reference standard when in, or
crossing through, other time zones around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent item in Q&AMP;A described the War Powers Act as a law.
It then referred to it as a resolution. So which is it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's correct to call it a resolution, an act and a law. By
whatever name, it was passed by Congress in 1973. This is how it
evolved that year:
</P>
<P>
   Bills limiting the power of a president to commit U.S. forces to
future hostilities without congressional approval were passed July
18 by the House and July 20 by the Senate. The Senate version,
unlike the House bill, defined emergency situations in which the
president could commit forces without prior congressional approval,
but set a limit of 30 days on such action unless Congress approved.
And there were other variations in wording.
</P>
<P>
   The two bills went to a conference committee for resolution of
differences. The final bill passed the Senate on Oct. 10 and the
House on Oct. 12. But on Oct. 24 President Nixon vetoed it, saying
it placed unconstitutional restrictions on the flexibility of the
president to defend the United States, and that it was not in the
best interests of the nation. Then on Nov. 7 the House, by a vote
of 284-135, and the Senate, by a vote of 75-18, overrode the
president's veto. So the bill, a resolution of the differences
between the original versions passed by the two chambers, became
law.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have some cans of old paint that I want to get rid of in an
environmentally proper way. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Georgia Environmental Protection Division offers this
advice: Put cat litter or sand, which will absorb the paint, in the
cans. When it dries and hardens, seal the cans and put them in your
regular garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are my senior citizen eyes deceiving me? Is the lawyer who
just filed a suit in the Littleton, Colo., shooting case the same
one involved in the recent Jenny Jones case?
</P>
<P>
   A: One and the same. Lawyer Geoffrey Fieger, best known for
representing Jack Kevorkian, filed a lawsuit May 27 in state court
in Denver on behalf of the parents of a Columbine High School
shooting victim.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, the first stemming from the shooting, was filed on
behalf of Vonda and Michael Shoels, whose 18-year-old son, Isaiah,
was the only African-American among the 12 students and one teacher
gunned down April 20 by Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17. The
lawsuit, against the parents of the gunmen, alleges that they were
negligent in how they supervised their children. It doesn't specify
a dollar amount, although Fieger said he will seek $250 million
from the two sets of parents. Colorado law, however, sets a cap of
$250,000 in a negligent death lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In the case involving TV talk show host Jenny Jones, Fieger
asked a jury in Pontiac, Mich., to award $71.5 million in damages
against her program and its corporate owner, Warner Bros., for the
death of a gay man who was killed after revealing a crush on
another of the program's guests. After deliberating for seven
hours, the 12-member jury on May 7 delivered a $25 million verdict
against ``The Jenny Jones Show'' show for negligence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
