<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, June 10:
</P>
<P>
   EAMES-EXHIBITION (Undated) _ You could smell the plywood at the
Library of Congress, where ``The Work of Charles and Ray Eames: A
Legacy of Invention,'' an exhibition of the two American designers'
multi-faceted achievement, recently opened. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   WEGMAN-AT-HOME (New York) _ At home with William Wegman, who is
just now putting the final touches on a memoir (to be published
Oct. 1) of living and working with Fay Ray, the Weimaraner who
helped to make him the world's most famous dog owner and
portraitist. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   SHAG-RESURGENCE (Undated) _ There's nothing quite like a good
shag. Its long, soft wool demands to be stroked, petted like the
pelt of some rare mountain sheep. The thing is almost obscenely
sexy, a vaguely naughty artifact from a more swinging age that
makes you want to exclaim, in a bad impersonation of Austin Powers,
``Oh, behave!'' By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOOR-FLOORS (Undated) _ An outdoor floor used to be forever.
To install a terrace, patio or deck meant waiting on professionals,
with their own inscrutable timetables. Now, with do-it-yourself
kits and loose-lay flooring, you can just about bring home the deck
and put out the lounge chairs. By Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered.
</P>
