<HEADLINE>
IN AIR TRAVEL, BANGOR IS ALL THE RAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGOR, MAINE _ By 12:15 a.m on Monday, when Delta flight 064
made a hasty landing at Bangor International Airport, passenger
services knew the drill: remove the belligerent passenger from his
position hogtied in the aisle, calm down the flight attendants who
had been sitting on him, wipe the blood off the cabin ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   When Bangor's two FBI agents showed up to take Christopher Bayes
into custody, the situation seemed almost normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like anything else,'' said Sergeant James Owens of the
Bangor Police Department. ``You do it enough times, you get used to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 31 days, three separate airliners have made
emergency landings in Bangor to remove British passengers who have
gone into violent and threatening rages during transatlantic
flights. And while other airports might shrink from airborne
discipline problems, Bangor is actively marketing its willingness
to handle them. After the offenders are safely incarcerated in the
Penobscot County Jail _ all three are there right now _ Bangor
airport sends the aircraft off with the message that they are
welcome to come back the next time.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency landings are bread and butter for Bangor, where a full
25 percent of landings are unplanned stops for refueling or
emergencies, which can bring in $10,000 apiece. With a runway long
enough for a space shuttle landing and a strategic position en
route to any northern European destination, Bangor is an obvious
choice for pilots who need to get out of the air fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, other airports aren't that interested in doing
this,'' said Jeff Russell, head of marketing for the airport.
``It's the dregs of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies have suggested that air-rage incidents are on the
upturn, although the emotional stresses of flying _ a loss of
control and a sense of containment _ are still the same. Among
air-rage incidents that have been documented, the most common
grievance was attendants' refusing to serve alcohol to passengers.
The second was seat assignment, the third was flight attendants'
attitude, and the fourth was airline food, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Bangor International Airport has handled
between 8 and 12 air-rage landings per year, and in March 1988
airport officials tentatively began marketing its air-rage services
at a convention of European carriers. In a business where an
unscheduled stop can wipe out a flight's profit margin, Bangor's
main selling point is a quick turnaround time. But there's also a
geographical asset, according to Russell _ Bangor's airspace seems
to be a hot spot for passenger misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've been flying for five, six hours, you've seen the movie,
you've eaten the food, you've written in your journal and it's time
to act up. Trouble seems to develop within 250 nautical miles of
Bangor in either direction,'' said Russell.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, this spring has brought an alarming amount of
business. On May 3, an Airtours International flight made an
emergency landing en route from Orlando to Manchester, England when
a British mechanic kicked out an interior window in a violent rage
and threatened to kick in the outer window, which could have caused
a dangerous sudden loss of cabin pressure. Bryan Neal, 25, of
Manchester, was enraged when flight attendants refused him alcohol,
and by the choice of an in-flight movie that he had seen already.
</P>
<P>
   Neal is serving a 60-day sentence and owes the airline $25,000
for the damage to the plane.
</P>
<P>
   On May 26, Shabiya Davidson _ also of Manchester _ assaulted a
flight attendant. It was later discovered that Davidson had been
transporting cocaine in a condom in his stomach and the condom had
burst, said Bangor police. Davidson is also serving a 60-day
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident, like the first, was directly
alcohol-related. Bayes, 41, who is also from Manchester, sexually
groped two female flight attendants, cursed loudly and tried to get
into the cockpit to demand another drink, Russell said. The cockpit
door was locked and two male flight attendants subdued Bayes and
tied him up, using nylon restraints as well as three cloth napkins.
When a passenger services team boarded the plane, the flight
attendants were sitting on him, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Bayes, who was arraigned Tuesday, faces charges of assault and
interference with the flight crew.
</P>
<P>
   The two flight attendants who struggled with Bayes were treated
for minor injuries and released, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   After ground crews cleaned blood from a cut on Bayes's mouth off
the seats, the floor and the ceiling of the cabin, the flight
departed Bangor again at 2:22 _ less than two hours after its
emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the industry, many blame the incidents on an increasing
casualness about air travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air travel used to be a special thing to do. People used to
get dressed up to go on a flight,'' said Russell. Now, he said,
``Pilots will tell you it's like driving a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say the relaxing of travel decorum is only part of
the story. Air-rage reports also may be up because flight
attendants are no longer expected to humor boorish and drunken
passengers, and they are taken seriously by the airline when they
complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times the crew felt the air-rager was being supported.
They were spirited off and given free tickets and mollycoddled,''
said First Officer Drew Engelke, a communications officer for the
Allied Pilots Association. That all changed on a United Airlines
flight in 1995, when a passenger in a drunken rampage defecated on
a food trolley, Engelke said.
</P>
<P>
   By going public with the event, and by prosecuting the
passenger, United helped shift airlines' approach to unruly
passengers. ``I think that maybe the norms that were always there
are just being enforced,'' Engelke said.
</P>
<P>
   From ground level in Bangor, though, there's nothing new about
rowdy drunkenness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all that different from taking a drunk out of a
bar,'' said Owens, of the Bangor police. ``Up here we call it a
`want-out.' Somebody is wanted out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the coincidence that all three men now in detention are
from Manchester, England, Owens said, ``You can make your own
assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Special agent Paul Palumbo, who along with Wayne Hedrick staffs
Bangor's FBI office, is watching Bangor's air-rage population grow
with some amusement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole new wing at the Penobscot County Jail for
Englishmen,'' said Palumbo. ``We're serving tea and popovers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
