<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-COPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD VOTES TO LIMIT POLICE ROLE AT SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Unified School District
approved a resolution Tuesday that limits the presence of police
officers on campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, approved late Tuesday by a 5-1 vote, requires
that staff members first contact school administrators to resolve a
problem with a student unless the student poses an immediate threat
to others or has broken the law. It also includes an amendment
requiring on-campus officers not to carry guns while on school
grounds for non-emergency matters.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. James Dudley of the Police Department's juvenile division
had urged the school board not to vote on the measure until the
police had a chance to review it.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote on the ``Safe Schools'' measure, Dudley
criticized the decision, saying it would keep officers in the dark
about potential acts of violence or troubled youths. He also said
the district didn't have the authority to govern police practices
on school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they refuse to have us on campus with guns, I don't know
who that will benefit,'' Dudley said.
</P>
<P>
   The board was divided about whether to postpone a vote on the
resolution because of Police Department objections and questions by
the district's own lawyers over the wording of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been multiple meetings,'' said school board member
Jill Wynns. ``Every effort has been made to reach as much consensus
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure says school officials will continue to foster good
relations between students and police officers assigned to the
various schools. But instead of involving the officers in routine
disciplinary matters, as some school officials currently do, the
measure requires the school staff to first notify a school
administrator before calling the police.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also requires school officials to contact an
offending student's parents and give them reasonable time to
respond and be present during police questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley said he feared the measure would leave officers in the
dark about problems among students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that some incidents that we should know about will
slip through the cracks,'' Dudley said. ``Our presence helps to
break down the stereotypes of what police officers are.''
</P>
<P>
   While the police may have opposed the measure, the people who
attended the meeting were supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker after speaker urged the school board to help create a
less intimidating environment on campus. Some carried signs reading
``Schools, not jails,'' ``Cops aren't teachers'' and ``Stop making
us criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How would you feel walking into your learning environment and
have police breathing down your neck,'' said Jamie Motley, 16, a
junior at Wallenberg High School. ``I need someone to talk to about
my problems, not arrest me for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Gallegos, a parent, said she thought school officials
were too quick to involve the police in disciplinary matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to use some common sense in what long-term effects
having all this police presence at the schools has,'' Gallegos
said. ``We need to have more counselors, not police.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
