<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-N.H.-GUNS-BOS &LR;      06-09 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.H.-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. TAKES WARY APPROACH TO GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA _ As Congress struggles to approve gun-control measures
this week, so the state of New Hampshire struggles, too.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates Elizabeth Dole and Al Gore are
advocating tighter gun laws in campaign appearances here. But state
legislators have been stymied this year on a variety of proposals.
</P>
<P>
   If there has been a shift in public opinion about the need for
gun control since the tragedy at Columbine High School in Colorado,
it is not clear that the reverberations are being felt in the
Granite State.
</P>
<P>
   For example, bills to prevent children's access to guns and to
ban large-capacity magazines were defeated in the Senate recently.
</P>
<P>
   A domestic violence bill was greeted by vociferous opposition in
the House because it contained a provision requiring people to
surrender their weapons to police if a temporary restraining order
is pending against them. The bill eventually passed the House and
is pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Gun Owners of New Hampshire, a pro-gun group, has also
opposed a bill to form a commission to examine gun violence and
children. The bill, which calls for a representative from the
organization on the panel, passed the Senate and is pending in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, the former head of the American Red Cross, said in an
interview that she has been impressed by the positive reception she
has received in New Hampshire and around the country for her
proposals to place child safety locks on guns, to ban assault
weapons, and to outlaw ``cop-killer'' bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of people in this state who say `right on,'
'' said Dole, acknowledging New Hampshire's longstanding aversion
to gun restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people in New Hampshire are independent and they
respect the fact that you'll state your views forthrightly and not
shift and change and be inconsistent about what you believe,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dole is also mindful that many voters here would disagree
with the stand she has taken, and take pains to note that she is
advocating small, not draconian, steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always had a strong belief in the Second Amendment and
the Constitution, but these are things that are reasonable,'' she
said. ``I can't imagine why anybody would need an Uzi or an
AK-47.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore said he also believes that people here are
more receptive to gun-control measures since the shootings in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a sea change,'' Gore said during an interview.
``How many incidents does it take?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at the University of New Hampshire's graduation ceremony
last month, the audience of 20,000 cheered when Gore bragged that
he had cast the deciding vote in the Senate to require mandatory
background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Young, a Republican political strategist, said it has
not been that long since Democrat Dick Swett lost his House seat
for reneging on a promise to oppose a ban on assault weapons. In
1994, Swett voted for legislation that would bar certain
semiautomatic assault weapons and spent the bulk of his campaign
trying to explain why he broke his promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a pro-gun state,'' said Young, an adviser to
Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes. ``There are still a
lot of sportsmen here, there are still quite a few people who live
off the land here.''
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Peter Hoe Burling, the Democratic leader,
said he owns guns and many of his neighbors in Cornish keep guns,
too. But Burling said he has seen a slight modulation in public
opinion over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This state was totally berserk on the subject of guns,'' he
said. ``People were allowed to have anything up to and including an
atomic cannon to use on their neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Burling said, he believes New Hampshire voters think that
there are responsibilities that go along with gun ownership, such
as keeping their guns securely locked away from children. But he
said that the public does not want further government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   That is something Representative Steve Vaillancourt, a Democrat
from Manchester, would agree with. Most of the constituents he
hears from are gun owners who oppose regulations. And while people
in other parts of the country are rethinking gun laws in the wake
of Columbine, Vaillancourt said, ``I don't think things will change
as rapidly as in other places.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
