<HEADER>
A8938 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTAURANTS-NEWORLEAN     06-09 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANTS-NEWORLEANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRESCENT CITY BECKONS; WE ANSWER THE CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Brown this, brown that, smothering sauces, nothing
remotely crunchy. And butter, butter everywhere. It doesn't take
too many formulaic creole meals in the Crescent City to remember
why Cajun and nouvelle New Orleans cuisine became and remain so
popular.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, though, there's something to be said for maxing
out on cholesterol. After all, places such as Commander's Palace
and Galatoire's, Antoine's and Arnaud's have between them centuries
of experience poaching pompano, stirring roux and spiking their
bread pudding.
</P>
<P>
   So it was in a spirit of adventure that my family and I embarked
on three days of traditional creole eating at some venerable
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   We found ourselves groaning after every meal, too, and
occasionally unimpressed. (Anticipating an overload of expensive
food, we didn't even bother with alcohol.) But we also were excited
by some of the discoveries we made about food that might take all
day to cook. Discoveries about real subtlety and delicacy of
texture, and depth of flavor bordering on unfathomable. About
service at once genial and sober, and dining areas that feel more
like home than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TUJAGUE'S
</P>
<P>
   You don't hear about Tujague's as often as the others, but it's
New Orleans' second-oldest restaurant. Located near the river, it
was opened in 1856 as a workingman's eatery by a French emigre
butcher named Guillaume Tujague. The lively dining room is
original, and Steven Latter _ only its third familial owner _
offers several vintage dishes.
</P>
<P>
   The set menu opened with shrimp remoulade, in a darkly zesty
sauce on shredded cabbage and lettuce, and ended with a petite
serving of bread pudding, accompanied by coffee served in glasses,
with spoons in to prevent the glass from breaking.
</P>
<P>
   In between, we were treated to creole vegetable soup _ a
Wednesday special _ served in soup plates and replete with chunks
of cabbage, celery, green bell pepper, carrot, onion, potato and
corn. Next came morsels of beef brisket that had been boiled to
make the soup stock.
</P>
<P>
   The standout entree was crawfish Florentine, served in a rich
and musty, slightly yellowish roux (thanks to seasoning with
crawfish fat), chock-full of crustaceans and spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Tujague's Restaurant, 823 Decatur St., (504) 525-8676.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ANTOINE'S
</P>
<P>
   Antoine's you hear about all the time. Founded in 1840, it's the
oldest restaurant in New Orleans and a very classy place. However,
it also can be quite unreliable. My experience there was with a
group from the New Orleans Museum of Art, and we were served from
one of the banquet menus in a cavernous room.
</P>
<P>
   Although I'm sure my host wanted us to have a special
experience, I found it quite ordinary, despite the presence of
several Antoine's specialties, including oysters Rockefeller
(served with pureed green vegetables and not simply spinach) and
oysters Foch (served with a sherry-laced hollandaise sauce).
</P>
<P>
   After the (brownish, perhaps due to overbaking) oysters
Rockefeller and the brown-on-brown-on-brown oysters Foch, I was
ready for something a bit brighter in color, at least, if not in
taste. So, given the choice of seafood gumbo, alligator soup and
crawfish bisque, I took option three.
</P>
<P>
   The creamy plate of soup I envisioned, however, turned out to be
a cup of thick, brown broth dotted with bits of meat. Exasperated,
I sampled my companions' cups of the other two. I discerned no
difference between the crawfish bisque and that seafood gumbo. The
alligator soup varied only in that alligator is tangier than either
of the other two meats.
</P>
<P>
   Another mistake was ordering poached pompano. Instead of a
delicately steamed chunk of fish, lightly sauced, I was served a
parchment pouch filled with oozing sauce, flecked with about seven
bites of fish.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine's Restaurant, 713 St. Louis St., (504) 581-4422.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GALATOIRE'S RESTAURANT
</P>
<P>
   Friday, I was told, is the day New Orleanians with an affinity
for creole food line up in front of Galatoire's, waiting for the
doors to open at 11:30 a.m. We arrived at 11:15 a.m. on that very
day and took our places at the end of the queue. After the doors
opened, we were shown to one of two window tables.
</P>
<P>
   Memories of Brasserie Lipp danced in my head as I looked around
the mirrored room, glowing in a golden light and brimming with
local clientele, who were greeted with warm familiarity. The menu,
too, featured the sort of urbane home cooking that Lipp serves,
although it was creole and not Alsatian.
</P>
<P>
   The obligatory shrimp remoulade, half-portion of oysters
Rockefeller (with spinach), asparagus omelet and broiled snapper
(they were out of pompano) with lump crab meat, and side of
broccoli all were impressive _ cooked perfectly and presented with
understated refinement.
</P>
<P>
   Dessert, however, was an extraordinary experience. Not the
chocolate nut sundae, a satisfying hit with my sons, who had not
been tempted by anything but bread and butter until then. That left
me alone with a modest (but not skimpy) serving of pleasantly
sticky bread pudding, topped with a (rum?) sauce that _ oh my gosh,
oh, oh, oh, yes _ penetrated the depths of my soul.
</P>
<P>
   Galatoire's Restaurant, 209 Bourbon St., (504) 525-2021.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DOOKY CHASE'S
</P>
<P>
   So far, our meals in New Orleans had been of the French creole
variety. For our last dinner there, though, we trekked to Dooky
Chase's _ for legendary African creole cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant was established in 1941 by its namesake and his
wife, Leah, who has presided over the kitchen as chef/owner since
her husband's death _ assisted by her son, Dooky Jr. We ate early
on Saturday evening, well before dinner hour and _ perhaps because
the kitchen was quiet _ Leah Chase came out to greet the handful of
diners. She stopped at our table, chatted a bit, teased the boys
and promised that she would make them up some complimentary shrimp
and French fries.
</P>
<P>
   She did, and they didn't eat it. So I did _ along with Dooky's
special seafood platter _ an encyclopedic selection of tidbits,
delicately breaded _ a side of sweet potatoes and steamed rice, my
share of the shrimp remoulade, a cup of pea soup, a glass of
chardonnay, some of my husband's slightly oily seafood gumbo and a
dessert of praline pudding.
</P>
<P>
   It was all so good, apart from my husband's cheesecake _ like
mediocre store-bought _ that I didn't mind spending the rest of the
evening in a state of extreme discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Dooky Chase's, 2301 Orleans Ave., (504) 821-0600.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
