<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHENGADGETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT SLICES, IT DICES, IT JULIENNES. BUT DOES IT REALLY, REALLY
WORK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Night owls and cable subscribers know the spiels by heart. A
facile salesman dices, schmoozes, peels and cajoles. He's selling
the answer to your prayers _ one miracle machine that transforms
you from cooking goof to culinary genius with one simple payment on
your credit card. But is he a snake-oil salesman or a messiah?
Here's what we found.
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   Eurosealer
</P>
<P>
   What they say: Seal in flavor and freshness, and seal out
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   What I say: A man must have invented this product. It's
superfluous in any home with a twist tie or plastic storage boxes.
Strike No. 1 _ the sealer is powered with batteries, an idea that
chills parents. Strike No. 2 _ an electric adapter is also
included, destined for the junk drawer.
</P>
<P>
   If you press the Eurosealer too tightly or too long, it melts
the bag. And it doesn't do anything that something far easier to
use, like a plastic clip, does quicker. Give it two years and there
will be a Eurosealer at every other American garage sale.
Particularly garage sales at homes outfitted with satellite dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Availability: Find the sealer on the Internet at www.jlryan.com
</P>
<P>
   Price: $16.50
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Express Gourmet
</P>
<P>
   What they say: The Kitchen Miracle that Chops, Slices, Shreds
and More!
</P>
<P>
   What I say: The pick of the litter, this little wizard is an
ideal wedding gift.
</P>
<P>
   This hand-operated setup is a combination food
processor-mandolin that handily chops onions and garlic, nicely
shreds carrots and even whips cream.
</P>
<P>
   But wait _ there's more! An egg separator is also included.
</P>
<P>
   Even for households with a food processor, this is a useful
addition. It's great to have on hand when you need to do a little
slicing and dicing but don't want to lug out the heavy electric
monster to do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Availability: Find Express Gourmet at www.asotv.com
</P>
<P>
   Price: $17.99
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Citrus Express
</P>
<P>
   What they say: Cuts perfect slices, every time!
</P>
<P>
   What I say: Anything that can take the pain out of segmenting
and peeling oranges and grapefruit is a welcome helper. This does
the job halfway. The gadget does cut the fruit away from the peel
and also cuts it into segments. Problem is, the membrane between
the segments remains. That doesn't bother me, but it scotches the
usefulness in my household because the male elements want even
their orange juice strained. Puuhleeze.
</P>
<P>
   Availability: On the Internet at www.cyberworld-marketing.com
</P>
<P>
   Price: $19.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Rotato
</P>
<P>
   What they say: Rotato peels away potato, vegetable and fruit
skins in just seconds, with one easy motion. Most important, Rotato
puts the timely, messy chore of peeling in the past!
</P>
<P>
   What I say: A great gadget to entice children into the cooking
process. My 7-year-old, not the most coordinated boy in his class,
gets a kick out of peeling potatoes and cucumbers with this
turntable operation.
</P>
<P>
   Unadvertised bonus _ the long, skinny peelings make for
interesting garnish opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Availability: Find it on the Internet at www.jlryan.com
</P>
<P>
   Price: $18
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen Gourmet Granite Hot Plate
</P>
<P>
   What they say: Keeps Food Hot For Entire Meal!
</P>
<P>
   What I say: That's why God invented microwaves. Most family
meals last no longer than 15 minutes; the average church supper
perhaps 15 minutes longer. This plate does keep food hot for up to
an hour, but really, why bother?
</P>
<P>
   Availability: Walgreens
</P>
<P>
   Price: $5.99
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen Gourmet Defrosting Tray
</P>
<P>
   What they say: Unique Aluminum Tray Thaws Food in Minutes!
</P>
<P>
   What I say: No, it doesn't. After 45 minutes, our 6-ounce
tenderloin was still solid in the middle. And excuse me, but how
difficult is it to put the meat in the refrigerator the night
before or to plunk a shrink-wrapped steak into a sink of cold
water?
</P>
<P>
   Availability: Walgreens
</P>
<P>
   Price: $7.99
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
