<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENWAY PLANNERS OF TODAY SHOULD REMEMBER OLMSTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One major witness in the case of Fenway Park influenced its
development more than Babe Ruth, Bucky Dent, or Willie Tasby. When
Frederick Law Olmsted, an American genius, planned the nearby Fens,
he succeeded in his aim to provide ``Turf, trees, water, and other
natural objects, unnaturally arranged but not in the main
unpleasingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Olmsted would admire the proposed right-field facade because it
restores a nearby street as a major boulevard. As for inside the
park, he always liked ``a simple, broad, open space of clean
greensward.''
</P>
<P>
   Excessive reverence for ``The Green Monster,'' a name for the
park's left-field wall since 1975, might puzzle Olmsted, although
he understood how grandiose titles grow. The wall was just the wall
before Carlton Fisk willed a home run over it one October night.
What many now call ``the Emerald Necklace'' was to Olmsted a
logical and utilitarian series of sewers and drainage projects from
the Muddy and Charles Rivers to Stony Brook, Jamaica Pond, and
Franklin Park.
</P>
<P>
   Farsighted about change and growth, Olmsted said in 1870, ``It
is practically certain that the Boston of today is the mere nucleus
of the Boston that is to be. It is practically certain that it is
to extend over many miles of country now thoroughly rural in
character.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1878, Olmsted was at the zenith of landscape architecture,
having designed, with Calvert Vaux, New York's Central Park and
Prospect Park in Brooklyn. Boston's parks commission asked him to
plan 106 acres reclaimed from fetid swamps. ``Back Bay,'' now a
byword for elegance, was then, Olmsted said, ``a gulf of mud and
water.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 2, 1886, Olmsted told the Boston Society of Architects
how the Fens, where the Muddy meets the Charles, was crucial to his
plan. He worked with the superintendent of sewers and the city
engineer, Joseph Phineas Davis, who told him, ``If the state of
Massachusetts had been hunted over, a space combining more
disadvantages for a park could not have been found.''
</P>
<P>
   The conduits, channels, and causeways he designed would stretch
5 miles by 1886, from the Fens to Franklin Park, which Olmsted
considered ``of greater lasting consequence to the city than those
of other of its public works at the present time.'' As one who
spent a childhood equidistant from and happily infesting both, I
agree that Franklin Park will always be Boston's focus of freedom
and variety, far more important than Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Olmsted thought the short Boylston Street bridge over the Fens
``the most conspicuous object in all the scheme.'' He asked his
friend, Henry Hobson Richardson, the architect of Trinity Church,
to design it. The Massachusetts Historical Society and St.
Clement's Shrine stand as grand sentinels before Richardson's
bridge of Cape Ann granite.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Fens, Boylston's planned grandeur
yields to unplanned junk. In 1982, Cynthia Zaitzevsky wrote in
``Frederick Law Olmsted and the Boston Park System,'' that ``The
Fens is a rather peculiar collection of spaces that appear to be
connected entirely by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   With a revived Sears building breathing retail life into a
campus of colleges and hospitals, a new ballpark will make Boylston
a grand entrance and stabilize what Olmsted once called ``an
unhealthy and pestilential neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Olmsted avoided cliches. The new ballpark does not. Preserving
the old wall and the infield is a generous gesture, but reproducing
it is a hackneyed impulse that will hurt the home team. Over the
current wall, a real city looms. The new one will squat underneath
the ultimate cliche, a gee-whiz billboard-scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   The left-field wall protected Fenway Park from the soot and
noise of the Boston &AMP; Albany Railroad, now long gone. Olmsted would
have seen no organic sense in enshrining an obsolete artifact. The
man who mastered nature for Boston's benefit was always more
practical than romantic.
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
