<HEADER>
A8948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-09 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIES TARGET GUN MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is an honest desperation about the lawsuits being filed
against gun makers by Boston and 19 other cities. There was no
alternative as Congress plays the hit man for the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress agonizes over the most minor of gun restrictions and
clatters in abject cowardice over sweeping gun control, the mayors
got the message that NRA money still means more in Washington, even
in its somewhat devalued state after the Littleton schoolyard
massacre, than spilled blood, spent medical resources, and
traumatized neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Littleton, the mayors faced an indefinite state of
abandonment. So it should have been no surprise that when the NRA
went ahead with its convention in Denver this spring, despite the
events in Littleton, loudest protest came from Denver Mayor
Wellington Webb. Despite the $18 million the convention was said to
be worth to the city, Webb said, ``We don't want you here.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb's fellow mayors are saying likewise. Over the last nine
months cities that include Chicago, Miami, New Orleans, Atlanta,
Los Angeles, Detroit, San Francisco, and Bridgeport, Conn., have
filed suit. Some of the suits stress the aspect of public nuisance.
Others stress the issue of product liability and unfair business
practices. So far, Chicago has made the biggest monetary claim _
$435 million.
</P>
<P>
   Boston joined the list last week, filing suit against 31 gun
manufacturers. Boston accuses gunmakers of being a public nuisance,
using reckless marketing practices that make guns far too easy to
be purchased by youths and criminals. The city calculates that from
1993 to 1998, the resulting gunfire cost $100 million in deaths,
injuries, and lower tax revenues from neighborhoods where such
violence shot down property values.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, like many cities, filed the suit with a notable defiance
despite going where no higher layer of government has gone before
against the NRA. In Chicago, Mayor Richard M. Daley said, ``This is
just the beginning.'' In Los Angeles, city attorney James Hahn
declared the LA suit to be ``a pretty big stick.'' In Bridgeport,
Mayor Joseph Gamin said, ``We are saying to the gun industry, `From
now on, you are responsible for the costs associated with your
dangerous products.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Peter Welsh, the director of policy and planning for
Mayor Thomas M. Menino, said, ``We don't intend to lose, we're
entering this to win.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains for Boston and the other cities to determine is the
definition of victory. Whether it is Boston's $100 million or
Chicago's $435 million, most of the suing mayors are smart enough
to say that this is not about money alone, but about accessibility
to guns and forcing gun makers to make guns more ``safe,'' with
reliable locking mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
   That is a positive step and the cities have a good chance at
forcing change on those fronts. The gun industry, while quite
lethal, does not have the deep pockets to defend itself constantly
in court state by state. Without the deep pockets, the industry has
already shown a willingness to compromise with government officials
on minor gun restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's compromises have caused a rift with the NRA,
which views every gun restriction as the next coming of communism.
</P>
<P>
   But minor restrictions are not enough to gain victory for the
citizens. It is unclear if the suits, while properly speaking to
the reckless marketing of guns, can do anything to blunt the actual
production of guns, as well as their trafficking from gun-happy
states such as Georgia, Texas, and Virginia to the more congested,
gun-shy states of the North.
</P>
<P>
   It is particularly unclear what a victory in Boston or
Bridgeport will ultimately mean, if a similar measure fails to get
out of the starting gate in, say, Georgia, where the NRA has
already gotten the state Legislature to pass a law banning Atlanta
from pursuing its suit against the gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   If the gun makers are not cutting production, the guns will
still go to the states of least resistance, which surely will
become the states that pay the least attention to out-of-state
sales. Boston may have named Smith and Wesson, only two hours away
in Springfield in its suit, but there is nothing Boston can do to
stop Smith and Wesson to flood another city on the ``I-95
pipeline,'' a pipeline that was a deadly boomerang for Boston
earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The boomerang of bullets will stop only with national gun
control. Eventually, the lawsuits have to become either so
voluminous and unified as to create a wall of legal resistance to
guns, or they have to wreak so much havoc on the conscience of
politicians that the states, Congress, and the White House stop the
cowardly clatter and create national controls.
</P>
<P>
   No one else has yet gotten the nation's politicians to pay
attention to the spilled blood, the spent emergency resources, and
the traumatized neighborhoods. The mayors might as well try. But
victory cannot be theirs city by city. They will win only if their
suits get the governors, House representatives, senators and the
president to say to the NRA, ``We don't want you here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
