<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING OFF THE DEEP END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, I was unable to talk about my pool problems. It was
like suffering from a rare neurological disorder that affected only
rich people. Pool owners are to be mocked, envied perhaps.
Definitely exploited with false bonhomie during heat waves. But not
sympathized with.
</P>
<P>
   Then I became a pool owner. It wasn't my fault. We bought a
house; it had a pool. The previous owner, a dermatologist (or was
it a plastic surgeon?) built it. Naturally, the real estate broker
didn't mention the pool in the listing, because then anyone who had
ever owned a pool wouldn't have answered the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of size _ mine is the proverbial whole 9 yards long,
and about 10 feet wide _ pools are enormous, costly headaches. To
prevent the water from turning a spinachy green requires
Nobel-level chemistry skills. And the chemicals are expensive.
Baking soda costs about a dollar a box at the supermarket. But when
transformed into ``Pool Balance Plus'' and packaged under a bright,
sunshiney label, sodium carbonate costs five times as much.
</P>
<P>
   About three years ago, I finally conquered my pool-related class
anxiety. I was sipping garage coffee with the guys who fix my car
and heard them kvetching about their pools! Their complaints were
the same as mine: ``I can't get the Ph to balance''; ``The spring
on my skimmer weir is jammed''; or: ``Is it a hygiene problem if
you find a drowned squirrel in the outtake line?'' (Yes).
</P>
<P>
   The scales fell from my eyes. If these regular joes could
complain about their pools, so could I! I subsequently learned that
I needn't have been so shy. I am one of about 250,000 Bay State
pool owners. Indeed, we are the third most pool-owning state in the
union, trailing only Florida and Arizona. Aside from my mechanics,
I don't know anyone who owns a pool, but, theoretically, they're
out there.
</P>
<P>
   And they are complaining. Because once you start, you never
stop. The first summer I owned the pool, I resolved to ``do the
chemistry'' myself. How hard could it be? These pool maintenance
guys weren't exactly Mensa fodder. The pool chemistry tests are a
lot like home pregnancy tests, except instead of bodily fluids, you
pour a few drops of pool water into reagent-treated plastic
beakers. Whatever was supposed to happen never happened for me. I
wasted bucketfuls of chemicals, languished in self-loathing, and
eventually begged the service guys to handle the job for me.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the cruel fact: Pools are fine as long as you don't put
anything in them. New England's acid rain throws off the chemistry.
Every species of wildlife seeks out your pool for its gory,
waterlogged Viking suicide ritual. Except frogs, of course; for
them you've created the northern part of heaven: a cool, snake-free
environment. Kids love' em! Wives, not so much.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst thing to put in your pool is people. Perspiration,
those skin oils, foot dirt _ yuck! As soon as my sons and their
hot-weather friends get out, two buckets of chlorine go in.
Otherwise, that wispy algae peach fuzz starts to _ well, you really
don't want to know.
</P>
<P>
   If you think pool owners complain a lot, you should hear my pool
service people. They hate pool work because it's hot and sweaty,
and they miss their real profession _ that of ski bum. They
complain about their boss because he's exploiting them as seasonal
labor. And they hate me because I own a pool.
</P>
<P>
   Their boss has become a friend of mine, and he complains
constantly, about his workers, about his subcontractors, about his
clients. As far as I can tell, all his other clients are rich jerks
who make his life miserable if their pool isn't open by Memorial
Day. I'm not rich; maybe my pool will be ready to use by July
Fourth.
</P>
<P>
   I know. You're like everybody else. You don't want to hear me
complain. You just want to come over and use my pool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
