<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIEST REBUTS SKEPTICAL ASSESSMENT OF NEW TESTAMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After nearly 2,000 years, Jesus continues to fuel raging debates
among scholars seeking to illuminate the life of the rebel Jew who
has shaped much of our history.
</P>
<P>
   At the cusp of the third millennium, publishing houses have been
churning out a steady stream of books devoted to revealing the
``historical'' Jesus, the facts about his life.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, trying to paint a biographical sketch of the man
Christians regard as the Messiah is a sure way to provoke
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerome Murphy-O'Connor, a Dominican priest, has spent
more than three decades studying the Bible hoping to gain insights
into the life and times of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   A respected and internationally known scholar, Murphy-O'Connor
welcomes the critical study of Scripture and the effort to provide
as complete a record of Jesus's life as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But during a recent visit to Boston he took issue with the work
of the ``Jesus Seminar,'' a group of scholars that has gained
widespread attention for challenging the veracity of some of the
New Testament accounts of Jesus's ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jesus Seminar folks treat Scripture as defendants in a
trial with a very bad record,'' Murphy-O'Connor said during a
lecture last week at St. Ignatius Church at Boston College. ``The
burden of proof lies with the text. No 2,000-year-old text could
ever stand up to that kind of scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jesus Seminar, Murphy-O'Connor said in an interview, has
``duped'' the media, in part, by promoting its findings at
Christmas and Easter, two times when the media are keenly
interested in religion stories.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the Jesus Seminar has generated a backlash,
with scholars such as Murphy-O'Connor refuting some of the
seminar's findings.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy-O'Connor is a professor of the New Testament at the
prestigious Ecole Biblique in Jerusalem and the author of numerous
books, including ``The Holy Land,'' a best-selling archeological
guide-book of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy-O'Connor's approach to the Bible is more positive than
that of the scholars of the Jesus Seminar. ``The text should be
treated as a witness who is basically trying to tell the truth,''
he said during his lecture.
</P>
<P>
   One important source of contention regarding Jesus's life is the
crucial role played by the fishermen who followed Jesus. Some
scholars dismiss them as unreliable sources of information because
they were lower-class people who would be expected to exaggerate
accounts of Jesus to elevate their status.
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy-O'Connor disagrees, arguing that the fishermen were
actually astute middle-class businessmen. As evidence he says the
fishermen had employees and they moved their fishing operations to
another town on the banks of the Galilee to avoid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were not, as some people believe, some wandering
religious nuts who would have followed anyone,'' Murphy-O'Connor
said. `They were unlikely to make up stuff and certainly not if it
would have gotten them into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   A key focus of Murphy-O'Connor's lecture revolved around Jesus's
time in Galilee, a critical turning point in his life. It was
there, Murphy-O'Connor said, that Jesus experienced his second
conversion _ the first occurred when he was baptized by John the
prophet.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in Galilee, Jesus came to sympathize with the
plight of shepherds, a class of people Jewish law considered
sinners. But Jesus believed people were forced to become shepherds
because of economic circumstances and they needed to provide for
their families.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time, Murphy-O'Connor said, that Jesus
challenged Jewish law and it began the course that led to his
crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
