A8970 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-POETRY-BOS &LR;      06-09 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-POETRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREACHING ABOUT POETRY; TACTILE LINES FROM IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT TAYLOR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
HOW TO READ A POEM 
And Fall in Love With Poetry 
By Edward Hirsch 
Harcourt Brace, 352 pp., $23 
 
SELECTED POEMS 
By Michael Longley 
Wake Forest University Press, 132 pp., $12.95 (paper) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost 60 years ago, the University of Chicago sage Mortimer
Adler published ``How to Read a Book,'' in which he declared, ``The
most direct sign that you have done the work of reading is fatigue.
Reading that is reading involves the most intense mental activity.
To read books passively does not feed a mind. It makes
blotting-paper out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue, however, is not a sensation associated with MacArthur
fellow Edward Hirsch's ``How to Read a Poem.'' ``Reading poetry,''
he says, ``is an adventure in renewal, a creative act, a perpetual
beginning, a rebirth of wonder.'' In other words, passion is the
key to understanding poetry, along with ``adventure,'' creativity,
``wonder.'' Hirsch, who is certainly well intentioned and armed
with insightful commentary on individual poems, seeks to enlarge
poetry's audience. He seems reluctant to admit that certain poems
have a formal structure as complex as calculus.
</P>
<P>
   His problems begin with his title. Falling in love with poetry
suggests the emotional approach he prefers, the romantic notion
that reading poetry has a redemptive quality. Perhaps; but people
rarely fall in love on an analytical basis. Do we read poetry
because it is good for us? The inseparability of form and matter in
a poem does not lead to virtue but to the pleasure of recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the question, for whom is this book intended? It
opens with a trenchant discussion of figurative language and the
transaction that occurs between poet and reader. Hirsch, citing the
Russian poet Osip Mandelstam, sees poetry as ``a message in a
bottle'' washed onshore to be discovered by the reader, ``its
secret addressee.'' He celebrates his own lyrical responses to
poetry, and there's nothing wrong with that _ only his hortatory
tone reminds one of a vibrant teacher attempting to convey the
importance of Whitman, Dickinson, and Auden to the back row of a
class occupied by students sunk in a torpor.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch is at his best when he reveals by example the layers of
meaning of Sylvia Plath's ``Edge,'' Elizabeth Bishop's ``In the
Waiting Room,'' Christopher Smart's jubilant ``My Cat Jeoffrey.''
Readers of poetry, though, are usually familiar with the hurdles he
guides us over. The question lingers: Has Hirsch really increased
poetry's audience? One suspects, alas, that obvious intelligence
and rhapsodic feeling won't do, and that, notwithstanding an
attractively designed format and a useful glossary of poetic
conventions, his book is another case of preaching to the
converted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Longley is probably the least publicized of the northern
writers _ Seamus Heaney and Derek Mahon among others _ who
revitalized Irish poetry during the '60s. A rare melodic clarity
characterizes Longley's lines, and ``Selected Poems,'' now
available in paperback, is notable for its classic restraint.
</P>
<P>
   In Belfast, where he makes his home (his wife, Edna, is a
well-known literary critic), Longley has been actively involved in
literary and arts council programs. His poetry exhibits the shadows
of a 20-year period of social upheaval _ ``Wreaths,'' for example,
etches miniature portraits of innocent people murdered in mundane
surroundings _ but he also achieves substance through metaphor and
imagery derived from nature. Landscapes are vividly tactile: He is
a poet of tender, fleeting observations _ the crushed blossom, the
foam-flecked wave, the darting minnow. And sometimes his language
has the timeless character of a Chinese scroll, as in ``Out
There'':
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)
</P>
<P>
   Do they ever meet out there,
</P>
<P>
   The dolphins I counted,
</P>
<P>
   The otter I wait for?
</P>
<P>
   I should have spent my life
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the waves.
</P>
<P>
   (end ital)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1518EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
