<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      06-09 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON AND HOLLYWOOD; GIRL POWER; GENDER CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CYNTHIA DOCKRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was going to be a ``Star Wars''-free column, but Samuel L.
Jackson's Jedi role has earned him cover stories in two current
magazines. Face it, the menace is with us.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Jackson's part in this movie is simply an excuse to
take a look at where the actor has been and where he's going. He's
profiled at length in the June edition of Icon as well as in a new
monthly, Code, which bills itself as ``the style magazine for men
of color.'' (``Style'' is the key word here; imagine a deeper shade
of GQ.)
</P>
<P>
   Both stories emphasize Jackson's ascendancy in Hollywood in
recent years. Whereas he used to get parts rejected by Denzel
Washington or Wesley Snipes, now, thanks largely to his
performances in ``Jungle Fever'' and ``Pulp Fiction,'' he's the guy
directors go to first.
</P>
<P>
   Not that his choices are without controversy. As Icon's Evan
Wiener writes: ``If you want to keep working (and golfing) in
Hollywood, you have to play by some of the town rules. If you're a
black actor and you've established yourself playing a crackhead and
a killer, that means you're going to be playing lots of variations
on crackheads and killers. And you're going to be dealing with all
the antagonism that comes with that territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson does not apologize for the gun-toting roles that some
critics say reinforce a white-America stereotype about black men.
While he does take part occasionally in lower-budget fare such as
the new ``Red Violin,'' Jackson makes no bones about wanting the
big-bang roles that pay. Given his solid acting background in
everything from theater to commercials, and a yearslong drug habit
that's finally been vanquished, you can hardly blame him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Outside magazine launched its sister
publication, Women Outside. It was planned as a quarterly, but here
it is June and the second issue has just come out. The editors
promise to have a third installment on the stands by September, and
they claim to have a committed editorial team that will keep this
thing going. We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the summer issue has every bit as much girl power _ and
I don't mean that figuratively _ as its predecessor. A whole range
of physical courage is displayed here. Women hang glide, they run
100 miles at a clip and still have time for their kids, they skirt
snakes and flesh-eating bacteria in the Amazon just to study a
vine. Looking at photos of wildwater kayakers and rock climbers
hanging like bats above Morocco, I got to wondering if I was really
the same gender as these people.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the stories star Wonder Women (good thing _ readers for
whom such adventures could never be a reality may be lost readers).
Some of the features are general enough to have appeared in any
number of magazines. One, about the demand for echinacea, raises
alarms.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years this plant has been so widely touted as an
herbal cold remedy that the Great Plains, where it grows wild, have
been virtually stripped. Writes Daniel Glick, one witness
``described hillsides so pockmarked with shovel holes that it
seemed like a passel of prairie dogs had held a drunken frat party
on the plains.'' Poachers and others who've smelled the money to be
made in this business have contributed to what environmentalists
see as an eco-disaster: Like dominoes, other species of plants and
animals may fall into extinction. There is a complex social
component to this story, too, as Native American tribes contend
with the conflicting interests of making money and preserving
what's left of their land and culture.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, this article will make you think twice about
reaching for an herbal remedy next time you visit the drugstore.
Echinacea is just one plant in our burgeoning arsenal of
alternative medications. How many others are we killing off?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the civil rights movement gave every minority the right to
stand up and be counted, few have failed to do so. But one group
has been so profoundly misunderstood that it has stayed hidden
until now.
</P>
<P>
   In the May/June Lingua Franca, Emily Nussbaum offers a
fascinating report on hermaphroditism, a broad term for ambiguous
gender. Intersexuals, as they are known, are born with neither
overtly male nor overtly female genitals; most often they have
characteristics of both sexes. Traditionally doctors have operated
on these babies soon after birth, making them into either boys or
girls (usually girls, since that's easier), and then no one outside
the infants' families is the wiser. But in the last few years, many
intersexuals have come forward to protest what they see as
butchery. Making one's genitals conform to this or that sex, they
say, doesn't necessarily make them any good.
</P>
<P>
   Many intersexuals believe that children like them should be left
alone to grow up ambiguously and entrusted with the decision to
become wholly male or female later on. Not surprisingly, most
doctors disagree with this position, in large part because of the
social complications. As Nussbaum quotes one physician who has
worked with intersexual kids, ``What are you going to say, `Boys
get in this line, girls get in that line, and all the little
hermaphrodites get in this other line'?''
</P>
<P>
   No one pretends to have answers to questions like this, but at
least intersexuals are beginning to shed their shame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
