</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNICATIONS-SHIFT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INDUSTRY RUSHES TO REGENERATE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years after America's telephone monopoly was broken into
eightpieces, the US telecommunications industry is caught up in
such a mad rush to merge back into an ever-smaller number of giants
that it might be fair to wonder: Why did we ever bust up AT&AMP;T?
</P>
<P>
   The original seven Baby Bells will soon be down to four, and
most are launching their own megadeals to become national and
international powerhouses. The old Southwest Bell will soon range
from Connecticut and Ohio to California, Bell Atlantic (which
absorbed Nynex two summers ago) is merging early next year with
local and long-distance provider GTE, and U S West is pursuing a
complex marriage with international cable owner Global Crossing and
local provider Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, meanwhile, is buying cable TV companies such as TCI and
MediaOne, spending $130 billion to own a wire into two-thirds of US
homes in hopes of once again becoming your local carrier. All signs
indicate the industry will only further consolidate to a handful of
huge players.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make some people who still rue the demise of
``the phone company'' wonder whether all the disruption and
confusion they have faced have really been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm kind of rooting for AT&AMP;T to come back and be in
charge of everything,'' said Les Hallenack, a semi-retired software
consultant in Watertown, Mass., who still thinks Ma Bell should
have been better regulated, not separated.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Hallenack's pet peeves are the endless string of numbers
he must dial to make a charge-card call on a pay phone, and the
dozen pieces of junk mail he gets every month from AT&AMP;T competitors
wanting his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when they broke it up it was kind of stupid. Rates
could have gone down had we just left AT&AMP;T intact and tried to
better regulate them,'' Hallenack said. ``I figure at the rate
things are going, we'll be back to one company in about seven
years, and if we control it properly, we'll all be in better
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   But while many people like Hallenack lament mind-boggling
telephone bills and dinner-hour long-distance telemarketing calls,
most industry analysts and government authorities find it
unimaginable consumers would be enjoying anything like today's
reduced costs, improved service, and explosion of new products had
AT&AMP;T survived as the omnipresent Ma Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breakup of the Bell System, in terms of what it set out to
do, has to go down as possibly the most successful antitrust policy
in the country's history,'' said Lee L. Selwyn, president of
Economics and Technology Inc., a Boston consulting firm that
advises the Massachusetts attorney general's office on
telecommunications policy.
</P>
<P>
   Phone usage skyrockets &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Selwyn has calculated that in real dollars, the cost of a
three-minute coast-to-coast call has dropped by 91 percent since
1969, almost all of the reduction since the AT&AMP;T divestiture on New
Year's Day, 1984. The typical long-distance call today costs no
more than the typical local call did in the 1950s, Selwyn said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are ``voting with their feet,'' Selwyn noted, making
probably quadruple the number of long-distance calls they did in
1984. From 1984 to 1995, the most recent year available in Census
Bureau reports, ``daily conversations'' on the US phone network
grew ninefold from 1.2 billion to 11.6 billion, plus untold
billions more data and fax calls.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the headlines may suggest the industry is in the
process of undoing the AT&AMP;T breakup, at most the spate of
consolidations will lead to a strongly competitive oligopoly, with
multiple national telephone and cable television companies battling
each other to provide telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
   US Representative Edward J. Markey of Massachusetts, the ranking
Democrat on the House telecommunications subcommittee, said to many
casual observers, the trend of ``recombinant telecommunications
DNA'' may look like ``AT&AMP;T is trying to put Humpty Dumpty back
together again.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Markey notes, there is a huge difference now: ``If AT&AMP;T is
Humpty, Bell Atlantic is Dumpty, and the law says they can't go
back together again.'' Plus there is another factor: cable and
utility companies are stringing competing lines into homes and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the land-line companies converge, booming wireless
companies, which count more than 60 million Americans as customers,
will provide competition from another front to keep pressure on
calling costs.
</P>
<P>
   Breakup fueled technology advances &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1984 resolution of the federal government's 10-year-old
antitrust suit against AT&AMP;T aimed, among other things, to open up
the telephone industry to competition in residential long-distance
service and in the supply of telecommunications equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Once AT&AMP;T's 22 local operating companies were split into seven
Baby Bells, local companies had no particular incentive to steer
long-distance business to Ma Bell and no requirement to buy most or
all of their equipment from AT&AMP;T's Western Electric unit, now
Lucent Technologies. Nor could they use inflated long-distance
charges to business customers to subsidize local calling.
</P>
<P>
   Besides driving down long-distance bills, the AT&AMP;T breakup is
credited with fostering a vibrant, innovative US telecommunications
manufacturing sector that now totals $120 billion a year in sales,
including a market for home phones that customers once had to rent
at inflated prices from AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have services today that 15 years ago people never dreamed
of when the telephone company was a fat and happy monopoly,'' said
Gary Morgenstern, spokesman for AT&AMP;T's northeastern operations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8984 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMUNICATIONS-SHIFT-     06-09 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNICATIONS-SHIFT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... AT&AMP;T's northeastern operations.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And when MCI and Sprint began building fiber-optic networks
promising, in the memorable ad, sound so clear you can hear a pin
drop, the threat pushed AT&AMP;T to develop its own fiber-optic network
years sooner than it might have otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   From 82 percent in 1985, AT&AMP;T's share of the long-distance
market has dwindled to 62.2 percent as of September, according to
the Yankee Group in Boston. MCI-WorldCom has more than doubled its
business in that time to 12.3 percent, followed by Sprint with 5.1
percent, Excel with 2.5, and GTE at 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Call waiting, caller ID, home voice mail, and all the other
goodies that are now commonly offered by Baby Bells probably would
have taken years or decades longer to become available if AT&AMP;T had
remained a monopoly, industry analysts contend.
</P>
<P>
   But the progress has not been painless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly people who were very used to doing business with the
old Bell system found it very comfortable and very attractive to
make one phone call and get anything fixed or anything delivered,''
said James Cullen, president and chief operating officer of Bell
Atlantic. As a young executive on loan to AT&AMP;T from New Jersey Bell
in 1982, Cullen helped lead planning for the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the competitive benefits that have been released have
gone primarily to businesses, and less so to consumers,'' Cullen
said. But, he adds, ``We had something akin to the Pentagon or the
Post Office doing Soviet-style five-year plans. We did unleash a
lot of competition and entrepreneurship and very accountable market
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Ringing headaches &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, what some see as market-responsive forces, others _ such
as business people interviewed last week in the Boston suburb of
Somerville _ find to be a big headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is we get 10 calls a day asking us to switch
carriers, and it's a little aggravating,'' said Frances Travassos,
who manages the Ultima Hair Design salon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My one comment on'' what long-distance competition has
achieved ``would be: confusion,'' said Mary Baker, who runs a
travel agency across the street. ``People try to explain it to me,
but a lot of people feel the best thing is to take the easiest way
out'' and keep AT&AMP;T, which she has done.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the costs of the AT&AMP;T divestiture are hard to
calculate, one became plainly visible on Bell Atlantic customers'
bills last month: a new 23-cent-a-month ``local number
portability'' charge to cover the cost of allowing people to switch
local service from a Baby Bell to a competitor, even though most
residential users can't make the swap yet. Elsewhere in the country
these fees are as high as 53 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, for example, estimates it will spend $1 billion
to open up its Maine-to-Virginia network to competition, although
it says most of that cost will be borne by its shareholders, not
phone customers.
</P>
<P>
   Had AT&AMP;T survived in its original form, Americans likely never
would have heard of slang such as ``slamming'' and ``cramming'' _
terms for unscrupulous practices by competitors who switch
unwitting customers to another carrier or hit them with obscure,
unwanted charges on their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Markey, however, calls those problems solvable by regulations
and overall ``a relatively small price to pay for the huge,
economic Information Age transformation our country has undergone
in the last 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Another huge, if hard to measure, cost has been the confusing
proliferation of area codes across the United States since AT&AMP;T was
broken up. That trend has been driven largely by the need to supply
new blocks of phone numbers for Baby Bell local service
competitors, although many contend the blame lies in poor planning
and management of number allocation by state and federal
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, the number of US area codes has boomed from 125 to
more than 330. Massachusetts has gone from two to five and may need
nine by 2002. By some estimates, more than 60 percent of all
Americans have been subjected to an area-code change since 1995,
paying all that entails in new stationery and signs, reprogramming
of computers, and general disruption.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, though, most residential users and business owners
seem happy with the outcome of the AT&AMP;T breakup.
</P>
<P>
   John R. Wiseman Jr., who runs a family insurance agency in
Somerville, said, ``We don't miss the old AT&AMP;T as much as I thought
we would.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought at first it was terrible, but I think what has
happened is the competition has kept the prices down for small
businesses like ours, contrary to what I would have expected,''
said Wiseman.
</P>
<P>
   His agency continues to use AT&AMP;T for long distance, and he
marvels at how cheap it has become to, for example, send a fax to
Florida or California.
</P>
<P>
   And national surveys by the Yankee Group, a leading
telecommunications analysis firm, indicate people are substantially
happier with their telephone service than any other wire or
communications device coming into their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said, `Why did they break up something that worked so
well? We had the best system in the world _ why did we destroy it?'
'' said analyst Fred Voit of the Yankee Group.
</P>
<P>
   But in his firm's September 1998 survey of 2,040 Americans, the
percentage of people calling their long-distance service excellent
or good was 84 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That compared to 81.3 percent for local phone service, 71.4
percent for Internet access, 70.1 percent for cellular, 67.2
percent for electric, and 61 percent for cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Given what a vastly different world it is now compared to 1984,
with telephone companies facing global competition and alternative
technologies like ``cable broadband'' and cheap cellular calling
that were barely envisioned then, many analysts are comfortable the
current reconsolidation cannot squelch competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AT&AMP;T cable acquisitions do not bother me at all, and in
fact I think they are good things,'' said Selwyn, the Boston
consultant. ``The fact that this market ends up an oligopoly is not
unexpected or necessarily bad, in that lots of industries end up
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic hopes to close its merger with GTE sometime early
next year, which will give it a major presence in states such as
California, Florida, Illinois, and Texas as well as potentially
nationwide access to the long-distance market it is now trying to
enter one state at a time in Massachusetts New York, and, soon,
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   As Bell Atlantic's Cullen puts it, in today's climate, ``You
need to move up on the size-and-scope food chain to be able to
compete with an AT&AMP;T or an MCI.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1526EDT &QL; 
