<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-BKN-HOLDSCLAW-BOS     06-09 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-BKN-HOLDSCLAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WNBA STAR IS BORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The non-paying crowd of about 500 had come to the
MCI Center on a hot Monday afternoon not to see the NBA's Wizards,
but to see the Mystics, the city's WNBA franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd came to the preseason practice to see the team
scrimmage, shoot, and dribble, and to hear the coach explain what
kind of defense the team will execute this season.
</P>
<P>
   Which was all very nice, but when practice ended and the team
members lined up to introduce themselves, it was obvious who the
main attraction was. There was polite applause for Jennifer Whittle
and her Australian accent, and more rousing applause for returning
guard Nikki McCray, who averaged 17.7 points per game last year.
</P>
<P>
   But when Chamique Holdsclaw stepped to the mike, there were
hoots and hollers by fans who hope the No. 1 draft pick will do for
the team what she did for the University of Tennessee and for her
high school in Queens, N.Y. _ make it number one.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they don't just hope Holdsclaw will bring the magic
touch. They assume it.
</P>
<P>
   Her resume of awards, records, and championships is why she's
being referred to as the next Michael Jordan, why her mug has been
on the cover of TV Guide, and why the ``Today'' show, Rosie
O'Donnell, and David Letterman were all courting her. It's why she
garnered a paycheck way above scale (estimated at $200,000) and a
multiyear contract with Nike.
</P>
<P>
   It's why the Mystics _ who last year had the league's best
attendance but worst record _ hope they can reverse their losing
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans were so loyal last year and endured a 3-27 season.
Their reward is to have Chamique here,'' said coach Nancy Darsch.
In other words, they more than deserve the star.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of Holdsclaw is a much-needed bright spot for
women's basketball as the WNBA opens its third season Thursday
night. The sport suffered a setback when the rival ABL folded last
December, but the upside is that about three dozen players from the
ABL were drafted by WNBA teams.
</P>
<P>
   So despite a labor dispute that threatened to delay the start of
the 32-game season, the league should now be bolstered by all the
best women basketball players in America.
</P>
<P>
   Those players include Olympians Sheryl Swoopes of the two-time
national champion Houston Comets; Dawn Staley, former ABL player
now with the Charlotte Sting; and Teresa Weatherspoon, two-time
WNBA defensive player of the year, with the New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Chamique. Or 'Mique. Or Meek. Or however her fans want
to spell it.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, after practice and before going into the weight room,
Holdsclaw was handed a stack of mail that she looked at and shook
her head, saying, ``They all probably want my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. One was from a stockbroker company, but another
addressed in ball-point pen to MEEK HOLDSCLAW was aparently from a
fan, and another _ the envelope she opened right away _ had an 8 x
10 color picture of her with the national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's been a crazy spring, definitely,'' she said. It
started with the WNBA draft on May 4, graduation from the
University of Tennessee on May 14, the wedding of friend and
teammate Kellie Jolly to Jon Harper the next day, and going to WNBA
training camp the day after that. And through it all, she said
``having to go this way and that way for the WNBA.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the national attention is novel, the popularity isn't.
</P>
<P>
   So she sounds more matter-of-fact than immodest when she says
that, ``I've been in the spotlight ever since high school, so it's
not something that's new to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was on-the-court, on-the-job training, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says, `Chamique does a exceptional job at handling
it,' but that's 'cause I'm kind of used to it,'' she said with a
laugh and a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw led her Christ the King High School team to four
championships. At Tennessee, she became the school's leading scorer
(3,025), leading rebounder (1,295), and was a four-time Kodak and
Associated Press All-American. She is on the US national team, and
won the gold medal in the worlds with them last year. Tennessee won
three straight NCAA championships, falling short last spring when
they lost to Duke in the quarterfinals, when Holdsclaw was last
seen on national TV sobbing on the sidelines with her coach, Pat
Summitt.
</P>
<P>
   But Holdsclaw, who finished the season averaging 20.4 points and
8.8 rebounds, said that's behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I was upset, but I've been blessed and I'm not going to
sit there and go, `oh, I'm so depressed,' '' she said. ``I know
that not too many people are going to accomplish what I had or what
the team did for three years. So I'm content with it now, I'm
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Between her record, and the No. 23 jersey that Holdsclaw wears,
one can't help but think about the Michael Jordan analogy.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw said that she does like Mike _ ``he's the man'' _ but
the reason she wears the number is because of the 23d Psalm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always No. 10, but then my grandmother told me about the
psalm, I can't really remember, I must have had a bad game or
something, and I was like, `OK, I'm going to wear this number from
now on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And both she and Rita Williams _ who wore 23 on the Mystics last
year _ insist there was no wrestling match involved in getting
Williams to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw rolls her eyes and sighs in mock hardship, recalling
that, ``Yes, I had to buy her some golf clubs, and I have to go
take lessons with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who now wears No. 13 (``I was the 13th draft pick last
year''), confirmed that she did get a set of clubs, but that ``it
was a just a mutual thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw knew of Williams, a University of Connecticut
graduate, from being NCAA rivals, and knew of teammate McCray, a
fellow Tennessee grad.
</P>
<P>
   The two never played at the same time _ McCray was class of '95
_ but benefit from having learned under the same coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Summitt is a great coach, so it's great when you have
another player playing alongside of you that knows the same things,
and terminology,'' Holdsclaw said.
</P>
<P>
   And don't expect the rookie star to muscle the veteran out of a
job, said Holdsclaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're totally two different players,'' she said. ``Nikki's
more of a transition player, going to create off the dribbles, and
I'm more a rebounder. I'm also a scorer, but you're going to see me
go out every night and try to get 10 to 12 rebounds, whereas Nikki
is going to try and stop the other player.''
</P>
<P>
   Darsch scoffs at any suggestion that the addition of Holdsclaw
will make for a divisive team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there are players that get antsy about taking shots,
because they're used to being in that position to take shots,'' she
said. ``But I think as we develop as a team, the cohesiveness will
only get better as we share the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that everyone is glad that Chamique's here,'' Darsch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not the least of whom is the coach herself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
