<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-FOLK10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hootenanny heyday gets fitting tribute
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone with a hootenanny past will find it tough not to sing
along to this thoughtful tribute to folk-rock's birthplace.
Guitarist Steuart Smith co-produces and pays homage to the mighty
six-string on all cuts, which stretch from Jonatha Brooke's
scene-setting title number (first done by Simon and Garfun-
</P>
<P>
   kel) to an instrumental version of Pete Seeger's ``Turn! Turn!
Turn!'' Loudon Wainwright III and Iris DeMent turn Richard and Mimi
Farina's ``Pack Up Your Sorrows'' into a
harmonica-and-banjo-powered rag; Jules Shear channels John
Sebastian on his weirdly romantic ``Darling Be Home Soon.'' Curious
timepieces (Chrissie Hynde's reverential reading of Tim Buckley's
``Morning Glory''; Buzzy Linhart's ``The Love's Still Growing''
given spooky wings by Suzzy and Maggie Roche) bracket the songs you
know by heart (``Reason to Believe,'' ``Everybody's Talkin''' and
``Let's Get Together'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Bleecker Street: Greenwich Village in the '60s''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists.
</P>
<P>
   Astor Place. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Eileen M. Drennen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
