<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8993 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS10-COX     06-09 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of recently released CDs
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin Powers:
</P>
<P>
   The Spy Who Shagged Me''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Maverick. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   As psychedelic swinging detective Austin Powers, comic Mike
Myers has managed to make the '60s more crassly fun now than they
were during the height of flower power, and this CD captures all
the shaggin' spirit of the films. A batch of quirky tunes from the
era has been placed in the hands of contemporary artists, who stir
up more fun than a Twister party. Lenny Kravitz scorches through a
stoned-out version of the Guess Who's ``American Woman.'' Melanie G
(a.k.a. Scary) shows there may be life after the Spice Girls when
she turns Cameo's ``Word Up'' into a techno-inspired dance chant.
R.E.M. revives the silliest lyric in rock history _ ``Huggin' a
tree when you get near it'' _ on a near-perfect cover of Tommy
James' ``Draggin' the Line.'' Even the goofiest tracks are groovy
fun.
</P>
<P>
   _Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan Knight''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Knight. Interscope. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   This former New Kid on the Block's solo debut is a minor
miracle, considering his past affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The lascivious ``Give It to You'' is an inspired combination of
Timbaland-style hip-hop tricks and light psychedelia. As the first
single and leadoff track, it hints at an inventiveness that the CD
can't sustain, but the rest is solid and engaging fun. ``A
Different Party,'' with a hefty sample from Sugarloaf's
``Green-Eyed Lady'' and an effervescent chorus, is a perfect summer
single.
</P>
<P>
   The producers, including Jimmy Jam, Terry Lewis and former New
Kid Donnie Wahlberg, create a lot of the magic, but Knight
certainly deserves a good chunk of the credit. His voice is a much
more expressive instrument these days. He does a skillful revamp of
a high-caliber Prince nugget, ``I Could Never Take the Place of
Your Man,'' turning the bouncy original into a lovely, insinuating
ballad.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino and Shane Harrison write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
