u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSELING-HOMELESS-A     06-09 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSELING-HOMELESS-ART-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFUSING ANGER: COUNSELING HELPS HOMELESS GET PAST ABUSE,
SUFFERING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
(For release Sunday, June 13) 
 
(Attn: Tenn.) 
 
By JANETTE RODRIGUES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The bruises from the last beating Ann suffered at the
hands of her abuser have faded, but her anger lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a comfortable chair, her soft, Southern drawl hardens
when she talks about the childhood neglect and violence that sent
her looking for a man who would protect her.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he punished her.
</P>
<P>
   For years, she suppressed her feelings about the beatings over
things as innocuous as going shopping without his permission, the
constant put-downs and being cut off from the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor/Star of Hope Family Counseling Center, a program that
provides individual and group psychotherapy for homeless women and
children, is helping Ann understand the anger she's now free to
feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had anybody to talk to about the abuse, so I kept a
lot of anger inside,'' said Ann, 28, not her real name. ``But when
you're in the group you're not afraid to let it out, because the
others have been through the same thing and we support each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Located at Star of Hope Transitional Learning Center in Houston,
the program is one of only a handful in the country that offers
intensive, individual and group counseling, psychological testing
and evaluations to the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The program helps residents of the shelter understand their
problems and change the behaviors and conditions that may have
contributed to their homelessnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The types of problems we see over and over again with clients
involve past or present family violence _ physical, sexual, verbal
and emotional abuse,'' said Warren Holleman, program director and a
Baylor College of Medicine professor and marriage and family
therapist.
</P>
<P>
   The program opened last September with the help of a $636,825
grant from Episcopal Health Charities.
</P>
<P>
   The funds allow a team of therapists, clinical psychologists,
family practice physicians, a social worker and interns associated
with Baylor to work with shelter residents five days a week.
Shelter residents can use the program for up to two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working at another homeless facility for several
years,'' Holleman said. ``And there it became obvious to me that
counseling is helpful, but counseling services are generally not
available to the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes that Houston is blessed with an unusually high
number of shelters that offer such counseling services to the
homeless. Lord of the Streets Episcopal Church and SEARCH have
similar programs.
</P>
<P>
   When the homeless do have access to psychotherapy, it's usually
in a group setting. Individual counseling is not the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to do that type of individual therapy, because
the money isn't available,'' said Pat Post, spokeswoman for the
National Health Care for the Homeless Council in Nashville, Tenn.
``It's a quandary (therapists) face around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The council is a membership organization of health care
providers that work with the homeless and advocates for health care
system reform.
</P>
<P>
   Post added that, in some cases, a person isn't ready to open up
in front of a group but will in individual counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Star of Hope approached Baylor about duplicating its
psychotherapy program at the center because ``there is so much
lurking beneath the surface of homelessness,'' said Marilyn
Fountain, shelter community relations coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 people currently receive services through the
program, which also has group counseling for children and a special
group for teen-age boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Baylor program has been a godsend to clients and staff,''
Fountain said. ``It helps people clean out their wounds, so that
they are no longer infected with their pasts, and they can heal
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that being reduced to living on the streets, or
depending on family and friends for a place to sleep, doesn't
happen in just one day.
</P>
<P>
   The National Health Care for the Homeless Council reported that
between 22 percent and 50 percent of homeless women surveyed over
the last decade identified domestic violence as the reason they
left their last residence.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent anger management therapy group at the center,
Holleman and a Star of Hope facilitator encouraged the women to
bring up past or present situations that sparked their anger.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Lewis, 43, told the group she had a run-in with an
authority figure at the shelter and told the other woman off for
treating her like a child.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has come a long way since she began attending the anger
management therapy group two months ago. She no longer flies off
the handle at real or imagined slights or situations she can't
control. But she feels she slipped up with the staff person.
</P>
<P>
   When the staff person first asked Lewis to adhere to the shelter
rule about no visitors in or outside rooms, she shooed them away
after a few minutes. But the staff person brought it up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come by to say hello and ask me how I'm doing,'' said
Lewis, who is on crutches after a knee injury. ``If they are doing
it out of care and love for me, I'm not going to tell them no.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in couches around a coffee table, the group turned the
incident over and around like a building block. Then some of the
women gave their opinions on whether Lewis' anger was justified or
not, and how she should handle it in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Group members told Lewis that her anger was justified because
she was provoked, but she shouldn't let others push her buttons.
They also pointed out that she didn't resort to violence, which she
would have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   After the hourlong session, Holleman noted that the women have
come a long way considering some of them wouldn't even talk about
being angry or the trauma that's often at the root of that emotion.
</P>
<P>
   The psychotherapy program is working at Star of Hope, said
agency and Baylor officials. But there have been a few failures
because some shelter residents aren't ready for counseling. Therapy
has to come at the right time, said mental health professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right time varies from individual to individual; it may
come when you've hit rock bottom and need help,'' Holleman said.
``The wrong time is when people tell you you need it but you don't
want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ann.
</P>
<P>
   Ann believes God led her to Star of Hope. She is putting her
life back together and is eager to re-enter the work force and find
a home of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Ann now says she has self-esteem and confidence. She wants
better for herself and her 2-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be dependent on any man, my family or
anybody,'' she said. ``I'm going to get a job in computers and show
my daughter what it's like to grow up in a normal family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
