<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peppers not quite so combustible
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lock up your daughters, the Red Hot Chili Peppers are back. But
do they really need to be? The quintessential Southern California
punk-funkers are one of those early '80s arrivals that's showing
unsexy wear and tear, a band that's knocked around so long you
wonder if bassist Flea's toe-to-temple tattoos don't conceal a
fading expiration date. Between the fabled drug addictions,
notorious sexcapades, revolving cast of guitarists and the stupid
tube-sock-as-codpiece gimmick they once flaunted, the Chili Peppers
have so much rock-star credibility it's a wonder they're still
alive _ let alone capable of sequestering themselves in a studio
long enough to make another album. Besides, a generation of
white-guy funk and rap acts has, rather unfortunately, followed
their example, reminding us all why you need to be licensed to ill.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, you can view ``Californication'' _ the sometime
quartet's first disc since 1995 _ as a triumph of the human spirit
or merely a way to generate momentum for a new tour (the only place
where the band, in its full Dionysian glory, ever really defines
itself).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the indefatigable snap of rhythm guerrilla Flea's bass
and the insurgent bite of re-enlisted guitarist John Frusciante,
``Californication'' is one long-winded slog of an album. The
problem is easy enough to diagnose. The patented bad-boy raps of
vocalist Anthony Kiedis are tiresome and recycled, and he's not
enough of a real singer to make the contrite ballad stuff fly. It's
as if he's trying to turn the confessional success of ``Under the
Bridge,'' the band's early '90s mainstream breakthrough, into a
broader statement on the discontents of Hollywood high life. Which
is fine, if you want to be remembered as the '90s answer to the
Eagles, but it's never half as convincing as the firestorm of riffs
and rhythm the band gamely concocts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Californication''
</P>
<P>
   Red Hot Chili Peppers. Warner Bros. 15 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
