<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hitchcock still master of suspense
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one movie, he's the guy who misses the bus. In another, he's
seen walking the dogs. In a third, he's briefly spotted strolling
in front of Janet Leigh's car as she begins her ill-fated drive to
the Bates Motel.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Hitchcock was a director who knew good gimmicks and stuck
with them rather religiously. Such as doing walk-ons in many of his
movies. Missing that bus at the beginning of ``North by
Northwest.'' Walking that pet as Rod Taylor steps into a store to
buy two feathered friends in ``The Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have wormed my way into my own pictures as a spy,''
Hitchcock once said. ``A director should see how the other half
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wouldn't have minded doing something similar with the
press. ``I have a secret yen to interview them, to pose them for
still pictures,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning was simple, or ``purely sinister,'' as Hitchcock
put it: ``I find that the easiest way to worry people is to turn
the tables on them.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, he did just that with his marvelous movies. The
original, sinister ``The Man Who Knew Too Much'' with Peter Lorre.
The psychological mind-bender ``Spellbound'' with Gregory Peck and
Ingrid Bergman. The crafty espionage yarn ``Saboteur'' with Robert
Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock ``does not lead us to like `sympathetic' characters
who are thrown into situations that ennoble them,'' the talented
French director Francois Truffaut wrote 20 years ago in The New
York Times. ``Rather, he attempts to make us feel and recognize in
ourselves insecurity, fear, compassion and relief.''
</P>
<P>
   This year is the 100th anniversary of Hitchcock's birth. And,
naturally, homages to the master of suspense are the order of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   At 8 p.m. Friday, Atlanta's High Museum of Art will screen
``Vertigo,'' the first of seven Hitchcock movies to be shown at
Rich Auditorium. The others: ``The 39 Steps'' (June 25), ``The
Wrong Man'' (June 26), ``Suspicion'' (July 9), ``Strangers on a
Train'' (July 16), ``Dial M for Murder'' (July 23) and, of course,
``Psycho'' (July 30). Tickets are $4-$5. (Information:
404-733-4570.)
</P>
<P>
   The summer film series at the Fox Theater includes ``Vertigo''
(70 mm) and ``Psycho'' on July 8 (ticket information: Ticketmaster,
404-249-6400). And New York's Metropolitan Museum of Art has a
summer-long Hitchcock exhibit and film festival.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other Hitchcock movies worthy of your own home
video festival.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Lady Vanishes'' (1938): Sort of the English version of
``Casablanca's'' take on neutrality. In a witty spy script that
bashes British pacifism, a kind old woman disappears on a train,
and a female passenger hunts her out as other Europeans lift their
eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rebecca'' (1940): Hitchcock's American debut won an Oscar
for best picture (but not the best director award). Based on Daphne
du Maurier's Gothic novel, Joan Fontaine plays the nervous bride of
filthy-rich Laurence Olivier and shudders in the long, dark shadows
of his late first wife.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Foreign Correspondent'' (1940): A European spy thriller with
a good number of visual spins. Hitchcock makes more than anybody
could out of umbrellas and Dutch windmills.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Shadow of a Doubt'' (1943): In one of Hitchcock's sometimes
forgotten gems, Joseph Cotten is a serial killer and a family's
kind Uncle Charlie in a small, true-blue American town.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Lifeboat'' (1944): Yes, all the action takes place at sea as
World War II-era passengers from a sunken ship discover that
there's a German among them.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rope'' (1948): It's all technique. Two young men stage the
``perfect murder'' and invite the victim's father to a party with
his son's corpse stuffed in a living room chest. Hitchcock shot it
as best he could as one continuous take, but the cameras of the
time held only 10 minutes of film. Thus there are several shots of
people's backs, so that cuts could be made. Maybe it doesn't really
work, but it's worth watching to see a directing genius at play.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rear Window'' (1954): A near-perfect voyeur mystery on a
near-perfect film set as James Stewart spies what might have been a
murder through his apartment window.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``North by Northwest'' (1959): Cary Grant is everyman Roger
Thornhill, mistaken for a spy and saddled with a murder rap in a
cross-country thriller. Best gimmick: Everybody says it's the crop
duster sequence, but there's much to be said for Hitchcock's
wickedly humorous spin as Grant's picture is snapped during a
stabbing at the United Nations and he winds up with his mug (plus
the knife in his hand) on the front page of The Evening Standard.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Birds'' (1963): Less psychologically chilling than
``Psycho,'' but quite a tingler as gulls attack a coastal town.
Among the better gimmicks: An unsuspecting Suzanne Pleshette smokes
a cigarette as menacing crows flock to the playground equipment
behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
