<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MONSTERS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A monstrously good performance
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   It won one Oscar for director Bill Condon's script. It should've
won a second for Ian McKellen's slyly nuanced performance.
</P>
<P>
   In this bit of fictionalized Hollywood history, McKellen plays
gay film director James Whale (``Frankenstein'') in the final weeks
before his death. Plagued by a stroke, he's troubled by sharp
memories of growing up as a poor young British boy and fighting in
the trenches of World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Fraser plays a welcome distraction: the new (and
straight) yard boy, whom the retired director befriends, despite
the suspicions of his fretting German housekeeper (Lynn Redgrave,
in fine, Oscar-nominated comic fettle).
</P>
<P>
   Director Condon delivers a melancholy meditation on creativity
and fatigue, friendship gained and love lost. On VHS (priced for
rental) and DVD ($34.98). Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
