<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-NEW10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer and Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Psycho'' (R) _ A slavishly faithful remake of the Hitchcock
classic, shot virtually scene by scene by Gus Van Sant. Why?
Excellent question. It's very well made and acted, with Vince
Vaughn as Norman Bates, Anne Heche as his unlucky hotel guest and
Julianne Moore as her sister. But it's an odd cinematic experiment
that never seems to know exactly what it intended to prove. On tape
(rental) or DVD ($34.98). Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``From the Earth to the Moon'' (unrated) _ Well-done but too
been-done. Many recurring scenes seem familiar from feature films
such as ``The Right Stuff'' and ``Apollo 13'' and documentaries
such as Turner Broadcasting's ``Moonshot'': the astronauts' easy,
macho banter and pranks; the tense faces back in the control room
in Houston. Granted, these are necessary parts of any epic about
the space program, but Tom Hanks and HBO don't have enough new
tricks to freshen it up. Available in a six-tape box set, $89.92.
Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Kloer
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer and Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
