<HEADER>
A9001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-CANAL-WINDFALL     06-09 1517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-WINDFALL-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMA EXPECTS TO REAP BONANZA FROM CANAL OPERATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 13) 
(Eds.: Also see: Panama-canal) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALBOA, Panama _ To Americans, the Panama Canal is an icon of
progress and engineering savvy. But to Panamanians, who are about
to start running it, the canal represents a spillway of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Since the canal opened in 1914, more than 700,000 ships have
passed through its locks, shelling out billions of dollars in user
fees. The Konkar Star, for example, paid $79,000 for its recent
transit through the 50-mile route.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian officials, who begin operating the canal Dec. 31,
believe that it will be an even bigger moneymaker. They plan to
streamline operations and push for higher earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Profit is not a nasty word,'' says Mercedes Morris Garcia, a
spokeswoman for the Panama Canal Commission, the U.S.-Panamanian
agency that has run the canal since 1979. In its first year of
ownership, Panama expects to earn $30 million off the canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make it a competitive organization that's much more
in line with basic business principles in a global economy,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts warn, however, that Panama must not treat the waterway
like a money machine. If too many corners are cut, they say, the
canal will lose its hard-earned reputation for safety and service.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people watch this place and think they can make it
into a real cash cow,'' says George Markham, the canal's transit
operations director, who will retire in June.
</P>
<P>
   But, the American adds, ``the Panama Canal is a plant coming up
on 100 years old, and it needs a lot of maintenance. You can't
screw around with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States set up the Panama Canal Co. at the turn of the
century as a nonprofit federal utility with an army of employees.
</P>
<P>
   One early canal worker quoted by historian David McCullough in
his book ``The Path Between the Seas'' described the company as ``a
bureaucracy that's got Russia backed off the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet hulking as it was, the system worked. Canal company
employees religiously followed a costly schedule of repairs and
maintenance. The number of ship-transits through the canal
multiplied. The locks functioned smoothly. Accidents were rare.
Maritime traffic ran on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary function wasn't efficiency, but to keep it
operating in a safe manner,'' said a Western diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   From 1914 until 1974, tolls were frozen at 90 cents per ton for
laden ships. Such charges were calculated to cover salaries,
maintenance, capital improvements and an annual stipend to the
Panamanian government.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that the canal's U.S. administrators could have
charged much more in tolls, because for decades the waterway was a
trade-artery monopoly. Ship captains much preferred the canal to
the expensive, monthlong voyage around the tip of South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, there were no alternatives. Under those
conditions, it could have generated huge profits,'' says Juan
Jovane, an economist at the University of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   But Panamanians have long complained that the low tolls
subsidized the canal's main clients, U.S. shippers, and
short-changed their own government. Of the $10 billion in revenue
collected since the canal opened, Panama has received $1.69
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy that benefited the most from the canal was the
U.S. economy,'' says Charles Langman, director of Associated
Steamship Agents, a Panama firm that represents canal users.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Fernando Manfredo, a former canal executive: ``Panama was
just getting crumbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Such resentments as well as growing nationalism drove Panama's
leader in the mid-1970s, Gen. Omar Torrijos, to seek a new deal
with Washington. In 1977, Torrijos and President Carter signed the
Panama Canal treaties, which mandated the gradual transfer of the
waterway to Panamanian control by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, more than 95 percent of the canal's workforce has
been Panamanian, including the top administrator of the Panama
Canal Commission.
</P>
<P>
   At noon Dec. 31, the newly formed Panama Canal Authority, an
autonomous Panamanian board made up of business executives and
canal veterans, will begin operating the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations are enormous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The canal has an incredible future,'' says Marco Gandasegui, a
Panamanian political analyst. ``Sea commerce is growing. We're in
the middle of a great bonanza.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, annual revenues have jumped from $329 million in 1989 to
a record $545 million last year. Panama's share of 1998 earnings
was $118 million, and that figure is likely to rise in the future.
</P>
<P>
   With 38 ship transits per day, the canal is running at full
capacity. But a project to widen the Gaillard Cut, the waterway's
narrowest section, will allow for two-way traffic through the cut
and increase transits to 43 ships per day by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Panama has told clients that no new toll hikes are in store in
the immediate future. But Langman says canal officials are
considering a new toll structure under which cargo with a higher
value would pay more.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the canal's operators are trimming expenses.
In the past year, hundreds of the waterway's 9,700 employees have
accepted buyouts and retired early. According to Morris Garcia, the
spokeswoman for the canal commission, the number of workers will
probably stabilize somewhere between 7,500 and 8,500.
</P>
<P>
   Others savings, she says, could come from privatizing what she
calls ``nonessential'' canal operations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's unclear just how much more money Panama can realize.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat says he has heard some Panamanian politicians talk
of nearly doubling profits to $200 million annually _ a figure that
many analysts call unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panama is getting a handsome profit from the canal right
now,'' says Jurgen Dorfmeier, president of the Panamanian Maritime
Chamber. ``I doubt very much that there is anyone who feels that
they can get much more out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several factors may work against an immediate surge in profits.
For one thing, the canal treaties stipulate that toll rates must
remain reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the canal is no longer the only transoceanic route.
If the current toll of $2.57 per ton is sharply increased, shippers
may opt for ship-to-rail land bridges across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be realistic,'' says Juan Jovane, an economist at
the University of Panama.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, when canal workers switch from being U.S. to
Panamanian government employees, any effort to cut more jobs or to
reduce salaries and benefits is likely to face stiff opposition
from labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we will have more work, not better service,'' says
Carmen Santamaria, a canal traffic controller, when asked about the
effect of possible staff cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, any increase in earnings could be partially offset by
the closing of 10 U.S. military bases and the withdrawal of 10,000
U.S. troops under the terms of the canal treaties. Panama is
expected to lose up to $300 million in annual economic activity as
well as 4,000 well-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the former U.S. bases and about 500 square miles of prime
real estate along the canal present a potential windfall for
Panama. Already, Albrook Air Base has been turned into a commuter
airport, and vacated U.S. troop barracks and other properties now
house factories and container ports. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``With the canal becoming an integrated part of the economy, I
think it will be a pole for development,'' says Langman of
Associated Steamship Agents.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics are concerned that Panamanian officials will
turn to the canal when tax revenues run short or that they will
favor their political allies with lucrative contracts in the canal
area, according to Gandasegui, the political analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for abuse was made clear last year. In an
embarrassing political scandal, two government ministers were
accused of receiving special treatment in the purchase of
canal-area homes left behind by departing U.S. military officers.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, President Ernesto Perez Balladares has been
criticized for naming several relatives to the nine-member board of
the Panama Canal Authority.
</P>
<P>
   But an official with Denmark-based Maersk Line, the canal's
second-largest client, says that the autonomous nature of the
authority should shield it from government pressures. He described
its members as well-respected executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys know what they are doing,'' says Hans Moller,
managing director for Maersk Lines in Panama. ``We are watching the
developments very closely, and we have a lot of faith that the new
administration will continue to offer safe and reliable service.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, Dorfmeier says, clients will simply go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shipping is not going to stop if the canal closes tomorrow,''
he says ``I think that Panama has learned that if they don't handle
this correctly, the only one that will lose out is Panama.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
