<HEADER>
A9013 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$     06-09 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV09-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: DOES DAN QUAYLE STILL HAVE THE WRONG STUFF? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, June 9)  
(nk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some overly sensitive readers surmised from a recent column that
I think Elizabeth Dole is unfit to be the next president of the
United States because she is ``structured'' to the point that she
makes her aides count the number of steps to the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be further from the truth. I admire people who are
well-organized and orderly even though those are qualities that I
do not personally possess. The way I look at it, a candidate who is
counting her steps to the podium, the bathroom, the snack machine,
whatever, is a candidate who is not taking credit for inventing the
Internet or claiming he never inhaled.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as a humor columnist, I'm not sure it is in my best
interest to support a candidate whose most amusing quirk is the
ability to walk blindfolded to the lectern. This might be good for
five, 10 columns tops, but after that it's back to funny headlines
and lawyer jokes and whatever odors might be emanating that week
from the newsroom refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   If I were to support a candidate for purely selfish reasons (and
what other reasons are there to support a candidate?) I would, of
course, endorse Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   There is nobody currently entered in either the Democratic or
Republican presidential race who is fit to carry Quayle's golf bag,
humor-wise. From 1988, when he was selected George Bush's running
mate, to that awful January day in 1993, when the office of vice
president was taken over by Al ``The Wood Man'' Gore, Quayle gave
America more entertainment value than a year's worth of ``Murphy
Brown'' reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Dan Quayle has been out of office for a while and
there is some concern that he may have lost his touch. Would the
man who said ``Republicans understand the importance of bondage
between a parent and child'' and ``We are ready for any unforeseen
event that may or may not occur'' still have the Wrong Stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Would he become just another mumbler about villages and bridges
to the 21st century or would he still be able to inspire us, as
Americans, to wet our national pants with such lines as ``A low
voter turnout is an indication of fewer people going to the polls''
and ``It isn't pollution that's harming the environment. It's the
impurities in our air and water that are doing it''?
</P>
<P>
   An encouraging sign was the publication this week of ``What a
Waste It Is to Lose One's Mind: The Unauthorized Autobiography of
Dan Quayle'' by Deborah Werksman and Jeffrey Yoder. The title, of
course, is taken from Quayle's remark at an NAACP luncheon in 1989
where he misquoted the motto of the United Negro College Fund (``A
mind is a terrible thing to waste'') as ``What a waste it is to
lose one's mind, or not to have a mind is being very wasteful. How
true that is.''
</P>
<P>
   In their book, the authors give us a glimpse of Quayle's mind on
a variety of subjects, including:
</P>
<P>
   Geography: ``I love California. I grew up in Phoenix, Arizona. A
lot of people forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Family values: ``One third of the children today are born into
homes without families.''
</P>
<P>
   Perseverance: ``My friends, we can and we will, never, never
surrender to what is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Public speaking: ``Verbosity leads to unclear, inarticulate
things.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, history: ``The Holocaust was an obscene period
in our nation's history ... this century's history ... We all lived
in this century. I didn't live in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Dan Quayle is a tough act for Dan Quayle to follow. But
his remarks following his announcement in January that he would be
seeking the Republican party nomination for president gave me hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question,'' Quayle said, ``is whether we're going forward
to tomorrow or whether we're going past to the - to the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Quayle winds up taking us, it's bound to be a fun ride.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
