<HEADER>
A9016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      06-09 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LESLIE LAND    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Growing Real Gherkins  &QL; 
Q. I've always made pickled gherkins from pickling cucumbers,
carefully harvesting the baby ones while they were still very small
and firm. Now I've been told that ``real gherkins'' are actually a
different vegetable. Is this true?  &QL; 
A. Real gherkins are really cool cucumbers, not a different
vegetable but a different species. Standard slicers and picklers
are both Cucumis sativus; gherkins are C. anguria. They're often
called West India gherkins, a reference to their route here from
Africa, or burr gherkins, a very good description of the small,
oval fruits, which are covered with soft spines. They have thin,
pale green skin, lots of tiny seeds and an agreeable, distinctive
flavor clearly related to that of cucumbers yet not exactly the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh gherkins almost never show up in stores or at farmers'
markets _if you want them, you have to grow them _ but they are as
easy to cultivate as any other cucumber. Easier, maybe, since the
vigorous vines seem to be somewhat less tasty to cucumber beetles
than those of C. sativus. Gherkins need lots of heat to flourish,
and don't be stingy with the water or you'll get bitter little
pills.
</P>
<P>
   Seeds, which can be planted any time from now to early July, are
available from the Baker Creek Heirloom Seed Co., 2278 Baker Creek
Rd., Mansfield, Mo. 65704; (417) 924-8917, and from Pinetree Garden
Seeds, Box 300, New Gloucester, Maine O4260; (207) 926-3400; both
catalogs are free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
To Avoid Double-Digging  &QL; 
Q. This fall, after the vegetable harvest, I will relocate two
3-foot-by-6-foot-by-10-inch raised beds (soil and all) to sites
that are currently covered by grass. Is there anything I can do to
the new sites to ease (or eliminate) turf removal, soil
double-digging and other preparation chores?  &QL; 
A. You can eliminate turf-removal by covering the area with
something thoroughly opaque: heavy black plastic or a solid
five-inch layer of paper (old telephone books and thick stacks of
newspaper work well). As long as no light gets through, the grass
will be dead by October. This is the easiest course of action, but
all you'll get out of it is dead grass, which probably won't become
useful compost until it has been under the bed for a while.
</P>
<P>
   If you're willing to work a bit, you can substantially improve
the soil and still avoid the heavy labor of double-digging. Start
by removing the sod, which is not a big chore if your spade is
sharp, then flip it over and replace it grass side down. Cover the
exposed roots and earth with a 3- or 4-inch layer of composted
manure, then a 12-to-14-inch-thick blanket of loose straw. Keep the
pile moist but not wet.
</P>
<P>
   By fall, everything except the top layer of straw should have
decomposed, enriching and loosening the earth underneath. When
moving day comes, just rake away whatever loose straw remains and
put the old bed on the new one. Then, with all that energy you've
conserved, mix the soil you've built with the soil you've moved to
bring it new vigor. Mystery Irritant  &QL; 
Q. Recently, while clearing overgrown honeysuckle and other
invasive vegetation, I pulled up 30 or 40 young thistles. Shortly
afterwards, I developed itchy, localized blebs on my hands and
face. Could the thistle juices on my leather gloves have caused an
allergic reaction? (In the past, I've dug up thistle plants and
handled them by the roots, bare-handed, without any problem.)  &QL; 
A. The highly invasive Canada thistle, Cirsium arvense, has a bad
reputation _ Wyman's Garden Encyclopedia describes it as a vicious
weed _ and you could probably raise a rash by rubbing your skin
with its prickly leaves. But neither this nor any other thistle
shows up on standard lists of common allergens, dermatologically
iniquitous plants or botanical toxins.
</P>
<P>
   It's still possible that you have an unusual allergy; almost
everything disagrees with somebody. But before you go off to the
doctor for the necessary testing, I suggest you consider the
possibility of plain old poison ivy. That evil vine often lurks
unsuspected in overgrown places. It's frequently seen (or, alas,
not seen) in conjunction with honeysuckle. And even the tiniest
seedlings contain enough urushiol _ one of the plant world's most
potent irritants _ to cause the symptoms you describe. Is Mulch
Good for Trees?  &QL; 
Q. My impression is that the heavy mulching of trees started as a
way to put some distance between tree trunks and aggressive lawn
trimmers, but that we've now been persuaded that lots of mulch has
an esthetic or even growth-nurturing purpose. Time and again when I
pull the mulch back I see bark softened by too much moisture and
damaged by beetles. Aren't all the mulch maniacs setting the stage
for widespread tree disease and death?  &QL; 
A. The problem is not with the mulch but with its over-cozy
relationship to the tree, which needs a bit of personal space to be
comfortable. Esthetic questions aside, almost all trees and shrubs
benefit from a moisture-conserving, weed-discouraging blanket over
their root zones, while none (except swamp dwellers) are happy when
moisture is conserved right up against the wood.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with the mulch-against-trunk-syndrome include damaging
fungus diseases, insect infestations and, especially in winter,
bark-eating mice and voles. All of these are easily avoided by the
provision of breathing space, and as long as they leave at least a
few inches of open ground between the mulch and the tree, the
maniacs are doing no harm.
</P>
<P>
   While we're on the subject, don't forget to be equally
respectful of your vegetables and flowers; soft-stemmed plants need
their space, too.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
