<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     06-09 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANING AND RESTORING WOOD DECKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After prolonged exposure to the elements, the color of the wood
in outdoor structures, like decks, lawn furniture and gazebos, will
turn from a warm brown to a dingy gray. Fortunately, a number of
products, called deck cleaners or deck revivers, can be used to
restore the natural color of wood.
</P>
<P>
   Besides making the wood look better, they are useful for
cleaning off mildew and mold and for removing stains. Mildew and
mold should be removed because they are unsightly and because they
make the wood surface slick and slippery. Once the deck is properly
cleaned, you can apply a sealer to protect the wood and keep it
looking good.
</P>
<P>
   Deck cleaners remove dirt and grime and also the surface layer
of dead cells in the wood. Their working action depends on the
chemical base in the formulation. Some cleaners contain only
detergents, but the majority are either carbonate- or oxalic
acid-based. Others have bleach (sodium hypochlorite) as a main
ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   Before buying any deck cleaner. read the label. Most cleaners
are formulated to work on wood types -- cedar, redwood and treated
pine -- commonly used for outdoor structures. Repeated use of
cleaners with a bleach base can eventually damage wood; so use a
bleach-based cleaner only if you have a wood surface that is
discolored with mold, mildew or berry stains. Use carbonate-based
cleaners to remove mildew and mold, and oxalic acid cleaners if the
wood is just discolored.
</P>
<P>
   The only tools you need are a cotton mop, paint roller or garden
sprayer; a long-handled scrub brush, and a garden hose. Deck
cleaners often contain caustic ingredients that can irritate the
skin, so be sure to wear rubber gloves, safety goggles, long pants
and a long-sleeved shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Most hardy plants will not be affected if they receive a splash
or two of the cleaner, but fragile plants like flowers could be
damaged. To protect them, first water around their roots, then
cover them with heavy plastic film. Also use the film to cover the
areas around the house where the deck is attached because some deck
cleaners can affect concrete and siding.
</P>
<P>
   Before cleaning the deck, examine the boards for damage. Loose
boards should be secured with galvanized nails or galvanized deck
screws. Look for splits, cracks and rotted sections. Deck cleaners
will not eliminate rot nor will they keep it from spreading. All
boards with large splits, cracks and rotted sections should be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Look carefully to see if the boards have been sealed or
varnished. In most cases, the cleaner will work through one or two
coats of wood sealer, but a heavy buildup of any finish could keep
the cleaner from working properly. You can remove thick layers of
finish with a commercial stripper formulated for decks (one brand
is called Powerlift).
</P>
<P>
   Some deck cleaners are available in liquid form and are ready
for spraying on the deck. Others are a powder that must be mixed
with water before they can be applied. Mix the powder with clean
water according to the manufacturer's directions.
</P>
<P>
   Apply the solution with a mop, paint roller or garden sprayer.
The wood surface should be cool. Do not apply deck cleaner to a
wood surface that has been exposed to the sun for any number of
hours. The hot surface could evaporate the liquid before it has had
a chance to work on the wood. Wait a few minutes to allow the
cleaner to work into the wood, then scrub the surface vigorously
with the brush to remove dirt and mildew. Rinse with clear water.
</P>
<P>
   The deck cleaner will restore the color to the boards, but
eventually even this renewed color will fade. Nothing can prevent
this weathering process, but it can be slowed down with
applications of stain and a clear finish. Unless a stain is
formulated with an ultraviolet screening agent, it will not do much
to protect the wood, but it can be used to hide any spots or
blotches and give the wood a uniform color. Whenever possible,
choose a stain and sealer that offers ultraviolet protection.
</P>
<P>
   Before applying any stain or sealer, allow four or five days for
the deck to completely dry out. Brush the stain on according to the
manufacturer's directions, allow time for it to dry, then apply the
sealer. It is best to apply only one coat of sealer, because thick
accumulations will attract and hold dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The deck will keep this renewed appearance for a long while. It
should be cleaned, however, whenever the wood shows signs of mildew
or graying. It is not necessary to apply a new coat of sealer every
time you use the deck cleaner. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
