<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can I permanently change the starting page of my Web
browser? A. The page you see first when you start up your Web
browser is usually called the default home page.
</P>
<P>
   When you get a new computer with preloaded software (or after
you have installed a new browsing program for the Web), the browser
will often take you automatically to the home page of the company
that makes it.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using Version 4.0 or later of Netscape Navigator or
Communicator, start the browser and go to Edit on the menu bar.
Select Preferences and click on the Navigator category in the box.
</P>
<P>
   You will see a list of options on the right side of the box;
where it says ``Navigator starts with,'' click the Home Page
button. In the box next to Location, type in the URL of the page
you'd like to always start with and click OK.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using Internet Explorer 4.0 or later on a personal
computer, go to your Start menu, then to Settings and click on the
Control Panel. Double-click on the Internet icon, and in the
Address box, type in the desired Web address.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using Explorer 4.5 for the Macintosh, first go to the
Edit menu, then select Preferences and click on Web Browser in the
box.
</P>
<P>
   Click on -Home/Search and type in the URL in the box under Home
Page.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to the
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com address. This column will answer questions of
general interest, but letters cannot be answered individually.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
