<HEADER>
A9029 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-POWERS-GAME-REVIE     06-09 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POWERS-GAME-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRIVIA FORMAT TO RIVAL CHANNEL SURFING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The opening screen is black, with a white triangle filled with
television snow. Over the hiss and squeak of lousy signal
reception, the voice of Austin Powers' arch nemesis is audible:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Evil here. I've taken over your computer. It's quite nice.
The wallpaper is lovely. I hope you don't mind if I make a few
long-distance phone calls.'' He titters. ``I have kidnapped Austin
Powers and am currently holding him prisoner in his own pathetic
hipster hangout, the Electric Psychedelic Pussycat Swinger's Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could easily kill him now, with poisoned gas, a pen or a
ripened avocado, and with Austin Powers out of the way, I could
take over the world. But just to make things more diabolical, we're
going to compete in a game show to decide the fate of the world.
Just for kicks _ like Twister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Win, Lose or (italics)Die.''(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   Thus begins Austin Powers Operation Trivia from Berkeley
Systems, maker of the best-selling You Don't Know Jack titles. The
game follows the popular format of the series _ fast-paced
multiple-choice questions about fads, fashions, movies, television
and gossip culled from the '60s, '70s and '80s, all presented
against a parody of 1960s graphic design (psychedelic colors,
Jefferson Airplane lettering, go-go girl silhouettes, op-art,
etc.).
</P>
<P>
   There is also a good deal of Austin Powers trivia, lest we
forget that this is a movie tie-in, timed to coincide with the
release of ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' (although,
with jumbo billboards of Austin Powers straddling a Virgin Atlantic
jet and ``Virgin Shaglantic'' commercials all over the radio, the
Austin Powers phenomenon is difficult to escape).
</P>
<P>
   Chalk it up to smart marketing, or something in the air or
something in the water, but we are in the middle of an Austin
Powers moment. Something about Mike Myers' foppish caricature of
swinging London has struck a chord, particularly in the new-media
community.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Alley, Powers' catch phrase, ``Yeah, baby!''
reverberates in an echo chamber of psychedelic stock valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a senior vice president of Macromedia, which makes
Shockwave and Flash animation software for the Web, presented a
preview of multimedia products dressed as a 1970s hipster, the
company said. He urged software developers to yell ``Groovy,
baby!'' at any features they liked and ``Shagadelic!'' at features
that really got them excited.
</P>
<P>
   Sound bites, baby! Groovy sound bites, yeah!
</P>
<P>
   Like all cult movies, ``Austin Powers'' is more fun to parrot
back than it is to watch. In Operation Trivia, or on the Web, all
you see and hear are the riffs _ visual and verbal.
</P>
<P>
   The digital experiences are extraordinarily shallow. But that's
the point _ the entertainment value of a cult movie is all on the
skin. Anything else is what you have to sit through to catch the
phrases you already know.
</P>
<P>
   On a minute-to-minute basis, Operation Trivia has a higher riff
quotient than the original ``Austin Powers'' movie. It's almost all
riffs. But in this case, superficiality is a plus. It accentuates
the supreme frivolity of the trivia and the blissfully undemanding
format of the questions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Trivial Pursuit, a game that forces you to dredge obscure
facts from the depths of your memory, Berkeley games, including
Operation Trivia, are based on simple recognition. Out of seven
choices, pick the four outfits that Powers wore in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting yes-or-no keys at a rapid-fire pace, distinguish
Australian bands from Irish bands. Pick films made by Joel Silver
vs. films made by James Cameron. Characters on ``Melrose Place''
vs. characters on ``90210.'' Students on ``Welcome Back Kotter''
vs. students on ``Head of the Class.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a trivia game that plays like a twitch game. It's quick
recognition _ firing at pop culture references. Got it, bing, got
it, bing, got it, bing. In a way, it's like watching ``Austin
Powers'' on screen (James Bond reference, bing, ``Avengers''
reference, bing, Andy Warhol, bing, Quadrophenia, got it, bing).
</P>
<P>
   Except that Operation Trivia is interactive. So it's actually
more like channel surfing, the channel-up, channel-down kind you do
with one thumb and no particular program in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom about arrow-button channel surfing is
that it's an aimless, mindless, vegetative activity. And it is
aimless. But it's not mindless. It's actually a form of solitaire.
It's a matching game that uses television channels in place of
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Every television channel has a slightly different visual
identity. It may be something obvious, like an MTV logo in the
corner. It may be the camera angles, or the colors, or the
typefaces, or the volume level. And then there is the programming,
which can also be recognized and categorized.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watches television has mental templates that
correspond to television channels, based on viewing experience, and
the second you spend on a given channel is the time it takes to
compare what you see on the screen with those templates and find a
match. When you find it, you change channels.
</P>
<P>
   It makes no more sense to linger on a program than it does to
linger on a playing card. Individual playing cards aren't
entertaining, and for the most part, neither are individual
television programs. But the game is mildly entertaining, if you've
got nothing better to do _ much like Operation Trivia.
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years, video games have produced something to rival the
experience of channel surfing. And the formula sells _ for better
or worse. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Austin Powers Operation Trivia, by Berkeley Systems; CD-ROM for
Mac 7.5.5 or later, and Windows 95 and 98; $39.95; for all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
