9, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT 202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGIA-KOSOVO-REACT. Augusta area lawmakers discuss the
possibility of peace in the Balkans and what it will take to keep
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic in check. By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA-GOP-CONVENTION. Two Hoosiers will play an organizing
role in the Republican Party's presidential nominating convention
that will be held next summer in Philadelphia. (250 words.) By C.J.
Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA-RAIL-FUNDS. The House Appropriations Committee on
Tuesday approved $4 million in federal funds for the South Shore
Rail Line in Northwest Indiana. (400 words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   IDAHO-GUNS. Rep. Mike Simpson talks about his stance on gun
control (400 words). Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   IDAHO-SNAKE-RIVER. Developments in the debate over the future of
the Snake River. (400 words.) By Tiffany Lynch
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-DEFENSE-SNOWE. The multibillion-dollar defense spending
bill the Senate approved Tuesday was, as usual, larded with
million-dollar projects for senators' home states. But not since
the end of the Cold War has Maine been on the receiving end of so
much Pentagon largesse. (600 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-WELFARE-BALDACCI -- Rep. John Baldacci, D-Maine, will
introduce a bill this week intended to make health insurance more
accessible to welfare recipients moving back into the workforce.
(400 words.) By Sara Kugler
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS-BOSTON-TRANSIT. The House Appropriations Committee
approved $54 million Tuesday for the South Boston Piers Transitway
to help pay for the construction of the underground bus tunnel
between South Station and the South Boston Piers. (500 words.) By
Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS-UNION-STATION (For Worcester). Working out the
funding details for next year's transportation projects, the House
Appropriations Committee Tuesday approved $2.5 million to help pay
for the rebuilding of Worcester Union Station. (600 words.) By Mark
D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-E-MAIL. Don't worry, says Rep. Steven C. LaTourette, the
Internet is not being taxed, nor is the Postal Service collecting
money for each e-mail sent. LaTourette, R-Madison Village, sent out
a statement Wednesday to dispel such rumors, which have caused
concern among his constituents. (200 words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-PHYSICS. As their friends hold graduation parties and work
summer jobs, two graduated seniors from Hawken School in Gates
Mills find themselves in a very different atmosphere -- doing more
school work. Devon Haskell and Kevin Wang spent hours a day
struggling with physics problems, working in labs, and doing
reports at the University of Maryland this week so they can win the
honor of representing the U.S. at an international physics
competition next month. (10-12 inches.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-GUN-MAYOR. Philadelphia Mayor Ed Rendell urged
Congress to pass a law requiring gun makers to switch to ``smart
guns'' that are inoperable by anyone but the legal owner. (500
words.) Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- NATURAL GAS SUPPLY ASSOCIATION. Four months after the
Natural Gas Supply Association ousted their president for suspected
embezzlement, they name R. Skip Horvath as their new head. Also,
updates on the civil case (400 words). Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-CENSUS-PRISON. Wisconsin holds the dubious distinction
of being the largest exporter of prisoners in the United States.
But while The Badger State is paying for the bulk of their
incarceration in other states, Wisconsin cannot claim the prisoners
in the census. With this in mind, Green Bay Republican Mark Green
testified before a House subcommittee on the census Wednesday about
his legislation that would require the census to consider such
prisoners from Wisconsin. Although this measure could probably not
keep Wisconsin from losing a congressional seat, it could mean more
federal dollars. (600 words) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-THOMPSON-EDUCATION. Singing his well-rehearsed song
promoting state sovereignty, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson
testified before a House committee Wednesday about the need to give
states control over education dollars. (400 words) By Matt Swenson
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-KOSOVO-REACT. Wisconsin lawmakers discuss the
prospects for peace in the Balkans. (400 words) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
