</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITY-EXAMS-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DISABILITY PROGRAM SOMETIMES RELIES ON QUICKIE MEDICAL EXAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 13)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNDSVILLE, W.Va. _ Years of work-related injuries, car
accidents, mental problems, a neurological disorder and a bout with
cancer drove Bradley Miller to seek Social Security Social
disability insurance in February 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Miller arrived at his medical examination hopeful the doctor
would validate his claim that aches, pains and shortness of breath
had disabled him. At his exam, he was asked to blow as hard as he
could into a tube, given an X-ray and then told he could go home.
</P>
<P>
   Although the examination had lasted 10 minutes, it yielded an
exhaustive six-page report describing details of Miller's feet,
ankles, hips, back, chest, abdomen _ his entire body. It described
listening to Miller's chest with a stethoscope, measurements of his
arms and legs, and making him stand on one leg at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Miller says no such examination had taken place. The report by
the examining doctor was signed by Dr. Bruce Guberman. But the
person who examined Miller was a woman. The agency responsible for
evaluating Miller's claim _ the West Virginia Department of
Rehabilitation Services (DRS) _ rejected his claim, citing the
report in ruling Miller was capable of holding a job.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's might be just another case of sour grapes by a rejected
seeker of government benefits. But Miller is just one of numerous
disability claimants in different parts of the nation who say they
were rejected after physicians performed superficial consultative
examinations, or CEs as they are known in Social Security jargon.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Newspapers have documented 76 similar cases in different
parts of the nation, including Texas and California. Lawyers who
represent some of these claimants say the actual number is a lot
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1954, the Social Security Administration has provided cash
benefits to workers whose disabilities may have prevented them from
finding and keeping jobs. In 1998, Social Security awarded $73
billion in benefits to nearly 11 million people under this program.
</P>
<P>
   Although the states manage the benefit program, the money comes
from the U.S. Social Security Administration, which also pays for
the CEs, which totaled 1.6 million last year. The state agencies
also decide whether to order CEs when medical evidence is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security officials say these CEs may be brief because
they are designed only to answer particular questions about a
claimant.
</P>
<P>
   But disability activists and others with experience in
disability law are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, the exams are so cursory as to be meaningless,
resulting in needless administrative waste,'' said Marty Ford,
co-chair of the Social Security Task Force of the non-profit
Consortium for Citizens with Disabilities, testifying last February
before the House Ways and Means human resources subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Harland, a 14-year veteran of the Social Security
Administration who now works as a paralegal in a Beaumont, Texas,
law firm that represents claimants appealing Social Security
disability denials, says physicians often ``do reports that are
five, six pages long, and they look like great reports, but they're
nothing more than computer printouts with a lot of canned language
in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Osterhout, a Pittsburgh lawyer who represents Miller and
four others in pursuit of a class-action lawsuit against the West
Virginia DRS, said that if doctors doing these examinations were
simply trying to fill in the blanks in a claimant's medical record,
they would not produce lengthy reports purporting to detail the
functions of all bodily systems.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and other similar claimants cannot be accused of sour
grapes if the medical examinations they received were too cursory
to prove or disprove their claims, Osterhout said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, all we get is another chance for our clients to
present their claims without reliance on doctors who don't really
examine their patients,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed by Miller and the others argue that the
brevity of these examinations violated the Social Security
regulations governing them.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security regulations say that doctors conducting such
tests must guarantee ``that sufficient time is made available to
obtain the information needed to make an accurate determination.''
A general medical examination should take at least 30 minutes; a
neurological exam 20 minutes; and a psychiatric or psychological
consultation should last between 40 minutes and an hour, the
regulations say.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say these regulations are undercut by the medical
economics of doing disability examinations.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security Administration reports spending about $180
on each CE. But that figure represents an average that includes
costly psychiatric and neurological exams. Doctors who perform
straight physical exams often receive $75 to $125 for each one.
</P>
<P>
   Many physicians, including the specialists whose skills often
are necessary to make difficult diagnoses, don't consider
consultative examinations worth their time.
</P>
<P>
   Into this vacuum have stepped so-called key providers,
essentially large medical practices that perform more than $100,000
worth of CEs annually. They do a high-volume trade, making money
through fast-turnover examinations of disability claimants.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Mizner, coordinating lawyer of the San Francisco-based Bay
Area Regional Benefits Access Collaborative, which receives federal
grant money to assist homeless people in obtaining federal
benefits, is critical of the mass-production aspects of medical
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a few of these doctors do a thorough job, but we
seldom see them last very long,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mizner speculated that ``a doctor who is any good will find
employment elsewhere and earn much more. That leaves only doctors
who can't find other work or don't care about doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Daniels, Social Security deputy commissioner for
disability and income security programs, defended the agency's
oversight of doctors who perform consultative examinations, saying:
``We know that not every CE is (of) the quality we would like it to
be. But we believe that we have a fairly solid system of dealing
with cases where we have inadequate information. We're comfortable
that we catch the quality problems, and that they're not
systemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, after being rejected, later filed a new disability
application and was examined by another physician, not a key
provider. The doctor tested his grip and reflexes, made him walk
and bend over, and checked his feet. This time, West Virginia
awarded him disability insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, Miller and the others are seeking an injunction
requiring the DRS to beef-up its monitoring of CEs, particularly
Dr. Guberman and his medical group, Tri-State Occupational Medicine
Inc. of Huntington, W.Va. Tri-State is not a named defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Osterhout estimated Tri-State performs 10,000 consultative
examinations a year, grossing $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Neither DRS director James Jeffers nor Jane Johnstone, head of
the division's disability determination section, would comment on
Tri-State. Jeffers confirmed that Tri-State is among the key
providers the division uses, but he declined to say how much
business the division gives the group, or whether officials are
satisfied with Tri-State's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Johnstone, the official with day-to-day responsibility for
approving and denying disability claims as well as selecting
doctors to perform consultative examinations, defended her unit's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the staff to develop these cases as if they're your own
family,'' she said. ``We do everything we can to help them prove
their case and (we deny benefits) only when the evidence is clear
they are undeserving.''
</P>
<P>
   Guberman declined an interview request. His lawyer, Philip
Melick, said in a statement: ``Neither Tri-State nor its associated
physicians is a party to the litigation involving the (West
Virginia DRS). It would be inappropriate at this time for Tri-State
or its associated physicians to comment on personal medical
information concerning any claimant.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
