<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAG-RESURGENCE-ART-N     06-09 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAG-RESURGENCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAG IS CHIC, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RICK MARIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing quite like a good shag.
</P>
<P>
   Its long, soft wool demands to be stroked, petted like the pelt
of some rare mountain sheep. The thing is almost obscenely sexy, a
vaguely naughty artifact from a more swinging age that makes you
want to exclaim, in a bad impersonation of Austin Powers, ``Oh,
behave!''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe that, until recently, this furriest of floor
coverings had been written off as the ultimate home-furnishing faux
pas. For most of this decade (and the last), not even the
aggressive sales force of ABC Carpet and Home could move shags. Now
it can hardly keep them in stock: huge white flokatis from Greece,
tulus crafted by Turkish nomads, groovy Scandinavian rya rugs from
the 1960s hanging on the walls like modern art.
</P>
<P>
   At downtown vintage emporiums like Las Venus, on Ludlow Street,
shags are all around vinyl sofas and elliptical floor lamps. A
recent New York magazine cover envisioned a dissolutely glam couple
lounging by a white shag on New Year's Eve 1999. Oh, and let's not
forget a certain sequel opening tomorrow: ``Austin Powers: The Spy
Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of this sequel, and the original ``Austin Powers,''
released two years ago, wistfully celebrates an era, the late '60s,
when everything, even carpeting, seemed to be about sex. In a
publicity still for ``Barbarella'' (1968), Jane Fonda strikes a
space-age sex-kitten pose against a backdrop of gold shag. As a
promotion for the new ``Austin Powers,'' Virgin Atlantic Airways
has decorated a jet in shag.
</P>
<P>
   Guests entering the lobby of the new Standard hotel in Los
Angeles will notice that one section is wall-to-wall shag.
Literally. The plush white carpeting smothers the floor, climbs up
the walls and across the ceiling. An employee had to be specially
trained just to rake it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to achieve sort of the relaxed feeling you would
have in an old-fashioned conversation pit,'' said Andre Balazs, an
owner of the hotel and its principal designer. ``There's a tactile
thing going on, but there's a quality of envelopment and quiet, a
complete deadening of sound.'' It's a womb room for baby hipsters
old enough to have crawled on shags as rug rats and still young
enough to want to play on them.
</P>
<P>
   The shag rug has become a necessary accessory. Retro fetishism
has rescued it from the paneled rec room of kitsch and placed it
prominently in the sunken living room of cool, contemporary decor.
The British designer Liza Bruce deployed one in her Los Angeles
home, a former convent. As Harper's Bazaar described Ms. Bruce's
domestic scene in its June issue: ``The downstairs ballroom, which
once served as the nuns' chapel, is now empty, save for the small
white shag rug, leather Eames chair and booming stereo all in one
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   That this symbol of tacky suburban interiors should have become
chic again shocks people who lived through the first time around.
To them, even the word shag is a fingernail on the blackboard. Mark
Saley, a marketing manager at ABC Carpet, prefers not to use the
word.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not calling them shags anymore, of course,'' he said.
They're flokatis, classic shags made in Greece, or tulus, smaller
rugs with simple graphic designs traditionally made by Turkish
nomads. After a stylist for Wallpaper magazine used a shag _ sorry,
flokati _ in a spread last year, ``they blew out of here,'' Saley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on size and quality, measured by the denseness of the
pile, the price of a new flokati at ABC or Einstein Moomjy can run
from $400 for one 4 by 6 feet to $2,500 for a 9-by-12. ABC's tulus,
new and vintage, go for about $1,000. The blindingly colored old
rya rugs in the Danish modern section of ABC's home furnishings
building are not for sale.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no shortage of shag around town, if you don't care
where they've been. Alan Sanchez bought a used rya rug three months
ago at R, a vintage modern-furniture store three blocks from his
apartment in Brooklyn. It's orange and black and white, with what
Sanchez described as a ``snail or seashell pattern.'' He got it for
$100.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like we were shag hunting,'' said Sanchez, a partner
in a metal fabricating company. Far from it. Sanchez, 39, grew up
in a heavily shagged house. ``Where one ended, another one began,''
he recalled. ``From the heavy shag to that cropped shag.''
</P>
<P>
   Shags had left a bad taste on his esthetic palate. ``But in
retrospect,'' he said, ``I kind of like the idea.'' Now he wants
another one.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez has re-enacted the shag's life cycle since its
introduction in this country a generation ago: exposure, rejection
and new acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Nordic invasion of mid-century American design, shag
has worked its way down the decor food chain from showroom to
suburban basement _ and back up again. It's a classic example of
how an idea can go from tacky (Graceland's abundant shag is all
lovingly preserved) to art (Rudolf Stingel made a career out of
covering galleries in electric-colored shag carpeting).
</P>
<P>
   But the shag's lineage goes back much further than David
Cassidy's haircut. Some scholars believe William the Conqueror wore
a protoshag when he led the Normans in the Battle of Hastings in
1066, said Jenny Wolfson, a dealer in 20th-century Scandinavian
design. In those days, she said, ``it was considered a mark of
power and prosperity to wear cloth, rather than fur.''
</P>
<P>
   Wealthier peasants used ryas _ note the similarity to the
English word ``rug'' _ rather than animal skins for bedding. This
decorative bedding mutated into floor covering during the 19th
century and, faster than you can say Ikea, into a mass-produced
must-have for anyone with a Dansk fondue set.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of fondue, the shag does have one undeniable downside.
Keeping one clean can be, to put it mildly, a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard had just opened this year when Balazs agreed to
rent out the lobby for an Oscar party. The Standard's
floor-to-ceiling pile was still virgin white. ``It's a very
expensive carpet,'' he said _ about $45,000, imported from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   As the date of the party drew nearer, he couldn't stop worrying
about stains. Then Karen Finley, the performance artist, suggested
he hire a ``carpet slave'' for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this guy on his hands and knees obsessing and picking
lint up from the carpet with tweezers,'' Balazs said. The young man
was led around the room on a leash held by a tall, striking blond
woman in a long evening gown.
</P>
<P>
   Very shagadelic.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1609EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
