<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9048 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRIS-MYSTERYMAN-960     06-09 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRIS-MYSTERYMAN-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN BEHIND HANNIBAL'S MASK ALMOST AS BIG A RIDDLE AS HIS KILLER
CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by HARRIS-REMINISCENCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
and JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some ways, author Thomas Harris is as much a mystery as his
terrifying creation, Hannibal Lecter, who resurfaced this week in
bookstores across America.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years after his last appearance, in ``The Silence of the
Lambs,'' the serial killer with the abominable appetite is back as
the title character of Harris' new thriller, ``Hannibal.''
</P>
<P>
   To that extent, Hannibal is even less elusive than Harris.
</P>
<P>
   No one's seen much of the Mississippi-born author, who is 58,
since publication of his first book, ``Black Sunday,'' in 1975.
Even old college pals at Baylor University haven't heard from him
since around the time of his second novel, ``Red Dragon,'' in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Harris first introduced his flesh-eating,
brilliantly bizarre villain. Now, after the success of ``Lambs,''
he's got one of the hottest novels ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will sell millions,'' predicts Kenneth Kirkland, an
independent book-industry analyst based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of thousands of people who never even read `Red
Dragon' or `The Silence of the Lambs' will buy the book because
they loved the `Lambs' movie with Anthony Hopkins as Hannibal
Lecter.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirkland calls it a monstrous slam-dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``No book will sell more copies in 1999, guaranteed, all because
of the character of Hannibal Lecter, who in a warped way has become
a real hero to Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   For its first printing, Delacorte Publishing has ordered a
million copies of ``Hannibal.'' Sales of 65,000 normally propel a
novel to the bestseller lists.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will be pleased to learn that Harris has an ``official''
Web site. They will be less pleased to know that all the
information it contains could fit on the back of a baseball card.
</P>
<P>
   The ``About the Author'' section reads simply:
</P>
<P>
   ``A native of Mississippi, Thomas Harris began his writing
career covering crime in the United States and Mexico, and was a
reporter and editor for The Associated Press in New York City ...
''
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention of his Baylor days in the early '60s and his
job at the Waco newspaper, where he covered the police beat and
general assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site provides the titles and publishing dates of his
four novels and includes a small photograph of Harris. Apparently,
he's a chubby, bearded chap with an engaging smile.
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte publicists say they cannot schedule interviews with
Harris or offer additional biographical information.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, several complain, he's a publicist's worst nightmare
_ a writer whom every TV network, newspaper and radio station wants
to interview, but who flatly refuses.
</P>
<P>
   Even stranger, he rarely communicates with his old buddies at
the AP in New York or his college and newspaper cronies in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with him from time to time until his second novel was
published,'' says David McHam of UTA, who was one of Harris'
journalism professors at Baylor in the early 1960s and who also
worked with him at the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember after he sold the film rights for `Black Sunday,'
he told me he wasn't going to talk to anybody anymore. He moved. I
moved. When I started trying to get back in touch, he was
unfindable. I hadn't realized when he said `anybody' that he really
meant `everybody.'''
</P>
<P>
   What's also unusual is that nobody seems to hold this reticence
against him, with the possible exception of his publicist. Long-ago
friends and colleagues still speak of him warmly and with genuine
affection.
</P>
<P>
   Universally, they describe him as a truly nice guy, intelligent,
a voracious reader, a hard worker, a bit of a dreamer, a dedicated
drinker and a softspoken gentleman in every sense of the word.
</P>
<P>
   Also, they say, he was drawn early on, if not to serial killers,
to bizarre murder cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just fascinated by them,'' says Charlie Reynolds, a
journalism professor at Tarleton State University who taught at
Baylor and who worked with Harris in the mid-1960s at the Waco
News-Tribune and Dallas Times-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   ``He collected everything on them, followed them, wrote about
them and studied all about them,'' Reynolds says. ``And it made him
millions.''
</P>
<P>
   In those carefree days, Harris enjoyed socializing after hours
with his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us would meet at a bar after we'd put the paper to
bed,'' Reynolds says. ``He wasn't hard to get along with, but he
was not a talkative member of the writing group. He'd sit around
listening to what other people were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Fort Worth Star-Telegram editor Mike Blackman, who
worked with Reynolds and Harris, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
