<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LANDMINES (Washington) _ When NATO troops enter the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo to enforce a peace treaty, one of the
deadliest threats they will encounter _ and a major obstacle to the
returning refugees _ are thousands of land mines planted by Serbian
troops. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ President Clinton accuses
House Republicans of formulating a weak gun-control bill ``ghost
written'' by the National Rifle Association. Democrats meet to plot
their strategy as the House marches toward considering gun-control
measures. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   HORMEL-CONTROVERSY (Washington) _ James C. Hormel will be sworn
in as ambassador to Luxembourg by a senior Clinton administration
official as soon as logistics are worked out, a State Department
official says. Preparations come as Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., vows not to allow Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., to
indefinitely block Senate action on White House nominations to
protest the recess appointment of Hormel. By STEWART M. POWELL and
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL (Washington) _ A key Senate subcommittee approves
$83 million to hire 1,000 new Border Patrol agents and implores the
Clinton administration to move swiftly to hire more recruits to
guard the borders. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-JUMP (College Station, Texas) _ Former President George
Bush takes his third parachute jump _ the first was during World
War II _ and lands safely at Texas A&AMP;M University, just three days
before his 75th birthday. By PATTY REINERT. (Photo to be available
on the NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HKN-STARS (Dallas) _ Dallas is baking in unusually warm weather,
but it isn't the heat that's giving the town ice fantasies. The
Stanley Cup is drawing thousands to the Dallas Museum of Modern Art
and the NHL finals are drawing tens of thousands to Reunion Arena.
Hockey, long thought to be an orphan sport in the land of Cowboys,
is cool, after all. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS (Indianapolis) _ Complete coverage of Game 5 of the
NBA Eastern Conference Finals between the New York Knicks and
Indiana Pacers. By MICHAEL MURPHY. (Game time is 9 p.m. Eastern.)
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITY-EXAMS (Moundsville, W.Va.) _ Bradley Miller lost his
bid for Social Security disability insurance after what he
describes as a 10-minute quickie medical examination that yielded a
detailed six-page doctor's report concluding he was fit to work.
Miller's case and dozens of others like it nationwide illustrate
what lawyers and advocates describe as a tendency of states and
Washington to rely on mass-production medical practices that do an
inadequate job of determining whether claimants are actually
disabled. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Let it be recorded that Bill
Clinton is a human Phoenix, rising repeatedly with renewed life
from the ashes of doom and destruction, like the colorful bird of
Egyptian religious legend. The latest example of his ability to
ride to triumph when disaster was predicted is the tenuous peace
agreement in Yugoslavia. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Already filed.)
</P>
