<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SPYPLANE-0610-     06-09 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SPYPLANE-0610-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI-MADE DRONE SPY PLANE SEIZED AS IT GATHERS 'NEWS' IN
KOSOVO
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0610.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIRKOVCI, Macedonia _ In another mysterious Balkans twist,
Macedonia was struggling to decide Wednesday what to do with a
high-tech Israeli-made spy plane that Macedonian police seized on a
mountaintop near the Kosovo border from Israeli technicians
claiming to be on a free-lance journalistic mission.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday local authorities detained seven Israeli citizens who
said they had been using the state-of-the-art drone observation
plane to film inside Kosovo for international television networks.
The Interior Ministry said none of them had press credentials.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, after furious cellular phone calls to the capital
Skopje, local police here took two of the Israelis into custody and
allowed the international press to photograph the plane, which
looked like a jumbo toy airplane with a wingspan measuring nearly
14 feet.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, after pressure from the Israeli Foreign Ministry,
authorities here accepted the Israelis' assertion that they were
merely zealous capitalists and released them all without criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if they'll get their equipment back,'' said Stevo
Pendarovski of the Ministry of Internal Affairs. ``I don't know
about other charges from customs or eventually from our civil
aviation service.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, a placid country which has been thrust against its
will into the center of a violent world crisis, was clearly
befuddled to find seven Israelis driving down a mountainside late
Monday with two truckloads of aerial surveillance gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this was for commercial purposes, or maybe it was for
military purposes, I don't know,'' said Valentin Jovanovinski, a
Macedonian civil aviation flight inspector who was called here to
examine the Israeli gear.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, the Macedonians trapped the Israelis at a roadblock
here at the village of Mirkovci, about 10 miles north of the
capital Skopje. The roadblock was erected after Macedonian police
received a tip from Norwegian military officers about the drone
taking off. The Norwegians were stationed in the mountains near the
Kosovo border as part of a NATO observer detachment.
</P>
<P>
   In its maiden flight here Monday afternoon, the Israeli drone
had also caused alarm in a NATO-run aircraft control tower at
Macedonia's main civilian airport when it flew -- without any
flight plan -- into the airspace of an airport partly occupied by
NATO forces. NATO and Macedonian flight controllers are monitoring
the nearby air space for possible Yugoslav air raids or terrorist
attacks from the air.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Israeli journalist Yigan Goren, a former diplomatic
correspondent for Israeli television, said in an interview it had
been his idea to assemble a team of Israelis to capture exclusive
aerial footage of the situation inside Kosovo and then sell it to
TV networks around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it becomes a big story between NATO, Israel and
Macedonia,'' said Goren. ``Why? As I understand the situation, the
Macedonian Government has a lump in their stomach against NATO.
They fear they are losing control of the country here. And NATO is
running the country. So they trying to apply force on my back.''
</P>
<P>
   Goren claimed that he got unofficial blessing for his
newsgathering plan from unnamed people at NATO headquarters in
Brussels and from a high-ranking Macedonian diplomat in London.
``It was not in writing, but we got an insurance, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian Interior Minister Pavle Trajanov told a Tuesday news
conference that police have confiscated the drone plane while the
government figures out what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were using non-piloted aircraft to observe the border
area,'' Trajanov told a news conference. ``They said they were
journalists, but they didn't have any journalistic accreditation.
Their film is being checked by NATO to see if it contained any
information about NATO troop movements.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The plane and its ground equipment is thought to be worth well
over $100,000. The Interior Ministry's Pendarovski said the drone's
seven-member ground crew included a retired major in the Israeli
Army who had specialized in drone surveillance operations.
</P>
<P>
   Following Trajanov's press conference, correspondents asked for
permission to see and photograph the drone plane. After several
hours of hesitation, the Macedonian authorities allowed journalists
to go into the garage of the Mirkovci police station.
</P>
<P>
   There on display was what looked like an oversized white toy
airplane, with a pencil-thin fuselage that was packed with cameras
and control gear. Mounted behind the wings was a gasoline motor
powering a rear-facing propeller.
</P>
<P>
   The drone contained no national insignias. But on the fuselage
and the ground control boxes were inscribed the name B.T.A.
Macedonian officials said the Israelis told them that B.T.A. is the
Israeli company that manufactured the drone.
</P>
<P>
   Goren, the Israeli entrepreneur who organized the filming, was
not among the seven Israelis detained by the Macedonians. He said
he had left the mountain launch area earlier in the day, in the
company of a Norwegian officer of NATO, to assure the dubious
Norwegian that he was not filming inside of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Goren said the Norwegian officer initially seized a video-tape
of material filmed by the drone inside Kosovo. Later on Monday,
according to Goren, he got the video back from a more senior NATO
official who had viewed it and found the contents to be
non-sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Goren flatly denied that the news-gathering company he formed
about two weeks ago, Sky Video International, was a cover for some
government intelligence-gathering operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's purely civilian,'' he said. ``It's my company. I decided
to take with me the people of a company called B.T.A. It is a very
small company, but they are the best in the world in using small
drones.''
</P>
<P>
   Goren said the B.T.A. drones contain ``a very sophisticated
camera in the bottom that you can zoom, pan it left and right, and
everything.'' He said the drones can operate at ranges of up to 36
miles and can remain in the air, transmitting images to a ground
crew, for up to six hours of nonstop flying.
</P>
<P>
   Goren said that his team's drone managed only one flight into
Kosovo before it was confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
