<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS (Kumanovo, Macedonia) _ Gen. Michael
Jackson, NATO peacekeeping commander, announces agreement with
Yugoslavs that he says allows for bombing pause. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO slowed but did not stop the
bombing of Yugoslavia Wednesday, allied officers said, insisting
that there would be no formal halt until Yugoslav commanders began
pulling Serb forces out of Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY (Cologne, Germany) _ Analysis or story on the
deal. Possibly: The one sentence that was blocking the deal, and
G-7 foreign ministers' decision to delete it. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Lapusnik, Yugoslavia) _ Todor is a soldier, a
factory worker from northern Serbia who volunteered to come here to
Kosovo and defend it for his country. He knows his war is about to
end. But he wondered Wednesday whether the outcome is worth the
price, both to his own comrades and to the ethnic Albanians of this
southern Serbian province. ``I'm angry about how it's ending,'' he
said, rubbing his hand along his dirty blonde beard. ``This should
have been done better. A lot of people have died for nothing. And I
believe that in four or five years, no Serb will still be living in
Kosovo.'' By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPY-CASE (Washington) _ Developments in the case of the
nuclear weapons scientist suspected as a spy for China. By David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-COMEDIAN-SLAIN (Mexico City) _ In his 30-year television
career, the round-faced comedian popularly known as Paco Stanley
charmed millions of Mexicans with his jovial but sharp-edged way of
clowning and mocking, of putting them down and exhorting them to be
good. So when Stanley fell victim at high noon on Monday to a
coolly professional gunfire execution, the jolt of disbelief spread
nationwide. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-TREATMENT (Phoeniz, Ariz.) _ A dozen years after the
national alarm over crack speeded the discarding of drug treatment
in favor of punitive laws that helped create the world's largest
prison system, drug policy is taking another turn. Treatment is
making a comeback, driven largely by a grass-roots revolt. By
Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-JUVENILES (Washington) _ President Clinton on Wednesday
denounced House Republicans' gun-control proposals as measures that
were ``plainly ghostwritten'' by the National Rifle Association,
which he and House Democratic leaders said had succeeded in
weakening the gun-control language in legislation passed by the
Senate last month. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FUND-RAISING (Washington) _ While fund raising is a feast
for George W. Bush, the Texas governor's huge financial success has
left the other GOP presidential contenders (except self-financed
billionaire Steve Forbes) fighting or table scraps. By Don Van
Natta.
</P>
</TEXT>
