<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9078 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMART-MICROWAVE-ART-N     06-09 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-MICROWAVE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMART' MICROWAVES THAT READ THE INSTRUCTIONS ON THE PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kit Keith Yam, a food-science professor at Rutgers University,
is not impressed with today's microwave ovens. They do an
acceptable job of warming a cup of coffee, he said, but they fail
miserably at cooking food that requires different heating levels
for different time periods. And it is a rare day when they can pop
popcorn without leaving a layer of stubborn kernels at the bottom
of the bag.
</P>
<P>
   What microwaves need, he believes, is intelligence. They should
be smart enough to detect exactly what foods they are about to zap,
taking into account the foods' freshness, temperature, and
packaging. They should be able to consult information about which
cooking times and heating levels work best for those foods, and
then cook them as instructed.
</P>
<P>
   An intelligent oven should know its users too, Yam said _
recognizing voices and remembering, for example, that certain
members of the household are allergic to peanuts. The oven should
tap into the Internet as well _ providing information about a
meal's nutritional content or warnings about foods that have been
spoiled or even recalled. In fact, while they're at it, he added,
the machines might as well display the day's weather forecast and
the status of rush-hour traffic. And you just wanted warm coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Yam and a team of researchers at Rutgers are now devoting their
time to developing such an appliance. They have succeeded so far in
building a microwave oven that can read the bar code on a bag of
popcorn and glean the popcorn's proper cooking time by referring to
a data base of information collected by food scientists. Other
packaged foods _ lasagna and fish fillets, for example _ have been
tested too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put together a knowledge base of food science and the tools
of information technology,'' Yam said. The team includes a Rutgers
professor, Paul Lachance, and a staff member, Raymond Saba, as well
as researchers for Samsung, the electronics company, and Symbol
Technologies, a bar-code scanning company.
</P>
<P>
   Yam demonstrated a prototype earlier this year. It was a regular
microwave oven hooked up to a bar-code scanner and a personal
computer. To pop a bag of popcorn, Yam held the bag over the
scanner, which picked up the product's identification number and
relayed that information to the computer. The computer used that
number to search a Rutgers data base for appropriate cooking time
and heating levels _ instructions that were sent to the oven. The
result, he said, was popcorn with a better texture, better taste,
and fewer unpopped kernels. (Unfortunately for popcorn lovers, Yam
promised participating popcorn companies that he would not publicly
reveal specific results of that particular study.)
</P>
<P>
   The Rutgers team is now putting the finishing touches on a
second prototype that will have a computer chip and scanner built
in, so that the appliance looks like a regular microwave oven. The
prototype, which will have to connect to the Internet as well as to
an electrical outlet, will use voice-recognition software and more
advanced bar-code information. To make the intelligent oven work,
however, the Rutgers group will have to get food companies to
increase testing on their products to determine optimal cooking
times in specific models of microwaves. And they will either have
to add more advanced bar codes to their packages to give the
microwave ovens information about nutritional content, or they will
need to submit that data to a large data base that could be
available through the Internet. Celentano, a company that
specializes in frozen foods, has agreed to help with the next
prototype.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Yam will continue to cook his favorite frozen
meal _ stuffed shells _ with a regular microwave, suffering through
the frozen middles and burned edges just like the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
