<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9080 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-09 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS FLASH: PEOPLE CAN BE HUMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - When his car broke down on Scottsdale Road
in the middle of the day with the temperature over 100 degrees, Lou
Furman didn't panic.
</P>
<P>
   A traveling man learns to take care of himself, and for decades
Lou was on the road selling ladies' clothing between Arizona, New
Mexico, Wyoming, Colorado, Utah and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to high fashion and highways, the key to success
is staying calm.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his mid-80s, Lou doesn't stray far from home. But on this
day, his wife, Adele, was attending a function at a local resort,
so Lou gave her a ride. Not long after he dropped her off, the
electrical system in the car short-circuited and the whole thing
went dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it goes, sometimes,'' he says. ``I pulled off
the road as far as I could and waited for a tow truck.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd just gotten out of the car when he heard a woman's voice.
She'd pulled up behind him and was hurrying over, saying, ``Are you
having a heart attack?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Lou said. ``My car did.''
</P>
<P>
   Then another car, with another woman behind the wheel, showed
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not having a heart attack,'' the first woman said to the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I got such attention from the ladies
simply by standing on the sidewalk,'' Lou says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRUCKLOADS OF HELP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the women left, a truck pulled over. A husky construction
worker hopped out and asked Lou if there was anything he could do.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did Lou thank the man for his trouble, and see him
off, when another truck stopped, this one filled with men employed
by a local lawn service.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to help me, somehow, though I don't know how
because they all spoke Spanish and I don't,'' Lou says. ``All we
could do was point and nod at each other, but I got them to
understand I was OK, and to say thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a police officer arrived.
</P>
<P>
   He was from Scottsdale, although technically Lou's car had
broken down in the adjoining town of Paradise Valley. Lou told the
officer he was fine. After the Scottsdale officer left, another
arrived from Paradise Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after he left, a sergeant from the Paradise Valley force
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   When he was gone, a young woman pulled over and offered Lou a
cold bottle of water, which he accepted with gratitude. Then,
another young woman stopped by, telling Lou, ``Don't worry, help is
on the way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered, `What help?' '' Lou says. ``I was waiting for a
tow truck. Then, I hear the siren.''
</P>
<P>
   In the distance, cruising up Scottsdale Road toward him, Lou
spotted a firetruck and an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HAPPY MAN, GOOD NEWS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In one half-hour, I watched the people of this Valley, who act
like strangers to each other, turn into real people,'' Lou says.
``Later, I told Adele the whole experience made me feel like I
could die a happy man.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife is nearby listening, as she has for 57 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, the only news we get on TV and read on the front
page of the newspaper is really bad news,'' she says. ``We're old
enough to know that these are not good times, to remember when
people were kinder to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my days as a traveling man, I developed into a loner,'' Lou
says. ``But I also learned to say, `Can I help you?' That's my
religion. I don't classify myself by any denomination. I stick out
my hand and say, `Can I help you?' This time, I got it in return.''
</P>
<P>
   He hadn't expected it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's all the bad news in the papers and on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Lou says, ``I'd just like it if, maybe, you
could find an inch of space in the paper where the man with the
gray beard stranded at Scottsdale Road and Vista could thank all
the lovely people who stopped to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the kind of thing that makes the front page. Lou and
Adele are right about that. There's no way a small good deed is
going to make headlines or get a person's face on TV news.
Everybody knows that. Everybody.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, all those people stopped. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
