<HEADER>
A9089 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-STEINWAY-TECHNOLO     06-09 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-STEINWAY-TECHNOLOGY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER TECHNOLOGY COMES INTO PLAY IN MAKING FINE PIANOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Outside the windows of the Steinway &AMP; Sons piano
factory in Queens, ventilators blow petals of wood shavings into
the air, creating what looks like a light snowfall all year round.
Down a hallway of administrative offices, several doors feature
bumper stickers crowing ``I Love Wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinway is a company devoutly committed to the craft of
woodworking. Many of its 600 employees arrived at the factory as
teen-agers, and in the course of their tenures there _ some decades
long _ have become masters at molding, chiseling, shaping and
bending some of a Steinway grand piano's 12,000 parts.
</P>
<P>
   Steinway calls each piano it builds ``a handmade work of art,''
and the number of instruments it produces each year (2,500 grands
and 500 uprights) remains more or less unchanged from 100 years
ago. In fact, much of the sprawling, 440,000-square-foot factory
looks as it might have 100 years ago. During a recent midmorning
break, a worker napped, sprawled across a cast-iron veneer-cutting
machine whose curlicued latticework reveals its industrial-age
origins, though it is still used today. The sun streamed down
through skylights onto hardwood floors that would be wildly out of
place in many a highly trafficked, modern factory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet little by little, technology has been wending its way onto
the factory floor, helping the wood crafters do their jobs _ not
necessarily faster, but certainly more efficiently and with greater
precision. Although most parts are still assembled by hand,
computer-run climate control rooms, chip-driven multipurpose
machines and three-dimensional measuring arms are also entering the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not at the point where we're pulling switches and
watching parts come out the other end,'' said Steinway president
and chief executive Bruce Stevens. ``It still takes us a year to
craft one of these things. But technology is assisting us in making
more precise parts that our people can assemble. It's helping us
create a better instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate consumers _ the players and the listeners _ may
notice these innovations in small ways; whether the changes have
made a difference in how Steinway pianos sound and feel to the
touch is debatable. Although many artists and technicians say that
Steinway pianos are built more solidly and reliably now than in
years past, some say that increased reliability has led to a slight
drop in the number of quirks that make each piano unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're getting better,'' said pianist Emanuel Ax, who
has been playing almost exclusively on Steinway concert grands for
more than 25 years. ``The best Steinways have always been pretty
fabulous, but for a time there you were finding one good one in a
number of not so good ones. Now there's a lot less variability
between pianos. There are still differences in sound quality _ some
are brighter, some are not as bright _ but they're all a notch
better than they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who described his job as ``a love affair with culture,
history and tradition,'' said the company was achieving a balance
between handicraft and technology-driven processes. ``But we're
careful not to sacrifice the quality of our instrument for the
expediency of modern technology,'' added Stevens, who, like many of
the company's executives, has a Steinway grand piano in his living
room, which he tinkers with but does not play.
</P>
<P>
   A Steinway grand piano is 85 percent wood. And like other
companies heavily involved in woodwork, Steinway treats the
different species of wood that go into its pianos with painstaking
care. Each temperamental piece, for instance, requires long periods
of time to dry in warm, dark rooms, or it will become too
``stressed'' to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is hard rock maple (used to build the inner and outer
rims of a grand piano), Alaskan sitka spruce (used for the
soundboards) or East Indian rosewood (used for exterior veneers),
all of Steinway's raw lumber is dried to a moisture level of 6
percent to make it suitable for building. A 6 percent moisture
level insures that the final product, whether it resides in a
living room in Florida or a concert hall in New York, won't warp,
blister or splinter because of stresses in the wood. Because
Steinway is focused to the point of obsession on the moisture
levels of its wood, for the last several years the company been
developing new ways to tightly control the drying process with
computers.
</P>
<P>
   When a load of 30,000 board feet of hard rock maple arrives from
a Vermont sawmill, for example, it is air-dried under sheets of
clear plastic in a lumberyard next to the employee parking lot for
several months, in a process little changed by technology. The wood
then goes inside a large kiln, where it is spread out, and a
combination of steam, temperature and ventilation systems continues
the slow drying process.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, computer-driven machinery enters the picture. The
drying kiln is controlled by a programmable logic controller, or
PLC, located in a room adjacent to the kiln. The controller makes
automatic adjustments to the temperature and humidity in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Once the maple reaches the magical 6 percent moisture level, it
is cut into laminates measuring 6 inches wide, 3 16 -inch deep and
8 to 10 feet long, depending on the size of the grand piano.
(Steinway makes five sizes of grand piano, with the smallest, the
Model S baby grand, measuring 5 feet 2 inches in length, and the
largest, the Model D concert grand, measuring almost 9 feet.)
</P>
<P>
   The laminates are then taken to the rim processing department on
the second floor. This department creates the grand piano's frame,
or rim, with its characteristic left-hand straight edge giving way
to an elegant curve down the right.
</P>
<P>
   Steinway takes special care with its rims, which encircle the
action, hammers, strings, soundboard, tuning pins and other
interior parts of the piano. The entire circumference of a rim is
made of stacks of two or three long pieces of high-grade maple
laminate, carefully joined at the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Steinway presses about 11 rims each day. During the process,
which takes about 20 minutes, department foreman Raphael D'Alleva
(a 38-year Steinway employee who is known for only three cracked
rims in his career) and six other men stand in a line as the
laminates emerge one on top of another from a glue applicator on a
conveyor belt. When the 18th layer is aligned, the ``book'' of
glued laminates looks like a giant wafer candy bar with caramel
seeping between the layers. The six men then hoist the finished
book over their shoulders and carry it over to the piano-shaped rim
press, where they align it and bang it into the clamps with big red
hammers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Once the glue sets, the rim is taken to one of the factory's 13
conditioning rooms for a minimum of eight weeks. Programmable logic
controllers in each room contain input and output sensors that
adjust the temperature and humidity levels every five minutes. All
the controllers are connected to a 75-megahertz Pentium PC in a
glass-enclosed office about 50 yards away. By looking at the
computer screen, a supervisor can control even the slightest
variations in temperature and humidity. If the system goes down
(which it occasionally does), the supervisor must go to each room,
check its wet- and dry-bulb thermometers and make adjustments
manually.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of eight weeks, the rim is able to withstand up to
45,000 pounds of tension from the strings that will be put inside
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take drying very seriously,'' said Robert Berger, director
of quality for Steinway. ``Monitoring the conditioning rooms from a
central computer allows us to make micro adjustments constantly. It
helps us avoid going into one of the rooms and saying, `Oh, wow,
this room's been going out of control for a couple of hours now,'
which used to happen on occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   In other areas of the factory, ``machining centers'' _ machines,
driven by programmable logic controllers, that contain
microprocessors and can be ordered to perform several different
repetitive jobs _ are replacing manually operated machines that
perform one function at a time. That is the case particularly in
the action department, the part of the factory that makes wooden
shapes that measure no more than a few inches and look as though
they belong in Santa's toy sack. Of the 85 different machines used
to build the piano's action, about 10 of them are run by
programmable logic controllers, said Chris Arena, a supervisor in
the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the older machines, you're relying on an operator with 30
years' experience to reset switches if you want to reprogram it,''
he said. ``Even then, there's a danger that if something's running
incorrectly, he won't be able to stop it in enough time to avoid
damage to the machine. With the PLC machines, we can make
adjustments in a snap by programming changes.'' As a result, Arena
said, the tolerances in the parts have decreased, and fewer parts
are being thrown away.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-operated measuring devices used in the quality
department are making it significantly easier to measure
hard-to-reach locations and unwieldy curves like the treble arc, a
sinuous curve that runs down the right-hand side of a grand piano.
Jimmy Argenziano, an engineer who has worked in Steinway's quality
department for four years, uses a portable coordinate measurement
machine to inspect the cast-iron plates to which the strings are
attached before they are put into the rims and wound with string. A
sort of three-dimensional mouse that hooks up to a portable laptop,
the measurement machine looks like a telescope and is shaped like a
human arm, with joints at the shoulder, elbow and wrist.
</P>
<P>
   By rotating the arm of the machine to different points around
the plate, Argenziano can make sure that the plate's dimensions
stay perfectly consistent with the contours of the piano rim. He
also downloads the coordinates into his laptop, where they are used
to create engineering drawings. Before he got the measurement
machine (which he first read about in a trade journal about six
months ago), Argenziano used two-dimensional measurement tools like
height gauges, calipers and rulers. ``I was crawling around on my
belly, doing things the hard way,'' he said. ``What used to take me
hours, even days, now takes me about 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the effects of the changes, another performer, Barry
Douglas, said that more than 10 years ago, certain Steinways might
have been right for playing only certain kinds of music. ``You
could argue that the older Steinways had a more individualistic
type of tone and voicing within each piano,'' Douglas said. ``One
might have had a certain deep sound that made it perfect for
playing pieces from the Romantic period.''
</P>
<P>
   Because many of these innovations are still relatively new, it
remains to be seen whether they'll enable Steinway to speed
production. In most cases, it takes several months between the time
a Steinway piano is ordered and the time it shows up on the
doorstep. According to a report from the Piano Manufacturers
Association International, Steinway produced and sold fewer than 10
percent of the 28,356 grand pianos sold in the United States in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But building more pianos is not a high priority for the company.
``We're still very much a handcrafted instrument, and I don't think
we will ever get away from that,'' Berger said. ``The technology
we're developing now gives us some amazing abilities in terms of
machining, but there are still many aspects of piano making that
are better done by human hands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
