u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAMES-EXHIBITION-ART-     06-09 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAMES-EXHIBITION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGN NOTEBOOK: TRYING TO DO WHAT THE EAMESES DID 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You could smell the plywood at the Library of
Congress in Washington, where ``The Work of Charles and Ray Eames:
A Legacy of Invention'' recently opened. At the exhibition of the
two American designers' multifaceted achievement, the cheap board
they made beautiful has a fresh, resourceful smell that makes you
believe anything is possible _ because the world might be as
pliable as new plywood.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was thick with people in their 20s and 30s,
discovering the Eameses' sculptural midcentury furniture and the
inventive assemblages of domestic artifacts from their 1949
prefabricated house in Pacific Palisades, Calif., which embodied
their inspiring intentions. As the show's banner graphics
explained, the Eameses ``aimed to improve society.''
</P>
<P>
   The notions that innovatively designed and economically
accessible objects like home furnishings could be ambassadors of
cultural change, that elegance can be ordinary and that being
serious can be fun, are still radical. They registered visibly for
a new audience trying the chairs or watching the flowers and toys
spin on the screens that displayed the designers' entertaining
educational films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa! That's nana's chair!'' a young man with a surfer's bob
of hair and neck beads said to his girlfriend as they approached
the famous rosewood lounge chair and ottoman ``that everyone in the
family is scoping out!'' Holding hands, they stood before it as if
it were the edge of the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   At the four-day International Contemporary Furniture Fair in New
York at the Jacob K. Javits Convention Center in May, the nation's
most comprehensive exhibition of contemporary home design, emotions
ran drier.
</P>
<P>
   Design is enjoying a moment in the sun, thanks to lots of
fashionable press. But it was hard to believe that the next team of
Eameses might have been at the 1999 fair.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there were stylish versions of everything fashionable
during the last few years: versions of minimal, cubistic, wenge
wood boutique-hotel fittings; versions of the bamboo-Bauhaus,
Asian-inflected interiors that designers build for rock stars'
vacation homes in Bali; versions of the Scandinavian 1960s, the
Italian 1970s, the Los Angeles architectural 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Off-site, there was a vigorous circuit of parties as New York's
design community played host to the trade and the fashionably
curious. At Cappellini Modern Age on Wooster Street, there were
twin muscle men in black T-shirts, velvet roping arrivals at the
door. At Troy on Greene Street, linen-shirted guests dipping frites
in mayonnaise sat at Maarten Van Severen's severe tables beneath
his police-station-style lighting, like people being interrogated.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the day, the decade, the century, the
millennium, tough thinking about the direction of design and its
power of solution was in short supply, which is too bad. Enthusiasm
for the subject has never been stronger. Does design still have a
mission? Should it? The Eames show and the furniture fair were an
opportunity to consider the market for contemporary design and the
relevance of its promise.
</P>
<P>
   Designers, manufacturers and retailers agree that the audience
is growing, with a new generation of furniture buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer is demanding more design,'' said Gary Friedman,
president of retail for Williams-Sonoma, the parent company of
Pottery Barn, whose sales in 1998 exceeded $550 million, an
increase of 37 percent over the previous year. ``People have been
subliminally educated about design by advertising, the Internet,
everything they enjoy, from snowboarding to music videos.''
</P>
<P>
   David Shearer, the owner of Totem, a Tribeca gallery
specializing in provocative designs, said: ``There's a trendiness
to design right now. We're getting a more-average customer.''
Totem, which also has a catalog and wholesale business, is close to
$2 million in annual sales, an increase of 40 percent over last
year. ``Twenty-five percent of our orders are going to the middle
of the country,'' Shearer said.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary home furnishings design has entered the equation of
stylish living, sharing younger consumers' attention with fashion
and travel. With that has come pressure to make it less elite, more
affordable and more accessible. Even flea-marketing, which
introduced a younger audience to modern design, is running thin as
an inexpensive outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Crate and Barrel, with sales approaching $200 million in 1998,
is experimenting with a lower-cost brand for younger consumers,
very much like the Gap's Old Navy chain, which analysts predict may
surpass Gap stores in sales in the next two years. Crate and
Barrel's first Generations X through Y store, tentatively called
Blueprint, will open in Chicago in August. Pottery Barn has similar
plans on the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's something for everyone to learn from Old
Navy,'' Friedman said. ``If you look at Pottery Barn's
demographics, which is people with incomes of $75,000 and above,
it's not catering to 65 percent of the population. There's a huge
opportunity there.''
</P>
<P>
   The large retailers, frequently accused of generic design that
will sell to the widest group through the lowest common
denominators, are bolstering their credentials by putting new
designers on the payroll. Pottery Barn has tripled its in-house
design department, to more than 30 employees, in the last year and
has introduced signature lines by designers like Jonathan Adler,
whose work reflects the popularity of the 1950s and '60s.
Williams-Sonoma last year hired Peri Wolfman, a New York retailer,
as vice president for product design. In May, Eric Pfeiffer, 30,
the founder of Bravo 20, a design business based in San Francisco,
was made the consulting creative director of Hold Everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've realized the bar had to go up on esthetics,'' Pfeiffer
said, speaking at Bravo 20's booth at the furniture fair. ``Simple,
clean, modern is the in thing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Within the last 15 years, the system of the few dozen
independent stores that sold contemporary design, often isolated in
their mid-size cities, has been challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've noticed larger companies walking the aisles, approaching
you to see how you can help them _ Target, Crate and Barrel, the
big-box retailers,'' Pfeiffer said. ``It was all about price. Now
design is the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Kmart has Martha Stewart's Everyday, a brisk, administrative
line of coordinating taste, which is expanding into furniture.
Target, which hired the architect Michael Graves to design
household products, is now talking with Blu Dot, a young furniture
company based in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Target's furniture buyers are younger than their typical
buyers,'' John Christakos, one of Blu Dot's principals, said.
``They're teen-agers or college kids _ young apartment dwellers.
And when big companies try to do products for young people, it's
like your father using a slang word. It doesn't come out right.''
</P>
<P>
   At the higher end of the market, design galleries are branching
out like more traditional retailers. Totem will open a second store
this fall in New York and one in Los Angeles. Salon Moderne in Soho
will open a new store, Property, in September. Moss on Greene
Street has taken the space next door. Format, showcasing Italian
manufacturers, opened on Wooster Street in May, the latest European
arrival to Soho.
</P>
<P>
   The new design stores are also Internet-based businesses,
erasing the boundaries of the market and making it available to
anyone looking for it, especially young customers in small towns.
(With prophetic fit, the Eameses are on line, too, through their
manufacturer. Web site transactions account for 20 percent of
Herman Miller's Home Collection sales.)
</P>
<P>
   Fashion _ the industry credited with helping make contemporary
furniture fashionable _ might be expected to take it forward. Donna
Karan's new 17,000-square-foot Madison Avenue store will sell
household products by Droog, a Dutch group interested in the
intellectual edge of design, in addition to two new home Donna
Karan lines. The Prada store, opening in SoHo, will also have a
substantial furnishings collection.
</P>
<P>
   But despite availability, popularity and an increasingly
sophisticated set of references, this visitor to the 1999 fair
found design's sense of leadership sadly missing among the largely
fashionable furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Gary McNatton, a senior vice president of Gap and creative
director of home design for Banana Republic, agreed: ``The '90s
were a lost decade. We went retro. Nothing happened. You look at
the masters, like the Eameses. It gives you a true appreciation of
what design has to give.''
</P>
<P>
   With its prospects improving, contemporary furniture might
reasonably be called upon to develop a vision that looks forward,
not backward, and that trades on ideas, not attitudes. During the
fair, many designers said that new materials and new technologies,
not unlike the legacy of the Eameses, were the unseen elements of
this decade's design, not new shapes.
</P>
<P>
   But with its success, the profession could easily lose its
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   What prevailed at the fair were fashion statements, not design
solutions. The historical moment has moved away from the postwar
American recovery that the Eameses helped galvanize with good
design. But practical issues of affordable, multifunctional
furnishings are as relevant to a young professional generation now,
living under the pressures of late-20th-century life, as they were
to a country constructing the future of peace 50 years ago _ and
eager for the best ways to do it. Purpose can be adventurous;
change can accommodate comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Davan Joy of USDA, a California design collective that exhibited
at a temporary gallery space on Grand Street as part of ``G7,'' a
collaborative of seven American designers who chose not to
participate in the fair, put his finger on the problem for both
designers and their public.
</P>
<P>
   As he waited with his colleagues to have his picture taken for
Harper's Bazaar _ Wallpaper was working on its shoot in the
background _ Joy said, ``Everybody needs to take a little bit more
of a risk.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
