<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9093 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRIS-MYSTERYMAN-2nd     06-09 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRIS-MYSTERYMAN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Harris, agrees. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Even then, he was writing for crime magazines and men's
magazines,'' Blackman says. ``It was pretty clear he had loftier
ambitions for his writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris married; he and his wife lived in Hubbard, outside of
Waco. They had a daughter but eventually divorced.
</P>
<P>
   After working several years at the Waco newspaper, Harris was
hired by the AP in New York. His drinking companions say young
Tom's editor in Waco was not much impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In six months,'' the editor predicted, ``you'll be coming back
here with your tail between your legs, asking for your old job
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite everything, the question remains: Why is Tom Harris not
talking?
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just naturally shy,'' says Sam Maull, a friend from his
AP days in New York. ``He doesn't seek the limelight. ... He feels
his work speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kelly, another of his former New York colleagues, agrees.
But Kelly says Harris never liked to ``meddle'' in other people's
personal lives and, in turn, probably doesn't want to surrender his
own privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only explanation I can give,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The second question we'd ask Thomas Harris is who or what
inspired him to create Hannibal Lecter. Sometimes characters in
books are thinly disguised clones of the authors, but that's
clearly not the case with this author and this character.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Tom Kelly had some funny thoughts while reading
``Lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As I kept reading, I kept thinking to myself, this isn't the
same guy. Then I thought ... well, if it is the same guy, maybe
that's why he's so quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Laughing, he says he decided Harris really is an oddball: ``I'm
not going to let him stay in my house overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Kelly, now the spokesman for the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, concluded that the writer and his made-up
monster actually do have some things in common.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw the `Lambs' movie and how (Lecter) was portrayed by
Anthony Hopkins, he reminded me of Tom,'' Kelly says. ``He did in
the sense he was so even-tempered, so almost removed from himself.
In some of those scenes, (Lecter's) dry wit made me turn to my wife
and say, `That's Tom Harris.'''
</P>
<P>
   Friends insist that Harris had but one major wish: to get a book
contract big enough to allow him to lie on the beach in Mexico, sip
cocktails and never answer a phone.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and two of his AP buddies on the night shift, Sam Maull
and Dick Riley, set the dream in motion in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by ``Naked Came the Stranger,'' a bestselling novel
written as a joke by staff members of the daily paper Newsday,
Maull, Riley and Harris decided to collaborate on a novel of their
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We exchanged ideas about it, about what characters we would
have and the plot,'' Maull says. ``We all did the research. After
we got into it, Tom sort of took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis, he was the one who whipped it into
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris left the AP to complete the project that became ``Black
Sunday,'' and was listed on the dust jacket as the sole author. But
royalties were split among the three journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after ``Black Sunday'' was published, Hollywood snapped up
the movie rights.
</P>
<P>
   Harris now had the money to go lie on a beach and drink, but he
appears to have chosen New York's Long Island over Mexico. And
obviously he continued writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a demonic hard worker,'' Maull says. ``I can't emphasize
that enough. He was good at helping relatively young writers out,
showing them how to put together a story. I, myself, was a
beneficiary of that. ... As far as interacting with other human
beings, he has almost no faults at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly says Harris did have his ``ornery moments.'' The most
notable occurred one evening as the two were working the 4
p.m.-midnight shift in the AP's New York City bureau.
</P>
<P>
   A deadly hostage situation developed in a Brooklyn gun shop, and
much of Manhattan and most of the available AP staff were caught up
in the saga.
</P>
<P>
   At midnight, when their shift ended, Harris and co-worker Walter
Stovall got up to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom, you can't abandon me now, pal,'' protested Kelly, the
supervisor that night. ``There's cops all over the place, and these
people are demanding an airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for cocktails,'' Harris replied coolly.
</P>
<P>
   While this was not quite as cavalier as it sounds, Kelly sensed
a potential dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   So he called the nearby Pig &AMP; Whistle bar and ordered a bottle
of Jack Daniels whiskey delivered to the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not drinking out of a paper cup,'' Harris announced
grandly.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly ordered glasses and setups.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Stovall stayed and helped work the story to a
conclusion. The next morning, Kelly was confronted by ``his'' boss
about the empty whiskey bottle and dirty glasses. Harris listened
in bemused silence until the bureau chief finished raking Kelly
over the coals and stormed off, then commented:
</P>
<P>
   ``No good deed goes unpunished.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, as he himself left that morning, Harris paused at the
door, turned to Kelly and said with a smile: ``I bet you don't have
the guts to put it on your expense account.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, really, doesn't that sound like Hannibal Lecter?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
