<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERS-SPYFILMS-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENTS PROVOCATEURS: WHY WE BONDED WITH THE SQUAD OF '60S
SUPERSPIES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by SPY FILMS-LIST) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The words sound like the latest piece of punditry decrying the
state of the entertainment industry. But they come from the early
'60s, when James Bond creator Ian Fleming commented on the
popularity of the earliest Bond movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a violent era,'' Fleming once said. ``As for sex,
seduction to a marked extent has replaced courtship.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, who died in 1964, didn't know the half of it. Spies
were fodder for entertainment long before ``Dr. No,'' the first
Bond movie, debuted in 1962. And spy entertainment continues to be
popular, as evidenced by the anticipated success of Mike Myers'
spoof ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' opening Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The current resurgence in spy-movie popularity, however, has
nothing on the '60s fad, and the craze only got more manic after
Fleming died. Bond clones abounded, from James Coburn's Derek Flint
to Dean Martin's Matt Helm. ``The Man From U.N.C.L.E.'' was just
the beginning of a flood of TV spies. Spies entered the Top 40,
with Shirley Bassey's ``Goldfinger'' and Johnny Rivers' ``Secret
Agent Man.'' They even infiltrated advertising, the most ludicrous
example featuring Los Angeles Dodgers star pitcher Don Drysdale as
a sudsy spy for Lifebuoy soap. Bond-influenced products ranged from
gadgety toys to a line of 007 colognes.
</P>
<P>
   Ask espionage-entertainment aficionados what made spies so hot
in the '60s and you're likely to get a variety of answers, few of
which resemble Fleming's comment. They all come back to three
words, though:
</P>
<P>
   Bond. James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``He appealed to the devil in every man,'' said Lee Pfeiffer,
author of ``Essential Bond.'' ``He was selfish when it came to his
own needs. He always got the best women, went to the most exotic
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer, who also publishes a spy-entertainment Webzine called
Secret Intelligence (www.secretintel.com), credits the success of
the Bond books to Fleming's real-life experiences as a British spy
in World War II. The movies, however, succeeded because of how
``little'' they reflected real life. The Cold War was at its peak,
but espionage in the Bond films had more to do with glamour than
global tensions. Although a Bond supervillain might be vaguely
Russian or Chinese, he would always be independently bent on world
domination, usually from some impregnable island fortress. And with
each new movie, it seemed like the series itself was trying harder
to rule the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Producer Cubby Broccoli continued to put more and more into
the Bond movies,'' Pfeiffer said. ``He never fell victim to what I
call the `Planet of the Apes' syndrome, that is, spending less on
each succeeding movie. He always wanted more exotic locations and
more exotic villains.''
</P>
<P>
   Broccoli's strategy worked, and the Bond series took off with
the third and fourth entries, ``Goldfinger'' (1964) and
``Thunderball,'' which came out in 1965, the year that secret-agent
mania peaked. Most of the spy-oriented TV series debuted that year,
as did many of the Bond-knockoff movies. The Beatles even got into
the act, with the spy-influenced plot of the 1965 movie ``Help!''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Giblin, editor and head writer for ``Secret Intelligence,''
says he believes that the 1965 spy-entertainment explosion was a
coincidence, a result of the cyclical nature of fads. But he
acknowledges that other factors might have been at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't yet become as jaded by things like Vietnam and the
'68 assassinations,'' Giblin said recently. ``Bond's imitators
seemed silly (after those events), when before they could be
tolerated, even enjoyed, as we craved that kind of escapist
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that that stopped silliness from permeating the genre _ but
knockoffs and parodies such as ``Our Man Flint'' and Dean Martin's
four Matt Helm movies had short shelf lives.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``These movies didn't last because they were cheap imitations,''
said Patrick Macnee, a spy aficionado who played John Steed in the
'60s spy series ``The Avengers.'' ``They became campier. It was all
an imitation of much better material.'' Even Bond became campy,
with the overblown 1967 parody ``Casino Royale.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Myers managed to successfully parody this
self-parodying era with 1997's ``Austin Powers: International Man
of Mystery.'' Powers, a bad-haired, bad-toothed, bespectacled,
lascivious superspy, bears little resemblance to the ultra-cool
Bond. Powers is probably closest in spirit to Matt Helm, easily the
randiest spy of the secret-agent era, although his glasses are
almost definitely a nod to Harry Palmer, a more serious, sardonic
movie spy.
</P>
<P>
   What the Powers movies reflect best, however, is the mod culture
of mid- to late-'60s London, which worked its way into many of the
spy movies. For the uninitiated, Powers was a '60s spy who was
cryogenically frozen and then thawed out in the '90s, when his
decidedly unliberated ways clashed with a more politically correct
era. In ``The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' Powers travels back in time to
groovy, fashion-conscious '60s London. The difference between
Powers and his cinematic counterparts, though, is that Powers
himself is mod.
</P>
<P>
   ``These male spies of the '60s probably weren't mod because it
was still a new movement, and perhaps was considered too trendy for
Hollywood to cast (its) leading male spies as mod,'' said Lyn
FitzGerald, creator of the Web site Fab Fashions of the Swinging
Sixties (www.geocities.com/FashionAvenue/5362). ``It is interesting
to note that the female spies in TV and film of the time, however,
`were' mod. Female spies were portrayed as great followers of
fashion as well as cunning spies, and the fashion of the day was
mod.''
</P>
<P>
   The fashion of the day barely made it to the early '70s, though,
and was replaced in part by the hippie movement, which never would
have fit into spy films. Similarly, the spy movies fell out of
fashion, the result of a glut of films both serious (''The Spy Who
Came in From the Cold'') and goofy (far too many to mention here).
</P>
<P>
   Bond, however, somehow never came in from the cold, and many
fans never thought the series was the same after Connery left to
make way for the cheekier Roger Moore and the darker Timothy Dalton
(an underrated Bond who was the closest in spirit to Fleming's
original). Pierce Brosnan, the current Bond, has been a commercial
success, although many Bondphiles find him too blandly pretty for
the role. He'll get his third chance to prove himself when the
latest Bond, ``The World Is Not Enough,'' comes out in November.
</P>
<P>
   Non-Bond spy movies have continued since the '60s, of course,
but they've tended to be more sobersided and reflective of their
eras. Post-Watergate spy films in particular, especially Francis
Coppola's ``The Conversation,'' took a more serious, coldhearted
look at the subject of invading privacy. Last year's ``Enemy of the
State'' was an entertainingly paranoid take on high-tech spying.
</P>
<P>
   Myers touched a nerve with the first ``Austin Powers,'' a wildly
uneven movie that became a hit largely through the box-office
dollars of a generation that was born after the '60s, a generation
that had never heard of Flint, Palmer or Helm, and thanks to
limited video availability, might never hear of the latter two (not
that that's any great loss in Helm's case).
</P>
<P>
   It would be exaggerating things to say that ``Powers'' is as
much in tune with 1999 culture as ``Dr. No'' was with 1962 culture,
and it would really be pressing things to assess the series'
success with a sound bite as doom-laden as Fleming's quote about a
violent culture. Myers, however, may have his finger on the pulse
of why spy movies were so hot in the '60s, and why Powers is so hot
now. When asked by USA Weekend why audiences made ``Powers'' a
phenomenon, Myers had a one-word response that could apply to Bond
as well as Powers:
</P>
<P>
   ``Naughtiness.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1700EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9096 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPYFILMS-LIST-TEX     06-09 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPYFILMS-LIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPY-BY-SPY RUNDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies POWERS-SPY FILMS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A by-no-means comprehensive '60s spy time line:
</P>
<P>
   1960: ``The Avengers'' debuts on British television, starring
Patrick Macnee as dapper secret agent Jonathan Steed and Honor
Blackman as his female partner. Macnee's most famous partner,
however, would be Diana Rigg as the mod Mrs. Peel; Blackman would
attain her greatest fame as a suggestively named Bond girl in
``Goldfinger.''
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 5, 1962: ``Dr. No'' premieres, starring Sean Connery as
James Bond, Agent 007. Less campy than succeeding entries, it was
bereft of certain Bond ingredients such as a pretitle sequence,
gadgetry or a henchman for the title supervillain.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 23, 1963: ``From Russia With Love,'' considered by many to
be the best Bond movie, premieres.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 22, 1964: ``The Man From U.N.C.L.E.,'' TV's most blatant
response to the Bond craze, premieres. The campy series, starring
Robert Vaughan and David McCallum, lasts till January 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 25, 1964: ``Goldfinger'' premieres, adding more gadgetry (a
versatile briefcase and a loaded Aston-Martin) to the mix. It's the
third-highest-grossing film of 1964; ``From Russia With Love'' is
second.
</P>
<P>
   Early 1965: ``The Ipcress File,'' the first in a trio of movies
starring Michael Caine as reluctant spy Harry Palmer, premieres.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 27, 1965: ``Goldfinger's'' theme song, sung by Shirley
Bassey, peaks at No. 8 on the ``Billboard'' singles chart.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 15, 1965: ``I Spy,'' notable for pairing black Bill Cosby
and white Robert Culp, premieres. It lasts till September 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 17, 1965: ``The Wild Wild West,'' a canny merging of the
spy and western genres, premieres. Robert Conrad stars as James
West, an undercover agent for President Grant; Ross Martin stars as
his sidekick Artemus Gordon, a master of disguise. Will Smith and
Kevin Kline will play their counterparts in an upcoming movie.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 18, 1965: ``Get Smart,'' a spy sitcom co-created by Mel
Brooks, premieres. Don Adams plays inept CONTROL agent Maxwell
Smart; Barbara Feldon plays his partner, Agent 99, the moddest of
all mod spies. The show lasts till September 1970; in 1995, Andy
Dick will star in a misguided and short-lived reprise on the Fox
network.
</P>
<P>
   December 1965: ``Thunderball,'' the fourth Connery Bond movie,
premieres.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas 1965: Colgate markets a 007 line of colognes and
grooming materials.
</P>
<P>
   Late 1965: ``Our Man Flint,'' starring James Coburn as cocky
superspy Derek Flint, fires the first cinematic salvo at the Bond
series.
</P>
<P>
   Late 1965: ``The Spy Who Came in From the Cold,'' a serious
adaptation of John Le Carre's novel, premieres. It stars Richard
Burton and earns a reputation as the best spy movie of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Early 1966: ``The Silencers,'' the first and best of four movies
starring Dean Martin as swinging superspy Matt Helm, premieres.
``Best,'' by the way, is a relative term.
</P>
<P>
   March 26, 1966: ``Secret Agent Man,'' Johnny Rivers' theme song
to the TV series ``Secret Agent,'' peaks at No. 3 on the
``Billboard'' chart. The song will create a far more lasting
impression than the Patrick McGoohan series, which lasted only one
year.
</P>
<P>
   March 28, 1966: Taking advantage of the spy craze, ABC imports
``The Avengers'' to U.S. TV, where it lasts till September 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 17, 1966: ``Mission: Impossible,'' the best and most
complex of the TV spy series, premieres. It lasts till September
1973 on CBS and earns a sporadic 1988-90 revival on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Late 1966: ``Murderers' Row,'' the second Matt Helm movie,
premieres. So does ``Funeral in Berlin,'' the second Harry Palmer
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Early 1967: ``In Like Flint,'' the sequel to ``Our Man Flint,''
premieres. So does ``Billion Dollar Brain,'' the third and final
Harry Palmer movie. Both spies will be revived in TV-movies.
</P>
<P>
   August/September 1967: ``You Only Live Twice,'' the fifth and
arguably weakest of the '60s Connery Bonds, premieres. It's notable
for introducing Donald Pleasance's bald, cat-stroking archvillain
Ernst Stavro Blofeld _ the inspiration for Dr. Evil in Mike Myers'
``Austin Powers'' movies. Connery briefly abandoned Bond movies
after its release.
</P>
<P>
   December 1967: ``Casino Royale,'' a renegade and uneven Bond
spoof featuring an all-star cast (David Niven, Peter Sellers, Woody
Allen and original Bond girl Ursula Andress), premieres.
</P>
<P>
   Late 1967: Raquel Welch stars in ``Fathom,'' a surprisingly
entertaining spy spoof. But spy culture shows signs of waning with
``Operation Kid Brother,'' starring Sean Connery's kid brother,
Neil, as James Bond's kid brother ... oh, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   Early 1968: ``The Ambushers,'' considered to be the worst of the
Matt Helm movies (although it's a close call), premieres.
</P>
<P>
   Early 1969: ``The Wrecking Crew,'' the fourth Matt Helm film,
premieres. Helm makes a brief comeback on '70s TV in the form of
Tony Franciosa.
</P>
<P>
   December 1969: ``In Her Majesty's Secret Service,'' starring
George Lazenby in a one-shot performance as the first non-Connery
Bond, premieres. It doesn't do as well as its predecessors, thanks
to the absence of Connery and to a general feeling that the craze
has faded.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   (Sources: Internet Movie Database, The Complete Directory to
Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows, The ``Billboard'' Book of
Top 40 Hits.)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
