<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRIS-REMINISCENCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS HARRIS? HE WAS A QUIET GUY. THEN HE CREATED HANNIBAL
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies HARRIS-MYSTERY MAN) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yeah, sure, I know Thomas Harris. So I guess you want me to
reveal the untold story behind spooky serial killer Hannibal Lecter
and ``The Silence of the Lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   I imagine you also wonder about the plot of his soon-to-be new
megahit, ``Hannibal,'' which appeared in bookstores Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And no doubt you're curious about his views on Hollywood's
handling of his first three novels and what we might expect when
``Hannibal'' and his strange tastes return to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Finally (you might reasonably insist), who is Thomas Harris, why
did he drop out of sight after ``Black Sunday'' and how come 11
years have passed since his last epic?
</P>
<P>
   Well, if I knew I'd tell you.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that I do know Thomas Harris. But like Darrell Royal
once said, he met Mickey Mantle before Mickey was Mickey Mantle. I
met Harris when he was young Tom and working for the Waco Herald
and News-Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we worked together for The Associated Press, but Harris
labored in New York and I in Texas. I'm sure he was no more aware
of me than I was of him.
</P>
<P>
   However, the circumstances of our meeting were unusual.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s, the AP assigned me to cover the most bizarre
gold hunt in modern Texas history. It was on Salado Creek, south of
Waco.
</P>
<P>
   The details are lost in time and memory, but the search centered
around a long-lost stash of Spanish gold, jewels and other
treasures hidden in a cave along Salado Creek near Jarrell.
</P>
<P>
   The search party was largely an unsavory group, and the whole
deal probably a scam. In fact, I came to believe it was just con
men caught up in their own weird scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, they were a colorful lot. My favorite was Pig Red, which
was most likely a nickname. Pig confided that a Mexican had
wandered drunkenly into the cave and discovered the treasures while
stumbling through a maze of tunnels. His drinking buddy's most
vivid recollection was a solid-gold bull's head with blood-red
rubies for eyes.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, they'd liquor up their obliging hero,
purportedly to try to pry from his foggy memory new clues to the
location of their elusive bounty.
</P>
<P>
   I suspected they also did so to impress reporters and potential
investors.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, young Harris and a friend of mine, David McHam, a
journalism professor at Baylor, showed up one morning to report on
this phenomenon for the Waco newspaper. McHam, who worked part time
at the newspaper, also brought along a student named Tommy West,
who would become an outstanding journalist in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   The four of us had breakfast that morning at the Stagecoach Inn
at Salado before heading out to the digging site.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered Harris much later as a bright, quiet, curly-haired
young man who wore glasses and spoke with a charming and richly
Southern Mississippi accent. He didn't have a beard then, and was
relatively tall and slender, two things I've never been.
</P>
<P>
   And that's about it.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason or another, we didn't get into the creekside
drilling site that day. Pretty soon, the gold hunters grew weary of
digging in the snow and rain and began dynamiting the place.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a bull's head, they probably obliterated it in
their haste.
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Waco, Harris took a photograph of Pig Red,
and West interviewed me about my dealings with Pig and his pals.
Afterward, McHam sent me Harris' photo of Pig along with West's
story.
</P>
<P>
   Many, many years later, at a party somewhere, McHam and I were
discussing books. He now is a journalism professor at the
University of Texas at Arlington. I mentioned that I had read ``The
Silence of the Lambs'' and recently seen the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought both were excellent,'' I told McHam. ``I'd love to
meet a guy who could create a character like Hannibal the
Cannibal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You did,'' McHam replied. ``He was the kid with Tommy West and
me at the Salado gold hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
