<HEADER>
A9100 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NIGHT-VISION-2TAK     06-09 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NIGHT-VISION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISION GEAR FOR THE DARK AND STORMY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo.)   (bl)  
 By DAVID KUSHNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a long day of work as a mechanical engineer, Tom Malphus
likes to hop onto his mountain bike and head into the hills around
San Diego to blow off steam. Mission Park provides a rugged
setting, with off-road trails, wide-open spaces and wildlife. And
even after dark, Malphus sees it all, with the power of his night
vision goggles.
</P>
<P>
   Night vision technology, which amplifies available light through
battery-powered optics, is not just for the military anymore. When
most people think of night vision, they imagine grainy greenish
camera views of bombs falling on Beirut or that chilling scene in
the movie ``Silence of the Lambs.'' But these days, night vision
products are dropping in price, and civilians who are not Hannibal
Lecter wannabes are getting in on the action.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, it's easy to pick up night vision goggles that
cost thousands of dollars not too long ago for less than $350. Some
buyers are gearheads, hungry for the latest in optic gadgetry.
Others are adventurers, looking for ways to hike through
Yellowstone at midnight or raft down the Colorado River before
sunrise. It's a novelty that can quickly become an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Morgovsky, owner of Hi Tek, a company that produces night
vision products for consumers, said that ``once people acquire the
ability to see in the dark, they like to keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   Night vision devices were invented during World War II for
military purposes, with countries like Britain and the Soviet Union
leading the way. In the 1959, a private American company called ITT
Industries Night Vision began creating night vision goods for the
U.S. armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Night vision products eventually became available on the
commercial market in the 1980s. But they did not become popular
until the winds of change began to sweep across the Soviet Union
and surplus Russian devices were first allowed on the market. Even
though the Soviet products were of considerably lower quality than
the American gear, they helped fan public interest because they
were more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   After the Persian Gulf war, defense spending was reduced,
leaving companies like ITT with a surplus of night vision wares.
For the past six years, ITT has been going after the consumer
market. The company says consumers now account for 15 percent of
its annual sales _ about 10,000 to 15,000 goggles and other
devices, which cost around $2,000 each. A handful of other
manufacturers and distributors, like Hitek International, Moonlight
and Sovietski have entered the consumer business as well.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. armed forces still get the highest-quality night vision
products, generally two to three times as powerful as consumer
versions, said Larry Curfiss, vice president for commercial
products at ITT. The basic technology behind night vision, however,
remains essentially the same.
</P>
<P>
   Even when a night looks impenetrably dark, a tiny amount of
infrared light, outside the range of human vision, is coming from
the moon and stars. A night vision device uses low amounts of
voltage to amplify this light until it can be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The process of amplification seems instantaneous to the viewer,
but it takes several steps. The light, which is made up of photons,
enters the night vision device through a lens and travels through a
tube called an image intensifier. Inside this tube, the photons are
converted into electrical energy. An electrostatic field increases
the intensity of the electrons, which strike a phosphorus screen
and can then be perceived through the eyepiece.
</P>
<P>
   Night vision technology has evolved over four generations of
devices; all but the first generation are still on the market.
</P>
<P>
   In the first devices, an external infrared light source was
required to illuminate whatever the watcher wanted to see, and the
resulting image tended to be distorted. Second-generation systems
can function with just starlight. Third- and fourth-generation
devices can amplify the light even further, by accelerating the
electrons through a wafer-thin glass disk, called a microchannel
plate, that is perforated with millions of tiny holes. That
improves the image quality when the electrons strike the screen. A
light image can be amplified up to 5,000 times.
</P>
<P>
   Because the night-vision device is dealing with infrared light,
the final image is monochromatic and could be rendered in various
colors, but the color that is used for the image is green. Curfiss
said the U.S. government had decided to use green because an Army
survey determined it to be the easiest color for the human eye to
see. ``If they wanted,'' Curfiss said, ``they could have chosen
orange.'' The Soviet Union also chose green.
</P>
<P>
   One common misconception among consumers is that night vision
devices can be used in complete darkness. When there really is no
available light _ deep within a cave, for example _ an infrared
``flashlight'' must be used for illumination. In the military, such
illuminators can prove dangerous because enemies can perceive them
with their own night vision optics. But consumers can readily use
infrared beams as night vision flashlights when there isn't enough
available light.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Consumers might not understand the potential hazards of night
vision devices. Because the optical equipment amplifies light so
much, bright lights or even daylight could damage the eye,
especially in the older models. Many newer models have protection
features that automatically dim the image when the device is
pointed at a source of bright light.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur and commercial night owls are finding more uses for
night vision devices. Hunters use night vision goggles and
binoculars in dark woods; people who suffer from retinal
degeneration, which makes it hard for them to see at night, use
lightweight night vision goggles; boat racers wear waterproof Night
Mariners, from Hitek, to navigate on the water at night.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are even offering night expeditions for tourists.
In Vale, Colo., the Lakota River Guides company runs night rafting
journeys. Darryl Bangert, the company's owner, said the sight of
the sci-fi headgear was initially unsettling for riverside
residents. He said the tourists generally had a similar reaction:
``Nine out of 10 people say the same exact thing when they put on
the goggles: `Wow, this is so cool.'''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT DESCRIPTIONS FOR SEVERAL NIGHT VISION DEVICES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Name: Hitek Cyber Eye 002
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer or distributor: Hitek; (800) 546-4448,
www.nightsight.com
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer's suggested retail price: $1,400
</P>
<P>
   What is it? Handheld monocular with multiple attachment options,
including a camcorder adapter so you can hook it up to the lens of
any old camcorder, and a head mount to keep the hands free.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Compact, powerful, easy to slip into your coat
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ITT Night Quest 220
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer: ITT; (800) 448-8678, www.ittnightvision.com
</P>
<P>
   Price: $3,295
</P>
<P>
   What is it? Waterproof night vision binoculars with built-in
infrared illuminator and interchangeable lenses. Useful for
boaters.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Stylish, with incredible performance, brought to
you by the people who make United States military equipment.
Pricey, but you get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Moonlight MPN 40K
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer: Moonlight, (619) 625-0010,
www.moonlightproducts.com
</P>
<P>
   Price: $699
</P>
<P>
   What is it? Heavy Russian-made binoculars with an external
infrared illuminator.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Cumbersome, so-so performance; you can see why the
Soviets lost the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Name: Sovietski Night Vision Goggles
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer: Sovietski; (800) 442-0002, www.sovietski.com
</P>
<P>
   Price: $695
</P>
<P>
   What is it? Developed by Soviet air force pilots, these
head-mounted goggles are sometimes used by paratroopers and
commandos.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Big and heavy, and they hurt the back of the neck;
so-so performance.
</P>
<P>
   Name: Sony DCR-TRV310 Digital Handycam
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer: Sony; (800) 222-7669 www.sony.com
</P>
<P>
   Price: $1,099
</P>
<P>
   What is it? A camcorder that comes with Sony's ``nightshot''
technology, an infrared system that allows users to shoot in
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Gets the job done, but how many people really need
to take movies in the dark?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
