<HEADER>
A9106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENIOR-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      06-09 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS, WHITE HOUSE TARGET CRIMES AGAINST SENIORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Vt.)  (Eds: Senior Policy and Politics is a monthly column from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
 (bl)  
 By CARL HULSE   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Preying on the aged is certainly not a new criminal
enterprise. Vulnerable older people nervous about their finances
have always been susceptible to hustlers of shady investment
schemes; elderly homeowners worried about a roof leak can become
victims of fly-by-night contractors.
</P>
<P>
   But fraud against older Americans is entering a new realm with
slick Internet scams, irresistible sweepstakes offerings and a
mind-boggling array of health care swindles. And the problem is
expected to escalate as baby boomers pass into their retirement
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors are the most rapidly growing segment of our society,''
said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. ``As we all grow older, we begin to
depend more on others _ whether it's the ability to shop for
groceries or getting to doctors' appointments.''
</P>
<P>
   To combat fraud against older Americans, Leahy, the top Democrat
on the Judiciary Committee, is leading the effort to enact a
sweeping package of anti-crime provisions intended to reduce
offenses against seniors.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would establish new safeguards for pension and
retirement programs, grant authorities more power in pursuing
health care fraud and give added protection to nursing home
residents.
</P>
<P>
   It would also take aim at a form of fraud that appears to hit
older people harder than others _ telemarketing scams. The Federal
Trade Commission estimates that Americans lose $40 billion a year
to fast-talking telemarketers and 56 percent of those victims are
older than 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest threat many older Americans face is not a
criminal armed with a gun, but a telemarketer armed with a
deceptive rap,'' said President Clinton in an April radio address
as he endorsed senior-crime legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Building on a law passed in 1998, Clinton and the Senate authors
of the measure would empower the attorney general to pull the plug
on fraudulent telemarketers by cutting off their phone service, an
option helpful in fighting foreign-based scam artists who can
otherwise avoid U.S. prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The Leahy measure, known as the Seniors Safety Act of 1999,
would also establish an FTC clearinghouse to allow people to check
the track record of various telemarketing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the increased sophistication of the schemes, another
factor spurring the senior crime legislation is the fact that older
Americans don't appear to be benefiting as much as other groups
from the steady decline in the U.S. crime rate. Leahy notes that
the violent crime rates for people over 50 were the same in 1997 as
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Stomping out senior crime has long been a political staple as
lawmakers curried favor with the powerful voting bloc. It is hard
to argue against protecting the elderly. In the past, Congress has
entertained stiffer penalties for crimes against older Americans
and sought to stamp out deceptive direct mail campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the American Association of Retired Persons teamed
up with national police organizations to create community programs
intended to reduce crime against seniors and the Federal Trade
Commission has emphasized this area as well.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the initiative by Leahy and the White House different
from the past is the breadth of the proposal. Previous efforts
typically concentrated on one area _ telemarketing for instance _
while Leahy casts a much wider net to include health care fraud,
pension abuse and mistreatment of nursing home residents.
</P>
<P>
   The package, which he hopes to have considered this year, would
establish new criminal and civil penalties for those who show a
willful disregard of the health and safety of nursing center
residents and protect ``whistle-blowers'' who report such problems.
Bilking pension and employee benefit programs could bring new
punishment as well.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the measure would direct the Justice Department to
develop new strategies for reducing crimes against seniors and
include older Americans as a special category in national crime
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an ugly fact that criminal activity against seniors
inflicting physical and economic harm is a significant and
persistent problem,'' said Leahy, who called his program a ``new
safety net that aims to crack down on crimes that seniors are most
vulnerable to.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
