u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-70     06-09 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-700-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TWO DAYS, INDONESIA STILL AWAITS RESULTS OF HISTORIC ELECTION

</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Two days after the national election, the
talk of the town on Wednesday was not about who won or lost but
about the fact that nobody had any idea of the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Election returns have been arriving here from around this
sprawling nation with excruciating slowness, and officials of some
parties are expressing alarm over the possibility of vote
manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it taking so long?'' said Amien Rais, the leader of the
National Mandate Party. ``These delays could raise suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of all three of the other leading parties also pointed
fingers at each other, crying thief.
</P>
<P>
   Most local and foreign election monitors _ including former
President Jimmy Carter, who spoke at a news conference on Wednesday
_ said there was no evidence at the moment that the slow count was
deliberate or that it was being used as a cover for cheating.
</P>
<P>
   Carter and other monitors continued to voice optimism that the
election process would turn out to have been for the most part free
and fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until some allegations have been made that have some
foundation I think we need to believe that the process is
orderly,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``Election monitors will have to be vigilant from
now on. I don't think we'll know until November, when a final
choice for president is made, whether democracy has indeed come to
Indonesia in its fullest form.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters on Monday were selecting 462 representatives who will
make up only part of a 700-member assembly that is scheduled to
choose a new president in November. There will be no shortage of
opportunities in the future to cheat.
</P>
<P>
   The still-minuscule returns continued to show the popular
opposition party of Megawati Sukarnoputri in the lead, with the
incumbent party, Golkar, trailing significantly.
</P>
<P>
   But election analysts said the totals so far were too small to
form the basis of a projection. They also said Golkar's strength
tended to be in more distant and rural areas where reporting is
slower and where manipulation is easier.
</P>
<P>
   Andi Mallarangeng, an official with the General Elections
Commission, said late Wednesday that after initial delays and
mix-ups the tallies had begun to arrive in Jakarta much more
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   He said 50 percent of the results might be available by late
Thursday. Election commission officials had said earlier that they
expected to have 50 percent of the results in hand by late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A foreign election expert said that had been a wildly
unrealistic hope.
</P>
<P>
   Andi noted that this was Indonesia's first competitive election
since 1955, filled with new technicalities and safeguards that were
complicating the vote count.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed an excess of deliberateness in which totals were being
passed slowly up an administrative ladder _ from polling place to
village to sub-district to Jakarta _ waiting at each step for every
last report and every last signature.
</P>
<P>
   A foreign election observer, speaking on condition of anonymity,
asserted, however, that the complex electoral process was a
jerry-built structure that was itself partly to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Even several days after the election, he said, officials had no
firm figure for the number of registered voters. About 130 million
people are eligible to vote in this nation of more than 200
million.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a discrepancy of as many as 20,000 in the reported
numbers of polling places, the observer said. If each polling place
had 500 voters, this would amount to 10 million votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is not clear how many people actually voted,'' he said,
``it becomes difficult to tell if there was any manipulation and if
so the extent of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Within this context of uncertainties, Adi suggested that the
painful slowness of the vote processing was also a direct reaction
to the fraudulent elections that re-anointed former President
Suharto every five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are being very, very careful about the results at the
lower levels because of the previous trauma of cheating,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
