<HEADER>
A9152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEGMAN-AT-HOME-ART-2T     06-09 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEGMAN-AT-HOME-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WEGMAN'S WORLD, A FAMILY MOVES ON 8 FEET AND 8 PAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Those citronella eyes, set in a velvety gray pelt,
stare out from every corner of the Wegman studio, a sprawling
converted nursery school in Chelsea. It is also the family home of
William Wegman, the conceptual artist and dog-theme merchandiser,
whose fans respond to his outpouring of videos, PBS programs,
books, commercials, posters and kitchen magnets as if answering the
siren call of a high-pitched dog whistle. He is finishing a memoir
(to be published Oct. 1) of life with Fay Ray, one of the
Weimaraners who inspired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, you might not want to sit there,'' one of Wegman's five
assistants said, just as a visitor was about to drop into an
upholstered chair last week. ``It's covered in dog hair.''
</P>
<P>
   While the walls are covered with posters of bewigged Weimaraners
and the floor is scattered with stuffed-toy versions, the sparse
furnishings are covered with a dusting of short, gray hairs. A live
Weimaraner snoozes in the only other chair by the door, oblivious
to all, especially her own celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Wegman's wife and operations manager, Christine Burgin, calls
this Wegman World, noting that as a child she loathed dogs and
lakes. ``Now I spend half of each year by a lake in Maine with a
bunch of dogs,'' she said, alluding to their summer house.
</P>
<P>
   From the potential tedium of five dog walks a day to the
exhilaration of working with muses drooling to please, their life
has its pros and cons. The Wegmans try, in the midst of
caninecentric careers, to raise their own two children (Atlas, 4,
who doesn't especially like dogs, and Lola, 18 months, who does)
and live normal human lives. Wegman feels guilty leaving them _ the
dogs _ alone just to go to the movies. His wife is restarting her
life as a gallery owner after a seven-year hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   The intimacy of being in residence with two large dogs (Wegman
works primarily with four Weimaraners, but only Battina, 9, and her
son, Chippy, 4, live in New York) permeates the 5,300-square-foot
loft. But for anyone familiar with the Wegman book ``ABC''
(Hyperion, 1994), where each letter of the alphabet is shaped by
pretzel-pliant dogs' bodies, the animals at home seem almost
perversely doglike. They didn't spell anything for a visitor, and
they didn't dress up in flouncy outfits, displaying eerie human
hands. They pretty much lay sprawled on the floor or trotted off in
whatever direction Wegman led.
</P>
<P>
   The loft didn't smell like an animal house. But all the doors
and windows were open onto a breezy roof garden. Deborah Berke, a
New York architect, renovated the loft with dogs in mind. The
built-in cabinets are plywood. The floors are polished concrete
``to protect against those doggy nails,'' said Ms. Berke, a dog
enthusiast, who integrated dog-food bins into the kitchen cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   For the roof garden, Ms. Berke consulted specialists from the
Bronx Zoo to come up with a surface treatment _ a mixture of
concrete and rubber used in the gorillas' habitat _ that could
survive the assault of dogs' relieving themselves. Rebecca Cole
from the Potted Gardens in Greenwich Village landscaped the roof,
using copper-plated planters. Thanks to the dog urine, they will
age to a charming ``antique'' verdigris. Green splatter marks are
already visible.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, dog nests, a kind of beanbag chair flattened to a lumpy
canvas pancake, are everywhere: under a desk, in the hall, in the
bedroom. There are none in the living room. There, the dogs lie on
the couch, which is upholstered in a moss green-gray velvet, like
the coat of a certain familiar dog breed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't sit on the couch,'' Wegman said. ``The dogs look
so good on it that no one wants to make them get down. Not even my
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Most guests, he added, prefer to sit at the kitchen table. When
the visitor seemed surprised at how free of hair the white coverlet
on the master bed looked, Wegman said simply, ``Oh, they sleep
under the covers.'' Battina, called Batty, sleeps on Ms. Burgin's
side, Chippy at Wegman's feet. When Crooky, Batty's sister, pays an
overnight visit (she lives with a dentist in Maine), she curls
around Wegman's head. The children stay in their own rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the Wegmans grew up with dogs between the sheets. The
dog Wegman had as a child in Springfield, Mass., slept in the
basement. (``It wasn't my idea,'' he said.) Ms. Burgin was ``not a
dog person,'' she said. She recalled the early days of Wegman's
courtship. Batty and Fay Ray, the Weimaraner that followed in the
paw prints of Wegman's first dog, Man Ray, went along on their
first date. Wegman remembered the click of his future wife's heels
on the cobblestones of SoHo. She recalled thinking, ``There's no
way I'm going to be able to tell these dogs apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping arrangements were straightforward. ``I was the
dispensable one,'' she said. ``I knew from the start that sleeping
with the dogs came with the territory. I might end up somewhere
else. They wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Three litters later, Ms. Burgin can tell all the dogs apart and
she is used to being crowded out of bed when Wegman is not there to
defend their turf.
</P>
<P>
   Wegman has worked with 25 Weimaraners but still seems in awe of
their personality differences. Man Ray was ``an everything guy,''
who grew up with Wegman as an artist in the 1970s. ``He was so
inside me it was spooky,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Fay: ``I was in my 40s, and I was a man. Fay was like
a woman. I would try to play tug of war with her the way I'd done
with Man Ray, and she'd just look at me like `Why are you shoving
me?' '' Her death from leukemia four years ago is painful for the
couple to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's Batty: ``She's got these eyes I've looked at for 10
years, and I get to know them more and more each year.''
</P>
<P>
   The simple life of walking, working and sleeping with dogs got
complicated when the children arrived and assumed center stage. In
the couple's private quarters, the larger-than-life Polaroids on
the walls are all Atlas and Lola, not the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   At nursery school, when the children were asked if they had pets
at home, Atlas said he did not. His favorite stuffed toy is a cat.
When his father told a separation-anxiety story about the dogs'
howls being audible all the way across the lake in Maine, Atlas
added with the daggerlike clarity of childhood: ``That's because
you were with me, and they like you.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Atlas doesn't like the dogs on his bed because they make it hot.
Lola treats them like plush dolls, sitting between their paws to
eat a snack and flinging herself on them with abandon. ``Lola is
more sensuously involved with the dogs,'' Wegman said.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Wegman clearly relishes the mundane tasks of dog care, brushing
and shampooing his dogs himself. But does he let them lick his
face? He reacted with revulsion. ``They have so many germs!'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs may appear at Barnes &AMP; Noble book signings, on ``Sesame
Street'' and at the Brooklyn Academy of Music, but, Wegman
contends, ``I don't parade them around as special. Even though I
dress them up, I know they're animals.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Their life with dogs is a kind of Zen art of appreciation. Ms.
Burgin spoke of how the dogs' delight at waking up and ``lying in a
piece of sunlight'' was contagious. Wegman said he didn't mind
giving them six walks a day (or having an employee do it) because
``they've given so much to me,'' adding: ``They are heartbreakingly
good.''
</P>
<P>
   And time is relatively short. ``Bill knows the clock is
ticking,'' Ms. Burgin said. ``Both Man Ray and Fay were taken away
before their time. He wants to work as much as possible while he
still has them.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Batty and Chippy had lumps (benign, it turned out)
removed from their legs. The thought of losing his dogs triggered
an existential moment: ``It really upset me when Man Ray died,'' he
said. ``I lived alone then, and it was just so quiet. The whole
idea of the door became meaningless. It didn't matter if I went out
or came in.''
</P>
<P>
   As he got up to take the dogs out for yet another walk, he
added, ``I just love working with them, though it's not as often as
people think, maybe one week out of the month. Most of the time
they're just pets.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Wegman needed to fill a role in a photo shoot, he had
no qualms about stopping a walker out with a dog. In the coming
book ``Surprise Party!'' the punch line arrives dressed as a pizza
man with eerie human hands. It's Jake, a yellow Labrador.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
