<HEADER>
A9166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOKYO-AIRPORT-FARMERS     06-09 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOKYO-AIRPORT-FARMERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION OF TOKYO'S TROUBLED AIRPORT IS STALLED BY FARMERS'
PROTESTS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(fb) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NARITA, Japan _ When he feeds his chickens or tends his
eggplants beside the huge jumbo jets at Narita International
Airport, Shoji Shimamura seems a puny, Quixotic figure, with all
the chance of victory of a mosquito challenging an elephant.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the water here must breed extraordinary mosquitoes.
Shimamura and a handful of other farmers have lately scored yet
another triumph over the elephant, delaying expansion of Narita and
adding to its reputation as one of the world's most catastrophic
airports.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of Shimamura's battle is that greater Tokyo _ the
world's largest metropolitan area, with some 35 million people
living within 40 miles of the Imperial Palace _ still has an
international airport with just a single runway. And it is an
airport, with its barbed wire, riot police and guard towers, that
on the outside has the ambiance of a prison.
</P>
<P>
   The feuding over Narita has been going on for 34 years so far,
and riots at the site in the 1970s left five people dead and 8,000
hurt. Partly because of that grim history, there is far more
airplane exhaust in the air than understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're threatening that planes will fly right over my
house here,'' Shimamura said bitterly, as he sat at his kitchen
table after his evening chores. ``So isn't it natural for me to be
stronger in my resistance than ever, for me to be even more against
the airport than ever?''
</P>
<P>
   There may also be some larger lessons hiding among Shimamura's
eggplants. Shimamura's ability to hold up a vast project like
Narita, at incalculable economic costs for Japan, underscores the
difficulties that the Japanese political process has in creating
losers.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese society has been outstanding in sharing losses, in
cutting benefits equally to get through hard times. But it has not
been as good at picking out a few people to hurl out of the
lifeboat so that the others can survive, and these days there is a
growing conviction in Japan that this is what is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Many argue that to revive its economy, Japan needs a brutal
industrial restructuring that will slash employees at big companies
and end protections that keep inefficient businesses alive. Yet the
story of Narita Airport underscores that just because consensus is
highly valued in Japan does not mean that it is easily achieved,
and that chaos can erupt when change is instituted without
consensus.
</P>
<P>
   The airport feuding erupted when government officials announced
in 1965 that they would build a three-runway airport at Narita, a
bit more than an hour's drive from Tokyo. The announcement would
have been normal enough in America, but in Japan it was seen as
arrogant and high-handed. Officials were expected to consult first
with local farmers, asking them for cooperation and spending months
soliciting their views.
</P>
<P>
   So the angry farmers refused to cooperate, and the government
then compounded their anger by trying to seize the land. Leftist
students backed the farmers, and the resulting riots delayed the
opening of the airport until 1978. Even then, it had just a single
runway, and security costs have helped make landing fees and air
shipping bills some of the most expensive in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, with just one runway, there is a desperate shortage of
landing slots. Airlines that have rights at Narita have been able
to charge relatively high fares because they face limited
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to get a second runway in place,''
Yoshijiro Hirayama, a vice president of Narita's airport authority,
said with a sigh. ``Japan is co-hosting the World Cup soccer
matches in 2002, and we'll have so many visitors that it's very
important that we have a second runway in place by then.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, Hirayama and other officials have
changed tactics, emphasizing conciliation and dialogue. They have
pledged not to use force and, publicly at least, they put on sweet
smiles when speaking of farmers like Shimamura.
</P>
<P>
   Charm seems to have worked better than bulldozers, and airport
officials are winning the public relations war. Some 260,000 people
have signed a petition in favor of building a second runway, and
many of the farmers have agreed to sell out.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Shimamura's three acres still sit squarely
in the path of the planned 8,200-foot second runway, and he refuses
to budge. In fact, he refuses even to talk to the airport
officials.
</P>
<P>
   So last month, Narita officials gave up their plan of having
that runway in place by March 2001. Instead, they are talking about
building a 7,200-foot second runway by 2002, dodging the property
of Shimamura and one of his equally obstinate neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that even the shorter runway would include a tiny
parcel that is 1/82nd owned by an opponent of the airport, Shohei
Horikoshi. He declined to discuss his plans, but he may be able to
use his fractional share _ the equivalent of a few clods of dirt _
to block the runway.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, a 7,200-foot runway is too short for jumbo jets,
and 90 percent of the flights to Narita now use jumbo jets. Still,
the airport authority says that the jumbo jets can continue to use
the original runway, and additional flights can use smaller planes
on the second runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is possible to make it work,'' said Keita Arakaki,
a manager at the airport authority.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd that in a society like Japan that so treasures
harmony a handful of farmers should block what seems to be
overwhelming public approval of the airport expansion. But to
farmers like Shimamura, the breach of propriety came from the
government's side, and everything has flowed from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the difference between the Japanese people and the
Japanese government,'' Shimamura's wife, Fujiko, fumed. ``Ordinary
people apologize to each other all the time and are very polite and
considerate. We all try to live in harmony. But the government has
all the power and it uses it to try to get its way. And that's the
fundamental problem here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
