<HEADER>
A9167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRAFT-EMPIRE-ART-NYTR     06-09 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAFT-EMPIRE-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING AN EMPIRE ON TACKY GLUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RON TRUJILLO Santa Barbara News-Press   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUELLTON, Calif. _ Entrepreneur Aleene Jackson has always been a
crafty businesswoman, looking for any opportunity to peddle her
work.
</P>
<P>
   From the first few years of television in the early 1950s to the
fast-growing Internet today, Jackson has become a multimedia master
_ educating and entertaining crafters for more than 50 years. The
soon-to-be 75-year-old is far from slowing down. She has a national
cable TV program, a monthly magazine, how-to books and more than
500 products sharing retail shelf space in thousands of stores in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should do whatever your passion is,'' said Jackson,
founder of Aleene's Creative Living in Buellton.
</P>
<P>
   Crafts are Jackson's passion. They also provide her livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   A one-time florist in the 1940s, Jackson created a
multimillion-dollar operation with easy-to-use products, from her
best-known Tacky Glue to the modern and out-of-the-ordinary
Boxmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something for every age,'' said Jackson, who's been
featured in Life magazine and honored as the craft industry's
leading promoter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just affordable, simple stuff,'' said Tony Hershman,
Jackson's son and chief executive officer of Aleene's Creative
Living. ``We really see ourselves more as delivering a lifestyle to
women.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's far-reaching objective is helping manufacturers
lure shoppers and thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crafters are probably the most dedicated consumers you can
imagine, but we have to go after different markets,'' said
Hershman, who introduced the magazine Aleene's Craft Club _ at $12
a month an issue _ and the Internet site (www.aleenes.com) during
the past several years. ``Aleene's Creative Living'' has evolved
into a one-hour television program every weekday. ``That younger
consumer who is not a crafter right now, you have to find them
through other means. We've already missed the Generation Xers.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a battle cry industrywide, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Though four of every five households have crafters, spending has
stalled. The crafting industry's revenue increased from $7.8
billion in 1994 to $10.9 billion in 1996, before falling to $10.4
billion last year. It's far from a drastic drop, but an issue
nonetheless, industry leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crafting is not something people have to do,'' said Cynthia
Gould, spokeswoman for national retailer Michaels Stores. ``We have
to create projects that are aware of the time constraints on
people. When you see the ebbs and flows, crafting is a leisure-time
activity _ and we compete for time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershman and Jackson agree, saying their company's crafts have
become easier and faster.
</P>
<P>
   The company's craft show airs at noon weekdays on The Nashville
Network, rivaling talk shows and soap operas during the time slot.
The program's ``very homey, very comfortable'' approach is the key
to its success, said Brian Hughes, vice president of programming
for TNN in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they can invite any of us over for dinner,'' said
energetic co-host Katheryn Bieber about viewers, during a break in
the daily eight-hour tapings in a small studio in Buellton.
``There's nothing special about any of us. We're just real people
who love to craft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just simple how-tos that don't exclude anyone,'' said
Hughes, who has watched the program evolve from one day a week in
1990 into every weekday. ``It incorporates every age group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aleene's Creative Living'' attracts about 250,000 viewers
daily, with many buying crafts featured on the program. The
company's call center handles 2,000 to 3,000 customers daily, with
most received during or immediately after the program, said
Hershman, adding the average call generates about $35 in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Call-center employees are ``very suggestive sellers, but not too
aggressive,'' Hershman said. The employees will answer any question
about crafts from people who phone in. The company also offers a
100 percent guarantee _ once refunding money for about 45,000 tubes
of glue that turned slightly yellow and replacing a $10,000 wedding
gown affected by the problem. Orders are shipped from a Chicago
warehouse within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But Aleene Jackson's beloved craft company has hit rough
stitches. The company's cost-saving and expansion effort of moving
manufacturing operations to Mexico became a nightmare in the early
1990s. Employees stole endless items, which led to body checks and
security guards to watch workers. A five-year contract forced the
company to remain in Mexico, at a loss of $500,000, and eventually
it filed for bankruptcy protection in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The move to Mexico was a mistake, Jackson said. She had earlier
moved the family-owned company from the Los Angeles area to
Buellton in 1975. But Santa Barbara County's strict growth control
led to the shift to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't realize it was hemorrhaging money until it was too
late,'' she said about Mexico
</P>
<P>
   The company _ which had attorneys' fees of $1.5 million from the
bankruptcy _ laid off local employees and limited its one-time
1,000 items to a more manageable 100 products in order to survive.
Almost 50 of Aleene's customers approved advancing $500,000 to
continue the operations.
</P>
<P>
   The changes paid off. Now, Aleene's Creative Living _ a
130-employee operation, the third-largest employer in the Santa
Ynez Valley _ is booming, with more than 500 products and a
multimedia marketing outlook. The company completed its
debt-repayment program in March.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Barbara News-Press in Santa Barbara, Calif., is part
of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
