<HEADER>
A9181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY10-COX     06-09 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KASICH OFFERS PLAN TO REFORM SOCIAL SECURITY
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential candidate John Kasich
became the latest GOP hopeful to unveil a Social Security reform
plan Wednesday, suggesting a cut in benefits for today's baby
boomers but higher returns for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Social Security is reformed, the program will not have
enough money to fully pay benefits after 2034.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich said his plan offered the promise of no tax increases and
no reduction of benefits to those currently 55 or older. He would
reduce the initial payment for those under 54 by pegging the
formula that is used for computing benefits to prices rather than
wages.
</P>
<P>
   The formula shift would begin to be noticed after 2010. By 2020,
the change would mean the average starting benefit would be $23,532
a year instead of $27,408. By 2070, about when a child born now
would begin receiving benefits, the starting payment would be
$118,368 under Kasich's plan compared to $213,840 under current
law.
</P>
<P>
   To offset the lower starting benefit, Kasich would allow workers
to voluntarily invest a portion of their payroll tax in private
investment accounts. The amount invested would be 3.5 percent for
those making up to $30,000, 2.5 percent for those making up to
$72,600, and 1 percent for those making more.
</P>
<P>
   For every dollar invested in private accounts, Social Security
benefits would be cut by 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich predicted that the average 45-year-old would see a
reduction in benefits of about 1.7 percent, but the average
25-year-old would see a boost of about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GOP candidates Steve Forbes and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., have
previously offered Social Security reform plans.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the House Ways and Means Committee began a
two-day hearing on various proposals to change the federal
retirement system. The proposals covered a variety of options, but
had one element in common: almost all of them would use a portion
of general revenue to pay for or augment Social Security benefits.
Since the program began in 1935, benefits have been financed solely
through payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is expected to conclude Thursday with an examination
of the plan offered by two of the panel's Republican leaders, Reps.
Bill Archer of Texas and E. Clay Shaw Jr. of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
