<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9184 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-AUCTION-AZR &LR;      06-09 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-AUCTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB AUCTION NETS SKY-HIGH PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Some people say that music is priceless. But when it
comes to '80s country queen Sylvia, there is a price: $280, to be
exact.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much Joe Martin paid last week for a single copy of
Sylvia's 1983 CD ``Snapshot.'' The long-out-of-print disc was up
for grabs on the Internet auction site eBay (www.ebay.com) and
soared to an extremely rare, very lofty perch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's blowing me away,'' said Rick Lasseter, the lucky soul who
was selling the disc. ``I had several Sylvia CDs last fall, and
they all sold for like $35 or $40. I knew ``Snapshot'' was the
rarest one, but I had no idea how rare.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet-auction craze has sparked some interesting CD
bidding wars on eBay. Liza Minnelli's ``Live at the Olympia'' is
going for $45. ``Walking in the Shadow of the Big Man'' by
Guadalcanal Diary (remember them?) is up to $41.67. A Ricky Martin
disc is hovering at the $90 mark, but that one boasts an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   All impressive, but none come close to the disc by one-named
wonder Sylvia _ for which Lasseter originally paid $6.99 at a
used-CD store.
</P>
<P>
   Before you get mad at the Texas entrepreneur, he makes some good
points. First of all, if people are willing to pay that much, he
would be foolish to stop them. Secondly, he's doing customers a
service by locating these deleted discs in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't have time to go out and look for this
stuff,'' he said. ``They want something and they don't want to
bother looking through pawn shops and swap markets, so that's what
I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a 33-year-old graphic designer from Norfolk, Va., didn't
mind parting with the cash, though this is the first time he ever
put so much down for one disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the first country artist I really liked,'' he said.
``There's a sentimental attachment there. I've got a buddy laughing
at me for buying it, but you drop your money where you drop it.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been looking for the disc ``off and on'' for a couple of
years. He'd never even bought anything from eBay before until the
Sylvia disc popped up. His first bid was $60, then he got locked
into a battle with another eBay-er and things escalated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of crazy, but you get into that auction mentality,''
he admits. ``But it's a whole collector thing. And I've got a
sentimental spot for Sylvia _ kind of a geeky fan thing, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   I can relate. I was in the ``Snapshot'' bidding war, but got
blown away early on. As with Martin, Sylvia was one of those voices
from high school that I always enjoyed hearing. She wasn't the
greatest singer who ever lived, but she had a quality that was
quite endearing.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like it would be odd to be at the center of this
attention. But Sylvia herself, who lives in Nashville and recently
put out a terrific folk-flavored album, ``The Real Story''
(www.songs.com/Sylvia), takes it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one level, I'm flattered,'' said the singer from her
Nashville home. ``But if someone is willing to pay that price,
maybe RCA (her old label) should think about putting it back in
print.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she gets letters every week asking where people can
find her '80s hits _ she had 20 of 'em, making the fresh-scrubbed
beauty the Faith Hill of her day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I think it's really sweet,'' she said. ``I'm trying
to think of who I would spend $280 on a CD for, and I can't think
of anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The singer, who recently auditioned for a role in the Broadway
musical ``The Civil War,'' thought it was (begin ital) really (end
ital) sweet. She even sent Martin a little thank-you e-mail, so
she's pretty sweet herself.
</P>
<P>
   Since she was on the phone anyway, I figured I'd ask: Any extra
copies of ``Snapshot'' lying around the house she'd be willing to
part with?
</P>
<P>
   ``I only have one or two copies of each CD,'' she said with a
laugh. ``I think my mom has one of each, and my brother might have
one, too. They really are hard to find.''
</P>
<P>
   Rats. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached randy.cordova(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
