 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATES
 &HT;    Eds: Adds: KOSOVO-RETURN, GORE-SENATORS, KOSOVO-SPYPLANE;
 &HT;    Deletes: KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, MICROSOFT
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, June 9,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ While the bombing of
Serb-dominated Yugoslavia continues, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright has apparently worked out an agreement in Bonn with her
counterparts in the G-7 + Russia for a U.N. resolution. Developing.
(Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SPYPLANE _ MIRKOVICI, Macedonia _ In still another
mysterious twist to the Balkans crisis, Macedonian police on
Tuesday displayed a sophisticated Israeli-made spy plane that they
had seized on a montainside near the Kosovo border from seven
Israeli technicians who said they filming for an Israeli TV
network. Developing. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RETURN _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ The world's aid agencies are
making plans to rush food into Kosovo when the peace agreement
takes hold, but fear that returning refugees may face unforseen
hazards such as booby traps set inside houses by fleeing Serbs. For
instance, the Baltimore-based Catholic Relief has 40 trucks ready
to roll, with enough food to feed about 50,000 internally displaced
Kosovar refugees. The UN's World Food Program is ready to supply
1,000 metric tons of food a day and will set up mobile bakeries and
mobile warehouses to keep the food coming. Developing.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA _ TIRANA, Albania _ The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army,
which has been fighting Serb troops inside Kosovo province, said
Tuesday that it will abide by NATO orders to stop shooting Serbs.
The KLA also said the Serbs have used chemical weapons in recent
days and claim Serbs are hauling truckloads of Kosovar Albanian
bodies for reburial and cremation. They have photos and witnesses
and are turning info over to the Yugolsav War Crimes Tribunal at
The Hague. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 20. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Now that the refugees
will be stuck in Macedonia even longer, is the tension that was
building between them and the locals in danger of building again?
Developing. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   SERB-REFUGEES _ The bombing in Serbia and Kosovo has strained an
already edgy situation in nearby Bosnia-Herzegovina. 20,000
Kosovars are seeking refuge in and around Sarajevo being housed in
accomodations ranging from rustic U.N. camps to their own hastily
rented apartments. Thousands of Serb refugees are crowding into the
nearby Republika Srpska _ the ethnic Serbian-half of Bosnia _
having fled Serbia from the bombing or still homeless after being
driven out of Croatia over the last five years. (Bebbington, Dayton
Daily News). 45.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GUNDEAL _ WASHINGTON _ One percent of the nation's gun dealers
sold nearly half of the guns used in crime last year and many of
those businesses show up year after year as major sources of crime
weapons, according to a new study of federal firearms data. The
study conducted by the office of Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y.,
marks a new phase of a growing effort to hold firearms dealers
responsible for gun violence. Georgia ranks high on the list as a
supplier of guns used in crime. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-VIOLENCE _ WASHINGTON _House Republican leaders decide not
to send juvenile crime bill to Henry Hyde's House Judiciary
Committee tomorrow, but to send it directly to the House floor next
week. The legislation would restrict youth access to video games,
movies and other items containing violent and sexually explicit
material and would require the music industry to provide stores
with copies of song lyrics as a means of allowing adults to keep
questionable products from their children. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GORE-SENATORS _ WASHINGTON _ A group of former senators endorses
Vice President Al Gore's presidential candidacy. (Montgomery, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MOVIES _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and theater
owners announce a policy that will require viewers of R-rated movie
to show photo identification to prove they are 17. (Shepard, Cox
News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   STUN-BELTS _ WASHINGTON _ Retired police detective Frank Serpico
joins the daughter of Muhammad Ali at an Amnesty International news
conference to release a new report on the stun belt, a widely used
law enforcement device that Amnesty says is ``potentially lethal to
people with heart ailments, epilepsy or on tranquilizers.'' (Hill,
Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-CARE _ WASHINGTON _ Child care advocates say that a report
they'll release Tuesday afternoon, endorsed by Education Secretary
Richard Riley, will show that ``quality'' child care helps kids in
early learning and school readiness. Past studies by others have
been ambiguous. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/CHILD-CARE-TIPS _ Child care information tips. (Cox News
Service).
</P>
