<HEADER>
A9186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANNIBAL-BOOK-REVIEW-     06-09 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANNIBAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HANNIBAL': LECTER RETURNS, AND ONE OF HIS VICTIMS WANTS REVENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Special Agent Clarice Starling of the FBI is in trouble at the
start of ``Hannibal,'' Thomas Harris' ghoulish sequel to his two
previous crime thrillers, ``Red Dragon'' and the superb ``Silence
of the Lambs,'' featuring the murderous psychoanalyst Hannibal (the
Cannibal) Lecter.
</P>
<P>
   Long resented by some of her superiors for her success, Starling
now has made herself vulnerable by taking part in a botched drug
raid and shooting to death a mother with a baby in her arms,
resulting in negative publicity even though the woman shot at
Starling first with a Mac-10 she was hiding behind her baby. (The
Guinness Book of World Records is preparing to list Starling as
``having killed more criminals than any other female law
enforcement officer in United States history.'')
</P>
<P>
   But then Harris' plot twists for the first of many times. On the
brink of being disciplined, Starling is suddenly reassigned to the
behavioral science section of the FBI Academy at Quantico, Va.,
where as a student volunteer she helped track down Jame Gumb, one
of the serial killers in ``The Silence of the Lambs.'' Her indirect
benefactor turns out to be no less than Lecter, who seems to have
resurfaced in Brazil. Among her first assignments is to interview
one Mason Verger, the heir to a meat-packing fortune who is the
only one of Lecter's victims to have survived.
</P>
<P>
   Not that what follows isn't thoroughly suspenseful. The horribly
mutilated Verger only pretends to cooperate with Starling. He
really intends to capture and punish Lecter himself, and to use
Starling as his bait to that end. The cat-and-cat game that follows
is cleverly worked out with every lethal swipe of a paw.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, so great is the fund of fascination with Lecter built
up in Harris' previous novels _ for his being a superman embodying
absolute yet comprehensible evil, and for his being so brilliantly
brought to life on screen by Anthony Hopkins _ that almost nothing
can dissipate his malign attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Hannibal'' simply lacks the compact power of the previous
books. For one thing, Harris seems determined to top himself in
monstrosity at any and all cost. What Lecter has done to Verger is
to get him high on methamphetamines and ``acid'' and then suggest
that Verger cut off his own face and feed it to his dogs (albeit
for being a sex molester and sadistic tormenter of children).
Instead of skin, vessels have been grafted ``over the bones of his
face to feed it blood; their regular dilation was like worms
swallowing.'' The result shades toward the stuff of comic books.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the character of Lecter is gradually compromised. At
first he grows as a figure of pure and brilliant evil, like Satan
in the Book of Job, ``going to and fro in the earth and walking up
and down in it,'' and, like some ancient orator, exploring the
spacious ``memory palace'' of his mind, a mnemonic system ``built
according to the rules discovered by Simonides of Ceos and
elaborated by Cicero 400 years later.''
</P>
<P>
   But then slowly Lecter acquires a biographical background: likes
and dislikes, sexual preferences, parents, ancestors, a birthplace,
a childhood and even a traumatic psychology that incidentally
explains his complex attitudes toward Starling. This seems to
contradict everything he stood for earlier, which he articulated
succinctly to Starling at one point in ``The Silence of the
Lambs'': ``Nothing happened to me, Officer Starling,'' he tells her
when she challenges him to understand himself. `` &UR; I &LR;  happened. You
can't reduce me to a set of influences. . . . Typhoid and swans _
it all comes from the same place.''
</P>
<P>
   Reduced to a set of influences in ``Hannibal,'' Lecter shrinks
to less than a man. Even his elegant tastes seem trivialized. What
seemed passionate and austere in him when pursued in the starkness
of prison is reduced to effeteness when indulged in freedom.
Despite his preference for Scarlatti and Bach's ``Goldberg''
Variations, one expects to hear in the background Bach's ``Toccata
and Fugue in D minor,'' a staple of horror films, as the doctor
swirls his brandy in a chimney ballon purchased at Christofle.
</P>
<P>
   Even Harris' prose comes a cropper as the overwrought plot
progresses. Scene-setting passages become the shorthand of a
screenplay. (``Morning, and the armored concrete cage of the Hoover
Building brooding under a milky overcast.'') Sentences grow
Teutonically clunky. (``Came sobs of apprehension and pleas, the
scream building, and ahead of Starling, beyond the fence, she heard
movement through brush . . .'') Grammar lapses. (``From the clarity
of his speech, Dr. Lecter may have been awake for some time.'')
Harris even forgets a character's name, changing Fredrica Bimmel,
one of Jame Gumb's victims, to Fredericka.
</P>
<P>
   True, ``Hannibal'' remains full of wonderful touches, typical of
Harris' grasp of arcane detail. ``We were talking about inherited,
hardwired behavior,'' Barney, one of Lecter's attendants at the
Baltimore State Hospital for the Criminally Insane, tells Starling
when she asks what Lecter thought of her. ``He was using genetics
in roller pigeons as an example. They go way up in the air and roll
over and over backwards in a display, falling toward the ground.
There are shallow rollers and deep rollers. You can't breed two
deep rollers or the offspring will roll all the way down, crash and
die. What he said was: `Officer Starling is a deep roller, Barney.
We'll hope one of her parents was not.'''
</P>
<P>
   But as Starling rolls deeper and deeper into this tale of
revenge taken over the top, the reader is overcome by revulsion and
incredulity. Late in the novel, Lecter sits in an armchair doing
mathematical calculations. ``The pages are filled with the symbols
of both astrophysics and particle physics,'' the narrative
explains. ``There are repeated efforts with the symbols of string
theory. The few mathematicians who could follow him might say his
equations begin brilliantly and then decline, doomed by wishful
thinking: Dr. Lecter wants time to reverse _ no longer should
increasing entropy mark the direction of time. He wants increasing
order to point the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lecter, the dark prince of chaos, giving away to wishful
thinking, and wanting more order? Lecter being so dumb as to think
if the universe contracted, time would reverse? Bring on the noisy
lambs, then. They might as well be roaring.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HANNIBAL'
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Harris
</P>
<P>
   486 pages. Delacorte Press. $27.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
