<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASE-CLOSING-HNS &LR;      06-09 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASE-CLOSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOT PROGRAM SEEKS TO CURTAIL MILITARY BASE CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Taibl is CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A plan to protect a Texas Air Force base from
budget cuts and possible closure has cleared a crucial hurdle in
the Senate, where a provision included in a defense spending bill
would allow the city of San Antonio to provide services to reduce
the Pentagon's costs.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual proposal San Antonio is offering the Air Force is
being closely watched by other cities that might seek to protect
military facilities that are vulnerable to future base realignment
and closure commissions, commonly referred to as BRACs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can BRAC-proof a base, but what you can do
is put a base on another economic footing. This is a very smart
move,'' Paul Taibl, policy analyst with the Washington-based
Business Executives for National Security, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio Mayor Howard Peak said the proposal that would
affect Brooks Air Force Base ``just makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It presents a whole new way of doing things, cheaper and
better. It's going to work for everybody,'' Peak said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to transform Brooks into a ``city base'' grew out of a
task force the mayor created shortly after Brooks narrowly escaped
the scrutiny of a 1995 base closure commission that ordered nearby
Kelly Air Force Base shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, and Rep. Ciro Rodriguez,
D-Texas, were instrumental in taking the city's ideas and crafting
them into legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The language was tucked into the $265 billion defense spending
bill that was approved by the Senate, 93-4, late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our legislation will reduce the costs and increase the
efficiency of operations at Brooks AFB,'' said Hutchison, who
inserted the measure into the defense bill from the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who represents part San Antonio in the House, said
the Brooks project ``can be the model for operating urban Air Force
bases more efficiently in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I envision Brooks operating as a public-private and
military-civilian research park in a way that makes the base even
more valuable to the Air Force and South Texas,'' said Rodriguez, a
member of the House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   If similar language is not approved by the House, Hutchison
would have to protect the measure when a House-Senate conference
committee crafts a final version of the bill. Hutchison, a member
of the Senate Appropriations Committee, will have a seat on the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation allows the Air Force and Defense Department to
enter into business agreements with San Antonio and local entities
that can provide water, sewer, utilities, fire protectio and road
repair services at lower costs than the military.
</P>
<P>
   Peak said the ``economy of scale'' would allow the city police,
road crews, utilities and network of fire stations to serve Brooks
at a cheaper rate. The Air Force would pay the city for the cost of
services, while saving money by eliminating overhead and purchases
of equipment, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor could not estimate what the Air Force would have to
pay the city or which services it might want.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would let the Air Force lease space at the base to
private companies and ``tenants who can jointly use and help pay
for the unique facilities,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the city is protecting a job base of high-paying,
high-technology research salaries that annually pump roughly $158
million in payroll into the economy, according to figures compiled
by the Greater San Antonio Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, which employs 1,800 civilians and 2,100 military
personnel, does high-tech research for the Air Force, including
studies of the effects of new aircraft on pilots.
</P>
<P>
   And the Air Force published a study this year that paved the way
for the pilot project, calling for the elimination of legal
barriers that have prevented the military branch from entering into
leases and agreements with other public entities and private-sector
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peak said he has heard of the interest of other cities and towns
worried about protecting military installations in an era of
defense cuts and closures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what happened at Kelly,'' Peak said of the decision to
close the aircraft repair depot that was once San Antonio's
largest, single-site employer.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 base closure commission ordered Kelly closed by 2001,
despite arguments from San Antonio that Kelly jobs had created the
city's Hispanic middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, these bases need to be contributing
something,'' Peak said, citing San Antonio's goal to make Brooks
more ``efficient and effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Taibl, whose organization advocates business practices to make
the military more cost effective, said the concept would not
guarantee against closure of a military installation deemed
obsolete by Pentagon accountants.
</P>
<P>
   But having a city as a partner will bring about a ``smoother
transition,'' if the facility is closed and turned over to local
officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
