<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9191 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-CANAL-ART-3TAK     06-09 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-ART-3TAKES-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RITE OF PASSAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  As time nears for U.S. to cede control of the Panama Canal, leaving
it all behind is proving difficult for many Americans whose
livelihoods are linked to the waterway 
 
 
(For release Sunday, June 13) 
(Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Attn: La., Fla.) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE KONKAR STAR, Panama _ ``Dead slow ahead!'' barks
Robert Holden, a pilot on the Panama Canal, as he guides a Greek
freighter through the world's most famous shortcut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead slow ahead!'' echoes Nanidis Spiridon, the fidgety,
chain-smoking Greek captain whose ship, the Konkar Star, is packed
with 57,000 metric tons of yellow corn on a voyage from New Orleans
to Nagoya, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead slow ahead!'' confirms the coxswain, as he follows
Holden's order to cut the ship's engines to minimum speed.
</P>
<P>
   Here on the Panama Canal, Holden, a Massachusetts native who has
worked on the waterway since 1969, is part autocrat, part artist.
</P>
<P>
   His curt instructions set off a chain reaction of bustle and
fuss by the Konkar Star's captain and crew that will allow the ship
to fool nature by floating up and over the isthmus separating the
Atlantic and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   But Holden and the rest of the Zonians, the thousands of
Americans who have lived and worked along the canal for nearly a
century, are a disappearing breed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1977 Panama Canal treaties, the United States must
turn over full control of the waterway to Panama at noon Dec. 31
and close the last of its 10 military bases in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The actions will complete the handover of the U.S.-administered
territory once known as the Canal Zone and will mark the end of the
American Era in Panama, an epoch that began in 1904 when President
Theodore Roosevelt vowed to ``make dirt fly'' by digging a great
trench across the Panamanian isthmus.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``The Path Between the Seas,'' historian David
McCullough writes that Roosevelt viewed the project as ``a mighty
battle in which the national honor was at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm of the former Rough Rider, who led a charge
during the Battle of San Juan Hill in Cuba during the
Spanish-American war of 1898, caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Although thousands of workers, mostly laborers from Caribbean
islands, were killed during the construction process, the Panama
Canal was an unparalleled engineering feat that became a symbol of
the pell-mell rush for progress.
</P>
<P>
   Jungles were tamed, mountains were moved, malaria and yellow
fever were conquered. Nearly as amazing, the mammoth public works
project came in $23 million under budget. The United States spent
$352 million to build it.
</P>
<P>
   When the Panama Canal opened in 1914, the planet seemed to
become smaller. Sea travel from New York to San Francisco was
shortened by 8,000 miles and several months' time, since ships no
longer were forced to sail around Cape Horn in South America.
</P>
<P>
   The canal also helped make the United States a naval power. The
triumph was celebrated on the official Canal Zone seal: ``The Land
Divided _ The World United.''
</P>
<P>
   Panamanian officials predict that the handover of the canal will
be routine. But Holden calls the Panama Canal treaties ``a big
mistake'' and worries that the waterway's new owners will seek
higher profits by cutting back on maintenance, personnel and
training. Until now, the canal has functioned as a break-even
utility, with most of its earnings plowed back into operations and
upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   Since Holden moved to what was then the U.S.-run Panama Canal
Zone 30 years ago, he has married, reared two children and coaxed
more than 2,400 ships safely through the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with it,'' says Holden, moments after the
Konkar Star had been lifted 85 feet by the first set of locks on
the Atlantic side and released into the artificial Gatun Lake.
</P>
<P>
   The length of three football fields, the Konkar Star can stow
the equivalent in weight of 250 Boeing 747s. This floating
leviathan must be shoehorned into the canal's snug-fitting locks
and squeezed through its bottleneck channels. At times, Holden's
margin for error is a matter of inches.
</P>
<P>
   The task is so tricky that the Panama Canal is the only body of
water in the world where, by law, the ship's captain must
temporarily turn over command of his vessel to the pilot _ a leap
of faith that skippers are normally loath to take. Canal pilots
earn up to $160,000 a year, more than the top executive on the
Panama Canal Commission, the joint U.S.-Panamanian agency that runs
the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very demanding pilot's job. In my mind it was the
optimum career for a seagoing person,'' says Holden, a graduate of
the Federal Maritime Academy on Long Island and a Navy veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Because of shifting world trade patterns and competition from
rail lines that haul giant freight containers from seaports to
customers, the canal is no longer the vital strategic link or the
shipping monopoly it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Yet business is booming.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 14,244 ships passed through the waterway, shelling
out a record $545 million in tolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of the world's ships can go through here.
That's amazing for something this old,'' Holden says.
</P>
<P>
   The waterway was so well-designed that it functions almost
exactly the way it did 85 years ago, with many of the original
parts. The canal is built like a Brink's truck but runs like a
Swiss watch, said transit operations director George Markham.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A BIT OF HISTORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the late 1800s, French engineers who were inspired and
cajoled by Ferdinand de Lesseps, the mastermind of Egypt's Suez
Canal, spent 20 years in Panama trying to excavate a sea-level
waterway.
</P>
<P>
   One member of a pickax crew was Paul Gauguin, the French
painter, who described the job in a letter to his wife: ``I have to
dig from 5:30 in the morning to six in the evening, under tropical
sun and rain. At night, I am devoured by mosquitoes.'' Gauguin
lasted a few months, then sailed for Martinique.
</P>
<P>
   De Lesseps' crusade was eventually undone by disease, landslides
and flooding from the mighty Chagres River, which cuts through the
middle of Panama. Then the U.S. government stepped in, paying the
French $40 million for the canal rights and properties and
fomenting Panama's revolt from Colombia. After the Panamanians
gained independence, the Americans took over the canal's
construction in 1904.
</P>
<P>
   Following much debate, they settled on a lock-and-dam system to
lift vessels, step by step, up and over the isthmus, then lower
them back to sea level. One of their models was the Soo Locks, the
gateway between Lake Superior and Lake Huron that was, at the time,
the world's most heavily traveled lock canal.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, U.S. planners were determined to harness the
power of the Chagres River, which was considered ``the lion in the
path'' of the waterway. By damming the Chagres and flooding the
jungle, they formed a massive reservoir to serve as a kind of water
bridge for nearly half of the canal's route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, the river would become the lifeblood of the system,
rather than its mortal enemy,'' writes historian McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   The result is Gatun Lake, which covers 163 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   To Holden, the lake is the easiest and safest part of the canal
transit, and he keeps the Konkar Star churning through its
whitecaps and toward the Pacific Ocean at a steady 10 knots per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   But the pilot must stick to a tight schedule. It takes about
nine hours to cross the 50-milelong canal, and flotillas of
tankers, container ships and cruise liners wait at both entrances
for the green light to begin their journeys. A 15-minute delay by
Holden could translate into a four-hour wait for a crew three ships
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   With its pilots, traffic controllers, radar, cargo handlers,
fueling stations and 24-hour operations, the Panama Canal can seem
like a sprawling, congested international airport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The threat of accidents is constant. The morning Holden boards
the Konkar Star, a Panama City newspaper carries a front-page story
about a ship that had collided with a canal dredge.
</P>
<P>
   Some vessels carry nuclear waste in their holds. Others are what
shippers call ``drugstore tankers,'' vessels packed with liquid
propane, ammonia and other chemicals. A fully loaded petroleum
tanker contains more potential energy than the atomic bomb that
detonated over Hiroshima in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, ships don't have brakes and may require 10 minutes
to stop by reversing the engines, calling in tugboats or, as a last
resort, dragging their anchors. On the high seas, captains like to
stay miles away from other vessels. On the Panama Canal, the leeway
can be a few hundred feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's four or five hours of boredom followed by five minutes of
sheer terror,'' says Holden, who is perched on a red vinyl stool in
the Konkar Star's wheelhouse and wearing sunglasses and a black
baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   Holden always gives passing ships the widest possible berth. He
learned that lesson a decade ago when an oncoming vessel carrying
automobiles lost power and slammed into Holden's vessel, ripping a
200-foot hole in the hull.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of a passing ship, he says, ``You have to bend to her,
because she's not going to bend to you.''
</P>
<P>
   From day one, Panama Canal pilots are indoctrinated with safety
regulations. They train and work for eight years on smaller vessels
before earning ``senior pilot'' status, which allows them to handle
so-called ``panamax'' ships, such as the Konkar Star. These are the
largest ships that can fit through the canal's locks.
</P>
<P>
   Training includes tests in a multimillion-dollar pilot
simulator, which re-creates the conditions inside a ship's
wheelhouse during a transit. By twisting a few knobs, technicians
can add rainstorms, oncoming tankers and a shifting floor. It's so
realistic that students in the simulator, which is located near the
canal, have become seasick and vomited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all the dynamics of real life,'' says David Constable,
a pilot-training coordinator. ``Over here is the place to make a
mistake, not in the canal.''
</P>
<P>
   Delays may be frowned upon, but, in the name of safe passage,
they are unavoidable. At the Panama Canal pilots union hall,
someone has posted a sign reminding members: ``Your schedule is
more flexible than your ship.''
</P>
<P>
   In his training manual, Markham, the transit operations
director, warns rookies against getting self-righteous about their
ship's course with this verse by an anonymous scribe:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the grave of Mike O'Day,
</P>
<P>
   Who died maintaining his right of way.
</P>
<P>
   His right was clear, his will was strong,
</P>
<P>
   But he's just as dead as if he'd been wrong.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A DANGEROUS JOURNEY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Gatun Lake, the Konkar Star enters a narrow ribbon of
water.
</P>
<P>
   This 8-mile passageway is known as the Gaillard Cut, but those
who built it called it Hell's Gorge. Their job amounted to removing
a tropical mountain of rock, shale and mud. It took seven years and
millions of pounds of dynamite to complete the task. Avalanches and
accidental explosions killed hundreds of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flesh of men flew in the air like birds many days,''
according to a West Indian laborer quoted by McCullough in ``The
Path Between the Seas.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where the sensation of the equatorial wilderness being
rolled back is the strongest, where the canal resembles an immense,
man-made culvert.
</P>
<P>
   Dirt hills rise sharply out of the water and tower over the
ship. Due to landslides and erosion, bulldozers, dredges and
sappers work continuously to keep the cut more than 50 feet deep,
which allows the passage of the panamax ships. The nearly nonstop
excavations have stained the canal's sparkling blue-green water a
chalky gray.
</P>
<P>
   The trip through the cut is a squeeze for the Konkar Star, but
finessing the vessel into the canal's three sets of locks seems
almost impossible. The ship is 106 feet wide; lock chambers are
just 110 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like trying to force an olive into a full wine bottle
without spilling,'' Holden says.
</P>
<P>
   On this transit, the chore of entering the canal's second set of
locks will be left to another pilot, because Holden is ready for a
breather. It's 1 p.m., and he's been up since 3 a.m., sipping
coffee all the while to stay alert. He drinks 12 to 14 cups a day.
</P>
<P>
   Panamax vessels require two pilots on board during a voyage
through the canal, and Holden is relieved by Jose Lin Young, a
30-something Panamanian outfitted in pressed Tommy Hilfiger khaki.
Holden trots down the metal staircase to the officers' mess, which
is decorated with Greek tourism posters, and digs into a plate of
spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   As Young guides the Konkar Star into the Pedro Miguel locks,
where the ship will begin its descent to sea level, Spiridon, the
Greek captain, inhales deeply on a Dunhill cigarette and studies
the new pilot's every move.
</P>
<P>
   After a ship moves into a lock, the water beneath the vessel is
forced out, creating pressures and currents that can push the ship
off course. Stability is provided by tugboats, which nudge the
stern of the Konkar Star, and by land-based locomotives with cables
that are attached to the port and starboard sides of the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how close the ship is to the lock wall, Holden, who has
returned to the wheelhouse to watch the ship's progress, looks down
and replies: ``Right now? About 9 inches.``
</P>
<P>
   But Young makes it in, and the lock gates close behind the ship.
As water drains from the chamber, the Konkar Star slowly sinks 31
feet. By the time the ship reaches the Pacific, 52 million gallons
of fresh water will have been flushed from the canal out to sea _
the equivalent of a two-day water supply for a large city.
</P>
<P>
   When the front gate opens, the Konkar Star struggles forward. As
the locomotives strain, the port side of the ship touches the lock
wall, making a low-pitched grinding sound. Gray debris scraped off
the lock flies into the air and lands on the ship's deck.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting instructions to his mostly Filipino crew, Spiridon
races down five flights of stairs to inspect the damage. It's
impossible to see the scrape from the deck, so he climbs down a
rope ladder on the side of the ship to a tugboat waiting below.
</P>
<P>
   With both vessels moving through the canal, the portly Spiridon
balances on the deck of the tug and rubs his hands over the
20-foot-long scratch above the ship's waterline. The paint is gone,
but there appears to be no structural damage.
</P>
<P>
   After the inspection, Spiridon demands to be returned to his
ship immediately, even though the tug captain had planned to stop
briefly at a nearby wharf first. ``I don't want to leave this pilot
alone!'' Spiridon shouts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Later, after the emotion of the moment ebbs, Spiridon explains
that maritime veterans are uneasy about the exodus of the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the canal's remaining U.S. pilots will retire this
year, including Holden, who plans to move to Palm Harbor, Fla., at
year's end. The pilots union says that, to make up for the loss,
the incoming canal officials may cut back on training requirements
for senior pilots and reduce the number of pilots required aboard
panamax ships from two to one.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the captains? They are having a heart attack,''
Spiridon says in heavily accented English. ``They don't prepare the
new pilots very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Young shares some of these concerns. But he points out that more
than 200 of the current 275 canal pilots are Panamanians. That is
the highest number since the canal opened. Yet last year, just 30
serious accidents occurred, the lowest number since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes Morris Garcia, a spokeswoman for the Panama Canal
Commission, insists that the transition will be smooth. But she
admits that Panama bears the burden of proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can say it until we're blue in the face,'' she said. ``But
people won't believe it until they see it.''
</P>
<P>
   After clearing the final set of locks, the Konkar Star steams
into the Port of Balboa on the Pacific at dusk. Because of Panama's
slender, twisting shape, the area around Balboa is the only spot on
the globe where the sun rises over the Pacific and sets on the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   As he bids farewell to the Konkar Star and hops aboard a tugboat
for the wharf, Holden is feeling a bit turned-around himself. He
will try to adapt to retirement in Florida, but his heart is
anchored in the former Canal Zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very comfortable life. People thought of it as a
Utopia,'' says Holden, who plays tennis and bridge with other
Zonians in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, their way of life is ending. Panamanians are taking over
the jobs once held by the Zonians, and the Panamanian government is
taking over their housing. Just a handful of Americans will be
rehired by the incoming Canal Authority, and their jobs will be
temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Americans have already left Panama. Others are
making reservations for the journey back to the United States,
though a few have decided to settle in Panama. Families must leave
by mid-August if they want the U.S. government to pay their moving
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Americans' neat, cinderblock duplexes are already
vacant. Boats with ``for sale'' signs line the streets. Every
weekend, dozens of garage sales are held. Banks, churches and
baseball leagues have all shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Balboa High School, the main school for Zonians, graduated its
final senior class May 15 and will soon become Panama's Foreign
Ministry building.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving it all behind is proving difficult. The other day, a
Zonian who was clearly drunk was so bitter that he refused to speak
with a reporter. Nearby, in the sleepy, palm-lined American
community of Cardenas, tensions are on the rise as families are
uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is all stressed out,'' says Geri Foster, a former
teacher and the wife of a canal pilot who has lived in Panama since
1966. ``You're talking about a whole community being displaced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five years ago, it never seemed like this was going to
happen,'' says Foster, shaking her head. ``But here we are. It went
by awfully fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of an era has many Americans waxing nostalgic.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Wainio, a former canal commission official, calls the
former Canal Zone an example of Plato's idea of the benevolent
dictatorship. The zone was a government creation in which U.S.
bureaucrats managed everything from canal traffic to garbage
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Duffus, 47, a dredge operator who retired a few months ago
and is preparing to pull out, says: ``It was a socialist
atmosphere. We had a government hospital. We saw government
doctors. We had a company store.''
</P>
<P>
   Markham, the canal's transit operations director, who is moving
to Florida later this month, agrees. ``When I came down here,'' he
says, ``we had our own schools, fire department, health clinics,
furniture stores and post office.''
</P>
<P>
   In the zone, many Americans maintain, there was no poverty
because everyone had a job.
</P>
<P>
   As he drank a bottle of beer by a boathouse on the edge of the
canal, a former Canal Zone police officer remembers that when he
was on patrol, there was little to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little larceny, a little burglary. Drugs were not
prevalent. Cocaine was nonexistent,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls indicate that most Panamanians wish the Americans
would stay put. They fear that the national economy will suffer
once the U.S. government and the American residents leave. But
others are delighted to see the Canal Zone disappear after more
than nine decades.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
END OF AN ERA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 1903 treaty between the United States and Panama established
the Canal Zone as a 10-mile-wide strip of land hugging the proposed
canal route that was to be controlled by the United States ``in
perpetuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington was also granted the right to expropriate other lands
required for the construction and operation of the waterway. Such
one-sided treaty terms later became a bone of contention for
nationalist Panamanians.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, some claimed, the zone had become a racist enclave.
Retired West Indian canal workers remember the zone as a kind of
apartheid state in which neighborhoods were labeled ``gold'' and
``silver'' to distinguish between white and black areas.
</P>
<P>
   When civil rights leader Jesse Jackson toured the zone in the
1970s, he was appalled by the racial divisions. Few of the Zonians
learned Spanish and even today, some butcher the names of the towns
where they have lived for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people would work here and never leave the zone,''
Markham says.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end came in 1964, when anti-American riots
broke out after students from Panama City tried to raise the
Panamanian flag next to the U.S. flag at Balboa High School.
Panama's former military ruler, Gen. Omar Torrijos, called the zone
a ``colonialist tumor'' and vowed that it would be abolished _ even
if that meant going to war.
</P>
<P>
   By negotiating the canal treaties with President Carter,
Torrijos became a national hero. But among Zonians, the two former
leaders are widely scorned for having signed away their
livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   Besides mandating the turnover of the canal, the treaties
returned jurisdiction of most of the Canal Zone to Panama in 1979
and set a schedule for the gradual drawdown of U.S. troops and the
closing of military bases.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen of his rented whitewashed bungalow near the banks
of the canal, Holden unwinds from his 14-hour day on the Konkar
Star with a glass of rum.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that U.S. control of the waterway is an anachronism.
But somehow, pulling out also feels wrong, he says.
</P>
<P>
   For veteran pilots like Holden, life on the Panama Canal was not
a job, but a calling.
</P>
<P>
   Holden and his wife, Judy, a native of New Zealand, have
reluctantly shipped some of their belongings to their house in Palm
Harbor, near St. Petersburg. But Holden refuses to leave until the
canal actually changes hands Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't feel like I'm ready to retire,'' he says. ``It's
like a horse with blinders. When you have a good life, you look
straight ahead, and you don't want to see it come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
