<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON   Training in Building Trades 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: I heard that there is a government program that encourages the
hiring and training of apprentices in the building trades by paying
a portion of their wages while in training. Where can I get the
information on this and possibly other related programs?
<P>
   A: The U.S. Department of Labor finances a vast array of
job-training programs and the funds typically flow through state
and local organizations. The best clearing house for information is
the Private Industry Council, which has offices in many counties.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Private Industry Council of San Francisco has
an annual budget of about $20 million, according to Interim
President Ray Holland, and more than 80 percent of the
beneficiaries are small businesses with fewer than 50 employees.
</P>
<P>
   PIC will pay qualified employers up to 50 percent of the wages
for a training period of up to 490 hours. It also administers
various youth training, welfare-to-work and tax credit programs.
For more information call (415) 431-8700 or visit the Web site at &LR; 
www.picsf.org &LR; . In Santa Clara, contact the Silicon Valley Private
Industry Council (408) 953-1500 or Web site:  &LR; www.svpic.com &LR; . In
Oakland, you can call (510) 891-9393 or visit the Web site
 &LR; www.oaklandpic.org. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Another source of information is the Division of
Apprenticeship Standards within California's Department of
Industrial Relations which you can find at the state government Web
site at &LR;  www.dir.ca.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Prospecting for Patrons
</P>
<P>
   Q: My friend and I are graduating from high school and want to
open a business this summer to teach people basic skills about
using a computer and the Internet. I was wondering how to make
ourselves known to people.
</P>
<P>
   A: I gather you don't want to spend much money on promoting your
services, like taking out an ad in your favorite newspaper. One of
the best ways to promote your services, as illustrated in the
feature story today on kid entrepreneurs, is by word of mouth. No
doubt schoolmates, friends and family are aware of your abilities
and could recommend you to their friends and acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   Using free community bulletin boards is another way to go,
according to Jay Levinson, consultant and author of ``Guerrilla
Marketing.'' Post notices with detachable tabs with your name and
phone number at markets, laundries, libraries, bookstores, schools,
computer stores, senior centers and other places that provide free
bulletin boards. Since the fastest-growing sector of the Internet
is senior citizens, Levinson especially recommends going after this
market, especially since they are happy to get lessons during the
daytime when many other prospective clients are working.
</P>
<P>
   You might consider offering your services as a free guest
speaker at senior centers or other community organization. At the
end of your discussion, you might let it be known that you also
offer individual instruction and leave some flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson notes that your local chamber of commerce and reference
librarian are good sources of information on community groups and
clubs looking for speakers and instruction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Sizzle and Steak
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in new ways to attract both customers and
employees. There's a lot of competition for both.
</P>
<P>
   A: Alas, there are no easy answers. Rieva Lesonsky, editorial
director of Entrepreneur Magazine and co-author of ``303 marketing
Tips Guaranteed to Boost Your Business,'' suggests the need to
separate your self from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   For example, instead of sending out solicitations in plain
envelopes that often get tossed before they are even opened, she
notes that some businesses gain attention by putting something
lumpy inside or having a fake coffee spill printed on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But you better make sure that once someone opens the envelope
there is something inside to capture his or her attention. Gimmicks
alone don't work. These days, Lesonsky says, ``you have to have
both sizzle and steak.''
</P>
<P>
   To find and keep employees, you also have to be creative. Most
small businesses can't compete with big companies on salaries and
benefits. ``You have to think outside the box,'' Lesonsky suggests.
For instance, hire someone over 70 or a teenager who wants a
part-time job and doesn't care about all the other stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
