<HEADER>
A9197 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-HENS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-09 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-HENS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETS OF SUCCESS 
 &HT;     
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim.     &HT;     By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN RAFAEL, Calif. _  &LR; Cornish hens are great for a dinner party,
but let's face it _ they can be pretty boring. Not, however, in the
case of this impressive dish from Las Camelias in San Rafael.
<P>
   Gabriel Fregosa has adapted his family recipes for the
restaurant, and the hens are one of my favorites. They get an
explosion of flavor from marinating for 24 hours in a mixture of
water, ginger, onions, garlic and tequila. You can actually taste
the warming effects of the alcohol after roasting.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this dish special is the fact that the hens are
allowed to rest for a half-hour after baking. Then they are sauteed
to add even more complex flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the sauce, made from tomatoes, mushrooms, cilantro,
pickled jalapenos and the strained marinade. It simmers for at
least a a half-hour, producing a thin, intense broth.
</P>
<P>
   Other dishes that have made Las Camelias one of the best Mexican
restaurants in the Bay Area include roasted stuffed poblanos,
tamales, chicken in poblano sauce and a wonderful fish taco.
They're served in a charming restaurant that feels like a hacienda.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Las Camelias, 912 Lincoln Ave. (between Third and Fourth &LR; 
 &LR; streets), San Rafael, Calif.; (415) 453-5850. Lunch &LR; 
 &LR; Monday-Saturday; dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marinating the hens.  &LR; Tequila and other ingredients infuse the
birds with flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roasting and sauteing.  &LR; The technique of roasting the birds,
letting them rest and then sauteing them quickly over high heat
produces seductively crisp and juicy hens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
LAS CAMELIAS' CORNISH GAME HENS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup tequila
</P>
<P>
   20 cloves garlic, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces fresh ginger, grated
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 Cornish hens, about 18 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces mushrooms, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh tomatoes, peeled, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup coarsely chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 pickled jalapenos, seeded and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water, tequila, garlic, ginger, onion, salt and
pepper in a bowl large enough to hold all the Cornish hens.
</P>
<P>
   Wash the hens and put them in the marinade. Make sure to get
some of the onions and ginger inside the cavity. Cover the hens,
refrigerate them in the marinade for at least 8 hours or up to 24
hours, if possible.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the hens from the marinade, scraping off the onion
mixture. Strain marinade and reserve it for the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Place the hens on a rack in a
low-sided baking pan or broiler pan, salt and pepper them
generously and roast them for 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the hens from the oven and allow them to rest for 30
minutes. Reserve any juices that collect in the pan for the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   While the hens are resting, make the sauce. Melt the butter in a
saucepan over medium-high heat. Add the mushrooms and cook 3 to 4
minutes until soft but not browned. Add the tomatoes and simmer 6
to 8 minutes. Add the cilantro and the jalapenos and stir for 1
minute. Taste and add salt as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Add the reserved marinade, turn up the heat and bring the
mixture to a vigorous boil. Reduce the heat and let simmer at least
30 minutes until the sauce has reduced and thickened slightly. Add
any pan juices and continue to reduce. The sauce will have a thin,
brothlike consistency but will be intensely flavored. Taste the
sauce and add salt, if needed. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, heat the olive oil in a large saute pan
over high heat. Cut the Cornish hens in half and put them in the
pan, cut side up, to sear. Turn the hens several times to evenly
brown and crisp the skin, about 5 minutes in all.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the hens accompanied by the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 665 calories, &LR;   &LR; 76 g protein, 7 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 29 g fat (8 g saturated), 236 mg cholesterol, 1,065 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 2
g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
