<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9200 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOURCE-CHER-SFCHRON &LR;      06-09 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-CHER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE SOURCE  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. As a bonus, Georgeanne Brennan will offer tips for using
the bounty in fresh, innovative ways.     By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Even in the demanding Bay Area market, where
great-tasting fruit is commonplace, Goldbud Farms cherries stand
out.
 &HT;    Plump, firm and deeply colored, the farm's flavor-packed Bings
and Rainiers have drawn crowds in years past at the Ferry Plaza
Farmers' Market, despite the fruits' breathtaking price (typically
$3.50 to $4 a pound).
 &HT;    Grower Ron Mansfield credits his mountain location for the
cherries' exceptional taste. Grown near Placerville at elevations
from 2,500 to 3,000 feet, the trees enjoy warm, not hot, days and
cool nights.
 &HT;    The moderate climate allows the fruit to mature slowly, so it
maintains natural acid as the sugar content rises. At harvest, when
the cherries may be 25 percent to 30 percent sugar, they still have
a pleasing acidity.
 &HT;    ``What you end up with is a piece of fruit that's very well
balanced,'' Mansfield says. ``You know it has sugar, but there's a
little tang, too.''
 &HT;    The area's volcanic soil has a high mineral content, which
Mansfield is convinced contributes to flavor. His painstaking
harvest regimen helps, too.
 &HT;    Color and flavor tell him when the Bings are ready to pick.
``When they get to that deep burgundy, we start to taste,'' he
says. ``When they start to take on that deep-purplish hue, they're
ready.'`
 &HT;    Workers pick each tree four to six times during the
approximately four-week course of the harvest, selecting the
darkest fruit each time. Using only their hands, they harvest the
cherries with stems attached, put them into small boxes and take
them to a packing shed. There, the fruit is graded, sized, packed,
chilled and shipped _ typically within 24 hours.
 &HT;    ``Our fruit is priced substantially higher than most,''
Mansfield says, ``but if you were to follow our harvest procedures
through delivery to market, you'd see why.''
 &HT;    The grower's 18 acres of cherries are dominated by Bings and
blush-colored Rainiers but also include Burlats, Vans, Lamberts and
the sought-after Montmorency, a sour cherry prized for pies.
 &HT;    This year _ no surprise _ the cherries are running about two
weeks late. Mansfield expects his Bing harvest to get under way in
mid-June, with the Rainiers a few days later.
 &HT;    At the market, shoppers should look for shiny cherries with
plump stems that are at least partly green, Mansfield says. Bings
should be a deep burgundy; Rainiers should be strongly blushed. The
latter variety has less natural acidity than the Bing but a flavor
Mansfield describes as ``rich and almost butterscotchy.''
 &HT;    ``I just think Ron does a fantastic job,'' says Amy Suyama,
produce buyer for the Real Food Co. ``He knows soils so well, and
he's always learning something new _ about pest control, for
example. His fruit has consistently been fantastic.''
 &HT;    Unfortunately for farmers' market shoppers, Mansfield won't be
doing the Ferry Plaza market this year. Instead, his farmers'
market crew is running a commercial kitchen, packing cherry jam and
cherry sauce from Goldbud Farms fruit. Mansfield expects those
items to be available at retail markets selling his fresh fruit.
 &HT;     Goldbud Farms cherries in season are available in the Bay Area 
 at Real Food Co. (1023 Stanyan St., 3939 24th St. and 2140 Polk 
 St., San Francisco, and 200 Caledonia, Sausalito); Monterey 
 Market (1550 Hopkins St., Berkeley); Woodlands Market (735 
 College Ave., Kentfield); Market Hall Produce (5655 College 
 Ave., Oakland), and Sigona's Farmers Market (2345 Middlefield 
 Road, Redwood City, and 399 Stanford Shopping Center, Palo 
 Alto). 
 &HT;     Visitors to the gold country also can stop by the farm store 
 at 2501 Carson Road, Placerville, (530) 626-6521, for fresh 
 cherries and the new cherry products. The store is open from 10 
 a.m.-5 p.m. daily. 
 &HT;     
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) 
 
 GEORGEANNE'S KITCHEN  
   
 By Georgeanne Brennan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; With cherry season just getting started, here are
some recipes to use when the bins start to overflow.
<P>
   &UR; Brandied Cherries &LR; . Put clean, dry, firm cherries into a
sterilized jar. Add a little sugar, and cover with brandy. Close
the jar and store in a cool, dark place. Turn the jar every day
until sugar dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cherry Cobbler &LR; . Preheat an oven to 400 degrees. Make a
favorite cobbler crust. Pit and stem about 4 cups of cherries. Put
in a bowl, and toss with 11/2 cups flour, 1 teaspoon lemon juice
and 1/2 cup sugar. Put the cherries in a baking dish, top with the
crust and bake for about 20 minutes, or until the crust is lightly
golden and the juice is bubbling around the edges. Let stand 10
minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cherry Sauce. &LR;  Pit and stem about 2 cups of cherries. Put them
in a saucepan with 1/2 cup sugar and 1/4 cup water. Bring to a boil
over medium heat and cook, uncovered, about 15 minutes or until the
juice has thickened. If desired, strain. Serve the cherries warm or
cold over ice cream or cake.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chocolate Cherry Cake &LR; . Make a favorite two-layer chocolate
cake and chocolate frosting. Spread one layer with frosting; then
spread with very sweet chopped cherries. Add the second layer and
frost. Top with a cluster of whole cherries with stems attached.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pain Perdu With Poached Cherries &LR; . Pit about 20 cherries. Put
them in a saucepan, and add about 3/4 cup water and 1/4 cup sugar.
Bring to a boil over medium-high heat. Reduce to a simmer, and
poach for 10 to 15 minutes or until a syrup forms and the cherries
are soft but still hold their shape.
</P>
<P>
   Dip thick slices of country-style bread in beaten eggs. Melt a
nugget of butter in a skillet. Saute the dipped bread until golden.
Serve with the cherries and their juice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Georgeanne Brennan, a food and garden writer who lives in Yolo
County, is the author of ``Aperitif'' and ``The Food and Flavors of
Haute Provence.'' She can be reached by e-mail at
 &LR; food &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
