<P>
   COX-MP3 _ ATLAN TA _ Cox Interactive Media Inc. and MP3.com Inc.
on Wednesday announced a joint venture to create and operate a
number of music-related Web sites. Cox Interactive Media, which
operates a network of 30 local Web sites, will invest $45 million
in MP3.com, one of the leaders in online music distribution. The
two companies will make equal investments in the joint venture,
according to a statement released by the companies. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HOMEDEPOT-CANADA _ ATLANTA _ Home Depot plans a major expansion
in Canada, where it will double its presence over the next 3-4
years. The expansion, which includes 15-20 stores in Quebec, is
possible because a previous non-compete agreement with a Canadian
firm has been nullified. Depot's Canadian operations have
fluctuated since it first entered the market in 1994. A rebounding
housing market makes it a good time to expand in Canada. (Bond,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-QWEST _ BellSouth Corp., which provides local phone
services in nine southeastern states, said it's considering buying
Qwest Communications International Inc. or boosting its stake in
the long-distance phone company. BellSouth, which last month paid
$3.5 billion for 10 percent of Qwest, said in a filing with the
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission that it could take a
controlling position in the Denver-based company. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING-SUED _ Neil Horsely, who runs the Christain Gallery
Web site (the one encouraging users to murder abortion doctors) is
suing MindSpring for $50 million in a suit filed today.MindSpring
was the original host of the Christain Gallery site and pulled the
site citing user compalints, terms of service agreements with users
and after an planned parenthood lawsuit named Horsely's site in an
injunction. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SUPERCOMM-SHOW _ ATLANTA _ Experts on communications networks,
gathered in Atlanta for Supercomm99, are busy building network
capacity to keep up with rolling demand. But the biggest challenge
they face is creating access. ``Right now we have a communications
superhighway, with dirt road access,'' said one official. An
official from Atlanta-based Mindspring piped up: ``We work the dirt
roads, and we're having a lot of fun!'' Telecommunications
officials say that Internet and similar communications are
burgeoning, driven by e-mail, electronic commerce and other hot
areas of activity. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WOLFCAMERA _ Wolf Camera will buy The Dark Room, a 17-store
photo processor in Baltimore. It's the latest in a string of
acquisitions by Wolf, which has more than 700 stores. (Bond,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DUPONT-CEO _ DuPont Photomasks, Inc. (NASDAQ:DPMI), commonly
referred to as DPI, today announced that J. Michael Hardinger,
chairman and chief executive officer, has stepped down from these
positions effective immediately. Hardinger will assist the company
in the transition to his successor. The company also announced that
the board of directors has formed a search committee to identify a
new CEO and has named Marshall Turner, a current member of DPI's
board, as interim CEO and chairman. (Mahoney.
Austin-American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Banking Committee hears from
congressional witnesses, including Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, on
threats to Americans' financial privacy. (Hill, Cox News Service).
18.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-HANDICAP _ Tony Perrone lost the use of his legs in 1986
when a jack under a truck he was working on broke. He had been a
network administrator for an international company. When he
recovered, he still had his knowledge of computers, but found
companies unwilling to give him a job because he was in a
wheelchair. So he started N. Ga. Wheelers, a group that trains
disabled people to use computers so they can work at home.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
