<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-TAM-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses
more than a half century old.    Roosevelt Tamale Parlor Is Still on a Roll 
 &HT;      
 &HT;     By Jennifer Straus  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; One step off the bus at 24th and Bryant
streets and you know you're in the Mission _ and in sort of a time
warp. Here the '70s mixes with hip-hop youth culture. Your feet
begin to move to the Santana riff that repeats itself in your head.
An elderly Latino, complete with a leather cowboy hat, wrinkled &LR; 
 &LR; cowboy boots and bolo tie, nods his head.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from a mural-adorned park sits the Roosevelt
Tamale Parlor, a business that has remained authentic through
decades of the neighborhood's evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by siblings Juan and Rose Carrasco, the Tamale Parlor
serves colorful and full-flavored food to neighborhood residents
and those visitors who seek it out. ``We get quite a lot of
tourists that have never tried real Mexican food and they really
like it,'' Rose explains.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt Tamale Parlor was opened in the early '20s by a
Dutchman with the last name of Roosevelt. He also owned a dry
cleaners and the Roosevelt Theater (today it's called Brava for
Women in the Arts). The restaurant changed ownership several times
before it was purchased in 1950 by Juan and Luz Carrasco, parents
of the current owners, who had come to San Francisco from Jalisco,
Mexico, in the mid-1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Juan and his mother, Beatriz, went to work immediately to revamp
the entire menu. ``The previous owners were serving enchiladas with
spaghetti and French bread instead of tortillas ... They were doing
everything wrong,'' Rose says.
</P>
<P>
   Juan was the head cook until his death in 1961 when Luz took the
role of training new cooks and managing the business. By the time
she died in 1988, Rose was ready to take over as manager. She has
run the place ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't cook,'' Rose says. ``I just eat. The cook tells me,
`Go taste it.' I taste it and say, `Yep, that's it!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Carrascos intend to maintain their grandmother's Jaliscan
menu. ``I'm concerned with keeping the food at a high quality,''
Rose says. ``If there is something wrong, I expect my regulars to
say something. They keep us on our toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we make things not too spicy because a lot of our
clientele is non-Latino. We try to keep it middle-of-the-road _ not
so spicy that you can't eat the stuff. We give them a bottle of hot
sauce on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamales are particularly in demand on holidays. At Christmas,
many non-Latinos order as many as four dozen apiece. Christmas is
also the time to special-order sweet tamales with strawberries or
pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   Rose and her head cook, Maria Perez, have experimented with
using oil rather than the traditional lard to accommodate their
clients' health concerns. But, Rose admits, ``I'm sorry to say, but
the beans taste better with lard in them; you gotta put the lard in
them. It gives them just the right flavor.'' The rice, she says,
tastes fine made with oil.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of vegetarian items, including chimichangas and
burritos, are relatively recent additions. ``When my mother was
alive we didn't have that stuff,'' Rose says. But on another health
front, ``a point of pride for us is that we went non-smoking a year
before the law went into effect,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   From the street outside the Tamale Parlor you can peek into the
window of the apartment upstairs where Rose lives with her cats and
her year-round Christmas tree. She was born and raised in the
neighborhood and has lived there for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice neighborhood. Of course we have our problems with
kids tagging the buildings, but I tell people that I'm going to be
here until I die ... And they're going to bury me in my back
yard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
