<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9205 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORMEL-CONTROVERSY-HN     06-09 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-CONTROVERSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST OPENLY GAY AMBASSADOR EXPECTED TO BE SWORN IN NEXT WEEK
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL And JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ambassador-designate James C. Hormel will be sworn
in to take over the long vacant U.S. diplomatic post in Luxembourg
by a Clinton administration official, possibly while President
Clinton is out of town next week, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the 66-year-old heir to the Hormel Meat Co.,
fortune may take the oath from Vice President Al Gore or a
lower-ranking official while Clinton is on a week-long trip to
Europe beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, a San Francisco philanthropist and gay rights advocate,
will become the first openly gay American to serve as a U.S.
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   White House Deputy Press Secretary Barry Toiv said he expected
Hormel to be sworn in ``in a week or so, give or take a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said ``there is a sense of urgency to getting this done,'' adding:
``We want to get the ambassador to Luxembourg as soon as possible
because the embassy has been without an ambassador for sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton resorted to an obscure provision in the U.S.
Constitution last Friday to unilaterally install Hormel in the post
without Senate confirmation. Clinton used the recess appointment to
bypass Senate opponents who had sidetracked Hormel's nomination for
18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution permits a president to fill vacancies during a
congressional recess without Senate approval. Congress returned
from a 10-day Memorial Day recess three days after Clinton's
action.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel can serve in the diplomatic post until the end of this
session of Congress, which approximately coincides with the end of
the Clinton presidency in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swearing in is just a matter of logistics and how quickly
we can put the ceremony together and get family members and friends
to Washington,'' the State Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   Preparations for Hormel's swearing in came as Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and the White House squared off on
Clinton's use of the recess appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm offended by this nomination and the way they did it,''
Lott said Wednesday. ``I think it's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lott said he would not join Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., in
retaliating against the White House by freezing Senate action on
the 125 Clinton nominations awaiting Senate action.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe announced Tuesday that he will seek to indefinitely block
Senate action on all Clinton nominations to protest the president's
recess appointment of a controversial nominee who has been awaiting
Senate action since approval by the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee in November, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe vowed to use his senatorial prerogative to put ``holds''
on Clinton's nomination of Lawrence H. Summers to serve as
secretary of the treasury, Richard C. Holbrooke to serve as U.N.
ambassador and dozens of other nominees awaiting Senate action. A
hold allows a single senator to block a floor vote, though the
Senate majority leader can cancel a hold by another senator.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he ``always...initially'' honors senators' so-called
``holds'' on presidential nominations but indicated he wouldn't
permit Inhfoe to stop the confirmation process.:
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think we have a responsibility to move the president's
nominations if they are qualified, if they don't have legal,
ethical or moral or whatever problems,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he would seek pledges from the White House to make
sure that the Clinton administration does not resort to recess
appointments in the future without extended advance notice.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he would take steps ``so they will not do this
again,'' adding that it was important for the White House to
``understand there will be a price to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made 57 recess appointments over the course of his
presidency _ far less than the 239 made by President Ronald Reagan
and the 78 made by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Toiv, the White House spokesman, said presidential aides have
notified the Senate leadership in advance on every recess
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This White House has done far more notification and
consultation with the Senate on recess appointments than previous
administrations _ and that will continue,'' Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
   Toiv disputed Lott's charge that the White House had not
notified the Senate leadership in advance of the Hormel
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House notified the Senate about this recess
appointment _ and it was not on the same day that it was made
either,'' Toiv said. ``The White House is prepared, as we have
always done, to provide appropriate consultation and
notification.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Gary Bauer, a declared Republican presidential
candidate, said Inhofe had shown ``rare moral courage'' by standing
up to the Clinton administration's's effort to install an
ambassador ``who has leagued himself with those who mock and
denounce people of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Birch, executive director of the Human Rights
Campaign, a pro-gay rights organization, condemned Inhofe for a
``churlish tirade and spectacular display of anti-gay
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com) (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be
reached at 202-298-6920 and by e-mail at jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
