<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-09 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET ANXIETY SEIZES BRITONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a mad world, book publishing, that's bound to go down. At
least it always views itself in tatters. Surely, for instance, the
invention of bookstore chains means the end of independent sellers.
(Just as the idea of selling books in supermarkets meant the end of
bookstores.) Or that huge author advances would kill off
publishers. Or that international publishing conglomerates would
kill off the huge advances.
</P>
<P>
   Now the buzz horror is that the concept of publishers' owning
and controlling the territorial rights to books is about to be shot
dead by the Internet. Which is one reason, although not the only
one, that many British publishers are setting up or planning
outposts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that if a publisher in the future wants to be a
serious player in the global English-language market, the world's
largest, the publisher cannot stay out of its biggest and most
profitable realm, the United States. And down the road there lurks
the fear, real or exaggerated, that the Internet will snatch away
whatever profitability there is for a publisher to buy the foreign
rights to a book whose original publisher is American. If, for
instance, a customer in London can use the Internet to buy an
American author's work more quickly, and often more cheaply, than
by waiting for its British publication, then why wait? And if
buyers don't wait, what good is owning the territorial rights in
Britain? That's the theory.
</P>
<P>
   Conglomerates that own publishing houses in the United States
don't have to worry, which is why they bought American: Bertelsmann
owns Random House, Pearson owns Penguin Putnam, and Holtzbrinck
owns Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, for instance. Now is the time for
smaller British publishers to set up houses in the United States or
perhaps buy them, and some plan to do so. That will certainly make
authors and their agents happy, since there will be more buyers at
a time when many agents complain that their market is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomsbury, an independent literary publishing house in London
and Australia, has already launched Bloomsbury USA. It is led by
Alan Wherry, an Irishman who works out of London and whose
editorial director is Karen Rinaldi in New York. Wherry said,
``We're not a huge company, but we feel the market is quite wide
open in America for an independent publisher of strength.'' He said
that fear of being a prisoner of the Internet was not their main
reason, that that is a problem that will take care of itself.
``It's like the farmers are always complaining, but they keep on
making record advances,'' he said. ``We have no intention of being
a British publisher operating in America, but an American
publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rinaldi has signed four books in the last few months for
fall publication as she has started to build an American list. The
first was a world rights deal for a debut novel about a young girl
and her sisters fighting against the madness of their parents. The
novel, by a 22-year-old woman, Suneeta Peres da Costa, was sold by
Tiffany Richards, an agent. ``For us it's fantastic; it's an extra
place for us to sell,'' Ms. Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rinaldi also bought a psychological thriller and a satirical
novel. ``I'm finding a lot of really good work,'' she said,
``because the bigger houses aren't taking as many risks.'' Her main
competitors are the small- to medium-size houses (Grove, Atlantic,
Norton, and Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, for instance), but she doesn't
rule out Random House either.
</P>
<P>
   Such an American presence gives Bloomsbury the prestige and
clout to negotiate for world rights for a book, if it can come up
with the cash, which obviously protects its territorial rights.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, Victoria Barnsley, the publisher of Fourth
Estate, a successful and lively independent publisher in London,
said she was ``in the process of deciding how best to start some
sort of operation in America, in order to buy books on both sides
of the Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barnsley is less sanguine than Wherry about the Internet.
``Many in Britain feel that the whole territorial copyright will
eventually collapse because of the Internet,'' she said. ``Not
immediately, but there will be quite a breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're simply in the exploratory stage. If we don't do
something, Britain is going to be another state of the United
States, at least in book publishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orion Group in Britain is also expected to extend eventually
into America. But the grandest British entrance into American
publishing may well be the one being contemplated by Hodder
Headline, which published 1,300 titles last year, some of which
were best sellers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Britain's biggest bookseller, W.H. Smith, acquired a 51
percent controlling interest in Hodder Headline, suddenly giving
the publisher very big pockets to buy American. Tim
Hely-Hutchinson, group chief of Hodder Headline, who recently was
saying he was in no hurry to get to the United States, said he
didn't know if the publisher would try to buy an already existing
American publishing house or start a new one. ``We'll see what's
available that represents a good value,'' he said. ``If we cannot
find one, we'll make a publisher starting from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of which books actually translate between the
readers of English and American is a different subject. Generally
American books do better in Britain than British books do in
America (except that English thrillers and mystery stories sell
well here), which is another reason the British publishers would
like to set up shop here and compete to be the original publishers
of American writers.
</P>
<P>
   The British used to own the language but now Americans own the
airwaves and the entertainment industries. The British literary
tradition is no longer Thackeray and Dickens, but the popular
Barbara Cartland, Frederick Forsyth, Jeffrey Archer and John le
Carre, so the battle is over who is to own the profits from books
written in the common language.
</P>
</TEXT>
