<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICKCOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEKEND COOK  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with enough
leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes plus
suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow.    By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  June gets us thinking about the lazy days of
summer _ until we remember it's a month of celebrations, with
Father's Day and graduations for starters. And that gets us
thinking of what to make for dinner that is easy, festive and
somewhat unusual.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crepes _ thin French pancakes _ are a good choice. You can make
them ahead; fill them with fish, fowl, fruit and more; and fit them
into any course from hors d'oeuvre to dessert. Crepes can be
refrigerated up to four days or frozen up to a month, so a batch
made on the weekend can hold you in good stead for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There is one trick to easy crepe making: Use a nonstick pan.
With a nonstick finish, the thin film of batter practically peels
off when it's cooked. Lacking a nonstick pan, you can use a heavy
saute pan and brush the bottom with a little butter between cooking
each crepe.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of Father's Day, today's Weekend Recipe skips
right to dessert with a dish that puts a summery slant on crepes
Suzette. The components of the weeknight recipes may be made on the
weekend, so finishing either dish during the week _ whether for
family or company _ is quick and easy. In fact, the cannelloni is a
good entree for a graduation celebration. You can assemble it
before the ceremony and bake it after.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; MASTER RECIPE: BASIC CREPES
</P>
<P>
   Note: These crepes are fast and easy to make. If you have 2 pans
the same size, you can make 2 crepes at once.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   12 eggs
</P>
<P>
   71/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup butter, melted, + additional butter for frying crepes
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the flour in a large mixing bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly whisk the eggs until well blended. Whisk in the milk
and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly whisk the liquid into the flour. When the mixture is
lump-free, whisk in the melted butter. Cover and refrigerate for 2
hours before using.
</P>
<P>
   To make the crepes, heat an 81/2-inch nonstick saute pan over
medium heat. Brush it lightly with butter.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the batter to recombine. Pour 2 tablespoons or so of the
batter into the pan. Swirl the pan so the batter covers the bottom
and slides up the sides a little. Cook 1 minute, or until the edges
of the crepe look dry and start to pull away from the pan. Peel off
the crepe with your fingers and turn it over. Cook the second side
until it is lightly speckled, less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Place the crepe flat in a wax paper-lined storage container.
Continue making crepes in this manner, stacking them between sheets
of wax paper when finished. You probably won't need to butter the
pan again.
</P>
<P>
   When all the crepes have been made, tightly cover the container
and refrigerate for up to 4 days. The crepes may also be frozen,
stacked between wax paper and enclosed in a freezer container or in
a double layer of freezer storage bags, for up to 1 month. Defrost
them before using.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 30 crepes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CREPE: &LR;   &LR; 190 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 21 g carbohydrate, 9
g &LR;   &LR; fat (5 g saturated), 105 mg cholesterol, 309 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WEEKEND RECIPE: SUMMERY CREPES SUZETTE
</P>
<P>
   Note: You can also make this in 2 saute pans, which will
accommodate the ingredients a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces fresh or frozen raspberries
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh-squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   12 crepes (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brandy
</P>
<P>
   8 large strawberries, hulled and cut lengthwise into
1/4-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   Unsweetened whipped cream, as needed
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Puree the raspberries in a food processor. Strain them, pressing
on the pulp and seeds to release as much puree as possible. You
will need 1 cup puree for this recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together the puree, orange juice and sugar in a large saute
pan over medium-high heat until the sugar melts; bring to a boil.
Add the butter, swirling it until it melts. Remove the pan from the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, dip both sides of each crepe into the liquid. Fold
each crepe in half then in half again to make a triangle. Leave the
crepes in the pan.
</P>
<P>
   When all the crepes are folded, return the pan to medium-high
heat. Bring to a boil. Add the Grand Marnier and brandy; bring to a
boil, spooning the sauce over the crepes to baste them. Add the
strawberries, submerging them in the sauce. Simmer for a minute,
until the fruit is just heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Serve 3 crepes per person, along with a portion of sauce and a
dollop of whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 902 calories, &LR;   &LR; 23 g protein, 108 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 42 g fat (24 g saturated), 354 mg cholesterol,
1,050 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 6 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: GARLIC &AMP; HERB CHEESE CANNELLONI
</P>
<P>
   Note: These are delicious. The sauce may be made and the crepes
may be filled on the weekend. Cover and refrigerate both
separately, for up to 2 days. Assemble and heat the dish just
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 can (28 ounces) diced tomatoes in juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 large garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons minced basil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (5.2 ounces each) Boursin ``garlic and fine herbs''
cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces part-skim ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, well beaten
</P>
<P>
   12 crepes (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup shredded Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sauce:  &LR; Process the tomatoes and their juice to a
textured puree in a food processor; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a saucepan over medium-high heat. Add the onion
and garlic and saute, stirring frequently, until the onion begins
to color, about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the tomatoes. Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer,
stirring occasionally, until the mixture has thickened, 5 to 8
minutes. Stir in the basil and salt. Simmer for another minute.
Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the cannelloni:  &LR; Cream the Boursin with a wooden spoon.
Add the ricotta and the pepper, stirring to combine thoroughly.
Blend in the egg.
</P>
<P>
   Place the crepes prettier-sides down on a work surface. Place a
heaping tablespoon of filling in the center of each crepe,
spreading it a little toward the edges. Roll up each crepe.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the warm tomato sauce in a baking dish large enough to
hold the crepes in a single layer. Place the crepes in the dish and
sprinkle the cheese evenly over the top. Cover tightly and bake for
45 to 50 minutes, until the Parmesan has melted and the filling is
heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 805 calories, &LR;   &LR; 38 g protein, 67 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 44 g fat (26 g saturated), 357 mg cholesterol,
1,834 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: MUSHROOM CREPES WITH CREAMED SPINACH SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Note: The filling may be made and the crepes may be filled on
the weekend and refrigerated, airtight, for up to 3 days. Assemble
and heat the dish just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 large shallot
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 hot Italian sausage link, casing removed
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   10 crepes (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (10 ounces each) frozen creamed spinach
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup shredded Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Instructions: &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; To make the filling:  &LR; Process the mushrooms and shallot in a food
processor until they are finely chopped; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a saute pan over medium-high heat. Add the oil and sausage;
saute, breaking up the meat into tiny pieces, until it is just
cooked through. Add the mushroom mixture and saute, stirring
frequently, for 8 to 10 minutes. Transfer a bowl. Stir in the
ricotta and season with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Place the crepes prettier-sides down on a work surface. Working
with one crepe at a time, place a tablespoon of mushroom filling
just off center. Fold the crepe in half, then in half again to form
a triangle. Press the triangle lightly with the palm of your hand
to flatten it slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; Boil or microwave the creamed spinach in its
pouch until it is heated through. Spread the spinach in a baking
dish large enough to hold the crepes in a single layer. Place the
crepes in the dish. Sprinkle with Parmesan. Cover tightly and bake
until the filling is hot, about 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 845 calories, &LR;   &LR; 37 g protein, 63 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 50 g fat (24 g saturated), 357 mg cholesterol,
1,806 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
