<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9212 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDSIDE-KIDSIDE_SFCHR     06-09 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDSIDE-KID </SLUG>
 SIDE _ SF CHRON  
 Programs for Enterprising Youth  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR; Chronicle Senior Writer
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; Various entrepreneurship programs have been designed to turn K-12
students onto the joys of business creation. Here are a few of
them:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; BizWorld &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 400 Seaport Court, Suite 250A, Redwood City, Calif. 94063;
(650) 368-0777. Web site: &LR;  www. &LR;   &LR; bizworld.org &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Created by Redwood City venture capitalist Tim Draper two
years ago, BizWorld brings volunteers into the classroom to
encourage third- through eighth-grade students to learn about
business. About 150 schools have offered BizWorld's four two-hour
sessions where students learn about entrepreneurship by designing,
making and selling friendship bracelets and creating balance sheet
and income statements. The program is also available online.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Global Education Partnership &LR;
</P>
<P>
   310 Eighth St., Suite 303, Oakland, Calif. 94607; (510)
834-7255. Web site:  &LR; www.global &LR;   &LR; edpartnership.org &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Started in 1994, this nonprofit organization will have six
programs this fall to teach entrepreneurship to high school-age
students in East Palo Alto, Oakland and San Francisco. Participants
learn the basics of entrepreneurship, including importing and
selling handicrafts from Kenya. They set up ``one-day'' businesses,
where they can keep the profits, learn to write a business plan and
compete for $700 in awards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Junior Achievement &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 400 Oyster Point Blvd., Suite 419, South San Francisco, Calif.
94080; (650) 737-0370. Web site:  &LR; www.ja.org &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Junior Achievement has tried to get Americans hooked on free
enterprise at an early age since 1919. It now reaches more than 3
million U.S. students a year, and volunteers teach the nonprofit's
K-12 programs in more than 128,000 classrooms. The organization has
local offices in Santa Clara and Santa Rosa as well as South San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; KidsWay Inc. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   5589 Peachtree Road, Chamblee, Ga. 30341; (888) 543-7929. Web
site:  &LR; www.kidsway.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   KidsWay offers books, classes, camps, books and other
instruction to would-be entrepreneurs. The Kidsway Presidents Club
membership of $25 a year includes a year's $16 subscription to the
bimonthly Young Entrepreneur Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Pier 11/2 Embarcadero, San Francisco, Calif. 94111; (415)
273-7700; Web site:  &LR; www.nfte.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   NFTE (pronounced ``nifty'') is an international nonprofit
organization that introduces low-income teens to the
entrepreneurial world by teaching them how to develop and operate
their own small businesses. Locally, NFTE operated in nine local
high schools this past school year, including some in San Leandro
and Woodside. It also operates summer BizCamps in partnership with
Microsoft. A two-week, free camp will be held at Stanford
University August 9 to 20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; National Inventors Hall of Fame &LR;
</P>
<P>
   221 S. Broadway, Akron, Ohio 44308; (330) 762-4463. Web site:
 &LR; www.invent.org &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This organization was established in 1973 by the U.S. Patent and
Trademark Office and what is now the National Council of
Intellectual Property Law Associations. It has several programs
aimed at kids, including an annual young inventors &UR;  &LR; award, an
invention training curriculum for schools and a Camp Invention
summer program. Bay Area sessions of the summer camp will be held
at Walnut Heights Elementary School in Walnut Creek June 21 to 25
and Del Rey School in Orinda July 19 to 23.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; The East Bay Outreach Project &LR;  &QL; 
Haas School of Business, UC Berkeley, S545 Student Service Building
No. 1900, F501 Berkeley, Calif 94720; Phone: (510) 643-0923. Web
site:  &LR; www.haas.berkeley.edu &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   UC Berkeley's business school and MBA student volunteers train
educationally disadvantaged high school youth in entrepreneurship
during an intensive two-week summer camp, followed by year-round
educational and business planning workshops and field trips.
Students compete for venture capital funding _ up to $500. Deadline
for applications for the summer and year-round program is July 15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Enterprise for High School Students &LR;
</P>
<P>
   450 Mission St., Suite 408, San Francisco, Calif. 94105; (415)
896-0909.
</P>
<P>
   This San Francisco nonprofit helps more than 2,000 students a
year find jobs, connect with the workplace, learn about career
paths, and gain skills and experience. Pay for short- and
long-duration jobs range from $5 to $12 per hour. To qualify,
students must go to school or live in San Francisco, have at least
a 2.0 grade point average, provide a teacher recommendation and
attend job readiness and retention workshops before they get a job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9214 &Cx1f; tie-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-INTERNET-ART     06-09 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-INTERNET-ART-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR KOSOVO'S SCATTERED REFUGEES, THE INTERNET IS A LIFELINE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.J.)  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: Also moving in `a' category as part of Tuesday's Circuits
package.) 
(rk) 
 By LISA GUERNSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT DIX, N.J. _ Twice a day for the last week, 52-year-old
Ramize Bajrami has walked up the metal steps into the makeshift
Internet trailer here, hoping to find news about family members she
left behind in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   She sits down at one of the trailer's 12 computers and begins to
scroll through Web sites, her gray hair pulled back in a white
kerchief. Her hazel eyes search the screen for names she has
written on a crumpled paper she clutches in her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day she comes in here and says to me, `How can I find my
children?' '' said Kujtim Latifi, a 17-year-old Albanian refugee
and computer assistant who speaks enough English to translate for
the U.S. Information Agency staff members in the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bajrami, a refugee, has four sons who are fighting for the
Kosovo Liberation Army and a son and a daughter who she thinks are
still in Kosovo. She recently heard from her brother that another
son and his family are in Macedonia, but she has not been able to
get in touch with them them.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Internet is her only hope _ and in that sense, Ms.
Bajrami is lucky. She has access to Web sites, to Internet radio
broadcasts, to e-mail. Refugees in most other camps around Europe
do not yet have Internet trailers like the one here; many are still
relying on dribbles of information that come in letters or week-old
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   To change that, the USIA is coordinating the Kosovar Refugee
Internet Assistance Initiative. The Internet trailer at Fort Dix is
the project's first online center. A similar center in Germany just
opened this week, said David Zweigel, USIA's overseas technologist.
</P>
<P>
   Another in Germany, two in France and two in Poland are also
about to go online, Zweigel said. Getting Internet access to the
camps in Albania and Macedonia is trickier, because fewer Internet
hubs were already in place, but officials hope to connect a pool of
laptops in Macedonia via a satellite link this week and in Albania
by mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   If the experience here is any indication, those centers will be
packed as soon as they open. Since the Fort Dix trailer opened on
May 20, Zweigel said, hundreds of refugees have visited it each
day.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, nearly 50 people had crowded into the 40-foot-long
trailer. The sounds of multiple radio and video broadcasts _ all in
Albanian _ were bouncing off the trailer's walls. In one corner,
six gray-haired men bent to the computer, listening. Next to them,
Latifi helped Ms. Bajrami find a Web site that might enable her to
send an e-mail message that could be delivered to the Macedonian
refugee camp. A little girl stood next to her, holding her hand.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the trailer, a handful of teen-age boys sat
stone-faced, scrolling through photographs of victims of a massacre
that, according to international monitors, took place in Racak in
January. The photos, displayed on an anti-Serb Web site called the
Kosova Crisis Center, show slain men sprawled on the ground and a
dead baby covered with cuts.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why the boys wanted to look at such horrific
pictures, Latifi paused then spoke: ``Because they would like to
see what the Serbs have done.'' On Monday, he said, a man who was
looking at the pictures ``saw his uncle, killed.'' Then, he said,
the man looked away and cried.
</P>
<P>
   Providing open access to information is the USIA's primary
mission, said Jonathan Spalter, associate director and chief
information officer for the USIA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access to objective and reliable information will be key to
restoring structures of civil society for these terribly dispersed
communities of Kosovars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reconnecting family members is also a major part of the project.
On Tuesday, a 20-year-old refugee named Liridon Durigi, whose
parents are still in Kosovo, found that a cousin is now in a
refugee camp in Albania. He found his cousin listed on a Web site
called the Family News Network (www.familylinks.icrc.org/), which
was opened in mid-May by the International Committee for the Red
Cross. Pointing to the name, he asked a nearby computer assistant
to help him send an e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kosovo peace settlement is actually carried out, reliable
connections between people could become even more important, added
Zweigel. ``People will be able to correspond and say, `I'm going
home. You can come home too,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, many visitors to the Internet trailer are happy to
be able to read Albanian Web sites and hear Albanian news
broadcasts. ``When these people came in and heard the news in their
own language, it was amazing,'' Zweigel said. They had just arrived
in the United States, with foreign customs and a foreign language
spoken all around them. ``It was like they felt that this made them
real people again,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   More than a dozen companies and foundations are participating in
the USIA project. Nongovernmental organizations and foundations are
managing the donations and helping to distribute equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups are directing projects that could tie into the USIA
effort, such as a project led by professors and students at the
Chicago-Kent College of Law. They have been helping organizations
in Macedonia and Albania create a Web-based database of refugees'
registration information and information about what they saw in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But hurdles abound. The telephone system in northern Albania,
for example, is so limited that stringing high-speed Internet lines
is very difficult. And often the people that refugees have the
least information about _ families hiding in Kosovo, for example _
are the least likely to provide information on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Villarrubia Olga, an official for the Central Tracing Agency at
the International Committee for the Red Cross, said that people
inside Yugoslavia or in Macedonia are unlikely to give information
because they fear being discovered by Serb forces. ``They are more
comfortable'' elsewhere in Europe, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bajrami, meanwhile, sat in front of a computer here, her
eyes welling up as she wondered aloud why she had not heard from
her daughter and son still in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But then her voice strengthens. ``Everyday,'' she said, slapping
her hands against her lap and looking around her, ``I will come
until I find them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
