<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIVACY10-COX     06-09 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STRENGTHEN PRIVACY LAWS, LEGISLATORS URGE CONGRESS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress needs to provide stronger protections for
personal and financial information, legislators told a Senate panel
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Current privacy laws have not kept up with an increasingly
technological society, said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., a member of
a bipartisan panel that testified before the Senate Banking
Committee, which is exploring new privacy legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said banks can sell customers' personal financial
information to telemarketers in return for a commission. He said
this information includes not only addresses and telephone numbers,
but also credit card purchases, payment dates and account balances.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy also said medical records are not adequately protected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medical records contain the most intimate, sensitive
information about a person and must be safeguarded,'' Leahy said.
``Yet cross-industry mergers and consolidations have given banks
and other financial institutions unprecedented access to consumers'
medical records.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., said Congress needs to take action
to prevent such abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``These abuses are not just theoretical, they are occurring,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the solutions Leahy proposed were requirements for full
disclosure to consumers by financial institutions, authority for
civil suits that would allow consumers to recoup financial damages,
and expanding the power of state attorneys general to enforce
financial privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   The panel heard a dissenting view from Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas,
who said Congress should make a careful distinction between
``protection of'' and ``violation of'' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that we are going one step too far and we are
invading,'' rather than protecting privacy, Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, the status of private medical records should be
determined by negotiations between patients and doctors, with any
necessary laws and regulations being passed and enforced by state
governments.'' He added that individuals can protect their privacy
by refusing to work with institutions that do not provide adequate
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, no one can refuse to deal with the ultimate monopoly
_ government,'' Paul said. ``I would say go more cautiously.''
</P>
<P>
   More credit should be given to the good intentions of
government, businesses and banks, said Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said government is trying to address the public's
privacy protection concerns while still allowing for legitimate
third-party access to information. For example, medical research
depends on access to sensitive information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't automatic that government regulation wants to use
information to be Big Brother. It just may be that someone wants to
use information to better serve customers,'' Bennett said. ``To
deny that information may end up hurting the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
