<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9224 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SEARCH-0610-CO     06-09 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SEARCH-0610-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLORIDA BUSINESSMAN'S TRIP TO FAMILY FINDS HORRORS OF KOSOVO
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0610.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURRES, Albania _ Florida restaurant owner Anthony Hoti took his
hypertension pills and hid his feelings, but those in the large
Kosovar Albanian family he came home to reunite could not control
their emotions.
</P>
<P>
   His sisters cried as they saw him and began recounting how they
were threatened away from and burned out of their homes by Serb-led
Yugoslav forces. His beautiful niece Diana, 18, hugged him and
wept, then collapsed to the ground, shaking and hyper-ventilating.
She was carried away and laid under the shade of a nearby tree.
</P>
<P>
   Once a young fighter in the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army,
relatives explained she has had panic attacks since Serb soldiers
held her for a night and tortured her in ways she has yet to fully
describe. Her father, Hoti's brother-in-law, has not been seen
since his capture by the Serbs months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first day of homecoming for Hoti and his wife, Sadie,
who were born in war-torn Kosovo province and immigrated to
America. By telephone, they had spoken to some of their relatives
who had fled Kosovo along with more than 800,000 ethnic Albanians
since NATO began bombing Yugoslavia on March 24. Now, Hoti came to
see them and see about getting some to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After 24 hours on the ground Wednesday, this is what was known:
One niece's husband was killed; a brother-in-law was missing; a
niece was traumatized beyond control. Some had been beaten and
others had spent a week in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   There was some good news. Hoti found three sisters and a
brother, and Sadie had spoken to her sister. But, they were
scattered around private homes and refugee camps, and they were not
as they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recognize the faces, they look so bad,'' Sadie
(pronounced, ``Sa-DEE-yeh'') Hoti said after climbing back into the
car from their first stop. Her in-laws, prosperous in Kosovo, were
now gaunt and bored.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotis, who are from Lake Worth, Fla., last visited Kosovo
three years ago. There, they had seen their families in large homes
and happy, though concern was evident over the growing animosity
toward the province's majority ethnic Albanian population from the
Serbs who control the rest of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   When Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, the president of
Yugoslavia, rejected a peace plan in March and NATO warplanes began
nightly bombings, Yugoslav troops and Serb police intensified their
terrorizing efforts to drive Kosovar Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Hoti, 43-year-old owner of Little Daddy's Pizza Restaurant,
helped run a pro-Kosovar rally in West Palm Beach, Fla., and tried
to get in touch with relatives. He and two brothers have homes and
restaurants in Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   He and Sadie, 31, had brief phone conversations with some
relatives, now refugees from their hometown of Djakovica in
southwest Kosovo. But, they have not tracked them all down.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of an uncle in an Albanian-Austrian aid agency,
they found the families of three of Hoti's sisters in a small
farmhouse near this coastal city, about an hour from the Albanian
capital, Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   The homeowner, an 80-year-old retired miner, had seen the ragged
refugees riding on the road near his home and invited them to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accepted them as Albanians. They had no place to live,''
said Hussein Kadria, who now has 38 people sharing his
three-bedroom house. In addition to a large suitcase of clothes for
his own family, Hoti left the man $1,000 in gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Around a table on the porch, Hoti's family reviewed their last
two months.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before leaving Djakovica in early April, Hoti's
brother-in-law Sefadin Arapi, 35, had been arrested and beaten into
unconsciousness by Serb police. He was now recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Police had held a knife to the throat of his wife Nanije, Hoti's
sister. They destroyed and looted their home, eventually burning
it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the international peace plan being brokered by NATO
leaders, and whether she would feel safe returning, Nanije Arapi
cannot answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brain is blocked. I'm confused. The situation is
impossible,'' she said gazing at a field where a few cattle grazed
near an abandoned slaughterhouse. ``All our hopes are with the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members talked about seeing neighbors shot while unarmed
and how they were given just minutes by masked Serb paramilitary
thugs to gather a few things and begin a day's walk to the Albanian
border.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour's drive away from the farmhouse, Hoti found one of
his brothers living in a refugee camp made set up in an abandoned
military warehouse. About 300 Kosovars live there, fortunate that
they are not under the same scorching summer sun as their
countrymen in tent camps here.
</P>
<P>
   But, Shefki Hoti, 51, said that 70 people share each bathroom.
He and his family of seven have one small room with no furniture,
just mattresses on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A high school biology teacher, Shefki Hoti fled with his family
for a week in the Kosovo mountains, then tried to return to their
town before being chased away again. His home was looted and
burned, as was his Mercedes-Benz and high school. He tried to put
his family up in a hotel, but is now out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say? I want to join my brothers in the United
States. I am the oldest one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Hoti said he is applying through the Red Cross to bring
his family out of Albania to the United States. Most said they
would someday like to return to Kosovo and rebuild their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have strong emotions that I cannot show them because I know
they are going to cry,'' Hoti said in a moment away from his
brother. It was mid-afternoon and he was about to set off on a
three-hour a drive to a town where they hoped to find Sadie's
sister.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
