<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTORS-STAGE-VS-SCREE     06-09 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTORS-STAGE-VS-SCREEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING TO CAMERA OR LIVE AUDIENCE, ACTORS CALIBRATE THEIR CRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Throughout the Broadway revival of ``Death of a
Salesman,'' Brian Dennehy's fingers keep worrying his brow, as if
trying to relieve or erase all the burdens bearing down behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Were he playing the role of Willy Loman on film, Dennehy said,
the camera might simply capture such a gesture with a close-up.
Instead, he said, he must make the movement absent-minded enough to
seem real, yet deliberate enough to reach an audience of 1,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The torture that he's going through is very much an emotional
torture,'' Dennehy said of his character. ``It has physical
manifestations but it's through the eyes where you see the agony
that he feels. Your job as an actor is to indicate that close-up to
a large number of people. Obviously, if you have a camera it's
easier to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy, winner of this year's Tony Award for leading actor in a
play, is one of an army of actors who have appeared onstage this
season and who are as well or better known for their work in film
and television. Others include Kevin Spacey, Natasha Richardson,
Uma Thurman, Jennifer Jason Leigh, Tony Danza, Nicole Kidman,
Swoosie Kurtz, Tom Wopat, Dylan Baker, Richard Chamberlain,
Bernadette Peters, Stockard Channing, Matthew Broderick and
Laurence Fishburne. The list seems endless.
</P>
<P>
   Each has developed the distinct arts of playing to a camera and
playing to an audience. And while they say there is no one right
way to act in each medium, actors have arrived at their own
conceptions of what works.
</P>
<P>
   They also have clear ideas about the differences between the two
mediums in terms of preparation, concentration, priorities, their
relationship to the audience and who is ultimately in control.
``Film is a director's medium; your performance is shaped by him
and the editor,'' Ms. Richardson said. ``Whereas you shape it in
the theater every night and finally the director has gone home and
it's just you doing those words.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the benefit of a camera up close on the eyes, actors say
they have to enlist their entire bodies consciously to convey
thoughts or feelings. ``Something happens to your body when you're
onstage,'' said Ms. Peters, who won a Tony for leading actress in a
musical for her performance in the revival of ``Annie Get Your
Gun.'' ``It has to be real, but it also has to fit the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Richardson said her current role in ``Closer'' would in many
ways be easier on film because so much of the play is about the
minute, private moments that draw and divide two people. She
recalled an observation about acting for the theater by Peter
Brooks in Al Pacino's film about the making of his production of
``Richard III,'' something to the effect that, ``Acting truthfully
loudly is much harder than acting truthfully quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why this play is particularly hard, because it's so
intimate,'' said Ms. Richardson, whose engagement in ``Closer''
ends this weekend. ``A lot of the time the audience is like flies
on the wall in a scene that really might be more suited to film.
But you have to communicate to a 1,200-seat house of some people
sitting miles away. It's very hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of this need to project physically and vocally, actors
say they have to be more careful to pace themselves. ``You have to
be in better shape for Broadway,'' said Wopat, who is starring
alongside Ms. Peters and is best known for his work in the
television series ``The Dukes of Hazzard.'' ``In television, you
can go in there sick as a dog and pull it together for a minute on
screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, watching actors go through emotionally wrenching
experiences onstage, it is hard not to wonder how they do it night
after night, sometimes twice a day with matinees. How do they go to
the despairing, draining precincts of, say, a Willy Loman without
winding up exhausted or depressed themselves?
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, it's acting,'' said Dennehy. ``If I really
was going there, I'd be in a rubber room. So you don't really go
there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was because he failed to keep this in mind, Dennehy said,
that he wound up in a hospital with high blood pressure last March,
forcing the show to cancel three performances because he has no
understudy.
</P>
<P>
   His cardiologist, who came to see the show, put him on
blood-pressure medication and advised him to drink less alcohol,
eat more fruit and vegetables and have his meals regularly and
earlier in the day rather than after the evening performance. And
to exercise. ``He said, `Your body doesn't know it's acting,'''
Dennehy said. `` `Your body feels this enormous stress. So your
heart is pounding, your blood pressure is rising.'''
</P>
<P>
   Because film work requires one or two takes, Dennehy said, the
process is less taxing; it's the waiting around and the 14-hour
days that wear him out.
</P>
<P>
   As much as physical presence, words count onstage in a way that
they don't in the movies, many actors say. ``In the theater,
language is sacred,'' said Ms. Kurtz, who won an Obie Award in May
for her performance off-Broadway in ``The Mineola Twins.'' ``On
film, what people say is really the least important thing. It's the
things that happen between the lines that are the most profound.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences require different methods of preparation. In
film, several actors said, the process generally amounts to
practically nothing at all. ``You meet the man who plays your
husband at 7:30 and immediately you start filming the scene where
he tells you he's leaving you,'' Ms. Kurtz said. ``You're expected
to still deliver under these circumstances. You're still expected
to create a fully rounded character.''
</P>
<P>
   Other actors, like Jennifer Jason Leigh, who starred in
``Cabaret'' earlier this season, say they prepare extensively,
doing research on their roles through reading or reporting, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their homework for movie roles, the actors said, they
are largely expected to undertake it by themselves, with little or
no rehearsal or acting direction. ``Film is all about working on
your own, coming up with everything that you can about the script,
relationships with other people, how you want the scene to go,''
said Baker, who appeared in the film ``Happiness'' and the
off-Broadway revival of ``That Championship Season.'' ``It's all
work done before you get to the set.''
</P>
<P>
   In theater, on the other hand, ``a director wouldn't consider a
play rehearsed unless he had an hour for every page of a script,''
Baker said. ``With film scripts, if you get a director who likes to
rehearse, you might spend two to three minutes per page and that's
your rehearsal,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   David Marshall Grant, an actor who played one of the first
recurring gay characters on a drama series on ``Thirtysomething''
and who appeared in ``Angels in America'' on Broadway, said it may
be best not even to attempt such preparation when working in
television or film. ``I have carefully planned things out and
thought about the most interesting choice I could make and when I
get on set, all it's doing is getting in the way,'' he said. ``The
decision to tap my foot to indicate nervousness may not even get in
the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Grant, who wrote the off-Broadway play
``Snakebit,'' argued that the best acting technique for film and
television may be no technique at all. ``The more you can relax and
forget that you're being filmed, the better off you're going to
be,'' he said. ``That's why you can take people off the street and
put them in a movie and they can be brilliant. Stage acting
requires a certain amount of technique. I'm not sure what
techniques there are in film acting other than being truthful. The
actors who do it best live their roles 24 hours a day, so there's
no entering and leaving a part. They just behave until the movie's
over.''
</P>
<P>
   In film, actors say, they need to develop greater powers of
concentration, because there are so many distractions on the set.
In theater _ with the exception of a few snoozers or
candy-wrapper-openers _ people are paying attention. ``Everybody's
looking at you and listening to you,'' Dennehy said. ``In film, you
can be doing an emotional and powerful scene while behind you, 25
guys are drinking coffee and nobody cares.''
</P>
<P>
   While working on her television series ``Sisters,'' which ran
until 1996, Ms. Kurtz said she simply grew accustomed to acting
amid activity. ``Someone fastening a body mike, somebody pinning my
costume, someone fixing my hair, someone powdering my nose, all two
seconds before a take,'' she said. ``I just got used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In theater, actors say audience members are far from passive
observers; they play a decisive role in the quality and energy of a
performance. As a result, actors often get asked ``How was the
house?'' meaning, how was the crowd. At one recent performance of
``Closer,'' for example, Ms. Richardson said she was thrown because
the audience laughed during the difficult final scene of Act I,
when she is breaking up with her husband. Usually, she said, there
is utter silence. ``How they respond makes you respond
differently,'' Ms. Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of give and take, of going through something with an
audience, actors say, is entirely lacking in film. Actors say they
never get to experience such immediate reaction to their film roles
as they are performing them. ``You're no longer part of the
dance,'' Grant said. ``You could be in Miami when someone else is
having this extraordinary relationship with you. And I'd rather be
there when it gets hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the nicest thing about film, actors say, is being able
to do a scene until it is right and never having to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'd like to say, `I got off on the wrong foot. Can
we just say cut and start again?''' Ms. Richardson said. ``That's
the great frustration, that you have to live with less than perfect
moments. The great satisfaction of film is at the end of the day
you've done it and for good or for bad you've accomplished the work
and it disappears into the ether.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many actors say, it is exactly because they
cannot stop and do it over _ because they have to make a scene work
while it's happening _ that theater keeps them coming back for
more. ``I love the terror of it, the fact that I don't know what's
going to happen moment to moment and I have to keep going no matter
what,'' Ms. Kurtz said. ``And that you are out there without a
net.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
