<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERSIDE-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHER ON FILM  
 (ADV: WITH CHER-MUSIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   aspect of Cher's career. She's got a whole film career to fall
back on if the hits ever stop. Here's a look at some of her best:
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Times'' (1967) _ Probably not one of her favorites, but
Sonny and Cher are goofy and endearing in this comic fantasy about
the duo making their first film. Plenty of musical numbers,
including an ``unplugged''-style ``I Got You Babe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come Back to the Five and Dime Jimmy Dean, Jimmy Dean'' (1982)
_ Robert Altman directed this twisty little fable about the reunion
of a James Dean fan club. Secrets unfold as the Dean disciples
gather in Texas, near the spot where the actor filmed ``Giant.''
Cher is both funny and poignant as the trash-mouthed Sissy, while
Sandy Dennis, Karen Black and Kathy Bates round out the fine
ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mask'' (1985) _ Cher is the mother of a child suffering from
facial disfigurement in a heartfelt performance that should have
won her an Oscar but didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suspect'' (1987) _ In the '70s, the thought of Cher as a
sober-minded public defender would have inspired laughs. In the
'80s, it made for a potent thriller that teamed her with Dennis
Quaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moonstruck'' (1987) _ She deservedly won the golden statuette
for this wistful romantic tale, scripted by John Patrick Shanley
(also an Oscar winner). The scene where she slaps a love-struck
Nicolas Cage and yells ``Snap out of it!'' is worth the price of a
rental alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mermaids'' (1990) _ A nifty coming-of-age story starring Cher
as a free-spirited mom, with Winona Ryder and Christina Ricci
first-rate as her two daughters. Cher's romance with Bob Hoskins is
sweetly underplayed, a nice touch. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
