<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9236 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIBURN-KIMMELMAN-TEX     06-09 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-KIMMELMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CRITIC AT THE KEYBOARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The piano recital took place on an autumn afternoon
in Seymour Bernstein's Upper West Side flat. It was the beginning
of a journey that would affect Michael Kimmelman profoundly.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman, chief art critic for The New York Times, had allowed
17 years to pass before reviving a serious interest in piano. He
had last played publicly during the 1981 Leschetizky Competition,
where he placed second, and had only lately returned to studying
with Bernstein, his childhood mentor.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bernstein who had encouraged his student to retest the
arena of performance, and now a dozen Times culture writers were
seated in Bernstein's living room, awaiting Kimmelman's musical
unveiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat to his left and turned the pages for him,'' recalls
Bernstein, ``and he went through a half-hour program like a veteran
pianist. He inspired himself and he inspired me, and the audience
was dumbstruck at the level of his playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kimmelman, 41, performs in the first round of the Cliburn
International Piano Competition for Outstanding Amateurs. Piano is
once again an essential part of his life. It has given Kimmelman a
refuge outside his work and altered his worldview. It has changed
the rhythm of his days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having gone back to music has been one of the most joyous
things that's ever happened in my life,'' Kimmelman says, sitting
at his desk on the fourth floor of the Times building. ``It's not
just the enormous pleasure of making music, it's also a sense of
being able to express myself in a way that can't happen in any
other aspect of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman's office is a glorified cubicle that he shares with
film critic Janet Maslin, though neither spends much time writing
here, he says. Stacks of art books cover his desk and shelves, but
otherwise there are no potential distractions _ no half-empty
coffee cups, no photographs of his 6-month-old son, Harry, whom he
wrote about in a recent essay for the Times magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing at the moment gives me more pleasure than sitting him
down in my lap at the piano, which he seems to like,'' says
Kimmelman, betraying a modicum of fatherly pride.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman's own lessons began when he was 5, in his family's
Greenwich Village apartment. His older half brother and his father
both had taken lessons from Bernstein, a close friend of the
family. Now it was Michael's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked to play piano,'' Kimmelman says, ``and then I spent my
entire childhood not practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, he hardly needed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael was captivating and always brilliant,'' says
Bernstein, a composer and associate professor in the New York
University graduate piano program. ``From the moment he struck his
first note on the keyboard, he infused it with a deep emotional
intention.''
</P>
<P>
   As an undergraduate history major at Yale, Kimmelman struggled
with whether to pursue a career in music. He applied to the Mannes
College of Music but then turned down his acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a pianist ... requires an enormous amount of narrow
concentration,'' he says. ``I felt my life as opening up at that
point, and I wasn't ready to narrow it down.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Leschetizky Competition, a national competition held
in New York City, Kimmelman turned away from piano and toward other
interests. He accepted a fellowship from Harvard and received a
master's degree in art history. He was pursuing a doctorate there
when the Atlanta Journal-Constitution offered him the job of music
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman had written for publication before _ mainly for the
architecture and design magazine ID. And while he considered
himself a dedicated academic (he assumed he would teach for a
living), he found himself both increasingly frustrated by the
``self-absorbed'' nature of academics and drawn to the idea of
engaging a broader public in intellectual debate.
</P>
<P>
   Enter journalism. Kimmelman took the job in Atlanta in the
mid-'80s, and within a matter of months, the Philadelphia Inquirer
had spirited him back north. Two years later, in 1988, he joined
the Times.
</P>
<P>
   But he would find himself increasingly unsuited for music
criticism. As a critic, he sat through upward of seven concerts a
week and was required to focus on their practical aspects _ looking
at the business of music, comparing one performance with another.
As a musician, he found this distracting. When the Times offered
him the opportunity to switch to art criticism, he did.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bernstein who nudged Kimmelman back to piano, three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like falling in love all over again,'' Kimmelman says.
It was ``a part of me that wasn't dead, it was just dormant. It was
a shock. I also found I could play better than I used to and with a
much deeper understanding of what I was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago in May, Kimmelman performed a sold-out concert for
the Chopin Foundation in New York, a momentous occasion for him
both personally and musically. He bought the Steinway grand piano
that he played that day, and the foundation invited him to give a
second concert this past spring.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman's audience had grown to hundreds in the Polish
Consulate from a handful in Bernstein's apartment. But both
experiences fulfilled a similar desire: to share the music with
people he cares for.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that relates to this competition in a way,'' he says,
``because in the end, what is this about? It's about making music
for other people.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
