<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Cosby, Tenn. _ The 23rd annual Dulcimer and Harp Festival is
Friday and Saturday at the Folklife Center of the Smokies. Music
(play or just listen), homemade food, crafts and nightly concerts.
423-625-9675.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ Riverbend Festival Friday through June 19
features more than 100 musical artists on five stages, sport
events, family activities, fine arts, food and fireworks.
423-265-4112 or www.chattanooga.net/cvb.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eufaula, Ala. _ Eufaula Jam '99 on Saturday, headlined by the
Atlanta Rhythm Section, will be held in scenic Old Creek Town Park
on Lake Eufaula. The concert, beginning at 11 a.m. Central Standard
Time with five regional bands, also will be broadcast live on the
Web at www.liveonthenet.com. 1-800-524-7529 or visit www.ebcchamber
</P>
<P>
   .org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jekyll Island, Ga. _ Headliners for the ninth annual Country
by the Sea Music Festival on Saturday are Sammy Kershaw, Toby Keith
and Marty Stuart. On the Jekyll Island Beach Deck. 1-800-841-6586
or www.jekyllisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Braselton, Ga. _ Chateau Elan's Swinging on the Grapevine
Summer Concert Series continues June 19 with ``Swing Night''
featuring Zoot and the Swingin' Suits (free swing lessons before
the concert). The series continues July 3, 10 and 31 and Aug. 7, 14
and 28 in the open-air pavilion next to the winery. All shows $25
per person. 770-932-0900 or 1-800-233-9463.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cherokee, N.C. _ The annual outdoor drama ``Unto These Hills''
opens Friday. The drama tells the story of the Cherokee people from
1540 through the 1800s. Through Aug. 21. 828-497-2111 or
www.dnet.net/(tilde)cheratt/tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blowing Rock, N.C. _ The June edition of Art in the Park on
Saturday at the American Legion Grounds behind Blowing Rock
Memorial Park features 120 regional arts and crafts exhibitors.
Free shuttles from Food Lion or Shoppes on the Parkway on U.S. 321.
828-295-7851.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tryon, N.C. _ The sixth annual Blue Ridge Barbecue Festival on
Friday and Saturday at Harmon Field will feature free lawn concerts
_ from country to zydeco, from bluegrass to rock 'n' roll. Also,
North Carolina State Barbecue Championship, Foothills Craft Fair
and Children's Fun Park. 828-859-6236.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pensacola, Fla. _ Fiesta of Five Flags through Saturday
celebrates the founding of Pensacola in 1559 by Don Tristan de Luna
with citywide events including a parade, music, sand castle
competition and children's activities. 850-433-6512 or
www.fiestafiveflags.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williamsburg, Va. _ The Yorktown Victory Center presents an
exhibition, ``The Washingtons of Colonial Virginia,'' in observance
of George Washington's death 200 years ago. The exhibition focuses
on the first president's ancestors in Virginia and their role in
the history of the colony. Through February. 1-888-593-4682.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richmond _ The Virginia Museum of Fine Arts presents the
exhibition ``The Splendors of Egypt,'' a panoramic view of one of
the world's oldest and most sophisticated civilizations, with more
than 200 masterpieces, some at least 5,000 years old. Through Nov.
28. 804-367-0878 or www.vmfa.state.va.us.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ Spoleto Festival USA fills historic
theaters, churches and outdoor venues with performances in opera,
dance, theater, jazz and symphonic and choral music. Through
Sunday. 843-722-2764 or www.spoletousa.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta _ The Container Store is hosting free ``Organized
Traveler'' workshops at 1 and 3 p.m. Saturday and 3 p.m. Sunday.
3255 Peachtree Road, 404-261-4776.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans _ The New Orleans Museum of Art presents ``Degas
and New Orleans: A French Impressionist in America'' through Aug.
29. In addition to works created in New Orleans during Degas' visit
with relatives in 1872, the exhibition includes paintings done by
Degas of relatives visiting France prior to his U.S. visit, and
examples of his most recognized subjects, such as opera and racing
scenes, completed after his return to Paris. 1-800-409-9959.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Augusta , Ga._ The Morris Museum of Art presents ``Robert
Stackhouse: Major Works 1969-1999,'' the first retrospective for
the painter and sculptor, through Aug. 22. 706-724-7501.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Macon , Ga._ ``Such Beautiful Things _ Highlights From the Hay
Porcelain Collection'' will be exhibited through July 18 at the
1859 Hay House, an 1859 Italianate Revival mansion that is now a
museum. 912-742-8155.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Petersburg, Fla. _ The exhibition ``Between the Skin and
the Distance: Four Contemporary Spanish Artists'' at the Salvador
Dali Museum features artists from Zaragoza and the Aragon region.
Through Sept. 19. 727-823-3767 or www.daliweb.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
