<HEADER>
A9241 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY109-COX     06-09 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY109-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beau Rivage full of beauty, but hotel is still ironing out kinks
 &HT;    By Sandra Eckstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILOXI, Miss. _ It really is as beautiful as Elizabeth Taylor
promised in those julep-accented TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   From the mosaic floors and soaring magnolias, thousands of
flowering blooms in the atrium, polished brass, exotic woodwork,
expensive fabrics, Spanish and Grecian marble and original artwork,
Beau Rivage, the newest Gulf Coast gambling resort is a visual
delight.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the grandest of the 13 Mississippi coast casinos. The
hotel boasts 1,780 rooms, 12 restaurants, a 31-slip marina, a
shopping promenade, a spa and salon, convention facilities, a large
concert hall and a permanent home for Cirque du Soleil with a
1,550-seat theater.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel and casino have been flooded with people since the
doors opened March 16. The resort aspires to five-star status, but
intense crowds and newly trained staff have caused some
difficulties, including long lines, dirty guest rooms and slow
service.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you can't deny the place looks great.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms are beautifully appointed with a huge bed covered with
a half-canopy. Tasteful hardwood furniture fills the space,
expensive draperies dress the windows and the large bathroom is
lined with marble. A double vanity sink, soaking tub and a large
separate shower room are luxurious. Little extra touches include
robes and slippers, a lighted magnifying mirror and built-in hair
dryer.
</P>
<P>
   But during our recent visit, the room's floors were not
vacuumed, gum was stuck on a bedroom tabletop and the beds were not
triple-sheeted, as promised in the resort's advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Bourland, the resort's director of public affairs,
acknowledges the hotel has had some initial problems. ``Every
property goes through these kinds of issues during their opening,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beau Rivage's hasn't exactly been a quiet opening either: The
hotel has been sold out every weekend since the second week it
opened.
</P>
<P>
   Bourland said heavy turnover in the housekeeping and food
service staffs in the first two months has exacerbated the
situation. The promised triple-sheeting, a luxury required to get a
five-star rating and appreciated by guests concerned with health
issues, has been suspended while Beau Rivage works out laundry
problems, he said. But the hotel plans to resume the service soon.
</P>
<P>
   The $650 million resort is affiliated with the Mirage Resorts
chain, which includes Las Vegas' Bellagio and Mirage resorts.
Bourland said housekeeping experts from Mirage resorts are being
brought in to help with training.
</P>
<P>
   Checking in or out of the hotel can present a challenge on
weekends, often taking more than 30 minutes. It can take just as
long to get your car from valet parking. Restaurants, especially
the buffets, can have waits of more than an hour on Fridays and
Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Bourland said Beau Rivage has increased staffing at the check-in
counters and valet parking, and is working to stabilize the
resort's work force.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the better restaurants are booked several weeks in
advance, so visitors wanting a fancy meal are advised to make early
reservations. But it's worth the effort _ food at the resort is
exceptional. And with a dozen to pick from, there are restaurants
to fit most any taste or yen. For the gambler who wants to get back
to the tables, small delis, several just off the casino playing
floor, serve quick, large sandwiches. There is an ice cream shop,
coffee shop and a micro brewery featuring a fine selection of beers
and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Want barbecue? Head to the Memphis Q. Asian cuisine? Try
Noodles. Japanese? Take Maku is for you. La Cucina serves Northern
Italian, Coral specializes in seafood and steaks and has the
coolest setting, with all four walls formed by giant aquariums.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Brad Hall, who said he has taken a few years off from
work to travel, was very impressed by Beau Rivage during visits in
March and April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the nicest one down there,'' he said on a flight to
Biloxi. ``It compares to the casinos in Las Vegas. It's not as big,
but it's as beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, of course, is there because of the casino, the reason
most people visit Biloxi. The casino has all the usual table games,
and the latest dizzying assortment of video games and slot
machines.
</P>
<P>
   But some guests have complained about the lack of no-smoking
areas on the gaming floor. Bourland said the casino is designating
no smoking areas, but that was too late for recent guests Pat and
John Hanes of Pensacola, Fla. The couple stayed at the hotel one
night, then switched to the Grand Casino, the area's largest and
most luxurious casino until Beau Rivage opened. Pat Hanes said she
preferred the no-smoking floor at the Grand. Both said they thought
the Beau Rivage casino was ``over-hyped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty, but somewhat overpriced,'' John Hanes said.
</P>
<P>
   If guests tire of gaming, there are other diversions available
without leaving the site. The resort has an expansive spa facility,
with state-of-the-art exercise equipment and a large assortment of
services, from massages and manicures to hair colorings and herbal
body polishes. The separate men's and women's saunas, steam baths,
hot tubs and plunge pools are clothing optional.
</P>
<P>
   Guests can pay $12 daily and use the tubs, plunge pools,
exercise equipment, sauna and steam room, or the facilities are
free with any other paid spa or salon service.
</P>
<P>
   The resort also hosts Las Vegas-style shows, at Las Vegas-style
prices. Alabama tickets were about $54 each; Vince Gill tickets
$64. And just last month, Cirque du Soleil opened ``Alegria'' in a
permanent theater at the resort, playing eight shows a week.
Tickets are $42.80 for adults and $26.75 for children under 12
(ages 5 and younger aren't permitted).
</P>
<P>
   The hotel has a number of clothing, jewelry, and gift shops, but
unless you've hit the jackpot and have money to burn, the prices
may deter you.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the resort's facilities are geared to adults, so those
seeking a family weekend might want to consider other options.
While some of the area casinos have elaborate, free baby-sitting
services, Beau Rivage has none.
</P>
<P>
   There is no kiddie-pool at the beautifully landscaped swim area.
Parents must either hold young children, or let them play on the
steps leading into the pool. The arcade has few games to entertain
those younger than 10. Only one shop, a Warner Bros. Studio Store,
has items of interest to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling is an adult activity and this is a resort,'' Bourland
said. ``And while we don't discourage people bringing children, we
consider our resort as more of a romantic getaway for couples, a
convention site for businesses, a destination for single travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much available on the Gulf Coast for families,''
he added. ``That's not necessarily what we do best.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourland said some of the start-up problems are beginning to
fade, although the crowds remain heavy on weekends. For now, he
recommends staying Sundays through Thursdays, when the hotel is
much quieter.
</P>
<P>
   Or just wait a few months until the novelty wears off. But do
consider a visit. It's as pretty as Liz promised.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Biloxi is a six-hour drive via I-85 to
Montgomery, I-65 to Mobile, and I-10. Nonstop airfares, with a
14-day advance purchase, are $59 each way on AirTran Airlines and
$188 round trip on Delta/Atlantic Southeast Airlines. There's a
free shuttle from the airport to the resort for AirTran passengers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beau Rivage information: Hotel rates are about $90
Sunday-Thursday nights. About $130 to $150 on Friday and Saturday
nights. Reservations: 1-888-567-6667. On the Web: www
</P>
<P>
   .beaurivageresort.com. Cirque du Soleil reservations:
1-888-566-7469.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other area attractions: There also are 20 golf courses,
deep-sea fishing, 26 miles of beach, Jefferson Davis' home
Beauvoir, and several charming historical areas with shops and
museums.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tourism information: Mississippi Gulf Coast Convention and
Visitors Bureau, 1-888-467-4853. On the Web: www.gulfcoast.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
