<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9244 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-REMODELING10-COX     06-09 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-REMODELING10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decisions, decisions: Renovation of own home presents tough
choices for pro
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't try this at home.
</P>
<P>
   That seems like odd advice coming from a remodeling pro. But
after renovating his 1930s Decatur (Ga.) home, Craig Kennedy admits
the job is no model for his clients. Although he and his wife,
Lisa, were pleased with the outcome, some decisions made along the
way proved inefficient and costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did things the hard way,'' said Kennedy, a partner in
HammerSmith, an Atlanta design/build firm. ``Like most homeowners,
we had no idea what we were getting into. Once you move in, it's
hard to renovate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, kitchens and baths, typically the most expensive _ and
disruptive _ remodeling projects, should be done while the house is
vacant. But like many young home buyers, the Kennedys couldn't
afford to do everything they wanted when they bought their Glendale
Estates home six years ago. So they tackled a variety of projects,
including the kitchen, in phases.
</P>
<P>
   That meant the renovation, like their tastes, continued to
evolve. Driving some of the changes were two family members _
Davis, 3, and Henry, 4 months _ who were born since they launched
the project.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other homeowners, the Kennedys didn't fall victim to the
typical remodeling pitfalls _ hiring a contractor without first
checking references, putting down too much money up front, failing
to put all terms in writing. But when the homeowner is in the
business, the process can be frustrating in other ways, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough remodeling for yourself. I'm exposed to so much
stuff every day in my work. I see it, and I want it,'' he said.
``So we had to make some tough decisions that I usually have to ask
my clients to do.''
</P>
<P>
   They started by making just enough improvements to make their
home attractive and functional.
</P>
<P>
   The 1937 house had some structural problems _ the attic sagged
about 4 inches, some structural sills were rotten _ that required
repairs. While the three bathrooms had never been updated, the
Kennedys chose to only ``jazz them up a little'' for now, he said,
painting the walls in decorative finishes.
</P>
<P>
   In a second phase, they replaced the siding, selecting vinyl the
same size as wood to make the exterior appear old, replaced the
windows and refinished the hardwood floors.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the Kennedys tackled finished attic space, where they
created a den and office. Vinyl floors, jalousie windows and
fluorescent lights were traded for wall-to-wall carpet, new windows
and track lights. They also opened the office space by vaulting the
ceiling and adding skylights.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the back yard, building terraces and retaining walls
to correct drainage.
</P>
<P>
   And finally there was that kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen of their dreams
</P>
<P>
   Craig wanted the kitchen to contain everything, from a fireplace
and breakfast area to appliances with the latest bells and
whistles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the remodeler's curse,'' said Lisa, an attorney turned
full-time mom.
</P>
<P>
   But finances required the couple to approach the room in phases
_ a process they don't regret because it gave them time to get to
know the space and determine their needs.
</P>
<P>
   They began by replacing its laminate countertops with granite
and installing a new sink. Open, stainless steel restaurant-style
shelves were added as temporary storage, but they wound up liking
them so much they kept them instead of hanging new wall cabinets.
``We really fought the traditional kitchen so we went without
them,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the floors, ceiling and walls, all inspired by
kitchens in Tuscany where the Kennedys once vacationed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest response we get is to the floor. When we moved in
we had no kids, just dogs, so we've since made it child proof,''
Lisa said of the Italian ceramic tile in three sizes and a combo of
colors, including rust, mauve, tan and gray, that hides dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedys opened up more of the attic to create a cathedral
ceiling with Tuscan-style cedar trusses, where track lighting was
installed to supplement canned fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Then the dangers of not having a master plan for the room began
to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Dream or nightmare?
</P>
<P>
   New windows had been installed on each side of the stove, but
one later had to be removed when the couple decided to purchase a
48-inch wide Sub Zero refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we decided the walls were the problem,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   So they added old-style ceramic tile in a running-bond pattern
half way up the walls. Above, they applied an old plaster finish,
made of plaster of Paris, latex paint and tinted wax, to the
Sheetrock.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of surfaces here,'' Craig said, ``but when you
spend a lot of time in the kitchen, things like that and proper
lighting really matter.''
</P>
<P>
   And spending time there proved something else: The Kennedys
wanted an eat-in kitchen, but a table and chairs made the new
kitchen crowded. Craig's parents suggested they convert the
adjacent dining room into a breakfast room and open it to the
kitchen by removing a wall. In place of the table, an island with
roll-out shelves gave them much-needed counter space.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, lack of planning, along with special features such
as roll-out windows with no center bar, a custom-designed range
hood and a child-proof dishwasher, made the $100,000 kitchen
project far more expensive than planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you manage a project, you can get good results,'' Craig
said. ``We did it all in phases so that spread it all out.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-learned lessons haven't cooled the Kennedys' remodeling
fever; they next plan to expand their bedroom to make a master
suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're getting close to being done,'' he said. ``We've
created a lifestyle out of renovation, so when we're done, does
that mean we move for a new lifestyle?''
</P>
<P>
   The couple don't think so. ``We like this house,'' Craig said.
``It isn't perfect . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   But what old house is?
</P>
<P>
   B E F O R E Y O U R E M O D E L
</P>
<P>
   Remodeling can be frustrating enough with the barrage of
decisions and constant disruption that accompany a project. But
those challenges pale in comparison with being victimized by
unreliable contractors and shoddy workmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Before launching a renovation project, be sure to:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check with real estate agents for property values in your
neighborhood before deciding how much you should invest.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Develop a realistic budget. Add at least 10 percent because
most remodels run over either from inaccurate budget forecasting or
from additions to the original plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask friends for references on contractors they have used and
inspect their work.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Interview several contractors who are licensed and have
Workers' Compensation and general liability insurance. Ask to see
licenses and insurance certificates as proof. All general estimates
for the work should be free.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask contractors how long their companies have been in business
(It typically takes at least five years to establish a financially
sound business).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check court records to determine whether the contractor has
been sued.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure you can communicate well with the contractor because
misunderstanding can lead to cost overruns and delays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Insist on a written contract once you hire a contractor that
indicates the estimated start and completion dates and descriptions
of the work, materials and prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Check to see if the contract includes a warranty covering
workmanship and materials.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ask for working drawings to ensure your ideas have been
properly translated.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure no work is done until the contractor purchases the
necessary building permits.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't pay cash for work and don't pay more than one-third of
the cost in advance, one-third midway into the project and the
balance upon completion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't sign a completion certificate for the job before it has
been inspected and properly completed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
