<HEADER>
A9245 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-EXCHANGE-2TAKES     06-09 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EXCHANGE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA SUSPENDS SOME CULTURAL EXCHANGES, CITING NATO ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Mass., Pa.)  (Eds: Also moving in `i' category.) 
(rk) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years of negotiations with Chinese cultural
representatives, the American Ballet Theater was close to a deal
last month to piggyback five performances in Beijing onto a July
tour of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Then came NATO's errant bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Beijing visit was off _ ``shelved at this
sensitive stage'' by China's Ministry of Culture, a Chinese arts
representative, Chen Jixin, informed the ballet company, blaming
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   At least three other major American-Chinese cultural exchanges,
involving the Boston Symphony Orchestra, Lincoln Center Jazz
Orchestra, and the New York Choral Society, were also put off by
the Chinese after the May 7 attack, which killed three Chinese
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In communications with some of the groups, Chinese officials
linked the broken plans to widespread outrage over the embassy
bombing, which NATO officials called a mistake made because of an
outdated maps.
</P>
<P>
   Arts managers say it could take years to reschedule the
disrupted performances.
</P>
<P>
   Yu Shuning, a spokesman for the Chinese Embassy in Washington,
said, ``After the bombing the whole Chinese population was
extremely sad so it was not appropriate to listen to music.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that China had demanded an investigation into the
bombing and that once the issue was settled ``the atmosphere will
improve and things will go back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   But he and other Chinese officials said cultural exchanges would
be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events weren't canceled but postponed by mutual consent,''
said Gao Qi of the China Performing Arts Agency's Culture and
Entertainment Co. under the Ministry of Culture in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   With the Boston Symphony scheduled to arrive May 12, days after
the bombing, he said in a telephone interview, ``Beijing citizens
were infuriated and the environment was not friendly.'' The
orchestra was also worried about its security, he said. In the end,
he said, ``we decided to postpone the performance'' although both
sides were talking about rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Culture and Art Corp., which is now semiprivate
but retains some government ties, another Chinese official, Zhang
Hang, said the bombing was at least partly to blame for what he
called the ``temporarily postponed'' performances of American
Ballet Theater and the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that financial concerns had also played a part. He
said no other American groups were scheduled to visit China in
coming months but that a violinist from Germany, which is also a
member of NATO, had just played a successful concert without
incident in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Yu said that officials were not aware of any canceled visits by
Chinese groups and that apart from the ``bad atmosphere'' from the
bombing, ``we did not stop cultural exchanges.''
</P>
<P>
   With the proliferation of private cultural contacts between
China and the United States, Chinese and State Department officials
said, there is no master list of bilateral exchanges and therefore
no way to say how many arrangements have been disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   One major Chinese-American artistic landmark that stirred
controversy last year _ a production of the 16th-century classic
opera ``The Peony Pavilion'' _ is not affected by the political
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai officials had blocked the production from coming to the
Lincoln Center Festival last year, but a new 20-hour production
with two Chinese stars who have been in the United States for some
time will proceed as scheduled next month, festival officials said.
</P>
<P>
   While the de-invitations to the Americans were generally phrased
politely and presented as postponements rather than cancellations,
the crowded booking calendars of leading ensembles means that the
trips cannot be reconstituted easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to try it again in 2001,'' said John Lawson,
executive director of the New York Choral Society. The society, an
avocational chorus, had spent more than a year assembling 230
singers from New York, Philadelphia and Kansas City to join 310
Chinese vocalists and instrumentalists for a mammoth performance of
Mahler's 8th Symphony in Shanghai on July 30, to be followed by a
recital of Brahms' ``German Requiem'' in Beijing on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   On June 3, Lawson received a letter from the society's Chinese
host, the Shanghai Acting Co., saying that the joint performance
``cannot be carried on now because we have not received the
approval from the relevant administration till now'' and delicately
suggesting a postponement. The singers were able to turn in their
$2,300 airline tickets but lost about about $100 each in
nonrefundable outlays.
</P>
<P>
   Yu, the Chinese Embassy spokesman, said that while certain
bilateral contacts on military affairs, disarmament, security and
human rights were officially suspended in protest over the bombing,
no break in cultural relations was announced.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official, who spoke only on the condition of
anonymity, agreed that cultural relations did not appear in
jeopardy and that American Fulbright scholars, for example, were
still being welcomed by China. But he said that many of today's
arts exchanges were on a private basis outside the purview of the
American government.
</P>
<P>
   Claudette Donlon, general manager of the American Ballet
Theater, said the company was wrapping up a contract for a visit
``literally years in the works,'' when the bombing took place. The
company of about 125 was booked for 12 performances in and around
Tokyo in early July and had arranged to go on to China afterward
for at least five performances, some in the Great Hall of the
People.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  That all came to an end on May 11 with a fax from the China
National Culture and Art Corp. whose representative, Chen, told Ms.
Donlon that due to the ``Chinese tragic experience in Yugoslavia,''
American cultural programs were being shelved by the Culture
Ministry. However, he held out hope for another booking, including
possibly a separate tour of China by next February.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Herman, a manager at ICM Artists in Manhattan who often
works with American Ballet Theater, said that after the canceled
date, the Chinese had inquired about booking a smaller ballet
production at no fee, suggesting that financial concerns played
some part in the withdrawn invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herman said that two other of her projects involving the
Chinese were in some doubt in the wake of the bombing, a
cooperative venture between American Ballet Theater and the
National Ballet of China, and a plan for another Chinese dance
company, which she declined to name, to come to the United States
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra, with Wynton Marsalis, had
been scheduled to perform from July 13-20 in Shanghai, Guangzhou
and Beijing, but said it had agreed to suspend the tour.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Symphony suffered perhaps the most precipitous
cancellation. Last in China 20 years ago, the orchestra and its
conductor, Seiji Ozawa _ who was born in China but is Japanese _
were in Tokyo and planning to move on to Beijing when the Belgrade
bombing set off street protests and rock throwing at the American
Embassy in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Volpe, the orchestra's managing director, said he spent
hours trying to contact American officials and finally concluded
the visit was too risky and had to be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have arrived just as the ashes of the victims were
coming home,'' he said. Ozawa did travel to China alone to teach
some master classes and conduct a student orchestra and was well
received.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhang Yu, general director of the China Performing Arts
Agency, faxed a letter to the orchestra on May 9 saying: ``This
barbarous atrocity of NATO has invoked the utmost indignation of
the Chinese government and people. As such, we believe the
favorable atmosphere for this China tour at the moment is no longer
there, and no longer is it appropriate for the tour to be conducted
as originally scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
