<HEADER>
A9247 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN10-COX     06-09 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Our flowers furnish more than furniture ever could
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From time to time Lyn and I get into those . . . let's call them
discussions about which is more demanding, house or garden. Which
calls for more work. You can guess which side I'm on.
</P>
<P>
   She Who Does Not Garden But Appreciates (and that's the way I
like it; I've always believed in one gardener to a garden) talks
about what a long, hard job it is, towing a vacuum cleaner from
room to room, floor to floor. I point out that it's no picnic
dragging a big old Japanese maple from site to site, trying to find
a home for it in 90-degree temperatures. Well, mopping floors all
through the house wears you out, she retorts. Yeah, and so does
wetting the ground all around a parched garden.
</P>
<P>
   And so it has gone for years, as we debate the merits of taking
care of our respective domains. (She does not garden, but she's
starting to get opinions: ``You pruned one limb too many off that
dogwood.'')
</P>
<P>
   The other day, however, we broke new ground, focusing not on the
work required to keep a house or garden going but on the emotional
value of what's in the house and garden _ furniture vs. flowers. We
achieved rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of conversation you have when you're taking
stock of what you have, or when you're thinking of what you'd face
_ physically and psychologically _ if you moved, or when you're
just trying to get rid of stuff, lighten your load.
</P>
<P>
   Our conversation, part practical, part philosophical, was
launched as we dove into a weekend effort to pare down closets,
clear pathways through mountains of office papers.
</P>
<P>
   What about this blue sofa in the parlor, I said. We've had it
since Washington. Would we keep it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It could go,'' answered Lyn. ``I have no emotional attachment
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The same went for television sets, of course, and all other
electronic pieces. The kitchen table, various chairs. Most of
what's in the house was expendable, leavable, in our hypothetical
conversation. There were, of course, exceptions _ recorded music,
books and pictures, which are in a category of their own; you just
have to keep them. And the big dining room table of solid oak,
along with a 100-year-old wooden chest and a tall painted bookcase.
</P>
<P>
   A common thread that wove through our short list of keepers was
uniqueness. Unlike most of our furnishings, these things cannot be
replaced. And even if they are not the only pieces of their kind,
they feel like it.
</P>
<P>
   In the garden, there is no doubt; each plant is one of a kind in
ways that furniture cannot be.
</P>
<P>
   Each plant has a story, a history. Most important, they, like
people, grow.
</P>
<P>
   Some are passed from one friend or relative to another. As do
all gardeners, I look at my plants and see connections.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the English oak sent through the mail by old friends from
Massachusetts a few years ago. It was bare-root, wrapped in
newspaper, a spindly little thing. Now, it grows stronger each
year, as do the memories of good times with good friends.
</P>
<P>
   There's the black bamboo, shared from a hugely graceful mother
plant one autumn nearly a decade back. One cane and a few rhizomes
is how it began. Now, there are enough canes to form a fine clump;
they multiply like the conversations and meals we've shared with
the bamboo sharers.
</P>
<P>
   Many plants came from nurseries, which my car refused to pass
during jaunts around the region. Some were just babies when I
hauled them to the garden, dug holes for them, pampered them,
watched them grow and change. The little twice-blooming cherry tree
that was just a short stick several years ago now stares into my
second-story office window. The 2-foot-high native azalea I bought
during a visit to Fairhope, Ala., has doubled its height and its
sweet floral output. A sparse patchwork of dwarf mondo planted
about five years ago has, little by little, woven into a quilt of
green in a space out back.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike furniture, plants need to see us often _ though,
admittedly, not as often as we need to see them. There is a
distinct and necessary interaction between plants and people that
can never exist between furniture and people. Even if those people
are artists or master crafters. Gardeners birth, nurture, feed,
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Lyn agreed. As she put it: ``I didn't grow that couch.''
</P>
<P>
   So furniture vs. flowers is an easy call. Can we settle the
debate centering on house chores vs. garden chores? Not without a
lot of work.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   (at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
