<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zoos' news: Exotic animal exhibits blossom
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, June13
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want to get really ``wild'' this summer? We're not talking about
beer blasts on the beach or skinny-dipping by the light of the
August moon. We're talking about locking eyes with a 400-pound
gorilla, watching hippopotamuses paddle daintily (yes, daintily)
around a tropical lagoon and trading growls with a ferocious tiger
or two.
</P>
<P>
   These and other exotic beasts can be found in new zoo exhibits
across the country. Several zoological parks and aquariums are
beefing up their facilities in anticipation of the busy summer
season:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The San Diego Zoo recently unveiled its $4.4 million Ituri
Forest exhibit, a two-acre habitat modeled after Africa's Congo
River Basin. Visitors not only get an underwater view of those
surprisingly graceful hippos, but they can commune with forest
buffaloes, spotted-necked otters and great blue turacos.
(Information: 619-234-3153 or www.sandiegozoo.org.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Philadelphia Zoo opens its 2.5-acre, $24 million Primate
Reserve on July 1. Built to resemble an abandoned timber mill, the
reserve will house 11 species of primates, including western
lowland gorillas and Sumatran orangutans. There are also lemur,
marmoset and tamarin exhibits, with no barriers between animal and
man. (215-243-1100 or www.philadelphiazoo.org.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Closer to Atlanta, the Jacksonville Zoological Gardens plans
to open a new animal hospital in August. The $1.5 million facility
comes equipped with a viewing window where visitors can watch
medical staff treat the animals. There are also plans to expand the
primate compound by early August. (904-757-4463 or www.jaxzoo.org.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some big cats have new digs in Texas. The Dallas Zoo recently
unveiled its $4.5 million Exxon Endangered Tiger Habitat. The
one-acre rain forest habitat is home to Sasha and Paul, two rare
Sumatran tigers. (214-670-5656 or www.dallas-zoo.org.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Many of our finned and flippered friends have found a home
near Cincinnati. The just-opened Newport Aquarium in Newport, Ky.,
boasts more than 11,000 aquatic residents. And its innovative
Surrounded by Sharks tunnel gives visitors a 360-degree view of
tiger, lemon, nurse and other sharks. (606-261-7444 or
www.newportaquarium.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
