</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LANDMINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV TROOPS WILL RETURN TO KOSOVO FOR MINE-CLEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The land mine threat in Kosovo is so serious that
NATO wants hundreds of Yugoslav troops to return to the province to
help remove minefields, Pentagon officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace agreement signed by NATO and Yugolsav forces,
Yugoslav military units are required to remove as many mines as
possible as they withdraw from the province and provide NATO with
maps detailing the locations of minefields.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will certainly be responsible for identifying mine fields
and clearing them to the extent possible,'' Walter Slocombe, the
Pentagon's under secretary of defense for policy, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yugoslav withdrawal, NATO and Yugolsav commanders will
meet to decide ``how a relatively small number _ hundreds not
thousands'' of Yugoslav troops would return to Kosovo to clear more
mines, as required by the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is yet to come,'' Slocombe added.
</P>
<P>
   The 50,000 NATO troops entering Kosovo and the returning
refugees will face an unknown quantity of minefields and explosive
booby-traps planted by Yugoslav troops. There is no accurate tally
of how many land mines are scattered throughout Kosovo but some
estimates run to the tens of thousands. Conducting a ``mine
census'' will be one of the first missions for NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said Wednesday that there were
reports that Yugoslav forces were still laying mines this week.
``We'll have to be very careful in the early days about making sure
that the routes are well cleared,'' Bacon added.
</P>
<P>
   Citing reports from ethnic Albanian refugees, the office of the
U.N. High Commission for Refugees said recently that Yugoslav
forces have placed land mines in ``an indeterminate number of
locations'' within Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The organization said land mines were ``certainly'' planted
along Kosovo's borders with Albania and Macedonia, the major routes
for returning refugees and the NATO forces that will protect them.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. office added that in order to safely return some 1.6
million ethnic Albanian Kosovars to their homes, ``land mines must
be cleared.''
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the peace deal require Yugoslavia to provide NATO
with maps detailing the locations of minefields. However, many were
laid in the heat of battle between Yugoslav forces and the Kosovo
Liberation Army, and Pentagon officials fear that there aren't
definitive maps for these.
</P>
<P>
   That's why among the first U.S. forces to enter Kosovo will be
U.S. Marines equipped with mine-clearing equipment, including large
armored land movers to bulldoze a pathway for refugees and troops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A contingent of about 1,900 U.S. Marines and 1,700 Army troops
will be the first wave of U.S. forces sent to Kosovo. President
Clinton has promised a force of 7,000 U.S. Army peackeepers. Of the
NATO allies, the United Kingdom is supplying the largest force _
12,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace plan, Kosovo would be carved up into five
sectors. The United Kingdom will be responsible for the largest
sector, about 50 percent of Kosovo, including the capital of
Pristina, while the United States, France, Italy and Germany will
control equal segments of the remaining half.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. section will be along the Macedonian and Serbian
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a province of Serbia, which is the dominant republic
in Yugoslavia. NATO bombing over the last 11 weeks was intended to
halt ethnic killings and removals by Serb troops against the ethnic
Albanian population of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Minefields were a major impediment for returning refugees in
Bosnia where only 50,000 mines out of an estimated 1 million have
been unearthed and deactivated in the last three years. Some
estimates indicate that it will take another 20 years to rid Bosnia
of land mines set during the 1992-95 civil war among Serbs, Croats
and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
