<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SUMMERATTRACTI     06-09 1747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SUMMERATTRACTIONS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A roundup of ideas for warm-weather fun
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, June 13
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONE WORLD, MANY RHYTHMS
</P>
<P>
   Joan Baez, Joan Armatrading, Johnny Clegg and Taj Mahal head up
a roster of more than 40 international acts appearing at the WOMAD
USA Festival, held for the second year in a row at Marymoor Park in
Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   From July 30 through Aug. 1, the 500-acre park (about 15 miles
east of Seattle) will host musicians and dancers from Africa, Asia,
Australia, Europe and North and South America. There also will be
art workshops, ethnic crafts and international cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1980 by British rocker Peter Gabriel, WOMAD, which
stands for World of Music and Dance, has taken its multicultural
road show to such far-flung locales as Australia, South Africa,
Indonesia and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tickets are $25 for a one-day pass or $65 for a
three-day pass. Call 206-628-0888.
</P>
<P>
   WHOOPI,
</P>
<P>
   WINFREY IN WAX
</P>
<P>
   As if Las Vegas isn't synthetic enough, famed London wax museum
Madame Tussaud's is opening a branch in the Nevada gambling mecca
in mid-July. Sculptures of such disparate celebs as Babe Ruth,
Bruce Springsteen, Oprah Winfrey and Cybill Shepherd (?) will greet
visitors with fixed smiles in themed sections.
</P>
<P>
   Witness a fantasy fight between Muhammad Ali and Evander
Holyfield in the ``Sports Arena'' section, then bop on over to
``The Big Night'' for a Hollywood soiree with Whoopi Goldberg and
Arnold Schwarzenegger. (How can you tell the Schwarzenegger figure
is fake? It's more expressive than the real thing.) The ``Finale''
is a multimedia tribute to Las Vegas legends such as Tony Bennett,
Tom Jones (at left) and, of course, Siegfried and Roy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: The museum, located in the Venetian Resort Hotel
and Casino, will be open 10 a.m.-10 p.m. daily. Admission: $12.50.
702-414-1000.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN FESTS
</P>
<P>
   If you think the Edinburgh International Festival is about
haggis and caber tossing, think again. The Scottish capital's
annual highland fling, which this year runs Aug. 15-Sept. 4 , is
classy and then some.
</P>
<P>
   The 167 performances range from classic ballets to contemporary
Chinese opera to experimental theater. Highlights include a concert
by the Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra, returning to the festival
after a 23-year absence; a production of the Puccini opera
``Turandot,'' directed by Japanese choreographer Saburo
Teshigawara; and performances of ``Giselle'' and ``Sleeping
Beauty'' by the Cullberg Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Nary a sheep entrail graces the menu at Cafe Hub, the chichi
bistro located in the Festival Centre. But peckish festivalgoers
can dine on barley and root broth; potato, pumpkin and green bean
pie; and bread and butter pudding with raisin confit.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tickets for most shows start at $3.
011-44-131-4732000 or www.eif.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   The annual du Maurier Quebec City Summer Festival dances to a
decidedly wilder beat. From July 8-18, the streets of Quebec City
will rock to the rhythms of more than 400 international acts,
including African percussion ensembles, French and Canadian pop
groups, folksingers and jazz combos. There will also be street
performers, circus acts and lots of international cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   A partial list of performers, including folkie cult faves Kate
and Anna McGarrigle, is available on the festival's Web site,
www.infofestival.com. More acts should be added in coming days.
Past festival lineups have included superstars such as Celine Dion
and Paul McCartney.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: A $6 festival pass is good for entry into all
shows. 1-888-992-5200 or www.infofestival.com.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC IN THE AIR
</P>
<P>
   Even world-renowned British orchestras need a little sun and fun
every once in a while. That's one reason why the London Symphony
Orchestra has made Daytona Beach, Fla., its ``official American
summer home'' since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Every July, the esteemed ensemble ventures to the coastal
Florida playground. This year's series of concerts, held at the
Peabody Auditorium and the Ocean Center in Daytona Beach from July
31 through Aug. 7, range from classic Beethoven and Mozart to light
orchestral pop. For the Aug. 7 series finale, Cincinnati Pops
conductor Erich Kunzel teams up with the LSO for a salute to
Hollywood. The program includes music from ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _
The Phantom Menace'' and ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerts are part of the 1999 Florida International
Festival, which also features performances by cabaret singer and
former ``Designing Women'' star Dixie Carter, saucy Cajun combo
Beausoleil and the Martha Graham Dance Ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tickets for the London Symphony Orchestra
concerts are $19-$55; other performers $12-$35. 904-257-7790 or
www.fif-lso.org.
</P>
<P>
   For the third year, the majestic Biltmore Estate in Asheville,
N.C., is the site of the diverse Summer Evenings concert series. As
the sun drops behind the surrounding mountains, music fans will
gather at the estate's south terrace to hear famous names from the
worlds of jazz, pop and swing.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, the Washington Symphony Orchestra kicks off the
series with ``Voices of Freedom,'' a concert of patriotic music
capped off by a fireworks display. Fluegelhorn player Chuck
Mangione plays his hit ``Feels So Good'' and other contemporary
jazz tunes on Aug. 7. Carolina country-bluegrass great Doc Watson
picks with Kathy Mattea on Aug. 14. The series closes on a swinging
note on Aug. 28 with the big band sounds of the Tommy Dorsey
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tickets, $35. Concerts begin at 8 p.m. Call
828-274-6311 for reservations.
</P>
<P>
   LIVE FROM
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN CENTER
</P>
<P>
   Stamina is the key to enjoying Lincoln Center Festival 99, a
daunting 2 1/2-week extravaganza of theater, dance and musical
performances at New York's premier cultural venue. This year the
festival, which runs July 7-25, hosts two marathon events: a
production of the 20-hour Chinese opera ``Peony Pavilion,'' staged
by Chen Shi-Zheng, and ``House Full o' Praise,'' a nine-concert
overview of African-American gospel music.
</P>
<P>
   Other lengthy presentations include a four-part tribute to
minimalist composer Steve Reich, and the New York Philharmonic
performing the complete Beethoven piano concerti, with pianist
Emanuel Ax. The Philharmonic will also perform the U.S. premiere of
``In Memory of Yitzhak,'' a choral and symphonic work dedicated to
assassinated Israeli leader Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Should one remain unquenched after this cultural deluge, there's
the airborne ballet of Kayassine, a French trapeze troupe, and the
Gate Theatre's production of Chekov's ``Uncle Vanya,'' revamped by
hot Irish playwright Brian Friel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 212-546-2656 (general information), 212-721-6500
(CenterCharge ticket agency). Web site: www.lincolncenter.org.
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   AND ARTIFACTS
</P>
<P>
   Just because the kids are out of school for the summer doesn't
mean they should take a break from learning. Why not take them to
see one of these new exhibits, on display at museums around the
South?
</P>
<P>
   Russian royalty comes to Mobile, Ala., with the exhibition
``Nicholas and Alexandra: The Last Imperial Family of Tsarist
Russia.'' This collection of pre-communist artifacts from the
Romanov dynasty, more than 700 pieces gathered from international
museums and private collections, made its Bible Belt debut Saturday
at the Mobile Civic Center. Highlights include a 190-foot panoramic
painting of Moscow, the 1917 letter of abdication written by
Nicholas II and several decorative pieces designed by Karl Faberge.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Open 9 a.m.-8 p.m. daily (last entry at 6 p.m.),
through Nov. 14. $14.95 adults, $13.45 senior citizens, $8.95
college students, $4 children (grades K-12). 1-888-395-0005 or
www.nicholasandalexandra.com.
</P>
<P>
   Walk like an Egyptian and remember to invite your mummy to the
``Splendors of Ancient Egypt'' exhibition now showing at the
Virginia Museum of Fine Arts in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   This extensive display includes a gilded sarcophagus dating to
1490 B.C., an 18-foot papyrus scroll from the Egyptian Book of the
Dead, ancient limestone urns and an unwrapped mummy.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors may also want to check out the IMAX film ``Mysteries of
Egypt,'' playing at the nearby Science Museum of Virginia. Narrated
by Omar Sharif, the 45-minute movie explores the legends
surrounding figures such as Nefertiti and King Tutankhamen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Showing 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Thursdays, 10
a.m.-6 p.m. Fridays-Sundays through Nov. 28. $15 adults, $8
students 13-18, $2 children 4-12. 1-888-349-7882. ``Mysteries of
Egypt'' shows five times daily through Dec. 3. Packages for
exhibition and movie are available. 1-800-659-1727.
</P>
<P>
   When Parisian impressionist painter Edgar Degas visited New
Orleans in 1872, he fell under the spell of the lazy, hazy
Louisiana city. He felt so comfortable that he painted 24 works
during his six-month stay, including ``A Cotton Office in New
Orleans.'' That great work is the centerpiece of the New Orleans
Museum of Art's current exhibition ``Degas and New Orleans: A
French Impressionist in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with FrancoFete, Louisiana's statewide celebration of
300 years of French influence, the exhibit features 16 other works
painted by Degas during his stateside sojourn. Photographs, jewelry
and drawings relating to the painter's American family (his mother
was born in New Orleans) also are included.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Open 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Sundays through Aug.
29. $10 adults, $9 senior citizens and college students, $5
children 3-17. Call 1-800-409-9959 or visit www.ticketmaster.com.
</P>
<P>
   The 2 3/4-ton ``Monument to Victor Hugo'' is the centerpiece of
an exhibition of sculptures by Auguste Rodin at the Cummer Museum
of Art and Gardens in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioned in 1889, Rodin's mammoth sculpture pays tribute to
France's most beloved author. Originally cast in plaster, it was
recast in bronze in 1952, after Rodin's death. Nineteen more of the
sculptor's works _ in bronze, marble, plaster and terra cotta _
round out the collection, which is on display through Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Open 10 a.m.-9 p.m. Tuesdays and Thursdays; 10
a.m.-5 p.m. Wednesdays, Fridays and Saturdays; noon-5 p.m. Sundays.
$6 adults, $4 senior citizens and military personnel, $3 students,
$1 children 5 and under. 904-356-6857.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
