<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
repeating to fix slug in notes field (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A languid, sultry air mass will continue to stifle the Deep
South on Thursday. In the western Gulf States, scattered showers
and thunderstorms will develop across east Texas and southern
Louisiana in concert with the leading edge of the sea breeze moving
inland. With lethargic steering winds 18,000 feet aloft, storms
will move slowly, setting the stage for moderately heavy rains and
flash flooding in spots. Isolated waterspouts may accompany
thunderstorms over coastal waters.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, sultry conditions with widely separated
thunderstorms will persist in the eastern Gulf and Southeast
States. Storms will be more active along the east coast of Florida
and the eastern Gulf Coast from Mississippi to the panhandle of
Florida, where the sea breeze acts as a catalyst to lift very humid
air. In the southern Appalachians, a few storms may approach severe
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, isolated thunderstorms will develop over the
Middle West, with the most active weather erupting just ahead of a
cool front approaching the western Great Lakes and upper
Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Any vestiges from this week's hot spell in the Northeast will
fade Thursday as a south-southwestward moving cool front reaches
the Middle Atlantic States. A stripe of low clouds along and behind
the cool front will span from the northern Middle Atlantic Seaboard
to parts of the central Appalachians. Meanwhile, clouds will
crumble in northern and central New England as cool, dry air
filters south from a high pressure system over the Gulf of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Raleigh Heat
</P>
<P>
   The temperature rose to 100 degrees in Raleigh, N.C., on Tuesday
for the earliest reading of 100 degrees since records began in
1944. It also marked the first time the temperature reached the
century mark since August 14, 1995, nearly four years ago.
Raleigh's average temperature from late June until mid-August is
nearly 90 degrees. It is surprising that for three consecutive
summers, the mercury never rose more than 10 degrees above normal.
The heat wave will persist Thursday, but cooler air from the
northeast should keep temperatures closer to 80 degrees Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
