<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9258 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-HONEY11-COX     06-09 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-HONEY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honey is all the buzz
 &HT;    WITH FOOD-HONEYRECIPES
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EBANON, Ohio _ The honey bees have polished off the appetizers,
the spring dandelions and honey locust, and now they're ready for
the main course _ the clover.
</P>
<P>
   Roaming over pastures a mile or two away from home, they're
gathering the nectar that provides the mild taste of honey produced
and sold in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of what we eat, there is a season _ even for honey. In
early May, the only honey in tended hives was at the bottom,
reserved for the bees. But then flats to collect the fresh nectar
were installed in the top of each hive. The bees went to work as
the Miami Valley broke into bloom.
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks, Ray Alley, a beekeeper who sells his honey at
the Warren County Farm Market, will be able to start bottling this
year's production of an estimated 700 quarts.
</P>
<P>
   Alley has hives in six locations throughout Warren County,
including nine hives at the back of his lot in a strip housing
development. That may seem like an odd place to raise a
half-million honey bees, given that their home is within a few feet
of neighbors and close to a kid's climbing gym.
</P>
<P>
   A wooden fence separates the hives from view, but bees have no
regard for a fence.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, neighbors working in their yards do sometimes get stung.
</P>
<P>
   It goes with the territory, which is why Alley's good-neighbor
policy is a periodic gift of honey. Once a new neighbor threatened
to sue him, but the man found out what Alley already knew: ``Ohio
is an agricultural state, and I can have bees anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been working with the bees for 19 years and moved from
Phillipsburg to Lebanon 12 years ago because he thought the
abundant pastures of alfalfa for horse farms would be a source of
nectar for his bees. Then he found out farmers cut the alfalfa
before it flowers.
</P>
<P>
   So he settles for a July harvest of mild clover honey and a
September harvest of honey made from the nectar of goldenrod and
asters.
</P>
<P>
   What he sells is raw honey, merely filtered to strain out any
odd bee parts left behind in the comb. The honey is spun out of the
comb with a centrifuge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the cheapest honey,'' he says. ``But it's pure local
honey and it's raw honey.''
</P>
<P>
   The clover honey that is summer's crop is what most people think
of as honey. It is mild and sweet, right for hot biscuits or, Alley
says, dribbled over ice cream. The fall harvest is more fragrant
with a more assertive taste, and he recommends it for baking or
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Beelieve it or not
</P>
<P>
   _ A bee lives four to six weeks and never sleeps. The single
bee's lifetime foraging yields only a twelfth of a teaspoon of
honey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bees, like all creatures, are subject to illnesses. Mites are
a problem that require treatment with antibiotics. Responsible
beekeepers shut down honey collection while the bees are being
treated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Raw honey, available from small producers, is minimally heated
and filtered. Commercial honey is sometimes a blend and often is
pasteurized to extend shelf life and filtered for clarification.
Unscrupulous dealers may add corn syrup to the honey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flower children of the '60s adopted ``raw'' honey as a natural
alternative to processed sugar, but honey has its down side, too.
Because it clings to teeth, it rots teeth faster than sucrose, and
raw honey has also been linked to a form of botulism, which is why
health practitioners advise not giving honey to children younger
than 2.
</P>
<P>
   _ It is difficult to pinpoint the source of the nectar used to
make honey because bees fly one or two miles to gather it. But
knowing the seasons help identify contributors. Honey harvested in
the Miami Valley in July likely is produced from the clover that's
abundant in June. In the fall it is the flowers of local goldenrod
and asters that provide nectar for the bees. That honey has a
stronger flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Beekeeper Ray Alley has a couple words of advice for backyard
gardeners whose flowers attract bees.
</P>
<P>
   Don't swat at the bee. If you do the bee releases a pheromone
smell that alerts other bees that they are under attack and they'll
come to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   If a bee does sting you, scrape off the stinger rather than
plucking it, which releases the chemical which causes swelling.
</P>
<P>
   And remember they don't like black. Honest. That's why Alley
removes his watch _ which has a black band _ before he goes to the
hives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
