<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-HONEYRECIPES-COX     06-09 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-HONEYRECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweet, syrupy honey complements variety of dishes
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The mention of honey evokes images of sweet
desserts, from Greek baklava to Jewish honey cake.
</P>
<P>
   But in some cuisines honey shows up in the main course. A
classic is the Moroccan dish of chicken with tomatoes and honey
called Djej Matisha Mesla. The chicken is cooked in an abundance of
tomatoes finished with honey, and the sauce is cooked down to a
veritable tomato jam.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally the dish should be made with fresh ripe tomatoes, but
Elisabeth Rozin's ``Ethnic Cuisine'' (Penguin, $14.95), offers a
version that uses canned Italian-style plum tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   MOROCCAN HONEY CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 pounds chicken parts or quarters
</P>
<P>
   1 28-ounce can Italian-style tomatoes with juice, coarsely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, mashed
</P>
<P>
   1 6-ounce can tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fragrant dark honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon additional cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   2 additional tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   In a large heavy pot or Dutch oven, combine all the ingredients
except the last three. Mix well and cook covered over low to
moderate heat for about one hour, until the chicken is very tender.
</P>
<P>
   Remove chicken from pot and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cook down the sauce in the pot over moderate heat, stirring
occasionally, until it is as thick as preserves. When it is thick
enough, add the additional cinnamon and honey. Taste for salt and
adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Return chicken parts to the pot and cook until chicken is heated
through. Place on a serving platter and coat well with sauce.
Sprinkle sesame seeds over.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving (to reduce fat and
calories, skin the chicken): 613 calories; 28 g fat; 202 mg
cholesterol; 688 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   I started with a recipe from Bon Appetit and made substantial
changes to come up with these chicken wings with Asian accents. The
honey plays a submissive role when paired with ginger, garlic,
sesame oil and star anise.
</P>
<P>
   If you are the kind who thinks more is always better, don't be
tempted to marinate these longer than 12 hours or the soy sauce
will overwhelm the other flavors.
</P>
<P>
   SESAME CHICKEN WINGS
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white or rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno chile, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 star anise
</P>
<P>
   20 whole chicken wings
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced cilantro
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl combine the soy sauce, vinegar, honey and sesame
oil. In a food processor or blender combine the green onions,
ginger, garlic and chile to make a paste. Stir into the soy
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the wings into pieces at the joints, discarding the wing
tips. Add to the marinade and stir to coat the pieces well. Cover
and refrigerate overnight, for a maximum of 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Arrange wings on two foil-lined
baking sheets. Pour the marinade into a small saucepan, add the
star anise and bring to a simmer. Let reduce over low heat for
about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Roast the wings for 30 minutes, turning once. While the wings
cook, place the sesame seeds in a small skillet and toast in the
oven for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the wings are nicely browned, remove to a serving dish.
Sprinkle with sesame seeds and cilantro. Strain the thickened
marinade into a bowl and use as a dipping sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with plenty of napkins because this is messy finger food.
</P>
<P>
   Flick out the seeds but leave the white ribs in place. That's
what provides the heat in peppers.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per piece: 69 calories; 4 g
fat; 14.5 mg cholesterol; 361 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is from the newly revised edition of ``Keo's Thai
Cuisine'' by Keo Sananikone (Ten Speed, $19.95). While the dishes
are from his Hawaii-based restaurants, the techniques are simple
enough for home cooks. A stop at an Asian store may be necessary
for ingredients such as lemongrass and Sriracha sauce.
</P>
<P>
   That sauce is a very hot chile sauce and is an essential
component for the typical Thai balance of hot and salty, sweet and
sour tastes in this dish.
</P>
<P>
   THAI-STYLE HONEY GLAZED SPARERIBS
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds baby spareribs
</P>
<P>
   4 stalks lemongrass
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons coarsely chopped fresh ginger root
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coconut milk (not coconut creme)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Sriracha sauce
</P>
<P>
   Cut the spareribs into individual ribs. Cut the top off
lemongrass stalks, reserving the bottom 6 inches. Peel off and
discard the outer layers of the lemongrass to reach the more tender
inner core. Chop the lemongrass coarsely.
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor combine the lemongrass, garlic, ginger,
cilantro, honey, coconut milk, soy sauce and salt. Blend until
smooth. Pour sauce over ribs and marinate overnight in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place the ribs in an open pan and
bake for 1 hour. Alternatively grill the ribs over hot charcoal.
Serve with Sriracha sauce for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   There is no substitute for lemongrass, and it is usually only
available at Asian markets. You also can grow it _ it becomes a
sizable clump with enough stalks to supply all your friends and
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   If you grow your own cilantro in abundance you can use the
chopped roots instead. That's what the original recipe calls for.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate nutritional analysis per serving: 878 calories; 42 g
fat; 176 mg cholesterol; 1,060 mg sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
