<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9266 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS &LR;      06-09 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-PATROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL APPROVES MONEY FOR MORE BORDER AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans on a Senate approrpriations panel
criticized Wednesday the Clinton administration's record on hiring
Border Patrol agents and approved $83 million to hire new recruits
or to boost pay for sworn officers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers have voiced frustration with the Immigration and
Naturalization Service's recruitment record while violent incidents
among smugglers, illegal immigrants and U.S. agents increase along
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a crisis along the border,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas. ``Our borders are being overrun by drug dealers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations subcommittee for Commerce, Justice and
State Departments approved the funds to hire 1,000 new Border
Patrol agents for the 2000 budget year, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee also included language blocking the Clinton
administration and the INS from using the funds for purposes other
than raises for agents or new hires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either the Clinton administration is going to hire 1,000 new
agents, or there will be bonuses to attract new agents and reward
experienced ones,'' Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, told a news
conference. ``We're not providing any flexibility for anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Spencer Abraham, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
subcommittee on immigration, said he was puzzled by the
administration's failure to use money appropriated last year to
hire 1,000 new agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an administration that wants to put 100,000 new police
on the streets but can't put 1,000 new agents on the border,'' said
Abraham, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, though, told lawmakers earlier this
year that the Border Patrol is growing too quickly. With at least
9,000 agents, the Border Patrol has more than doubled since 1993,
when there were 4,000 agents.
</P>
<P>
   Reno pointed to a recent study that found that 39 percent of
Border Patrol agents had less than two years' experience.
</P>
<P>
   Groups representing immigrants also have questioned the lack of
experience of Border Patrol agents, citing a growing number of
human rights complaints against federal law enforcement personnel
along the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, escalating violence along the Southwest border
makes it imperative that INS ``must not take a breather, but
redouble its efforts to hire more Border Patrol agents this year,''
said Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress appears to be realizing the need to address the
federal government's failure to control illegal immigration and
drug smuggling along our Southwest border,'' said Kyl, a member of
the Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hutchison has proposed legislation that would boost
the salary for Border Patrol agents with a year's experience to
$41,000 from $34,000. Hutchison said a pay raise for agents would
help recruitment efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
