<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAREWARE-REVIEW-2TAK     06-09 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAREWARE-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL VARIETY STORES: AISLES OF FREE FILES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Midwestern town where I grew up, there was a store called
Soukup's, which sold just about everything: nested mixing bowls,
``No Trespassing'' signs, sidewalk chalk, badminton birdies and _
if you took the creaky elevator to the third floor _ an enviable
variety of colorful fishing lures. My mother still treasures the
egg timer shaped like a chicken (its wings moved when it ticked)
that I bought for her birthday when I was 10.
</P>
<P>
   After Soukup's disappeared (like so many family-owned variety
stores), I despaired of ever wandering in wonder down aisles
crammed with an exotic, chaotic profusion of items.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day I discovered shareware _ and was saved.
</P>
<P>
   Now I spend hours browsing dozens of Internet sites that
maintain downloadable libraries of software files. I always come
home with useful merchandise. The other day, I picked up a nifty
little program called Netstock, which discreetly displays stock
prices on screen. I also got a copy of Phone Ferret, which
streamlines the process of searching through numerous online
databases to find vital phone numbers, of, say, old boyfriends (not
that I have called any of them). ICQ, the instant message program
that changed my life last year by making it possible to conduct the
Internet equivalent of a dozen simultaneous personal calls, made
its debut as shareware before the company was purchased by America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   The shareware concept dates to 1981, when an IBM employee named
Jim Knopf wrote a database program called PC-File for his own use,
as a substitute for an expensive commercial version. It worked so
well that he distributed copies of it to a few friends, who passed
it on to a few more, who passed it on. Soon the term shareware
referred strictly to software distributed on the honor system to
users who were expected to subsequently send payment.
</P>
<P>
   The label has evolved over the last two decades to encompass
such a wide variety of software that shareware is used almost
generically to refer to any program that you download from the
Internet instead of obtaining in a retail store.
</P>
<P>
   You will still have to pay for some shareware after a trial
period, by sending payment directly to the developers. But other
programs are free (called freeware) and still others are
stripped-down versions offered as free demos. Other programs, known
as guiltware, goad you for payment whenever you use them. And some
untrusting developers create so-called crippleware, which stops
working if you fail to pay after a trial period.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are an expert or a novice, the process of copying
programs from the Internet _ and then actually getting them to work
properly on your own computer _ has become faster and more reliable
over time. I have seen a major improvement in just the last year.
That is because more and more developers are relying on standard
installation programs to make it easy for users to set up their
software. As an increasing number of commercial software makers
move to electronic distribution as a primary means of getting
products into the hands of customers, they are also creating more
stable shareware to lure new customers.
</P>
<P>
   While many software developers put shareware on their own Web
sites, for a wider selection I recommend one of the reliable and
comprehensive Internet sites with large collections. All three of
my favorite sites _ ZDNet's Software Library, CNet's Download.com
and Tucows _ organize their shareware in easily searchable
categories, review programs to make sure they work and check files
for viruses.
</P>
<P>
   While the Tucows library is smaller than the others, offering a
Best of the Best of Internet-related programs, the other two have a
broad variety in just about any category you might want: tools and
utilities, small business applications, games, graphics and
multimedia, browsers and tons of the variety-store novelties I
like. If the overall feeling of sameness you get from their
inventories makes you feel a little more like you wandered into
Wal-Mart than Soukup's, so be it. After all, some days you don't
want an egg timer shaped like a chicken. You just want one like
everybody else has.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   ZDNET SOFTWARE LIBRARY  &QL; 
www.zdnet.com/swlib  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, this site's home page looks like a carnival
midway with brightly lit booths stuffed full with blinking icons.
So where do you start? If you already know what program you're
after, it's easy enough: the search function is prominently
displayed in the middle of the page. But if you're browsing? Do you
click first on Files in the News? The Weekly Top Ten? Killer
Downloads? Free File of the Day?
</P>
<P>
   All of those are tempting, but I like to start with Hot File of
the Day. Because ZDNet's staff reviews all of the site's collection
of more than 30,000 titles, users get an accurate thumbnail
description of the program. Last week I succumbed to temptation and
downloaded the day's hot file _ an arcade-like maze game called Ant
Run Pro _ and spent an hour playing it.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly I got bored with being an ant and deleted the game
from my hard drive. This is a typical user pattern. The day's hot
file is like candy: it lures you with its shiny wrapper, keeps your
interest briefly with its sweetness, and then you crash from the
sugar high and realize you don't need the calories on the hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   If you have not downloaded shareware before, click on the site's
EZ Download Guide. The step-by-step instructions walk Windows users
easily through the process, from creating a download folder on your
computer to installing and running a demonstration program. The
site includes files for Macintosh users and says it plans to add
instructions for downloading Mac files.
</P>
<P>
   To see ZDNet's trove of new programs, click on Launchpad (in the
Shareware Library Directory), which recently offered a program
called Blackbox to encrypt files and a program to control a remote
computer. The Launchpad area is not to be confused with ZDNet
Exclusives, a compendium of programs written for ZDNet, where
earlier this week you could find a Y2K screen saver with an image
of a computer run amok. I also like Preston's Picks, a collection
chosen by the executive editor, Preston Gralla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CNET DOWNLOAD.COM  &QL; 
www.download.com  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CNet site's home page has easily searchable categories
(Business, Education, Development Tools) highlighted right under
the prominent search box. The page's design makes it appear drier
and considerably more streamlined than the ZDnet shareware home
page, but scroll down and you'll realize that CNet's site probably
offers as many choices.
</P>
<P>
   Information here is more layered. For example, to dig deeper
into dozens of subcategories, from Genealogy to Interface
Enhancements, click on Expanded Listings.
</P>
<P>
   The site's Beginner's Guide to Downloading is slightly more
comprehensive than ZDNet's, offering instructions for Macintosh and
Windows users. To find new files that are currently exclusive to
CNet, click on Exclusives. But you won't find any programs created
specially for CNet. ``We're a media company, not a developer,''
said Scott Arpajian, the site's founding producer, ``so we stay
focused on finding the best software.''
</P>
<P>
   Download.com does not maintain copies on its own servers of the
more than 20,000 files in its directory. Instead, the site is like
a huge search engine that links users to other sites where files
can be downloaded. The download process is so seamless that most
users won't even notice.
</P>
<P>
   While some people might argue that it is easier to maintain
quality control if you house your own collection, others would
counter that offering numerous download sites improves access and
speed. I think both methods work just fine. And CNet does
temporarily house 50 of its most popular software files on its own
servers to insure that users have reliable access. Among the most
popular this week were a screen saver with images of waterfalls and
a program that enables you to continue downloading a file even
after being disconnected.
TUCOWS  &QL; 
www.tucows.com  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking a generalist approach like the other two
sites, Tucows specializes in software for Internet applications.
Among the site's collection of 2,000 titles are e-mail tools,
browser tools, server tools, online stock quote programs,
multiplayer games, parental control packages, FTP and telnet
programs _ basically anything that is related to anything you could
imagine doing on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Another big difference at Tucows is the download process. The
site's library is housed on hundreds of affiliates' computers
worldwide. Known as mirrors, these affiliate sites contain
identical copies of Tucows' software files. So before you can
download a file, you have to choose a geographical location from
which to download. Tucows says that having so many mirrors gives
the site an advantage: there is never a traffic jam when you want
to download a popular file. In my experience, the method works
fine, but I'd be hard pressed to say that it's any better than the
others.
</P>
<P>
   After choosing a mirror site, you connect to a well-organized
home page with a directory, a search box and a left-hand column of
informational topics, including background on how Tucows picks and
rates software. Be sure to click on Head of the Herd to see the
outstanding program of the week. Instead of stars, Tucows awards
cows to rate programs. Last week's five-cow Head of the Herd
program for Windows users was ECBuilder, software to help users set
up online businesses.
</P>
<P>
   With its streamlined design, Tucows offers an easily navigated
directory of programs. But it has less help for beginners than the
other two major sites. The Help area offers Tucows Specific Tips
that aid in downloading, but there is no step-by-step guide to
teach a novice how to download and install software.
</P>
<P>
   ASSOCIATION OF SHAREWARE PROFESSIONALS  &QL; 
www.asp-shareware.org  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This site is an invaluable resource for ferreting out less
well-known collections of shareware. Click on Download Sites in the
lefthand column of the home page to see a chart that lists dozens
of smaller, independent shareware sites around the world, including
www.ded.com/nonags (known for its refusal to stock guiltware _
programs that nag you for payment), www.filepile.com and
www.sharewarejunkies.com.
</P>
<P>
   Click on Sites of Interest for a list of links that lead to such
entertainments as a history of shareware. The site's FAQ answers
shareware questions ranging from ``What if I don't like the
evaluation version?'' to ``What about viruses in software?'' If
you're looking for something even more offbeat than you can find
here, subscribe to a free e-mail newsletter called Lockergnome
(www.lockergnome.com). Recent issues had pointers to Prevaricator,
a freeware lie detector, and a character-name generator that spews
out fictional names to aid authors. So far, however, no screen
saver with an image of an egg timer shaped like a chicken.  &QL; 
Here are additional shareware sites, some of which feature more
specialized programs:  &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOFTWAREVAULT.COM: www.softwarevault.com Allows searching of a
database of Windows, Macintosh, OS/2 and Linux programs; has a list
of new titles and some software reviews.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
PUBLIC SOFTWARE LIBRARY/DIGIBUY: www.pslweb.com A searchable
database of 20,000 downloadable titles. Reviews titles and
publishes a monthly CD-ROM of new programs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
DAVECENTRAL: www.davecentral.com Specializes in software related to
the Internet, like e-mail and conferencing programs, for Windows
and Linux.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
MACUPDATE: www.macupdate.com A comprehensive site for Macintosh
programs, offering reviews, search capability and lists of new and
popular programs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HAPPY PUPPY: www.happypuppy.com Specializes in games and game
reviews. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GARBO: garbo.uwasa.fi Based at the University of Vaasa in Finland,
this site has an extensive collection of MS-DOS programs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALBERT'S AMBRY: www.alberts.com The database includes Amiga
programs, as well as Macintosh, OS/2 and Windows titles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
