<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUN-LOLA-RUN-FILM (Undated) _ Not many films have inspired both
a hair color and a conservative politician's campaign poster. But
the German director Tom Tykwer's ``Run Lola Run'' certainly did.
The film, which has sold more than two million tickets in Germany
and which opens in Manhattan on Friday, is the anarchically charged
story of a flame-haired punk, Lola (Franka Potente), who races
through the streets of Berlin in a desperate attempt to save her
boyfriend's life. By Laura Winters. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANITA-EKBERG-FILMS (Genzano, Italy) _ With Anita Ekberg, 68,
talk usually revolves around the Fountain of Trevi, a monument
forever associated with the scene in ``La Dolce Vita'' in which she
dances in its waters so alluringly. It has been many decades since
she looked like the dewy sex goddess who entranced Marcello
Mastroianni in Fellini's 1960 classic. Or sounded like one. Her
once satiny, babyish whisper (``Marcello, come, join me'') has
become harsher with time and tobacco. But with her deep,
authoritative voice, imperious manner and carefully tended face,
she still looks and acts very much the diva. The Belgian director
Yvan Le Moine has cast her as a mercurial retired opera star in his
feature film debut, a Fellini-esque art film called ``The Red
Dwarf,'' which opens in New York on Friday. By Alessandra Stanley.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COYLE-LISTEN-THEATER (Undated) _ Brendan Coyle has spent almost
400 performances, his elbows propped on a bar, a lager or a whisky
at the ready, listening to his fellow players in ``The Weir'' turn
a litany of ghostly tales into a haunting study of collective
self-revelation. But playing a bartender also named Brendan, Coyle
never gets a story of his own, unless you believe _ as some do _
that Brendan's tale begins once Conor McPherson's play ends. Can
listening be its own reward? As Coyle's acclaimed performance shows
_ in February, he won an Olivier Award in London for best
supporting player _ listening has the capacity to be as potent as
speech. By Matt Wolf. (Moved). Photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DANCE-MEMOIRS (Undated) _ Here's a little secret I wonder
if it's wise for a critic to share: I often find that traveling to
someplace new, or at least someplace not routinely familiar, puts
me in a good mood for seeing performances. By Jack Anderson.
(Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ORCHESTRAS-FUTURE (Undated) _ When the Cleveland Orchestra was
at Carnegie Hall last month, giving concerts led by its music
director, Christoph von Dohnanyi, and a former principal guest
conductor, Pierre Boulez, Ara Guzelimian, the hall's artistic
adviser, took the opportunity to convene a public discussion. The
two maestros and Joseph Polisi, the president of the Juilliard
School, were asked to speculate on what orchestras might be like in
the next century, as institutional bodies and as artistic machines.
By Paul Griffiths. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOULEZ-MUSIC (Undated) _ The modernest composer, Pierre Boulez,
development as a major musician of our time has been well
documented on disk. Now 74, he has understandably begun to cut back
his conducting commitments. But he continues his work in the
recording studio. Three important recent releases on
Deutsche-Grammophon, the company with which he has been most
closely associated of late, present Boulez as conductor and
composer. By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PROVINCETOWN-ART (Provincetown, Mass.) _ Whether they come to
party or to produce, diverse artistic types still succumb to
Provincetown's natural beauty and mystique. This summer,
Provincetown marks its centennial year as an art colony. By Ann
Wilson LLoyd. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ Jean Nouvel's new design for a
hotel and cineplex on the Brooklyn waterfront strikes me as one of
the most imaginatively conceived pieces of architecture New York
has seen in a long time. By Herbert Muschamp. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   HERMITAGE-MUSEUM (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ For a museum that
has miraculously survived the 20th century (two revolutions, two
wars and Russia's messy eight-yearlong lurch toward democracy), the
Hermitage, keeper of one of the world's greatest art collections,
is doing its best to get a jump on the coming millennium. This
week, it will launch what experts describe as one of the best
digital libraries on a museum Internet site, put together by IBM
technicians working with the latest scanning technology, some of it
designed especially for IBM's $2-million Hermitage project. By
Celestine Bohlen. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MINI-SERIES (Undated) _ A look at some of the proposed
television mini-series for the fall. By Ron Wertheimer. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEPERO-ART-ANTIQUES (Miami Beach) _ The stunning variety of
works the Italian painter and designer, Fortunato Depero, produced
are explored in ``Depero Futurista Rome-Paris-New York,
1915-1932,'' an exhibition here at the Wolfsonian museum of design,
through July 26. Most of the 160 items on view were produced before
1932, but some date to the late 1940s. Aside from a chair and
several books from the Wolfsonian collection, the objects on view
were lent by the Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art of Trento
and Rovereto, towns 20 to 30 miles north of Verona in northern
Italy near Fondo, the village where Depero was born. But from
earliest childhood until his death at 68 in 1960, Depero lived
mostly in Roverto, where he worked at the House of Art, the studio,
showcase and shop for his art and furnishings. By Rita Reif.
</P>
