<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-COMEDIAN-SLAYING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN TELEVISION NETWORKS ADD POLITICS TO GRIEF OVER SLAIN
COMEDIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In his 30-year television career, the round-faced
comedian popularly known as Paco Stanley charmed millions of
Mexicans with his jocular but razor-edged way of clowning and
mocking, of putting them down and exhorting them to be good.
</P>
<P>
   So when Stanley fell victim at high noon on Monday to a coolly
professional execution by gunfire, the jolt of disbelief spread
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The two major national television networks seized on the
shooting to blame the head of Mexico City's government, a leader of
the opposition, for failing to protect people. The media assault on
Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, who is expected to run for
president next year, transformed the crime into a traumatic
polarizing event at the opening of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But 24 hours later police announced that Stanley was carrying a
stash of cocaine in his pants when he was killed. The political
tide spun about, and Mexicans got another devastating revelation of
the influence of drugs and organized crime in segments of life they
had hoped were clean.
</P>
<P>
   The operation to kill the comedian, whose full name was
Francisco Stanley Albaiter, was carried out ``with a high degree of
criminal precision,'' in the chilling words of Mexico City's
attorney general, Samuel del Villar. But three days into the
investigation, del Villar has not speculated about a motive and
carefully avoided linking the homicide directly to drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Just after Stanley, who was 56, climbed into the passenger seat
of his minivan after a hearty brunch at a favorite taco joint, at
least two men dressed in gray strode up to the car and started
firing high-caliber semiautomatic pistols. In all, police found 26
rounds imbedded in Stanley's face and scattered in and around his
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Stanley's chauffeur nor his two bodyguards, who were
unarmed, nor his son, Francisco Stanley Pedroza, who was in the
back seat, were injured. But a restaurant customer, Juan Manuel de
Jesus Nunez, was killed by flying bullets. Nunez's wife, a
restaurant parking attendant and Jorge Gill, a television reporter
who was with Stanley, suffered gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen used a a crosswalk over a highway streaming with cars
to flee and drove away in a stolen 1999 Volkswagen Jetta sedan that
was waiting for them on the other side. Police found the abandoned
getaway car Tuesday morning. Blood stains on a car handle and on
the crosswalk led investigators to believe that one of the gunmen
was shot by a restaurant security guard and was limping during his
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Both national television networks had a reflex reaction to the
murder of one of their most well-loved and valuable colleagues,
which graphically revealed their underlying favor for the federal
government run by President Ernesto Zedillo and his Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Both networks all but ignored the details pointing to an
organized crime execution. Instead they concentrated on the grief
about the loss of a light-hearted entertainer and the fury about
the wave of common crime in the capital city, which, in fact, is
little abated.
</P>
<P>
   Televisa, which for decades had a virtual monopoly protected by
the government, brought a battle horse news anchorman, Jacobo
Zabludovksy, back from retirement to lead the hours of live
coverage. Stanley worked together with Zabludovksy at Televisa for
27 years as hosts of variety shows that were watched devotedly by
Mexican housewives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hostages to crime everywhere,'' Zabludovksy said as
cameras scanned the gory crime scene. ``How can the city
authorities possibly try to tell us that crime has gone down?''
</P>
<P>
   TV Azteca, the competition that lured Stanley away earlier this
year, was even more indignant. The network's president, Ricardo
Salinas Pliego, cleared the airwaves for his own nationally
broadcast attack on the city authorities. One TV Azteca anchorman,
Jorge Garraldo, berated Cardenas personally and said, ``Someone has
to resign and make way for people who really can protect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas, whose reticence before the press is legendary, endured
the punishment in silence until late Monday night. Finally he
fought back with a communique calling the killing ``a clear
demonstration of the power of organized crime'' and accusing the
television networks of ``creating anxiety among city residents and
taking political advantage of the events.''
</P>
<P>
   The clash continued Tuesday, as both networks gave lavish live
coverage to Stanley's raucous funeral. Some four thousand fans
surged into the cemetery, trampling nearby graves. The mourners
nearly upended Stanley's coffin and crushed his relatives as they
tried to make their way into the spacious, marble-lined family
crypt.
</P>
<P>
   TV Azteca positioned a camera inside the crypt and provided
close-up views of the weeping bereaved throughout the burial
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice! Justice!,'' the mourners chanted. Some carried
placards comparing Stanley's killing to the still-unsolved 1994
assassination of the PRI's presidential candidate, Luis Donaldo
Colosio, a crime that continues to haunt Mexican politics.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the networks were soon forced to lower their volume and the
federal government and the PRI's presidential candidate suddenly
found themselves on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   At an evening press conference, del Villar, the attorney
general, announced that police found half a gram of cocaine in
Stanley's pocket, a stainless steel powder grinder with residues of
the drug in his car and a small lesion inside his nose that
forensic specialists described as common to those who frequently
snort cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   While Stanley' blood tested negative for cocaine, his urine
tested positive, the head of city forensic services, Dr. Pedro
Estrada Gonzalez, said. He said the findings strongly suggested
that Stanley was a habitual cocaine user. The authorities did not
produce any evidence that showed he was engaged in drug commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Bezares, Stanley's veteran comic sidekick who was with him
at the restaurant, also tested positive for cocaine, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The police also discovered that Stanley was carrying a photo
credential issued by the national Interior Ministry. It identified
him as an employee and authorized him to carry ``any firearm
permitted by law for personal civilian use.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, when the credential was issued, the interior minister
was Francisco Labastida Ochoa, now the front-runner to be the PRI's
presidential candidate and probably to face Cardenas in the
elections next year. It is a federal crime for a public security
agency to identify someone as an employee who is not.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Jorge Tello Peon, the deputy interior minister for
public security, acknowledged that the agency had issued the permit
to Stanley, at his request. Stanley had said that he had been
assaulted several times and needed to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the way permits should be issued,'' Tello said.
``It was an exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's family members continued to insist that they never
knew him to use drugs. But some of Stanley's fans began to wonder
openly and sadly if they ever knew who he really was.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as Saturday night Stanley had taken time on his show
to launch an appeal in his seductive deep base voice for an
anti-drug campaign aimed at Mexican youth that TV Azteca has
sponsored. It is called ``Live Without Drugs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
