<HEADLINE>
A PHONE FOR THE INTERNET WITH MORE SPEED AND LESS GLARE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Norway, The Netherlands, Calif.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, Infogear, a start-up company, introduced its iPhone,
a phone for the Web with built-in e-mail and browsing software. The
new generation, the iPhone Series 2000, is a marked improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The black-and-white touch screen is still just a quarter of the
size of a standard PC monitor, but now it tilts to eliminate glare.
The pull-out keyboard is a comfortable size for touch typing. The
new model has a second jack so voice and data connections can take
place simultaneously, and it has a much speedier 56K internal
modem. A speakerphone has been added as well.
</P>
<P>
   Like its predecessor, the new iPhone is relatively easy to use.
Connecting to the Web is a straightforward matter of taking the
machine out of the box, plugging it into the wall, attaching a
phone line and going through five screens of registration. E-mail
is just as easy.
</P>
<P>
   Infogear's idea is to have customers place the iPhone on a
kitchen counter, or in any high-traffic section of a home, and use
it with the casual frequency of a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback to the iPhone is the steep cost. The retail price
of the iPhone will be $299 to $399. But Infogear, based in Redwood
City, Calif., is negotiating with several large telephone companies
that would subsidize the unit and sell it for as little as $199,
together with monthly phone and Internet service, said the
company's chief executive officer, Ed Cluss.
</P>
<P>
   The iPhone is currently available through Big Planet
(www.bigplanet.com), an Internet service provider in Provo, Utah,
and will go into wider distribution this summer. KATIE HAFNER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   TO ENTER THE WORLD OF E-MAIL, INSERT BATTERIES AND PLUG IN  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A simple and inexpensive device will now let the computerless
get e-mail, too.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the thinking behind the Mail Station, a $99
e-mail appliance, the size of a small laptop, from Cidco
(www.cidco.com). Like the network computer desktops of old, the
Mail Station is a stripped-down computer with a simplified
operating system. At 2.2 pounds and 8 inches by 10 inches, it is
the size of a laptop, but its unlit monochrome screen, measuring 6
inches by 2.2 inches, makes it look markedly different. To send and
receive e-mail, you simply pop in some AA batteries (or use the AC
adapter), plug the unit into a wall jack and start typing. A list
of local-access phone numbers is provided.
</P>
<P>
   Cidco engineers threw in a 1,000-item address book that can
capture and add addresses, a spell checker, a calendar and a
33.6-kilobit-per-second modem that can also send faxes. A
12-megahertz processor and 512 kilobytes of memory may not sound
zippy, but e-mail without graphics requires no more.
</P>
<P>
   What the Mail Station can't do, of course, is surf the Web. The
intended market is people without PCs who just want to push one
button to get their mail.
</P>
<P>
   Mail can also be received at a Web site, handy for viewing
messages with pictures attached that are too big for the system.
The unit can also be attached to a printer, which will be handy
because it can't save the same number of messages as desktop
systems. It saves up to 400 e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   The device costs $99 when a buyer also pays $99 in advance for a
year of e-mail service. If a buyer opts for an e-mail account at
$9.95 monthly, the device costs $149. The device is currently
available only from Cidco, bundled with an e-mail account. In the
future, others may resell the device with other services. MARTY
KATZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A VIRUS CHARTS A NEW COURSE USING E-MAIL AND CHAT ROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Another virus bent on rummaging through your electronic address
book has turned up in recent weeks. Pretty Park, like the notorious
Melissa, finds its new victims by picking up e-mail addresses that
are stored in an infected computer's address book and sending
itself to dozens of your friends and family members.
</P>
<P>
   But Pretty Park does more than spread spam. The virus _ which is
technically a worm, a file that replicates itself _ tries to open a
channel from its host computer to a chat room. If it succeeds, it
has opened a pipe through which files can be downloaded from and
uploaded to the host computer without the computer owner's
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unusual,'' said Steve Trilling, director of research
at the antivirus research center run by the Symantec Corp.. ``We
haven't seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the author of the virus is still unknown, Symantec's
engineers have been able to analyze the worm's code and determine
the chat rooms it is using, Trilling said. As of Tuesday, about 600
computers were connected to the chat rooms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many software companies that sell antivirus software have now
added Pretty Park to their databases of viruses to block. LISA
GUERNSEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DR. MOUSE TO THE ERGONOMICAL RESCUE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest entrant to enter the carpal tunnel battle is a mouse
that looks as if it has a pen stuck into its back. The device,
called Dr. Mouse, looks more like a World War II movie fighter's
joystick than a standard mouse, with a handle sticking up and mouse
buttons instead of a trigger.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer, Animax International of Norway, says the
design changes the way a user holds a mouse, consequently reducing
stress on the nerves and muscles in the arm and reducing the
likelihood of several forms of cumulative trauma disorders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the one-size-fits-all approach of a regular mouse,
Dr. Mouse comes in a small and large version, designed to fit hands
of different sizes. It is available for Windows, Macintosh and
several Unix-based workstations, and there is a USB version for the
iMac. STEVEN E.BRIER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A SEARCH ENGINE WITH AN EYE FOR THE EMERGING COMMUNITIES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do inflatable sumo-wrestling suits and machine shops in
Taiwan have in common? They are the subjects of communities of
linked Web sites, communities so obscure or ill-defined that many
Web directories don't list them.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of undiscovered Web communities _ from sites devoted
to Brazilian sports newspapers to Japanese oil spills _ have been
uncovered by a new search engine, Clever, developed by researchers
at the IBM Almaden Research Center in San Jose, Calif. Clever
identifies the most authoritative Web sites on a topic by using the
information implicit in the links people place from their Web page
to others. The Clever team observed that related pages frequently
linked to the same cluster of pages; that pattern of links,
associated with the core of a Web community, is the flag the new
software looks for.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Web rings, the communities found by Clever are unplanned.
Unlike newsgroups, they spring up spontaneously as people create
new Web sites and link to other pages _ they are more like
shantytowns than planned suburbs. Clever can detect communities in
their nascent stages, even before members are aware of their
community's existence.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clever nor the new software is ready for the market,
but, an I.B.M. spokesman, Mike Ross, said several search engine
companies had expressed an interest. A Clever researcher, Dr.
Sridhar Rajagopalan, said the ability to follow the birth and
growth of online communities might be useful for studying the
structure and evolution of the Web. SARA ROBINSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   A $25 PIECE OF MOLDED PLASTIC TURNS A MONITOR INTO A CANVAS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the iMac looks great out of the box, but once it's covered
by Post-It notes and coffee cups, it starts to resemble other
desktops. A new product can give a desktop, iMac or not, the
curved, cluttered look of more expensive computers.
</P>
<P>
   The EEGO Desktop Environment is, despite its grand name, a $25
piece of plastic that attaches to a standard 15-inch monitor with
Velcro strips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired of looking at the beige square box in front of
me,'' said EEGO's creator, C.William Smith. ``I thought there must
be a more creative way.'' The colorful oval-shaped mount has two
large corkboards for pinning up pictures and notes and an erasable
board on top. EEGO will be available at the end of June from the
www.eegomania.com site. BRUCE HEADLAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Financial Stop on the Way to Elective Cosmetic Surgery
</P>
<P>
   In the category of things-you-hadn't-expected-to-do-online, a
new entrant: a Web site where you can apply for a tummy tuck loan.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a Chicago company, Unicorn Financial Services, which
finances elective cosmetic surgery, opened a Web site
(www.howtopayforit.com) that enables prospective patients to fill
out a brief credit application. Within minutes, said Unicorn's
co-founder, Anne M. Tynion, the application is processed. ``We
believe that this system will put the patient more at ease, knowing
they're approved before they walk into the doctor's office,'' Ms.
Tynion said.
</P>
<P>
   _ TERRY McMANUS
</P>
<P>
   BACTERIAL FALLOUT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A theory of progress says that for every technological advance,
there is an unintended consequence. Some researchers recently
discovered some particularly unsavory reverse effects. Bug-zappers,
the devices hung around backyards in barbecue season, do kill flies
and mosquitoes, but they also cause airborne bacteria and
virus-laden particles from the insect's surface area and digestive
canal to rain down. ``We're finding really significant amounts on
the surface of the fly will survive,'' said James Urban, an
associate professor of biology at Kansas State, in a press release.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A PLACE TO BROWSE WHILE WAITING FOR VAN GOGH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados of Vincent van Gogh may have felt like cutting off
their own ears lately: the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam has been
closed for renovations since September 1998. So for those who could
not get through the spring without ``The Langlois Bridge'' or ``The
Potato Eaters,'' the museum put much of the collection on its
impressive Web site (www.vangoghmuseum.nl).
</P>
<P>
   When the museum reopens in late June, a renovated Web site will
also be unveiled, featuring a virtual room-by-room tour of the
museum, including close-ups and background information for each
painting and, of course, chat rooms for van Gogh fans, who never
seem to lack for intensity.
</P>
