<HEADLINE>
PATROL PUTS DRONES TO TEST FOR KEEPING EYE ON BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ The U.S. Border Patrol is encouraged by secret
tests of unmanned planes that could use cameras and remote controls
to sweep isolated portions of the Rio Grande for drug traffickers
and illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Four drones, ranging from a hand-launched spear with wings to a
650-pound model that looks like a shopping cart with an airfoil and
giant fan, were part of a $1.8 million study that quietly wrapped
up here last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are not flawless. In theory, the technology
exists to benefit Border Patrol operations,'' Lee Bargerhuff,
assistant chief for the patrol's Laredo sector, said Wednesday as
the agency disclosed the tests.
</P>
<P>
   They were conducted out of the public eye on a private ranch
about 30 miles northwest of the border city of Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   The small aircraft, known as Unmanned Aerial Vehicles, can be
outfitted with cameras that see night or day and can transmit live
images to agents stationed up to 50 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Some drones can be programmed using global positioning systems
and other satellites. Others are remotely controlled by operators
sitting in vehicles or using mobile control panels with joy sticks
and shoulder harnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Findings of the study, which was conducted with the Air Force
Operational Test and Evaluation Center in New Mexico, are to be
forwarded to Congress in July, Bargerhuff said.
</P>
<P>
   Consideration of the drones is still at in the preliminary
stage, and it would be up to Congress to fund more tests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The drones are seen as a potential way to patrol vast areas for
undocumented immigrants lost in the brush or to chase or monitor
smugglers until agents on the ground can arrive, Bargerhuff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clear limitations. They are not intelligent. They
can not look over their shoulder,'' Bargerhuff said of the unmanned
craft.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the craft could potentially conduct mundane watchdog
duties and alert agents to determine in advance if a group of
suspects appear to be harmless illegal immigrants or armed drug
smugglers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The technology boost would be yet another upgrade for the Border
Patrol. Infrared scopes and ground sensors are already part of the
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the patrol received a fleet of helicopters
costing $1.8 million each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
