<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business Week sees 24-hour trading
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Plans by the New York Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq
market to extend trading for several more hours after the current 4
p.m. closing time is just the next step toward 24-hour trading.
</P>
<P>
   It's an example, says Business Week (June 14), of the world's
move toward ``Internet time,'' where trading will be anytime,
anywhere, affecting all of the world's financial centers. And if
the Internet is the technology that will make 'round-the-clock
trading possible, competition is the motive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. exchanges _ particularly Nasdaq _ have been feeling
the heat from private trading systems known as Electronic
Communications Networks,'' says Business Week. These computerized
systems that match buy-and-sell orders from investors have stolen
more than a fifth of all trading in Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, many institutions _ such as mutual funds
_ that need a benchmark time against which to measure changes will
continue to treat 4 p.m. as the official market close, although a
later hour could be chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Extended trading will complicate the release of earnings and
other corporate financial reports and almost certainly result in
longer hours for some stockbrokers and financial journalists.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason brokers are not the ones who are driving this
change. The impetus is coming from the retail investor, who says
that we have 24-hour groceries, pharmacies, diners, casinos and
bowling alleys, why not stock markets?
</P>
<P>
   Guidance from Fortune
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for extended trading, Fortune (special issue) is
out with its 1999 ``Tech Buyers Guide,'' a compendium of articles
and advice on computers, software, the Internet and related
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``As every user knows, picking the right information technology
for work or home is a daunting task,'' the magazine explains,
adding that this guide ``offers readers the critical information
necessary to make technology product and services buying
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia Trend (June) profiles Roy Richards Jr., chairman and
chief executive officer of Carrollton-based Southwire, as recipient
of its 1999 ``most respected CEO'' award. Richards revamped and
streamlined the wire manufacturer's organizational structure to
increase its competitiveness, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   _ One of the surprises in world currency markets has been the
unexpected weakness of the euro, the new European currency. That's
bad for Europe but American tourists are feasting off the change
since the costs of goods and services are cheaper, Newsweek (June
14) reports. The cost to rent a yacht for a week in Spain has
dropped to $1,246 from $1,400 in January; a pint of Guiness in
Ireland is $3.20, a saving of 40 cents from the January price.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
