<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATELLITE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW PROFESSOR, STUDENTS DEVELOP SELF-PROPELLED `NANOSATELLITE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A University of Washington aeronautics professor and
his students on Tuesday unveiled ``Dawgstar,'' a basketball-size
space vehicle they will launch in 2001 as the first self-propelled
small satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``nanosatellites,'' a group of these tiny but
sophisticated devices will be launched to conduct studies in the
ionosphere _ an upper layer in the atmosphere above the
stratosphere where free ions and electrons roam, interfering with
radio and satellite communication signals.
</P>
<P>
   Three Dawgstar satellites, along with a half-dozen
nanosatellites from other institutions, will be released into orbit
by the space shuttle. The tiny satellites' own propulsion system
will then kick in, directing them to fly in a pattern formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been other small satellites built,'' said Mark
Campbell, UW associate professor of aeronautics and astronautics.
But few have ever been launched, Campbell said, and none have ever
had their own propulsion system.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least not that we know of, in terms of civilian
satellites,'' added Adam Bruckner, UW chairman of aeronautics and
astronautics. We don't always know what the military is doing with
its satellites, Bruckner noted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is the military _ the U.S. Air Force and the Defense
Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) _ that are primary
sponsors of the UW project. It's a hint nobody's beaten Campbell
and his ``nanosat'' team to the punch.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, some of the 27 UW undergraduates working on Dawgstar
presented their mission plan and design to representatives of
Primex Technologies, a Redmond, Wash.-based space, defense and
electronics company.
</P>
<P>
   Primex, which has been offering technical and professional
assistance to the UW since the Dawgstar project started last year,
is a world leader in propellant systems for use in spacecraft and
launch vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The Dawgstar will be using a tinier version of an electrical
propulsion system made by Primex for use in larger spacecraft and
satellites. Called a pulsed plasma thruster, it's driven by
electrical energy supplied by solar cells on the exterior walls of
the satellite.
</P>
<P>
   The electrical energy harvested by the solar cells is used to
create a high-powered spark between two electrodes located next to
a solid bar of Teflon. This electrical arc vaporizes the Teflon and
creates a plasma burst or pulse, which is violently ejected,
creating thrust.
</P>
<P>
   Primex took an interest in assisting the Dawgstar team because
it provided them an opportunity to test a refined version of their
thruster in a new way _ as a propellant but also for use as a
satellite positioning method.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to demonstrate another application of our
technology,'' said Scott Miller, project engineer in space systems
for Primex. ``This would be a test case.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell explained that the Dawgstar satellites, along with
nanosatellites built by teams at the University of Utah and
Virginia Tech, aim to fly in formation. Using GPS (global
positioning system) signals from other satellites, he said, the
nanosatellites will be positioned to orbit in formation.
</P>
<P>
   Testing this ``flying formation'' of all the satellites,
Campbell said, is also one of the research goals in addition to
studying the ionosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers need larger telescopes if they are to see deeper
into space, he said, but getting beyond the size of the Hubble
Space Telescope is cumbersome and expensive. One of NASA's goals is
to develop networks of satellites that can collect data coordinated
together over a larger area of space, Campbell said, and ``in
effect, create a huge telescope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The distance between the satellites is equivalent to the
diameter of the telescope,'' he said. In addition, deploying such a
system is much more inexpensive and easier than launching ever
larger telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Campbell said, the U.S. Air Force and DARPA have
contributed $100,000 to the Dawgstar project, which is named after
the UW Husky mascot. NASA has also supported the research, he said,
and Primex's donation of expertise has been invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the project is exciting and provides a good bridge
between his company and students at the UW. He and others spent
several hours Tuesday with the nanosat team, pointing up areas that
need more work and questions that still need to be answered.
</P>
<P>
   Once the design is approved, graduate students at the UW will
take over the actual manufacture of the satellite. Miller said
Primex has agreed to donate use of its facilities for this stage of
the project, along with its testing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said the plan so far is to have the nanosatellites
taken up by the space shuttle, or perhaps a Pegasus rocket, in
November 2001 where they will be released. Upon release, the
Dawgstar and its nanosat companions will thrust into position and
cruise throughout the ionosphere for several months, or until they
fail and burn up upon re-entry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
