<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HASEK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ORDINARY GOALIE? ANYTHING BUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He's just a goalie. That's what the Ottawa Senators
kept telling themselves as they were being drummed out of the
playoffs in four straight games in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   He's just a goalie. That's what the Bruins said even though they
had a Vezina Trophy finalist of their own in Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   He's just a goalie. That familiar refrain continued right
through the Sabres' series against the top scoring team in the
league _ Toronto, even though said goalie missed the first two
games because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Bruins were able to take the Sabres to six games. The
Senators were swept and the Maple Leafs lasted only five games in
the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Before Game 1 of the Stanley Cup finals Tuesday night, the
Stars, who had the best regular-season record in the league, kept
saying _ you guessed it _ he's just a goalie.
</P>
<P>
   After the Sabres had taken a 3-2 overtime victory, the Stars
realized what every team before them learned the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   Dominik Hasek is not just a goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had 10 power plays and poured 37 shots on Hasek, many of
which were outstanding chances. Brett Hull, who had the first Stars
goal, landed eight shots on Hasek, five in the first period alone.
</P>
<P>
   Even more remarkable than Hasek's performance was his reaction
when Buffalo defenseman Jason Woolley scored the winner at 15:30 of
the extra period. Hasek started down the ice, stopped, couldn't
make it far enough to celebrate with his teammates, and headed for
the dressing room instead.
</P>
<P>
   There was fear that Hasek's nagging groin problem had flared up,
but Wednesday he said that was the least of his problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played before in such a hot building,'' said Hasek,
who was hampered by cramps and dehydration. ``I was very tired. I
tried to drink as much water as I could but I remember in the
overtime, I made the save on (Pat) Verbeek and I got a cramp. I was
glad that a couple seconds later or a minute later that we scored
the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so tired. I tried to get to the other side of the ice
but I made a couple of steps and I said, (`No more') and I left the
ice. I don't remember when I've ever been so tired during a game.
My groin didn't bother me the whole game. I feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek wasn't exaggerating about his fatigue. The league's public
relations staff had to call and wake him up so he could attend the
Sabres' press conference Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said his entire team was affected by
the uncomfortable temperature in Reunion Arena although Hasek
suffered more because of his extra pads and the numerous power
plays he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building was very hot,'' said Ruff. ``In the first two
periods, we spent a lot of time in our zone. There were a lot of
scrambles, a lot of situations where Dominik was up and down and
making saves. A lot of those flurries are the things that really
tire you out. I thought at least in the third period we took the
pressure off and spent some time in the other end and gave him a
little bit of a break. Then again in overtime, we had to kill two
penalties. We were concerned with dehydration in a lot of our
players. Obviously a goaltender, where he has all the equipment on,
probably is a worst-case scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the result was a best-case scenario for the Sabres,
who took away Dallas's home-ice advantage. Hasek downplayed his
contribution, saying he simply was doing what he's paid for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my job,'' he said. ``In the playoffs, there's nothing
about shutouts or goals-against average. It's only about the win.
My goal is to win the game, to give up less goals than the other
goalie, and I've done my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek doing his job as well as he has enables his teammates to
better do theirs. Even though the Sabres committed some ill-advised
infractions, their aggressive penalty killing and Hasek's
reliability neutralized the mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of the year, every player knows where they're
supposed to be, they know the system we're playing,'' said Ruff.
``I think you've got to be loose. When you win your first game,
you're playing a bit more loose and we also stress that, with our
goaltender, we can take a few more chances. We can create some
problems for the other team by having the defense jump in and
having the defense pinch. We've gone that way a few times and it's
worked out good.''
</P>
<P>
   As the temperatures in Dallas remain high and the staff at
Reunion Arena try to come up with ways to keep the rink cool, Hasek
said he didn't expect to change his pregame routine for Game 2
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can do anything else than what I did before
the last game,'' he said. ``I was drinking lots before the game and
during the game. But there's only a certain amount you can drink.
Your stomach starts to get upset after you drink two bottles of
water and you can't drink any more.''
</P>
<P>
   What might be diminished somewhat, though, is Hasek's acute
nervousness. Ruff said he sensed a genuine case of jitters among
his young players and Hasek admitted Wednesday that he was not
immune to the butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very, very nervous before the game and during the
game,'' said the goalie. ``But there's nothing bad about it. It's
good to be nervous, it keeps you more focused and more
concentrated. The pressure helps me play better.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bode well for the Stars. Then again, he's only a
goalie, right?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
