<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFER JOHNSON A LEADER NOT ONLY IN TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first Special Olympics was held in a backyard.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the Special Olympics as we now know it, with
organizations in all 50 states and 143 countries, with 4,000
athletes and volunteers headed for the 30th anniversary of the
Southern California Special Olympics Summer Games this weekend at
Long Beach State.
</P>
<P>
   Rafer Johnson, a few years removed from world record and Olympic
medal-winning performances as a decathlete, was a guest at those
backyard games held in the mid-'60s by Eunice Kennedy Shriver,
whose older sister, Rosemary, was mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a gathering for one person who happened to be a
member of the Kennedy family. This was the first step of a movement
that literally took the mentally retarded out of the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The athletes there had the chance to swim, play touch
football, run and ride horses,'' said Johnson, chairman of Southern
California's Special Olympics Board of Governors. ``They were
enjoying themselves. It was very clear that they wanted this
opportunity and were enjoying it very much.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was not the way the mentally retarded were usually
treated.
</P>
<P>
   Rafer Johnson, a multi-sport star at UCLA who won the 1960
Olympic decathlon gold medal, was already thriving as a political
and community activist when he was invited to the Shriver home. It
didn't take him long to learn about the issue and make it a
priority in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Shriver thought something should be done,'' said Johnson.
``Not because of her sister, but because she knew what was
happening to the mentally retarded. At that time, most of the
mentally retarded were institutionalized. They were separated from
their families and had little access to any kind of learning or
physical activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson visited several of those facilities, where he saw the
mental retarded housed with those suffering from other, more
debilitating mental illnesses. He also met with doctors and
professors at those backyard competitions about what could be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw in those institutions were people who had been left
to die,'' he said. ``What I saw in the backyard were people who,
instead of being pushed or held back, were able to grow and enjoy
aspects of life that we're all entitled to, handicapped or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question about the impact sports and competition
can have. When they find success on the field, it gives them the
ability, awareness and desire to achieve in a job. It makes their
life whole. It fills a void that hadn't been filled before.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shriver's backyard camps evolved into the first Special
Olympics, which were held in Chicago in 1968. Johnson helped
organize those games and a year later launched the first western
regional event at the Coliseum. The event moved to Long Beach in
1970, and returns this year after many years at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has long been one of Southern California's special
people. His family moved from Texas to Kingsburg in central
California when he was 11, and its first year there lived out of a
railroad boxcar.
</P>
<P>
   He became a multi-sport star in high school and college. He set
a world record in the decathlon in 1955, won the Olympic silver
medal in the 10-eventer at Melbourne in 1956, played two years of
basketball for John Wooden (1958-59), and then won the 1960 Olympic
gold medal in Rome in a memorable duel with his UCLA teammate, C.K.
Yang. At the end of the decathlon's last event, the 1,500 meters,
the two literally leaned on each other in exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's sports background gave way to a life as an activist in
politics, charity and community work. He worked for Bobby Kennedy's
1968 presidential campaign, and was at the Ambassador Hotel when
the candidate and former U.S. Attorney General wasassassinated. He
was the finalcarrier of the 1984 Olympic torch,scaling the Coliseum
peristyle stepsto ignite the flame atop the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Few athletes are more qualified as role models. But the reality
is that Johnson has touched many more people as a civic leader than
he ever could have as a full-time athlete.
</P>
<P>
   His parents were his role models, activists in his schooling and
life as well as the Kingsburg community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom and dad always helped,'' he said. ``They coached and
helped build fields with other families for all of the kids in the
neighborhood. Growing up in a small town made me realize how
important it is for people to help each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not have found as much success as I have if I hadn't
had that kind of direction. I grew up with a deep to-the-core
feeling about giving back.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his colleagues in the Special Olympics have future
goals for their athletes. The organization wants to start directing
Special Olympics athletes into the athletic mainstream, just as
many have been redirected to regular classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   And Johnson has his own life goal to continue urging everyone,
from major corporations with many resources to the man on the
street who thinks he's strapped for time, to give back to the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are places where anyone can put his talents to use,'' he
said. ``Any time of the day or night. We can find something to fit
your schedule. People shouldn't wait for someone to come up with a
perfect scenario. They should just get involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anyone out there who got where he is just on
talent. Someone helped. Somebody created a program and pointed you
in the right direction. And it doesn't matter how many people give
time, how many programs exist, how much money is raised. We still
need more. There will never be enough volunteers or money or
programs to fill all of our needs. Look for places to help. They're
easy to find.''
</P>
<P>
   They could even be in your own backyard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
