<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-MOVIE-AWARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTING FOR KERNELS OF WIT IN MTV'S GOLDEN POPCORN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every now and then the camera at the MTV Movie Awards settles on
a strange man in the audience: shoulder-length auburn hair and long
beard, blue-tinted granny glasses, hands full of silver rings,
smoking a cigarette. He looks like he has been hiding out in a
tattoo parlor for 20 years only to emerge, like some biker version
of Rip Van Winkle, at a show dominated by hip-hop and glitz.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something familiar about his face, and it doesn't
take the whole show to figure out he's Jim Carrey, waiting to
collect his award for best male performance for ``The Truman Show''
and to offer a deadpan explanation of his get-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this year's so-called Oscar race,'' he begins, swaying
as if he's too stoned to stand and alluding to the fact that he was
not nominated for an Academy Award, ``I realized that answerin' to
the man just ain't where it's at.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a funny performance, reflecting the irreverence that should
be automatic for these awards. The trophy, after all, is a bucket
of gilded popcorn. The show, which was taped on Saturday, is about
entertainment, not suspense. Some acceptance speeches were recorded
in advance by absent stars like Gwyneth Paltrow; by now
``Entertainment Tonight'' and ``Access Hollywood'' have revealed
the winners. But this year's installment is so flat that the Carrey
stunt leaps out as a moment of high energy in a show that
desperately needs to regain its satiric edge.
</P>
<P>
   As in any failed satire, the problem is the writing. The movie
parodies that are the heart of the show are lame, even when the
usually dependable Mike Myers appears as both the villainous Dr.
Evil and the goofily heroic Austin Powers from his new,
overpromoted film, ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the Carrey moment, you can count the show's
highlights: two. In a satire of ``Armageddon'' called ``Armageddo'n
Sync'' a giant asterisk hurtles toward earth and only the group 'N
Sync can save the world. A fake prize category, ``best dramatic
pause,'' offers clips of actual films in which actors look
concerned just a little too long. In ``Deep Impact'' Morgan Freeman
and a room full of White House advisers stare silently at one
another when they learn a meteor (or is it an asterisk?) is heading
their way.
</P>
<P>
   The host, Lisa Kudrow, offers a smooth variation on her Phoebe
ditziness from ``Friends.'' For his song ``Wild Wild West,'' Will
Smith leads a splashy group of dancers in what can only be called a
production number. There is a stream of big-name presenters, from
Courtney Love to James van der Beek and Ricky Martin, every
teen-age girl's dream boy of the moment. Somehow an almost serious
Hollywood attitude has crept in.
</P>
<P>
   Of course everything is relative. Compared with Sunday's
moribund, self-important Tony Awards show, the MTV Movie Awards
seem positively raucous. However disappointing the script, you have
to love the idea behind an awards show with a category like ``best
villain,'' whose nominees include Chucky, the killer doll from that
masterpiece of cinema ``Bride of Chucky.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE CHIMP CHANNEL
</P>
<P>
   TBS, Thursday at 10
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it seems that a bunch of monkeys couldn't do worse
than what's already on television; apparently they can. This
half-hour sitcom about a television channel run by chimps proves
that it takes more than monkeys with wigs and dubbed human voices
to make a comedy. ``The Chimp Channel'' is so scattershot and
predictable it becomes tiresome in about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That the mogul chimp who owns the network has an Australian
(that is, Murdochian) accent is funny once, not repeatedly. The
brief parodies of television shows and movies offer mere glimpses
of wit.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Treewatch'' a diva chimp called Monica wears a blond Pamela
Anderson wig and a red ``Baywatch'' bathing suit. In
``Braveheart,'' the heroic chimp has a blue-painted face; it might
have been funnier if the punch line hadn't been about lightning
bolts flaring out of the chimps' rear ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
