<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS10-COX     06-09 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democrats decry NRA influence on gun control proposals
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and congressional Democrats
accused House Republicans on Wednesday of buckling in to the
National Rifle Association and gutting proposed gun control
provisions scheduled for a House vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a bill, plainly, ghostwritten by the NRA,'' said
Clinton, speaking at a Justice Department conference. ``I think it
is wrong to let the NRA call the shots on this issue. They've been
calling the shots on this issue for decades now, and we have failed
to do what is manifestly in the interest of our children and our
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton angrily invoked the shootings of 12 students and a
teacher at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can still remember Littleton _ it hasn't even been two
months _ then we ought to speak up and be heard,'' Clinton said.
``This is a classic, horrible example of how Washington is out of
touch with the rest of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton delivered his remarks as the first details of the gun
control proposals drafted by Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde (R-Ill.) and Rep. Bill McCollum (R-Fla.) began circulating
among both gun control advocates and the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed language by Hyde and McCollum, to be offered as an
amendment to a massive juvenile crime bill, would soften some of
the requirements for criminal background checks conducted at gun
shows. Closing the so-called gun show loophole was a major flash
point in the Senate, which three weeks ago adopted strict language
to govern when and on whom the checks must be conducted.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Hyde acknowledged that Judiciary Committee
members had consulted the NRA in drafting the gun control
proposals. But Hyde denied that the changes represented a
capitulation to the powerful gun lobby, which has waged a
grass-roots campaign to kill the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't help draft it; they looked at it,'' Hyde said.
They had some commentary. But it's not an NRA provision.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun control proponents seized on two aspects of the
Hyde-McCollum legislation they said would dramatically weaken
similar provisions narrowly passed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate bill, gun shows would be defined as any
gathering where more than 50 guns were offered for sale. The House
version changes that requirement to any gathering where more than
10 dealers are brought together.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Rand, an analyst with the Violence Policy Center, said
the change could conceivably mean that nine dealers could sell
thousands of guns but still not be required to conduct background
checks. Guns sold at flea markets, for example, might not be
covered.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul McNulty, chief counsel for the Judiciary Committee,
said the Senate language was so broad that private sales between
gun collectors could be defined as a gun show. The House language
also would reverse a fundamental provision of the 1968 gun control
law passed after the assassinations of President John F. Kennedy,
his brother, Robert, and the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. Under that
law, sellers at gun shows are prohibited from shipping guns to
buyers out of state. The House version would permit dealers to ship
guns out of state after conducting a criminal background check on
the buyer. In a live video feed on the NRA's Web site, an NRA
announcer trumpeted the change in language to allow guns to be
shipped to buyers, noting that the provision ``was not allowed
under current law.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he added that NRA leaders were still encouraging
members to contact their member of Congress and ``let them know we
don't need more gun laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), the only member of the House who is an
NRA board member, said through his spokesman that he could not
support the Hyde-McCollum amendment on gun shows ``as is.'' The
spokesman declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
