<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9309 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-09 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PERFECT COACH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The search for the perfect NBA coach continues.
</P>
<P>
   Should he be an all-time, all-time All-Star? Oh, hi there, Mr.
Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Should he be a pretty-good-but-not-great pro player who has
earned a reputation as a superb teacher, albeit a very neurotic
one? Right this way, Mr. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Should he be a very good pro player who always believed the game
was more of an art form than a science? Say hello to Mr. Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   Should he be a championship-oriented, role-playing pro whose
former reputation as an innovator has regressed into a new image as
the game's mad scientist/funny uncle? Make way for Mr. Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Should he be a coaching move-up-the-ladder lifer and workaholic
who patiently sits around until the big names over him implode, one
way or the other? Meet Mr. Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Should he be an end-of-the-bench pro player who lucks into a
team with superb talent and gradually assumes the aura of a Captain
Queeg-style loner of a ``genius''? Bonjour, Monsieur Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Should he be an OK college player who sees the world through the
military and who pays his dues at forgotten levels of college ball
before getting a professional entree from the aforementioned
neurotic professor of hoop? Best of luck in the Finals, Mr.
Popovich.
</P>
<P>
   Should he be _ Ryan, that's enough!
</P>
<P>
   Or _ bear with me one more time _ should he be a fine pro player
turned announcer who has never coached a day in his life?
</P>
<P>
   John Gabriel apparently thinks that's the way to go. He's the
man who has just hired Doc Rivers to coach the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   That's Glenn ``Doc'' Rivers, as in the 13-year NBA Doc Rivers,
as in the three-year NBA commentator for Turner Broadcasting, as in
the never-run-a-practice-in-his-life Doc Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The non-experience obviously doesn't faze Mr. Gabriel. I mean,
just listen to the Magic's general manager blow his horn for his
new coach.
</P>
<P>
   After stating that he was ``blown away'' by Doc's interview,
Gabriel shifted into high rhetorical gear. ``He has demonstrated
over the course of his career to be a true leader and has been
preparing for this day for some time. He has a magnetic personality
and a sharp basketball mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, John, why don't you tell me something I didn't know?
</P>
<P>
   Understand that there are a few of us around here who have felt
very proprietary toward Mr. Glenn ``Doc'' Rivers ever since he
showed up on the Chicago team in the Boston Shootout a few years
back and put on one of the great shows in the history of that
cherished event. He had a bum knee and didn't have much of a first
half, as I recall.
</P>
<P>
   I also recall him unwrapping an Ace bandage from his knee with a
theatrical flourish and then pouring in 31 points in the second
half, leading his team to victory. From that point on I maintained
a very healthy interest in Mr. Glenn ``Doc'' Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   A few years after that he showed up in the NBA as a member of
the Atlanta Hawks. They grabbed him with the 31st pick in the draft
back in 1983, and what they got was a very capable NBA guard who
was able to make the transformation from shooting guard to point
guard and who earned a reputation as a very solid professional. Was
he a great player? No, he was not. But he was a good one, and he
did get himself into the 1988 All-Star Game in Chicago, where he
played not merely like someone who was happy just to be there but
also like someone who seemed to believe he really didn't belong
there. His 5-for-11 performance from the line was testimony to his
nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   But in what was then the biggest game of his life _ the famed
Game 7 Bird-Dominique fourth-quarter shootout _ the next best
player on the court was Doc Rivers. You ought to get hold of that
tape. There was far more to that game than just Larry and
Dominique. It was a phenomenal game that puts to shame anything the
league can offer today. And on that occasion Doc Rivers out-DJ'd
DJ.
</P>
<P>
   He remains one of the most likable NBA players I've ever known.
Unfailingly polite and gracious, he also revealed himself to be a
thinker. There was no doubt in anyone's mind that a broadcast job
awaited him the minute he was through playing, and that's exactly
what happened. Nor did he disappoint. He was a good announcer who
was continually getting better.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting vice president Kevin O'Malley got to know
Doc during the past three years, and you can put him down as a
paid-up member of the Doc Rivers Fan Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very smart and capable guy,'' says O'Malley. ``People
talk about the need to motivate today's young player, and in this
regard I think Doc will be aces. He has an extremely positive
intensity about the game. He is intense about the game in an upbeat
and positive way. He is simply very extroverted about the game. I
think he will be a terrific players' coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The modern formula for success when the new coach is a
basketball guy who has never coached is to surround him with guys
who can. This is how Hall of Fame coach Chuck Daly, Doc's immediate
predecessor, entered the NBA. The 76ers hired Billy Cunningham to
be Billy Cunningham. Daly was minding his own business at Penn when
the Kangaroo Kid rang him up and asked him to be his X and O man.
It's the Larry Bird M.O., too. Larry knew all the things he didn't
know, so that's why he hired former head coach Dick Harter and
future head coach Rick Carlisle to be his, well, teachers, thus
freeing him to be Larry Bird, a job he can handle very nicely.
Rivers now needs his own support system.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guaranteed formula for NBA coaching success. Doc
Rivers is, after all, Orlando's fourth coach since the start of the
1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   Check that. There is one 100 percent, fully guaranteed path to
NBA coaching success. You get hired to coach Michael Jordan just
when His Airness has all his fitting-in-with-teammates issues
sorted out. No offense, Mr. Jackson, but we all know this to be
true.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
