<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-TOBACCO10-COX     06-09 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-TOBACCO10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia governor draws fire with plan to spend tobacco money
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes defended his plan to spend one-third
of the state's $4.8 billion tobacco settlement on rural economic
development rather than using it all on health care, contending
Wednesday that job growth promotes public health.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that Georgia is a tobacco-producing
state, and a large part of rural Georgia is going to be adversely
affected,'' Barnes said. ``I know of nothing that is more directly
connected with health than the ability to be employed and to be
able to eat. ... I don't consider that to be any kind of a change
from what I've said all along.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Barnes justified his new spending proposal, anti-tobacco
activists and some Republican legislators reacted with dismay,
saying the plan represented an inappropriate use of the tobacco
settlement, as well as a reversal of Barnes' promises to dedicate
the money to health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' said Lynn Thogersen, coordinator of an
Atlanta-based anti-smoking coalition, ``because the whole intent of
the settlement was to win this financial compensation for the
state, to help recoup a small portion of the state's money that's
been spent on tobacco-related illnesses. The intent was never to
subsidize farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were basically asked by the governor's office to work with
him to ensure that this money went for health care,'' Thogersen
added. ``This is a total shift from what we've been told.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Minority Leader Eric Johnson (R-Savannah) said the
governor's proposal to spend money _ about $68 million the first
year _ on rural development would generate ``a big debate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge amount of money,'' said Johnson, who supports
using the settlement for smoking prevention and for tax cuts. ``I
want to see a lot more details. But I would be hesitant at this
point to support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Georgia tobacco farmers will receive $309 million of
a separate $5.15 billion payment from tobacco companies to growers,
Barnes said a portion of the state's settlement should go to South
Georgia's tobacco-producing counties to ``encourage industry and
business to come there and help offset some of the lost jobs in
tobacco and to provide a better-trained work force for those
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes complained that any discussion of spending the
state's settlement is premature. ``We're straining here,'' he said,
``talking about things that are down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   He had outlined his ideas in a May 26 letter to state
legislative leaders, saying one-third of the settlement should
bolster ``the bottom 25 percent of the counties in Georgia that are
not prospering along with the rest of the state.'' The other
two-thirds, he wrote then, would ``offset some existing health care
responsibilities and expand health care to some uninsured segments
of our state.''
</P>
<P>
   If Georgia spent its entire settlement (to be paid out over 25
years) on health care, it would be one of the few states to resist
the temptation to dip into the tobacco loot.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids, a
Washington-based advocacy group, found that four states have
devoted most of their settlements to smoking prevention programs,
while 16 have spent nothing on prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some successes,'' said Peter Fisher, who supervised
the study. ``But more states are not spending it on tobacco
prevention than are.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
