<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARASS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court considers boss' staring: Harmless or sexual harassment?
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If a boss constantly follows an employee around the
workplace, is that sexual harassment? What if he also stares up and
down at her in a suggestive manner?
</P>
<P>
   During a lively argument Wednesday, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals considered a case likely to decide how far suggestive
behavior in the workplace can go.
</P>
<P>
   One federal judge suggested that the behavior alleged in the
lawsuit went beyond a sexual harassment claim _ it was enough to
prompt a self-respecting woman to throw a ``haymaker'' at the man
giving her the eye and following her around.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Red Mendoza began working for Borden Inc. at its Miami
facility. By late 1994, she was being followed constantly by Dan
Page, the highest-ranking executive at the office, her lawsuit
against the company claims.
</P>
<P>
   Page also stared at Mendoza, looking her up and down and then
fixing his gaze on her groin area, Mendoza contends.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge dismissed Mendoza's claims at trial, and she
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a three-judge panel of the 11th Circuit ruled
unanimously that her sexual harassment claims should be allowed to
go before a jury. But in March, a majority of the 12-member court
voted to vacate that decision and allow the entire court to
reconsider the issue. The court's decisions set federal law in
Georgia, Alabama and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under what circumstances, if any, does a supervisor's
'following' and 'staring' at an employee constitute a sexual
advance or verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature under
Title VII'' of the Civil Rights Act, the court asked both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rosemary Barkett, who wrote the initial ruling, reminded
her colleagues Wednesday that her decision stated that
``following'' and ``staring'' are not enough to make a sexual
harassment claim.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Parsons, a Miami lawyer representing Borden, said the
alleged behavior in the case against Borden was little more than
that. ``It's bad policy'' to allow sexual harassment cases to
proceed on that basis because ``too many disgruntled employees will
sue their bosses, saying, 'He looked at me wrong,''' Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   But Barkett noted that, during trial, Mendoza testified that on
one occasion, Page told her, ``I'm getting fired up,'' when she
entered the office. Another time, he rubbed his hip against hers as
she stood next to a copying machine, Barkett said, citing Mendoza's
testimony. Barkett repeatedly asked Parsons whether it could be
considered sexual conduct for a man to stare up and down at a woman
and fix his gaze on her groin area, even making sniffing noises on
occasion. ``That could never be considered sexual?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, who said Page may have suffered from allergies, told
Barkett that her question called for an answer that is ``utterly
subjective.'' He finally conceded, ``I'd say, your honor, that
you're trying to force me into a corner, and you're doing a good
job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Gerald Tjoflat, who joined Barkett in the initial opinion,
appeared incredulous when Parsons said that staring, following and
sniffing did not necessarily connote sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   If a woman had to endure such behavior, Tjoflat asked,
``wouldn't you to expect her to give you a haymaker or a kick in
another area?''
</P>
<P>
   Unyielding, Parsons replied that sniffing is ``so innocuous.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tjoflat pressed on. ``He's looking at the groin and
sniffing, in this testimony. What kind of response would you expect
from a woman with any kind of dignity and self-respect? Wouldn't
you expect her to slap him?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, your honor,'' Parsons said, suggesting that the
appropriate response would be for the woman to tell the man to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Tjoflat then shook his head, looked at Parsons and said, ``We
grew up in different times.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
