u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIGARS-RISKS-BOS &LR;      06-09 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGARS-RISKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CONCERN ON HEALTH RISKS OF CIGARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A California study has found that regular cigar smoking
significantly increases risks of heart and respiratory disease and
some cancers, and raises fears that cigars and alcohol together may
be a particularly hazardous combination.
</P>
<P>
   The findings add weight to research indicating that smoking
cigars is far from safe _ something that may not be recognized by
the many who have been making cigars fashionable in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the increased health risk was found in men who smoked
five or more cigars a day. Only 17 percent of the study subjects
smoked that heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus our findings should not be generalized to people who
smoke cigars infrequently,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Most worrying of the findings is the apparent synergy between
cigar smoke and alcohol, creating higher risks than with either by
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The popularity of cigar bars where both cigar smoking and
alcohol consumption are encouraged arouses special concern with
respect to the public health,'' commented Dr. David Satcher, the US
surgeon general, in an editorial being published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 1,546 cigar smokers and 16,228 nonsmokers showed
that cigar smoking raised a man's risk of heart disease and certain
cancers by as much as twofold. While significant, the hazard is
much less than from cigarette smoking, which increases risks 1.5 to
3 times for coronary heart disease, 9 to 25 times for emphysema and
related lung diseases, and 8 to 24 times for lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher, in the accompanying editorial, called for raising
federal taxes on cigars, which now are much less than for
cigarettes, and said that warning labels similar to those on
cigarette packages should be required for cigars. ``It is critical
that cigars not be construed as a safe or less costly alternative
to cigarettes,'' Satcher wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar sales increased nearly 50 percent between 1993 and 1997 as
part of a trend among young and middle-aged, mainly upscale men. In
California, the percentage of men smoking cigars rose from 4.8
percent in 1990 to 8.8 percent in 1996, according to Satcher.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's report is from a study by Dr. Carlos Iribarren and
colleagues at the Kaiser Permanente Medical Care Program in
Oakland, Calif. They drew their subjects from a group of 17,774
men, ages 30 to 85, who were enrolled in the health plan. None of
them had ever smoked cigarettes and did not currently smoke a pipe.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,546 men who smoked cigars, 76 percent smoked fewer than
five a day and 17 percent smoked more than five daily. Compared
with the men who did not smoke cigars, those who did were more
likely to be black or white and less likely to be Asian, to have no
college education, and to drink alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing health records, the researchers concluded that
the cigar smokers, taken as a whole:
</P>
<P>
   --Had moderately higher risks for coronary heart disease and
obstructive lung diseases such as emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   --Had about twice as much risk of mouth, throat, and lung cancer
as nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   --Had about the same risk of cancer as nonsmokers when all
cancer types were lumped together.
</P>
<P>
   --Appeared to have greater risk of mouth and throat cancer if
they both smoked and drank three or more drinks a day than if those
two risk factors were considered alone. This pattern has been seen
in those who smoke cigarettes and drink alcohol, but had not been
reported for cigar smokers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the authors said this apparently link should be treated
cautiously because the number of such cases in the study was small.
</P>
<P>
   Cigars give off toxic smoke similar to that of cigarettes, but
more potent, say health officials. The health risks of cigarettes
are higher because the smoke is more likely to be inhaled, but
cigar smokers may not realize how much they are inhaling, said
Gregory Connolly, head of the state Tobacco Control Program in the
Department of Public Health.
</P>
</TEXT>
