<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9326 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SLAYING-BOS &LR;      06-09 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLING DETAILS EMERGE ABOUT SLAIN COMEDIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ On Monday, when Mexican comedian Francisco
``Paco'' Stanley was gunned down in broad daylight on the street,
there was all-out rage.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, when his gray casket was lifted from a flower-strewn
hearse, carried passed teary mobs and placed in the family's
mausoleum, there were wails of grief and the mournful strum of
mariachi guitars.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as shadowy details of Stanley's private life began
to emerge _ including signs of cocaine paraphernalia in his car,
cocaine in his bloodstream, and alleged links to drug kings _ many
Mexicans coped with the news by reverting back to the cynicism that
has hardened their views of life in one of the world's most
dangerous places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, but not really surprised,'' said Gabriela
Lozano, a 22-year-old college student, said Wednesday while sitting
in a park with three friends. ``It didn't seem like something by
chance. From the beginning there was something strange about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no suspects yet and police say they have few leads,
but plenty of troubling details have emerged about the popular
56-year-old entertainer, who was killed outside a Mexico City
restaurant in an attack that police said appeared planned.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators confirmed that cocaine was found in Stanley's
blood, and that small packets of the drug as well as a small mortar
and grinding pestle were recovered around Stanley's body, which was
found slumped in the front passenger seat of his Lincoln sport
utility vehicle. A bystander was also killed.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, several Mexican newspapers published reports quoting
Mexican and US narcotics intelligence sources linking Stanley to
one of Mexico's most notorious drug figures, Amado Carrillo
Fuentes, saying the comedian received lavish gifts from the leader
of the Juarez cartel before Carrillo Fuentes's death in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The sources also noted that the method of the slaying _ a flurry
of more than two-dozen bullets shot at close range _ was similar to
killings carried out by a rival drug cartel run by Benjamin
Arellano Felix.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures seemed to dampen the anger that swept across the
country on Monday, when citizens, among them network anchors, cried
out for an end to Mexico's nearly five-year-old crime wave and
demanded that authorities resign their posts for failing to stop
it.
</P>
<P>
   But not even the disappointment in learning the sordid details
of a slain star can douse people's sense of frustration that comes
with feeling that their lives are constantly in danger, said one
psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that most crime against ordinary people is random, so
we get tired of constantly being on our guard,'' said Sylvia
Aguinilla, a therapist who specializes in family counseling.
``Meanwhile, the sensational crimes against celebrities stay in our
memories and add to our insecurities.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials defend their work by noting that
statistically crime is down compared to last year in several
categories in this metropolis of 20 million residents. But a poll
published Wednesday by the daily Reforma showed that half of the
respondents still feel powerless and unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   Another item found on Stanley's possession _ an Interior
Ministry ID card identifying him as a government security agent _
underlined many Mexicans' desire to seek as much protection as they
can from lawless elements.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley drama has also produced an unusual backlash against
the country's two television networks. Politicians on Wednesday
accused Televisa and TV Azteca of unfairly blaming them for
Stanley's death.
</P>
<P>
   Only days before the shooting, TV Azteca celebrated the first
anniversary of its renowned anti-drug campaign on a prime time
program featuring Stanley, who exhorted viewers not to take drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Both Televisa and Azteca, which devoted hours of live coverage
on Monday and Tuesday, have mentioned little about the medical
examiner's results and even less about the newspaper reports
alleging Stanley's connections to organized crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
