<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLFGOUGE10-COX     06-09 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLFGOUGE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Price-gouging discouraged as tourney nears
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Visitors to next week's U.S. Open golf
championship need to watch their wallets to make sure no hotel,
restaurant or golf course is slicing an extra deep divot out of
them.
</P>
<P>
   A night's stay in a two-bedroom suite at the Marriott Residence
Inn will cost $499, more than double the typical rate. A round of
golf at Plantation Golf Club will go for $200, an $85 premium over
the regular green fee.
</P>
<P>
   The Magnolia Inn is doubling its nightly room charge to $400.
That does include breakfast and dinner in the 1896 inn in the heart
of Pinehurst, where businesses hope to cash in on the village's
first U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Some in this famous golf resort in North Carolina's Sandhills
fret that people will feel ripped off and won't come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job that week is to show the world what a wonderful
product we offer, not to gouge the world and have them go home
saying, `Isn't Pinehurst an expensive place?''' said John
McDougald, golf director of Talamore Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   As president of the Sandhills Golf Association, which represents
12 courses and 17 hotels, McDougald is among officials urging
businesses to curb the urge to sock it to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard, though, for businesses not to get excited about the
prospect of 50,000 people _ many with plenty of money to spend _
pouring in every day. In strictly business terms, demand outstrips
supply for many services in Pinehurst and the nearby towns of
Southern Pines and Aberdeen.
</P>
<P>
   Pure Gold, an adult night club, is adding dancers and cocktail
waitresses. Hotels for miles around have been booked for a year or
more. Restaurant reservations are hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating waiting lines of two or three hours, Outback
Steakhouse plans to add tables on the patio and fire up grills in
the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Even the village of Pinehurst is getting something extra. It is
collecting $275,000 for renting approximately 150 acres for
tournament parking.
</P>
<P>
   Typically at this time of year, golf courses are charging summer
rates, among the lowest of the year. Many, however, plan to charge
the spring rate during the tournament, resulting in fees of about
30 percent higher, said Bill Tracy, who arranges Sandhills
hotel-and-golf packages.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its sharply higher green fee, the Plantation Golf Club
``has a waiting list for tee times on most days,'' golf director
Jimmy Mikol said. ``I don't think the (higher price) is going to
hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some merchants are holding the line on prices, despite the bucks
that big corporations are throwing around to entertain customers at
one of America's most prestigious sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most visible signs of extravagance is a temporary
tent city, called the Corporate Hospitality Village. Erected along
the golf course where the tournament will be played, it consists of
49 big canvas tents, each renting for $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   At the Villager, a breakfast and lunch deli, owner Carol Horne
said raising prices would be unfair to locals and other regular
diners. Added her husband, Gene, ``Hopefully, a lot of people will
come back to Pinehurst, revisit Pinehurst and eventually move to
Pinehurst.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some who are charging higher fees said they're not
exploiting customers. At Magnolia Inn, where the dinner charge is
$55 for nonguests, the restaurant has incurred the expense of
buying extra china and silver to accommodate big crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``An event like this typically costs more than you make,'' chef
Mark Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Inn manager Jennifer Ormond said she turned down a request by
Charlotte-based Bank of America to rent the entire 11-room inn. If
she had rented it, she said she would have been unable to
accommodate some of her regular guests who were willing to pay $400
a night.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the get-rich frenzy swept through this village of
8,059 people. Talk began circulating that hospitality groups were
willing to pay thousands of dollars to rent peoples' homes for
business people to socialize.
</P>
<P>
   One house near Pinehurst Resort and Country Club's famed No. 2
course, the tournament site, did fetch $80,000. But the sports
management company running the tournament stuck by the United
States Golf Association's recommendation that residents charge a
weekly rate of $1,500 to $2,000 per bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Swindon, accommodations manager for Pinehurst
Championship Management, said his office rented about 200 houses
within those guidelines. He said he turned down another 500
homeowners. Swindon estimated that property owners and managers
rented another 100 private residences on their own.
</P>
<P>
   When he began looking for ``affordable housing'' in March,
Atlantan Glen Harris settled on Pine Lake RV Resort. He and his
three friends will each pay $150 for four nights in a trailer.
</P>
<P>
   With plans to play four rounds of golf and watch the tournament,
Harris figures his group will be tired at night. He hopes that will
make the modest sleeping arrangements more acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our eyes closed and it being dark, what difference does
it make?'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
