<HEADER>
A9329 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-09 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CHILDREN IN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you want to see something shaky, take a look at
the health of the homeless kids in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless got a lot of air time in the '80s, but that's over.
The mask of the triumphant suburbanite is the face of the '90s, and
poverty is no longer discussed in polite company.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani dumped the slackers off the
welfare rolls and a nation applauded. Forget about the effect on
kids. We learned in Littleton, if we hadn't realized it before,
that our concern with children depends largely on where and what
color they are.
</P>
<P>
   There remain, however, in this dismal and cynical environment,
some remarkable individuals who insist on donning unfashionable
trunks and swimming upstream. Dr. Irwin Redlener, the president of
the Children's Hospital at Montefiore Medical Center in the Bronx,
is one of them. In addition to his position at the hospital,
Redlener is president of the Children's Health Fund, a nonprofit
group that provides desperately needed pediatric services to
homeless children.
</P>
<P>
   He is releasing a report on Thursday that tells us a lot of
those kids are in trouble medically, and not nearly enough people
are paying attention. The report is called ``Still in Crisis: The
Health Status of New York's Homeless children.''
</P>
<P>
   The most serious problem is the asthma that is rampant among
homeless children. An astonishing 38 percent of the more than 8,000
kids in the city's shelter system have asthma. Redlener said that
was ``the highest prevalence of asthma in any child population
that's ever been reported.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``This worries me a great deal, because asthma is,
first of all, life-threatening for children. But besides that, even
in its milder forms, it fits into the category of chronic
conditions that adversely affect the ability of a child to function
in school.''
</P>
<P>
   What is particularly frustrating, said Redlener, is that the
severe distress encountered by homeless children with asthma is
almost entirely unnecessary. ``Asthma is eminently treatable,'' he
said. ``The reality of the new protocols for asthma treatment mean
_ and I am not overstating this _ we should accept no missed school
days because of asthma, no staying up all night and coughing, and
no missed physical activities.''
</P>
<P>
   But connecting homeless children to the proper medical protocols
is extremely difficult. Just keeping track of the kids is
difficult. The report makes clear that the ``real'' problem for
such children is their lack of access ``to vital preventive care
and the management of chronic conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the chaos of homelessness, small problems are always in
danger of spiraling out of control. Ear infections are a common
childhood ailment. They are more prevalent among homeless kids than
the general childhood population. The report notes that a simple
ear infection, if not treated properly, ``can lead to hearing loss
and less than optimum speech development resulting from an
inability to hear sounds clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   A homeless kid who goes off to school with an undiagnosed
hearing disorder has been exquisitely prepared to drown
academically.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that more than 60 percent of 2- and 3-year-old
children in the shelter system had not been properly immunized
against measles, mumps, whooping cough or a range of other
preventable diseases. And Redlener mentioned that many of the
children were suffering from the severe stress that so often
accompanies the unrelieved chaos of homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are frightened,'' he said. ``They live in a very unstable
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Redlener is upset by the extent to which poor children languish,
neglected and vulnerable, in the shadows of American life. ``I've
been at this for 30 years now, dealing with underserved children,''
he said. ``I find myself very frustrated and distressed. The safety
net that's really supposed to be in place from the public sector _
from government _ is very much failing our children.''
</P>
<P>
   A new and more creative look at this old problem is required, he
said. And if government is unwilling to fulfill its role, then
other, less traditional sources of help will have to be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to re-energize this notion of needing to take care of
those who are most vulnerable in our society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
