<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD GUYS STAY TO BURY THE DOG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Just before a recent New Hampshire kaffeeklatsch for
Representative  &UR; John Kasich &LR; , R-Ohio, a would-be presidential
contender, hostess  &UR; Linda Kaiser &LR;  realized that she was short on
ice. When she jumped into her car and backed down the driveway, she
hit and killed her 13-year-old family dog.
</P>
<P>
   When the candidate heard about the accident, he offered to
cancel the coffee, but Kaiser insisted on going ahead.
</P>
<P>
   And when the event was over, he insisted on helping to bury the
dog. ``He said, `If I ever told my wife I left without burying this
dog, we'd be divorced. Get a shovel,''' Kaiser told the Manchester
Union Leader.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate had ``revealed himself as a real person,'' said
Kaiser. ``I can't imagine  &UR; Elizabeth Dole &LR;  or  &UR; George W. Bush &LR; 
burying my dog.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT THEY'RE WEARING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Major League Baseball Barbie, to go on sale in a week, will
wear the home uniform of the Los Angeles Dodgers, Chicago Cubs or
New York Yankees. Each outfit will include authentic logo, pants,
jersey, cap, jacket and shoes, and each package will include a
miniature glove, ball and wooden bat.
</P>
<P>
   In another Barbie developments &LR; , Mattel has announced that it
has taken ``Butterfly Art Barbie'' _ with its giant midriff tattoo
_ off the market. ``We've just had some consumers who didn't like
it,'' said  &UR; Lisa McKendall &LR;  of Mattel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Tom Ed McHugh &LR; , the mayor of Baton Rouge, La., has declared
June 1 through September 6 Casual Summer. Workers are encouraged to
forgo suits and formal dresses in favor of khakis, golf shirts and
summery frocks (sounds like the men get a better deal).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Elizabeth Emanuel &LR; , who designed  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 's wedding
dress, is bankrupt, and lawyers for her creditors are asking that
scraps from the dress _ found in a trunk _ be auctioned to pay them
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a terrible situation,'' Emanuel told the Sunday Times of
London. ``The trustee is telling me how much the auction house is
dribbling at the thought of selling this. Everyone is drooling over
it _ it makes me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Bianca Jagger &LR;  is so angry about a Talk of the Town piece in
last week's New Yorker that described her as ``the  &UR; Rodney &LR; 
 &UR; Dangerfield &LR;  of philanthropists,'' sincere but not always perfectly
informed, that she is threatening to sue. MSNBC quotes a letter to
the magazine in which Jagger called the story defamatory and
accused its writer of taking ``the misogynist view that a woman's
work cannot be judged on its own merit.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Adrian Perry &LR; , 18-year-old son of Aerosmith guitarist  &UR; Joe &LR; 
 &UR; Perry &LR; , starts at Stanford in the fall. Papa Perry told the Boston
Herald that Adrian wants to be a lawyer, ``and if there's one thing
I found out, it's that one of the most important things to have in
this business is a good lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Deborah Kwan &LR;  was delighted by New York Times restaurant
reviewer  &UR; William Grimes &LR; ' description of a ``hypertrained''
waiter, ``late 20th century model,'' who told him of the scallops
being served: ``They are harvested by divers. Most scallops are
machine-harvested, which traumatizes them.''
</P>
<P>
   - Celebrity biographer  &UR; Kitty Kelley &LR;  was at a state dinner for
the president of Hungary the other night. The Washington Post
suggested that the  &UR; Clinton &LR; s may have wanted to make nice to
Kelley, author of a notoriously nasty biography of  &UR; Nancy Reagan &LR; ,
to head off any notions of writing about would-be New Yorker
 &UR; Hillary &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELEMENTARY IDEAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In response to yesterday's call for name suggestions for
Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory's new elements 116 and 118:
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bellium and 3-Comium ( &UR; Jim Schock &LR; ); millennium ( &UR; Roger &LR; 
 &UR; Estrella &LR; ); ellingtonium ( &UR; John Hules &LR; , in honor of the composer's
centenary); linoleum ( &UR; David Mostardi &LR; ); intelligencium and
attentionspanium ( &UR; Paul Sullam &LR; , keeping in mind the elements'
short half-lives); Dumbo ( &UR; Bob Wieder &LR; , who got through chemistry
thinking an element was a four-legged animal with a trunk). More to
come, and the suggestion box is still open.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``(Madonna) probably hates my guts. But I hope not, because I'm
a big fan.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Salma Hayek &LR;  telling Glamour magazine about developing a
movie about Frida Kahlo, in which she'll star.  &UR; Madonna &LR; 's plans to
play the celebrated Mexican artist fell through.
</P>
</TEXT>
