<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, June 10. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead stories:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Kumanovo, Macedonia) _ The Yugoslav military accedes
to an agreement that will permit a military force commanded by a
NATO general with sweeping powers to occupy Kosovo, clearing the
way to an end to the Western alliance's first war. By Steven Lee
Myers. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
Eds.: This story was budgeted earlier as KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS.
</P>
<P>
   The stories run under a 4-column, 2-line hed.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Lapusnik, Yugoslavia) _ Todor is a soldier, a
factory worker from northern Serbia who volunteered to come here to
Kosovo and defend it for his country. He knows his war is about to
end. But he wonders whether the outcome was worth the price, to his
own comrades and to the Albanians of this southern Serbian
province. ``I'm angry about how it's ending,'' he said. ``This
should have been done better. A lot of people have died for
nothing. And I believe that in four or five years, no Serb will
still be living in Kosovo.'' By Steven Erlanger. (Scheduled to move
by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 3-column photo; with map.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-TREATMENT (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ A dozen years after the
national alarm over crack speeded the discarding of drug treatment
in favor of punitive laws that helped create the world's largest
prison system, drug policy is taking another turn. Treatment is
making a comeback, driven largely by a grass-roots revolt. By
Timothy Egan. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   Special Report: 3,100 words. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Eds.: an abridged version will also move.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   GOP-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ While fund raising is a feast for
George W. Bush, the Texas governor's financial success has left
some other GOP contenders fighting for table scraps. By Don Van
Natta. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ There may be a relative peace
in the Balkans, but the 120,000 Kosovar Albanian refugees who have
staggered across the border are still anxious about how they will
ever safely go home again. Many refugees were stripped by Serbian
officials of all identity cards, drivers' licenses and passports as
they fled from Kosovo. And if Serbs control the re-entry process,
then the Kosovar refugees say the Serbs will simply keep them out
by telling the refugees that they have no proof that they belong in
Kosovo. By Elizabeth Bumiller. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET
in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLICE-RACE (Washington) _ Declaring racial profiling
``morally indefensible,'' President Clinton orders federal
law-enforcement agencies to compile data on the race and ethnicity
of people they question, search or arrest in order to determine how
often suspects are stopped because of the color of their skin. By
Steven Holmes. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-CLOUD (Undated) _ Scientists have discovered to their
surprise that a haze of air pollution about the size of the United
States covers the Indian Ocean in the wintertime, and they say it
may have important implications for global climate and the regional
environment of both Asia and the tropical ocean. By William K.
Stevens. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-JUVENILES (Washington) _ President Clinton assails House
Republicans' gun-control proposals as flawed measures that are
``plainly ghostwritten'' by the National Rifle Association, which
he said is successfully whittling away at the modest new
restrictions on firearms approved by the Senate last month. By
Frank Bruni. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-EXCHANGES (Undated) _ China has canceled at least four
American-Chinese cultural exchanges over anger at the U.S. bombing
of embassy in Belgrade. By Ralph Blumenthal. (The story has moved
in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
