<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Thursday, June 10. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BUSH (Phoenix) - Two weeks ago Congressman Matt Salmon made a
pilgrimage to Austin Texas, where he sipped tea with Texas Gov.
George Bush and asked the presidential candidate a simple question:
Would the front-runner make a stand in the state of Arizona? Bush,
in an attempt to put to rest rumors that he was ceding the state to
John McCain, said yes. By KRIS MAYES. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MOVIES (Phoenix) - There is a lack of good alternatives to R-rated
movies for teens, and many of the alternatives are flops at the box
office. Why? These R-rated movies are marketed to teens. The
movie's success depends on this market. And even if they stayed
home from the movie and watched the WB instead, they'd still see
sex and violence. Even teen magazines are chock full of ads for
sex. We'll also mention that parents take their kids to the r-rated
movies anyway. Call that the moral decline of America. By JAIMEE
ROSE. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``E'' categories. &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - I was biting into the best tortilla of my
life at my favorite Mexican restaurant in Los Angeles when I saw
her. Sitting at the next table behind my friend Jeff's head, there
she was. My eighth-grade math teacher. I couldn't mistake her still
jet-black hair, the soft curve of her almond-shaped eyes and her
thin, pursed lips. It was her, all right. By LAURI NOTARO. Story
moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHER-MUSIC (Phoenix) - The joke is so old that now Cher even tells
it on herself. Q: Name the only creatures that will survive a
nuclear holocaust? A: Cockroaches and Cher. With CHERSIDE-MUSIC. By
RANDY CORDOVA. Stories moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MUSIC AUCTION (Phoenix) - Some people say that music is priceless.
But when it comes to '80s country queen Sylvia, there is a price:
$280, to be exact. By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
