<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9343 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER10-COX     06-09 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speedup in primaries raises stakes in state straw polls
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The nominating process for the 2000 presidential
election, already speeded up beyond any comparison with previous
election years, has come a-tumbling in the past few days _ perhaps
all the way back to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire House voted 29-5 Wednesday to eliminate the
requirement that its primary be held in the presidential election
year, giving the New Hampshire secretary of state the power to set
the date as early as December.
</P>
<P>
   That unprecedented move followed the decision by the South
Carolina Republican Party late last week to hold its primary on
Saturday, Feb. 19. That change in turn was a reaction to Michigan's
decision to move its primary up to Feb. 22, and by Virginia's move
to Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire may not opt to move all the way back into '99, but
it's almost certain to schedule its primary no later than Feb. 8.
And since the Iowa Caucuses are currently set for Feb. 9, there
will probably be another round of changes in the election calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional early states are racing to stay ahead of the
pack, but at this rate, they'll have to vote before the current
heat wave breaks to ensure their lead. Pundits take comforting
assurance in the words, ``It's too early to tell,'' which in the
past always had the ring of wisdom about them. This time, however,
``too early to tell'' will be Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that these developments can only give a greater
advantage to the usual suspects, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice
President Al Gore. With the accelerated schedule, the ability to
raise a lot of money this year and set up effective organizations
in the key states becomes even more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a money and endorsements and team-talent primary that
precedes the firing of the first gun,'' said Ralph Reed, the former
Christian Coalition leader who now is working for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The politically dubious arena of state party straw polls will be
where much of this early contest will be fought out. This year,
they are earlier and more numerous than ever. Iowa, mirroring its
first-in-the-nation (until now) caucuses, will hold the first GOP
straw poll Aug. 14. The Alabama Republicans have just scheduled one
on Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Bush, the only Republican likely to benefit from the
speed-up is Steve Forbes, simply because he doesn't have to raise
money and is already on the air and in newspapers with campaign
ads. But this was scant comfort to Rusty Paul, Forbes' Southern
political director.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it probably helps my guy somewhat, it's still a heck of
a way to pick the leader of the free world,'' Paul said Wednesday.
Paul, the former Georgia GOP chairman, said he would even favor
Congress stepping in at this stage to stop the states from
``running amok.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest anyone think this means the race is over, there was another
piece of political news Wednesday. Bush, in a letter to Grover
Norquist, head of Americans for Tax Reform, pledged he would
``oppose and veto'' any income tax increases as president.
</P>
<P>
   What could have prompted him, leading the pack by a mile or two,
to sign a letter that brings back to mind the ``read my lips''
pledge that was so instrumental in his father's defeat in 1992?
Maybe there's time left for a race, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
