<P>
   The New York Times plans two and a half pages on Kosovo for
Thursday, June 10.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Kumanovo, Macedonia) _ The Yugoslav military accedes
to an agreement that will permit a military force commanded by a
NATO general with sweeping powers to occupy Kosovo, clearing the
way to an end of the war. With the agreement, signed at a French
helicopter base not far from the border of the province prized by
the Serbs for centuries as their Jerusalem, NATO's political
leaders gave the alliance's Secretary General, Javier Solana, the
authority to suspend the bombing once the military verifies that
the Serbian-dominated Army, police and paramilitary units begin to
withdraw from Kosovo. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   (This story was budgeted earlier as KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (LAPUSNIK, Kosovo) _ Talking with Serbian soldiers:
In this blasted, burned-out village, where Serbian soldiers keep
guard from inside destroyed Albanian houses and shops, Todor, a
volunteer, wondered today whether the outcome was worth the price,
to his own comrades and to the Albanians of this southern Serbian
province. ``I'm angry about how it's ending,'' he said, rubbing his
hand along his dirty blond beard. ``This should have been done
better. A lot of people have died for nothing. And I believe that
in four or five years, no Serb will still be living in Kosovo.'' By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ There may be a relative peace
on the horizon in the Balkans, but the 120,000 an refugees who have
staggered across the border into this hot, dusty and rubble-strewn
mountain town are still anxious about how they will ever safely go
home again. By Elizabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The scene in the beleaguered
Yugoslavian capital as the lights in the central square are turned
on for the first time in 10 months and people flock into the
streets. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Cologne, Germany) _ A detailed reconstruction of
how the delicate and carefully timed negotiations that led to an
agreement unfolded. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ Six weeks ago, as NATO
leaders met in Washington, commentators and White House officials
described the war in Kosovo as big casino for Bill Clinton _ the
pivotal moment of his presidency. Tuesday, as the pieces of a
political settlement fell slowly into place, as if in stop-action
photography, the domestic political impact of the fighting in the
Balkans seems sure to be less dramatic. By R.W. Apple.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ Defense Secretary Cohen and other
U.S. military officials give their assessments of how the American
involvement will progress from this point. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: for space reasons, the following story may fold into the
above, under the single slug KOSOVO-MILITARY.).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO slowed but did not stop the
bombing of Yugoslavia Wednesday, allied officers said, insisting
that there would be no formal halt until Yugoslav commanders began
pulling Serb forces out of Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ House Republicans, backed by
Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, revive attempts to bar money for
American peacekeeping troops in Kosovo. Democrats said the move
would make Congress ``a laughingstock'' and subvert the search for
peace at the moment the Yugoslav Army agreed to withdraw from
Kosovo. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ The vote by the U.N. Security
Council. This story will not move until and unless such a vote
takes place later tonight. By Judith Miller.
</P>
