<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ELATION IN THE CAPITAL OVER KOSOVO, BUT NOT MANY RUMBLINGS,
EITHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Six weeks ago, as NATO leaders met in Washington,
commentators and White House officials described the war in Kosovo
as big casino for Bill Clinton _ the pivotal moment of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, as the pieces of a political settlement fell
slowly into place, as if in stop-action photography, the domestic
political impact of the fighting in the Balkans seems sure to be
less dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   A defeat or a quagmire might well have damaged Clinton's
reputation severely; his poll ratings had begun to sag, slowly but
surely, when no end to the conflict could be discerned.
</P>
<P>
   But a victory, if that is the right word for the outcome of a
war that nobody really won, appears unlikely to improve the
president's standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success, such as it is, will not fundamentally reshape
people's views of Bill Clinton,'' said Andrew Kohut of the Pew
Research Center, a polling organization. ``Americans saw this war
as an important event, and they think the president did the right
thing morally. But they never thought our national interests were
at stake, as they thought they were during the Gulf War.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a senior fellow at the Brookings Institution who
has been watching presidents for decades, said in April, ``Kosovo
and the Balkans will consume his presidency.'' He revised that
opinion Wednesday, conceding that ``things undoubtedly changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, Hess said, ``did lose that small window of
opportunity with the Republicans in Congress right after the
impeachment trial, when they might have agreed on a small
domestic-policy agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But that was never central,'' he continued, ``and it's clear
now that this will not be a defining event. The sand is running out
of the hourglass, his term is coming to an end, and I doubt that
we'll see any great change in his legacy over the next 18 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, that will be up to the historians to decide. They
are still arguing over the accomplishments of James K. Polk. But in
the near term, the president will gain few points with voters or
with Congress, where many members already regard him as a figure
whose powers decline with each day. Relative success in Kosovo,
even substantial success, will not change that.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be no sense of elation, either in Washington or
elsewhere in the country, that the Kosovo bombing is coming to an
end. It is not yet clear how many refugees will be resettled in
Kosovo, at what cost, for how long, with what degree of safety.
Keeping 7,000 American troops in Kosovo and helping to rebuild the
Balkans could cost the United States $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no telling how long the force will have to stay to
keep the Kosovo Albanians and the Serbs from each others' throats.
Clinton promised that the American military would be out of Bosnia
in a year; troops have been there three and a half years, and they
are not about to leave soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even a relatively clear-cut victory, of course, carries no
guarantee of immediate political benefit. President Bush, the
victor of the Gulf War, went down to defeat by Clinton not too long
thereafter, as public attention swung from foreign policy to
domestic economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Vice President Al Gore appears to be one of the
beneficiaries of the evolving settlement. It would have been
difficult for a man so closely identified with Clinton and his
policies to campaign in the midst of a war that dragged on and on.
The example of Hubert H. Humphrey in the campaign of 1968, during
the Vietnam stalemate, has been much on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, the war provided a welcome distraction from his
impeachment trial, a chance to take the offensive as commander in
chief after having been on the defensive so long as an admitted
philanderer and accused of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, of course, is that his approval ratings went up while
he was on trial, and fell slightly, from about 61 percent to about
53 percent in some polls, during the war. A Washington Post/ABC
News poll taken last week, while peace talks were going on, found
the country roughly evenly divided on whether it had been wise for
the United States to get involved in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton himself never went all out to identify his
presidency with the Balkans, he came close, especially in a speech
in April to the American Society of Newspaper Editors. On that
occasion, he said NATO was engaged in ``a great battle between the
forces of integration and the forces of disintegration, the forces
of globalism versus tribalism, of oppression against empowerment.''
He warned that the road ahead could be long and hard.
</P>
<P>
   He did not hammer away at that theme, however, like his British
counterpart, Prime Minister Tony Blair, who talked constantly about
Kosovo and its importance, both on national television and in
Parliament. Blair also took a firm policy line from the beginning,
arguing publicly and privately that the alliance must at least
consider the use of ground troops to keep the pressure on President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany, a Social Democrat, and
his foreign minister, Joschka Fischer, a member of the Green Party,
also took strong public stands, despite opposition from some
elements within their parties.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was proven right, at least within the domestic political
context. His advisers told him that as long as he did not commit
ground troops and as long as there were no significant casualties
among air crews, he could do as he thought best without fearing a
backlash at home. As one aide put it, ``We thought we had enough
support in the country and on the Hill to keep at it for a long
time, as long as we didn't cross those lines.''
</P>
<P>
   What in fact happened, Hess argued, is that people lost
interest. Hess kept a tally of the number of minutes each week the
three main broadcast networks devoted to Kosovo. At the end of
April and beginning of May, the total was 215 minutes. Then it
fell, to 180, to 63, and finally, when he stopped keep track in
mid-May, it reached a low of 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few things that caused an uptick was the accidental
bombing of the Chinese embassy, which may have suggested to some
people that vital American interests were indeed becoming involved
in the Balkan fighting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
