<HEADER>
A9354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GUN-CONTROL-H     06-09 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BLASTS GOP LEADERSHIP FOR SUCCUMBING TO NRA PRESSURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton accused House Republican leaders
Wednesday of ignoring important child safety issues by allowing the
National Rifle Association to rewrite gun-control legislation
designed to help keep weapons out of the hands of criminals and
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic, horrible example of how Washington is out
of touch with the rest of America, and it is time that the rest of
America corrected it,'' Clinton declared at a gathering of law
enforcement officials at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to House Republicans who succumbed to NRA
pressure during the past two weeks to weaken key provisions of a
bill passed by the Senate last month. That bill would require
background checks for buyers at gun shows, force manufacturers to
sell safety locks along with handguns and ban the importation of
large-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his meeting with law enforcement and civil rights
officials to rally public support for passage in the House of the
same gun-control measures that were approved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the memory of the Littleton, Colo., school shooting and
bombing incident that killed 15 people and wounded 21, the
president called on Americans to ask their representatives to vote
against the Republican legislation he said was ``plainly
ghostwritten'' by the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can still remember Littleton _ it hasn't even been two
months _ then we ought to speak up and be heard,'' Clinton said,
adding that ``it is wrong to let the NRA call the shots on (gun
control).''
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leaders also joined in criticizing the
Republican rewrite of the Senate bill. They said the House bill
appears to be aimed at appeasing the NRA, which has spent more than
$1 million since the Senate bill passed May 20 trying to rally
support among House members to defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a time for partisanship. It is not the time to let
special interests write legislation. This is the time to do the
right thing,'' said House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said before Congress
adjourned for its Memorial Day recess two weeks ago that he would
support efforts to bring gun-control legislation to the floor, with
members being allowed to offer amendments to address their
concerns. Other Republican leaders also said at the time that
gun-control measures would be debated in the House Judiciary
Committee before being introduced on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee phase of consideration was abruptly eliminated
this week when Republican leaders announced that they would bring
their own bill directly to the floor for a vote next week. The
Democrats hope to offer the Senate-passed bill as their substitute
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to offer our substitute,'' said Julian
Epstein, chief Democratic counsel for the House Judiciary
Committee. ``But we don't know if we're going to get that chance
... The same (Republican) extremist group that led the Congress on
impeachment (of President Clinton) is running the gun-control issue
now. We don't know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The gun-control measure that Republican leaders plan to offer
contains significant changes in the definition of what constitutes
a gun show.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate bill, a gun show is defined as any gathering of
collectors, sellers or dealers where guns are being sold, including
flea markets. But in the language rewritten with the help of NRA
lobbyists and Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, who serves on the NRA
board, only events in which 10 or more gun sellers participate
would be regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charged that the language change would create a
loophole that would allow individuals, especially criminals and
even young people, to buy weapons without undergoing the mandatory
background checks
</P>
<P>
   The House bill also would replace language in the Senate bill
designed to preserve the Brady law by requiring that only 72 hours
at most be allowed for conducting so-called ``instant background
checks'' instead of a full three business days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no justification for shortening law enforcement's
time to do checks,'' said Gephardt, who also complained that the
Republican rewrite of the Senate bill would allow non-law
enforcement ``special registrants'' to run background checks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking differences in the two gun-control
measures is that the House bill would not require guns to be sold
with locks or other safety devices if they can be rendered unusable
by removing the firing pin, trigger or some other part.
</P>
<P>
   Another key provision included in a draft of the Republican bill
but not in the Senate version would limit the civil liability of
gun owners, distributors, manufacturers and sellers in cases
involving deaths or injuries caused by weapons. The liability
provision was pushed by House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas,
among other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., called
the Democratic criticism of the Republican bill ``their typical
knee-jerk reaction'' to efforts aimed at winning broad support from
both sides of the aisle for ``sensible'' gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   He called Democratic claims that the NRA wrote the GOP bill
``nonsense,'' although he acknowledged that both the NRA and Craig
did ``make known their views'' to House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that gun shows ought to be defined more precisely,''
Hyde said, summing up the main thrust of the GOP measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last analysis, the government cannot solve the problem.
But what we can do, we will do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said it's still unclear what the final bill will look like
when Republicans offer it on the floor next week and suggested that
there may be ``several versions'' that members end up voting on,
including one that raises the age limit for gun purchases from 18
to 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill does not contain an age limit provision.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are hopeful that raising the age limit for gun
purchases will help attract more support for their measure and help
ease public concerns about the GOP's position on gun-control
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Their own internal polls show that they have reason to be
concerned about a public backlash against them, especially in the
wake of the Littleton incident. A GOP survey conducted last month
found that 80 percent of those polled favored tougher gun-control
measures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
