<HEADER>
A9364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-DOBBS10-COX     06-09 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-DOBBS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Severance clause puts Dobbs out of business
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Inside CNN's Atlanta newsroom Wednesday, the troops
were calling events leading up to ``Moneyline'' anchor Lou Dobbs'
departure ``The Clash of the Titans,'' referring to Dobbs' in-house
battles with CNN President Richard Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs did not return phone calls Wednesday, and CNN executives
weren't adding to their official news release. In that release, Tom
Johnson, chairman of the CNN Newsgroup, said Dobbs' ``contribution
to CNN and the world of financial reporting have been
immeasurable.'' Dobbs said he leaves CNN ``with the utmost respect
for the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences between Dobbs and Kaplan went public last month
on ``Moneyline,'' when Kaplan told Dobbs to switch to President
Clinton's press conference in Littleton, Colo., and Dobbs informed
his viewers that he was being ordered to switch by Kaplan, a breach
of protocol that shocked many inside the network.
</P>
<P>
   In leaving, Dobbs has emphasized that becoming chairman of, as
well as an investor in, Space.com, which will provide news and
entertainment about outer space, is a new opportunity that excites
him.
</P>
<P>
   So don't look for Dobbs, who was also president of the financial
subsidiary CNNfn, to show up on CNN rivals CNBC or Fox News
Channel, despite some reports. Part of Dobbs' severance package
with CNN reportedly is a multiyear ``noncompete'' clause, meaning
he can't go to work for any competitor.
</P>
<P>
   That's a little consolation for CNN, but network executives also
know that his departure will not sit well with ``Moneyline's'' key
audience of business executives and Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing the franchise of Lou Dobbs is a tremendous blow to
CNN,'' said Don Fitzpatrick, a San Francisco-based TV news
consultant and headhunter. ``There is not a person on television
anywhere that has the reputation Lou Dobbs has as a business
journalist. He wrote the book.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no one at CNN waiting to step in who has Dobbs'
stature. Willow Bay, a ``CNN &AMP; Fortune'' and ``CNN &AMP; Entertainment
Weekly'' co-anchor, will be interim anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs went all the way back to the first day of CNN, on June 1,
1980, and his deep friendship with founder Ted Turner was legendary
within CNN. Dobbs has been a frequent guest of Turner at his
Montana home, fishing and horseback riding, and Turner reportedly
protected Dobbs in past disputes. The two were so close that back
in 1982, when Turner decided he liked the idea of doing personal
``editorials'' on CNN, it was Dobbs who sat down with his boss, one
to one, and explained why it was a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   But Dobbs also had a reputation for pushing his own agenda hard
and threatening to resign. He expected to be named president of CNN
in 1991 when there was a vacancy, and offered to resign to Turner
when Johnson was named instead. In 1997, Dobbs wanted CNNfn to
expand its hours of coverage, and was so close to resigning that
CNN had prepared his severance package. But Dobbs wound up getting
at least part of the expansion and staying.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
