<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV ARMY SIGNS WITHDRAWAL PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ In a long-awaited deal that prompted joyous
celebrations among Serbs here and among Kosovar Albanians in border
refugee camps, the Yugoslav Army signed an agreement Wednesday
night with NATO that calls for the withdrawal of 40,000 Serb forces
from Kosovo over the next 11 days and the effective end of the
11-week war.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb withdrawal, extended by four days as part of a NATO
compromise, was expected to begin at dawn Thursday. If NATO pilots
verify the pullout has begun, NATO later Thursday is expected to
suspend its air strikes after 78 days of bombing that has
devastated Yugoslavia's infrastructure. That, in turn, would lead
to passage of a United Nations Security Council resolution
outlining the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Once that resolution is passed, NATO troops will begin going
into Kosovo, hot on the heels of retreating Serb forces. Within a
month, the first of the more than 800,000 ethnic Albanian refugees
who were driven from Kosovo could begin returning home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war has ended,'' said Yugoslav General Svetozar
Marjanovic, who signed the agreement with Lieutenant General Mike
Jackson, the commander of NATO forces in Macedonia that are poised
to enter Kosovo. Serbian General Obrad Stevanovic, who commands the
Interior Ministry police units that have been blamed for expelling
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, also signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Celebratory gunfire erupted around Belgrade Tuesday night. In
the Yugoslav capital, spared by NATO bombs in the hours before the
pact, motorists honked horns, Serb security forces fired off
weapons, and police tried to prevent foreign camera crews from
capturing the celebrations on film.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports of widespread celebratory gunfire in
Pristina, the Kosovo capital, where some ethnic Albanians said they
were threatened with death by roving gangs of Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Macedonian capital, Skojpe, about 100 young ethnic
Albanians danced to Albanian pop music and waved flags from the
United States, Britain, and France, confident that the pact would
lead to a quick return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think that I could be going back soon, it's unbelievable. I
love America,'' shouted Petrit Bytyqi, 19, a refugee from Pristina,
Kosovo's capital. Grabbing the American flag out of his hand, his
friend Muharrem Berisha screamed above the music: ``We're going
home.''
</P>
<P>
   The US government, burned last week by a Yugoslav government
agreement that Belgrade backed out of Sunday, reacted cautiously,
and officials say large-scale resettlement will not begin for
several months, under best conditions.
</P>
<P>
   After five days of on-again, off-again discussions between
generals Jackson and Marjanovic, NATO compromised, giving the Serbs
11 days instead of an initially agreed seven days to get their
forces out. NATO also agreed to reduce a buffer zone by retreating
Serb forces from 15 to 3 miles.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, furious with what he saw as Serb footdragging,
warned Yugoslav officials, saying that if Serb forces break the
agreement, the bombing will resume.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said there will be discussions on how some
Serb forces will be allowed back to assist with the removal of
mines that Yugoslav forces put down in Kosovo. Serb security forces
will also be allowed back to guard religious and heritage sites in
Kosovo. But those forces will be in the hundreds, and Wednesday's
agreement effectively made Kosovo an international protectorate.
</P>
<P>
   Government-controlled television here announced that the
agreement was proof that the politics of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic had won. The official media did not tell the
public here that its military leaders were in discussions with
NATO. Instead, official media said the agreement was reached with
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was nowhere in sight, continuing his refusal to
address the nation. But the ability of him and his government to
convince the Serbian public that this was an agreement with the
United Nations, rather than a capitulation to NATO, is crucial to
retaining power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the moral victors of the war,'' said Nebojsa Vujovic,
the Yugoslav deputy foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the withdrawal and suspension of the air strikes
were meant to guarantee smooth sailing of the resolution through
the UN Security Council. Russia and China had said they would not
approve the resolution unless there was a stop in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about verifying the withdrawal as far as I'm
concerned; it's about ending the bombing,'' said Sergei Lavrov,
Russia's UN envoy.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said China would abstain on the resolution after NATO
nations and Russia earlier Wednesday rejected several amendments to
the resolution proposed by Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   One amendment would have removed a reference to cooperation with
the International Tribunal in The Hague, which two weeks ago
indicted Milosevic for alleged war crimes. A proposal to include a
reference to the principles of the UN Charter was accepted by the
West and Russia, though diplomats said this was a mere formality.
</P>
<P>
   A US diplomat said NATO air strikes could resume, even after the
resolution passed, if the Serbs reversed their withdrawal. With
international peacekeepers entering Kosovo as the Serbs pull out, a
possible scenario could see Western troops on the ground while
hostilities resumed.
</P>
<P>
   The sequencing of events was crucial to winning the agreement of
the Western allies, who hail from NATO members, and Russia, which
is an ally of Yugoslavia and has been trying to broker a
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army has said it would not attack
withdrawing Serb forces. Yugoslav generals had expressed concerns
about leaving their troops open to ambush by rebel forces as they
left Kosovo. US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright got the
Kosovo Liberation Army leader, Hashim Thaci, to publicly say his
troops would not attack retreating Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Yugoslav generals balked at signing the
agreement that stipulates the routes and timetables of their
pullout from Kosovo. Serb officials delayed the initiation of the
pullout so they could characterize it as the United Nations
assuming control rather than NATO.
</P>
<P>
   While the Western allies and Russia were able to bridge their
differences, mainly by moving any reference to NATO to the annex of
the draft UN resolution, there remains a dispute over who will
control the nearly 50,000 troops that will form the international
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   The six-page document signed by the NATO and Yugoslav military
leaders in Macedonia outlines procedures for withdrawal of Serb
soldiers and police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the NATO general, said the military-technical agreement
``details how the army, the interior police, and all other forces
should conduct a phased, verifiable, and orderly withdrawl from
Kosovo. It also provides a clear, legal basis for the deployment of
the international security force known as the Kosovo force.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson suggested that domestic Serbian politics had delayed the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tragic that intransigence has made it necessary for the
international community to resort to airstrikes to reach a
settlement,'' said Jackson. ``However, NATO's resolve in conducting
a sustained air campaign has finally achieved this agreement, and
now is the time to look ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Marjanovic, the deputy chief of staff of the Yugoslav Army,
spoke briefly to reporters, insisting the deal was reached not with
NATO but ``the international security forces . . . under the
auspices of the United Nations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
