<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO DEADLOCK BROKEN AFTER SHARP LONG-RANGE EXCHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KOSOVO-RDP) 
(jt) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ The deadlock between Yugoslav and NATO
military officials negotiating in a tent on the barren Macedonia
border was finally broken after some sharp exchanges nearly a
thousand miles away in an elaborate 15th-century meeting hall.
</P>
<P>
   An irritated Russian foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, broke into a
discussion among his foreign minister colleagues on another matter
here late Wednesday afternoon. He charged that the Americans and
NATO were responsible for the stalemate in the tent, according to
accounts given by Clinton administration officials and other
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans could not solve the situation, Ivanov said, the
Russians would help them, one diplomat recounted afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov then pledged that Moscow would vote for the United
Nations Security Council resolution authorizing the international
security force immediately after NATO suspended the bombing of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   With this move, Ivanov gave the go-ahead for a delicately
arranged set of events that diplomats had dubbed the
``synchronization'' of the end of the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   This ``synchronization'' entailed five steps: the signing of the
military withdrawal agreement in the tent, the withdrawal of Serb
troops from Kosovo, verification of a partial withdrawal, a bombing
suspension, the vote in the Security Council and finally, the
deployment of the international security force under the leadership
of the Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who is attending the
meeting here of the G-8 foreign ministers from the seven most
industrialized countries and Russia, had been talking on-and-off
since breakfast with Ivanov about unlocking the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   But until Ivanov's statement to his colleagues at about 5 p.m.
at the Guerzenich Hall, Clinton administration officials said they
had doubted whether Russia would vote quickly for the Security
Council resolution that authorizes the entry of the security force
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At U.N. headquarters in New York, the Russians had refused to
agree that the draft resolution _ approved by the eight foreign
ministers meeting here Tuesday _ be placed into final form ready
for voting within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Without approval of the resolution in New York, the
international security force would not have the authority to enter
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Any delay between the suspension of NATO's bombing pause and the
deployment of the peacekeepers, diplomats argued, would create a
vacuum inside Kosovo that would create two kinds of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the Kosovo Liberation Army would feel free to
take revenge on the departing Serbian forces. Under those
circumstances, with the guerrillas fighting back at them, the
Serbian forces would be reluctant to leave. This was just the
endgame _ civil war instead of an orderly departure of Serbian
forces _ that NATO wanted to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem, diplomats said, was that any break in the
sequence of events carefully laid out by the NATO allies could
easily play into the hands of the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians' reluctance to get the Security Council resolution
ready for a vote in New York raised what a senior administration
official termed ``suspicions'' about whether Moscow would vote
quickly enough for the international force to move into Kosovo
immediately after the bombing suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ivanov gave his word _ during what British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook called a ``tense'' G-8 session _ the Clinton
administration made a move that satisfied the Yugoslav negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   The administration sent word through NATO that a sentence which
had been included in the military document and which the Yugoslavs
objected to could be removed from the text.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials accompanying Albright refused to tell
reporters the exact wording of the sentence. One official, speaking
on condition of anonymity, said the disputed sentenced described
``the sequence between the withdrawals and the Security Council''
vote, but declined to give more detail.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ivanov gave his word and the offending sentence was removed
from the military agreement, the Yugoslav negotiators who had
broken off the talks for more consultations with Belgrade drove
back to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the wheels of the Security Council moved the
resolution ahead. At NATO headquarters, officials who had left for
the day were called back to work.
</P>
<P>
   And when Jackson emerged from the tent to announce the accord,
Albright, Ivanov and the other foreign ministers were dining over
an elaborate meal at a chocolate museum here, where the speciality
is the history of confectionery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
