<SLUG> BC-CONN.-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMO MAY HELP FUEL CONNECTICUT LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still smarting over the New England Patriots' decision not to
move to Hartford, Connecticut officials have pounced on a memo
written by a Massachusetts consultant as a way the Nutmeg State
might be able to mount a multimillion lawsuit against team owner
Robert Kraft and the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   The memo, written by the team's environmental and transportation
consultants, Rizzo Associates, detailed the infrastructure
improvements that would be necessary if the Patriots went ahead
with plans to build a new stadium on land the team owns adjacent to
the current stadium. The memo was dated April 28, two days before
the Patriots terminated their agreement with Connecticut to build a
$374 million publicly financed football stadium and convention
center in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' deal with Connecticut prohibited the team from
entering into talks with other cities or states while it was
evaluating Connecticut's offer.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Rizzo officials, the memo was written at the
request of Massachusetts lawmakers and business leaders seeking to
keep the team in the Bay State _ and not New England Patriots owner
Robert Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots had nothing to do with that memo,'' said Sam
Park, a Rizzo principal. ``It was produced because Massachusetts
lawmakers wanted an update on information we had given them over a
year before _ certainly long before the team began negotiating with
Connecticut. The Patriots didn't even know we wrote it.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said that since his firm does a lot of business with
Massachusetts, Rizzo provided lawmakers and local business leaders
with the report ``as a matter of courtesy and respect.'' The Rizzo
memo was referred to in the legislation passed last month that
provides $70 million in state funds for infrastructure improvements
required for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed earlier this week, Connecticut Attorney General
Richard Blumenthal pointed to the memo as potent ammunition in a
potential lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memo raises a number of significant questions whether the
Patriots were dealing with Massachusetts officials at a time when
their contract barred them from doing so, and we are exploring that
in the course of our ongoing investigation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When told that Park said his firm had authored the memo without
the Patriots' participation, Blumenthal said he would have no
further comment on the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't ruled anyone out or in as a potential defendant,''
Blumenthal said Wednesday. ``Nor have we ruled out any potential
(grounds for the suit).''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said he expects to consult with Connecticut Governor
John G. Rowland and legislative leaders before he reaches a
decision about whether to file suit within the next two or three
months.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft terminated his agreement with Connecticut on April 30,
noting the difficulties the state had encountered in preparing the
polluted Hartford site and his doubts about whether the state could
meet the 2002 stadium opening date specifed in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contract, Kraft was allowed to pull out of the deal at
his ``sole discretion'' before May 2 without any penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The team unveiled its plans for a new $285 million stadium to be
built alongside the old one in Foxborough at a breakfast with
business leaders and NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
