</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MP3.com, Cox enter music Web site deal
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MP3.com, one of the major purveyors of downloadable
music files on the Internet, Wednesday announced that Cox
Interactive Media will invest $45 million in MP3.com in connection
with a joint venture the two companies will form to create music
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, both companies said they will make approximately
equal financial contributions to the new venture, which will also
include advertising and e-commerce revenue sharing between the new
venture and MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   In connection with CIM's investment in MP3.com, David Easterly,
president and chief operating officer of Cox Enterprises Inc., will
join MP3.com's board of directors. Cox Enterprises Inc., based in
Atlanta, is the parent company of Cox Interactive Media and The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative plans call for the two companies to work together to
create and operate music-related Web sites. Downloading music clips
from the Internet is rapidly becoming one of the most popular
pastimes for Internet users and music lovers. Amazon.com and a
variety of other major Web sites are forging alliances to bring
music downloads to customers. Even though the recording industry
maintains that MP3 technology encourages music piracy, many
recording artists are beginning to embrace the idea of making their
music available on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com is one of the most popular Web destinations for music
lovers. The company uses the Internet and data compression
technologies to enable a growing number of musicians to distribute
their music over the Web to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego-based MP3.com offers a catalog with more than
56,000 songs by 11,000 artists that can be downloaded for free. The
music is stored in a file format called MP3, which offers
near-CD-quality sound.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com sells albums and compilation CDs, which it mails to
customers, but most of its revenue comes from advertisers. The
company filed for an initial public offering in May.
</P>
<P>
   CIM, which operates AccessAtlanta and 30 local Web sites across
the country, has incorporated Cox TV, radio and newspaper content,
while providing other products and services including search, chat
and shopping services that complement local content.
</P>
<P>
   What is MP3?
</P>
<P>
   MP3 is shorthand for Motion Picture Coding Experts Group-1,
audio layer-3. An MP3 is a computer file format for audio. It can
be downloaded from the Internet, posted on a Web site, sent via
e-mail or stored on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   How to download songs
</P>
<P>
   1. Select MP3 player from a Web site, such as www.mp3.com. Click
and download the player you've selected.
</P>
<P>
   2. Go to the MP3.com home page to find music. Click on song and
download. The downloaded song will now appear on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   3. Double-click the file to begin playing the song.
</P>
<P>
   Storing the songs
</P>
<P>
   Music can be stored on your hard drive or on portable MP3
players, which can store up to 60 minutes of music transferred from
your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
