<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-CANADA10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot targeting Canada
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot plans a major expansion into eastern Canada
that will add more than 20 stores and create 4,000 jobs over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based retailer, which now has 43 Canadian stores,
primarily in British Columbia and Ontario, will open three stores
next year in Quebec, two in Nova Scotia and one in New Brunswick at
a cost of at least $8 million per store, said Annette Verschuren,
president of Home Depot Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, which currently has 10 percent of the $12.5 billion
Canadian home improvement market, will operate in eight of the
country's 10 provinces. Most of the expansion plans involve Quebec,
where Verschuren said there's a potential for 15 to 20 new stores
over the next three to four years.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Quebec, which is home to a quarter of the
Canadian population, was off limits to Home Depot because of a
noncompete agreement. Home Depot entered Canada in 1994 when it
bought a 75 percent stake in the Aikenhead's Home Improvement
Warehouse chain. Home Depot purchased operations in English Canada
and agreed not to compete with the French operations in Quebec.
Since then, the Quebec arm has gone through several acquisitions,
which nullified the noncompete agreement, according to Home Depot's
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to become a national retailer in Canada, and not being
able to get into one of its strongest provinces really held us
back,'' Verschuren said. ``This is going to give us a big base to
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot will open 11 stores this year in central and western
Canada. The company plans to grow 20 percent to 25 percent annually
in all of its operations.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is good for growth in Canada, said analyst Wayne Hood
of Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, Home Depot went into Canada at a time when the
economy was peaking and struggling, which led to slower growth for
them,'' Hood said. ``But those issues are resolved, so this is a
natural extension.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada's housing market is rebounding from a recession. Sales of
home improvement products increased 8 percent in 1998, according to
National Home Center News. Home Depot Canada increased sales 27
percent to about $1 billion in 1998, according to the trade
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
