<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abortion foe sues, claims MindSpring erased e-mail
 &HT;    By Frances Katz and Diane Lore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The owner of an anti-abortion Web site is suing
MindSpring Enterprises for $251 million, claiming the Atlanta-based
Internet provider destroyed hundreds of e-mail messages when it
closed down the site.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed Tuesday in the Superior Court of Gwinnett
County, asks for $1 million for breach of contract and $250 million
in punitive damages. It was filed by Neil Horsely, 55, a Carrollton
resident who operates the Christian Gallery Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Horsely says when MindSpring closed the account it destroyed his
e-mail, which he estimates averaged between 700 and 800 messages a
day. A key issue in the suit is MindSpring's alleged destruction of
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``MindSpring has no knowledge of the suit, and even if we did we
would be unlikely to comment on an active litigation,'' said
MindSpring spokesman Ed Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As MindSpring has publicly stated before, Mr. Horsely's
service with MindSpring was terminated for a violation of our
appropriate use policy with which Mr. Horsely is well versed
with,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Horsley's attorney, John Matteson, said: ``The punitive damages
are high to get (MindSpring's) attention. It's actually pretty
simple. It's a breach of contract suit for shutting down his site
and destroying his e-mail without justification.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost the minute I heard what they had done (by destroying
the e-mail and shutting down the site), I knew they had made a
fundamental legal error,'' Horsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Feb. 4, Horsely was a MindSpring subscriber and maintained
the site on MindSpring's server. Horsley said he believes he has
the money and the time to go forward with the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Horsely now runs the Christian Gallery site from his own server.
He's also started a new Web site called Restore the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Mark Clothier contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
