<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOMM-SHOW10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Telecom highway bumpy in spots
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even as they are building more and more network
capacity to keep up with rolling demand by business and consumers,
telecommunications companies say there is an even bigger struggle
to get dependable high-speed access to the networks for paying
users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have a communications superhighway, with dirt
road access,'' said Jesse Russell, vice president for advanced
communications at AT&AMP;T Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, with a showman's timing, Lance Wetherby of
Atlanta-based MindSpring Enterprises leaped on the opportunity:
</P>
<P>
   ``We work the dirt roads, and we're having a lot of fun,'' said
Wetherby, executive vice president of the Internet service
provider.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange took place Wednesday morning at Supercomm99 during
a panel discussion titled ``Network Convergence: Where Are We
Headed?''
</P>
<P>
   It was chaired by Russell, with participants from phone
companies like BellSouth, network builders like Qwest, and even
Microsoft, looking for ways the software giant can edge into
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Some 47,000 participants were expected at Supercomm99, up from
40,000 last year, coming from more than 100 countries, to learn the
latest in the changing phone business.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications officials say that Internet and similar
communications are burgeoning, driven by e-mail, electronic
commerce and other hot areas of activity.
</P>
<P>
   Growth is so great that this year the previously unthinkable
will occur _ the traffic in data will edge past the traffic in
voice communication by phone. With the pressure on, MCI said it
hopes to double its telecommunications capacity from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the demand, communications engineers are
hard-pressed to put up enough wires to carry all the bits of
information, forcing them to push harder into new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   These include creating fibers that carry more information
faster, as well as better switches for managing the flow of
information.
</P>
<P>
   Also, to help carry the growing information load with more
flexibility, growing numbers of wireless networks are being created
and deployed for data, not just voice messages.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-held pads already are being used to send and receive
written messages, retrieve stock quotations and other reports, and
send commands, including sales orders.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Charters, vice president of Qwest Communications, said,
``The new developments mean we must get bigger, with greater access
to all the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Qwest, now said to be the subject of merger interest at
BellSouth, is building a nationwide broadband network that will
carry voice, data and video traffic and may be looking for
acquisitions of its own.
</P>
<P>
   William Smith, vice president for network planning at BellSouth,
said his company is working on one of the imperatives in the
fast-growing, ever-more-complex communications business _ how to
make the huge apparatus more user-friendly, how to make useful
devices for customers who neither understand nor care about the
riddle of building global networks.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, BellSouth is working on a single receptacle for
voice mail, e-mail and other messages so the consumer can have a
handy way to stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   While some experts predicted that ultimately there will be one
great global network of networks, Thomas Koll, vice president for
Internet customers at Microsoft, differed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be at least two,'' he said, ``possibly including
DSL and a wireless network connection.'' Digital subscriber line is
a form of technology now being exploited by BellSouth, MindSpring
and others for bringing high-speed Internet connection through the
phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, most of the experts agreed that the competitive
battle will continue, including a struggle among the phone
companies, long-distance providers and the cable industry,
buttressed by AT&AMP;T's new cable strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is in for the fight of its life if it wants to pursue
that cable strategy,'' said Charters of Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also included Jack Waters, engineering vice president
at Level 3 Communications and vice president for network technology
and planning at MCI WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
