<SLUG> BC-WOLFCAMERA10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wolf Camera adds 12 stores in Baltimore
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wolf Camera's den keeps getting bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said Wednesday it will acquire the Dark Room, a 12-store
film developer in Baltimore. Wolf Camera already had five stores in
Baltimore from last summer's acquisition of the Fox Photo chain
from Eastman Kodak Co. Those stores, together with the Dark Room
photo labs, are a springboard for more expansion in the Baltimore
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll add two to three full-size stores like our store on 14th
Street,'' said Wayne Freedman, senior vice president of marketing.
``We typically like to have a combination of smaller stores and
large, very high-profile locations.'' The Dark Room stores will be
revamped to carry equipment and services similar to Wolf Camera's
concept, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion in Baltimore takes Wolf Camera founder Chuck Wolf
back to his roots. He got his start in the camera business in the
late 1960s by working for his uncle, Edward Ritz, at a family chain
in nearby Beltsville, Md. In 1974, Wolf traded his stock in Ritz
Camera Centers to start Wolf Camera with seven stores in Atlanta
and two in Charlotte, N.C. With about 900 stores, Ritz Camera runs
the nation's largest photo retail chain. But fast-growing Wolf
Camera now has 725 stores and is closing the gap with a string of
acquisitions and new stores.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf Camera's stores in Baltimore mark the first time Chuck Wolf
has taken the competition back to his roots. Atlanta will get a
taste of the family rivalry as well. Ritz Camera President David
Ritz, a cousin of Chuck Wolf, said recently he plans to open stores
in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman downplayed the competition, noting that the two chains
already go head-to-head in numerous markets around the country.
``As both of us grow, it's inevitable that we're going to compete
with each other,'' he said. ``Our main competition is
overwhelmingly the mass merchandisers.''
</P>
<P>
   Freedman added that Wolf Camera plans to add several locations
this year in metro Atlanta, where it already has more than 70
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
