<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ETHNICGROUPS-     06-09 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ETHNICGROUPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA'S NEW LEADERS FACE ETHNIC CLASHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAFANCHAN, Nigeria _ The trouble began when the 95-year-old emir
died in November after ruling this town in northern Nigeria for 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   The indigenous people, who had long resented being subjects of a
Muslim leader, demanded the abolition of the emirate and the
creation of their own chiefdom. The moment seemed right: Nigeria
was on its way toward the end of military rule and a civilian
government might listen to their aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Tense negotiations ensued between the Muslim supporters of the
emirate and the indigenous people, who belong to several ethnic
groups and are mostly Christian or animist.
</P>
<P>
   Then an unexpected announcement in May that the emir's
28-year-old son would be installed in a succession ceremony
shattered the fragile peace in Kafanchan. Just days before Olusegun
Obasanjo became Nigeria's first civilian president in a generation,
scores of people on both sides were killed and corpses were left
smoldering in the town center. During a weekend of fury, tree
leaves that are traditional signs of protest gave way quickly to
bows and arrows and machetes and semiautomatic rifles.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes here, like the ethnic violence that has erupted
elsewhere across Nigeria in recent months, were rooted in a
struggle over political dominance. As the imminent installation of
a civilian government raised Nigerians' expectations, ethnic
clashes multiplied, and they risk increasing now that power has
been handed over from the military.
</P>
<P>
   In a country with as many as 400 ethnic groups, where decades of
colonial and military rule reinforced the belief that each group is
being oppressed by another, it was perhaps inevitable that
fashioning some sort of social unity in Nigeria would be one of the
biggest challenges facing Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emirate system was used to suppress us,'' said Abednego
Majidadi, 52, a farmer here. ``That is why we resisted. We hope
that the present regime can do something better because we are now
in a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore that hope and the social instability it
entails, a new wave of violence swept the Niger Delta region a day
after Obasanjo's inauguration on May 29. In the oil city of Warri,
scores are believed to have died since then in fighting among three
ethnic groups. The groups, especially the Ijaw and Itsekiri, have
been fighting intensely since fall over land claims and the
location of a local government.
</P>
<P>
   From the southwest to the southeast, from the central area known
as the middlebelt to the north, people of different ethnic
backgrounds have confronted one another. Sometimes the fighting has
even pitted different subsets of a large ethnic group, like the
Ibo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unity does not exist in Nigeria,'' said Ado Mohammed Gawuna,
35, a Hausa politician. ``We just mouth it. Any Yoruba man I will
not agree with. In no matter will I call a Yoruba man a brother. I
will call him a Nigerian only in geographic terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Two men belonging to Nigeria's two other big ethnic groups _
Francis Ike, 27, an Ibo, and Olutayo Aro, 32, a Yoruba _ stood next
to Gawuna as he spoke to a reporter and they said they were
unwilling to abandon the idea of a united Nigeria. ``If this
government is good, Nigeria can exist,'' Ike said, throwing in
effect a challenge to the country's new civilian politicians.
</P>
<P>
   During the riots here in Kafanchan, neighborhoods were
ransacked, Muslim houses set aflame, non-Muslim ones left
untouched. Protesters stormed the emir's palace and burned down
parts of it, forcing the son, Muhammadu Isa Muhammadu, to flee on
his coronation day.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers now stand in front of the emir's palace and throughout
the town, preserving stability at gunpoint. The Muslims, who are
Hausa, and the indigenous people blame each other for igniting the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I begin to wonder if they are any different from the pigs they
rear,'' Magaji Mande, 45, deputy secretary to the emir's son, said
of the natives, who are mostly farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the indigenous people regard the Hausa as an
occupying force. The Hausa came here two centuries ago and
established the emirate. The emir's reach has extended over a
region called Jema'a, whose center is Kafanchan and where the Hausa
make up only about 10 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Its territorial lines drawn by British colonialists in 1914,
Nigeria stands now as Africa's most populous nation, bringing
together more than 110 million people with many more divisions than
commonalities. Over the decades, British colonialists and Nigerian
military rulers retained control over such a large, diverse and
unruly land by pitting ethnic groups against one another.
</P>
<P>
   They also succeeded in keeping their grip by leaving local
control in the hands of traditional rulers, like the obas, or
kings, in the south, and the emirs in the north. The traditional
rulers, who have no official powers, still hold tremendous
influence over their subjects, a point underlined during February's
presidential elections, when campaigning amounted to visiting local
rulers instead of individual voters.
</P>
<P>
   But as this town makes clear, the role of traditional rulers
will come under increasing scrutiny and challenge in the new
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hausa settled on our land when they conquered us and
imposed the emirate on us,'' said Nathaniel Biya, 56, a lawyer and
village elder. His village lies a few miles from the town center
and is home to the Kaninkon people. It is known in the region as
Ungwar-Bako, a name given to the villagers by the Hausa; it means
village of the black people, a reminder that Islam was spread in
sub-Saharan Africa by northerners of lighter complexion. Among the
Kaninkon, though, the village is called Gakyop, or village of rich
grass.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the village seemed to know when it was founded, though
the Kaninkon say they have been in the area for centuries, well
before the arrival of the Hausa in the early 1800s. Over the years,
Biya said, the emirate's control had eroded; a quiet resistance
took shape, as the villagers, for instance, began refusing to
donate grain to the emir.
</P>
<P>
   After two centuries, the Hausa are thus still considered
foreigners by the locals. Almost nine decades after the creation of
Nigeria and three decades after independence, there is no sense
here yet, or in other areas where there have been ethnic clashes,
that as citizens of Nigeria, people can resettle anywhere in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Nigerian,'' Biya said. ``They are Nigerians, but they
have their own land somewhere. They don't belong in this place.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
