<HEADER>
A9388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGERIA-ETHNICGROUPS-     06-09 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-ETHNICGROUPS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
KAFANCHAN, Nigeria: this place.' ' 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So after the emir's death in November, the Kaninkon and other
indigenous groups here began pressing the state government to
create a chiefdom for them.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, talks between the Hausa and the indigenous
people had gone well enough that they had agreed to permit the
emirate to remain here, though its reach would be curtailed to the
Muslim areas. In return, the indigenous people would be represented
by a recognized chief. But the negotiations stalled over the rank
that the chief would enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spirit of self-determination let them have their own
chiefdom,'' said Mande, the emir's deputy secretary. ``But these
tribes were making impossible demands to be on the same level as
the emir.''
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that are unclear, the state's military administrator
at the time, a Hausa, pre-empted the conclusion of talks by
announcing that the coronation of the emir's son would occur on May
22, a week before Nigeria's military government was scheduled to
yield power.
</P>
<P>
   On that morning, the indigenous people carried leaves as a
traditional sign of protest and set up roadblocks on the three
roads leading to Kafanchan, forcing the military administrator's
motorcade to turn around.
</P>
<P>
   The Hausa fear they would be unprotected without the emirate.
``If the emirate is abolished,'' said Suleiman Musa, 27, whose
father died after being set on fire, ``what will we, the Hausa, do?
Where will we be?''
</P>
<P>
   In the rioting that ensued, several mosques were set alight. In
this country with so many fissures, ethnicity and regionalism
represent the main ones, although religion is often used to widen
the divisions for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it started as a problem over the emirate,'' said
Mohammed Ndleman, 55, a Hausa and civil servant, standing before
the ruins of his house. ``But now I think it is a religious
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Bashir Idris, 31, shook his head as he showed off the remains of
his house and his children played amid the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government must consider the requests of every community
in Nigeria and treat them accordingly,'' Idris said. ``It is the
only way that everyone will feel part of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   It will not be easy, given the sometimes bewilderingly complex
nature of Nigerian society.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the riots, some Kaninkon invaded a block where
Muslims live next to Christians, stopping in front of a pink house.
The house belonged to Abdul Karim Yahaya, 45, a member of the
Kaninkon group, but a Muslim convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people said, `Don't burn it. He's our son,' '' Yahaya
recalled the rioters debating. ``Other people said, `He's Muslim.
Burn down the house!'''
</P>
<P>
   In this particular case, on this particular morning, for this
particular man, blood proved stronger than religion. Save a porch
light blown out by a bullet, the house still stood.
</P>
</TEXT>
