<SLUG> BC-YUGO-FUTURE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT CHALLENGE: RECLAIMING KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Historians won't remember June 9, 1999, as another VE Day _ a
time of global rejoicing after a long, bloody war. Nor will it even
have the same feel-good quality as Feb. 28, 1991, when the lopsided
Gulf War ended and President Bush exulted that America had ``kicked
the Vietnam syndrome once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   But the signing of the troop withdrawal agreement in Kumanovo,
Macedonia, on Wednesday at least is expected to bring an end to 2
1/2 months of unrelenting NATO bombing and the untold terrorization
of thousands of ethnic Albanians by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Chapter 2: reclaiming Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Thursday, NATO will begin moving into the province to
try to prevent a power vacuum as Serb forces withdraw. US and other
allied soldiers will have to disarm thousands of mines and booby
traps and neutralize unexploded NATO bombs that litter the
countryside. Up to 600,000 frightened, wounded, and hungry
civilians will be coming out of the woods and in need of critical
care.
</P>
<P>
   What's ahead in Kosovo will be a complex process of rescue and
rebuilding that doubtless will be complicated by the continued
machinations of President Slobodan Milosevic and his
ultra-nationalist backers in Serbia proper as they seek some way of
demonstrating that they did not lose. How peaceful the NATO
occupation will be is one of many questions that will be raised in
this new chapter in the centuries-old struggle over Kosovo. Among
others:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; When will the refugees return?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Pessimistic that 783,000 Kosovars who have fled to Albania,
Macedonia, Montenegro, and Bosnia will have homes to return to, the
UN High Commissioner for Refugees is preparing to winterize refugee
camps in those countries. In addition, relief workers will have to
set up new camps inside Kosovo to house the internally displaced.
Because homes have been destroyed and crops ruined, most Kosovars _
whether Albanian or Serb _ will be unable to survive without
massive aid. The first large organized return of refugees will not
occur until next spring, although refugee specialists say that some
Kosovar Albanians will trickle back on their own before then.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Will the people of Yugoslavia be punished economically while
Milosevic stays in power?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  They probably will not be denied humanitarian assistance,
which means that food and medicine could soon be arriving in
Yugoslavia via the Red Cross and sympathetic people in Russia,
Greece, and other parts of Europe. But American and European
leaders have vowed that official western aid to rebuild the
bomb-damaged bridges, highways, factories, offices, and homes will
not flow into Yugoslavia if Milosevic remains in power. This might
be an incentive for Yugoslavs to try to oust Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Will Milosevic and his lieutenants be tried for war crimes?
</P>
<P>
   Only if he can be captured, and that depends on whether he
remains in power. While there is much talk about opposition
politicians trying to bring him down, Milosevic has survived
numerous threats in the past, including mass demonstrations in
1996. In fact, his ethnic pot-stirring which led to wars in
Croatia, Bosnia, and Kosovo was largely about kindling a cause _
Serb nationalism _ that would help the onetime communist leader
survive in a post-communist era. Despite his losses in those
campaigns, he may still prove difficult to dislodge. Though there
are arrest warrants out for him in almost every country, as long as
he stays in office, he has the army of Yugoslavia to insulate him
from apprehension for trial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; How long will American and European troops need to remain in
Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The 48,000-strong Kosovo Force, or KFOR, under NATO command
will have a 7,000-member US component. A force of a similar size
was deployed in Bosnia in 1995 on what was originally billed as a
one-year peacekeeping mission. Without such a force in place,
Serb-Albanian conflict almost certainly will resume, especially if
Albanian nationalists continue to agitate for independence from
Yugoslavia. Expect a stay well into the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Will the ethnic Serbs in Kosovo be safe from retaliation? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, the Balkans have been known for vengeance
killings. Many of the murders that occurred during the conflicts of
the 1990s involved settling scores from the fractious era of Nazi
occupation in World War II. Knowing that they are imperiled, ethnic
Serbs have been leaving Kosovo since the first days of conflict.
Belgrade claims 60,000 have fled since March 24, when the air war
began. More will depart along with Serb forces. Many are twice
displaced: Driven out of Croatia in 1995, they were resettled in
Kosovo in an attempt to change the ethnic balance of the province.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Will the Kosovo Liberation Army be a benign police force for
Kosovoor carry on a guerrilla war that vexes NATO?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  If the KLA can transform itself from a guerrilla army into a
peacetime security force much as the Palestine Liberation
Organization has done in the Middle East, it will go a long way
toward creating the kind of civil structures that an independent _
or at least an autonomous _ Kosovo would need.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
