<SLUG> BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE ABOUT STEALING FROM MOM, NIGHT TRIPS 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: Last month when my mother wasn't looking, I took
her credit card from her purse to buy some clothes at the mall. I
went shopping and bought some clothes. She got the statement and
realized I took the card.
</P>
<P>
   My parents have grounded me and accused me of stealing the card
and money. Occasionally, I have taken a few dollars out of my mom's
purse, but never any large bills. I don't understand the big deal.
They're making me out to be some kind of criminal. Criminal.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Criminal: You had better learn from this or you will be a
criminal. You are lucky your parents care enough to discipline you
and teach you right from wrong. If you had done this to someone
else, they could have pressed charges.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ever take things that don't belong to you, including stuff
from your parents. They have provided you with a home, food and
clothing. You need to respect their belongings and ask for money if
you need it. Don't just assume it's yours or that it's OK to take
it.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I snuck out of the house recently and got
grounded. My best friend talked me into sneaking out with him and a
bunch of other kids. It was fun until I got busted!
</P>
<P>
   When I got back home my parents were waiting up. I got grounded
for two months. What can I do to get my life back? Grounded.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Grounded: The punishment apparently fits this crime. When
you snuck out of the house you lost the confidence of your parents.
Now you must work hard to gain that trust back again.
</P>
<P>
   Start by utilizing these two months as a communication bridge
between you and your parents. Offer to do special chores around the
house, from cleaning out the garage to watching your siblings if
you have any.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe these good behavior acts will get your parents to reduce
the two months of ground time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a problem or concern that needs an answer? The Class
Acts TeensTalk panel _ headed by Kathy Pope, a counselor at a Texas
junior college _ is comprised of teenage students who care about
other students. Write to: TeensTalk, c/o Class Acts, The New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
