A9421 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-DRASKOVIC-BOS &LR;      06-09 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-DRASKOVIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION LEADER FULL OF PROMISE, CONTRADICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ The day before Yugoslavia effectively surrendered to
NATO, Vuk Draskovic sat in his office, stroking his beard, already
plotting the future.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, in the hallway of the spacious headquarters of his
Serbian Renewal Movement, boxes of campaign literature were stacked
up, ready to go, even though there is no campaign yet.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, however, is ready. And he says Serbia and the rest of
Yugoslavia is ready once and for all to end its string of futile
wars, to return to the fold of the international community that has
burdened it with economic sanctions and, for more than two months,
blasted it with bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's grip on power has been
weakened by his capitulation to NATO. But whether Milosevic
resigns, which is unlikely, or is pushed aside depends on the
ability of this country's notoriously divided opposition to put
forward a candidate who can beat him.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the biggest opposition party in Serbia, Draskovic is
frequently mentioned as one politician who could replace Milosevic.
While many praise Draskovic's blunt and often courageous honesty,
they just as often bemoan his unpredictability and volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, a 52-year-old writer-turned-politician, embodies all
of Serbia's promise and contradictions. At one moment he is
preaching the virtues of democracy with the passion of a true
believer. Then he digresses into nationalist rhetoric and
reinforces the paralyzing perception of victimhood here, calling
Serbs ``the new Jews of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   A fervent anticommunist, he advocates the establishment of a
constitutional monarchy and return of the Yugoslav royal family
from exile.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has publicly called for Milosevic's ouster on many
occasions and led street protests demanding his resignation. Yet
last January, Draskovic joined Milosevic's cabinet as a deputy
prime minister. He said he wanted to change the government from
within. His critics say he sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no denying Draskovic's charisma, his ability to
attract and inspire an audience, or his bravery in a political
culture where there are few examples of people willing to incur the
wrath of Milosevic's shadowy, heavy-handed police.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, he was jailed for four days for leading protests
demanding a free press. In 1993, he spent 46 days in prison after
he organized demonstrations against the forced expulsions by Serb
forces in Bosnia. He was beaten regularly and went on a hunger
strike.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Draskovic was the first member of Milosevic's
government to publicly suggest that the country should cut its
losses by allowing an armed international peacekeeping force into
Kosovo under the auspices of the United Nations. Milosevic fired
him for such temerity.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Milosevic has accepted what Draskovic was urging more
than a month ago, Draskovic's stock with ordinary people has risen,
even as many remain skeptical that he could or should replace
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   People here still speak with admiration for how Draskovic stood
before tens of thousands of people and dared to say that Bosnian
Serb forces, backed by the Belgrade government, were killing and
expelling Muslims and Croatians. His wife, Danica, also spoke out,
dramatically challenging the government's denials by noting that
her Muslim friend, and maid of honor at her wedding, had been one
of those expelled.
</P>
<P>
   But many here who want a more open society can't quite bring
themselves to say that Draskovic is the best candidate to replace
Milosevic and bring Yugoslavia back into the embrace of the
international community, even if they can't think of one better
positioned to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Zarko Korac, who leads a small opposition party and is also a
psychologist, said Draskovic is a tough read, both politically and
psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a genuine pro-western nationalist. I think he genuinely
believes that he is the bridge to the west,'' says Korac. ``The
trouble with him is his ups and downs, his inconsistency. It
borders on being emotionally unstable, which is not good for a
politician.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultranationalist Serbian Radical Party, whose leader,
Vojislav Seslj, is positioning himself to challenge Milosevic,
claiming that Milosevic sold out the Serb people by giving in to
NATO, clearly fears Draskovic. The party's magazine routinely
depicts Draskovic as a drug addict, with cartoon caricatures of
Draskovic with needles sticking in his arms in every issue.
</P>
<P>
   Many democracy activists here, meanwhile, privately express
concerns about Draskovic's former close friendship with Seslj.
Draskovic and Seslj were best men at each other's weddings, but
have since had a falling out. But some see them as being cut from
the same demagogue cloth.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Draskovic insisted that his brand of
``democratic nationalism'' is far more constructive than the
``negative nationalism'' of Milosevic and Seslj, which is
authoritarian and antiwestern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democratic Serbian nationalism is healthy nationalism,
fighting for the interest of the nation but not against other
states,'' he said. ``Democratic Serbian nationalism means the
project for establishing democratic institutions, a non-ideological
army and police, private property as a basis of the economy, a free
media, a non-ideological justice system. It can transform Serbia
into a European state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Destructive Serbian nationalism is fighting for isolation, to
keep Serbia separated from Europe and the USA. It means the
promotion of the US and Europe as traditional enemies. It's a
program based on the sovereignty of the last century.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a democratic Serbia must respect and accommodate the 26
ethnic groups living in the country. He calls ``ethnic cleansing''
_ a term coined by Serbs to refer to the forced removal of a
different ethnic group _ ``a crime against humanity.'' But he says
it must be looked at in a historical context, and that Serbs have
been victimized just as ethnic Albanians were in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Draskovic advocated that those who refused to formally
declare allegiance to the Serbian government be expelled from
Kosovo. ``The war between Serbs and Albanians will be very short,''
he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Draskovic is more conciliatory. He admits that
some Serb forces ``committed crimes while expelling Albanians,''
but insists that most refugees fled on their own or on the
instructions of the Kosovo Liberation Army, which wanted to create
a humanitarian disaster to galvanize international support for
their cause.
</P>
<P>
   He says that, on his recommendation, Milosevic authorized the
arrest of any Serb forces who overstepped their authority in
Kosovo, and claims that more than 400 were arrested before he was
thrown out of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``My duty is to demand that any Serb who committed atrocities,
crimes against civilians, must be prosecuted. It is the only way to
protect our national face and tradition,'' he said. ``I would hope
terrorists and killers on all sides would be prosecuted.''
</P>
<P>
   In that list, he includes the NATO generals who killed hundreds
of innocent Serb civilians in more than two months of airstrikes.
He said at least 140 members of his party have been among the
victims. A family friend, 16-year-old Sanja Milenkovic, was killed
when NATO bombed a bridge just days after Draskovic gave her one of
his novels to read as she prepared for a mathematics competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I learned Sanja was killed, I almost cried,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the hostilities winding down, Draskovic is the only
politician here openly calling for reconciliation with the west.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic said his grandfather, Peter Draskovic, was a gold
miner in California who left the promise of America to return home
to fight during World War I. His father was a partisan who fought
the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather's last words to me were `Always love America.'
I'm not so brave that I could go to his grave and tell him, `Look
what America has done to us,' '''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he believes the development of democracy in Serbia, and a
willingness by the West to embrace the longtime pariah of the
international community, is the only hope for his country. He also
hints at more street protests and mounting a challenge to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that when the war stops, we have a big political
fight,'' he says. ``I will be out there the first day the bombing
stops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
