<SLUG> BC-OUT-KAYAK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING TO KAYAK IS NEW EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEREMY   BAGOTT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ There is no dignified way to lower yourself
into the cockpit of a kayak that is four inches above the water.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner this is understood and accepted, the sooner the other
great question of dock-rental kayaking can be addressed: how to
crawl back onto the landing when you're done.
</P>
<P>
   When I got to the Lake Casitas marina to claim a rental
sit-on-top craft, I watched the guy before me scoot down from the
dock, backside first, into a kayak. This sent me back to the car to
deposit my fishing gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're gonna get the seat of your pants wet,'' Chuck
Goodenough had warned me at the docks. The Los Angeles commercial
photographer has seen his share of these sit-on-top contraptions.
He was at the lake with his stepdaughter, Nadia Ghani, 13, and
family friend and kayaker Marcia Lindahl.
</P>
<P>
   Goodenough was right. Within seconds of lowering myself into one
of the marina's vessels, I was squirming to remove my wallet from a
quickly waterlogged back pocket, all the while keeping the paddle
balanced on my legs. Dropping either one would definitely have put
me up the creek without a ... oh, never mind. At that moment, I was
glad the fishing rod and tackle weren't part of the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Scuppers _ four holes about the size of silver dollars that keep
the kayak self-bailing _ are what cause the kayaks to seep water
into the cockpit. Of course, water trickling in and out is
immensely better than trapped water sloshing about in a closed one.
</P>
<P>
   This is the closest the boater will ever commune with
swimming-restricted waters here at the Ventura County reservoir.
The Casitas Water District has allowed kayaking for about two years
and its marina has been renting them for nearly a year. In the
early days, the district was reluctant and kayaking started out
very structured, said Casitas Marina manager Randy King.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to join a club and reach a certain level of skill
before they would certify you and let you go out,'' said King.
``And then you couldn't go farther than 150 feet off the north
shore.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time the restrictions eased; the only rule now is common
sense.
</P>
<P>
   For an agency so notoriously uptight about keeping its water
clean, it seemed a bit odd that the district would permit a vessel
that was now sending a steady stream of coolant through my
skivvies. But was I complaining? No way. It felt great, especially
as the day warmed.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain predictability about the sit-on-top kayak.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't roll in these,'' said Lindahl. ``It's impossible.
Once they start to tilt, they're even more stable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the worst-case scenario _ if the sit-on-top does go over _
you simply fall into the water and climb back on, she assured me.
</P>
<P>
   The only cautionary statement in her litany of assurances was to
get to the lake well after 6 a.m. _ when the lake opens _ so as to
avoid the steady wake of bass and ski boats being launched.
</P>
<P>
   I paddled along the eastern shore, my shoulders, arms and upper
back getting a workout as the kayak's nose swayed from side to side
with each pull. On placid water, the sensation is one of gliding
across a plain of Jell-O on a toboggan.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, when the water kicked up and a 10-knot wind
began to blow, every wavelet was a mini-tsunami, like riding in one
of those model ships they used for filming sea battles before the
age of computer graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the occasionally rough water, the kayak offers a great
advantage over boats for bird watchers and outdoor photographers.
</P>
<P>
   In a western finger of Casitas called Station Canyon,
spectacular blue heron build huge nests in sycamore trees at
water's edge. The kayak has traditionally been the preferred
transportation for sliding into wildlife-rich shallows unobserved.
</P>
<P>
   Bird-watcher Lois Coleman of Glendora, who has paddled in Alaska
and local ocean waters alike, was at Casitas in a tandem kayak with
her daughter, Lynn Coleman of Ojai.
</P>
<P>
   ``For bird-watching, it really doesn't get any better than
this,'' said the elder Coleman, jazzed over having spotted a
black-capped night heron.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Coleman was up for her birthday and the tandem was a nice
means for her to catch up on things with her daughter without
having to make herself heard from one kayak to the next.
</P>
<P>
   In general, two paddlers with equal ability and power will
travel farther and swifter in a tandem than they would in separate
boats. Another advantage with a tandem is that a parent can drop a
child into the bow cockpit and handle the paddling alone with a
minimal trade-off of speed and reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fish from these kayaks, not a problem,'' King had
assured me by phone. But for a beginner, it seemed to require too
much coordination.
</P>
<P>
   I hugged the reed beds along the lake's Wadleigh Arm and
continued south between the main island and the east shore, as
close to the water's surface as you can get without being
!ital!in!off! it. It was the best of both worlds: Sliding across
the water in a feather-light boat in the tradition of an Inuit
hunter, but with all the buoyancy and safety of a molded linear
polyethylene design. &QL; 
Staff writer Jeremy Bagott's boating and sailing column appears
monthly in the Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   KAYAK RENTALS
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Casitas marina rents both solo and tandem boats for $10
an hour or $30 for five hours and $15 an hour or $40 for five
hours, respectively. Information: (805) 649-2043.
</P>
</TEXT>
