<HEADER>
A9430 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-FOOTPRINTS-ART     06-09 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-FOOTPRINTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPRINT OF A BAREFOOT BOY FOUND IN CAVE IN FRANCE MAY BE OLDEST
FOOTPRINT IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the darkness of an underground cave lined with
prehistoric paintings, French scientists believe they have
discovered the oldest footprints of humans in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Embedded in damp clay, the imprints, slightly more than 8 inches
long, appear to be those of a boy, 8 or 10 years old, who was
walking barefoot between 25,000 and 30,000 years ago, prehistorians
who have studied the cave said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They said the dates are only hypothetical because there is no
precise way to determine when the markings were made in the moist
soil. But Michel-Andre Garcia, one prehistorian who has studied the
site, said that the carbon datings in the cave and the context make
this ``a very strong hypothesis.'' The four footprints were found
in the Ardeche region of southern France, deep inside the Chauvet
cave. Its chambers, decorated with extraordinary ice-age paintings
were discovered in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Formal study of the prehistoric site had been blocked by
lawsuits over who owned the land and therefore the rights to the
caves underneath. The issue is still not resolved. But
archeologists began formally exploring the underground caves a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   They see it as a unique treasure chest because it is the first
large cavern from the Paleolithic era to be found undisturbed, its
entrance sealed by an ancient landslide. Some of the panels of
stone etchings and multicolored paintings have been dated at 30,000
to 32,000 years old, making this the oldest cave art known to
science.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Clottes, the prehistorian who heads the team of explorers,
said 11 carbon datings have been made from material in the cave,
from campfires, torch marks and paintings. They are dated between
32,000 and 23,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing more recent than that,'' ? Clottes said. ``So
we believe the footprints belong to that time period, probably to
the last passage of humans in the cave some 25,000 years ago.''
That means, he said, that the footprints are the oldest known in
Europe and belong to Cro-Magnon man, the first humans known to
paint.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest fossilized human footprints were discovered in
South Africa in 1997 in sandstone estimated to be 117,000 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur spelunkers who came upon the French cave in 1994 had
already reported seeing footprints of bears and humans. But it was
not until last month that scientists examined the footprints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very exciting because when you find footprints it makes
a place very much alive,'' Clottes said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, a prehistorian with the National Center for Scientific
Research in Paris, who examined the footprints closely, said that
they are in an undisturbed far end of the main chamber, under a
three-feet-high passage between two caves.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead are several charcoal marks that appear to have been
made by rubbing a torch on the low ceiling to make it burn
brighter. The torch marks above the footprints were recently
estimated to be 26,000 years old through radiocarbon dating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible to prove that the marks on the ceiling and on
the floor are connected,'' Garcia said. ``But the soil in that part
of the cave was totally undisturbed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought the imprints belonged to a boy because of
their width. ``They are very clear and absolutely like a modern
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancient human footprints have been found before in other caves
in France, but they were held to be more recent.
</P>
<P>
   The two-week exploration in May produced other valuable finds.
Clottes said the group had found an eight-inch-long prehistoric
spear carved from a mammoth tooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found lots of little hints of people's presence, like a
piece of animal rib stuck in the crack of a wall,'' he said. ``You
look at the mural paintings and you look at that rib and it makes
you think people have been doing the same things for a very very
long time.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In May, the team, which includes a dozen specialists, also found
31 new paintings and engravings in the cave, bringing the gallery
with its wall panels full of lively animals to 447 images of 14
animal species.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the paintings here are exceptional because of their
age and the skill of their makers and, not least, because they are
mostly images of dangerous animals _ beautifully drawn groups of
lions running, mammoths, cave bears with their mouths open, a pair
of rhinoceroses fighting. Until this find, European cave art
usually depicted animals hunted by man.
</P>
<P>
   Clottes said he believed more discoveries will be made. ``I
think we will probably find more footprints and other valuable
remains,'' he said. ``There are vast areas we have not examined
yet.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
