<HEADER>
A9438 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIMBING-SELF-ESTEEM-     06-09 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMBING-SELF-ESTEEM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK-CLIMBING PROGRAM TEACHES GIRLS TO SCALE ALL SORTS OF HURDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Saleemeh's spirit is willing. But her body won't leave
the table.
</P>
<P>
   Her feet shuffle. Her eyes show fear. Her lips purse.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-grader stands at the edge of the waist-high table.
She could fall backward, like an Olympic diver pushing off a
platform. Or she could just give in to fear and step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my goooooosh!'' she opines, her arms crossed. ``I'm
scared!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fall, stay straight, like a board,'' a buddy yells. ``You can
do it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, OK,'' Saleemeh huffs. ``One ... two ... three ... I'm
falling!!!''
</P>
<P>
   She lands, face up, in a safety net formed by the outstretched
arms of her friends. Everyone whoops and claps and pats her on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piece of cake!'' she trumpets, flashing a grin at her
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of numbers, Saleemeh Razaghzadeh's fall was small _ 4
feet. In words, the distance could be described as larger than
life.
</P>
<P>
   The plunge, known as a ``Trust Fall,'' builds confidence and a
sense of teamwork that she and nine other girls share in Girls
Rock!, _ a Seattle -based program run by the non-profit group
Passages Northwest, which teaches them how to rock climb.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson in trust is vital. On a real rock climb _ away from
the indoor Vertical World in Seattle where they practice _ the
girls may need to help each other, or strangers. And that way of
thinking carries over into life.
</P>
<P>
   For the past nine weeks, the girls have believed in each other,
studied rock wall surfaces with each other, tied complex rope knots
next to each other, fastened safety harnesses for each other and
giggled _ a lot _ among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They climbed, too.
</P>
<P>
   But they have not laughed or learned just among themselves. The
program matches the girls, some of whom are from underprivileged
backgrounds, with climbing volunteers. Those adult mentors come
from professional and academic backgrounds, including education,
medicine and business. They share their rock-climbing prowess, aura
of confidence and brain power with the girls.
</P>
<P>
   The girls, in turn, set manageable goals to improve their own
scaling skills and get quite a workout. They also say the program
readies them for life's looming mountains: the pre-adolescent
hurdles brought on by dawning sexual anxiety, peer pressure and
self-doubt, which many young women face.
</P>
<P>
   In combination, those hurdles can prove so powerful that some
young people have dubbed their not-so-wonder years ``Triple-A'' _
agony, alienation and acne.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy, especially middle school,'' sighs Girl Rocker
Sarah Futhey, an articulate 12-year-old who goes to Eckstein Middle
School in Seattle. ``In my school there are huge popularity
contests. Who can be the best? Who can wear the nicest clothes? I
was never in the `in' group. I'm not into that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But watching the other girls here climb huge walls and go for
the gusto makes me want to do that. When you come to climb, you
don't have to be popular. You just have to believe in yourself, try
and have a good time and meet your goals,'' Sarah adds, before
dashing off for a practice climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever meet a challenging situation in life, I know I can
approach it like a climb _ step by step.''
</P>
<P>
   Program organizers know well the shoes in which the girls are
walking.
</P>
<P>
   Girls Rock! director Rana Betting recalled her preadolescent
years as being one of the most difficult phases of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Betting, who has been climbing for seven years, gets
pleasure from being part of an organization that helps girls feel
less awkward than she did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had had something like this when I was young,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Few would dispute the difficulty girls face holding onto
positive self-images. Pundits, feminist scholars and developmental
psychologists point to cultural sources _ the media, films, music,
advertising, the Internet _ that bombard girls with difficult,
sometimes confusing messages.
</P>
<P>
   Thin females are held up as having the paragon body type in pop
culture; sexual promiscuity in music and films tells kids they are
cool if they ``do it''; girls even receive subtle messages about
how _ or if _ to use brain power. Barbie dolls once chirped, ``Math
class is tough!''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, boys also suffer in their preadolescent years. But
long-standing research has shown the pronounced impacts girls face
living in a patriarchal society.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Gilligan, founder of the Harvard Project on Women's
Psychology and Girls' Development, conducted groundbreaking work
during the 1980s and '90s that showed while adolescent girls start
off promisingly, they fail to fulfill their potential.
</P>
<P>
   Girls make good progress in their early preteen years, around
the ages of 8 and 9, when their behaviors are confident and
outspoken. As they near adolescence, however, they become tentative
and conformist. They start to doubt their moral convictions and
lose self-confidence, Gilligan found.
</P>
<P>
   For some girls, the negative feelings can cause grades to slip.
Studies have shown girls typically become less academically driven
in math and science in late elementary school or early junior high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Downcast feelings can lapse into depression or spin the girls
into harmful behaviors, including eating disorders, drug use and
suicidal thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Pipher, the best-selling author of ``Reviving Ophelia,''
which deals with self-esteem issues among young women, believes
girls are coming of age in a sexualized and media-saturated
society. They become disheartened by America's ``girl-poisoning
culture'' and at puberty ``crash into junk culture,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Lareau survived her ``crash,'' but wanted to be sure
others could avoid collisions altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe I was smart when I was that age,'' says
Lareau, 31, who dreamed of a theater career when she was young.
``The feeling was, if you are dumb, then you go and act. I felt
that as a girl. ... My grades suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Lareau went on to college, where mentors nurtured her passion
for the stage, and she thrived academically. After college, she was
in Boston working in an all-female workshop of ``Henry V'' _ ``I
was Henry'' _ when she met Gilligan.
</P>
<P>
   That encounter inspired Lareau to pursue a master's degree in
education at Harvard, where she eventually studied under Gilligan.
</P>
<P>
   Lareau later moved to Seattle. In 1996, she and a friend, who
directed a science program at the University of Washington, got
together to launch Passages Northwest, a non-profit organization
promoting arts and wilderness education for girls and women.
</P>
<P>
   Passages Northwest branched into backpacking tours; next came
mother-daughter rope courses, followed by sea kayaking and
backpacking courses. In the spring of 1998, she collaborated with
Rebecca Bear, a Seattle educator, and they decided it was time for
girls to rock, but they weren't thinking about a band.
</P>
<P>
   Passages runs on an annual budget of $100,000, about $35,000 of
which is for Girls Rock! The program relies on financial donations
to keep going, primarily because most of the girls who participate
get a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   The current class of Girl Rockers comes from various
backgrounds. Saleemeh, for example, was born in Iran and moved to
the United States with her family. She said she would not have been
allowed to rock climb in her home country. ``I get more confident
every time I go up,'' she said smiling, before scooting up a
25-foot wall. ``I want to try everything in life that I can.''
</P>
<P>
   On another wall, Cody Bloomquist, an eighth-grader, scaled with
her toes pointed like a dancer on a vertical floor, a carryover
from her dance lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Girl Rocker Maddie Seales explained she has come a long
way from when the classes first started. ``I was scared half to
death. I felt so insecure. But now it feels normal,'' the
11-year-old aspiring lawyer or pediatric surgeon said. ``I love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes strength. It takes bravery when you are up there on
the rope,'' said Maddie's mom, Mary Kay Seales, who nonetheless has
caught the bug and has taken two climbing classes. ``I got hooked.
It just looked like too much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the girls said they have made progress from nine weeks
ago, and feel more inclined to challenge themselves at school, both
in the classroom and in other sports. A school counselor said one
girl became more assertive at Girls Rock! and she carried that
attitude back to the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The girls are bright, have energy and aspire to great things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the first female director of the FBI,'' said
Kezia Hopping, who has studied Japanese in school and held a
conversation in the language.
</P>
<P>
   The other girls were happy to speak in their new common
language: dropknee, highstep and traversing _ words for moves in
the rock-climbing world.
</P>
<P>
   Together they were happy they set goals and met them. Mentor
Krista Lindgren, a graduate student, said she was pleased that her
partner, seventh-grader Rachel Herman, recently moved to a higher
level of climbing difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both so happy,'' she said. ``And it's just so terrific
to be around their energy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, their energy level could go even higher.
The girls graduate from the program and get certificates. They will
high-five, smile, giggle, climb, giggle some more, climb and, of
course, show off for parents and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Saturday, things really get rockin' _ Girls Rock! will
head to a real rock wall so the climbing divas can show off their
stuff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
