</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SARAJEVO-BOSNIA10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delegation in Sarajevo sees `incredible progress'
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Hercegovina _ A delegation from Dayton today
will sign a Sister City agreement with the mayor of Sarajevo,
surrounded by a Balkan city that has used the 1995 Dayton Peace
Accords to try to leave behind the scars of war.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-member Dayton delegation that includes musicians,
academics, business representatives and city officials arrived
Wednesday at the grim Sarajevo airport on the city's southwest
side, then was driven into town past streets where an earlier
Dayton delegation saw only snow-covered ruins.
</P>
<P>
   While the signs of the three-year siege of Sarajevo are
everywhere _ pockmarks from bullets and shrapnel dot almost every
building _ Sarajevans have spent four years patching the damage and
trying to go on with their lives. New homes, apartments and shops
are everywhere. Many damaged buildings are surrounded by
scaffolding. The streets on this warm June day were busy and loud
with cars and residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely incredible to see what they have accomplished
in four years,'' Dayton Mayor Mike Turner said after the group
toured crowded bazaars and shops filled with goods.
</P>
<P>
   Turner visited Bosnia twice in 1996, the first time just months
after the fighting ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where before you would have to work to find buildings that
were not significantly damaged, now you have to, looking at the
neighborhoods, find buildings that are the exception, that have not
been restored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The armed siege began in 1992 when Bosnian Serbs, backed by the
Yugoslav Army, took to the hillsides with snipers and cannons and
rained death upon Sarajevo for three years. Residents learned to
shun the sight of the lush green hillsides that surround the city
on all sides and that had helped give the city its identity for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saying was, `If you can see them, they can see you,'''
said Miran Norderland, the Dayton group's guide Wednesday and
president of a media production company, FAMA Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Today, residents have returned to the hillsides' orange-tile
roofed homes, although they steer clear of some high areas that
were once the front lines of war and are believed to be mined.
</P>
<P>
   The peace agreement hammered out at Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base in November 1995 ended the fighting and began an otherwise
unlikely relationship between Dayton and Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Sarajevo had 500,000 residents before the war, much larger than
Dayton. It is also the capital city of Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   But the name Dayton and the connection have stuck. So many small
businesses and shops have made Dayton part of their name that the
word is common locally.
</P>
<P>
   The word, often spelled ``Dejton'' in the Serbo-Croation
language, is shorthand for the good and the bad of rebuilding
Bosnia, a process that includes slowly getting the ethnic Muslim,
Croat and Serb residents to reintegrate their cities and villages.
Most communities in the country, including Sarajevo, house
primarily just one of the three groups.
</P>
<P>
   But physically, at least, rebuilding is under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me the city is clearly working,'' said R. Bruce
Hitchner, a delegation member and director of the Center for
International Programs at the University of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   At a shady cafe, however, Norderland told the group the city's
apparent good health can be a little deceiving because the most
successful residents are the ones in the shopping district, which
now includes exclusive clothes boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see on the street is like in Zagreb and Belgrade _ it
is 10 percent of the population,'' Norderland said.
</P>
<P>
   While the city's economy is stronger now, there has been little
economic growth lately, he said. The country is struggling to
transform the government-run economy of a former communist state
into a market-based, free enterprise system, but outside investors
have been hard to attract.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the population gets by on a combination of government
pensions and odd jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton City Manager Valerie Lemmie said the delegation will try
to encourage contacts between Dayton-area businesses and some of
the rebuilding projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tremendous economic opportunities that are beginning
to emerge that will complement the social and cultural ties that
have developed over the years,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
