<HEADER>
A9444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-JUVENILES-580&AMP;AD     06-09 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-JUVENILES-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FAULTS HOUSE GOP'S GUN MEASURES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Wednesday assailed House
Republicans' gun-control proposals as flawed measures that were
``plainly ghostwritten'' by the National Rifle Association, which
he said was successfully whittling away at the modest new
restrictions on firearms approved by the Senate last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wrong to let the NRA call the shots on this issue,'' the
president said Wednesday afternoon. ``This is a classic, horrible
example of how Washington is out of touch with the rest of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's accusation was the latest salvo in a battle over gun
control in the House that was already adhering to the pattern
established in the Senate, where Republicans repeatedly attempted
to project a new receptiveness to gun control and Democrats
reliably portrayed those efforts as hollow, insincere and
influenced by the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Clinton and House Democrats were pointing out
significant differences between aspects of the gun-control measures
that the Senate passed and details of the proposals unveiled by
House Republicans on Tuesday. Those proposals indeed addressed some
of the most ardent complaints that the rifle association had issued
about the Senate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Most tellingly, the House Republicans' proposal for mandatory
background checks on all buyers at gun shows defines those events
much more narrowly than the Senate did, so that vendors at many
small, informal gatherings and flea markets would be exempt from
the requirement. The NRA was bitterly opposed to the broader Senate
definition.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., who heads the House Judiciary
Committee, acknowledged Wednesday that the committee aides who
drafted the gun-control measures ``spent a lot of time with a lot
of people, including the NRA''
</P>
<P>
   But he defended the NRA as a legitimate advocacy group with
informed opinions and accused Democrats of trying to saddle
Republicans with a new bogeyman, now that Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel, had receded from view.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also stressed that no organization _ ``not the NRA or the
IRA or the NCAA'' _ had written the gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   James Jay Baker, chief lobbyist for the NRA, said Thursday, ``We
made suggestions.'' But he noted that while some of those concerns
were accommodated, others were not, and he said that the NRA was
still engaged in aggressive lobbying _ the organization has spent
more than $1 million in the last four weeks _ to try to get
legislation it likes even better.
</P>
<P>
   As differences between the House proposals and the Senate
legislation came into sharper focus Wednesday, they provided a
snapshot of where House Republicans might be heading on gun
control: on which suggestions they deemed feasible, which they
found desirable and which they might like to jettison.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate fate and precise shape of the gun-control
measures were very much in flux. Senior Republican aides cautioned
that the House Rules Committee could make changes in the measures
before they reached the floor next week, and these aides said that
while Democrats were complaining that the package was too soft,
many Republicans were complaining that it was too strict.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, several of these aides said, many Republicans were more
conservative than NRA officials on gun control and were receiving
calls from constituents, including disgruntled members of the rifle
association, who were urging a fiercer opposition to gun-control
measures than the NRA had mounted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The broad spectrum of opinion within the Republican Party,
coupled with the hodgepodge of measures being piled onto the
juvenile crime bill that is the vehicle for gun control, left some
Democrats and Republicans fretful about the passage of the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hyde has proposed one particularly controversial
amendment that imposes new federal prohibitions on pornographic and
violent material to which children have access.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday about his motivation, Hyde said, that every time
he turned the television on he saw people having sex.
</P>
<P>
   The way Hyde's committee clustered its gun-control proposals
suggested that there might be significant Republican support for a
requirement that child safety devices accompany all handguns sold
by licensed dealers, for new restrictions on juvenile access to
semiautomatic rifles and for a ban on gun ownership for any adult
who committed a violent crime as a child.
</P>
<P>
   But there might be less support for a ban on the import of
high-capacity ammunition clips, which the Senate passed, and a
raise in the legal minimum age for all handgun purchases to 21 from
18, which was absent from the Senate package. Those provisions are
both opposed by the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and gun-control advocates Wednesday identified several
ways in which House Republicans' proposals diverged from the Senate
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans defined child-safety devices more broadly.
Perhaps more important, the Republicans' gun-show measure relaxed
record-keeping requirements; made tracing of firearms sold at gun
shows more difficult; exempted vendors without stationary positions
from conducting mandatory background checks, and eased restrictions
on the shipment of guns across state lines.
</P>
<P>
   But in allowing gun-show vendors three calendar days to conduct
a background check, the measure ignored appeals from NRA officials
for a 24-hour limit. Republicans also thwarted the NRA by including
a provision, not part of the Senate bill, that holds parents
criminally culpable if they do not store guns securely and children
get access to the weapons and cause harm.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said Thursday night that they would try to offer
amendments to the juvenile crime bill that would replace the
language in Hyde's gun-show proposal with the stricter language
from the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many Democratic proposals will be allowed to
the floor of the House, where the majority party has more control
over the debate than they do in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
