<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9446 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORTON-FOI-SPI &LR;      06-09 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORTON-FOI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC COMMITTEE WANTS TO EXAMINE CORRESPONDENCE TO SEN. SLADE
GORTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Slade Gorton's last campaign slogan was
``Slade Gorton works for you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Democrats are about to figure out whether that's
true.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee has filed Freedom
of Information Act requests with multiple federal agencies,
demanding copies of all correspondence from Gorton, R-Wash., and
his staff from the senator's entire 18 years in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, whose vice chairwoman is Sen. Patty Murray,
D-Wash., is seeking the same information about every other
Republican senator up for re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping Freedom of Information Act requests are part of
what's called in Washington ``opposition research,'' and is known
more colloquially as digging for dirt. The Democrats are seeking to
see what they might unearth that might be useful in a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton and Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., erupted with indignation
upon learning of the probe. Gorton compared the incident to the
Bush administration's perusal of candidate Bill Clinton's passport
records and the Clinton administration's review of FBI files on
numerous Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your committee may be within the strict letter of the law to
pursue this Freedom of Information Act request; however, in the
interests of privacy and decency I urge you to modify your request
so as to prevent the possibility that your campaign operatives will
root through the private files of constituents who contacted my
office,'' Gorton wrote to Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. and
chairman of the Senatorial Campaign Committee. ``My record on the
issues can and will be aired and debated openly on the campaign
playing field without instructing federal employees to intrude into
the private lives of individuals to fulfill a political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns marched down to the Senate floor to denounce the action,
and dashed off a letter to President Clinton demanding his
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing is an unprecedented attempt to corrupt
the non-political casework system of Senate offices for political
gain,'' Burns said. ``I find these efforts repugnant, and if there
are any Americans alive who think politics can't sink any lower,
they need look no further'' than the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials professed shock at the response, but said
they would clarify their request to emphasize their desire to
protect the privacy of constituents. They said the Freedom of
Information Act requests are ``a common, routine, and wholly
appropriate research function.'' They said the names of
correspondents would be blacked out before being released.
</P>
<P>
   ``This committee is seeking _ and by law can receive _ only that
information which goes directly to a senator's official duties and
interventions with federal agencies,'' said committee spokesman Jim
Jordan. ``In our view, a senator's contacts with and attempts to
lobby federal agencies are a perfectly legitimate subject of
scrutiny by this Committee and by the public alike, bearing
directly on his or her effectiveness and philosophy of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   William Walsh, a D.C. attorney who is an expert on the Freedom
of Information Act, said he considered the Democrats' request novel
but appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rather broad, to say the least, and it's unique in my
opinion,'' Walsh said. ``But it might serve a good purpose to show
how our officials are serving the public. If this was being done by
newspapers, it would be absolutely appropriate and incredibly
illuminating. All parties should do this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
