<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9450 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-CANADA-SPI &LR;      06-09 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-CANADA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON RUNS ON CANADA'S WEST COAST IN DISMAL STATE, REPORT FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Once-abundant salmon runs of Canada's west coast have
suffered drastic declines in recent years due to habitat
destruction, overfishing and changes in ocean conditions, the
Vancouver-based Pacific Fisheries Resource Council found in its
first report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, our salmon catches over the last five years are among
the lowest of the last 50 years. We seem to have gone from many
diverse fish stocks down to a few strong runs,'' said John Fraser,
the council's chairman and former speaker of Canada's House of
Commons.
</P>
<P>
   The decline is most dramatic among chinook and coho salmon,
species that are also imperiled in the Columbia River system and
throughout the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The return of coho salmon to British Columbia's central coast,
Fraser said in an interview, has declined from more than 500,000
fish to fewer than 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The report released Tuesday said that coho salmon are in danger
from the Skeena River, in northern British Columbia, south to
Vancouver Island and the Strait of Georgia. Last year, Canada
curtailed both the commercial and sport fishery for coho salmon.
</P>
<P>
   But even sockeye salmon, although still abundant in the Fraser
River, are in peril elsewhere along the Canadian coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central coast area once supported the second largest
sockeye fishery in British Columbia, after the Fraser. The Rivers
and Smith Inlet fisheries are now essentially closed,'' said the
Council report.
</P>
<P>
   The Council is a quasi-governmental body of experts appointed
last September to advise Canada's fisheries minister David Anderson
on how to conserve and restore endangered salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   Its report comes less than a week after the United States and
Canada reached a long-term agreement for conserving and managing
salmon runs from the Alaska border to the Oregon coast.
</P>
<P>
   The Council said Canada's Department of Fisheries and Oceans
doesn't have enough money to meet its current conservation mandate
and has lacked resources even to keep track of salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, there is a shortfall in basic (counting) and
assessment monitoring to the extent that only a few stocks,
primarily large ones, have adequate data for their management and
protection,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that fisheries officials cannot account for
what happened to 3.5 million sockeye salmon that swam up the Fraser
River last year but never reached their spawning grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of many salmon stocks is unknown,'' the panel
reported. ``The Council has found that there are such glaring
information gaps ... that no valid conclusions could be drawn about
the state of many stocks. Nonetheless, there is evidence that
salmon biodiversity is being eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 salmon catch along Canada's west coast was about half
the average catch of the last half-century, the Council reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that unfavorable marine conditions, past
overfishing and habitat damage have been significant causes of the
reduced catch,'' it found.
</P>
<P>
   The Council pointedly delivered its report to both the Canadian
government and British Columbia provincial government, which have
bitterly feuded over fisheries policy.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson on Wednesday defended his department, saying it spends
$220 million (Canadian) in the Pacific region and has invested
major work on restoring salmon habitat.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the streams and logged-over areas needing
restoration fall under the control of the British Columbia
government, noted Sharon Chow of the Sierra Club of British
Columbia, which endorsed the Council report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a huge problem between the province and the
federal government, and between Anderson and (British Columbia
Premier) Glen Clark,'' she added. ``And that is not good for
fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser noted, however, that the United States and Canada have
managed to come together after an often-bitter five year dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have created some stability and set out in the direction of
much closer Canada-U.S. cooperation to save fish,'' he said. ``Now
it is time to get our own house in order.''
</P>
<P>
   In a future report, the Council is expected to discuss
breakdowns in Canada's fisheries enforcement, particularly
overfishing in ocean waters and failure to catch poachers once
salmon have begun their upstream migration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0610-C     06-09 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0610-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO PREPARE TO MOVE IN, YUGOSLAVS TO MOVE OUT FOLLOWING
MILITARY PACT
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-SEARCH-0610; KOSOVO-SPYPLANE-0610.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMANOVO, Macedonia _ NATO was poised to end its air war against
Yugoslavia early Thursday, after Belgrade promised to start pulling
troops out of the embattled province of Kosovo overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of heavily-armed NATO troops stood by to begin pouring
across the Macedonian border into Kosovo within hours of a bombing
halt, under the terms of an agreement reached Wednesday by NATO and
Yugoslav commanders at this border outpost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war has ended,'' a somber Yugoslav Col. Gen. Svetozar
Marjanovic told reporters gathered here, as civilians hundreds of
miles away in Belgrade celebrated by honking horns and firing guns
into the night air.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Jackson, commander of NATO forces
in Macedonia, said he was prepared to deploy peacekeeping forces --
with British troops in the vanguard -- within hours of a bombing
halt. Jackson, who will also command the peacekeeping forces,
promised to conduct the force so as ``to even-handedly implement
this agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrendering after 77 days of bombing by U.S. and allied pilots,
Yugoslavia vowed to withdraw all of the 40,000 Serb troops, police
and paramilitary forces out of war-ravaged Kosovo by June 20. In a
concession, NATO agreed to allow the Serbs 11 days -- instead of a
proposed 7 -- to complete their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The pullouts are to take place in several phases, with specific
dates for Serb forces to clear out of three designated zones, as a
NATO-led peacekeeping force of 48,000 -- including 7,000 Americans
-- fills in behind the departing Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton expressed guarded optimism that
Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, the president of Yugoslavia,
appeared to be ready to implement the agreement he accepted in
principal last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the implementation blueprint agreed to on Wednesday
met the conditions essential for enabling an estimated 1.5 million
ethnic Albanian refugees to return in safety to whatever remains of
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sound agreement that meets all of NATO's demands,''
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters at the
Pentagon. ``If the Serbs live up to what they signed, this will end
the killing and begin the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   If Serbs renege, Cohen said, NATO stands ready to resume bombing
at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real test will be whether the Serbs live up to this
agreement,'' said Cohen. If not, he said, ``the air campaign would
then continue.''
</P>
<P>
   After 11 weeks of NATO bombing, Serbs were poised be begin
withdrawing from Kosovo early Thursday, under the watchful eyes of
U.S. reconnaissance aircraft, satellites and other intelligence
sources.
</P>
<P>
   If NATO verifies that Serb forces are pulling out of northern
Kosovo along designated routes, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark,
supreme commander of the alliance, would ask the North Atlantic
Council, or NAC, NATO's political arm, to call on Secretary General
Javier Solana to order a suspension in the strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance will suspend the bombing as soon as Yugoslav troops
begin to withdraw, Solana said following quick approval of the deal
by NATO ambassadors at a late-night meeting in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is a great day for the alliance, but, much more
importantly, it is a great day for the cause of justice for the
people of Kosovo,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said from the beginning ... we are ready to suspend
air operations once we have verified the beginning of the
withdrawal of the Yugoslav forces,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   A bombing halt would set the stage for immediate action by the
United Nations Security Council on a resolution laying out the
mandate for a NATO-led peacekeeping force in Kosovo. That would
likely be approved within hours of a bombing halt, and would kick
the ball back across the Atlantic to the NAC, which would then
issue orders for the peacekeeping force to begin moving into
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There are roughly 17,500 NATO troops already pre-positioned in
Macedonia, mostly British and French forces expected to spearhead
the Kosovo peacekeeping force, dubbed KFOR by military planners and
formally called Operation Guardian Force. The lead forces were
alerted earlier this week to be prepared to move on urgent notice
and were reportedly positioned early Thursday to mobilize on
command.
</P>
<P>
   The first U.S. forces to enter Kosovo -- 1,900 Marines -- were
aboard a ship in the Aegean Sea Wednesday night and were expected
to land in Greece either Thursday or Friday to begin moving toward
Macedonia en route to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon estimated that the Marines
could arrive in Kosovo as early as Sunday to begin setting up a
headquarters for U.S. forces in the town of Gnjilane in the
southern part of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the Marines' arrival, Bacon said, a group of 1,700
Army troops, including light infantry from the 82nd Airborne
Division forces from the 1st Armored Division -- now based outside
Tirana, Albania -- would move into Kosovo, along with 200 other
military specialists with expertise needed for establishing the
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Other U.S. forces from bases in Germany began preparing
equipment to be loaded onto trains, Bacon said, to move toward the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said that the full contingent of 7,000 U.S. peacekeeping
troops -- backed by tanks, combat helicopters and artillery --
should be in place inside Kosovo within roughly 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   As they move in, the 82nd Airborne units and the Marines would
move out, Bacon said -- meaning that some 11,000 U.S. troops would
be involved in the operation, but not all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the elements of peace appeared to fall into place late
Wednesday, NATO continued with air strikes focused on Serb forces
in the field in Kosovo, slamming tanks, artillery, military trucks
and troops wherever they gathered.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said over the past 24 hours its aircraft flew 523 air
missions, including 130 strike sorties and 56 aimed at degrading
the Yugoslav air defense system.
</P>
<P>
   In what appeared likely to be one of the last large attacks of
the war, a pair of U.S. B-52 Stratofortresses caught a large group
of Serbs at a staging area in southern Kosovo, and rained 88 bombs
-- weighing 500 pounds each -- down on the group.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, who briefed reporters on
the attack, said it appeared to have destroyed dozens of military
vehicles, including tanks, armored personnel carriers and trucks,
as well as artillery and other gear. He had no estimate on Serb
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0610-C     06-09 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0610-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO PREPARE TO MOVE IN, YUGOSLAVS TO MOVE OUT FOLLOWING
MILITARY PACT
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-SEARCH-0610; KOSOVO-SPYPLANE-0610.
