u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ROMANOVS-REHAB     06-09 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ROMANOVS-REHABILITATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
80 YEARS LATER, MOSCOW DECLARES FOUR ROMANOVS `NOT GUILTY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ More than 80 years after they died at the hands of
Bolshevik executioners, the son of Czar Alexander II and three
other members of the Romanov dynasty were cleared of wrongdoing
Wednesday night by the prosecutor general, Russia's chief law
enforcement officer.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Duke Pavel Aleksandrovich Romanov, Czar Alexander's son,
was rehabilitated along with three Romanov princes _ Nikolai
Mikhailovich, Dmitri Konstantinovich and Georgi Mikhailovich _
after a review of their case was demanded by a matriarch of the
family.
</P>
<P>
   The men were cleared by the Administpation for the
Rehabilitation of Victims of Political Repression, which reviews
the cases of people charged with crimes during more than 70 years
of totalitarian Soviet rule.
</P>
<P>
   Galina Vesnovskaya, the director of the office, said the new
judgment was based on what now seem obvious: that the four men were
victims of political reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   No further explanation was immediately offered. The Itar-Tass
news service quoted an employee of the prosecutor general's office
as saying that the review was hampered by scanty evidence of who
ordered the men's execution, but that it was clear in any case that
they had not been fairly charged or tried for any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet officials suppressed the true nature of the Romanov
executions for decades. But the prevailing view now is that the
Soviet political police, acting on the orders of Lenin and those
close to him, sought to end any remaining threat to the new
Communist regime from the Romanovs and their supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Wednesday that the four men were cleared after an
appeal led by Grand Duchess Leonida Georgiyevna, a matriarch of the
Romanov clan, who contends that her own grandson, Prince Georgi
Hohenzollern-Romanova, is heir to the Russian throne. Now in her
mid-80s, the grand duchess has led several battles this decade to
restore the Romanov name.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhaustively dissected story of the Romanovs, the
executions of Pavel Aleksandrovich and his relatives have received
comparatively little attention. Alexander II, Pavel
Aleksandrovich's father, was czar from 1855 to 1881 and was
succeeded by another son, Alexander III, who was the father of the
final czar, Nicholas II.
</P>
<P>
   The four men's deaths came several months after the bloody and
more infamous executions of Nicholas, his wife Alexandra and most
of their family in July 1918 by a group of Bolsheviks in
Yekaterinburg.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Russia became independent and the Soviet Union
collapsed in 1991, efforts to set the Romanov record straight were
under way, beginning with a successful effort in the 1980s to
unearth the long-hidden remains of Nicholas and his entourage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 Nicholas' uncle and former governor of Moscow, Grand
Duke Sergei Aleksandrovich Romanov, was reburied in a Moscow
monastery after his remains were found beneath a Kremlin parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   The grand duke had been buried in a 14th-century Kremlin church
after he was assassinated in 1905 by a socialist revolutionary. But
Stalin ordered the church torn down and the crypt paved over, and
for decades government limousines parked on top of it.
</P>
<P>
   After years of debate over the proper memorial to Nicholas II _
whose often-insensitive reign helped set off the revolt that
installed communism in the Kremlin _ the czar, his wife, their
children and their servants were reburied last July in a St.
Petersburg chapel that serves as a Romanov family mausoleum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
