<HEADER>
A9458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-REFUGEE10-COX     06-09 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-REFUGEE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New world: Refugees dive into cultural gulf
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pointing at a map, Fadil Redzic explained to some of
metro Atlanta's newest international residents that MARTA operates
in only two counties _ Fulton and DeKalb, the county in which they
now live.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this DeKalb County, how many villages does it consist
of?'' asked Judah Lul, a Sudan native who moved to Clarkston 12
days ago. ``There is the Mountain of Stone and what else?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stone Mountain,'' Redzic corrected, adding that DeKalb
includes a half dozen or so small cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there any place that is forbidden for the refugees?'' Lul
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. This is America. It is a free country,'' Redzic said.
``Wherever you want to go, you can go.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lul, who fled from Sudan first to Ethiopia, remained
uncertain. Some places in Ethiopia, he explained, are off-limits to
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America,'' Redzic said, ``there is no such place.''
</P>
<P>
   That exchange, and others like it during this introductory class
to American culture run by the International Rescue Committee, made
it clear more than just oceans separate the United States and the
native countries of Lul and his classmates. The cultural gulf is
wide, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that, the U.S. Department of State requires all
organizations that help settle refugees to provide basic
orientation about the American way of life. All refugees arriving
in Georgia _ and elsewhere in the United States _ received some
introduction to the local customs.
</P>
<P>
   But even without that mandate, the resettlement agencies would
probably do it anyway. And they have been orienting refugees _
often. Fleeing war or political persecution, more than 37,000
refugees from around the world have found sanctuary in Georgia
since 1981. More than 15,000 of those arrived in the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   As more refugees resettle in the metro area, orientation is
``critical for them to be able to move forward with their lives,''
said Deborah Inabinet, the church sponsor coordinator for World
Relief, a local resettlement agency. ``They would have no idea what
to expect if we didn't do this for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers with refugee agencies routinely witness why the cultural
introductions are so crucial. Refugees' ``point of reference is so
different,'' said Brian Burt, World Relief's volunteer coordinator.
``When I was in Czechoslovakia, I had friends who didn't comprehend
that I could go from Georgia to Florida without someone stopping me
at the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the first few days of arriving at their new American
homes, refugees must learn mundane lessons, such as how to read a
MARTA map and how to use 911. But if they leave their orientation
classes with nothing else, they must understand they are safe from
the conditions that drove them from their homes and that they have
rights and new responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department requires the agencies to cover certain
basics, such as registering for Selective Service, getting required
immunizations and obtaining Social Security numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But each organization conducts the sessions differently.
Catholic Social Services uses two full days to orient refugees they
are helping to resettle. That agency brings in police officers and
people from the Fulton County Health Department and from the state
Division of Family and Children Services to explain how to get food
stamps and other temporary assistance.
</P>
<P>
   World Relief sends caseworkers to the refugees' apartments to
cover the information _ and to explain things such as how to use a
dishwasher and other household appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphasize personal safety,'' Burt said. ``We tell them
America is a safe country. You don't have to worry about anyone
dropping bombs on you or Mexico invading you, but you have to be
careful here. You have to lock your door. And this is not a rural
area where other people will watch your children. You need to know
where your children are.''
</P>
<P>
   International Rescue Committee takes two hours for its
orientation and conducts the sessions at its offices.
</P>
<P>
   Lul and his three classmates received an introduction to the
mysteries of ATM cards, checking accounts, and laws requiring
drivers to fasten their seat belts and abstain from liquor.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between America and home were numerous _ and
surprising _ to Lul. Few women work in Sudan, and none would
consider striking their husbands in anger.
</P>
<P>
   There's no such thing as ``time out'' for unruly children, and
parents are never concerned about being accused of child abuse
after a severe spanking. And in his homeland, men are not permitted
to give women, even their wives, directions to a rest room, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Skender Shefkiu, a new refugee from Kosovo, and his family
attended the orientation class after Lul. IRC sorts refugees by
language to make translating easier.
</P>
<P>
   Shefkiu arrived in Atlanta last Thursday and doesn't know where
his wife and three younger children are, or even if they are still
alive.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Shefkiu, his sister, niece and son received their
introduction to MARTA. His anxiety over the move and the separation
from his family members seemed temporarily put aside this week as
he listened intently to Zerak Alisairany, an IRC volunteer, who
with the aid of a translator, explained the intricacies of monthly
passes, bus schedules and transfer points.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Shefkiu and his family exchanged a laugh with the
translator, Bejtush Krasniqi, who fled Kosovo three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Shefkiu's small town of Ferizaj has no public transit, nor
nearly as many cars as there are here. But what struck him most
about America was the social interaction among people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, there are lots of different people with many
religions,'' he said. ``In Kosovo, there are only three or four
religions and there is no peace. I don't see how there can be no
peace there with just three or four, and you have peace here with
so many nationalities and religions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
