<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PEACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PRICE FOR PEACE ESTIMATED TO COST $3.5 BILLION A YEAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If you think waging war is expensive, try keeping
the peace.
</P>
<P>
   The military agreement NATO and Yugoslavia signed Wednesday
contemplates an end to the allied bombing and the installment of
50,000 troops, including 7,000 Americans, to keep Yugoslav forces
out of the ravaged province of Kosovo. The U.S. cost of the
peacekeeping force could reach $3.5 billion annually, according to
the Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments, an independent
accounting organization in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This prediction does not include the as-yet undetermined U.S.
share of the $473.4 million in aid the United Nations estimates
will have to be provided to the approximately 1.5 million Kosovar
refugees who bolted from their homes to escape Yugoslav leader
Slobodan Milosevic's army. Nor does the estimated amount include
the cost of rebuilding homes, factories and other facilities
damaged or destroyed during the nearly 11 weeks of NATO bombing,
the center says.
</P>
<P>
   Those costs, however, might be quite small if Milosevic remains
in power. The Senate has insisted in a resolution that the United
States not pay toward rebuilding Yugoslavia while he continues to
rule.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has spent about $2.5 billion in waging the
bombing campaign, CSBA analyst Steven Kosiak said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In estimating the expense of peacekeeping, CSBA relied on the
Pentagon's March calculation that it would cost between $1.5
billion and $2 billion annually to deploy 4,000 troops to Kosovo, a
number that has since risen to 7,000. The center also made its
prediction by extrapolating to a Kosovo operation the approximately
$2 billion the United States has spent annually to maintain 9,000
peacekeeping troops in Bosnia during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Bosnia experience as a guide, CSBA broke down the
projected costs of a Kosovo operation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the Bosnia model holds, about 50 percent of the
U.S. peacekeeping expense would go toward sustaining the troops,
who must be housed, fed, clothed and equipped. In Bosnia, the
United States has used civilian contractors to help with these
functions, including the construction of troop housing, food
service, laundry operations and freight transportation, the center
said.
</P>
<P>
   The next major share of the expenditure _ between 10 percent and
20 percent _ would go toward maintaining and repairing equipment.
These costs would exceed the Pentagon's normal peacetime expenses
because, in a peacekeeping operation, aircraft log more hours in
the air and tanks and other vehicles are used more frequently, CSBA
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The actual deployment would require a relatively small 10
percent of the operation's cost, as troops would be transported to
and from Kosovo on a rotational basis. The additional costs of
paying National Guard or Reserve troops would account for about 10
percent of expenses, the organization said.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-deployment operations, such as special training and
equipment, would eat up about 5 percent of the cost as would the
special compensation for which military personnel serving in Kosovo
might qualify, such as hazardous-duty pay and family-separation
allowances.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's March estimate for Kosovo peacekeeping was twice
as high, on a per-troop basis, as the amount the United States has
spent to prevent hostilities in Bosnia, CSBA said. But the Defense
Department gave no reason for the disparity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be due to a wide variety of factors,'' CSBA's Kosiak
said. ``For example, (the Pentagon) may have believed that U.S.
forces in Kosovo would have to rely relatively more heavily on
support from forces elsewhere in the region than has been the case
with troops in Bosnia. In any case, given the level of damage to
buildings, bridges, roads and other infrastructure in Kosovo ...
this higher-end estimate may represent a better estimate of likely
peacekeeping costs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
