A9464 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-US-BOS &LR;      06-09 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS WRANGLE OVER US PEACEKEEPING ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite an agreement on peace in Kosovo, political
wrangling continued in Congress over how to handle the end of the
conflict. Members of both parties used the developments to defend
positions they staked out months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several House Republicans objected to the use of US peacekeeping
troops, vowing to vote Thursday to prevent funding for a ground
operation. Many Democrats heralded the peace agreement signed
Wednesday as proof the White House strategy had worked, predicting
that any effort to cut off military funding would be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   And yet for the first time in 78 days of NATO airstrikes, there
was a palpable sense of optimism that peace was at hand. Elected
officials spoke in far gentler terms than the month before, when
the House declined to support the air war and some Democrats
harshly questioned the US military strategy. On Wednesday, almost
no one attacked the Clinton administration for reaching an
agreement with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic _ a criticism
that was being aired as recently as last week.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did elected officials sound as skeptical that the plan would
work. Last Friday, Senator John F. Kerry said he had ``serious
questions'' about the plan accepted by Milosevic. Wednesday night,
after reviewing the details of the agreement, Kerry called it ``a
very positive next step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a significant advancing of the principles that
were set out previously,'' said Kerry, a member of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee. ``It's real progress. Obviously, the
key now is that they don't stall or stop somewhere...But I think by
and large we're on a good track.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John Warner, a Virginia Republican who is chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, emerged equally confident from
a phone conversation with Defense Secretary William S. Cohen,
saying: ``I'm just greatly relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, critics turned their attention away from the military
campaign and toward the peacetime strategy intended to take its
place.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans spent the afternoon debating defense
legislation that would cancel US funding of the airstrikes on Sept.
30. When Representative Ike Skelton, a Democrat from Missouri,
announced the Yugoslav peace deal on the floor of the House _
prompting a round of applause from both sides of the aisle _ it
became clear the issue of cutting off funds was moot.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans quickly shifted to address the composition
of the peacekeeping force, arguing that European troops should be
responsible for safeguarding their own continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people can rightfully ask: What are we getting
into? What are we being asked to do here?'' said Representative
Porter J. Goss, a Florida Republican who is chairman of the House
Select Intelligence Committee. ``I think this is a job the
Europeans could handle very well. And there are questions,
certainly, I want answered before one single American goes in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes echoed the cry,
calling the deal a ``a pivotal moment in US-European relations.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert refrained from the domestic
political debate. ``All Americans should be proud of the work of
our men and women in uniform, who conducted themselves in an
exemplary and professional manner,'' he said in a statement. ``I
hope the people of Yugoslavia see this as an opportunity to replace
their leadership, especially Mr. Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the House prepared to take up a measure that would
prevent funding for peacekeeping troops, a spokesman for majority
whip Tom DeLay said there were still many skeptical Republicans who
never wanted the United States to be involved in the first place.
DeLay's spokesman, Mike Scanlon, said ``peace was always good,''
but the provision to cut off funding had ``a good chance of
passing.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that even if the legislation does pass, funding
would come from another source, possibly in a supplemental spending
bill. But on the other side of the Capitol, Senator Phil Gramm, a
Texas Republican, indicated that the political divide over the
troops would not be so easily bridged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for peace,'' Gramm said. ``Unfortunately, it looks like
this so-called peace is going to keep us in Kosovo for another
25-30 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
