<HEADLINE>
IF ELECTED, BUSH SAYS, HE'LL OPPOSE TAX INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GOP-FUNDRAISING) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has broken with his
practice of keeping his views on controversial national issues
under wraps until he officially begins his presidential campaign by
promising that if he is elected president, he will try to block any
proposed tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the no-tax pledge has been a staple of Republican
politics in New Hampshire, which always holds the first
presidential primary. All of Bush's rivals for the presidential
nomination next year have taken the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, Bush had avoided doing so. But on Tuesday, he
sent a letter to Grover G. Norquist, director of Americans for Tax
Reform, who originated the idea of the pledge in 1986, saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``You know from our conversations that if elected President, I
will oppose and veto any increase in individual or corporate
marginal income tax rates or individual or corporate income tax
hikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such increases would reduce productivity, remove money from
the pockets of Americans at a time when taxes already take a record
peacetime share of national income and hurt our country's ability
to provide high quality, high paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will also oppose any further reduction or elimination of
income tax deductions and credits, unless offset dollar for dollar
by reducing tax rates.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Bush will begin his first campaign foray with trips
to Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Norquist said Bush had told him that he would sign the pledge
after the Texas Legislature ended its session on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the first year the pledge figured in the Republican
presidential primary, Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas refused to sign it.
Vice President George Bush, the governor's father, used this
against Dole and went on to win the primary, the Republican
nomination and the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican convention that year, he made his famous
pledge, ``Read my lips: no new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1990, to obtain a budget agreement with the Democratic
Congress, President Bush signed a law raising income taxes. When he
sought re-election in 1992, Bush was chided in Democratic
commercials featuring his pledge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
