<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS TO JOIN DAVIS CUP TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pete Sampras, the prodigal American, returned to the fold
Wednesday, properly contrite, humble, and speaking words of red,
white, and blue. Wednesday Sampras officially announced he has
agreed to play for the US Davis Cup team in next month's
quarterfinal matches against Australia in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very sensitive about jumping on the bandwagon, so to
speak,'' said Sampras, who said he was ``inspired'' watching Jim
Courier and Todd Martin lead the US over England in a first-round
match in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the commitment to go over there and I didn't,'' said
Sampras, who not only will play at the Longwood Cricket Club but
also has committed to play the rest of year if the US advances. ``I
want them (Courier and Martin) to know I'm sensitive to joining the
team and I don't want to come across that I'm taking away their
glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sampras is so sensitive to his appearance as a latecomer
that he stated categorically, ``I've decided I'm just going to play
doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier and Martin have made the sacrifice and deserve the
singles spotlight, Sampras said time and again. ``For me to play
singles,'' said Sampras, ``I'm not comfortable with that. The only
way I would feel comfortable would be if Jim or Todd got hurt,''
and he would be forced to fill in.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gullikson, the US Davis Cup captain, was not as definitive
as Sampras in relegating America's best player to doubles.
Gullikson more than left the door to singles play open, saying,
``Todd and Jim played great in England and they certainly deserve
first shot at singles but we are a team and once you get on a team
there is some flexibility'' as to who plays whom. ``A lot can
happen between now and July 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, for his part, displayed no ruffled feathers or bruised
toes from Sampras's refusing to play for the United States earlier.
If Gullikson decides to use Sampras in a singles match, ``I would
have no grudges about being substituted,'' said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was forced to miss the French Open with a sore shoulder
and played his first match in weeks this week at the Queen's Club
grass court tournament in England. Martin said he expects his
shoulder to be recovered by Wimbledon and the Davis Cup matches
here in July, but if the injury flares up, having Sampras in
reserve is a reassuring prospect.
</P>
<P>
   And, although Gullikson never said it directly, the captain most
likely will go with Courier and Martin in the opening singles
matches with Australia out of deference to their loyalty but might
call on Sampras in the closing singles, particularly if the US is
in dire straits.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is 16-7 (13-6 in singles) in five previous Davis Cup
appearances. And he explained his change of heart by saying he has
now realized there is more to life in tennis than being No. 1 in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being No. 1 takes a lot out of you,'' said Sampras, ``and at
the end of last year I was pretty miserable.'' Ironically, Sampras,
ranked third in the world, moved closer to regaining the No. 1 spot
Wednesday, thanks in part to losses by No. 1 Yevgeny Kafelnikov and
No. 2 Pat Rafter. Sampras struggled to beat Todd Woodbridge, 6-4,
6-7 (8-10), 6-4, in the second round of the Queen's Club tournament
as Kafelnikov lost, 3-6, 6-3, 6-3, to Sargis Sargsian. In Germany,
Rafter lost to Jan Siemerink in the Gerry Weber Open.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras conceded that he rejected overtures to play for the
United States before because of the effect being on the team would
have on his tour schedule and how it might affect his goal of being
the top player in the world. But he had a change of heart after
watching the gallant effort of Courier and Martin in defeating
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much as I would love to finish the year at No. 1,'' said
Sampras, ``I realized the Davis Cup was an event. It's not about
ranking as it is on the tour. It's about handling the pressure. The
pressure is greater in Davis Cup than the Wimbledon final.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more, he went on, ``there are certainly some great
moments'' being part of a team instead of the solitary struggle of
the tour. ``You come together and bond as a team, which you rarely
do on the tour,'' he said. ``It's a fun week.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after the US beat England, Sampras called Gullikson to
congratulate the captain. ``Pete also discussed his willingness on
returning to the team and his commitment to the Davis Cup,'' said
Gullikson. ``He felt very strongly that Jim and Todd deserved the
singles spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Several four-way conversations involving Sampras, Gullikson,
Courier, and Martin followed. The conversations were sensitive
because the three had more or less felt Sampras was an ingrate for
refusing to be part of the team. But finally, said Gullikson, ``We
all came to the same conclusion that having Pete on the team would
be great for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson said he would choose the fourth and final team member
within a week, and that fourth player ``will be a strong doubles
player.'' Martin most likely will not be asked to play singles and
doubles at Longwood, but Sampras said that while he and Courier
have played well as a doubles team, ``I'd like to have Todd'' as
his doubles partner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
