u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAMIN-SETTLEMENT-NY     06-09 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAMIN-SETTLEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 COMPANIES CLOSE TO $850 MILLION SETTLEMENT IN VITAMIN
PRICE-FIXING SUIT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three of the world's largest pharmaceutical and chemical
companies are negotiating to pay about $850 million to settle a
class-action lawsuit that charges them with conspiring as an
international cartel to fix the prices of vitamins for more than a
decade, according to people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies, all based in Europe _ Roche Holding AG,
Rhone-Poulenc and BASF AG _ are trying to resolve a case that just
a few weeks ago led to the largest antitrust fine in U.S. history,
when Roche and BASF agreed to pay more than $725 million to settle
price-fixing allegations. Because Rhone-Poulenc cooperated in the
early days of the government's investigation, the company avoided
paying a large sanction.
</P>
<P>
   In securing a settlement last month, government antitrust
officials said the decade-long conspiracy affected virtually every
American household. The vitamin conspirators, who met regularly and
sometimes referred to themselves as ``Vitamins Inc.,'' fraudulently
inflated the prices of bulk vitamins that went into everything from
breakfast milk and cereal to orange juice, meats, pet food and even
one-a-day vitamins. The vitamins affected were vitamin A, B2, B5,
C, E and Beta Carotene.
</P>
<P>
   According to people who have been briefed on the negotiations,
the three companies _ which dominate the world's vitamins market _
are eager to end the case, and a settlement is expected to come in
the next week or two. Roche is expected to pay the bulk of the
proposed settlement, up to $500 million, with BASF paying about
$250 million and Rhone-Poulenc paying about $85 million. The
class-action suit is primarily focused on vitamins A, C and E and
the proposed settlement is largely determined by market share.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens of plaintiffs in the suit are animal feed
suppliers, food processors and farmers. One of the earliest
lawsuits was filed by the J&AMP;R Feed Services, in Cullman, Ala., in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   If a settlement is agreed to, and people close to the
negotiations say the talks could still break down, that would mean
that altogether, Roche would have agreed to pay more than $1
billion to settle charges that company executives worked in concert
with executives at the other major vitamin makers to allocate
markets and fix the prices of human and animal vitamins, thereby
overcharging American farmers and food processors as well as
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the three drug companies, which control as much as 90
percent of the market for the most popular vitamins, would be
saddled with fines of more than $1.5 billion; the companies also
expect to face antitrust litigation, scrutiny or sanctions in
Canada and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Roche, which is based in Basel, Switzerland, BASF,
which is based in Germany and Rhone-Poulenc, which is headquartered
in France, were unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers with Boies &AMP; Schiller, the Washington law firm that is
leading the class-action settlement, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to the negotiations, however, said that the
settlement talks are moving ahead, and the discussion is
``primarily about the money.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Justice Department settlement, Roche paid $500 million
and BASF paid $225 million to settle the case. A former Roche
official, a Swiss citizen who headed the vitamins division, also
agreed to serve a four-month jail term in the United States, and
government investigators said that there could be more indictments.
</P>
<P>
   A number of smaller vitamin manufacturers have also pled guilty
to fixing prices in the market, and Federal investigators say they
are continuing to investigate what they say was an illegal
international cartel that operated in the vitamins market.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies have said that they have been cooperating
with Justice Department officials and publicly hinted that they had
been seeking to settle the class-action lawsuits. Roche has also
said it has begun talks with the European Commission in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Roche received the largest Justice Department fine, partly
because company executives misled government investigators around
the time it settled charges that it fixed prices in the citric acid
market along with the Archer Daniels Midland Company.
</P>
<P>
   In the class-action case, lawyers have charged thet Roche, BASF,
Rhone-Poulenc and others met repeatedly to allocate sales volumes,
fix and raise prices, and suppress competition in the market,
sometimes by driving out vitamin mixers in clear violation of the
Sherman Antitrust act. Vitamin prices were said to be inflated by
between 20 percent and 40 percent in many instances.
</P>
<P>
   Although the government has targeted a number of high-level
executives at the companies, the chief executive at Roche, said at
a press conference a few weeks ago, that the companies top
executives were unaware of the conspiracy and that the company
would do everything possible to regain the confidence of the public
and its customers.
</P>
<P>
   `'You will understand that this was not part of our
responsibility,'' said Franz B. Humer, the chief executive at
Roche. ``It is certainly not easy to understand the reasons for
actions of employees who in secrecy organized a conspiracy of this
kind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
