<SLUG> BC-OUT-FISHING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET PAPERWORK _ FISHING IS FREE SATURDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ever wish the red tape associated with angling
would just disappear for a day? Some might say fishing is just an
age-old recreation; Big Brother doesn't need to be watching so
diligently.
</P>
<P>
   But regulating the sport is supposedly a way of saving ourselves
from ourselves _ overfishing, poaching, polluting.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can forget about some of the politics _ and some of
the cost _ Saturday during Free Fishing Day, when no one needs a
sport-fishing license to dunk an anchovy or drown a worm. Now you
have one more reason to say, ``Gone fishin','' and concentrate on
relaxing, socializing and just enjoying nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time for passing on the tradition,'' said Jackie
Kourassis, coordinator of the Department of Fish and Game's
``Fishing in the City'' program for Los Angeles and Orange
counties. ``An angler can share the experience with family, friends
and peers who have wanted to fish but never had the opportunity,
been intimidated or didn't know where to start.''
</P>
<P>
   The event coincides with National Fishing Week. A second Free
Fishing Day is planned Sept. 25 to celebrate National Hunting and
Fishing Day. The DFG cautions anglers that all other fishing rules
and regulations apply Saturday, including size and bag limits,
fishing closures and bait and tackle restrictions. Three area DFG
events are slated:
</P>
<P>
   Juneteenth Fishing Derby: A free catfishing derby takes place
from 8 a.m. to noon at Magic Johnson Lake (formerly Willowbrook
Lake), 905 E. El Segundo Blvd. in Los Angeles, (323) 586-6543.
</P>
<P>
   Family Fish Day: Catfish will be stocked for the 8 a.m. to 1
p.m. event at Santa Fe Reservoir, 15501 E. Arrow Highway in
Irwindale, (626) 334-1065.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Discovery Day: Marine fish exhibits, a ``crab lab'' and
catch-and-release angling for the purpose of tagging skates and
rays for research are among the activities planned from 10 a.m. to
3 p.m. at the Upper Newport Bay Ecological Reserve and Regional
Park, 600 Shellmaker Road in Newport Beach, (949) 640-6746 or the
www.newportbay.org Web site.
</P>
<P>
   (See the Fishing Report page for a list of area lakes and
landings.)
</P>
<P>
   uuu
</P>
<P>
   In other fishing news: As a reminder to anglers concerned about
the Channel Islands fishing-ban proposals, the state Fish and Game
Commission next week will consider for the first time public
testimony regarding proposed language to better police
marine-managed areas.
</P>
<P>
   Comments taken at the June 18 commission meeting in Point Reyes
Station, north of San Francisco, will shape the policy. In turn,
the policy with impact two separate proposals to ban recreational
fishing and commercial harvesting along no less than 20 percent of
the shorelines of Anacapa, Santa Cruz, Santa Rosa, San Miguel,
Santa Barbara and San Nicolas islands and out to 1 nautical mile.
The commission also will hear a status report on the same pair of
Channel Islands ``no-take'' ecological reserve proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Can't make the meeting? That shouldn't be a problem. The
commission will next meet Aug. 5-6 in Long Beach. And while it will
consider publishing a notice to adopt the new marine-managed policy
and a suggested time line for its implementation, the commission
also is expected to hear further public comment on the issue.
Information: (916) 653-4899.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9475 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DANCE-MEMOIRS-     06-09 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DANCE-MEMOIRS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLEASURES OF THE FESTIVAL, PASTORAL AND OTHER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.C., Conn.)   (af)  
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a little secret I wonder if it's wise for a critic to
share: I often find that traveling to someplace new, or at least
someplace not routinely familiar, puts me in a good mood for seeing
performances.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder I like to pack my bags in summer and go off to the
Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in the Berkshire Hills of
Massachusetts and the American Dance Festival, since 1978 at Duke
University in Durham, N.C., but before that at Connecticut College
in New London.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling itself can be fun. The bus to Lee, the town closest to
the Pillow, goes along rivers, some spanned by covered bridges, and
through wooded hills and valleys. It's a soothing ride. Durham
requires an air trip.
</P>
<P>
   One journey there for a Merce Cunningham premiere in 1984 proved
unexpectedly and unduly exciting. A violent storm caused my plane
to sway and lurch and change its course for several bumpy hours. By
the time I reached Durham, the premiere was over. I spent the rest
of that evening in a restaurant. Durham has some nice ones.
</P>
<P>
   I vividly remember my first visit to the ADF, as everyone calls
the American Dance Festival. It was 1964, my first summer in New
York, and the program at Connecticut College featured the Martha
Graham Dance Company in works with scores by Louis Horst, Graham's
longtime musical collaborator who had recently died. It was also my
introduction to Graham's choreography.
</P>
<P>
   I was thrilled by the way Ethel Winter kept kicking her leg with
a pioneer woman's determination in ``Frontier.'' But when lines of
women marched solemnly onto the stage and surrounded Yuriko, who
symbolized the Virgin Mary in the stark ``Primitive Mysteries,'' I
was thunderstruck.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a man introduced to me only as Bill turned out to be
the choreographer William Bales. Selma Jeanne turned out to be the
dance historian Selma Jeanne Cohen, and that night, instead of
going home by train, I found myself riding to New York in a car
with her and other people. I dozed off briefly, then awoke to the
sound of Ms. Cohen reciting Yeats.
</P>
<P>
   I spent pleasant evenings in the Connecticut College auditorium.
But there were also memorable events outside it. In her ``Medley''
of 1969, Twyla Tharp sent a horde of dancers scattering across a
lawn. Then they paused, some close to the audience, others far in
the distance, and began to move so slowly that they scarcely
appeared to move at all. The effect was spellbinding.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Meredith Monk made the entire Connecticut campus
her stage for ``Needle-Brain Lloyd and the Systems Kid'' and had
the audience follow her dancers from site to site.
</P>
<P>
   The piece began and ended with people rowing across a lake in a
boat. Lawns were filled with galloping horses, speeding
motorcycles, 18th-century aristocrats, genteel croquet players and
Western pioneers. This was mixed media on a grand scale.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know what to expect of Durham. But I soon grew fond of
this university town, which is also a tobacco town with the aroma
from the factories hanging above the streets. Durham has its
Greenwich Village, a few short but lively blocks on Ninth Street
filled with cafes and bookshops. Duke itself attracts attention
with its two architecturally distinctive campuses: one in the
Georgian style, the other English Gothic and dominated by an
imposing chapel on the scale of a cathedral. I sometimes go there
for noontime organ concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dances I've admired at Duke are Cunningham's
deliberately nonsensical ``Roadrunners'' (1979), in which quirky
movements were accompanied by recitations of fantastic Chinese
legends; Eiko and Koma's ``Beam'' (1983), which made its dancers
struggle up and down a sand dune as if it were Mount Everest; and
Mark Dendy's ``Ritual'' (1996), a spectacle with crowds of people
dancing on stage, up the aisles, along the theater's side walls and
in the lobby in a joyous tribute to the act of performing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, the festival staged some events in nearby Raleigh.
There, Johanna Boyce presented ``Waterbodies'' in a swimming pool
and had dancers artfully splash and paddle to harp music.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember when I first went to the Pillow, as Jacob's
Pillow is known. Nor do I recall what I saw. But I do know I was
charmed by the rustic festival site. Originally a farm, the Pillow
still looks like one and although it was specifically built for
dance, its principal theater resembles a barn.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, too, has its appeal. It's a quiet town and at the head of
its green stands a venerable New England church with a tall white
steeple.
</P>
<P>
   Some summers, Jess Meeker, the Pillow's longtime music director,
would invite visitors for drinks on the little terrace outside his
cabin. A genial man, he would reminisce about Ted Shawn, the
Pillow's founder, and about dance luminaries who had appeared there
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Once, when asked asked why he kept coming back to the Pillow, he
spread his arms wide and said, ``Just look at the place, just look
at the place.''
</P>
<P>
   I, too, love to look at the place, and at performance there.
Over the years, I've attended several programs by soloists from the
Royal Danish Ballet. The sweet, bouncy Danish style seems
especially buoyant in a woodsy setting.
</P>
<P>
   But unusual forms of dance also flourish there. Take ``Unspoken
Territory,'' the astonishing 20-minute solo that the choreographer
Dana Reitz and the lighting designer Jennifer Tipton created for
Mikhail Baryshnikov in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Baryshnikov appeared to be wandering on a journey out of gloom
and into dimly lighted places. At one point, cascades of light
poured down upon him. Yet darkness once again prevailed and he
continued venturing into unknown realms. Baryshnikov seemed to be
exploring an enchanted forest and the fact that there was a real
dark forest outside the theater made the occasion especially
wondrous.
</P>
<P>
   Light and movement were blended in other ways in ``Moving
Images,'' an ingenious program of 1986 in which three
choreographers combined dancing with films. Thanks to cinematic
technology, Victoria Marks made dancers' shadows take on lives of
their own, Kathy Rose danced with cartoons and Pooh Kaye showed
films of apparently rebellious trash cans racing through the
streets while, on stage, dancers tried to manipulate some
particularly unwieldy cans.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think I've ever been at the Pillow when Ted and Ruth
have flown into the theater. I don't mean the ghosts of Shawn and
his wife, Ruth St. Denis, the modern dance pioneer. I'm referring
to two bats, fondly named after these dancers, who make sporadic
Pillow appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Because those bats are reputed to bring good luck, one might
fantasize that they must visit the ADF as well. Both festivals have
been blessed with luck, and I feel lucky to attend them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
