<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9476 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORCHESTRAS-FUTURE-$AD     06-09 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORCHESTRAS-FUTURE-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE EVOLVING ORCHESTRA FIT TO SURVIVE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Cleveland Orchestra was at Carnegie Hall last month,
giving concerts led by its music director, Christoph von Dohnanyi,
and a former principal guest conductor, Pierre Boulez, Ara
Guzelimian, the hall's artistic adviser, took the opportunity to
convene a public discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The two maestros and Joseph W. Polisi, the president of the
Juilliard School, were asked to speculate on what orchestras might
be like in the next century, as institutional bodies and as
artistic machines.
</P>
<P>
   Being asked to think about the future often makes people talk
about the past, for the good reason that we can know what direction
we are facing only if we know where we came from. So it was here.
</P>
<P>
   Polisi _ not only an educator but also a bassoonist, and a
bassoonist's son _testified to the increasing technical
accomplishment of orchestral musicians and to the correspondingly
more rigorous audition procedures orchestras have had to introduce.
He and Dohnanyi also pointed out that because musicians are now
chosen by a panel rather than by the music director alone, there is
less room for individual taste in orchestral sound.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps another reason for that homogenization is the triumph of
recorded music, which has created a single, global audience. Thirty
years ago, Russian, French and Czech orchestras still had quite
special sounds, and there was a radical difference between, say,
the Cleveland Orchestra and the Philadelphia, or the Concertgebouw
Orchestra and the Vienna Philharmonic. Gradually, the
characteristics are being ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   For Boulez, this is no great loss. He talked, to Polisi's
unconcealed delight, about the bassoon, and about how French
orchestras have in recent decades abandoned the French bassoon in
favor of the German model. The specifically French quality of their
sound has thus been diminished, but the orchestras now have
instruments that can speak in the low register.
</P>
<P>
   If there has to be a contest between a self-conscious
perpetuation of tradition and efficiency, for Boulez the choice is
clear.
</P>
<P>
   But if orchestras are becoming more uniform in general sound,
they are also becoming more adept at changing that sound in
response to what they are playing. Where Wilhelm Furtwangler's
Berlin Philharmonic performed Bach and Brahms in much the same way,
modern orchestras are having to develop historical techniques
appropriate to Bach, and indeed to Brahms, as we become ever more
aware of how musical practice has changed.
</P>
<P>
   So a variability rooted in geography, with orchestras in Paris
and Prague sounding quite different, is being replaced by one
responsive to time.
</P>
<P>
   Orchestras that are fixed in time rather than place _ like John
Eliot Gardiner's Orchestre Revolutionnaire et Romantique, which
rarely ventures outside the first half of the 19th century _
perform in the universal network of recording technology rather
than in a city concert hall. Also, they have to play a work only
once for it to be available all over the world and, potentially,
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Such orchestras have played the dominant role in the
period-style movement since the 1970s, and it could be that they
represent the future. Specialized groups of players, schooled in
the performance style of a particular epoch or composer, will come
together to make recordings, and their only concerts will be given
in a few large centers on promotional tours.
</P>
<P>
   But that cannot be a satisfactory vision for anyone who believes
in the values of live music, of the public musical occasion, of
diversity to balance specialization, and of the role music can play
in the life of a city. The question then becomes how to maintain
those traditional values of the orchestra while also facing the
challenges of the ways in which music changed in the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The usual posture so far has been to avoid those challenges,
whether they have come from the early-music movement or from living
composers. Indeed, there can be few institutions of any kind that
have survived the 20th century with so little change.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators (who are around all the time) may have more
weight now than music directors (who are not), but in terms of
concert planning, repertory, hall, season and financing, most
orchestras are doing now pretty much what they did a hundred years
ago. In the 19th century there was substantial change in all those
areas, as there was also in the orchestra's instrumental makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Two conclusions are possible. Either the orchestra, which has
survived so long and so much, will go on surviving, perhaps with an
even more conservative and circumscribed repertory, or else change
must soon come. Probably both stories will be played out at the
same time, with some orchestras continuing much as they are and
others looking for ways to change.
</P>
<P>
   Those in search of such ways might well begin with ideas that
Boulez has been trying to promulgate since he first became
associated with the Cleveland Orchestra, more than 30 years ago:
ideas that he began to institute when he was music director of the
New York Philharmonic and BBC Symphony in the 70s and that more
recently helped shape the Cite de la Musique in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   He passionately elucidated those ideas at the Carnegie Hall
symposium. Music now is far more various than it was in the days of
Brahms, and the life of an orchestra should reflect that variety,
for the sake of its members as much as its audience.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra should be not one thing but many: besides giving
symphonic concerts, it should at times be an opera orchestra, a
Haydn-Mozart orchestra, a contemporary-music ensemble. There should
be opportunities for players to give chamber concerts, and the
orchestra's home, the concert hall, should be open not just between
8 and 10 in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   It should, rather, be a center of documentation, printed and
electronic, where people could go to read about, study and listen
to music. It might also incorporate a music museum and an
educational institution.
</P>
<P>
   Most orchestras have adopted one or another of such endeavors in
recent years, but none have become the kind of multipurpose,
performing-teaching body Boulez has been advocating. Dohnanyi, for
his part, firmly endorsed his colleague's hopes, but gave, too, the
reason they have not been embraced by orchestras around the globe:
money.
</P>
<P>
   At a time of financial stringency in the arts, it might seem a
pipe dream to imagine an orchestra working from within a
library-school-museum-auditorium complex and providing, besides its
big public events, a multitude of smaller performances and
continuing opportunities for people to deepen and broaden their
musical experience through self-education.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the orchestra is not to be a real musical
heart for its city, what is it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
