<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remove money-taking Gators from record books, coach says
 &HT;    By Andy Staples
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Florida cornerback Tony George could go into the
school record book as the top player on last year's defense, even
though a trio of NFL draftees had better statistics and a bigger
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Florida coach Steve Spurrier hopes to expunge linebackers Jevon
Kearse and Johnny Rutledge and defensive tackle Reggie McGrew from
the record book after the players admitted under oath to taking
money from South Carolina-based agent William ``Tank'' Black while
still playing for Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have banned the three from the university's athletic
facilities, and the former players cannot visit practice or walk
the sidelines at games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to come up with a punishment to fit the crime,''
Spurrier said Tuesday before speaking to the Atlanta Gator Club.
``It's harsh, but they did wrong, and now they have to accept the
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrew's father, Taylor, said he thinks the coach is trying to
go too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed in the fact UF seems to think
they've done a horrible, horrible thing,'' he said. ``It's wrong. I
don't condone it. I think it's OK to ban the players, but to take
pictures down from the locker room is going too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, speaking Wednesday from Tennessee Titans training camp
in Bellevue, Tenn., said he was just trying to put the scandal
behind him and get on with his career. He did concede that not
being allowed to visit his former team hurt his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the whole story about why, but I guess I just
have to deal with it,'' Kearse said. ``It's just a long process,
and I'm going to have to put it behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida athletics director Jeremy Foley said no final decision
has been made to delete the players' names from the record books,
but he said they definitely are not allowed to use school
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Foley also said that Florida officials had made no decision
about suing the players to recoup the cost of an ongoing university
police investigation into Black's activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty simple decision,'' Foley said. ``Why would you
want them around our current players? We don't want them having
contact and giving advice to them. That's how coach Spurrier sees
it, and I don't think anything is too harsh in this situation. I'm
completely behind coach Spurrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearse, Rutledge and McGrew admitted in interviews with campus
police to taking money. Black also reportedly bought Kearse a
$133,500 Mercedes two days before the Orange Bowl. Black's
attorney, Leonard Mungo, said the car was a surprise and that
Kearse did not see it before the game.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth player, linebacker Mike Peterson, also was interviewed
but has not been connected to any illegal payments.
</P>
<P>
   All four players fired Black in late April. Kearse, Rutledge and
McGrew hired Leigh Steinberg, while Peterson hired Miami-based
agent David Canter. Black could face felony charges when the
investigation ends.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier, who has advocated paying athletes a monthly stipend,
said the scandal did not change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said we should have a college football playoff.
I've always said we should pay players $100 a month,'' Spurrier
said. ``But that doesn't change the fact that these guys broke the
rules, and now they're paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
