<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vieri heads to Inter Milan
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While Jean-Marc Bosman remains destitute and largely
ignored by the nouveau riche of European soccer, Christian Vieri,
the richest among them, continues to roll in a growing pile of
lire. Billions and billions of lire, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth time in the past five seasons, Vieri is moving to
a new club, and he has the unheralded Belgian to thank for
escalating transfer fees that came out of Bosman's push for
European free agency earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Vieri went from Lazio to Inter Milan on Tuesday for a
world-record transfer total of roughly $50 million (90 billion
lire), breaking last year's mark set by Brazilian Denilson in a $35
million move to Spain's Real Betis. That topped the $28 million
involved when Atletico Madrid shipped Vieri to Lazio in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bosman was playing for Belgian club Lierge when he challenged
its decision to command a transfer fee for his desired move to
France, even though he was out of contract. He eventually took his
case to the European Court, which invalidated that practice in 1995
and also eliminated limits on foreign players in European Union
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top 50 European transfer amounts, only eight are
pre-Bosman. Vieri's 1996 move from Juventus to Atletico Madrid for
$19.3 million to begin his personal revolving door is the
13th-highest. Players and their agents pocket roughly 10 percent to
15 percent of a transfer fee, with the remainder going to the
selling club.
</P>
<P>
   At Inter, Vieri will team up with Brazilian star Ronaldo, whose
move there from Barcelona after just one season in 1997 for $27.9
million is in fourth place, and whose price tag to Spain from PSV
Eindhoven was $20 million. As part of the Vieri deal, Inter will
ship Argentina midfielder Diego Simeone to Lazio in a transaction
worth a mere $11.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Like Curt Flood in baseball, Bosman never played professionally
again. According to this month's issue of World Soccer magazine, a
recent letter he mailed to top players in England, Germany, Spain
and Italy seeking donations for his expenses has gone largely
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Euro 2000: England on ropes
</P>
<P>
   So Kevin Keegan's managerial honeymoon is over. And how. Two
dismal ties in the past week have England gasping desperately to
make the Euro 2000 playoffs in the fall. Saturday's scoreless draw
with Sweden at Wembley Stadium was followed Wednesday by 1-1 tie
with Bulgaria in Sofia, even though England had a man advantage for
the final 30 minutes. Alan Shearer scored in the 15th minute, but
Bulgaria got the equalizer three minutes later and gave veteran
Hristo Stoichkov a happy farewell to his international career....
France got a penalty-kick goal from Frank Leboeuf with only four
minutes to play to pull out a 1-0 win over lowly Andorra and avoid
further embarrassment after Saturday's home loss to Russia.
Andorra, which is pointless in Group 4, had given up 19 goals in
its previous six qualifiers.... Despite two humiliating results,
Scotland still has a playoff chance. After a 1-1 draw with the
Faroe Islands on Saturday, the Scots couldn't hold a 2-0 lead and
lost 3-2 to the Czech Republic. Jan Koller got the winner in the
87th minute.... Romanian soccer hero Gheorghe Hagi disappointed his
countrymen when he retired after the World Cup last year, but what
was to have been a one-game comeback in a 2-0 win over Hungary on
Saturday has prompted the 34-year-old forward to resume his
international career. Hagi, who has 33 goals in 116 caps, was in
the lineup as Romania beat their Eastern European rivals for the
first time in 63 years.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Boy describes attack
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year-old French boy who saw four German hooligans viciously
attack a gendarme after a World Cup game last June described the
incident in court Wednesday, but could not identify any of the
suspects. The boy, testifying in an ongoing trial in Essen,
Germany, said officer Daniel Nivel was struck on the head with a
metal object and signboard and kicked repeatedly in a street in
Lens after Germany's draw with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The four men, ages 23 to 31, have been charged with attempted
murder. Nivel was in a coma for six weeks and has permanent brain
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Toluca wins thriller
</P>
<P>
   Toluca finally triumphed over Atlas 5-4 on penalty kicks Sunday
for the Torneo de Verano title after the teams were tied 5-5 in
aggreggate. A draining overtime session could not settle matters,
as Toluca twice hit the post in the final minutes. Atlas coach
Ricardo Lavolpe was sent off just as regulation ended at 2-2, and
he was treated to a shower of debris from home fans at Estadio
Toluca '70-'86 as he walked off the field. Penalty kicks were
interrupted for several moments when a member of Toluca's bench
baited some of the Atlas penalty-takers, causing a major scuffle.
Goalkeeper Hernan Crisante turned away Julio Estrada in the first
extra penalty-kick session, and Toluca won its second summer title
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   S. America: 5 ousted in friendly
</P>
<P>
   Five players were ejected, including two in an injury-time
hair-pulling incident, as Brazil topped the Netherlands 3-1 in a
friendly Tuesday. After a challenge for the ball with the final
whistle imminent, Brazil's Rivaldo grabbed Dutch midfielder Edgar
Davids by the dreadlocks and hauled him to the ground. A fight
ensued, and they were shown yellow cards.... Brazil has been chosen
to host the World Club Cup, an eight-team FIFA-sponsored tournament
featuring the continental club-championship winners that will take
place in January.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
