<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All pressure on Argentina in rematch
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The last time the U.S. faced Argentina, the 15,000 who
gathered in a small stadium during the 1995 Copa America in Uruguay
couldn't believe the final score: U.S. 3, Argentina 0.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Americans had beaten a major world
power outside the United States, but like several of their other
dragon-slaying wins, in the end it didn't have much staying power.
</P>
<P>
   And that's one reason why coach Bruce Arena isn't putting too
much emphasis on winning Sunday's friendly with Argentina at
Washington's RFK Stadium (1 p.m., ABC), the first match for the
U.S. team since it fell to Mexico in the U.S. Cup finals in March.
</P>
<P>
   It should be a good test as the Americans prepare for a
Confederations Cup pool this summer that includes Germany and
Brazil. ``It's important that we play well on Sunday, but it's not
life or death for us,'' Arena said. ``There's not a whole lot of
pressure on us to win this game.''
</P>
<P>
   For Argentina, even friendlies against such historical soccer
minnows as the United States are treated in a serious,
results-oriented vein. Argentina will be sending veterans Diego
Simeone and Ariel Ortega, as it gets ready for the Copa America
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Curse of the Cosmos?
</P>
<P>
   They're on their fifth coach in slightly more than three
seasons, a heavy turnover of players continues, and the Giants
Stadium faithful wonder whether the New York/New Jersey MetroStars
aren't being haunted by the ghosts of the Cosmos.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars sank to new lows Saturday in a 5-2 loss to Dallas
before only 11,567 at Giants Stadium. It was an all-American
lineup, but the franchise's futility knows no nationality.
</P>
<P>
   MLS officials say they're making progress in landing a
``marquee'' international player allocated in a trade last week
with the Miami Fusion, but for the moment it can't help a 4-7 club
that has dumbfounded even famous soccer miracle worker Bora
Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
