<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9481 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGA-CHAMPS10-COX     06-09 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-CHAMPS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Title town at UGA
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No other school in the nation will top the University
of Georgia's four national titles this year. The question for
athletics director Vince Dooley and his staff is what comes next.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bulldogs took national titles in gymnastics and women's
swimming and diving ealier this spring, they tied Georgia's
previous high in championships _ two in 1986-87, in gymnastics and
tennis. Then, Manuel Diaz's tennis team upset top-ranked UCLA two
weeks ago, and Chris Haack's golf squad won its NCAA title on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford holds the record with six national titles in one
academic year, with six in 1996-97. The Cardinal also won five last
year and probably will win the Sears Director's Cup again for
overall athletics excellence.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia, with 20 sports to Stanford's 30, probably will
finish No. 2 in the Sears standings for 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do with four national titles? ``I don't think
that the awareness level of what has been accomplished in 1999 has
been raised enough,'' said Don Leebern, one of Georgia's biggest
boosters and former president of the state University System's
Board of Regents. ``We've shown we have the ability to have a
consistently high standard in both academics and athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's establish it as a new level of excellence (and) raise
the bar,'' Leebern said.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the athletics success this year, most Georgia fans
would prefer a championship in another sport _ football. The
football program has made great strides in Jim Donnan's three
seasons in Athens, but it has been 19 years since Georgia won a
national title on the gridiron and 17 years since its last
conference title.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent success of the football team _ 17 regular-season
wins and a pair of bowl victories in the past two years _ has
helped Georgia fans get excited about the school's other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Provided the two most visible (sports), the two engines,
football and basketball, have people feeling good, we're in good
shape,'' Dooley said. ``I think people really feel good about
football, and people, for the most part, feel good about the future
of basketball. When those two make people feel good, they feel good
about all of our sports.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not unexpected for Suzanne Yoculan's gymnastics team to
capture the national title, as All-Americans Karin Lichey and Jenni
Beathard headed a group of key returnees from the 1998 championship
team. But the other top finishes came as surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, who coached five previous teams to the tennis finals,
conceded that some of them were far superior in talent to this one,
but this year's squad led by Talito Corrales, Hisham Hemeda and
Joey Pitts were talented enough to win it all. Jack Bauerle had
been coaching his swimmers 20 years without a title, but Kristy
Kowal and Courtney Shealy helped Bauerle and Georgia end a
championship drought.
</P>
<P>
   Champions to be honored
</P>
<P>
   Haack has been the golf coach in Athens only three years, but
Ryuji Imada helped to carry this team over the top. As the school's
former football coach, Dooley said, ``It took me 17 years to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's marketing director Avery McLain is meeting with a
collegiate licensing company to put together some plans for
capturing the year and taking advantage of it in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some T-shirts made up with the logos of the four
sports that read, `The Year of the Dog,''' McLain said. ``We're
planning a series of championship posters for the four sports to
give to the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley says the four coaches and teams will be honored at
football halftimes in the fall. The two winter sports will share
the halftime of one game, and the two spring sports will be honored
at another.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches will receive an extra month's salary for their
achievements, but more could be on the way, Dooley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been contemplating providing some contracts with
incentives for our coaches in those sports that have been very
successful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The four also should thrive, at least in exposure, from Dooley's
intent to have them at as many Bulldog Club meetings as possible
over the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting gets boost
</P>
<P>
   The success should help in recruiting, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not starting from scratch,'' Bauerle said. ``You have
credibility walking into the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' he said, ``four national championships will
impact everybody. I think it already has raised people's
consciousness. Just watching gymnastics and tennis, people are
going to see a high level of athlete. There's a real feeling for
sports outside of football and basketball, but it's great to be
successful in football, too, and I know that as a coach who's been
here for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps in recruiting coaches,'' Dooley said. ``We
were able to get (new baseball coach) Ron Polk. (New basketball
coach) Jim Harrick has the appreciation (that) this is an
all-around program.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley repeated a recent comment from Chris Scelfo, the former
football assistant who took the top job at Tulane: ``You know how
good the (Georgia) program is when you're there, but when you
leave, you really appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations raised
</P>
<P>
   Haack said, ``I think it'll help when kids think about where
they want to play, and maybe they'll put Georgia on their list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside is people's expectations that we should do this
every year,'' he said. ``It's hard to build a dynasty in a sport
like golf. We may have great teams for the next 15 years and not
win another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's tennis title helped the sport of tennis itself, Diaz
said. ``Locally, it has raised awareness for our sport,'' he said.
``Here in Atlanta, people are taking tennis up again. Tennis has
been on a little of a downslide, and this helped. It was also an
incredible accomplishment for our program.
</P>
<P>
   National championships certainly help the school's name
recognition, the tennis coach said. ``I think there's a great
awareness of Georgia. We had wrapped up our recruiting for this
fall before we won it, but to me the thing is our team competed
with a lot of class and composure. Those are the accolades I like
best, and that's what will draw the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauerle put the achievements in perspective. ``We're enjoying
what did happen, and we're not sure of what will happen,'' he said.
``For the time being, we have a lot of happy coaches right now, and
a very happy athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
