<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE TRAIL OF THE AZOREAN DIASPORA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALL RIVER, Mass. _ If you are searching for the soul of soccer
in the United States, inevitably you end up in places like the
Academica Club on South Main Street in this old fishing town. The
origins of the club are Portuguese, but if you are passionate about
the game, ancestry is irrelevant these days.
</P>
<P>
   There was a celebratory mood Wednesday in anticipation of Dia de
Portugal _ Portuguese Independence Day _ and Thursday night's
exhibition between Clube Desportivo Santa Clara and the Revolution
at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   CD Santa Clara is a small club by European, even Portuguese,
standards. But it has accomplished something big _ it became the
first club from the Azores to advance to the Primeira Division in
Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Santa Clara is taking a victory tour, making contact with
the diaspora, which by now far outnumbers the population of the
islands. Azoreans such as Afonso Costa, who set up this tour,
gambling on the team's success _ Santa Clara's promotion was not
assured until the final minutes of the last game of the season _
have found fortune and new lives in Canada and the US. Club
president Paulino Pavao is hoping this event will help reunite
immigrants with their roots.
</P>
<P>
   But the Santa Clara administrators, coaches, and players know
little about the Revolution, and are generally baffled by the
configuration and rules of Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nobody of the class of Zenga on our team,'' said coach
Manuel Fernandes, who played for Sporting on a US tour in the early
1980s. ``They might be more experienced than we are but my players
are not intimidated by anyone. We will not play defensively, to
keep the score close, but we will play to please the fans. We will
present a boa figura.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandes, 48, was a mainstay of the Portuguese national team
and captain of Sporting Clube. He played against Revolution
goalie/coach Walter Zenga in a European Championship qualifying
match, losing, 1-0, to Italy in Lisbon in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He is curious to see the progress of the game in the US.
</P>
<P>
   ``From analyzing the performance of the US national team, they
are more balanced and competitive than they were 10 to 15 years
ago,'' Fernandes said. ``They are investing more money into the
game and I am sure they will get better if they go to a 20-team
first division, like in England and other places, with a good
lower-division supporting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Azorean soccer has only produced one national team player _ left
winger Pauleta, who is now playing in Spain. The Azorean and
Madeiran immigrants brought their club tradition to the US, and
they must have also imported some of the higher levels of the
soccer gene pool. The US team that conquered England in the 1950
World Cup was composed of several players from the Ponta Delgada
Club of North Tiverton, R.I., named for the major city of the
Azores. And Fall River was the home of Adelino (Billy) Gonsalves,
son of Madeiran immigrants, and considered the best player in US
soccer history.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people from the Azores have not been back for 20 or
30 years, some descendents have never been there,'' Pavao said.
``This club represents the passion of all Azoreans, and I hope when
we play against the big clubs, Benfica, Porto, Sporting, this gives
them a reason to return and reacquaint themselves with the
Azores.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
