<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-JUMP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SPIRITS: FORMER PRESIDENT BUSH BAILS OUT IN BIRTHDAY BASH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Former President Bush, who turns 75 on
Saturday, celebrated early Wednesday by plunging out of an
airplane, free-falling for one minute, and then parachuting onto
the grounds of his presidential library.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had one of the biggest thrills of my life,'' Bush said
afterward. ``Old guys can still do stuff, and you might as well go
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Bush for the daredevil event was Army Gen. Henry H.
Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, whose participation
was not choreographed in advance. A spokesman for Bush said the
president was ``thrilled'' that Shelton, 57, was able to join him
at the last minute as a show of support for his former
commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who wore a white jumpsuit with his name stitched in blue
on his chest, leaped from a twin-engine &UR;  &LR; Shorts Skyvan at about
13,000 feet Wednesday morning, with two jumpmasters at his side. He
pulled his own white parachute, which bore the name of the
University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, and followed
several other sky divers to the ground. Before a crowd of about
1,500, the former president hit his target and appeared to make a
soft landing on his feet before falling backward.
</P>
<P>
   After the jump, Bush announced that a birthday celebration and
fund-raiser honoring him and his wife, Barbara, who turned 74 on
Tuesday, had raised $8.8 million for the Houston cancer center's
research. One of the Bushes' two daughters, Robin, died of leukemia
in 1953, and the couple serves on the cancer center's board.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's jump was Bush's third. His first was at age 20 when,
as a World War II pilot, he had to bail out of his burning torpedo
bomber in September 1944 after it was hit over the island of Chichi
Jima, 600 miles south of Japan. Bush was rescued by a Navy
submarine, but his two crew members were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Bush made his second sky dive in Yuma, Ariz.,
fulfilling a promise he had made to himself to make a nonemergency
jump just for the fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Barbara today would be my last time, but I enjoyed
myself so much that now I don't know,'' Bush said Wednesday. ``It
was darned exciting. It was heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bush and the former first lady watched from the landing field
following Bush's jump, Shelton and skydivers from the Army, Navy,
Air Force and Marines jumped in salute to their former
commander-in-chief. Bush greeted each with a double high-five as
they gathered their parachutes.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, a former paratrooper and decorated Vietnam combat
veteran, has jumped four or five times since becoming chairman two
years ago, according to a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Also jumping Wednesday were members of the Alexandria, Va.-based
U.S. Parachute Association, which organized the event. Although
their tribute to Bush was blocked by the clouds, the sky divers
spelled out Bush's initials and the number 75 before deploying
their parachutes.
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the group, who parachuted during a test jump
earlier in the day, is older than Bush. Tom Morrison, a World War
II veteran who turned 75 three months ago and has logged 8,660
jumps, had requested the chance to meet the former president when
he heard he would jump again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just called them up and said, `I'm 75 too, and I'd like to
be on board,' and they said, `Come on,''' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that along with drawing attention to research on
cancer, he hopes his jump will deliver a message to older people:
``You're not out of it,'' he said. ``I feel like a spring colt. I
don't feel 75. I know everybody doesn't want to jump out of an
airplane, but work it out to try something and not just sit in
front of the TV like I used to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also introduced to the crowd his wartime buddy Jack Guy,
who had traveled to College Station from his home in Atlanta to
watch his friend jump. Guy, 76, said Bush did a great job and
looked ``fantastic.'' Would he consider jumping? ``Would you mind
if I said, `Hell?''' he asked, laughing. ``Hell no.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush deflected only one inevitable question Wednesday, involving
Texas Gov. George W. Bush's presidential aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into politics on this beautiful,
nonpolitical day,'' he said. ``But of course, Barbara and I are
proud of both of our sons who are in politics, and we're proud of
the two who aren't. We're proud of all of our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush is the governor of Florida. The Bushes other three
children are daughter Dorothy and sons Neil and Marvin.
</P>
<P>
   The former president pulled his wife to the podium to answer
another inevitable question: Will she let him jump again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already told him he can do it when he's 80,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, asked if she felt proud, watching him parachute, she
shrugged: ``Not really. I expect the best from George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
