<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9489 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT &LR;      06-09 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYOUS CROWDS IN BELGRADE CELEBRATE END OF WAR
</HEADLINE>
   (With KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-SCENE, KOSOVO-DIPLO) 
(sw) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The street lights came on in downtown
Belgrade on Wednesday night for the first time in 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds that had gathered spontaneously in the main square sent
up a raucous cheer, celebrating both an end to the war and to the
blackouts that have plagued residents. Joy and bravado combined to
lead many to proclaim victory.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred young people danced and drank beer. One man
waved a Serbian flag. Another danced holding a red flare.
Firecrackers burst loudly among the feet of those in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   By midnight cars swarmed around Republican Square, lights
flashing and horns blaring and music pumping from their sound
systems. Girls and soldiers in uniform hung out of the car windows
or rode on the tops of cars, holding their fingers out in victory
signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came because the bombing stopped,'' said the driver of a
red open-topped jeep, gunning his engine. ``We came to celebrate
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Word spread quickly that Yugoslav and NATO military chiefs had
signed an agreement, and people who saw it on television said they
immediately thought to go downtown and see what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers arrived about an hour after the celebrations
began and moved along some of the cars, but otherwise allowed the
crowd to spill over in the street blocking the way for traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Then the street lights came on, pale at first, and gradually
growing in strength. Next, the floodlights of the National Museum,
an imposing building on the side of the square, began to glow, amid
still more cheers.
</P>
<P>
   A group of soldiers, two conscripts in their early 20s, and a
28-year-old reservist who gave his name only as Zeljko said they
had heard the news of the military agreement and immediately called
some friends to go out on the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the war to stop every night, and tonight was the
night,'' Zeljko said. ``We wanted to come out and have fun. We did
not want war, I think no one wanted it.''
</P>
<P>
   He stood in his uniform, his head closely shaved, talking
quietly, as people came by and slapped him on the back. His friends
passed round a bottle of whiskey, swigging huge gulps from the
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to celebrate victory,'' said one lanky conscript from
Western Serbia. ``We got through nearly 80 days of bombing. No one
else can survive that except us. That is a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   He told a story about his commander who he said had no friends
and did not talk to anyone. ``So he joined the army and now he
treats his men the same, he never talks to us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who won the war, NATO or Yugoslavia, he paused to think.
``We never lost the war,'' he said. Asked if people saw them as
heroes, he said: ``In a way, when you resist the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   Others in the crowd were celebrating the end of the bombing that
has so often kept them awake in the night over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here tonight to celebrate our victory, to show how
great Serbia is,'' said one man driving a car full of friends. ``I
have two children and they had to sleep with a pillow over the
window because of the bombing. Can you imagine what it is like for
children and their parents?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He like others had not believed the political agreement signed
by President Slobodan Milosevic last week would really end the war.
``They went on bombing, didn't they?'' he said. But now that the
military chiefs had reached agreement, he was more certain.
</P>
<P>
   `'It was when we saw that NATO general come out and announce the
agreement that we believed it,'' said a 21-year-old woman named
Gordana, who was out celebrating with several soldier friends.
</P>
<P>
   She had seen Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Jackson, commander of NATO
troops in Macedonia, announce the agreement live on CNN, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Behind her several cars were lined up, their doors and trunks
open, thumping with loud music and creating a disco on the street.
People shouted to friends and danced a few steps. It was a striking
contrast to recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade, usually famous for its nightlife, has been deadly
quiet during the nights of bombing, as few people ventured out on
the pitch black streets and many have not dared cross the bridges
over the Sava River into the city center at night, for fear the
bridges would be bombed.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration was certainly spontaneous and the feelings of
happiness genuine. For many it was just an excuse to have some loud
fun. Some in the crowd had just come to see what the noise was. One
man came by on his bicycle. A few did not want to appear
unpatriotic and spouted nationalist slogans to foreign journalists
and began singing Serbian patriotic songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to defend what is ours,'' said Djordje, a 22-year-old
cab driver. Kosovo will remain part of Serbia for ever.'' Yet he
said he was due to serve his military service later in the year and
admitted he was delighted that the war was over.
</P>
<P>
   One pair of men in black shirts, who said their were supporters
of the Radical Nationalist Party, said the people gathered were
stupid, since they did not understand that the agreement was bad
for Serbia and bad for their future.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrations were also reported elsewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Gunfire and celebratory antiaircraft fire were being fired in
the town of Novi Sad, north of Belgrade, one resident reported by
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, Serbian troops also greeted
news of the agreement with loud vollies of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   A huge crowd also gathered in southern Serbia firing guns in the
air and cheering on the main square in the town of Krusevac, where
thousands of people, reservists and their families, demonstrated
against the war last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
