<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-STANLEYCUP10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars vowing Hasek will see more pressure
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For the second consecutive season, the Dallas Stars
this year earned a piece of hardware called the Presidents Trophy,
awarded annually to the NHL's regular season champion. But
heightened expectations do not guarantee postseason success.
</P>
<P>
   Bounced from the playoffs in the Western Conference finals last
year, the Stars have made it to the Stanley Cup finals this season
but find themselves down 1-0 in the best-of-seven series to the
East's seventh seed, the Buffalo Sabres. Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock
went as far to say, ``We're in a desperate situation,'' going into
Game 2 tonight at Reunion Arena, and it would be hard to dispute
that.
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars lost Game 1 of the conference finals to Colorado
before coming back to win in seven games, Dallas' 3-2 overtime loss
to the Sabres on Tuesday night was stuffed with bad omens. The
Stars controlled the play, in part because of 10 power plays. But
37 shots on Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek weren't enough and Dallas
lost a home game in which it seemed well in control. What happens
when Buffalo plays well?
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock's words aside, Dallas players aren't showing any
panic. Joe Nieuwendyk even said, ``The great thing about these
series is, over time, the best team prevails.''
</P>
<P>
   If that smacks of arrogance, the Stars are convinced that as
much as they did right Tuesday, they could've done more. Either
that or they just didn't want to show that Hasek's wizardry was
getting to them psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   Right winger Mike Keane: ``I'm not talking about Hasek. We just
have to find a way to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Mike Modano: ``Hasek's their best player. We have to find
a way to expose their best player _ that's how you win games. When
we played Colorado, we found a way to get to (Peter) Forsberg. When
we played St. Louis, we had to get to (Al) MacInnis. We have to put
traffic in front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock: ``(Hasek) had an easy night. I don't care how many
shots we had. He didn't have to stop any second or third chances.
We have to make life a lot more difficult for him. I don't mean
take a run at him. I mean we have to get the puck in the right
areas and get him out of position.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to diminish thoughts that Tuesday's game was a colossal
upset, Hitchcock said, ``We've been on the right side of one-goal
games all year. But it's been a very fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek said he got a cramp in his hip, mostly from exhaustion,
after a save on Pat Verbeek in overtime just before the winning
goal by Jason Woolley. Warm conditions and continual Stars power
plays wore on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played before in such a hot building,'' Hasek said.
``I was very tired. In the overtime, before the winning goal, I
stopped Verbeek and I got a cramp. When the game was over, I tried
to take a couple of steps (toward his celebrating teammates at the
other end of the ice). But then I fell, and I thought, `That's
enough,' and I left the ice. I don't remember ever being so tired.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
