<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9498 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERMITAGE-MUSEUM-ART_     06-09 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERMITAGE-MUSEUM-ART_2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HERMITAGE SEES THE FUTURE, AND IT WORKS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13)
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Ira Konorskaya, a Ukrainian schoolgirl,
was making a tour of the Hermitage musuem with her grandmother
recently when she spotted a bank of computers at the museum's new
educational center. Curious, she took a seat and within minutes was
intently dragging images from a painting by the 16th- century
Venetian master Titian across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandmother couldn't drag her away; it was the first time
Ira, 12 years old, had ever had hands-on access either to a
computer or to the Italian Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   For a museum that has miraculously survived the 20th century
(two revolutions, two wars and Russia's messy eight-year-long lurch
toward democracy), the Hermitage, keeper of one of the world's
greatest art collections, is doing its best to get a jump on the
coming millennium.
</P>
<P>
   This week, it will introduce what experts describe as one of the
best digital libraries on a museum Internet site, put together by
IBM technicians working with the latest scanning technology, some
of it designed especially for IBM's $2 million Hermitage project.
</P>
<P>
   For openers, more than 2,000 masterpieces and treasures from the
Hermitage collection of 2.5 million works of art will be available
on the Internet site (www.hermitagemuseum.org) this week, all of
them of the highest available quality.
</P>
<P>
   The educational center _ up and running since last August _ has
already proved a big hit with visitors, schoolchildren in
particular, with some 150 visitors a day logging onto the center's
six computers. And a novel information system, centered on four
electronic kiosks, is also being inaugurated this month, offering
visitors a multimedia guide through the maze of state rooms and
corridors that is the Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a visitor who wants to go from the Rembrandt room
to the Impressionists is given a printout with a map and a
description of all the artworks to be seen en route.
</P>
<P>
   Housed along the banks of the Neva River in a palace built by
the Czars for themselves and their art collection, the Hermitage
has proved suprisingly adept at adapting to modernity. Besides the
two-year-old IBM project, which has given the Hermitage an edge in
the rush to virtual viewing, the museum has already proved itself a
leader among Russian cultural institutions in anticipating a new
role for itself, and its visitors.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, the museum has installed a well-staffed
information booth, a significant step out of the Soviet past when
visitors had to pry information out of surly gatekeepers. Soon the
museum plans to shift its main entrance altogether, back onto
Palace Square, once the main entryway into the Czar's Winter
Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a traditional museum, located in a palace with many
windows,'' said Mikhail Piotrovsky, 54, the museum's urbane and
dynamic director, who took over in 1992 and occupies the office
that was previously held by his father, Boris Piotrovsky, for
almost a quarter century. ``But we have to be inventive.''
</P>
<P>
   Necessity has already backed the Hermitage into a corner. Since
the collapse of communism and with it the Soviet system of mass
tourism, the number of visitors to the museum has dropped
significantly, from almost 4 million a year at its peak to 1.7
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are money problems that continue to nag the
Hermitage, just as they do all other state-supported institutions
in an economically hard-pressed Russia. ``Russia is a country of
extremes,'' said Piotroskvy. ``When we have no money, we really
have no money.''
</P>
<P>
   In Soviet times, the government plugged all gaps in the
Hermitage budget. Now the museum itself has to come up with about a
third of its annual $12 million budget, through tickets, licensing,
compensation for exhibitions taken abroad and, increasingly,
donations.
</P>
<P>
   The government's share, when it comes, comes slowly and
irregularly: so far this year, the museum has received only 60
percent of what is owed by Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two ways of dealing with difficult times,''
Piotrovsky said. ``One is complaining, which is very important. The
other is to have a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Piotrovsky's ambitions is a $150 million expansion plan
that would extend the museum across the vast Palace Square to the
handsome General Staff Building, next to the Victory Arch.
</P>
<P>
   With its five stories and courtyard, the 19th-century building
would provide an additional 430,000 square feet, of which 60
percent would be reserved for exhibitions and 40 percent for a
commercially run entertainment complex that would house bars,
restaurants and even a movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For this and other more mundane projects, the Hermitage has
joined a well trod international circuit looking for private
donations. The Hermitage being the Hermitage _ a museum on a par
with the Louvre in Paris and the Metropolitan in New York _ it has
been relatively successful. Besides the IBM grant, the Hermitage
has received donations from Honeywell, Coca-Cola and supporters in
Japan and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dutch money that paid for the recent renovations in the
room housing the Hermitage's stunning Rembrandt collections,
improving the lighting and fixing the ceilings. ``We sometimes joke
that we should move the Rembrandts from room to room,'' Piotrosvky
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is good and bad about the donation system is that people
only want to give to specific projects,'' he added. ``Nobody wants
to give money for the sewage system.'' But even there, he said, the
Hermitage has benefited from a Scandanivian consortium that is
using the museum as a pilot project to help St. Petersburg better
control its effluents into the Bay of Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last years, the Hermitage has also carried on its
regular maintenance, paying closer attention to security and
atmosphere control. Here, oddly enough, the biggest concern is not
the humidity that hangs over St. Petersburg's watery landscape but
the dryness that comes from a central heating system installed in
this century.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, fundraising has begun for the grand expansion
plan. The effort has been aided by a handsome, spiral-bound
brochure explaining the proposed restoration clearly and in detail,
a rarity for Russian cultural projects.
</P>
<P>
   Piotrovsky understands that the best approach is to proceed one
step at a time. By the end of the year, he hopes to complete the
restoration of 10 exhibition rooms in the new building in time to
house a show on the Empire style in France and Russia, titled ``In
the Shadow of the Eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Donations or no donations, we will do it,'' he said. In
Russia's close-knit cultural elite, many say that if anyone can do
it, Piotrovsky can. ``He is a great communicator and
intellectual,'' said Mihail Kamensky, deputy director of the
Pushkin Museum of Fine Arts in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hermitage deserves the best,'' Kamensky said. ``Were it in
New York or Washington, all the big millionaires would come
together and invest all that is needed. What is problematic in
Russia is that no matter how great the museum, and how valuable its
cultural heritage, the state is not able to invest an adequate
amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, private benefactors cannot be enticed with tax
deductions, as they are in the United States. ``We are only
starting to come closer to the real techniques of fundraising,''
Kamensky said.
</P>
<P>
   Piotrovksy's enthusiasm for the Hermitage's new Internet site
fits neatly into his view for a more open, more accessible museum.
Today, only five percent of the museum's collection is on display:
he would like to expand that to 20 percent. Eventually, through the
Internet, he hopes to make the whole collection available.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is democracy when everything is available,'' he said. A
recent convert to computer technology, Piotrovsky has kept a close
eye on the project; he was the one who spurred IBM's top image
makers to come up with a newly patented watermark, so deeply
embedded in the computerized image as to be invisible, that would
prevent its being printed out and used for commerical purposes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there has been little audible grumbling from Russia's
cultural purists. ``Art scholars in Russia are either computer
imbeciles _ which means they don't know anything about this _ or
they are computer-advanced, in which case they are positive,'' said
Kamensky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
