<HEADLINE>
DOW RETREATS; NASDAQ POSTS SOLID GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A late surge of interest in computer-related stocks
lifted the Nasdaq composite index to a solid gain Wednesday while
the Dow Jones industrial average continued to slide.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed performance came as long-term interest rates climbed
further and Wall Street braced for two major economic reports, on
retail sales and producer prices, scheduled to be released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists said that the market had decided that the Federal
Reserve was more likely than not to raise the overnight lending
rate between banks when its policy committee meets at the end of
the month. The case was largely sealed by hawkish comments on
Tuesday by two central-bank policy makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The noises coming out of the Fed are that they're going to
raise rates,'' said Charles J. Pradilla, chief investment
strategist at S.G. Cowen Securities.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that for the markets the crucial issue was whether
the Fed acts in the wake of benign readings on sales and inflation
or whether these suggest such a strong economy that multiple
increases could be in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot is in the balance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Long-term interest rates continued to climb Wednesday. The price
of the benchmark 30-year bond fell 13/32, to 89 12/32. Its yield,
which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 6.02 percent, from
5.99 percent on Tuesday, the first close above 6 percent in more
than a year. The yield on the Treasury's two-year note climbed to
5.61 percent from 5.55 percent, and the yield on the 10-year bond,
against which home mortgages are typically priced, moved to 5.87
percent from 5.82 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in computer chips, semiconductors and other
high-technology stocks that dominate Nasdaq pushed the index up
44.79 points, or 1.8 percent, to 2,519.35. Analysts attributed much
of this to Intel's announcement that it would begin using larger
silicon wafers in production by 2002 and to a report of improved
prospects for industry sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dow, laced with shares of companies more closely tied to
the business cycle, slumped 75.35 points, or seven-tenths of a
percent, to 10,690.29. A two-and-a-half-percentage-point divergence
between the Nasdaq and the Dow is unusual, even in the volatile
markets that have prevailed for much of the last year.
</P>
<P>
   According to Limresearch.com, an analytical firm, the divergence
between the Dow and Nasdaq has reached two percentage points only
five times: Dec. 31, 1998; three times in 1982, and once in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly a two-tier market,'' said David G. Dietze,
president of Point View Financial Services in Summit, N.J., adding
that any discernible trend would be suspect because of relatively
light volume. On the New York Stock Exchange, only 662 million
shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which includes
many Nasdaq and Dow issues, finished virtually unchanged. It inched
up 1.31 points, or one-tenth of a percent, to 1,318.64.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks were among the weakest group after US Airways
warned of lower second-quarter profits, following a similar warning
by UAL on Friday, and analysts lowered estimates for Continental.
The biggest declines were 3[ each for Continental and Delta Air
Lines, to 37 9/16 and 56 13/16, respectively, while UAL lost 1
15/16, to 61~.
</P>
<P>
   Military issues also stumbled, dragged down by a profit warning
from Lockheed Martin, which skidded 5 9/16, to 34~. United
Technologies fell 2 5/16, to 64 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble, which said its reorganization would cost
15,000 jobs, fell 2 9/16, to 92\. Philip Morris rose 1 13/16, to
40~, benefiting from a higher rating by a Morgan Stanley analyst
who cited an improved legal climate.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer was a casualty in a mixed drug group, sliding 6 1/16, to
104 15/16, after the Food and Drug Administration said use of the
company's Trovan antibiotic should be limited.
</P>
<P>
   In the resurgent technology sector, Texas Instruments jumped 6],
to 123]; Broadcom rose 6{, to 108}; Micron Technology increased 3
15/16, to 43[; Intel was up 1 7/16, to 53[; Hewlett-Packard climbed
2[, to 92 11/16; Microsoft rose 2 15/16, to 82 5/16, and Amazon.com
was up 2 7/16, to 114.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still want to own stocks,'' said Timothy M. Ghriskey,
senior portfolio manager at the Dreyfus Corp. ``But it's a very
dangerous market for momentum players _ people who go after the
latest trends _ who tend to get whipsawed'' by daily swings.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outpaced advancing ones by 1,555 to 1,392 on
the Big Board, with 52 stocks making new highs and 65 new lows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
