<HEADER>
A9511 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEPERO-ART-ANTIQUES-$     06-09 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPERO-ART-ANTIQUES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTERS AND TOYS: BACK TO A FUTURIST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ The Italian painter and designer Fortunato
Depero came late to Futurism. Indeed, this energetic art style of
vivid palette and dynamic images was four years old when, in 1913,
Depero went to Rome to meet the founder of the movement, the poet
Filippo Tommaso Marinetti, and to see the Futurist art of Umberto
Boccioni and Giacomo Balla. The trip changed Depero's life.
</P>
<P>
   He had begun as a Symbolist but was so moved by how the artists'
images of speed, machines and violence captured the excitement of
the industrial age that he switched to Futurism.
</P>
<P>
   He adopted the themes Marinetti had outlined in a 1909 manifesto
calling for the creation of a new art to transform the world and
for the destruction of museums and libraries. By joining the
movement, Depero expanded the Futurist presence in design and the
decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   His swift ascent to the inner sanctum of the Futurists, and the
stunning variety of works he produced, are explored in ``Depero
Futurista Rome-Paris-New York, 1915-1932,'' an exhibition here at
the Wolfsonian museum of design, through July 26.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 160 items on view were produced before 1932, but
some date to the late 1940s. Aside from a chair and several books
from the Wolfsonian collection, the objects on view were lent by
the Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art of Trento and Rovereto,
towns 20 to 30 miles north of Verona in northern Italy near Fondo,
the village where Depero was born.
</P>
<P>
   But from earliest childhood until his death at 68 in 1960,
Depero lived mostly in Roverto, where he worked at the House of
Art, the studio, showcase and shop for his art and furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   While Depero's paintings and drawings were richly colored and
aswirl with abstract forms, they were also more imitative than
innovative. But painting with the Futurists led him to other art
forms at which he excelled.
</P>
<P>
   The flat imagery he mastered while working with Balla, his
mentor, adapted well to graphic art, a new idiom spawned by
Futurism. And the rocketlike pencils and robotic figures in his
paintings were images he later translated into posters and puppets.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition makes clear why even as early as 1915 Boccioni
was so amazed at Depero's huge output and the diversity of what he
made that he called him ``the tireless worker.'' In 1917, Depero
took on theater projects, doing sets and costume designs for Sergei
Diaghilev and marionettes for the Gorno dell Acqua Company of Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the late 1920s, when he came to New York, he did
magazine covers for Vanity Fair and Vogue and advertising for Venus
Pencils. Facile though he was at these skills and at designing
typography, billboards, furniture, toys and tapestries, he could no
longer pay the bills after the Depression began, in 1929. So he
returned to Italy in 1930. Several later drawings with Fascist
imagery are also included in the show.
</P>
<P>
   Depero's contributions even included manifestos and books, works
that were sometimes as poetic as they were political, and far less
militant than the revolutionary tracts of Marinetti.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1915 manifesto by Depero and Balla, ``The Futurist
Reconstruction of the Universe,'' they saw the world becoming more
oppressive and advocated a new, freer expression in the arts to
make it more joyful. ``We will give skeleton and flesh to the
invisible, the impalpable, the imponderable and the
imperceptible,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   They also wrote that toys were meant to accustom a child ``to
completely spontaneous laughter.'' The type of toys that will
inspire such a response, they wrote, would have to eliminate the
sort of ``grotesque imitation'' common in toy trains. They called
for more fantasy and mobility in toys.
</P>
<P>
   Depero practiced what he preached in the toys and marionettes he
produced; they always seem to be moving: bears and rhinoceroses
appear to lumber along, ballerinas to twirl and workmen to be
hammering.
</P>
<P>
   Depero accentuated the simulated movements by painting the parts
of toys in contrasting colors, exaggerating the limbs or other body
parts and using three or more figures all in a row. The figures on
view are reproductions, from the 1980s, of originals produced from
1918 to 1930.
</P>
<P>
   To Marianne Lamonaca, the curator at the Wolfsonian who
coordinated the exhibition, what proved most challenging in the
exhibition were the inconsistencies in his work. ``Depero speaks
about the toys as transformative objects that must move,'' she
said. ``But they never do.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more problematic was Depero's view of his art. It was
supposed to envision the future when, in fact, much of it was
rooted in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Futurism did not change the world, but it did produce brilliant
and vigorous artworks, at least in the first stage, which ended in
1915. It also proved a bust at bringing about the destruction of
museums and libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, Depero's last Futurist creation, and his most
ambitious, was a museum, financed by Rovereto, which he designed in
1957. When it opened two years later, the Fortunato Depero Museum
was hailed as the first Futurist Museum in Italy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
