<HEADLINE>
BIG D IS HOT FOR ICE HOCKEY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dallas this week is steeped in an ice fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   The summer solstice is still nearly two weeks away and daytime
temperatures already are crowding triple digits. The sidewalks are
searing enough to render chicken fat and humidity hangs like napalm
in the afternoon air.
</P>
<P>
   But, the weather doesn't have anything to do with this fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've become addicted to it,'' said Nancy Hanson, whose white
blouse reflected and amplified the blazing sunlight outside Reunion
Arena, where the building's exhaust fans strained to preserve the
only ice in town that seemed to matter. ``My husband got me
interested in it. He's from Duluth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson arrived two hours early Tuesday for the first game of the
National Hockey League's Stanley Cup Finals pitting the Dallas
Stars and Buffalo Sabres. She waited in wilting heat for an event
that seems oddly out of its habitat, like an animal that strayed
from the frozen north and found itself surrounded by a strange,
gawking species in short sleeves and sandals.
</P>
<P>
   For days, the buzz on the radio and in the newspapers has been
Dallas isn't a hockey town and, to most of the locals, the Stanley
Cup is just another big beer mug. The Stars have been in town since
1993 and until this week there were serious sports fans about who
couldn't name three of the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, this is not a hockey town,'' Jerry Sullivan of the
Buffalo News wrote. ``I was in the city for two hours without
finding one shred of evidence the Stanley Cup Finals would be
opening here the next night. No banners. No souvenir stands. The
newspaper honor box had a photo of Juan Gonzalez, the baseball
slugger. We popped on a sports radio station and the first words we
heard were, `Overall, this city doesn't care about hockey.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly true.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Stars arrived, hockey has been like fescue grass,
taking root in the shade cast by the NFL's Cowboys, baseball's
Rangers and the NBA's Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Fans such as Hanson have been addicted to the sport for only a
few years, but they are hooked hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the action,'' she said. ``It's fast-moving and it's a
double-skill sport. They have to play the game and skate at the
same time.''
</P>
<P>
   This year the team sold out 40 of its 41 regular-season games.
In the first two days of this week, nearly 10,000 people stood in
line for as long as an hour to get a look at the Stanley Cup on
display at the Museum of Modern Art, where Stars souvenirs were on
sale in the museum store and the restaurant's hot dogs were renamed
the Stanley Dog.
</P>
<P>
   It might not have been apparent to out-of-town sportswriters,
but here is one measure of Dallas' devotion to hockey: The word
outside the arena Tuesday was that some ticket holders were being
offered $1,000 or more for prime seats and even a roost in the
nosebleed section was worth $300.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever been to a game?'' said Tom Guidry, as a way of
explaining his passion. ``Crazy fans. Rabid fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most North Texas natives, Guidry didn't discover hockey
until the Stars came to town. He's seldom missed a televised game
since. (A minor-league team, the Blackhawks, never had much of a
following and faded several years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Billy and Monica Stark are season-ticket holders and have been
ardent fans for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun,'' Billy Stark said. ``A lot of people
around here still don't understand the game, but if you can follow
soccer, you can follow hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the shade of a small tree, they explained they
arrived at the arena two hours early to beat the traffic and take
in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away a barbecue catering service had set up a chow line
for early arrivals ($8 for a plate of brisket and two vegetables),
the sides of a trailer swung open to convert to a souvenir stand, a
sports radio station was broadcasting live and two tables were
manned by four volunteers painting fans' faces the team colors,
green and gold.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Cindy Markman earns money painting temporary tattoos
on the arms of nightclub patrons, but Tuesday, she was sketching
stars on children's cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started an hour ago and I've painted more than 40 already,''
she said. ``It's been really wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey might not reign in Dallas, but even a whiff of the
Stanley Cup has driven the hard-core followers into the open.
</P>
<P>
   Marliessa Clark, waiting in line at the Museum of Modern Art,
said she and her husband drove up from Hamilton, about 120 miles
southwest of Dallas, just to see the Stanley Cup. They couldn't get
tickets to the game, which the Sabres won 3-2 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband recently decided he's going to be a hockey fan,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Thursday night's game trailing the Sabres 1-0 in the
best-of-seven series, Dallas doesn't own the Cup, yet, but just
playing for it has given hockey new stature in town. If the Cup
stays, two or three players could even become household names.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
