</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKHEED EARNINGS DROP SHARPLY, SENDING SHARE PRICES DOWN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin Corp., the nation's largest military contractor,
has had a streak of bad luck in the air. Orders for its C-130J
cargo plane _ the one seen delivering arms and supplies to global
hot spots _ are sagging and its satellites have been launched, and
then flopped.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, these problems in the sky fell to the bottom line
when the company announced a sharp drop in expected earnings for
the next two years _ to about half of what most analysts had
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   This sudden, and somewhat unexpected, announcement sent Lockheed
shares plunging $5.5625, or more than 13 percent, to $34.875, a low
not seen in three years. Lockheed also said top executives in
several divisions were being shuffled and it was thinking about
shedding some noncore businesses to improve its performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've substantially reduced our financial outlook for 1999 and
2000,'' said Vance D. Coffman, Lockheed's chief executive. ``As
CEO, I'm acutely aware of the severity of the problem and the
damage it does to both our credibility and our reputation. I am
disappointed to report that the financial review we initiated in
April has uncovered some negative surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter of 1999, the company predicts a loss of
10 to 15 cents a share. For the whole year, Lockheed estimates it
will earn about $1.50 a share. That compares with earnings of $3.10
a share expected by analysts, according to First Call, which tracks
Wall Street forecasts. In 2000, Lockheed expects to earn $2.15 a
share, compared with the $3.39 a share forecast by analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let anyone tell you that the fact Lockheed revised its
earnings downward was a surprise,'' said Pierre A. Chao, an analyst
with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``It wasn't. But the magnitude was
a surprise. Regardless of whether you were a bull or a bear on this
stock, no one expected anything this big.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubel, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., added:
``It's not a surprise Lockheed missed its earnings targets again.
The size of the decline is arresting.''
</P>
<P>
   What lies behind Lockheed's dismal announcement is a tale of a
tough confluence of business and technology, politics and the
Pentagon budget. A big contributor to the lowered earnings
projections was cutbacks in orders for the C-130J cargo plane by
the Air Force and foreign nations. This accounted for 70 cents a
share in the 1999 earnings reduction and 26 cents a share in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by a tight military budget and facing conflicting
priorities for other airplanes, the Air Force has delayed purchases
of C-130J's, and other countries have fallen behind in their
orders, too. This means Lockheed will slow its production line to
16 to 19 planes a year instead of 24. The company has already cut
21 percent of its work force, or 2,000 employees, at its C-130J
plant in Marietta, Ga. On the political side, the resignation from
Congress of former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, whose district
included Marietta, removed a powerful ally in Congress to keep
money flowing to this project.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there were the satellites that failed instead of flew.
Four satellite launchings have failed over the last eight months _
a costly and perplexing setback. With names like Titan, Proton and
Atlas, the satellite program has not been anything close to what
those mighty names suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our well-publicized launch failures have led to major changes
at the head of those business sectors,'' Coffman said. ``Our new
team is dedicated toward restoring mission success.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be a difficult task. ``The truth is that no one knows
what the problem with Lockheed's space program is,'' said Loren
Thompson, a military analyst at the Lexington Institute in
Arlington, Va. ``It's traceable to different specific failures
rather than a pattern of failures, and this makes it difficult to
anticipate when the program will get back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Thompson remained somewhat sanguine. ``If there's a
silver lining, Lockheed has gone from being fairly optimistic to
being brutally honest, and it is still probably the best positioned
of the major defense companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, and under previous management, Lockheed
diversified into a complex conglomerate, expanding beyond military
and aerospace into missiles and space, electronics, energy and the
environment and information technology. Yesterday, Coffman signaled
that the company might begin to narrow its focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense and aerospace is our core business,'' Coffman said,
adding that some noncore businesses would be shed through sales,
joint ventures or public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   He also said further management changes would be in the offing
if results did not improve. ``I am instilling a culture of
accountability that is very much different than it has been in the
past in this corporation,'' Coffman said. ``We owe it to our
shareholders and selves to be accountable for our performance and
anything else is simply unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubel of Goldman said, ``It's encouraging management has stepped
up to change the culture of the company, but I think it's important
to watch how the company performs before investors buy the
shares.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
