<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   P&AMP;G to Cut 15,000 Jobs
</P>
<P>
   In a Global Reorganization In an effort to loosen its stiff
corporate culture and free up more cash for product development,
Procter &AMP; Gamble said that it would cut 15,000 jobs worldwide _ or
13 percent of its work force _ close 10 plants and take $2 billion
in charges related to the reorganization. P&AMP;G also said that its
financial results for the current quarter would be flat and would
improve only modestly the next quarter. But Durk Jager, the
company's chief executive, nonetheless tried to assure analysts and
investors that the reorganization would spur future growth and save
about $900 million a year by 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Gains, but Dow Sputters
</P>
<P>
   A late surge of interest in computer-related stocks lifted the
Nasdaq composite index 44.79 points, or 1.8 percent, to 2,519.35.
But the Dow Jones industrial average slumped 75.35 points, or
seven-tenths of a percent, to 10,690.29. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index inched up 1.31 points, to 1,318.64.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Proposals Detailed
</P>
<P>
   Under sharp questioning by a Microsoft lawyer in the software
giant's antitrust trial, an IBM executive acknowledged that none of
the Microsoft contract proposals he read had stated that IBM must
stop shipping its OS/2 operating system to get a favorable price
for Windows. But the executive testified that the many sales and
promotion steps called for in the Microsoft proposal would have had
the ``effect of killing OS/2 in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   High-Speed Internet Network Set
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, Sun Microsystems and Cisco Systems are teaming up to
create a new wireless network to provide high-speed Internet
access. They envision consumers using cellular phones, pagers,
handheld computing and other wireless devices for tasks as diverse
as buying books to trading stocks on line.
</P>
<P>
   Cable and Wireless Wins Japan Bid
</P>
<P>
   Japan's first hostile takeover battle pitting a foreign suitor
against a domestic corporate titan ended in victory for the
outsider, Cable and Wireless of Britain, which gained enough
support to guarantee it majority control of International Digital
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Plans Cost-Saving Plants
</P>
<P>
   Intel, the largest maker of computer chips, plans to upgrade its
manufacturing plants to produce far more powerful processors. It
will reduce manufacturing costs by using silicon wafers that are 12
inches in diameter, compared with 8 inches now.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate to Buy CNA Business
</P>
<P>
   Allstate will buy the personal insurance business of CNA
Financial, expanding its business with independent insurance agents
who sell auto and homeowners' policies. Allstate will pay CNA $140
million in cash and commit as much as $950 million in new capital
to the business, as well as pay up to $110 million for use of the
CNA name. Allstate shares rose 68.75 cents to $38.6875, while CNA
fell 37.5 cents, to $42.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Rail Service Disruptions Reported
</P>
<P>
   Some shippers have begun reporting major disruptions in service,
including delayed trains and lost rail cars, since CSX and Norfolk
Southern took over Conrail on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sony to Sell Music at Kiosks
</P>
<P>
   Sony Music Entertainment announced a deal with Digital On-Demand
to let consumers buy music through in-store digital kiosks. They
will be able to choose from 4,000 albums, about half of Sony's
music catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs Says He Will Not Join Rival
</P>
<P>
   The day after resigning from CNN, business journalist Lou Dobbs,
who was the anchor of ``Moneyline News Hour,'' said he had no
intention of joining another network.
</P>
<P>
   No Deal Seen at Cathay Pacific
</P>
<P>
   Managers from Cathay Pacific Airways and representatives of the
Hong Kong airline's pilot union spent more than eight hours in pay
negotiations that industry analysts said were unlikely to avoid a
wave of pilot resignations and dismissals on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
