<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSBY-EXTORTION-NYT &LR;      06-09 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSBY-EXTORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION IN COSBY CASE IS OVERTURNED; RULING MEANS FREEDOM FOR
AUTUMN JACKSON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Pa.) (rk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal appeals court in Manhattan on Wednesday
overturned the conviction of Autumn Jackson, who went to prison for
threatening to tell a supermarket tabloid that she was Bill Cosby's
out-of-wedlock daughter unless he paid her $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by a three-judge panel of the Court of Appeals
raised the possibility of a new trial for Ms. Jackson, who has
already spent about 14 months in prison, and for two associates
whose convictions were also thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   It could also have broader legal significance, experts said, by
helping to clarify what constitutes an acceptable threat and what
constitutes blackmail or extortion.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that the jury should have been allowed to
consider whether Ms. Jackson believed she had a rightful claim to
the money in light of her claim that Cosby was her father. The
trial judge had told the jury that Ms. Jackson's belief was
irrelevant to whether she was guilty of extortion.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White, whose office prosecuted Ms. Jackson
and the two others in 1997, said that prosecutors were still
reviewing the opinion late Wednesday and had not reached a decision
about whether to appeal the new ruling or retry the case.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Ms. Jackson, meanwhile, said that they would seek to
have her released by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson, who was sentenced to 26 months in prison, has been
held at the Federal Correctional Institution at Dublin, Calif.,
near San Francisco. She had not yet learned of the ruling Wednesday
afternoon because she was out of the prison on a work detail, said
one of her lawyers, Edward S. Zas.
</P>
<P>
   Cosby did not issue a statement Wednesday, but his lawyer,
Andrew D. Schau, said the actor would ``respect and support
whatever decision'' is reached by Ms. White.
</P>
<P>
   The original trial, in the summer of 1997, captured national
attention because of Cosby's role as victim. The evidence showed
that Ms. Jackson made her $40 million demand on the same day that
Cosby's son, Ennis, was killed in California, though there was no
connection between the two incidents.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Cosby, who had built an enormous reputation
through television and books as a loving father and a symbol of
moral values, denied being Ms. Jackson's father but admitted to
having had a brief affair with her mother and to having paid the
mother more than $100,000 over the years to keep the affair secret.
</P>
<P>
   The defense contended that Ms. Jackson's conduct was not illegal
because she honestly believed she was the actor's daughter and
therefore had a claim against him.
</P>
<P>
   In upsetting the convictions, Judge Amalya L. Kearse, writing
for a three-judge panel of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ,
said that not all threats to reputation amounted to extortion.
</P>
<P>
   She said the jury should have been allowed to consider whether
Ms. Jackson believed she had a rightful claim to the money she was
demanding. At trial, Judge Barbara S. Jones of U.S. District Court
in Manhattan had instructed the jury that it made no difference
whether Ms. Jackson was Cosby's daughter or believed she had a
right to the money.
</P>
<P>
   Kearse noted, however, that even had the jury been given proper
instructions, the evidence was ``plainly sufficient'' to support
guilty verdicts against Ms. Jackson and her co-defendants because
the jury might have concluded her demands were too extreme, even of
a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Jackson were Cosby's child,'' Kearse wrote, ``a
rational jury could find that her demand, given her age (22), and
the amount ($40 million), did not reflect a plausible claim for
support.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling should help clarify the murky law on extortion, said
Leo Katz, a professor at the University of Pennsylvania Law School
and author of the book ``Ill-Gotten Gains: Evasion, Blackmail,
Fraud, and Kindred Puzzles of the Law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision will be treated as significant guidance as to
what sorts of threats you can make to get obligations met,'' Katz
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
