<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      06-09 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZONE BY ZONE: 1 DAYS TO SERBS' WITHDRAWAL AND OCCUPATION BY NATO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under the provisions of the Balkans military
agreement reached Wednesday, Yugoslavia is to withdraw its 40,000
troops from Kosovo along four designated routes within 11 days to
permit the rapid entry of a NATO security force into the besieged
province.
</P>
<P>
   The accord calls for an immediate cease-fire and divides Kosovo
into three zones for a four-stage withdrawal that tries to insure
an orderly pull-out and minimize the risk of clashes between
Yugoslav and NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   In the first stage, NATO is to suspend the 78-day air war if
Belgrade demonstrates within 24 hours of Wednesday's signing that
its forces in northern Kosovo, called Zone 3, are pulling out. The
allied military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, will decide whether
the Yugoslav forces are complying.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, all Yugoslav forces must leave Zone 1, a
V-shaped area in southern Kosovo that borders Albania and Macedonia
and runs up to Pristina, the provincial capital and headquarters
for the NATO peacekeeping force, which will be known as KFOR.
</P>
<P>
   By June 18, three days later, all Yugoslav troops in Zone 2, in
central Kosovo, must leave. And by June 20, all remaining Yugoslav
forces must have withdrawn, refraining along the way ``from
committing any hostile or provocative acts of any type against any
person in Kosovo,'' according to the five-page accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sound agreement that meets all of NATO's demands,''
said Defense Secretary William Cohen on Wednesday night at the
Pentagon. ``The real test will be whether the Serbs will live up to
this agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement and its two-page attachment grant sweeping
authority to the British officer heading the allied force, Lt. Gen.
Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international security force (KFOR) commander is the final
authority regarding interpretation of this agreement and the
security aspects of the peace settlement it supports,'' the accord
says. ``His determinations are binding on all parties and
persons.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord also gives Jackson the authority ``to do all that he
judges necessary and proper, including the use of military force,''
to carry out the mission.
</P>
<P>
   With a Yugoslav military withdrawal apparently imminent, the
first of 7,000 U.S. troops who are to join the 48,000-soldier
allied force prepare to move toward the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,900 U.S. marines on ships in the Aegean are to begin
landing at Salonika, Greece, at daybreak Thursday, Pentagon
officials said. The marines will drive north into Macedonia to
staging areas near its capital, Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 1,700 U.S. soldiers now in Albania will begin
moving overland into Macedonia at first light on Thursday, Pentagon
officials said. An advanced Army command unit with 200 troops is to
fly overnight to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   All the U.S. forces should be in place within five days, a
Pentagon official said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav forces that are to withdraw will assemble at
designated points and then travel along four routes on which NATO
has guaranteed safe passage.
</P>
<P>
   As they withdraw, Yugoslav forces will be responsible for
marking and clearing minefields, booby traps and other obstacles.
The accord requires the Yugoslav military to provide detailed
records, positions and descriptions of all mines, unexploded bombs
and other possible hazards within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon and allied officials have underscored that one of the
their troops' main jobs at the start will be to clear mines that
could hurt NATO troops and thousands of refugees returning home.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen indicated that refugees would be kept from returning until
the security forces could insure their safety. ``We hope to get
them back as quickly as we can, but as safely as we can,'' Cohen
said. ``Safety will be the primary driving factor here.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also calls for a 15-mile buffer zone from the
Kosovo border inward that is to be free from surface-to-air missile
batteries, and a three-mile buffer zone in which there are to be no
Yugoslav ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an upbeat assessment from Cohen and other allied
officials, the military agreement has enough ambiguity to cause
possible problems or confusion.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one provision requires that for the bombing pause
to take effect, Yugoslav ``forces located in Zone 3 will have
vacated'' within 24 hours of the agreement. Taken literally, that
would mean all the Yugoslav troops in that zone now and those that
would pass through it from the south would have only until Thursday
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said however that in this case they are
simply looking for a demonstrable withdrawal that shows Belgrade is
dealing in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision allows the Yugoslav military six days from
Wednesday to withdraw from Zone 1, in southern Kosovo. But NATO is
keen to move in its forces as soon as possible after approval of a
United Nations Security Council resolution backing the accord,
which could happen Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Allied commanders do not want to bump into Serbian troops on
their way out, but they also do not want what the agreement terms
``a security gap,'' which Yugoslavs fear could be exploited by the
guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army and which foreign
diplomats fear might be used by the Serbs in some unspecified way.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this will be General Jackson's call on the ground,''
a senior Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   The allies will use a wide range of technology to monitor the
withdrawal, from spy satellites to unmanned drones to a special
plane, Jstars, that tracks the movements of large troop masses on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But senior U.S. officials said it may be impossible to detect _
or stop _scattered violence or even atrocities committed by Serbian
forces as they pull out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly it's very difficult to verify 100 percent on any
agreement here,'' Gen. Joseph Ralston, the vice chairman of the
U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, told reporters Wednesday night. ``You
have to rely upon, certainly, the intentions of the people involved
and use all the evidence that you've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
