<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MOELLER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOELLER HAS FOND OPEN MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- Terry Moeller will be like millions of golf fans who
tune in to watch next week's U.S. Open at Pinehurst, but his
interest will run deeper than most because he's been there.
</P>
<P>
   It was 33 years ago that Moeller, head professional at Santa
Anita Golf Course, played in the U.S. Open at Olympic Golf Club,
where Billy Casper beat a fading Arnold Palmer. And it was six
years later that he competed in the Open at Pebble Beach, where
Jack Nicklaus hit his legendary one-iron off the flagstick on the
17th hole and won his third Open championship.
</P>
<P>
   Moeller said the passage of time has faded some of his memories
of those events, but others remain vivid -- like being inducted
into the Army two weeks after the '66 Open, going to Vietnam, being
shot and surviving through six operations in four countries in 52
days. He still suffers from lower back pain and has shrapnel in his
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He also remembers being around the likes of Tony Lema, Tommy
Jacobs and George Knudsen in 1966, then watching Casper rally from
seven strokes behind to catch a fading Palmer in a stunning upset.
Moeller said Casper never has received the credit he deserved,
despite shooting an impressive 32 on the back nine to tie Palmer in
Sunday's final round. He beat him in a playoff the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 33 years, people have been writing and talking about how
Palmer collapsed at Olympic,'' Moeller said. ``Every time I hear
that, I keep saying, `Wait a minute.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moeller also remembers hearing Nicklaus praise the shot-making
abilities of his good friend, Cesar Sanudo, after the third round
of the '72 tournament. Nicklaus told ABC television's Jim McKay
that it was one of the most impressive rounds he had ever seen from
tee to green, but Sanudo could not make a putt and finished with a
78.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm listening to them in back of the 18th green,'' Moeller,
who turns 53 in October, said, ``and Nicklaus is saying, `I just
saw a round of golf where I don't think a human being could strike
any shot any better.' He had hit every green in regulation, except
the par-5 second hole, and he was on that green in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, `This is about a guy I grew up with; this is
great. What a charge.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moeller, who failed to make the cut in each Open, is expecting
difficult conditions for next week's tournament at Pinehurst, only
because they have been that way in the Open for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to recognize the difference between any golf
tournament and the U.S. Open,'' Moeller said. ``It's almost like
soldiers going into combat, the difference between fun and fear.
It's played on a different golf course each year, but they all have
severe similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are slick and fast, the sand traps are as wide and
as deep as bomb craters, and the fairways are so narrow you can use
them to conduct sobriety tests. The rough alongside each fairway
and around each green is jungle deep. It's just grown thatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an Open, you must play defensively for pars just to protect
yourself from disaster on each hole. In the Open, there are 30,000
people out there, and they're all waiting for terrible things to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Moeller said he has no second thoughts about not giving the pro
tour a try. He tried to qualify for the Open in 1980 at Industry
Hills, but barely broke 80. The disappointing round solidified his
worst fears that he wasn't good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having grown up in San Diego, where there were so many good
players, I just knew I could play OK, but not at that level,'' he
said. ``Golf has been very good to me. I still continue to enjoy
it, and it's fun to get up and come here every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have it and I knew it. There's nothing wrong
with being marginal. I've had a lot of fun being marginal in my
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
