<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9534 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      06-09 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS COMPLETE SWEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Among his other talents, it may now be said that
Pedro Martinez can also raise the dead. He just couldn't save the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   With Olympic Stadium energized by the return of Martinez _ who
judging by the reception he got here Wednesday night was as popular
in this town as Rocket Richard, Jean Beliveau, and Ken Dryden
before he was traded _ the Expos hammered the Red Sox, 13-1,
completing a hat trick of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos, playing before a crowd of 19,012 that was bigger than
the last two combined, swept the three-game set from the Sox,
outscoring Boston, 26-4.
</P>
<P>
   They sent the Sox, who were outhit 14-5, to their fifth straight
defeat, the longest losing streak in more than a year for the Sons
of Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   They ended a nine-game winning streak for Martinez (11-2), who
hadn't lost since April 15 but was lifted after a yield of four
runs and six hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   And the night took an even worse turn before it was over, as the
Expos added an eight-run insult in the eighth inning against three
relievers _ Mark Portugal, Mark Guthrie, and John Wasdin. Guthrie
gave up a home run to an Expos pitcher Guillermo Mota, a converted
minor league shortstop who went deep in his first official at-bat.
Wasdin, who was taken deep in blowing a save in the opener here,
gave up a home run to the first batter he faced, Manny Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The cheers began for Martinez when he was shown warming up on
the video scoreboard. The first standing ovation came when he took
the mound, which elicited a wave from the Sox pitcher. There was
another ovation when he came to bat for the first time, and even
some polite clapping when he failed to put down a bunt.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of the left-field bleachers, where they were
tracking Martinez's ``K's'' as if they were sitting on Van Ness
Street in Boston, fans unfurled a huge blue-and-white banner
reading, ``Welcome Back, Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez clearly basked in the attention before the game, when
he deviated from his usual routine on days he starts. He was out on
the field, chatting amiably with fans and field workers, signing
autographs. When he pitched for the Expos, he always took batting
practice the day before he pitched. Wednesday, he took BP, and
behind the cage scolded Montreal's young star Vladimir Guerrero for
his slow home run trot the night before after taking Tim Wakefield
deep.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Martinez would deliver that message even more forcefully,
buzzing his friend with an eye-level fastball with the first pitch
he threw Guerrero in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Expos manager Felipe Alou scoffed at the idea that Martinez
would find it hard to pitch in the midst of the lovefest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be difficult for him,'' Alou said. ``Pedro's got
something good going, and he's also the guy who is expected to stop
a losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro's no fool. He's a responsible man and a competitive
pitcher. He understands what's expected of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou's words rang true as Martinez breezed through the first
three innings, striking out four and allowing just one base runner,
Shane Andrews, who walked. But the veneer of invincibility cracked
in the fourth, when Jose Vidro lined a double to the
right-center-field gap to open the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rondell White bounced a ground-ball single up the middle,
scoring Vidro with the game's first run. Orlando Merced was retired
on a tapper in front of the plate, White advancing to second, and
Guerrero pulled an outside pitch through the left side for an RBI
single to make it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Since giving up three runs in the eighth inning against Tampa
Bay in his second start April 10, Martinez had not allowed as many
as two runs in an inning in his next 10 starts, a span of 77 2/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, he did it twice, as the Expos widened their
lead to 4-0 in the sixth. White bounced a one-out single and went
to third as Merced doubled into the right-field corner. Martinez
elected to give an intentional walk to Guerrero, the first he's
issued this season, but rookie catcher Michael Barrett crossed up
that strategy by lining an 0-and-2 pitch into center for a two-run
single.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who reached double figures in strikeouts (10) for the
44th time in his career, ninth time this season, and 17th time as a
member of the Red Sox, was lifted for Portugal at the start of the
seventh. It was just the third time in 13 starts that he has not
pitched more than six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, meanwhile, were held scoreless for 15 consecutive
innings, from the time they scored a first-inning run Tuesday
against rookie Dan Smith until they broke through in the seventh
against Mike Thurman, a 25-year-old righthander who came into the
game with exactly six big league wins in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox showed a little more patience against Thurman than they
did Smith, but were victimized by some terrific Expos defense and
their own penchant to hit line drives directly at a Montreal
fielder, six times in the first eight innings. Mike Stanley, who
hit a towering drive inches foul in the sixth that could have been
a tying home run, followed with another drive into the gap in
right-center, where White crashed into the fence making a leaping
catch.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Trot Nixon opened the eighth with a smash that was
smothered by first baseman Ryan McGuire, who flipped to Thurman
covering. But Troy O'Leary, who came into the game in the seventh
in a double switch when Portugal entered, singled and scored on a
double by Jose Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman came out of the game to an ovation grander than any
afforded Martinez, and reliever Mota set down Jeff Frye and Nomar
Garciaparra to end the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
