<SLUG> BC-WHITTAKER-MERGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITTAKER'S BOARD OKS MERGER WITH BRITISH MEGGITT PLC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY _ Officials of aerospace specialist Whittaker Corp.
said that the company has agreed to be bought by a British defense
contractor for $380 million in cash and debt.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of 450-employee Whittaker said the proposed purchase
by Meggitt PLC, based in Wimborne, England, will help both
companies leverage their aerospace strengths. Simi Valley-based
Whittaker makes valves and fire-detection equipment while the
larger Meggitt specializes in aviation electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Meggitt spokesman Richard Wool said his employers do not plan to
lay off any Whittaker workers once the purchase is complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've bought an ongoing business with great growth
potential,'' Wool said, adding that when the sale is closed
Whittaker will operate as a wholly owned subsidiary. It is unclear,
however, whether the Whittaker corporate headquarters will remain
in Southern California, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker spokesman John Ottosaid that in the coming weeks
Meggitt officials will consider that question and other ways to
``maximize their investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Though approved by both companies' board of directors, the deal
must still be approved by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were enthusiastic about the proposed purchase, which
will pay stockholders $28 for each of their shares. ``It's a pretty
decent price,'' said Brett Hendrickson at B. Riley &AMP; Co. in Los
Angeles. ``I think if you told shareholders six months ago they'd
get $28 a share, they'd have been very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, financier Michael Tennenbaum in December offered to buy
Whittaker for $208 million, or $18.50 per share. Tennenbaum
reportedly increased his offer a few weeks later by an undisclosed
amount, but his offer was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker shares closed at $27.50 on Wednesday, up 62.5 cents.
More than 2 million shares traded hands, more than 60 times the
typical daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker has been on a roll of late, reporting earnings of
$48.5 million for 1998, compared with a loss of $163.6 million in
1997. Wednesday the firm reported second-quarter earnings of $8.9
million on sales of $40.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
