<HEADER>
A9544 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRIT     06-09 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV MILITARY AGREES TO LET FORCE LED BY NATO GENERAL OCCUPY
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs 4th and 5th grafs for clarifications; subs 13th graf to
insert KFOR in Clinton quote) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMANOVO, Macedonia _ The Yugoslav military on Wednesday night
acceded to an agreement that will permit a military force commanded
by a NATO general with sweeping powers to occupy Kosovo, clearing
the way to an end to the Western alliance's first war.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, signed at a French helicopter base not far from
the border of Kosovo, was immediately approved by NATO leaders
meeting in Brussels. The agreement gave NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana the authority to suspend bombing once the military
verified that the Serbian-dominated army, police and paramilitary
units had begun to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials have already reported detecting
preparations for a withdrawal after nearly 11 weeks of bombing, and
the air campaign could be suspended as soon as late Thursday or
Friday morning, an official here said, as long as the Serbs keep
their pledges and begin to pull out.
</P>
<P>
   The first of nearly 50,000 NATO troops will then move into
Kosovo, replacing the retreating Serbian forces as they abandon
their positions and head north. The Serbs will have 11 days to
fully pull out or face a resumption of bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the province will be ringed by a five-kilometer
buffer zone (about three miles) and divided into five sectors, each
under the charge of a major power. NATO is to provide for the safe
return of hundreds of thousands of Albanians who have either fled
the country or been driven from their homes and are hiding in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, the British officer who led the
negotiations here, will command the international peacekeepers,
with the power to use whatever military might he deems necessary to
enforce the peace, insure the Serbian withdrawal and keep Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's troops from returning to Kosovo in
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is tragic that intransigence has made it necessary for the
international community to resort to air strikes in order to reach
a settlement,'' Jackson said after emerging from a camouflage tent
at the base here at 9:45 p.m. ``However, NATO's resolve in
conducting a sustained air campaign has finally achieved this
agreement, and now is the time to look ahead,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement on the military details of Yugoslavia's withdrawal
from its southern province, cherished as a symbol of Serbian
history and culture, came a week after Milosevic's government
agreed in broad terms to all of NATO's demands. Those included the
withdrawal of all Serbian forces, the intervention of a NATO-led
peacekeeping force and the return of the Kosovo Albanians who fled
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In a compromise resolving one of the last, most nettlesome
disputes in the talks here, NATO agreed on the 11-day period to
complete the withdrawal of nearly 40,000 soldiers and police
officers from the province, even though Milosevic's government
agreed last week to do so in only a week. The Yugoslav delegation
here had asked for 17 days.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen on Wednesday night warned that
if Milosevic ordered his commanders to drag their heels or
otherwise violate the accord, the air campaign would resume in full
ferocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the event there's any reversal of their activities, in the
event there's any evidence that they intend to simply try to bog
this down in some other way, then we made it very clear, the
document makes it very clear, the pause will not longer be in
effect,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton spoke cautiously, perhaps
mindful of the week-long delay in nailing down the terms of the
Serbian withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement reached today by NATO and Serbian military
officials is another important step toward achieving our objectives
in Kosovo,'' he said. ``It lays out the details to meet the
essential conditions for peace: the rapid, orderly withdrawal of
all Serb forces from Kosovo and the deployment of an international
security force, called KFOR, with NATO at its core, which means a
unified NATO chain of command so the Kosovars can return home
safely.''
</P>
<P>
   But how long that will take - along with myriad questions about
the future of the Kosovo Liberation Army and its armed struggle for
independence _ remained unclear in spite of Wednesday night's
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the return of refugees has become one of NATO's
fundamental objectives in the wake of the bombing campaign, NATO
hopes to hold off a rush of refugees pouring into Kosovo until its
forces have made it safer. In addition to land mines and booby
traps left behind, a major concern of NATO commanders is the
possibility that at least some Serbian soldiers and police officers
will simply shed their uniforms and remain in Kosovo with weapons,
ready to harass NATO troops or returning refugees, the official
here said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the six-page agreement signed here Wednesday night
explicitly authorizes a resumption of the bombing if the Serbs
violate the timetable for withdrawal, it is not clear how NATO
could respond to low-level menacing of its troops.
</P>
<P>
   Another major concern is the willingness of the Kosovar Albanian
rebels to abide by the agreement, which calls for them to disband
as an organized force and turn over their heavy weapons. Clinton
said the alliance had contacted members of the force, the Kosovo
Liberation Army, and received assurances that they would not attack
retreating Serbian forces or try to seize the territory they
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9545 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRIT     06-09 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KUMANOVO, Macedonia: they abandon.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This will not be an easy operation and it will take time,''
Jackson said. ``I fully understand the wishes of the refugees to
return home quickly, and I promise that KFOR will do its utmost to
ensure this is done as soon and as safely as possible.'' The
acronym refers to the peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's agreement came after a final 24 hours of talks
that came perilously close to collapse once again. At one point,
they appeared to break down completely, when the Yugoslav
delegation, led by Col. Gen. Svetozar Marjanovic, abruptly left the
helicopter base here late Wednesday afternoon, saying they needed
to consult with authorities in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But the delegation made it only as far as a border post north of
here, in Serbia itself. After telephone discussions with
authorities in Belgrade, the delegation returned to the base an
hour after they left, and the talks resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 24 hours after this latest round began Tuesday night,
Jackson and Marjanovic signed the agreement in what one official
described as a subdued, unceremonious end to five days of wrangling
over the details of the Serb withdrawal. They did not shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to avoid the appearance of capitulating to NATO's demands,
the Yugoslav delegation had insisted that a withdrawal not begin
until the United Nations Security Council, with Russia and China
wielding veto power, had given the peacekeeping force its formal
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talks today have been, on the military level, generally
constructive,'' said NATO's spokesman here, Lt. Col. Robin
Clifford, shortly after the delegation drove off in a convoy of
sedans and NATO vehicles Wednesday afternoon. ``But as you will
appreciate, some political issues have begun to impinge.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it became clear to the delegation Wednesday that the
Security Council would not force NATO to halt its bombing before a
withdrawal and would authorize the peacekeeping under the chapter
of the U.N. charter that permits the use of force, they relented,
according to a NATO official who attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials, who have described these talks not as
negotiations, but rather the ironing out of the details of last
week's agreement, said the final document reflected refinements the
foreign ministers of the seven major industrial nations, along with
Russia, had agreed to Tuesday in Germany. It also put the NATO-led
peacekeepers under the auspices of the United Nations, giving them
what Jackson called ``a clear, legal basis'' for the peacekeeping
force. Not only the Serbs, but also some NATO allies had insisted
on that.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly for the Serbs, the document does not mention NATO
explicitly. Neither did Marjanovic when he appeared before a group
of television journalists to announce the signing Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that the war has ended,'' Marjanovic said. ``It also
means that the policy of peace prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the NATO official who attended the talks said the mood
was far from celebratory, indicating that the alliance remained
wary of Milosevic and his intentions over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what he says,'' the official said. ``It's not what he
signs. It's what he does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2221EDT &QL; 
