<HEADER>
A9546 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACIFIC-PACIFIC_SFCHR     06-09 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-PACIFIC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pacific Exchange's New System Lagging  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Pacific Exchange's highly touted electronic stock trading
system is attracting far less business than expected, a serious
blow to the San Francisco bourse's push to revive its faltering
stock business.
<P>
   The 5-month-old system, called OptiMark, is handling an average
of about 1 million shares a day, not the 2 million to 5 million
projected for it at this stage, said OptiMark Chairman Bill Lupien.
Problems connecting OptiMark with the order processing systems of
large brokerage firms are behind the shortfall, Lupien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to build volume. There's no two ways about it,'' said
Lupien during an interview at an electronic brokerage conference in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lupien and exchange officials said they remain optimistic
that OptiMark will overcome shakedown problems and establish a
marketplace niche for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early in the game,'' said Lupien. ``And, from the
standpoint of what other new systems have done, our progress is
outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   One positive sign, Lupien said, is that OptiMark has boosted its
number of institutional clients from 114 when it was launched to
167 today.
</P>
<P>
   OptiMark is one of the keys to reviving Pacific's money-losing
stock business, which is now supported with surpluses produced by
its options exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``OptiMark is still a critical step to building our equity
business,'' said Pacific spokesman Dale Carlson. ``We're still
committed to the system.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Pacific's share of the stock-trading business
has slipped as large rivals like the New York Stock Exchange cut
prices. Meanwhile, it faces a growing threat from a new generation
of electronic trading systems that bypass exchanges altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific is taking several other steps to make its stock business
competitive again, such as laying plans to close its Pine Street
trading floor to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   OptiMark's connection problems are due to its failure to link
with the in-house order processing systems used by securities
firms. Currently, most customers have to re-enter orders from their
own electronic systems on to OptiMark.
</P>
<P>
   The company's engineers are in the process of fixing the problem
by setting up electronic connections with customers' order
processing systems, Lupien said. So far, they have linked with the
systems of two large institutional investors and a major brokerage
firm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with Pacific's operations said there is still
time to fix OptiMark.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give up on OptiMark would be to give up on the whole equity
business,'' said Warren Langley who retired several months ago as
the exchange's No.2 executive. ``But I think they have until
year-end before they have to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   OptiMark, one of a number of competing electronic order
processing systems in the market or under development, allows
institutional investors to avoid moving the price of a stock when
they enter a large buy or sell order.
</P>
<P>
   When an order to buy, say, 1 million shares is given to a live
broker, the market price of the stock will often jump because
supply and demand fall temporarily out of balance.
</P>
<P>
   OptiMark allows a buyer to conceal his identity and the size of
his order. It is filled when a seller who is ready to trade at the
buyer's price enters a separate order anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific introduced OptiMark in January with only one stock on
the system. It has since extended it to some 2,200 stocks listed on
both Pacific and the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange is considering other electronic systems to handle
retail orders of a few hundred or thousand shares.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
