<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weiss to go onto disabled list
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An MRI on Wednesday revealed what the Braves had
figured: Walt Weiss' quadriceps injury is pretty serious, and the
15-day disabled list necessary, retroactive to Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as bad as we thought,'' Braves trainer Dave Pursley
said.
</P>
<P>
   So on with the business of life, for now without Weiss. Manager
Bobby Cox plans to use veteran Ozzie Guillen with an occasional
start by rookie Mark DeRosa, who arrived from AAA Richmond on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another option would be to move Chipper Jones to shortstop, the
position he played as a kid and throughout his minor league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always think about that,'' Cox said. ``But Chipper has
really settled in as one of the premier third basemen in baseball.
You really don't want to mess with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way is fine with Jones, who played 38 games at shortstop
in 1996 when Jeff Blauser was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely open to any move that would help make us a
better club,'' Jones said. ``I'm a shortstop playing third base.
I've always been a shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   DeRosa is up for the second time after playing five games for
Atlanta last September. He played with the big league club for much
of spring training and got a handful of starts while Weiss was sick
and Guillen had a sprained thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel comfortable in here,'' said DeRosa unpacking his
belongings in his locker next to Greg Maddux's. ``I definitely know
my place, keep my mouth shut... Spring training was a good test. I
don't want to say I'm comfortable with being out there, but
hopefully I'll get over those nerves pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Assist to Glavine
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine takes partial credit for Guillen's four hits on
Tuesday night, which was Guillen's first real sign of offensive
life this season. Glavine had loaned Guillen three of his bats
before Tuesday's game. ``I told him `Go ahead, I ain't doing
anything with it,''' Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   The bats were originally Brett Boone's, but they weren't the
model Boone wanted. Both Glavine and Guillen like them for their
thicker head, smaller handle. Thirty-four inches, 32 ounces. And of
course, they're better luck for Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen is keeping three of them, Glavine has three and they are
hoping those last until Glavine can get another order in. He had
sent six of the bats to his younger brother Michael Glavine in AA
Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen got to bask in his four-hit night, right up until he got
a phone call from his best friend Harold Baines, now playing for
the Orioles, who said the usual good-going, then added: ``Now
you've got 17 points to go to get to .200.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko back in left
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko was back in the lineup Wednesday night after missing
two games because of the flu, as the experiment continues of having
Klesko in left and a Randall Simon/Brian Hunter platoon at first
base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a whole lot of work out there,'' Klesko said.
``So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
