<HEADLINE>
MAN ENJOYS FIRST VISIT TO CINEMA IN HALF-CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JOHN SANDERS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Fifty years ago, the New York Yankees beat the
Brooklyn Dodgers in five games in the World Series. Harry Truman
was in the White House after beating Thomas Dewey. And a movie,
popcorn and a soda might cost less than 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago was also the last time that 91-year-old Waymon
Holloway saw a movie inside a theater, before he saw ``Star Wars:
Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never wonder how they could do all those things and
show them on film,'' Holloway, who turns 92 later this month, said
outside the Cinemark 22 cineplex, where he saw George Lucas' fourth
space epic in stadium-style seats with stereo surround sound.
``It's wonderful, a wonderful difference. It was amazing how they
could make those robot characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Much different than when Holloway saw his last movie in black
and white in 1949, ``Heaven Can Wait'' starring Don Ameche, who
later _ much later _ won an Academy Award for ``Cocoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway said that when he viewed ``Heaven Can Wait'' in
Sparkman, Ark., the town had one theater, where popcorn and a soda
were a nickel each and admission about 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway was surprised to see the prices in tickets _ $4.25 a
seat for the matinee Holloway attended with his daughter, two
granddaughters and two great-grandchildren _ how fast the movie
moved and all the new technology of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway said he had a Sprite, popcorn, M&AMP;M's and Whoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't he go to the movies for 50 years?
</P>
<P>
   `I just found other things to do,'' said Holloway, who came to
the Antelope Valley north of Los Angeles from Arkansas to visit
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was pretty courageous of him,'' said Holloway's
granddaughter, Nancy Arnold. ``My grandfather is very old-school.
He doesn't do a whole lot except farm. He was amazed to see the new
technology; to see everything, it blew him away.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway said he probably won't go to the movies anymore, but he
enjoyed watching ``The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' said Barbara Monks, another
granddaughter of Holloway. ``At 92 he's still traveling by himself
and he's open to new things. I was amazed he stayed awake. And his
mouth was open and he was just looking the whole time. I had fun
enjoying him.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
