r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-INTERNET_SFC     06-09 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-INTERNET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 E-Commerce Growing Faster Than Expected  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Companies doing business on the Internet generated $300 billion in
revenue and created more than 1.2 million jobs last year, according
to a study conducted by the University of Texas that's being
released today.
<P>
   The study, a comprehensive look at the Internet's impact on the
economy, found that electronic commerce is growing at a faster rate
than previously expected. Researchers found that sales of goods
online jumped 175 percent from 1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It also found that employees who work for companies with
Internet-related revenues are 65 percent more productive than those
in other lines of business, such as the automotive industry.
</P>
<P>
   While other studies have focused on the Internet's contribution
to the national economy, this is the first to measure such a broad
base of companies.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers involved in the study, which was funded by San
Jose's Cisco Systems, interviewed 3,000 firms doing business on the
Web. They range from startups to major corporations like Microsoft
and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the six-month study was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   According to the findings, sales of products on the Web both to
businesses and to consumers generated more than $101 billion and
created almost 492,000 jobs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the study did not look at the profits of e-commerce
companies, industry watchers said the revenue figure is significant
because it indicates how substantial online sales are becoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We identified over 11,000 players in the United States selling
products directly over the Internet,'' said Anitesh Baruna, who
co-conducted the study. ``One grocery chain is selling $32 million
of online groceries in one metro area.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Harris, an economist with Lehman Bros., said the study
shows that the Internet has become vital to businesses looking for
a cheaper, more effective way to operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the Internet is clearly a more efficient way to do
business,'' Harris said. ``We're substituting traditional
businesses that require heavy capital investment for a distribution
system that doesn't require all these stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said he was surprised by the breadth of products for sale
on the Net. While initial studies pegged CDs and books as the kinds
of items people would want to buy online, Harris said the study
shows that almost every product from cars to air conditioners can
find a home on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that there's so many different things being sold on
the Web makes you think (e-commerce) will become a good chunk of
the economy,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of doing business on the Web also is reflected in
the sales of products that make the Internet run. Things such as
routers and switches, which are the plumbing of the Internet,
accounted for almost $115 billion in sales, the study found. This
is the arena where Cisco plays, along with companies like Nortel
Networks and Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Although the $300 billion revenue figure is substantial, some
analysts said the study bears out what everybody has been saying _
that the Internet is a huge economic engine.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Page, who follows e-commerce for the Strategis Group in
Washington, D.C., said business-to-business e-commerce and the
sales of Internet products such as routers are at the front of the
train.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drives it is a lot of the cost savings,'' Page said. ``If
companies can automate, they can have fewer employees and do things
more cheaply. Everything can be done online, and it's a huge cost
savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Listwin, Cisco's executive vice president, said the company
funded the study so that it could determine the scope and value of
business on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Listwin said Cisco also will use the findings to craft business
models for companies that want to participate in the Internet
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies that change their business model and use the
Internet can get leverage from a new way of doing business and
drive the productivity up,'' Listwin said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the increased productivity of employees who work
for firms with Internet-related revenues as a catalyst for more
companies getting on the Web. The study found that average revenue
per Internet employee is $250,000 compared with $160,000 per
non-Internet employees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
