<HEADER>
A9559 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTE-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A_     06-09 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTE-COMPUTING </SLUG>
 Q&AMP;A _ SF CHRON  
 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A/David Einstein
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Windows 95 Has a Few `Minor' Y2K Issues &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Q: A very good friend, extremely knowledgeable about PCs, tells me
that Windows 95 is not Y2K compatible. Any truth to this, or is it
another hoax? If it is true, has Microsoft come up with a fix?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your friend is right. Microsoft insists that Windows 95 is
Y2K compliant except for some ``minor issues.'' I don't like the
sound of that.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, certain system files in English-language versions
of Windows 95 are going to have problems recognizing the year 2000.
But Microsoft, to its credit, has taken responsibility for the
situation and has made free upgrade software available. You can
download it and also can learn all about the Y2K problem by going
to &LR;  www.microsoft.com/year2000. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Regarding your column's ongoing discussion of connection
speeds, I thought I'd pass this on. I use a Motorola ModemSurfer
56K to connect to my Internet service provider, Pac Bell. When they
went to V-90, I took advantage of Motorola's free software upgrade.
Where I had been connecting regularly at 46,000 bps, I now normally
hook up at 115,200. What a difference!
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry to spoil your day, but you're still getting around 46K,
which is a typical speed on a 56K line. V-90 is just a standard
that unites what had been two different ways of delivering 56K. The
115,200 you think you're getting is actually the throughput between
the modem and the computer. To get an accurate speed reading, you
may have to reset the dip switches on the modem so that they
recognize the new V-90 software. You also might try installing an
updated modem driver, which you can probably download from
Motorola's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has anyone ever investigated the relative costs of various
types of printers? My inkjet was cheap to buy and the cartridges
aren't too expensive, but they constantly need changing. Would a
laser printer cost less per page to use?
</P>
<P>
   A: Comparing costs of laser printers and inkjets is difficult
for a couple of reasons. All inkjets now are capable of printing in
color, while consumer-level laser printers still print only in
black and white. To get a color-capable laser printer you must
spend at least $2,000, while inkjets start at less than $200. Laser
printers that only print in black can be had for under $400.
</P>
<P>
   Just for the sake of filling up this column, let's do some
comparisons, with numbers supplied by Hewlett-Packard, which makes
both inkjets and lasers. For printing only in black, cost-per-page
for a typical laser printer is about 2 cents. For an inkjet, it's
2.5 to 3 cents. When you go to full color, both the inkjet and
laser printer cost 6 to 8 cents per page, depending on the model.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that for everyday printing, which
increasingly involves color, an inkjet is probably your best bet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TRANSLATION UPDATE: &QL; 
My last column featured a discussion of software designed to
translate English to foreign languages. A reader needed it in order
to send e-mail to a cousin in Italy. It turns out that you don't
need to buy software to get the job done. AltaVista, the Internet
search engine, has a free online translation feature at
 &LR; babelfish.altavista.com &LR;   &LR; /cgi-bin/translate?  &LR; (Be sure to include
the question mark at the end.) It lets you instantly translate
English into French, Italian, German, Spanish or Portuguese, as
well as changing those languages into English. You just enter your
text and hit the Translate key. When the translation pops up, you
can copy and paste it into an e-mail message. Not too shabby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Working at a computer can ruin your eyes, your back and your
arms. But by following a few ergonomic principles, you and your PC
can have a healthy relationship. Try not to have direct light
either in front of or behind your monitor _ light from the side is
better. Place the monitor so that your eyes are level with the top
of the screen. And make sure your keyboard is at a height that lets
you type with your lower arms parallel to the floor. Typing uphill
is bad.
</P>
</TEXT>
