<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9560 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOULEZ-MUSIC-2TAKES-$     06-09 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOULEZ-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WARMING OF A LUCID INTELLECT: BOULEZ AT 74  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the 1950s, Pierre Boulez's reputation as a cutting-edge
modernist composer and imposing musical intellect was already
secure. During the next decade he also emerged as an orchestra
conductor of probing insight and technical finesse, particularly in
the French Impressionist repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet back then, the restraint in his interpretations could
sometimes seem cool. Over the years, as he continued to explore the
standard repertory, his performances took on a greater pliancy and
warmth, qualities that were especially evident in two remarkable
programs of Ravel and Debussy that he presented with the superb
Cleveland Orchestra last month at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Boulez's development as a major musician of our
time has been well documented on disk. Now 74, he has
understandably begun to cut back his conducting commitments. But he
continues his work in the recording studio. Three important
releases on Deutsche Grammophon, the label with which he has been
most closely associated of late, present Boulez as conductor and
composer.
</P>
<P>
   The first includes the two Ravel works for piano and orchestra
with Krystian Zimerman as soloist and the London Symphony
Orchestra, as well as the orchestral version of the piano piece
``Valse Nobles et Sentimentales'' (289 449 213-2; CD); the second
offers Mahler's Symphony No. 1 with the Chicago Symphony Orchestra
(289 459 610-2; CD). &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Finally, as part of Deutsche Grammophon's series 20/21: The
Music of Our Time, Boulez conducts the Ensemble Intercontemporain
in his ``Repons,'' a major composition here captured in an
exhilarating performance (289 457 605-2).
</P>
<P>
   Ravel's Concerto in G has too easily been taken for a
Gershwinesque work with brilliant piano writing and impishly clever
orchestration, right from the crack-of-the-whip effect that gets
the piece going. Boulez and Zimerman will make you forget such
notions. From the opening measures, it's not Ravel's excitement
over 1920s jazz but his bracing deployment of bitonal harmony
(shades of Stravinsky's ``Petrouchka'') that comes through. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Zimerman's clean, spindly articulation of the whirling piano
figurations emphasizes the clashing tonalities and makes the
passage seem far more than decorative, even as the solo flute and,
later, brassy trumpet dance blithely above it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the performance lacks a jazzy touch. Zimerman's way
with the sultry solo theme that creeps in and Boulez's shaping of
that tune when the orchestra takes it over transport us momentarily
to a mellow blues club. But both musicians are more concerned with
making the shifting rhythms incisive and bringing out the pungency
of the harmony.
</P>
<P>
   The tranquil second movement, which begins with a long piano
solo, a wistful spinning melody over a slow waltz accompaniment,
has an affecting reserve as played by Zimerman and echoed by Boulez
when the orchestra enters. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In the finale Zimerman plays the toccatalike piano part with
both driving intensity and a sense of fun. Still, there is
something eerie, and rightly so, in the way Boulez encourages the
weird lines of orchestral soloists to intrude. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Though the performance has warmth and adventure, the concerto
has never sounded less like a piece for pops orchestras, where you
too often hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Ravel wrote the Concerto for the Left Hand during 1930 and 1931
on commission from the Austrian pianist Paul Wittgenstein, who had
lost his right arm in action during World War I. That Wittgenstein
had staunchly conservative tastes was unfortunate, since the only
way he could continue his career was to commission works for left
hand alone. &UR;  &LR;  Prokofiev, Britten and others answered his call. But
Wittgenstein disliked most of what he paid for, including the
Ravel. He declined to play the premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Later he grew to respect the work. But this performance suggests
why he may initially have found it forbiddingly modern. Boulez
makes the grim opening episode for orchestra, with its primordial
grumblings in low strings and accumulating melodic fragments for
contrabassoon and quiet brasses, seem more sinister than the
beginning of Wagner's ``Siegfried.'' &UR;  &LR;  He builds the music to a
harrowing climax until Zimerman pushes the orchestra aside with his
arresting account of the keyboard-spanning piano outburst. The
performance continues to capture the strangeness and ferocity of
the music, while delivering the dreamy bits with elegant restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restraint'' is the operative word for Boulez's performance of
the ``Valses Nobles.'' Yet without being didactic, he also calls
attention to the biting quality in Ravel's harmony. In the
ruminative second waltz, he trusts in the tenderness of the melody
without milking it for sentiment, as so many conductors do. The
third waltz sounds here like music for a children's game. But the
game is deceptively innocent.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During Boulez's early career he had little sympathy for the
bittersweet late Romanticism of Mahler. He grew to see Mahler as an
authentic master and a role model for dealing with two difficult
problems in composition: how to organize music over long spans of
time and how to fashion disparate musical materials into a coherent
language. &UR;  &LR;  Since then, Boulez's clearheaded performances of the
Mahler symphonies have been highly respected, and the new recording
of the First Symphony is especially fine.
</P>
<P>
   This symphony is often called the ``Titan,'' a title many
conductors take as permission to turn it into an overbearing,
emotive mess. But under Boulez the work's titanic nature is heard
in the boldness of Mahler's musical thinking and the haunting way
the composer pits texturally complex passages against guileless
evocations of folk song and dance.
</P>
<P>
   The famous opening of the first movement, with its eerie
sustained notes for high strings in harmonics, sounds transformed
here. The sustained tones seem not just some background color to
create a sense of nature's awakening but an upfront musical element
to set the listener on alert. &UR;  &LR;  Boulez captures the folkloric
quality of the symphony's melodic materials, while never letting it
take over.
</P>
<P>
   The third movement, properly, sounds like some heavy-footed
country dance, or a farmer's ambling ox-cart. Yet the soft-spoken
insistence and rhythmic integrity in the playing focus the ear on
musical matters. After all, no real ox-cart moves with such
steadiness. The tumultuous finale, which can sound bombastic, is
riveting because Boulez and the Chicago Symphony bring uncanny
clarity to the intertwining contrapuntal lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Boulez is a composer who also conducts, not a
conductor who also composes. So for him, and for posterity, the
most important of these new recordings is that of his own
``Repons.''
</P>
<P>
   The work's title refers to the responsorial aspect of Gregorian
chant, in which a solo voice is answered by a responding choir.
This simple call-and-response technique is found in lots of music,
including gospel singing and big-band jazz. &UR;  &LR;  Boulez adds a spatial
dimension here. ``Repons'' was written for a specific place (the
performance hall at Ircam, the music research institute founded by
Boulez at the Pompidou Center in Paris) and specific performers
(the Ensemble Intercontemporain, which Boulez directs).
</P>
<P>
   He worked for three years on ``Repons,'' revising and expanding
it until 1984, when the version heard here was first performed.
Three separate entities were involved in the performance: six
soloists, who played cimbalom, piano, xylophone and other
percussion instruments; an instrumental ensemble of 24 musicians,
and an electroacoustic system with a computer that transformed and
spatialized the sound, played through six loudspeakers. &UR;  &LR;  The
ensemble and conductor were placed in the center of the hall,
surrounded by the audience. The soloists and speakers were placed
equidistantly along the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, a recording cannot recreate the effect of sitting
among these conversing musical forces. But the new disk gives a
good sense of what it was like: you hear xylophone riffs, for
example, bounce from one speaker to another.
</P>
<P>
   Like all of Boulez's music, this 42-minute score is intensely
complex. But if you rid yourself of concern for the methods used to
pick the pitches and listen for color, shape, character and
darting, skittish rhythmic writing, the music is hard to resist. &UR;  &LR; 
There are delicate and stunning instrumental effects, wondrous
masses of sound that get manipulated like children's blocks, and
the constant edge-of-the-seat drama that comes from the interplay
between the live performers and the computerized transformations of
what they play.
</P>
<P>
   The recording also includes a somewhat similarly conceived work,
the brilliant ``Dialogue de l'Ombre Double,'' in which a solo
clarinetist, the virtuosic Alain Damiens, plays a series of six
``strophes,'' interspersed with short movements prerecorded by
Damiens, in which the music is again spatialized.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners who are naturally curious about the Debussy and Mahler
but reticent about ``Repons'' should check out this disk. They may
find the music more engrossing than they might have imagined. And
the same encompassing musical mind is at work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
