<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-SUSPECT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS HELP POLICE SEARCH FOR `THE MOST WANTED MAN IN TEXAS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ky.) 
 
By ERIC HANSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Law enforcement officials have received dozens of tips
regarding the search for an elusive drifter suspected of six
slayings in Texas and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten a lot of information from the public, which is
what we really wanted,'' said Don K. Clark, special agent in charge
of the Houston FBI.
</P>
<P>
   A command center at Houston FBI headquarters has been set up to
coordinate the efforts of numerous state, local and federal
officers searching for Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, who is wanted in a
string of brutal slayings dating to the summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of early this morning, we had received approximately 30
calls and it has probably doubled since that time,'' Clark said
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   To help generate more leads, authorities have increased reward
money from $50,000 to $60,000 for information leading to his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the calls vary widely with some offering only a few
vague hints, while others provide detailed leads. He said all
information is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a one- or two-word call may just very well be the
bit of information it takes to get us to the location (of the
killer),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies from across Texas have launched an
effort to find Resendez-Ramirez, who is a suspect in five killings
in Texas and one in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now he's the most wanted man in Texas,'' said DPS
Director Col. Dudley L. Thomas. ``We need to hear from anyone who
might have information that could lead us to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The DPS has contributed eight Texas Rangers and three Special
Crime Service investigators to the search.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is described as 38 years old, 5 feet 7 inches
tall and weighing about 150 pounds. He is said to have black hair
and brown eyes and his left forearm has the tattoo of a snake. He
has altered his appearance in the past with wigs and glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Resendez-Ramirez has been linked by evidence to all
five Texas crimes, but he declined to discuss details about that
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Police have said fingerprints belonging to Resendez-Ramirez have
been found in connection with slayings in West University Place, an
enclave of Houston, and Schulenburg, which is about 90 miles west
of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez also is considered a suspect in a killing in
southwest Houston, where the body of Noemi Dominguez, 26, was found
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   She died from a blow to the head, and her white 1993 Honda Civic
with license number JJH 57N was stolen. The car is missing.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said FBI specialists in Washington, D.C., and Houston are
developing a psychological profile of the killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can use this for lead information as to where we think this
person may go or what we think this person might do,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said investigators believe Resendez-Ramirez is probably a
transient without any roots to any particular location.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't know a lot else about him personally at this
point. We're hoping that as information comes in we can develop a
truer picture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of the slayings, including the one in Kentucky, happened
near railroad tracks and all the victims were beaten to death.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the killer is moving about the state by
hopping freight trains. In three of the cases, he has stolen
vehicles belonging to the victims. Two of those vehicles have been
recovered in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The first case occurred Dec. 17, when the body of Dr. Claudia
Benton, 39, was found in her West University Place home just a few
blocks from railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   She had been beaten and stabbed to death and sexually assaulted.
Her stolen Jeep Cherokee was found abandoned in San Antonio with
Resendez-Ramirez's fingerprint in the vehicle, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, he was indicted on a charge of burglary in the case.
This charge led to the federal count against Resendez-Ramirez,
allowing the FBI to search for him anywhere in the country, Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have linked Resendez-Ramirez to the deaths of the
Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife, Karen, 47. They were
found beaten to death with a sledgehammer in the parsonage behind
the Weimar United Church of Christ in Colorado County after they
did not show up for services May 2.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; About three weeks later, investigators said evidence found in
the Sirnics' home linked Resendez-Ramirez to the Benton case.
Authorities have declined to release specific details.
</P>
<P>
   The Sirnics' stolen pickup was found May 28 by police in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   One week later, a relative found the body of Josephine Konvicka,
73, in her house near Schulenburg in Fayette County, just 3 1/2
miles from the Sirnics' home.
</P>
<P>
   Konvicka had been beaten to death, and the killer tried to steal
her car but could not locate the keys. Resendez-Ramirez's
fingerprints were found in her home and also near railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington victim was University of Kentucky student
Christopher Maier, 21. He was beaten to death and his girlfriend
assaulted as they walked along railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Following that slaying, the woman was able to provide
investigators a description of her attacker that matches the
description of Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Police from Kentucky have been in Houston consulting with local
authorities. No charges have yet been filed in connection with the
Kentucky case, which occurred Aug. 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking to provide information on Resendez-Ramirez's
whereabouts can call the FBI Command Center at 713-479-6325 or
713-693-5000.
</P>
<P>
   Those with information also can call the Texas Crimestoppers
Hotline toll free at 1-800-252-8477 (TIPS).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
