<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORDSIDE-WORDSIDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   This Software Doesn't Live Up to Its Name 
 &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
As sophisticated as today's software may be, it can also be
extraordinarily stupid. Consider my first experience with Corel's
new WordPerfect Office 2000.
<P>
   When I restarted my PC after installing the new suite, I found
seven new inscrutable mini-icons in my ``system tray,'' the area on
the right side of the ``taskbar'' at the bottom of the Windows
desktop. The first one, I discovered, activated DAD, or Desktop
Application Director, a launching utility that's Corel's answer to
MOM, the Microsoft Office Manager. DAD presented me with a long
list of templates for various tasks. On a whim, I chose to try one
called ``Grade Schedule,'' a high-tech equivalent to the
time-honored teacher's grade book.
</P>
<P>
   I entered two names and a handful of grades into the file. Then
I clicked on a button labeled ``Sort the Student Names.'' Instead
of doing so, WordPerfect put up a dialog instructing me to select
the names to be sorted. I highlighted the two names and clicked the
button again. This time the program told me I'd exceeded its
32-kilobyte ``sort limit'' and should select a subset.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, I added a third name, selected all three, and again
clicked the Sort button. This time the program told me it was
``examining records'' _ a good sign, I thought. But it didn't stop
at three. In fact, in the blink of an eye the running total
presented in the dialog box had passed 20,000. At that point I
clicked Cancel.
</P>
<P>
   My three names still weren't sorted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
