A9566 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORD-WORD_SFCHRON &LR;      06-09 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORD-WORD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Upgrade to WordPerfect Is Polished, Powerful 
 &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Unless your computer career dates back to DOS days, you may not
realize that WordPerfect once dominated the word processing market
as surely as Microsoft does today.
<P>
   The program fell behind when the world moved to Windows, and in
just a few years it went from market leader to distant also-ran.
The company that originally created it is long gone, and the
product itself has been sold twice.
</P>
<P>
   But WordPerfect retains a loyal following, and its current
owner, Corel Corp. of Ottawa, has worked hard to keep it alive and
well even as Microsoft's market share has mounted. To compete with
Microsoft's multiprogram Office, Corel too has assembled a suite of
applications under the WordPerfect Office name. It includes the
Quattro Pro spreadsheet; a presentation program called, simply,
Corel Presentations; a personal information manager called
CorelCentral; and, in the high-end ``Professional Edition'' of the
suite, a corporate-grade database program called Paradox.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Corel delivered a major upgrade to the package under
a not-so-original name, WordPerfect Office 2000. The core
applications have all been improved, CorelCentral has had a
complete redesign (badly needed, but largely successful), and Corel
has added Trellix 2, a capable Web-page creation program. Both the
Professional Edition and a less-expensive Voice-Powered Edition
also come with Dragon Naturally Speaking 3.0, a top-notch
speech-recognition program from Dragon Software, and a good-quality
microphone to use with it.
</P>
<P>
   Full retail pricing ranges from $399 to $499, but upgrades are
only $109 to $209. Corel is even more liberal than Microsoft in
determining who's eligible for the discount. Basically, if you own
any other productivity software, you can get WordPerfect Office for
considerably less than any version of the Microsoft suite.
</P>
<P>
   System requirements are also a little less stringent than
Microsoft's, at least if you don't plan to use the
speech-recognition software. All versions require Windows 95, 98 or
NT 4.0, at least 16 megabytes of RAM (32 megabytes recommended),
and lots of disk space _ a bare minimum of 100 megabytes, but 280
megabytes for a typical installation. What you don't need,
according to Corel, is a Pentium: The suite is supposed to work on
any system with a 486 chip running at 66 megahertz or more. (I
didn't test it on a 486.)
</P>
<P>
   If you do want to use the bundled Dragon software, you'll need
more of everything _ RAM, disk space and processing power.
</P>
<P>
   I gave WordPerfect Office 2000 a brief tryout on my PC, and
mostly I liked what I saw. The core applications are all polished
and powerful, and I liked both Trellix 2 and the redesigned
CorelCentral a lot.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the various programs aren't nearly as well
integrated and consistent as Microsoft's, and I ran into a number
of glitches in this suite, too. Some of them, like finding only one
font available in WordPerfect, probably reflect my unfamiliarity
with the program more than any intrinsic deficiencies. But I also
encountered some screen redraw glitches (a problem I remember
plaguing WordPerfect more than a decade ago), and when I was
writing this story in the program, it mysteriously stopped being
able to save, posting a dialog that said only ``A required resource
was'' _ I had to switch back to Microsoft Word to finish the
article.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, I didn't see anything in the new Corel suite
compelling enough to get many users of Microsoft Office to change
horses. But if you already use an earlier version of WordPerfect,
you can't afford Microsoft's prices, or you just prefer to work in
a Microsoft-free environment, WordPerfect Office 2000 is a very
viable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
