<HEADER>
A9568 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OFFICE-OFFICE_SFCHRON     06-09 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-OFFICE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Versatile Microsoft Office 2000  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
With Microsoft Office now controlling roughly 90 percent of the
market for business ``productivity'' software, most of today's
office workers also are Office workers.
<P>
   So when Office changes, it matters. It's almost as if carpenters
the world over were about to see their hammers, saws and
screwdrivers replaced by ``new and improved'' tools.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true of the latest version, Office 2000, which
is slated to hit retail shelves today. It deliberately was designed
to promote new ways of working, ways Bill Gates and his colleagues
consider appropriate for the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   For those who work in companies ready to fully embrace
Microsoft's vision, Office 2000 is an impressive advance. For the
rest of us _ including, I'd guess, most home and small-office users
_ many of the biggest changes in Office 2000 are simply irrelevant.
But the package still offers a variety of welcome improvements,
along with some annoying problems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
_The Basics. Four versions of Office 2000 are available, with
different sets of additional applications accompanying the common
core: Microsoft Word, the word processor; Excel, the
number-crunching tool; Outlook, which serves as e-mail client,
calendar and contact database; and the Internet Explorer Web
browser.
</P>
<P>
   Retail prices for new users range from $499 to $799. You
probably won't have to pay that much, though, no matter what
version you want, because almost everyone who owns a PC capable of
running Office 2000 qualifies for upgrade pricing. That starts at
$249, and if you're upgrading from an earlier version of Microsoft
Office as opposed to competing products, you're probably eligible
for a $40 or $50 rebate.
</P>
<P>
   To run the new software, you need Windows 95 or 98 or NT 4.0
with Service Pack 3 or later. (There won't be a Mac version of
Office 2000, according to Microsoft, but Mac owners can look
forward to their own new Office release in another year or so.)
Hardware requirements include at least a 75-MHz Pentium or
equivalent (166 MHz required for PhotoDraw, the new graphics
program included in the Premium version).
</P>
<P>
   RAM requirements are complicated, depending on which version you
install and how many programs you want to keep open simultaneously,
but in general, I wouldn't bother with Office 2000 unless you have
at least 32 megabytes of memory. Disk-space requirements range from
nearly 200 megabytes for a minimal installation to more than 500
megabytes for the full Premium package. (Details are at
 &LR; www.microsoft.com/office/features &LR;   &LR; /ofc2000tour/Sysreqs.htm.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Take it to the Net. The single-most-important advance in Office
2000 is that each of its applications lets you save any document as
a Web page, without losing the ability to re-edit it later in
Office with all features intact. Previous versions let you save
some files in the Web's HTML format, but fewer Office formatting
options were preserved, and such documents ceased to be editable in
Office without a lot of extra work.
</P>
<P>
   The translation process is still far from perfect, mainly
because HTML can't handle all the formatting options the Office
applications offer. Cosmetic glitches appeared in many of the
documents I created to test this feature. If you're aiming to
create cool Web pages, you'll still want a tool designed expressly
for that purpose _ either Microsoft FrontPage, which is included in
the Premium version of Office, or one of the many alternatives from
other companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the new translation feature does preserve the content and
most formatting of Office documents. That solves a couple of
important problems: Anyone using any Web browser can read such
documents, even if they've never owned a previous version of Office
or anything like it. And if you later want to make changes to the
document, you don't have to start all over formatting it in Office.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the new approach creates some new issues,
over and above the cosmetic problems. The biggest is that documents
saved as Web pages are broken up into numerous separate files and
folders that you _ and anyone to whom you want to send the document
_ have to keep together.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that hassle, you can instead save your documents in the
proprietary Office formats (Word, Excel, etc.). Because those
formats haven't changed (except in the case of Access), the files
will be readable, minus a few new formatting options, by anyone
with Office 97 for Windows, Office 98 for Mac, or any other
software that can read Office 97 formats.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can adopt the approach Microsoft is pushing: Save your
files as Web pages and share them via the Internet or your
organization's internal intranet. You can do that with any Web
server and browser, but Office 2000 provides lots of extra features
and conveniences for those who use Microsoft's own Web server
software (part of Windows NT Server) together with the company's
Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if your organization has an NT server and adds some
extra software that comes with Office 2000 (``Office Server
Extensions''), you can save a document directly to the server from
the Office applications just as if it were on your own hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues given the appropriate level of access to the server
then can attach comments to the file and respond to others'
observations directly from their browser. If they're using Internet
Explorer and still more extra Microsoft software is running on the
server, they can edit the contents of the file without leaving
their browser. You can even arrange to be notified automatically
via e-mail when comments are posted or changes made to files you're
interested in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Other enhancements. Even if you or your boss isn't quite ready to
adopt this kind of ``digital nervous system,'' as Bill Gates calls
it, Office users still will find lots to appreciate in the new
version.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Office 2000 applications are now, like Office 98
programs on the Mac, ``self-repairing'': If a critical file is
missing or damaged, it's supposed to be replaced automatically,
without making the user deal with cryptic error messages. If you
suspect additional problems, a new ``Detect and Repair'' command is
supposed to deal with them.
</P>
<P>
   These are nice ideas, and they should eliminate a lot of
time-wasting support calls and reinstallations. I should note,
however, that in my testing, I regularly encountered a message
about a ``compile error in hidden module: modMain,'' and even the
Detect and Repair feature didn't fix it.
</P>
<P>
   The user interfaces in the Office applications haven't changed
drastically, so you shouldn't have any trouble learning them. But
Microsoft did try to make them easier to use by simplifying dialog
boxes and shortening menus. There's also a new feature called
``adaptive menus,'' which takes options you never use off the
menus. (The downside: You can go crazy looking for a command you
 &LR; know  &LR; used to be there. Fortunately, you can shut off this
feature.)
</P>
<P>
   You'll also find some nice new conveniences in all of the
applications. Open and Save dialogs have been redesigned to show
more information and make it easier to jump to the files and
folders you use most often. The clipboard, which used to hold only
one item at a time, now stores up to 12, any of which you can paste
by clicking on the corresponding icon. A new Send To command on the
File menu enables you to e-mail the document you're working on
without leaving your application.
</P>
<P>
   In the individual programs, you'll find countless more
refinements. In Word, for example, you now can click anywhere on
the page and start typing without having to fuss with margin
settings or enter returns and spaces to get where you want, and you
can find and select synonyms from Word's thesaurus directly from
the right-click pop-up menu. Excel's PivoTables, a powerful but
confusing data-analysis feature, now are much easier to use.
PowerPoint text automatically shrinks to fit on your slides, and
numbered bullet points automatically are renumbered when you change
their order.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Bottom line. Altogether, Office 2000, whichever version you
choose, is an amazingly rich software tool kit _ there's not a lot
you can't do with it, and the new features generally make doing so
 &LR; it easier to use than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, though, I'm not convinced that the package is
really ready for release. In just a couple of weeks of testing,
I've already had more crashes, freezes, anomalies (such as blank
menus) and error messages than I saw in years of work with Office
97 and Office 95. Reviewers in the trade magazines report few such
problems, so maybe there's just something wrong with the two PCs
(notebook and desktop) I tested on, but I'm suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   One other note: If you don't have any use for the advanced
Web-related features and you mainly use Word, you might want to
wait for a new release of Microsoft Works scheduled for later this
year. It will include Word 2000, plus basic spreadsheet, database
and graphics features, and it undoubtedly will cost less than any
version of Office.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, by then Microsoft might have the bugs fixed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
