<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUC10-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      06-09 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC10-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Governor Finally Fills 2 PUC Vacancies  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Governor Gray Davis named a union executive and a
lawyer-turned-entrepreneur yesterday to the state Public Utilities
Commission, one week after he temporarily appointed two members of
his staff to the regulatory agency.
<P>
   The latest appointees, who presumably will serve full six-year
terms with annual salaries of $98,000, are Carl W. Wood, national
representative for the Utility Workers Union of America, and Joel
Z. Hyatt, co-founder of Hyatt Legal Services.
</P>
<P>
   The appointments fill out the five-member PUC panel for the
first time in six months. During this period, the commission has
had to postpone votes on a wide range of important issues.
</P>
<P>
   The pair will attend their first PUC meeting tomorrow although
Wood isn't expected to be sworn in until June 21. To eliminate any
conflict of interest, Wood first must resign his union position and
end his ``union leave'' status with Southern California Edison,
which he joined as an electrician in the utility's nuclear power
division in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Wood is the first appointee with a labor background in more than
two decades. He said yesterday that it would be a ``mistake,
however, to assume that I've been appointed to represent labor's
narrow interests. My constituency is the consumers of the state and
I want to see the commission act in a way that's more responsive to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Wood, Hyatt is expected to bring a strong consumer focus to
the PUC. Hyatt, who's been a personal friend of Davis for years,
attracted national attention when he became one of the first
attorneys to take advantage of a U.S. Supreme Court decision that
permitted attorneys to advertise their services, beginning in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Promoted heavily through television ads, the Yale-educated Hyatt
built a network of more than 200 storefronts offering inexpensive
legal services, often at flat fees, to middle-income clients who
make too much money for legal aid services but are too poor for
$150-to-$300-an-hour attorneys. Most of those franchiselike offices
since have been sold to the attorneys managing them.
</P>
<P>
   His successor company, Hyatt Legal Plans, pioneered the concept
of offering legal services to consumers through their employers as
part of benefits plans. For flat monthly fees, more than 1 million
members got full legal services.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've tried to do is make the legal system work better on
behalf of the people it hasn't served very well,'' Hyatt said
yesterday. ``I'll be bringing a passionate interest in good public
policy to the PUC.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Hyatt ran for the U.S. Senate in Ohio, hoping to occupy
the seat being vacated by his father-in-law, Democratic icon Howard
Metzenbaum. In his only attempt at elective office, he won the
Democratic primary but lost in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Hyatt and his partners sold Hyatt Legal Plans to
MetLife for an undisclosed sum. Hyatt moved to Atherton to assume a
position as visiting scholar at the Hoover Institution. For the
past year, he has lectured in entrepreneurship at the Stanford
University business school.
</P>
<P>
   Wood and Hyatt have their work cut out for them.
</P>
<P>
   Many important issues are before the PUC, established by
Progressive Republican governor Hiram Johnson in 1911, and
currently under attack as an anachronism in an increasingly
deregulated world that trusts markets to deliver the benefits that
formerly were the purview of regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he has the strongest grounding in energy issues,
particularly in electric deregulation _ which his union opposed as
contrary to the interest of consumers and utility workers.
</P>
<P>
   Hyatt said he's devoted considerable energy to understanding
telecommunications issues. He feels California should be a leader
in having progressive telecommunications policies ``since we have
Silicon Valley and no one else does.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the PUC was set to vote on one such matter when Davis
temporarily put two staffers on the commission. They delayed a vote
that could affect how much consumers pay for Internet services.
That issue will come back today for reconsideration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, both  &LR; Wood and Hyatt will face important votes in
coming months about implementation of the state's electric
deregulation plan and changes in the telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure that competition actually leads to
well-functioning and effective markets,'' said Hyatt. ``What's best
for consumers, today, may be different than 20 years ago. The
challenge is to figure out the right solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood, 51, lives in San Diego with his wife. A daughter graduated
from the University of California at Santa Cruz last year and a son
graduates this week.
</P>
<P>
   Hyatt, 49, lives in Atherton with his wife and sons, ages 12 and
16.
</P>
<P>
   Both appointments require confirmation by the Senate, which has
a year to take up the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Still up the air is an appointment by Davis to fill the
directorship of the PUC's Office of Ratepayer Advocates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
