<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SURVIVIR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH SURVIVOR ARRIVES HOME _ BY LAND 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY BLANEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four days after surviving the crash of Flight 1420, Richard
Sowers was out of a hospital and ready to return home to Tucson,
Ariz., choosing to travel by train rather than go through another
plane landing.
</P>
<P>
   But just outside Little Rock, Ark., he began suffering
flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had completely forgotten about the shaking and the noise,''
he said, noting that he hadn't taken a train in years. ``It was
just like skidding on the ground, the same jerking me back and
forth.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, American Airlines rented a 1999 Lincoln Executive
Town Car and a driver to resolve Sowers' problem. Sowers and his
daughter Gail Bell, who had flown to Little Rock to accompany him
home, were chauffeured to Tucson, American spokesman John Hotard
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sowers' wife, Audrey Sowers, 65, who flew to Little Rock after
the American Airlines crash, said it was clear that her husband
wouldn't arrive in Tucson via rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He barely made it to Dallas,'' she said. ``He was champing at
the bit.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued on the train to Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sowers and Bell spent Monday night in Midland and
arrived home Tuesday afternoon, the day before his 69th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Sowers praised American for catering to his need to find another
way home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have offered me a golf cart if I had asked for
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the June 1 crash, American gave each passenger on
the plane a check for $25,000 to help defray expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Sowers said he was in Seat 24F when the McDonnell Douglas MD-82
crashed at Little Rock National Airport. Nine people died and more
than 80 were injured when the jet crashed after landing in a
violent thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Sowers suffered a fractured rib and several cuts, including a
gash on his left foot. He was released June 2 from Southwest
Regional Medical Center in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen people injured in the crash were in five Little Rock
hospitals Wednesday. Two were listed in critical condition, one in
serious condition and the remainder in good or fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   One was expected to be released late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At Arkansas Children's Hospital, Rachel Fuller, 14, of
Arkadelphia, Ark., Samantha Salmans, 8, of Cabot, Ark., and Kristin
Maddox, 22, of Ponca City, Okla., were receiving treatment for
burns they suffered when the jet burst into flames at the end of
the runway.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
