A9575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-ART-N     06-09 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS REVIVE BID TO BAR PEACEKEEPER FUNDS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans, backed by Speaker Dennis
Hastert, Wednesday revived attempts to bar funds for American
peacekeeping troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the move would make Congress ``a laughingstock''
and subvert the search for peace at the moment the Yugoslav army
agreed to withdraw from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and the Republican leadership shelved the effort 13 days
ago, at the White House's request. Key conservatives immediately
rebelled and blocked the bill to which the ban was attached, a $289
billion military spending authorization.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the conservatives won Hastert's support for ``a
discussion and vote on this issue,'' said his spokesman, John
Feehery. In exchange, the conservatives unlocked the military bill,
which now becomes the vehicle for the House to argue over the
ending of NATO's war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker supports an amendment barring funds for peacekeepers
without congressional authorization, Feehery said. He said ``the
House should work its will'' on another amendment outlawing any
money for peacekeeping in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Those measures, scheduled to be debated on Thursday, will be
hotly contested. The House in April refused to give its political
backing to NATO's air campaign in Yugoslavia. Republicans called
the bombing ``Clinton's war.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will veto any military spending bill restricting
Pentagon funds for operations in Kosovo, said a White House
spokesman, P.J. Crowley. ``It would be very unwise for Congress to
take any action that undercuts U.S. policy precisely at the point
when success is in reach,'' he said. ``We need to see the
peacekeeping operations through.''
</P>
<P>
   The House minority leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri,
criticized ``the spectacle of Republicans bringing up amendments to
cut off funding at the very moment that we should be trying to
consolidate the peace.'' And Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, said the
Republicans, by bringing the amendments to the floor, made the
House ``appear both a laughingstock and irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   In its first vote on the defense bill Wednesday, the House
unanimously backed an amendment enacting recommendations by the Cox
committee, the House panel that reported last month on assertions
of Chinese espionage at the nation's nuclear weapons laboratories.
The labs are run by the Department of Energy, whose military
activities are covered by the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment is aimed at strengthen intelligence-gathering and
stepping up spy-catching operations at the Energy Department. It
temporarily bars foreign visitors from the weapons labs and
tightens access to classified information by Energy Department
employees.
</P>
<P>
   It orders the White House to monitor the use of high-performance
American computers sold to China and it requires the president to
report to Congress on Chinese military technology and espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox committee's ranking Democrat, Rep. Norm Dicks of
Washington, said the measure ``would go a long way'' toward curing
longstanding security problems at the labs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
