<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-SUN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA AND SUN TO BUILD JOINT SYSTEM FOR FAST NET ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Motorola Inc., one of the world's largest makers of
wireless communications equipment, and Sun Microsystems Inc., which
is best known for its Solaris operating systems and the Java
programming language, said Wednesday that they were teaming up to
create a new wireless network to provide high-speed Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies said that the new system would allow consumers
within the next few years to tap into the Internet through cellular
telephones, pagers, hand-held computing devices and other wireless
devices for tasks as varied as buying books, trading stocks online,
viewing multimedia programs and sending and retrieving digital
photographs. The group said it expected to have a new platform
ready by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to create an infrastructure for a global network that
offers high-speed Internet access, Motorola, earlier this year
formed a joint venture with Cisco Systems, the networking giant.
Under it the two companies are to spend $1 billion over the next
four or five years and open four joint-research and development
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sun Microsystems has joined them in hope of creating a
wireless and Internet triumvirate to sell Internet servers and
routers to Internet service providers, like telecommunications and
cable companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially what we're creating is the next generation
telecommunications architecture,'' said Christopher Galvin, chief
executive of Motorola, which is based in Schaumburg, Ill. ``We're
building a wireless infrastructure for computer applications, so
that a day trader can make trades wherever they are, and so that
you can have wireless electronic commerce and ATMs.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the futuristic promise, analysts caution that
building wireless systems is fraught with difficulty and that
contractual arrangements could make selling such a system to
Internet service providers challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, wireless infrastructure has been a very difficult
thing to deploy,'' said Michael Slater, an analyst at Cahners
Microdesign Research in Sebastopol, Calif. ``There's a huge amount
of infrastructure that is needed to make this stuff happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Those obstacles have not, however, dulled excitement in the
wireless arena. Microsoft, Qualcomm and a number of European
telecommunications giants are preparing for wireless access to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Cisco Systems, Motorola and now Sun Microsystems said their
plan was among the most ambitious. The three companies, for
instance, have agreed on an open Internet Protocol-based system
that would be more flexible, scalable and open to customization,
even from competitors; the system would incorporate Sun's Solaris
operating system and its Java programming language.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement announced Wednesday, Motorola will invest
about $1 billion over the next decade in the venture. Motorola
servers would be used, along with hardware and software from Sun
Microsystems and Cisco routers and packet-switching technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The open system allows us faster time to the market,'' said
Jerry Campbell, a vice president in the network products and
emerging technologies division at Motorola, and ``much higher speed
data transport.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cellular telephones, he noted, were already being equipped
with browsers, and other wireless devices were blurring the lines
between pagers, cellular telephones and electronic storage devices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
