u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGAPORE-FOOD-BAN-NY     06-09 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGAPORE-FOOD-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BELGIUM'S DIOXIN SCARE, SINGAPORE PURGES FOOD STOCKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Switzerland, South Korea, Japan, Taiwan, Hong Kong,
Malaysia, Belgian, Australia and New Zealand. ) By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ The free-range chicken is gone, the Camembert is
dwindling and there's only enough foie gras to last the week.
Beyond that, the future looks bleak to Justin Quek, chef of
Singapore's most exclusive French restaurant, Au Jardin.
</P>
<P>
   This town has been declared a foie-gras-free zone. The same goes
for bratwurst, weisswurst, feta and Morbier. Scratch, too, the
prosciutto, Stilton, and saucisse a l'ail. Anything containing meat
or dairy products from Europe has been yanked from grocery store
shelves following a snap government order last weekend in response
to news that animal feed contaminated with the cancer-causing
chemical dioxin may have poisoned a variety of products from
Belgium and elsewhere in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Swedish meatballs are off the menu at the local Ikea. At the
Cold Storage grocery on Orchard Road, Singapore's busiest shopping
boulevard, hurried staff simply taped white butcher's paper over an
entire case of imported cheese, pates and cold cuts.
</P>
<P>
   It caught everybody off-guard, says the general manager, Huw
Jenkins, who spent the weekend with a hastily assembled task force
of employees pulling suspect items off the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The ban put Singapore on a growing list of nations, from
Switzerland to South Korea, that are blocking some imports of
European food in response to the concerns. Japan, Taiwan, Hong Kong
and Malaysia have all announced similar restrictions on Belgian and
other European imports.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps no country has been so quick or so thorough as
Singapore in eradicating all trace of Continental delicacies from
its shopping list. Singapore's ban extends to any food made with
European meat, eggs or dairy products. Hence, European cookies,
chocolates and even some pastas have been whisked away.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the European shortbreads, mayonnaise and even the
Toblerone chocolate bars. Citizens have been advised to throw out
or return anything from Belgium and put other European foodstuffs
at arm's length until the authorities deem them edible. The
Ministry of Environment says it has hundreds of inspectors scouring
the city for remaining items.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence for any Belgian leftovers is unequivocal:
incineration.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that so many European foods can be
found on tables here in the land of fish-head curry and pepper
crab. A growing expatriate community, more than a century of
European influence and, more recently, per capita incomes that
rival Europe's support a smorgasbord of foreign cuisines in this
prosperous tropical city.
</P>
<P>
   More remarkable is that even local manufacturers have been
affected because so many ingredients they use are shipped from
Europe. Some local bakeries, for example, have been deprived of
European egg powder for cakes and pastries. That a chicken eating
poisoned feed in Belgium could foul wedding cakes in Singapore is
yet another reminder of how borderless the global economy has
become.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, according to government figures, Singapore has
imported 14 tons of frozen Belgian pork, 60 tons of canned Belgian
pork and 17.6 tons of Belgian egg powder.
</P>
<P>
   Shops are posting signs vouching for non-European ingredients.
The ban has been a boon for products from Australia and New
Zealand, which offer alternatives to European products. ``We never
bothered to look at labels before,'' said one local shopper as he
scrutinized the fine print on a pint of Haagen-Dazs ice cream (made
in the United States) at the Cold Storage market.
</P>
<P>
   The dioxin debacle is actually the second food scare Singapore
has faced so far this year: A viral epidemic on Malaysian pig farms
diminished Singapore's taste for pork so severely that a local
television station broadcast scenes from a new, modern abattoir on
its prime-time news.
</P>
<P>
   Quek already buys Au Jardin's beef and veal from the United
States and Australia, a vestige of the mad-cow scare. But he prides
himself on using only French pigeons, ducks and free-range
chickens. Local chickens are raised in cages, he says, and are
comparatively flabby and tasteless. ``It will require the best
sauces,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The government ban exempts European products produced before
January, which means a reprieve for most slow-maturing hard
cheeses, Jenkins of the Cold Storage grocery said.
</P>
<P>
   But at Au Jardin, the cheese tray will take on a decidedly
different accent. ``We'll have to use Tasmanian,'' Quek says.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
