<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE GOP PUSHES BILLS TO INCREASE PATIENT'S RIGHTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Democrats stepping up the pressure for
Congress to overhaul the managed-care system, several influential
House Republicans introduced a package of legislation Wednesday
that would increase the rights of patients but would not remove the
high hurdles to suing managed-care providers.
</P>
<P>
   The bills put forward by Reps. Bill Goodling of Pennsylvania and
John A. Boehner of Ohio won quick praise from Speaker Dennis
Hastert of Illinois, who called them common-sense proposals. His
remarks suggested that the package was the approach the Republican
leadership now favored, after months of searching for a party
position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats plan to start signing a petition next week
intended to force their own competing legislation on health
maintenance organizations to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial question is whether Republican moderates will be
content with the signs that their party is now ready to engage the
issue or whether some will join forces with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic measure, called the patient's bill of rights, won
its first Republican co-sponsor Wednesday, Rep. Michael P. Forbes
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation urgently needs HMO reform, and the best bill out
there currently happens to be this patient's bill of rights,''
Forbes said. ``I believe in it to my core.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of giving patients more rights in a health-care
environment increasingly dominated by managed-care plans stirs more
interest than many issues before Congress. Both parties see it as a
potent issue in the election next year, when control of the House
will be up for grabs. That has made the maneuvering over health
care more intense than ever in both the House and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation similar to the new Republican package squeaked by in
the House last year, on a 216-to-210 vote, but was never considered
by the Senate. Since then the Democrats have won five more House
seats, and it was not clear how that would change the dynamics of
the issue in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said the measures they introduced Wednesday would
give patients more access to emergency rooms and allow patients to
go directly to obstetricians, pediatricians and gynecologists for
routine care without prior approval from their insurance companies.
They would also prohibit health plans from restricting what doctors
tell patients about treatment options.
</P>
<P>
   The package would allow consumers to appeal health-care
decisions to an outside board. Unlike last year's Republican
measure, the new package would consider the results of such an
appeal legally binding and enforceable through both prosecution and
fines, the Republicans said. But the legislation does not make it
easier for patients to sue HMOs under state law for punitive
damages the way the Democrats' bill and some competing Republican
versions do.
</P>
<P>
   The package would also allow employers to pool together to buy
health care for their workers, so they could try to negotiate lower
prices. The sponsors said this could help provide some coverage for
the 43 million Americans without health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and some Republicans argued Wednesday that the package
of legislation included many loopholes and still did too little to
help patients.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charlie Norwood, Republican of Georgia, who has been
drafting legislation closer to that put forward by the Democrats,
said he did not want to subject insurance companies to frivolous
lawsuits. But Norwood added that expanded rights to sue were
important to ``discourage insurance companies from dragging their
feet and taking forever'' to approve a costly treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John D. Dingell of Michigan, chief sponsor of the
Democratic bill, expressed suspicion that the Republicans were
presenting a package of individual bills instead of one
comprehensive measure to clear the way for only the least
controversial bills to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell asked why the Republicans had introduced multiple bills,
and he noted that there were various comprehensive measures already
drafted in the House.
</P>
<P>
   In both the House and the Senate, Democrats have been pushing in
concert for action on the health-care issue, which they have called
one of their highest priorities for the 106th Congress. With House
Democrats beginning their petition drive to push their legislation
to the floor, Senate Democrats have threatened to start trying to
tack their plan onto other Senate bills as an amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the Senate passed their own managed-care
legislation _ similar to the House proposal _ out of one committee
earlier this year. But the bill has been bogged down in the
tax-writing committee because of disputes over tax incentive
provisions and review processes to settle disputes between patients
and health plans. Senate leaders are trying to reach an agreement
that would allow the legislation to come to the floor this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
