<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON, VISITING BINGHAMTON, PRAISES TECHNOLOGY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton stepped gingerly into
her apparent political campaign Wednesday, taking questions from
workers at an electronics plant and mixing with contributors at a
fund-raising reception for a Democratic congressman. It was Mrs.
Clinton's first trip to New York state since she announced plans to
form an exploratory committee to consider running for the U.S.
Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   While she never specifically discussed the topic of her
anticipated campaign, it was clear that Mrs. Clinton was being
taken increasingly seriously by politicians and the public as the
likely Democratic contender in next year's Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   At the reception Wednesday evening, a fund-raiser for Rep.
Maurice D. Hinchey, Mrs. Clinton received an enthusiastic response.
While she spoke broadly on themes varying from the need for
refurbished school buildings to manufacturing products under
environmentally friendly techniques, the crowd of more than 300
seemed receptive to Hinchey's description of the first lady as ``an
important resource for this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters following the reception, Mrs. Clinton was
asked about an issue that is expected to play a dominant role in
the campaign: criticism of her as a carpetbagger who has never
lived in the state of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made any decision yet,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``And
when and if I do there will be plenty of time to talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, sounding as if she had already entered the race in
earnest, she said, ``I have found in my many visits to New York
that the kinds of issues that people in New York talk to me about
are the kinds of issues that I have worked on for more than 30
years and have worked on very intensely in the last six and a half
years.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that what New York voters ``really care about is a
partnership between the public and private sectors, about how we're
going to keep good jobs; how we're going to keep the best education
system.'' Those issues, she said, ``are the kinds of issues that I
have a long interest and experience in.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Mrs. Clinton has been trying use her frequent
travels to New York as a way of establishing some connection to the
state, where she has never lived. It was her 11th visit to New York
this year. After the fund-raising event for Hinchey, a four-term
Democrat who represents the Southern Tier near the Pennsylvania
border, Mrs. Clinton departed for New York City, where she will
appear on the NBC television program ``Today,'' on Thursday
morning, and visit a school in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's first stop here was at a Lockheed Martin
electronics plant in Union, a town on the outskirts of Binghamton.
At the plant, where electronic controls are made, Mrs. Clinton met
with about 40 employees. She took questions on subjects including
health care and Federal spending on research and development. But,
as has been her custom in her last 10 visits, Mrs. Clinton's visit
was carefully calibrated, keeping her far from the public and at
arms length from the press.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as a harbinger of the passions her candidacy is likely
to unleash, about 100 demonstrators stood outside of the Holiday
Inn hotel, where the fund-raising reception was held. Many of them
jeered Mrs. Clinton, holding signs reading ``Hillary Go Home'' and
``Hillary: Go Back to Arkansas, You Carpetbagger.'' There were also
cheering supporters outside the hotel, holding signs saying
``Hillary, Our Next Senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Her visit to the Binghamton area appears to focus on the kind of
terrain that pollsters have suggested the First Lady will need in
her apparent effort to win election next year: areas where
Republicans have won but where Democratic candidates can still gain
a receptive ear.
</P>
<P>
   This area, which has voted often for Republicans statewide and
overwhelmingly supported Gov. George E. Pataki, has been
represented in Congress by Democrats since 1975. While Republicans
hold the mayor's office and a majority of the City Council in
Binghamton, there is a Democratic Town Supervisor in Union, its
more populous neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for New York City, Mrs. Clinton pledged that she
would return. ``There's something I'm particularly looking forward
to,'' she said. ``And that's listening to the people of New York.
So, I'll be back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
