<SLUG> BC-ALLSTATE-CNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLSTATE BUYING PART OF CNA'S BUSINESS FOR $1.2 BILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (rk) 
 By SHOLNN FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Allstate Corp. said Wednesday that it would buy the personal
insurance business of CNA Financial Corp. for $1.2 billion,
expanding its business with independent insurance agents who sell
auto and homeowners policies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Allstate will pay CNA $140 million
in cash and commit as much as $950 million in new capital to the
business. Allstate will also pay CNA Insurance a marketing royalty
for use of the CNA name over the next six years, a payment that is
projected to total about $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate plans to set up a new unit called CNA Personal
Insurance, which will hire all 2,000 employees of the CNA Financial
unit. It will be headed by Bruce W. Marlow, a former chief
operating officer of the Progressive Corp., a large insurer, and
based in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Allstate rose 68.75 cents Wednesday, to $38.6875,
while CNA fell 37.5 cents, to $42.437.
</P>
<P>
   CNA will maintain ties to the new unit, with the appointment of
a special adviser to its board. The CNA management team for
personal lines of insurance will largely remain the same, CNA said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will bolster Allstate's personal insurance
business segment that is serviced by independent agents, who help
clients choose the best policies among several insurers.
Historically, Allstate has generated most of its business through
its own 15,000 agents who sell only Allstate policies. Before
Wednesday, it ranked ninth in the market of personal insurance sold
through independent agents.
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of the CNA unit, which has about 3,800
independent agents to sell its personal insurance products,
Allstate will become the nation's third-largest insurer selling
personal policies through brokers representing multiple companies.
Allstate's total annual insurance premium revenue from that market
will more than double to $3 billion. Independent agents account for
a total of $45 billion in revenue in the personal insurance
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's announcement is very consistent with Allstate's
strategy to expand independent agent channels with acquisitions,''
said Kenneth S. Zuckerberg, a senior analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP;
Woods. ``It seems to be a very good strategic fit.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call Wednesday, Bernard L. Hengesbaugh, chief
executive of CNA Insurance, said CNA was selling the personal
insurance line so that it could get back to its core business of
commercial and casualty insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Debreceny, a spokesman for Allstate, said the deal would
face no significant regulatory hurdles. CNA policyholders will not
see any big changes, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
