<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA STARTS SEASON WITH UPBEAT ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The WNBA is set to begin its third season today in the best of
both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   With the inclusion of 35 players from the defunct American
Basketball League, a celebrated college star, two new franchises to
bring the number of teams to 12, a 32-game schedule, an extended
playoff schedule, and the inaugural All-Star Game, the league is
poised to better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact that the country's top talent has finally unified
into one league makes it that more appealing. Add to the mix
top-draft pick Chamique Holdsclaw, a four-time All-American from
Tennessee, and the competition in the WNBA this season will be a
notch above the previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that every team in the league has
gotten better and I believe there is going to be some compelling
stories this year,'' league president Val Ackerman said. ``How
Houston will do for example, whether Brian Agler can bring his
magic in Columbus to Minnesota, how quickly some of the college
seniors will emerge top players, and in particular Chamique
(Holdsclaw), and obviously the impact of top-quality players like
Dawn Staley, Jen Azzi, Yolanda Griffith, Natalie Williams, and
Katie Smith, when she's finally able to play after her knee is
officially recovered?''
</P>
<P>
   The two-time defending champion Houston Comets will be
hard-pressed to stay on top, particularly with the Western
Conference improving drastically with the drafting of high profile
players like Griffith to the Sacramento Monarchs, Williams to the
Utah Jazz and DeLisha Milton to the Los Angeles Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that there is any doubt that everybody else has
closed the gap on us talent-wise,'' Houston coach Van Chancellor
said. ``And everybody in this league is so much better. The games
are going to be so much closer.''
</P>
<P>
   But the undisputed heavyweight Comets still did a lot to improve
upon a team stacked with talent in two-time MVP Cynthia Cooper,
Sheryl Swoopes, and Tina Thompson. However, instead of using their
first pick to draft a point guard to replace Kim Perrot, who
underwent surgery to remove brain tumors, Chancellor went for size,
taking 6-foot-3 Natalia Zassoulskaia from Russia in the first
round. But they added capable Sonya Henning from the ABL to fill
the void at the point.
</P>
<P>
   Is a third championship in store for the Comets?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we have a shot at it,'' Chancellor said. ``We've
lost Kim (Perrot). That's an adjustment. We've had a lot of
adjusting to do. But a lot of teams have. It boils down to does the
ball go in at the end or does it come out at the end. You never
know.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 runner-up Phoenix Mercury are going to be knocking on
the door, but Cheryl Miller's challenge is to integrate her foreign
players, many whom were playing in the European Championship, into
her game plan quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Agler, winner of two ABL championship with the Columbus Quest,
surrounded himself with some of his former players with Smith,
Andrea Lloyd, Tonya Edwards and Trisha Fallon to the Minnesota
Lynx.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like there is some pressure,'' Agler said. ``Everybody
looks at that Columbus team and some of those players, but I don't
consider us being Columbus, I consider us being the Minnesota
Lynx.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Eastern Conference, Charlotte is looking more like a
championship contender after adding leadership to a veteran squad
when they brought in Dawn Staley, who left the ABL before it
folded. She joins an experienced squad that finished second in
conference last year with Andrea Stinson and Tracy Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte head coach Marynell Meaders was just happy and
surprised to see Staley still available by the ninth pick in the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question about it, what she has brought to our
team has been leadership,'' Meadors said. ``She has brought
consistent shooting from the perimeter, which is something we
needed to address in the draft. I think the number one thing she's
brought to our team is that she's a well-respected veteran point
guard and people are listening to her and going on her cues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Mystics, which had the best attendance in the
league last year, shouldn't have a problem duplicating their
success at the gate and the standings (they won only three games
last year) between Holdsclaw and Nikki McCray.
</P>
<P>
   New York has a new coach and new hopes; Orlando, under the
tuteledge of Carolyn Peck, the former Purdue coach who led the
Boilermakers to their first NCAA championship, is expecting to find
success in the pros; while Detroit and Cleveland are working
through injuries to prepare for their opener.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the WNBA's third season looks more like the
beginning of something new and better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
