<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMENS-WORLD-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN WORLD CUP TEAM REAPS BENEFIT OF AMERICA'S SPECIAL EXPORT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has required no slight adjustment for the Mexican-American
players who make up half the roster on Mexico's team for the
Women's World Cup. In contrast to the well-oiled machinery of U.S.
women's soccer on and off the field, the simple act of catching the
Mexican team bus can turn into an action movie.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, before an exhibition match in Mexico City, the
bus failed to show up. The Mexican team found itself stranded at
its training center, miles from the stadium. Soccer being a game of
spontaneous, unexpected moves, the players improvised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We flagged down a public bus; luckily it was empty,'' said
Laurie Hill, a midfielder from Los Angeles, who added that 17
players, two coaches, the team doctor and the equipment manager,
along with ice coolers and ball bags were crammed into a bus,
capacity 15. ``And we bribed the guy to take us to the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hill and her colleagues, given the chance to play in women's
soccer's premier event, are not complaining. Eligibility rules have
always been an elastic _ and sometimes abused _ aspect of
international soccer. FIFA, the sport's world governing body,
limits every player's career to one national team. Beyond that, it
abides by the citizenship rules of individual countries.
</P>
<P>
   David Regis, a Frenchman, played for the U.S. men in the 1998
World Cup because he married an American woman and had his American
citizenship expedited under a law usually reserved for the families
of servicemen. The captain of that American team, Thomas Dooley,
grew up in Germany, the son of a German mother and an American
soldier, and he could not speak enough English to buy a postcard
when he obtained his citizenship in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Under a recent law, people with a parent born in Mexico can
claim Mexican nationality. Hill was a three-time all-American at
the University of California-Santa Barbara whose mother is a native
of Mexico City. Monica Gerardo, the career leading scorer at Notre
Dame, qualified because her father was born in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it as an opportunity to play soccer at the highest level
and to check back into my heritage,'' said Hill, 29, who twice
attended American training camps but never made the women's
national team. ``I knew my chance to play for the U.S. was past.
When I got this chance, I jumped on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said she had made only several trips to Mexico before
joining the national team. A story in the Mexican news media
accused her of being a soccer carpetbagger, she said, and
questioned whether her mother, Ida, was actually born in Mexico.
She was, Hill said, adding that an uncle still lived in Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm playing for China,'' Hill said. ``I think
most players feel a connection with the people and the culture.
Mexican people feel soccer in their blood. I've always had that
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea to use Mexican-Americans came from Karlo Pedrin, a
restaurateur in Tijuana who lives in San Diego, and whose
16-year-old daughter, Tawnie, is an accomplished club team player
in Southern California. Women in Mexico are still fighting the
perception that they are unwomanly if they play soccer. The
national team trained for all of two weeks before trying, and
failing, to qualify for the 1995 Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   North of the border, however, the sport thrives. Pedrin figured
that Mexico could qualify for the Women's World Cup, and the
Olympics, with Mexican-American players, affording his daughter a
possible chance to play in the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Pedrin persuaded the Mexican soccer federation to use his plan,
but he has since cut his ties to the team. He has filed a lawsuit
against the federation claiming that it owes him $50,000 for his
role in recruitment. One soccer official said he left in a power
struggle. Pedrin, a native of Mexico, said he became concerned that
players too removed from their Hispanic roots _ Americans whose
grandparents, not parents, were born in Mexico _ were being placed
on the team.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was concerned that fake birth certificates had been
used and that an American player named Monica Gonzalez had played
in an exhibition against the United States in March before she
received her Mexican nationality. Pedrin feared Mexico could suffer
penalties, just as the men's team was prevented from participating
in the 1990 World Cup in Italy because it had used overage players
in a youth tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Aceves Campos, an official in the Mexican soccer
federation, said that six players were born in the United States,
and that those with Mexican grandparents were also eligible for
dual nationality. Campos said proper procedures were followed and
accused Pedrin of being on a ``personal campaign to discredit the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo Cuellar, coach of the Mexican women's team, said the
citizenship issue had been a distraction, complete with anonymous
letters sent to the Mexican federation, but that he had been
assured ``that everything is in order.'' Keith Cooper, a spokesman
for FIFA, said he was unaware of any formal complaints against the
Mexican team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have gone through a legally binding procedure, and
documents have been issued by a sovereign state, who are we to cast
aspersions on that process?'' Cooper said. ``It is a remarkable
tribute to American soccer that Mexico is able to use American
women to bolster its team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuellar, a former star of the Mexican men's team who also
coaches men's soccer at the University of California-Los Angeles,
took over the women's team last November and guided it into the
World Cup with two playoff victories over Argentina. He said he
called 29 soccer associations in Mexico, seeking the best female
players, but only six associations responded. ``We have some
amateur leagues, and it is growing on the college level, but is
more recreational soccer than anything organized,'' Cuellar said.
``It's a cultural thing, that ladies shouldn't do athletic and
aggressive sports. Mexican women have always been around soccer,
but mostly to support men. It's not like in America, where girls
start playing at 5 years old. But we have created a curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   At a mountain training camp, Hill said the players had no heat
and little hot water, and had to build their own fire and sleep in
several layers of clothing to stay warm. In Mexico City, she said,
guards patrol the training center and players are not allowed to
leave without permission, for fear of their safety. Because the
men's under-20 team is also in camp, Hill said, the 20 members of
the women's team have been squeezed into four rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never had a women's team,'' Hill said. ``It's kind of
like they don't know what to do with us, what to allow us. It's
quite a different experience, but I love Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the native and naturalized Mexicans have required
adjustments, Cuellar said. The result is not the most talented team
in the World Cup, but one of the most intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have several players who had never gotten on a plane, some
who had never been out of the country, some who have college
degrees, some who finished only elementary school,'' Cuellar said.
``A couple of the Mexican girls are very wealthy. Some live in
places where there is no running water. Everyone feels welcome.
It's nice to see how they have melded together through preparation.
Our common goal is to play strong.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
