<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BETTMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL COMMISSIONER ISSUES A WARNING TO THE ISLANDERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If the New York Islanders trade Zigmund Palffy while
trying to reduce their payroll, they had better get some hockey
value for him and not just a large sum of money.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bettman, the commissioner of the NHL, has enough financial
embarrassments to deal with, particularly the bankrupt Pittsburgh
Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual news conference Wednesday at the Stanley Cup
finals, Bettman discussed the Islanders in language which, for him,
was unusually blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will monitor all of the trades and make sure that we are
comfortable from a hockey standpoint that the team simply isn't
being stripped down,'' Bettman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected the Islanders' management to present a team
``that hasn't just simply been created to slash payroll without
regard to the hockey consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding a transaction for any combination of players, draft
choices or money, Bettman did not discuss a specific threshold or
formula that might trigger a nullification. But he implied that he
had the power to stop such a deal and would be willing to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to go through a balancing act of making sure that
the losses aren't so severe that the ownership doesn't give up,''
Bettman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders have discussed a trade for Palffy, their
highest-paid and most-talented player, with several teams. Among
those teams are the New York Rangers, Chicago Black Hawks and Los
Angeles Kings, three of the league's high-profile teams who play in
major markets, have significant cash flow and missed the playoffs
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, 27 years old, is a six-year veteran who will earn $5
million next season on a long-term contract. In 331 NHL games,
Palffy has scored 331 points, 168 of them goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders have been a significant league concern for several
seasons. Recently, their current owners have battled Nassau County
and their Nassau Coliseum management firm over the condition of
their arena and the terms of their lease, which does not expire
until 2015.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders have said that they lost more than $20 million in
1998-99, a season that began when they threatened to vacate the
Coliseum, alleging safety concerns. The majority owners are Howard
Milstein, Edward Milstein and Steven Gluckstern, who bought 90
percent of the team for a reported $195 million in 1998 with the
expectation of a new arena on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``While ownership clearly has made mistakes, the fact is the
prospects of being in the Nassau Coliseum for the next 15 or 20
years for the duration of that lease is not something that anybody
in their right mind would continue to fund on an ongoing basis,''
Bettman said. ``Last year the club lost a lot of money. Some of it
was self-inflicted.''
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that the Islanders, through general manager Mike
Milbury, are trying to cut the payroll for next season. They
recently traded Trevor Linden, another of their best players, to
Montreal for a first-round draft choice. Linden earned $2.5 million
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman has urged the current ownership group to sell the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a specific warning call from the
commissioner,'' John Sanders, the Islanders' new president, said
Wednesday in a telephone interview when asked about the parameters
for trades.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders acknowledged that Bettman's concerns are known to
the Islanders' ownership and management.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might look at anyone on the roster, and Ziggy's on the
payroll and the roster,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about a possible sale of the team, Sanders said the
current owners are not trying to sell now and that it was unlikely
that someone would want to buy the franchise under its current
lease.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, negotiations with the county could resume soon
and the team's owners hope for a better outcome. Only then, Sanders
and Bettman acknowledged, could a new buyer be interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is particularly interested in finding themselves in the
same situation we are in now,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, the Penguins are in U.S. Bankruptcy Court under
Chapter 11 conditions. A decision on their future is expected June
24, Bettman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was asked if the Islanders, in view of their financial
condition, would consider similar tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not considering a bankruptcy,'' Sanders said. ``Our
focus is a new arena.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
