<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUPONT-CEO10-COX     06-09 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPONT-CEO10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DuPont Photomasks loses CEO Hardinger
 &HT;    BJerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ J. Michael Hardinger, who guided DuPont
Photomasks Inc.'s spinoff as a publicly traded company in 1996 and
oversaw its global expansion while the chip industry suffered
through a three-year slump, resigned as the company's chief
executive and chairman Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old Hardinger said he will help oversee operations
of the company while it searches for a new CEO. In the meantime,
board member Marshall Turner will serve as interim CEO and
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Photomask makers such as DuPont etch chip makers' patented
designs on quartz plates. The plates are used to produce integrated
circuits on silicon wafers.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-year employee of E.I. DuPont de Nemours and Co., Hardinger
was tapped by the Wilmington, Del., research and technology giant
to help take its wholly owned photomask subsidiary public on June
13, 1996, when the chip industry was in a cyclical slump.
</P>
<P>
   The stock opened at $17 a share and reached a high of $72.62 1/2
on Sept. 30, 1997. Wednesday, the stock closed at $42.25, up 50
cents, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hardinger, DuPont Photomasks added manufacturing
facilities in Round Rock, Oregon, and Asia, bringing to 10 the
number of manufacturing sites.
</P>
<P>
   Since going public, the company has grown from about 1,200
employees to 1,500, including 300 at its headquarters in Round
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   While its size has grown, its profits haven't.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1998, DuPont Photomasks' revenue grew 4 percent to
$271.6 million, but profit declined 9 percent to $33.5 million, in
part because of the slump.
</P>
<P>
   Hardinger, whose base salary was $315,000, and other senior
executives did not get bonuses that year, according to reports
filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts give Hardinger credit for guiding the company
through its transition to a public company and leaving it
positioned for recent recovery in the chip industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook has improved,'' said Susan Billat of BancBoston
Robertson Stephens in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hardinger is leaving at a time when they've come through a
difficult period. They were aggressive on both the capacity and
technology side.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wu of ABN Amro in San Francisco said Hardinger's departure
is a logical transition for the company and an opportunity to hire
a CEO with a more technical background.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably need someone who comes in with a higher profile
. . . in the semiconductor world,'' Wu said.
</P>
<P>
   Hardinger said he and his wife, Cara, hope to stay in Austin. He
said he has no immediate plans to look for another job, but said he
looks forward to spending more time at home and ending a grueling
schedule _ about 75 percent of his time _ meeting with customers
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
