<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
DiSARCINA OPENS REHAB AT SINGLE A 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shortstop Gary DiSarcina had X-rays on his left
forearm Wednesday, which showed his broken bone has healed
properly. He'll begin a rehab assignment today at Single-A Lake
Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, who was examined by hand and wrist specialist Dr.
Norman Zemel, will stay in Lake Elsinore through the weekend before
traveling Monday to Erie, Pa., to play with the club's Double-A
affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels play an exhibition game against Erie on June 21, an
off day during their next trip. DiSarcina is expected to join the
club then and travel with his teammates to Seattle, where he'd join
the lineup on June 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to be released from parole,'' DiSarcina said.
``There's no reason to be cautious. I knew physically before the
X-rays I could do it. To hear the doctor say you're all right takes
a lot of pressure off your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina broke a bone in his left forearm Feb. 21 in his first
workout of spring training when coach George Hendrick inadvertently
hit him with a fungo bat. DiSarcina had surgery to insert a metal
plate in the forearm April 1.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't expected back until the All-Star break but said
there's no reason to take it slowly now.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I'm going to bail out of Erie as soon as I feel
I'm capable of playing in the big leagues,'' he said. ``There's a
little nervousness. It's like spring training, a little of
everything. I'm eager to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the Angels' injuries and how desperate
they are to get those players back. But DiSarcina said he won't
carry the weight of the team's troubles on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel pressure, but I believe one person can make a
difference,'' he said. ``It's a matter of what type of difference.
I've seen games when I know I could have made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) I'm not going to produce like last year immediately. I'm
not going to blink my eyes and get back to that level. Every swing
is going to be a battle. Every swing is going to be ugly. Guys are
going to laugh at me, but I'm going to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares update: Pitcher Omar Olivares, who missed Wednesday's
start because of a strained left hamstring, will return to the
rotation Sunday against the Arizona Diamondbacks at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omar threw off the mound (Tuesday) and it didn't bother him,''
Angels manager Terry Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares hurt his hamstring last Friday trying to beat out an
infield grounder against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Giants left fielder Barry Bonds returned to the lineup
Wednesday for the first time since having surgery on his left arm
April 20. Bonds was expected to miss 10 weeks but returned in seven
weeks. He went 0 for 4.... The Angels are off today. They begin a
three-game series at Edison Field against the Diamondbacks
beginning Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
