<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-DOCUMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SEES PRIVACY THREAT IN DEMOCRATS' BID FOR DOCUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont.)   (bl)  
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move that has touched off a furor on Capitol
Hill, Democratic strategists are seeking reams of official
documents in a search for grist to use against Republican senators
up for re-election next year.
</P>
<P>
   The document hunt was undertaken under the Freedom of
Information Act, a tactic that the Democrats called perfectly
appropriate but that the Republicans characterized as a threat to
personal freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute became public Wednesday when Sen. Conrad Burns of
Montana, one of the 10 Republicans up for re-election in 2000,
complained on the Senate floor about a letter the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee sent to the Department of Health and
Human Services on May 18 seeking copies of all correspondence
between the department and the senators from their first days in
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there are any Americans alive who think politics can't sink
any lower, they need look no further than the DSCC,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said the Democrats' efforts, if successful, could
invade the privacy of countless ordinary, nonpolitical Americans
who get help from their senators in dealing with the vast federal
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This effort is as constitutionally breathtaking as it is
politically suspect,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Jordan, a spokesman for the Democratic senatorial
committee, said the Republicans' complaints reflected ``a
fundamental misunderstanding'' of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not impinging _ we do not want to, and we cannot _ on
the privacy rights of anyone,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the Freedom of Information Act, passed by Congress
in 1966 and used by journalists and private citizens to obtain
official records, requires that personal information be crossed out
before the documents are turned over. A Senator's contacts with and
efforts to lobby agencies ``are a perfectly legitimate subject of
scrutiny,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns' chief of staff, Matt Raymond, said the Democrats'
document search could have ``a chilling effect'' on Americans who
need help from lawmakers. The senator himself said he was so
outraged that he wrote to President Clinton to complain.
</P>
<P>
   And a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, said Lott
was ``extremely troubled'' and would meet with Minority Leader Tom
Daschle to express his unease.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Roy, Jordan's counterpart at the Republican senatorial
campaign office, said his organization had not used the Freedom of
Information Act, at least in the two years he has been with the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said that Democrats had used the Freedom of Information
Act before and that requests like the one sent May 18 to the
Department of Health and Human Services and signed by Alexis
Schuler, the Democratic senatorial committee's research director,
had been sent to several other agencies. Jordan said those agencies
would be notified that ``only that information which bears directly
on a senator's discharge of his or her official duties'' was
sought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0497 </DOCNO>
