<SLUG> BC-CATHAY-AIR-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTLOOK DIM AS CATHAY PACIFIC AIR NEGOTIATES WITH PILOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Managers from Cathay Pacific Airways and
representatives of the Hong Kong airline's pilot union spent more
than eight hours Wednesday in pay negotiations that industry
analysts said were unlikely to avoid a wave of pilot resignations
and dismissals Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to cut labor costs and return to profitability, the
airline has given its senior pilots until noon Friday to accept
stock options in return for pay cuts or quit with a severance
package. Pilots who fail to pick either option by the deadline will
be dismissed with three months' pay, Cathay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to leave the company, the best thing to do is
accept the voluntary separation scheme and leave with dignity and a
lot more money,'' said Tony Tyler, the director of corporate
development at Cathay Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials were not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Many pilots have responded to the ultimatum by saying they are
under too much stress to fly. Large numbers of pilots have called
in sick over the last two weeks, and Cathay has been force to
ground up to 60 percent of its scheduled flights and charter planes
from 13 airlines to help take up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate the airline is losing roughly $30 million
(Hong Kong), or $3.9 million (U.S.), a day in revenue, not
including what it has to pay other airlines to carry its
increasingly disgruntled passengers. The union has threatened to
call a strike vote if pilots are dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   According to analysts, the latest round of negotiations is
unlikely to produce any new compromise because Cathay is cash-rich
and can afford to allow many of its pilots to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler said that most Cathay captains earn $220,000 (U.S.) a
year, making them among the most highly paid in commercial
aviation. The union disputes that figure, but independent industry
surveys of pilot pay are kept confidential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-09-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990609.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-09 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WNBA-NYT &LR;      06-09 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WNBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOOK TO START WNBA SEASON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chamique Holdsclaw had just been made the first pick in the
Women's National Basketball Association draft last spring, and
already the technicians were scurrying around her. Within five
minutes, she was looking into a camera as her carefully styled
hair, makeup and wardrobe were beamed out for a league that will
use her to launch it on a new trajectory when its regular season
opens on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw's arrival is propitious for the WNBA as it commences
its third season, perhaps its most pivotal. Gone, by the admission
of the league's president, Valerie B. Ackerman, is the novelty of a
women's professional league, a newness that was exploited with
perfect pitch by the vast marketing machine of the National
Basketball Association, which created the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   With the demise of the American Basketball League, the other
women's league, the WNBA is poised to present a level of play that
will back up the ubiquitous promotion. That is partly a result of
an extraordinary draft in which the WNBA absorbed a crop of
collegians and foreigners along with 40 players from the ABL, a
league that had a wealth of player talent but a dearth of business
savvy.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA has expanded to 12 teams and the schedule to 32 games
this year, including, for the first time, an All-Star Game, to be
played July 14 at Madison Square Garden. Six teams will make the
playoffs, an increase of two over the first two seasons. At last,
everyone agrees, it is time for the women's game to be judged on
the talent of its players and the competitiveness of its games, not
on the business acumen of its founders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever curiosity that may have existed about the league is
long past us,'' Ackerman said. ``Now, more than ever before, people
are going to be looking to the quality of the play to determine
whether or not we really have a future. Our league is going to
stand or fail on that basis: how good a game we have and how much
fans want to support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw will be one of the critical players in that judgment
as she plays her rookie season for the Washington Mystics. She
comes from Astoria, N.Y., by way of the University of Tennessee,
where she was twice selected the collegiate player of the year.
Already she is being compared to Michael Jordan _ she will wear his
number _ and is considered, perhaps prematurely, the greatest woman
to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   The stars who helped build women's professional basketball might
have something to say about that. Cheryl Miller, coach of the
Phoenix Mercury, and Nancy Lieberman-Cline, coach of the Detroit
Shock, first made people pay attention to the women's game. Rebecca
Lobo, playing center for the New York Liberty, helped bring it to a
mainstream audience.
</P>
<P>
   But with the WNBA now having enough talent to complement the
star power of Holdsclaw, she is expected to propel it to the next
level, presumably a very successful and lucrative one.
</P>
<P>
   ``With myself and the ABL players, definitely in a couple of
years the players and league will grow,'' Holdsclaw said. ``I think
the sky is the limit. You have the best talent all in one league.
Of course you expect it to be two times better.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if her rookie game lags a bit, Holdsclaw's more immediate
impact will be at the cash register. Despite winning only three
games last season, the Mystics led the league in attendance with a
crowd average of almost 16,000 a game, and they hope to sell 1,000
to 2,000 more season tickets than last season. Thursday night, the
Mystics expect a sellout crowd of 20,000 as they open the season
against Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw should also be a huge draw on the road, which will
help some teams that are struggling. Franchises in Los Angeles and
Sacramento have failed to average even 8,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said the WNBA was optimistic about its overall
finances. All sponsorship deals will be up for renewal, because
they were negotiated for three years when the league began. She
expects the league to average 10,000 fans a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Some teams have been doing well, like the Liberty, which has
been second in attendance in both seasons. The Liberty has exceeded
last year's season-ticket sales of 6,300 and drew a staggering
crowd of 13,690 for an exhibition game on May 22 in the Garden
against the Houston Comets.
</P>
<P>
   So confident is the league of success that it has added two
teams this season, in Orlando and Minnesota, and will expand with
four more next season. Because of the wealth of talent from the
ABL, this is not typical expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Orlando nor Minnesota _ which could select five ABL
players each while the established teams could choose three _
should be a league doormat. Every team got much better with this
draft, and the days when one team would dominate, as the Comets did
last season, are probably over.
</P>
<P>
   Close, well-played games should make the league more interesting
to casual fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think if there isn't a breakout, there's trouble,''
Lobo said. ``But this year, there's potential for that kind of
explosion. The focus isn't going to be on which is the better
league, is this hollow promotion, should women play in summer,
because all those questions have been answered. Instead, they will
focus on the play on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Chancellor, coach of the Comets, the two-time defending
champions, sounded a note of caution, however. He has been a
women's basketball coach since 1978 and has watched the sport's
slow, laborious ascent. While he expected observers to be shocked
by the improved level of competition this season, he also predicted
it would take a bit longer before the league wins over doubters
about the quality of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand this: It's only our third year of
existence,'' he said. ``So many people want a miracle. Let's be
realistic. It's important to us to have a good year, but let's have
expectations that aren't so high we can't possibly meet them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can expect an improvement. Is that going to catch on
overnight? I don't know. Any product you put out there, it takes
time for word of mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor's concerns are well-founded. When the major
professional sports leagues are listed, the WNBA is not among those
for football, baseball, basketball and hockey. It is lumped with
Major League Soccer, somewhere in the nether world of sports.
Perhaps that will be Holdsclaw's greatest responsibility as she
begins her first season: to hoist the WNBA on her narrow shoulders
and carry it to a higher level of legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a year for us to take a step,'' Chancellor said. ``The
fans will be amazed at the talent of these players. You're going to
notice a difference. When the product gets out there, I think the
fans will love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
