<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MULL ROSTER CHOICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
LOS ANGELES _ The Rangers are unsure whether outfielder Mike Simms
will be reinstated from the 15-day disabled list Friday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Simms (torn left Achilles' tendon) completed his second
medical-rehabilitation assignment Monday, and the Rangers will have
to make room on the 25-man roster if the outfielder is to be
reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Could that be the reason for right-hander Danny Patterson's
marked improvement of late?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's a coincidence,'' said Patterson, who went
into Wednesday's game with a streak of 72/3 scoreless innings
spanning four appearances. ``When your back is up against the wall,
that's when you find out what you're made of.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, who once appeared to be the leading candidate to be
optioned to Triple-A Oklahoma to make room on the roster for Simms,
pitched 31/3 scoreless innings with three strikeouts in the
Rangers' 7-6, 13-inning victory Tuesday against Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope it's not too little, too late,'' Patterson said.
``We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could leave Simms on the 15-day disabled list and do
nothing. ``There's a difference between being OK and 100 percent,''
Oates said. Gonzalez ejection Plate umpire Wally Bell ejected right
fielder Juan Gonzalez after Gonzalez's ninth-inning at-bat Tuesday
resulted in his third strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who drove in the 999th run of his career with a
first-inning homer off right-hander Darren Dreifort, dropped his
bat at the plate in disgust after the called third strike and
walked directly to the Rangers' dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Bell instructed Gonzalez to ``pick up the bat,'' said the
outfielder, who added that he said nothing to the umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said absolutely nothing, but that's all right,'' said
Gonzalez, who suffered his first ejection in the major leagues.
``I'm fine today.'' Unclothed appearance The Rangers' two-game
winning streak includes a streaker.
</P>
<P>
   An unidentified spectator rushed the playing surface wearing
only an unbuttoned Dodgers uniform in the top of the eighth inning
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took a 6-4 lead into the bottom of the eighth inning
before right-hander Tim Crabtree and closer John Wetteland
surrendered eighth- and ninth-inning solo home runs to Los Angeles'
Raul Mondesi and Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was their rally streaker,'' Crabtree said. Morgan records
first balk Right-hander Mike Morgan committed the Rangers' first
balk this season in the third inning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's right foot slipped out of the hole in front of the
rubber, and he delivered an awkward pitch after losing contact with
the rubber. The balk allowed center fielder Trenidad Hubbard to
score from third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to go grab him and keep him from crossing the
plate,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who allowed four runs on six hits and two walks in 32/3
innings, said fatigue played a role in his undoing. The Rangers
reinstated Morgan from the disabled list before the game, but
inactivity obviously hindered his stamina.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that 39-pitch third inning, it was a problem,'' Morgan
said. ``That slammed me. We won as a team, but I beat myself.''
Briefly On Wednesday, the Rangers agreed to contract terms with
outfielder Orlando Cruz of Jose Collazo Colon High School in Puerto
Rico, their 17th-round selection last week in the 1999 draft. Cruz
will be assigned to the Rangers' rookie-league affiliate in the
Gulf Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers stole a season-high six bases Tuesday with Dodgers
catcher Todd Hundley behind the plate. Hundley underwent major
reconstructive surgery on his right elbow in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' 35-22 record matches their best record through 57
games. The 1996 and '98 Rangers also won 35 of their first 57 games
en route to the organization's two American League West titles. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
