<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER SAYS VOLPE WOULD TAKE POLYGRAPH 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The lawyer for Justin A. Volpe, who pleaded guilty to
torturing Abner Louima in a station house restroom, said Wednesday
that Volpe was willing to take a polygraph test to establish that
another police officer was wrongly convicted on Tuesday of helping
carry out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The contention by the lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, who said his
client maintained that the officer convicted Tuesday, Charles
Schwarz, had not even been at the scene of the torture, added a
bitter twist to the explosive case. It stirred new rancor as both
the prosecution and Schwarz's lawyer denounced Kornberg's assertion
and offer.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor said Kornberg was not to be believed and suggested
he was promoting a hoax. Schwarz's lawyer, Stephen C. Worth, said
that Kornberg's claim and offer were of no legal value to Schwarz
and suggested that Kornberg was seeking a return to the limelight
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz was convicted by a jury in U.S. District Court on
Tuesday of having violated Louima's civil rights by holding him
down while Volpe _ who had interrupted the trial to plead guilty _
rammed a stick into Louima's rectum, inflicting severe injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Two other officers, Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder, were
acquitted of beating Louima in a police car before the stick
attack, which occurred in a restroom at the 70th Precinct station
house in Brooklyn. A sergeant, Michael Bellomo, was acquitted of
charges that included trying to cover up the reported beating.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdict was read on Tuesday, Kornberg told reporters
that the jury had wrongly convicted Schwarz. Kornberg said that, on
Volpe's behalf, he had told the prosecutors _ several days before
his client's guilty plea on May 25 _ that the second officer who
had been in the bathroom with Volpe and Louima had not been Schwarz
but someone else. Kornberg said he had given the prosecutors that
officer's name.
</P>
<P>
   One of the prosecutors in the case, Alan Vinegrad, had responded
Tuesday that Kornberg and Volpe had no credibility on that or any
other issue. Wednesday, Kornberg answered that dismissal by telling
reporters that Volpe ``would be willing to take a polygraph with
respect to this issue of who was in the bathroom with him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Vinegrad, chief of the criminal division of the
U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn, made it clear that his view had
not changed. Referring to the offer of a polygraph test, Vinegrad
said, ``Comments or suggestions from the Volpe defense team _ which
tried to perpetrate an enormous hoax during the trial of this case
_ have no credibility and are not worthy of response.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``hoax'' remark was Vinegrad's critical assessment of
Kornberg's suggestion, in his opening statement in the trial, that
Louima's torn rectum and bladder had come not from Volpe's shoving
a stick into his rectum but from a consensual sex act with another
man.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz's lawyer, Worth, also dismissed Kornberg's statements,
saying, ``The time for Volpe to have come forward with this
information was when he pled guilty in open court and on the
record.'' He said that now, with the trial over, and with only
``news stories from his lawyer about what Justin Volpe would say,''
Kornberg's statements were of ``no legal significance.
</P>
<P>
   When Volpe pleaded guilty, he did not identify the other officer
in the bathroom, and described his role as someone who only ``saw
what was going on'' and ``did nothing to stop it.'' Volpe and
Kornberg have not identified that officer publicly, but it appears
from court documents that Volpe was referring in his plea to Wiese,
who told investigators in the days after Louima was attacked that
he had walked into the bathroom just after the assault.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz and Volpe, both now dismissed from the police force,
could be sentenced to as much as life in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
