<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MACHINISTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACHINISTS DON'T WANT BOEING TO CONSIDER FLEXIBLE WORK WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. won't sit down with its Machinists to
craft a new contract for two months, but workers are already making
one demand clear: Don't stretch out their work week.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Boeing and union officials will try to negotiate a
new contract for 40,000 Machinists. The company has already
suggested altering its work schedules by adding 40-hour work weeks
that start at mid-week. The idea calls for some employees to
receive regular pay, not overtime, for working on Saturday and
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Many Machinists have rejected the idea, arguing it would disrupt
their family obligations, cut into potential overtime and
complicate their child care arragements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a situation we are even willing to address,'' said
Bill Johnson, president of the International Association of
Machinist's District Lodge 751, referring to members' opposition to
the idea. Johnson, however, under U.S. labor law must at least
discuss the idea if Boeing brings it to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Revising schedules is only one of myriad disputes the two sides
must resolve when they begin negotiations on Aug. 15. Other
potentially explosive items include Boeing's ability to hire
outside contractors and whether union employees should pay more for
health-care benefits. The current contract expires Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives say they want to extend the work week to use
employees more efficiently, up to 24 hours a day, seven days a
week, when the company faces heavy workloads. The idea is part of a
broader plan to slow the growth of its labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also claim workers could reap benefits from the
change, because it could create new jobs at the aerospace giant.
More than two years ago, Boeing attempted to alter schedules at the
painting division to cope with an increasing number of planes
arriving from the assembly line. The proposal was never implemented
and the company eventually farmed out work to vendors, according to
Boeing executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we moved to some form of this it could result in the hiring
of more people,'' said Peter Conte, a spokesman for Boeing, the
largest airplane manufacturer in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Conte, however, is quick to point out that Boeing won't bring
any preconceived ideas to the table. And the company's chief
negotiator, Jerry Calhoun, has said the company would consider a
targeted approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to look at one area like the flight line or further
back in the factory like wing and body join,'' Calhoun said in an
interview earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, changes seem unlikely if the union has its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see an argument the company can put up that will be in
the best interest of the membership,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company should consider making better use of the
existing schedule, the union said. Johnson points out that 60
percent of Boeing's employees work the first shift, 30 percent
arrive for the second shift, and only 10 percent are employed in
the third shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Boeing can't fully utilize their facilities and personnel
during the normal work week, why would they be better off with a
non-traditional work week?'' the union asked in the latest issue of
its newsletter, the Aero Mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   While Boeing and its workers are bound to disagree over such
things as schedules and benefits, both sides say they are hopeful
this year's negotiations will be smoother than the last round in
1995. Four years ago talks broke down and Boeing's Machinists went
on strike for 69 days, disrupting production and angering airline
customers who were forced to wait for new airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood is optimistic,'' said Thomas Buffenbarger, president
of the International Association of Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing would welcome a smooth negotiation, with the company
scheduled to deliver a record 620 planes this year. The company is
also striving to polish its image on Wall Street, and boost its
stock price, by becoming more efficient, which means resolving its
labor problems quickly and without disruption.
</P>
<P>
   The union, facing another two years of layoffs, is seeking
security on a variety of fronts, from preserving generous medical
benefits to preventing additional layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also learned valuable lessons from the last round,
such as the importance of discussing flexible work weeks and other
matters in the months leading up to negotiations, according to
observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more sensitive to the fine art of contract
negotiations ... on both sides,'' said David Olson, a political
science professor at the University of Washington. ``If you want to
write a scenario about (how) the negotiating process breaks down,
that one was a classic example.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employees, however, are less upbeat. David Clay, a member
of the union who challenged Johnson in a past election, said the
extended work week could be divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a definite strike issue,'' Clay said.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Intelligencer reporter Bruce Ramsey contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
