<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HOW LONG DOES IT TAKE TO MAKE A NEW YORKER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York's infant U.S. Senate race has no official candidates,
but it does have an issue. Hillary Rodham Clinton has fewer local
roots than a giant cactus, and her potential opponents are already
playing the carpetbagger card. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani keeps
demanding to know how Arkansas voters would feel if he ran for
their Senate seat _ a question that probably depends on how many
Arkansans have seen pictures of the New York mayor's performance in
drag as ``Rudy/Rudia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, she doesn't live here,'' said Rep. Rick Lazio of Long
Island, another Republican Senate hopeful. ``Everybody in New York
realizes that this is not about serving the people of New York.''
If Lazio is on the right track, voters will never get past the idea
that Mrs. Clinton's motives for moving here were not confined to
our inherent lovability.
</P>
<P>
   The non-residents Robert Kennedy and James Buckley managed to
get elected senator from New York. But both had at least tenuous
ties to the state. Mrs. Clinton would be like the victim of a
sudden corporate relocation, rushing in with a couple of suitcases
and a list of real estate brokers, leaving furniture and spouse
behind in the old house. She must understand that her lack of
connections looks a little weird, since she recently got caught
trying to transform a childhood car ride through New York into a
``visit'' to Elmira.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not really unusual for a politician to go shopping for
a winnable district in which to roost. Sen. John McCain admits that
he was so new to Arizona during his first campaign that he kept
getting lost on his way to rallies. President George Bush claimed
three different states as his home before finally settling on
Texas, where his legal residence was a hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   Our forefathers always believed that home is where the
opportunities are. In the 19th century James Shields, an Irish
immigrant, was elected to the Senate from Illinois, Minnesota and
Missouri in succession, moving on whenever he lost an election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of starting over is part of the American dream,''
says Donald Ritchie, a historian for the Senate. ``You make a
mistake in one place, you move and try again.'' Arkansas is the
mistake Mrs. Clinton is trying to put behind her _ it's hard to
return to the bosom of old friends when so many have been indicted.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's status as an outsider might actually work to
her advantage in New York. This is the capital of sectional
antagonism, where people might prefer a stranger to a lifelong
resident from the other side of the state. As a Republican TV ad
vividly suggested, the residents north of Albany think of downstate
politicians as sharks swimming up the Hudson to get their money.
City residents dismiss the rest of New York as irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downstate people don't realize upstate people exist,'' sniped
a Democratic politician from Niagara Falls recently, after
Giuliani's office released a schedule that referred to the mayor's
visit to ``Niagra.'' (This is likely to be a campaign in which
candidates are challenged continually to spell the names of towns
and identify local highways. Eventually they may follow the lead of
a current Washington D.C. official, who told reporters he was
running for mayor, not taxi driver.)
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that almost nobody in New York knows the whole
state well, and almost all politicians learn about it by running
for office. Hold a statewide election, and candidates who could not
tell a cow from a water buffalo suddenly start wringing their hands
about the plight of the dairy farmer. The Rev. Al Sharpton says he
never realized that there were white people in more dire straits
than his supporters in Bedford-Stuyvesant until he campaigned for
Senate in rural Sullivan County.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maurice Hinchey, who hosted Mrs. Clinton's visit to
Binghamton on Wednesday, has led more than one urban Democratic
hopeful through his huge upstate district. He says most are fast
learners _ except former Mayor Ed Koch, who spent his gubernatorial
campaign trying to live down his description of rural residents
having ``to drive 20 miles to buy a gingham dress or a Sears,
Roebuck suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's carpetbagging problems may fade with time. The
election, after all, is more than a year and a half away. Kennedy
jumped into his race so late that he was still a registered voter
in Massachusetts when he was elected senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton would have time to get a house, plant a garden
and watch the tulips come up before she even becomes the Democratic
nominee. By then she would have spent more time in upstate New York
than the Deputy Commissioner for Tourism, and be able to rattle off
the name of every exit off the Taconic Parkway. If she loses
anyway, there will still be plenty of time to follow the example of
Shields, and seek political fortune in Nebraska or Kansas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
