<HEADLINE>
NORDSTROM MOVES TO THE NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Nordstrom Inc. moves up to the New York Stock Exchange
Thursday with flair.
</P>
<P>
   The upscale retailer will drape the exchange's building with
three pairs of 55-foot giant legs fitted with the company's
specialty item, shoes, when trading on its stock begins on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   The four-story-high legs will dangle down the front of the
exchange, greeting traders and visitors to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chairman and chief executive officer, John
Whitacre, announced May 18 at the company's annual meeting in its
new Seattle flagship store that it will trade on the Big Board
under the symbol JWN, the initials of the company's founder, John
W. Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the opening bell being rung by the company's
chairman, a tradition at the exchange, Nordstrom salespeople from
across the nation will do the honors from the exchange's bell
platform. They will be flanked by mannequins sporting custom-made
clothes fashioned especially to celebrate the move to the NYSE from
Nasdaq, where its stock traded under the symbol NOBE.
</P>
</TEXT>
